<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: EBBING CONFIDENCE IN TOKYO 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, June 27:
</P>
<P>
   Japanese voters handed a well-deserved rebuke Sunday to the
Liberal Democrats, the party that has held power in Tokyo for all
but 18 months since 1955. The chief opposition party, the
reform-minded Democratic Party, gained an impressive 32 seats,
almost as many as the Liberal Democrats lost. But the opposition
forces remain weak and divided, and the present ruling coalition
will retain a slim majority.
</P>
<P>
   The long-run message for the Liberal Democrats, however, is
bleak. Young urban Japanese have grown disenchanted with the
party's factional maneuvering, secretive ways and inability to
extricate the country from a decade-long economic slump.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Yoshiro Mori, who is party leader, has further
diminished the Liberal Democrats' appeal through his stumbling
performance. His two months in office have been marred by a series
of verbal blunders, including some disturbing invocations of
Japan's militarist past. During the campaign he invited undecided
voters to ``stay in bed'' on Election Day, a distressing posture
for a leader who should be expanding democratic participation. Mori
is expected to stay in office through next month's G-8 economic
summit meeting in Osaka. But he will probably be replaced as prime
minister before elections for Parliament's upper house next year.
</P>
<P>
   The Liberal Democrats' problems run deeper than one individual,
of course. Established during the Cold War as a bulwark against
Communism and Socialism, the party has had little competition from
other parties. With all meaningful politics occurring inside party
ranks, the Liberal Democrats developed strong internal factions,
glued together by campaign cash and patronage. Factional leaders
secretively manage all important decisions, including the choice of
prime ministers, with no public accountability. The selection of
Mori, after the sudden disability of his predecessor, was handled
particularly clumsily.
</P>
<P>
   The Liberal Democrats' main strategy against recession has been
public works spending, with projects awarded disproportionately to
rural districts where the party is strong. This has alienated urban
voters and has created huge deficits without triggering sustained
growth. A healthy recovery is unlikely without broad reforms,
including the kind of aggressive deregulation the Liberal Democrats
traditionally resist.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition Democrats do not have a fully convincing economic
program either. They strongly favor needed deregulation, but they
also campaigned for public spending cuts and tax increases. With
Japan's economy barely stirring, such deflationary policies would
be a serious mistake.
</P>
<P>
   For now, however, it is the policy choices of the Liberal
Democrats that count. Sunday's stinging reverse should spur the
party to adopt a more transparent leadership process and to embrace
the necessity for economic reform. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
