<HEADLINE>
CONGRESS REJECTS FUNDING CURB ON SMITH &AMP; WESSON DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVEN A. HOLMES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For the second time in less than a week, the House
of Representatives turned back an effort to scuttle an agreement
between the Clinton administration and Smith &AMP; Wesson on gun
marketing and safety measures.
</P>
<P>
   By a vote of 201-196, the House defeated a measure by Rep. John
Hostettler, R-Ind., that would have prevented the Justice
Department from spending any money to implement or enforce the
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Smith &AMP; Wesson and the administration remain at odds on just
what the agreement requires.
</P>
<P>
   The vote was virtually a mirror image of the tally last
Wednesday when the House defeated an earlier amendment, also
sponsored by Hostettler, that would have barred the Department of
Housing and Urban Development from spending any money to carry out
the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not gun control,'' said Rep. Carolyn B. McCarthy, a
Long Island Democrat who spoke out against the amendment and in
support of the agreement. ``This is gun safety where a manufacturer
comes before us and says it will do what it can to make our
communities safer.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday's action is the latest twist in the effort by the Clinton
administration to break the solid wall of opposition to gun control
by the nation's gun manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   In March the administration announced that it had reached an
agreement with Smith &AMP; Wesson, the country's oldest and largest
maker of firearms and a unit of Tomkins PLC of Britain. In return
for Smith &AMP; Wesson's entering into the agreement, the
administration and several cities agreed to drop their lawsuits
seeking to recover the expenses to government they contend result
from gun violence. Smith &AMP; Wesson was one of several gun
manufacturers being targeted by the lawsuits, which are still
pending, and the only one that agreed to the settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, the accord commits the company to placing a
second serial number that would be hidden on all new guns to make
it harder for criminals to erase a gun's identification.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Smith &AMP; Wesson agreed to provide all new guns with
trigger locks and to promise to use 2 percent of its revenues to
develop so-called smart-gun technology that would allow a weapon to
be fired only by its owner.
</P>
<P>
   Among the more contentious parts of the agreement was the
requirement that all Smith &AMP; Wesson-certified dealers make buyers
wait 14 days before buying a second handgun, and the promise,
administration officials say, by Smith &AMP; Wesson not to sell any
firearms at gun shows where background checks of buyers are not
conducted.
</P>
<P>
   In the weeks after the agreement, however, the administration
and Smith &AMP; Wesson diverged in their interpretation of this
critical provision.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials contend that the agreement barred the
company from selling firearms at shows where sellers _ whether they
are employed by Smith &AMP; Wesson or not _ do not conduct checks into
buyers' background.
</P>
<P>
   Smith &AMP; Wesson officials contend that the provision applies only
to gun shows where Smith &AMP; Wesson employees do not conduct
background checks.
</P>
<P>
   Should Hostettler's amendment have passed, and should Smith &AMP;
Wesson and the administration fail to resolve the differing
interpretations, the Justice Department would have been prevented
by lack of funding from going into court to force the Springfield,
Mass., company to comply with the administration's interpretation
of the accord.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
