<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S TIME TO MAKE THE RUN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILLY WITZ  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ The Anaheim Angels packed their equipment and
loaded their bags Monday afternoon and headed for Seattle after a
10-6 home loss Sunday to the Minnesota Twins. Noticeably absen
luggage was any sign of momentum.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels begin a critical 10-game stretch tonight against the
Mariners and Oakland Athletics, whom they trail by 5 and 5 games,
respectively, in the AL West.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners have won their last six and 12 of 15, and the
Athletics have won nine of their last 10. The Angels, meanwhile,
lost two of their last three to the lowly Twins. If those trends
don't get reversed, the Angels might find themselves with a
double-digit deficit by the All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't say there's a sense of urgency as much as this is
where you want to be,'' first baseman Mo Vaughn said. ``When you're
going head to head, it's time to make your move.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main thing is to be in position at the All-Star break.
Then you get hot and make your run in the second half. If we're
(behind) five or six games at the break, we're right there.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Angels are to get there, they'll have to do a better job
pitching and hitting than they did over the weekend when they split
four games with the Twins.
</P>
<P>
   Jarrod Washburn, coming off three straight brilliant outings,
was the third consecutive starter to get shelled against a team
that is 13th in the league in batting average and runs. The
left-hander, who had allowed a total of three earned runs in his
last three starts, was raked for eight runs and eight hits in just
3 innings, his shortest outing of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, I got knocked back down to earth a little bit,''
Washburn said. ``(The Twins) are making adjustments, but I know I
didn't do my job.''
</P>
<P>
   Washburn's performance is symptomatic of a staff whose biggest
winner, with six victories, is reliever Shigetoshi Hasegawa. The
young guys, like Washburn and Brian Cooper, are inconsistent, and
the veterans, like Tim Belcher, Ken Hill and Kent Bottenfield, have
been too frail.
</P>
<P>
   The four big bats in the middle of the lineup _ Vaughn, Tim
Salmon, Garret Anderson and Troy Glaus, who missed the last two
games with back spasms _ batted a combined .159 in the seven-game
homestand.
</P>
<P>
   Even when the Angels do hit _ with the exception of Darin Erstad
_ it's rarely been in the clutch.
</P>
<P>
   ``We play 21 straight days heading into the All-Star break and
20 in a row after,'' Scioscia said. ``There's not as much of an
opportunity to get them off their feet as much as I'd like.''
</P>
<P>
   Scioscia, whose team hasn't won more than three in a row all
season, insisted his team is playing good baseball and thinks a
winning stretch is looming.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, I'd like to be in first place,'' Scioscia said.
``But where we are is a position we can strike from. . . . The
challenge is to play consistent baseball. I think it's a matter of
time, whether it's right now or a month from now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
