<SLUG> BC-HKN-LINDROS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS SPEAK WITH LINDROS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL SEGUNDO, Calif. _ Los Angeles Kings general manager Dave
Taylor spoke Monday to Eric Lindros about playing in Los Angeles,
but the Philadelphia Flyers center remains uncertain whether he is
ready to resume his career after suffering four concussions in the
past year.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings have joined the New York Rangers and Toronto Maple
Leafs in pursuit of Lindros, the former Flyers captain and one of
the game's brightest stars whose time in Philadelphia appears over
amid charges that the club mishandled the treatment of his head
injuries.
</P>
<P>
   The Flyers want to trade his rights before Saturday, the day
Lindros can become an unrestricted free agent. Any club wanting to
sign him would have to give Lindros $8.5 million, which is what he
earned last season.
</P>
<P>
   That has limited the bidding to teams from the league's biggest
markets. The Kings claimed this past season they would lose money
even after moving into the Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor said last month he has been given the green light to
spend money to upgrade the club.
</P>
<P>
   Lindros grew up in Toronto, which is the richest club in Canada.
The Rangers have the NHL's largest payroll.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest issue, however, is health. Lindros suffered his
latest concussion in late May during Game 7 of the Eastern
Conference finals against New Jersey. Taylor called his
conversation with Lindros ``a general discussion'' and refused to
discuss specifics about the center's condition.
</P>
<P>
   ``We spoke,'' Taylor said, ``but I think it would be
inappropriate to say anything further about Eric or our dealing
with the Flyers.''
</P>
<P>
   The reason is simple. No one, not even Lindros, knows whether he
is going to play again. Lindros, who missed 27 games last season,
has discussed taking off a season. He has talked about playing in
Europe, where the game is less physical.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's message to Taylor was no different than the one Lindros
gave Sunday to new Rangers general manager Glen Sather.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Glen I don't know if I can play yet,'' Lindros told the
Philadelphia Inquirer. ``Right now, so much is up in the air. I
myself have to make a decision on whether I will play again and
whether it is worth playing again.''
</P>
<P>
   Lindros has had six concussions in his career. Three years ago,
his brother Brett retired early from the New York Islanders because
of the effects of several concussions.
</P>
<P>
   He has reported some improvement but also says he still is
having headaches related to the concussions.
</P>
<P>
   Lindros' rift with the Flyers escalated late in the regular
season when he believed the club withheld the severity of his head
injury.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia general manager Bobby Clarke has said Lindros is
ready to resume playing. But the final decision will be based in
part on the findings of Chicago-based neurologist James Kelly, who
has been treating Lindros.
</P>
<P>
   The problem for the Flyers' leverage with other clubs is that
Kelly has not released his findings on Lindros' fitness to play and
is out of the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-27-00 0024EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
