<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COL-PHONES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORGET THE GENOME. IS TIME SPENT ON HOLD LOST FOREVER? 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLYDE HABERMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Technology keeps bringing us new hopes and fears, a
perfect example being the announcement on Monday that scientists
had decoded the human genome. Now we have all these giant questions
to ponder, like whether the deciphering of the genetic code will be
used to find a cure for cancer or be hijacked by some mad scientist
out to create an entire race of Martha Stewarts.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, such worries are someone else's department. Fact
is, until recently we thought that ``genome'' was a misspelled
reference to Rumpelstiltskin and his kind.
</P>
<P>
   This space is better equipped to discuss the social and ethical
implications of truly meaningful technological change. Like the new
telephone that the bosses installed a while back.
</P>
<P>
   What a telephone! It can do just about everything except hum the
``Marseillaise.'' It even has a little panel on top that identifies
the incoming number when the phone rings, a device that can come in
handy when you're trying to duck people like the bookie wanting to
know when you plan to come up with the vig.
</P>
<P>
   But for months, the panel's flashing of one number after another
has presented a social dilemma. What is the correct response when
you know off the bat who is calling? Do you pick up the phone all
knowing and jolly: ``Hey, Jim, wussup?'' Or do you offer a
no-frills hello and let the other person go through the familiar
motions of identifying himself?
</P>
<P>
   This is a profound issue of daily consequence that technological
advances have wrought. Forget the genome.
</P>
<P>
   Perplexed, we turned to our etiquette guru, Letitia Baldrige.
She recommended the more traditional approach. ``Be very
nondescript,'' Baldrige counseled. ``Less is more. The less
information we give out, the better.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the thinking, too, of Virginia Russell, marketing
director at Gibbs Training and Consulting, an offshoot of the
venerable Katharine Gibbs School. . Russell, who developed a course
on telephone skills for businesses, recalled how a law firm had
complained to her that its employees were too informal in answering
the phone when they recognized the caller. The old ways work best,
she advised.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an invasion of someone's space'' to use an overly
familiar manner, she said.
</P>
<P>
   That settled that. But the discussion turned to phone manners in
general, a hot topic these days, judging from the anger generated
by so many cell phone users, especially the leather-lunged ones who
believe that the entire bus has to hear the shopping list for
dinner. What do you call those people, cell phoners or cell
phonies?
</P>
<P>
   The latest wrinkle is something called ear buds. You may have
seen them on the street. They are tiny earpieces and microphones
worn by people who can now talk and walk without the dreadful
burden, poor dears, of having to hold actual cell phones. The
problem for the rest of us is that it is hard to tell at first if
these people are harmless (if irritating) cell phonies or possibly
dangerous crazies talking to themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Years ago, Lily Tomlin had a one-woman show on Broadway in which
she expressed the wish that all the people muttering to themselves
on New York streets would pair off so that it would look as if they
were having real conversations. The ear bud tribe might want to
give that idea some thought.
</P>
<P>
   Proper phone behavior, Russell finds, is a big concern for her
corporate clients. All too many employees, she said, are clueless
when it comes to politeness. It hasn't dawned on them that
screaming at a customer or a client is not good business.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe more maddening are the mechanical devices that are now
universal _ automated answering systems, voice mail and the like. A
lot of companies, she said, have no idea how much they drive people
crazy with these gizmos, a point easily appreciated by anyone who
has bounced haplessly from voice mailbox to voice mailbox, an
electronic Flying Dutchman never making contact with a live human.
</P>
<P>
   Let's not even dwell on the vast stretches spent on hold, day in
and day out. Why couldn't the genome researchers apply their
talents to a truly cosmic issue, like how to recover precious
minutes and hours of lost life?
</P>
<P>
   At least it has dawned on some companies that they need to make
nice. Their act still needs work, though.
</P>
<P>
   One airline, trying to show how cool it is, urges you on a taped
message to think of being on hold as ``quality personal time.'' You
can, the voice says, ``reflect on what you've done with your
life.''
</P>
<P>
   What is there to do after advice like that except sigh and hang
up?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-27-00 0029EDT &QL; 
