<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-MARLINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS BATTER MARLINS, 10-5 
</HEADLINE>
   By TYLER KEPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For most of the first two months of the season, New
York Mets rallies died once they got past Todd Zeile, the No. 6
hitter. When the order turned over to the No. 2 hitter, Derek Bell,
the Mets were able to start something again.
</P>
<P>
   Things changed, though, when the light-hitting No. 8 hitter Rey
Ordonez was injured on May 29 and Jay Payton secured the No. 7 spot
with a torrid start to June.
</P>
<P>
   One of the main reasons the Mets are playing better, General
Manager Steve Phillips said, is that they ``have a chance to score
every inning.''
</P>
<P>
   With five home runs on Monday night from hitters in the Nos. 7,
8, 9 and 1 spots, the Mets overwhelmed the Florida Marlins, 10-5.
</P>
<P>
   Benny Agbayani had two homers, and Payton, Melvin Mora and
pinch-hitter Mark Johnson also cleared the fences. Johnson was
batting for the Mets' starting pitcher, Al Leiter, who improved his
record to 9-1.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first five-homer game for the Mets since Sept. 15,
1997, when Bernard Gilkey, Butch Huskey and Brian McRae combined
for five home runs against Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets had taken a 4-3 lead by the time Johnson, who was
called up from Class AAA Norfolk on Monday, crushed a fastball from
Joe Strong over the fence, just to the left of dead center.
</P>
<P>
   The homer gave the Mets a 6-3 lead, and they blew the game open
with four runs in the seventh, when Payton, Agbayani and Mora
homered.
</P>
<P>
   With their fifth straight victory, the Mets (42-31) moved within
three games of first-place Atlanta in the National League East. The
Braves will visit Shea Stadium for four games this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   In the Mets' third inning on Monday night, facing the
right-hander Reid Cornelius, Payton led off with a single to right,
giving him a career-high seven-game hitting streak.
</P>
<P>
   Agbayani, batting eighth, then crushed a breaking ball into the
left-field bullpen to give the Mets a 2-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   After an out, Mora, the leadoff hitter, reached on an infield
single and went to second on a groundout.
</P>
<P>
   Edgardo Alfonzo walked, and Mike Piazza singled Mora home to put
the Mets ahead by 3-1.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza drove in a run for the 10th game in a row, matching his
own club record.
</P>
<P>
   The lead did not last long. The Marlins scored their first run
on a homer by Mike Lowell to lead off the second, and they got
another bases-empty homer in the fourth, by Derrek Lee, to pull
within 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   In the fifth, Luis Castillo ripped a leadoff single, then
attempted his 33rd stolen base.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza received Leiter's pitch, a high fastball, and fired to
second, the ball meeting Alfonzo's glove just before Castillo slid
in. He was out, and he must have regretted it, for Dave Berg
followed with a triple and Cliff Floyd with a single.
</P>
<P>
   That tied the score, 3-3, but this time Cornelius could not
stand the prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   After a one-out single by Bell in the fifth, he walked Alfonzo
and Piazza to face Robin Ventura with the bases loaded.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura is at his best in that situation, and while he did not
hit a grand slam, he drove in a run, grounding to second to score
Bell and put the Mets ahead, 4-3.
</P>
<P>
   In 132 career at-bats with the bases loaded, Ventura has 14
grand slams and 157 runs batted in.
</P>
<P>
   Cornelius retired Zeile on a groundout to end the inning, but
Payton led off with a single in the sixth and one batter later,
Cornelius, a former Met, was removed from the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets thought so highly of Cornelius in 1995 that they traded
their opening day first baseman, David Segui, to Montreal to get
him. Cornelius went 3-7 in 10 starts in his only season with the
Mets.
</P>
<P>
   Cornelius, 30, has played for five organizations (including two
stints with Florida) and has been released three times since the
Mets dealt him to Cleveland in a deal for pitcher Mark Clark in
March 1996.
</P>
<P>
   He resurfaced in the majors last year, pitching in five games
for the Marlins, and has pitched well in their rotation the last
month.
</P>
<P>
   He can probably count Agbayani out of his fan club. Agbayani
came to bat with two outs and no runners on in the fourth inning.
</P>
<P>
   It was his first at-bat after the homer, and Cornelius's first
pitch drilled Agbayani in the thigh.
</P>
<P>
   Agbayani stared at Cornelius for several seconds, raised his bat
as if he were going to slam it, then tossed it aside and trotted to
first.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter did not have the chance to retaliate against Cornelius;
he had been the Marlins' last hitter the previous inning and did
not come to bat again.
</P>
<P>
   With two outs in the seventh, Turk Wendell hit Marlins shortstop
Dave Berg with a first-pitch fastball to the same area where
Agbayani was hit.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter pitched six innings, allowing three runs on seven hits
and three walks.
</P>
</TEXT>
