 KRON EMBARKS ON ROAD TO INDEPENDENCE  &HT;     By DAN FOST 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ After more than 50 years of local ownership, San
Francisco's KRON (Channel 4) officially changed hands Monday in the
most valuable deal in television station history.
</P>
<P>
   Young Broadcasting of New York bought KRON and a 51 percent
interest in its cable affiliate, BayTV, from Chronicle Publishing
Co. in a deal valued at $737 million _ including $650 million in
cash and roughly $87 million in stock.
</P>
<P>
   The owners of privately held Chronicle Publishing, which also
owns The Chronicle, will receive almost 3.9 million shares of Young
stock. Young stock closed Monday at $22.38, up $3.13, but down from
its 52-week high of $65.25, reached in September.
</P>
<P>
   The station is in for major changes, as it will lose its NBC
network affiliation in January 2002, causing some employees to
consider other jobs.
</P>
<P>
   NBC, thwarted in its bid to buy the station, demanded that Young
reverse the traditional model of having the network pay the local
affiliate to carry its content. Young balked, but KNTV (Channel 11)
in San Jose, Calif., agreed to pay the network $36 million a year
for the next 10 years to become the Bay Area's NBC affiliate.
</P>
<P>
   Although the change won't take place for another year and a
half, it has already roiled the station. ``This is not a red letter
day in the history of KRON,'' said reporter Anthony Moor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to leave,'' Moor said. ``Without a network
affiliation, it's like you're working for the minor leagues. ...
It's not what I signed up for.''
</P>
<P>
   But Moor, like most of the other on-air talent, is under
contract and can't switch stations without permission. He said at
least two other reporters had job opportunities arise, only to have
them squashed by contractual obligations.
</P>
<P>
   KRON and BayTV employ 350 full- and part-time workers.
</P>
<P>
   Vincent Young, chairman of Young Broadcasting, was at the
station's Van Ness Avenue offices in San Francisco on Monday,
meeting with executives and staff members.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's a whole lot of change in the offing
here,'' Young said in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   While Young said he wants to keep things running the same as
now, with a commitment to local news, others in the industry said
he would face significant hurdles in running an independent
station.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is, can he come up with the right mix of news and
syndicated programming to make a go as an independent,'' said Harry
Jessell, editor of the trade publication Broadcasting and Cable.
``That's a tall chore.''
</P>
<P>
   Eric Hulnick, vice president of news and operations for KNTV,
said his station's deal to become the Bay Area's NBC affiliate
``makes life 18 months from now a lot easier for me. I'm very
curious to see how KRON is going to fill its prime time.''
</P>
<P>
   Hulnick said he's already received resumes from some KRON
staffers.
</P>
<P>
   Vincent Young also said Wall Street was not optimistic about
KRON's prospects as an independent, which explains the dramatic
drop in Young Broadcasting's stock price. But he said bankers
supported his company's plans, which required the company to take
on millions in debt.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Young said it would hire Paul ``Dino'' Dinovitz as
vice president and general manager of KRON and BayTV, replacing Amy
McCombs. Dinovitz, who runs two Hearst-Argyle stations in
Sacramento, Calif., will start at KRON on January 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got purgatory coming up for the next six months''
waiting to see what changes Dinovitz will implement, said reporter
Moor.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason for Young's optimism is that the company
already owns the nation's largest independent station, KCAL in Los
Angeles. And part of the reason for the staff fears at KRON is that
Young had to make drastic budget cuts when it bought that station
from Walt Disney Co. in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   But Vincent Young said KCAL employed 150 more people than any
other station in Los Angeles, and needed ``tens of millions of
dollars in expense cuts. ... Here, we'll do things differently. We
might spend a little less here or there, but there's nothing
dramatic being proposed.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Dan Fost at  &LR; fostd(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
