<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FUNDS-RENAMED-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WADDELL &AMP; REED IS RENAMING FUND FAMILIES AND CREATING FOUR FUNDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK DAVIS  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo _ Waddell &AMP; Reed Financial Inc. said Monday that
it plans to rename its two mutual fund families, create four funds
and sell some of its funds through sources other than its sales
force for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   The Overland Park, Kan.-based company currently sells its United
Funds and Waddell &AMP; Reed Funds through about 2,600 Waddell &AMP; Reed
financial advisers. The advisers are the only source for buying
those funds.
</P>
<P>
   Starting next month, the United Funds will become Waddell &AMP; Reed
Advisors Funds. Also, the current Waddell &AMP; Reed Funds will take an
abbreviated name as the W&AMP;R Funds.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Butch, the company's chief marketing officer, said the
longtime United Fund name amounted to a ``historical misalignment''
with the company that manages the funds, namely Waddell &AMP; Reed
Financial.
</P>
<P>
   ``That certainly doesn't maximize the Waddell &AMP; Reed brand and
isn't consistent with what you find in the industry,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said changing the name takes advantage of recognition that
Waddell &AMP; Reed Financial is getting as a publicly traded company.
Shares of the fund company first traded in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The company's United Funds account for about 90 percent of its
mutual fund business.
</P>
<P>
   The W&AMP;R Funds will expand by adding four funds under the new
name. Each mirrors one of the existing United Funds in how it
invests and helps fill out the W&AMP;R group's offerings.
</P>
<P>
   The new W&AMP;R Funds:
</P>
<P>
   - The W&AMP;R Large Cap Growth Fund managed by Daniel P. Becker, who
will continue to manage the United Vanguard Fund.
</P>
<P>
   - The W&AMP;R Mid Cap Growth Fund managed by Zachary H. Shafran, who
will continue to manage the United New Concepts Fund.
</P>
<P>
   - The W&AMP;R Tax Managed Equity Fund, which the company announced
in April, managed by Cynthia Prince-Fox, who will continue to
manage the United Continental Income Fund.
</P>
<P>
   - The W&AMP;R Money Market Fund managed by Mira Stevovich, who will
continue to manage the United Cash Management Fund.
</P>
<P>
   The Waddell &AMP; Reed Growth Fund will change its name to the W&AMP;R
Small Cap Growth Fund as part of the reorganization.
</P>
<P>
   Waddell &AMP; Reed Financial said it will begin to sell the W&AMP;R
Funds through outside sales channels beginning in the fourth
quarter this year.
</P>
<P>
   The funds will be offered through 401(k) retirement plans,
through wrap accounts in which a broker offers investors a package
of funds, and through fee-based advisers who will be able to offer
access to W&AMP;R Funds through fund supermarkets.
</P>
<P>
   Butch said the new channels won't compete with the 2,600 Waddell
&AMP; Reed advisers who currently offer the funds directly to
investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to be selling funds directly to the public
through mutual fund supermarkets,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Waddell &AMP; Reed will have to reach sales agreements with 401(k)
plan administrators and consultants, brokerage firms and fund
supermarkets to make the W&AMP;R Funds available through those
channels.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to get out in the market and create those selling
agreements,'' Butch said.
</P>
<P>
   The funds soon to be called W&AMP;R Funds, currently available only
as class C shares, will be offered as class A and B shares as well,
the company said.
</P>
<P>
   The A shares charge a sales load, or commission, at the time
investors put money into the fund. The B shares carry a fee at the
time the investor sells, though the amount declines over time, and
they convert to A shares with no exit fee after eight years.
</P>
<P>
   The funds' C shares charge a ``level load'' throughout the time
the investor owns them.
</P>
<P>
   The current United Funds also offer A, B and C shares.
</P>
<P>
   Butch said offering the same share classes in the W&AMP;R Funds will
allow investors to more easily switch among the groups' funds using
the same share classes.
</P>
<P>
   The existing Waddell &AMP; Reed Funds had originally been sold only
as B shares. But those shares didn't convert to A shares after a
few years and were discontinued last year. Investors' B shares were
converted to the C shares.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-27-00 0037EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000627.0015 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 00:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5895 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-WEBVAN-MERGER-SFCHRON     06-27 0943
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEBVAN-MERGER-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 WEBVAN GROUP, HOMEGROCER TO COMBINE IN BILLION-DOLLAR STOCK DEAL  &HT;     By CAROL EMERT 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Webvan Group of Foster City, Calif., agreed to
join forces with HomeGrocer.com of Kirkland, Wash., Monday in a
merger of the No. 2 and No. 3 players in the Internet grocery
business.
</P>
<P>
   The all-stock deal, which involves 138 million Webvan shares,
was valued at $1 billion at market close Monday. Webvan will
exchange 1.076 shares for each share of HomeGrocer. Webvan's stock
fell 16 percent to $7.31 yesterday, while HomeGrocer's declined 15
percent to close at $6.88.
</P>
<P>
   For Webvan, the deal both eliminates a tough competitor and
gives it an immediate presence in six new markets. The combination
also will save a projected $20 million to $30 million annually in
redundant overhead costs.
</P>
<P>
   The deal was announced as Webvan and HomeGrocer were on the
verge of butting heads on multiple fronts.
</P>
<P>
   HomeGrocer was about to launch in the Atlanta area, the only
market outside of the Bay Area where Webvan operates. Webvan was
planning its foray into HomeGrocer's home territory of Seattle and
both were gearing up for entry into Chicago, home of rival Peapod.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the frailty of the capital markets and how important it
is to conserve cash, it seemed to us that this is the time to put
the companies together,'' Webvan chief executive George Shaheen
told The Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   This way, Webvan can ``more efficiently spend our marketing
dollars on the real competitors'' _ conventional supermarkets, said
Shaheen, who will remain president and CEO.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's announcement had the collateral effect of linking
Webvan, one of the Web's top ``fulfillment,'' or delivery,
companies, with Amazon.com, one of its leading e-commerce sites.
Amazon, which owns a 22 percent stake in HomeGrocer, will own about
6 percent of Webvan when the acquisition becomes final later this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Webvan has ``not had discussions with Amazon at this time, but
we're looking forward to the opportunity'' to explore partnerships,
said Shaheen. Webvan has been gradually expanding its product
offerings to include items such as best-selling books and pet
supplies.
</P>
<P>
   While Monday's deal has obvious advantages for Webvan, the jury
is still out on whether any Internet supermarket can be viable,
said Heather Dougherty, an analyst with Jupiter Communications.
</P>
<P>
   Grocery ``is a very low-margin business, both online and
offline,'' Dougherty said. Companies like Webvan and HomeGrocer,
which take orders over the Web, fill them at distribution centers
and deliver them to doorsteps via their own fleet of trucks, have
tremendous infrastructure costs, she added.
</P>
<P>
   It is not yet clear whether the HomeGrocer purchase will speed
Webvan toward profitability, Shaheen said. The company still
intends to try to raise $200 million to $300 million from the
capital markets in the second quarter of 2001 to continue
expanding.
</P>
<P>
   But that may be a tall order unless Webvan gains more currency
on Wall Street. Shares have fallen from their $15 public offering
price amid a general downturn among consumer-oriented dot-com
shares.
</P>
<P>
   At least Webvan doesn't have to worry about the HomeGrocer deal
falling through because of Webvan's stock price. HomeGrocer did not
insist on a ``collar'' that would allow it to pull out if Webvan
stock fell below a minimum threshold.
</P>
<P>
   A HomeGrocer spokeswoman said a collar was not considered
necessary because ``this is a transaction based on a good strategic
fit, we wanted to get this done and we're confident in (its)
long-term value.''
</P>
<P>
   With Monday's deal, Webvan will operate in 13 markets by the end
of this year. It will open just two new distribution centers in
2001. Its goal remains to operate 25 such facilities by the end of
2002, but that will depend on whether additional funding can be
secured, Shaheen said.
</P>
<P>
   Webvan will study HomeGrocer's fulfillment system and try to
reduce its delivery window to 30 minutes from the current 90,
Shaheen said. Webvan promises home delivery within a 30-minute time
frame.
</P>
<P>
   In the long term, Webvan hopes to replace HomeGrocer's smaller,
less automated distribution centers with more technologically
advanced facilities like Webvan's, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The combined company, which will use the Webvan name, will post
estimated revenues this year of $320 million, rising to $1.1
billion in 2001 as the company enters markets, said Peter Swan, an
analyst with Pacific Growth Equities.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Peapod Inc., which is the largest Internet grocer
but which is also growing much more slowly than its competitors, is
expected to ring up only $123 million this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly (Peapod is) now facing a much more formidable
competitor,'' said Shawn Milne, an analyst with E-Offering Corp. On
the other hand, Peapod has a well-capitalized ally in Royal Ahold
NV, a multinational supermarket conglomerate that recently rescued
Peapod from insolvency with a $73 million investment.
</P>
<P>
   Milne attributed the decline in Webvan's share price Monday to
the inherent uncertainties surrounding acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   In the first quarter, Peapod registered sales of $24.9 million
on a loss of $12.7 million. That compares with sales for HomeGrocer
of $21.2 million on a loss of $43.5 million and Webvan's $16.3
million in revenue on a loss of $57.8 million in the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Webvan founder Louis Borders will remain chairman of the
company, and Jim Barksdale, a HomeGrocer board member and
co-founder of Netscape Communications, will join the Webvan board.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Carol Emert at  &LR; cemert(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
