</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GENOME-CODE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 GENETIC CODE, A `WONDROUS MAP' PRESENTED AT WHITE HOUSE  &HT;     By TOM ABATE AND CAROLYN LOCHHEAD 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Two scientific teams announced Monday that they
have finished the first complete reading of the human genetic code,
an accomplishment that promises to speed up advances in drugs and
diagnostic tests even as it raises new ethical questions.
</P>
<P>
   The ceremony at the White House _ attended by J. Craig Venter,
president of Maryland-based Celera Genomics, and Francis Collins,
director of the National Human Genome Research Institute _ caps
years of trying to unravel the genome, the microscopic clump of DNA
that directs the actions of every living cell.
</P>
<P>
   As the doors to the ornate East Room of the White House slid
open, President Clinton strode in flanked by Collins and Venter to
recall how, two centuries earlier, Thomas Jefferson had stood in
the same room to view ``a magnificent map'' of North American
produced by the Lewis and Clark expedition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today the world is joining us here in the East Room to behold
a map of even greater significance,'' Clinton said. ``Without a
doubt, this is the most important, most wondrous map ever produced
by humankind.''
</P>
<P>
   The genome map, however, is also possibly the most inscrutable
map ever produced. It is made up of more than 3.1 billion bits of
chemical information represented by four letters _ A, T, G and C _
repeated time and time again in a long and bewildering sequence.
</P>
<P>
   According to Collins, if the genetic code were printed out on
standard paper, the stack would stand as tall as the Washington
Monument. And if a person started reading the code aloud, one
letter per second, it would take 100 years to finish, Venter added.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I suspect you would have fallen asleep before then,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   In his White House presentation, held in tandem with British
Prime Minister Tony Blair's London ceremony to underscore the
international nature of the effort, Clinton said doctors would use
the knowledge to ``cure diseases like Alzheimer's, Parkinson's,
diabetes and cancer by attacking their genetic roots.''
</P>
<P>
   Enormous Work Remaining
</P>
<P>
   But scientists said much work remains in filling in the gaps in
this first draft of the sequence.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, neither team offered a firm estimate of the number
of genes in human DNA. Before Monday's announcement, many
scientists had believed there were about 100,000 genes. But Collins
said Monday the public scientists had only identified 38,000 genes
for certain. Even though the final figure will undoubtedly be
higher, this preliminary finding contradicts what many scientists
thought just a few months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Finding genes is difficult because they make up only 5 percent
of human DNA, and scientists do not understand how to isolate these
coding regions. Nor do they know the function of the remaining 95
percent.
</P>
<P>
   But finding genes will be a snap next to the far more complex
task of figuring out how thousands of genes, operating
simultaneously in millions of cells, somehow orchestrate their
activities to produce the everyday symphony that is life.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know less than 1 percent of what we need to know to say how
your body works,'' Venter said.
</P>
<P>
   50 Years of Discoveries
</P>
<P>
   MIT geneticist Eric Lander, who heads the publicly funded genome
sequencing center at Boston's Whitehead Institute, said Monday's
announcement was the culmination of a half-century of advances.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is halftime for genetics,'' Lander said. ``It all started
around the turn of the century. Now the really interesting second
half of the game will begin.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Collins and Venter were all smiles and congratulations
yesterday, the two have clashed in the past over their different
goals and strategies for attaining the prize.
</P>
<P>
   Collins heads a government-funded program begun 10 years ago. It
has since grown to include 16 labs in the United States and five
other nations. Each night, this international team of public
scientists has freely published its gene discoveries on the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Venter, a scientific maverick who had chafed at the slow pace of
the public project, used private backing to create Celera in 1998
with an eye toward finishing the genome sequence first and making a
profit by charging drug and biotech firms for access to its private
gene database.
</P>
<P>
   During his White House remarks, Clinton, mindful of how Wall
Street misinterpreted his March statement on the genome project,
stressed that ``biotechnology companies are absolutely essential''
in the process of turning raw genetic knowledge into
``life-enhancing'' drugs and diagnostic tests.
</P>
<P>
   Ethical Issues Raised
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also touched on the ethical and social dilemmas
presented by the new genetic knowledge, starting with the
possibility that insurers or employers could abuse genetic
profiles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must guarantee that genetic information cannot be used to
stigmatize or discriminate against any individual or group,''
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   In their joint press conference, Collins and Venter both
emphasized the need to protect genetic privacy. A recent Time/CNN
poll found that 75 percent of those surveyed didn't want insurers
to have their genetic profile, while 84 percent wanted to keep such
information from the government.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists should take the lead, Venter said, in demanding tough
genetic privacy laws if they hope to avert the sort of ``debacle''
caused by a lack of trust in the technology used to create
genetically modified foods.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to do the right thing so people won't be afraid to
take genetic tests that could be of enormous use to them,'' Collins
added.
</P>
<P>
   Though their joint appearance marked an important thaw in their
relations, Collins and Venter have not yet worked out all their
differences. Both men said they hoped to simultaneously publish
their findings in a scientific journal and to collaborate on
analyzing the data, but haven't yet settled all the details.
</P>
<P>
   Awe and Unity
</P>
<P>
   The two were united Monday in awe of the enormity of their
accomplishment.
</P>
<P>
   Collins, a deeply religious man, said the genome offers us ``the
first glimpse of our own instruction book, previously known only to
God.''
</P>
<P>
   Venter, a combat medic during Vietnam, said he saw some men
survive horrible injuries while others died from minor wounds, an
experience that ``inspired my interest in learning how the
trillions of cells in our bodies interact to create and sustain
life.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Tom Abate at  &LR; abate(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
