r f BC-EXECOMP-LAVISH-SFCHRO     06-27 1335
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXECOMP-LAVISH-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 BAY AREA FIRMS LAVISH EXECUTIVES WITH ENORMOUS STOCK PACKAGES  &HT;     By ARTHUR M. LOUIS 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ &LR;   &LR; The guy who coined the phrase ``What goes up
must come down'' obviously didn't know much about executive
compensation.
</P>
<P>
   As they do every year, Bay Area corporate executives once again
enjoyed enormous pay increases during 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The 286 high-ranking executives from 55 large companies included
in The Chronicle's 16th annual compensation survey received an
average of $6.9 million last year in salary, bonuses, long-term
incentive pay and additional stock-option grants.
</P>
<P>
   That was a steep 40-plus percent increase from the average of
$4.8 million that the previous year's survey revealed executives
were paid.
</P>
<P>
   The bulk of last year's pay bonanza _ 81 percent, to be precise
_ came from option grants. The executives received options with an
estimated present value of $1.6 billion _ $5.6 million worth per
executive.
</P>
<P>
   Executives in the previous year's survey received $1.05 billion
worth of option grants, and the year before, the total was $733
million, or well under half the 1999 total.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as 1994, option grants accounted for less than
one-third of Bay Area executive pay, while salary and bonuses were
dominant.
</P>
<P>
   Today, thanks to the bull market of the '90s, options have
become the be-all of executive pay packages, with cash compensation
a pleasant but trivial afterthought.
</P>
<P>
   Sure Moneymaker
</P>
<P>
   ``Stock-option grants have gotten totally out of control,''
complains Graef ``Bud'' Crystal, an acerbic executive-compensation
expert and Bloomberg News columnist. ``There are no restraints on
the size of these grants.''
</P>
<P>
   For most executives, stock options are a sure moneymaker.
</P>
<P>
   The options typically give the executive the right to buy the
company's stock at the current price, and the executive usually can
wait as long as 10 years before exercising them, selling at the
prevailing price.
</P>
<P>
   It is the rare company whose stock doesn't rise, on balance,
during a 10-year period.
</P>
<P>
   The largest option grant last year _ $114.5 million worth _ went
to Thomas M. Siebel, chairman and chief executive officer of Siebel
Systems, the San Mateo, Calif., computer software producer.
</P>
<P>
   That huge grant allowed Siebel to rank first as well in total
compensation, with $117.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   Siebel's compensation last year boiled down to $13,423 per hour
_ 24 hours a day, seven days a week. (It seems appropriate to
reckon on a 24/7 basis, because companies assure us that their CEOs
are never off duty.)
</P>
<P>
   Siebel Systems officials did not respond to requests for
comment, but certainly the company performed admirably last year.
Its net income nearly tripled, and its stock price increased more
than fivefold.
</P>
<P>
   The company's proxy statement offers a rationale of sorts for
Tom Siebel's huge pay package.
</P>
<P>
   It says the company's compensation committee ``reviewed the
stock option positions provided to chief executive officers of
comparable software companies in connection with their employment
services.''
</P>
<P>
   Siebel's option package was ``intended to continue to maintain
the overall competitiveness of Mr. Siebel's compensation package
and strengthen the alignment of Mr. Siebel's interests with those
of the stockholders during a crucial phase of the Company's
development.''
</P>
<P>
   To which Crystal retorts: ``They just give this guy the moon in
terms of options. You need a degree in astronomy to handle numbers
that large.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rest of the Pay Iceberg
</P>
<P>
   Actually, last year's option grants _ as large as they were _
represent only the tip of the iceberg.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the rousing performance of the stock market _
particularly in high-tech issues _ the executives in The Chronicle
survey had accumulated $18.9 billion in profits from unexercised
options by the end of 1999. That works out to an average of $66
million per executive _ a tidy sum for a rainy day.
</P>
<P>
   Timothy Koogle, chairman and chief executive of Yahoo,
single-handedly accounted for about 12 percent of the option hoard,
with nearly $2.3 billion in untapped option profits.
</P>
<P>
   Also boasting more than $1 billion in unexercised option profits
were Siebel and Koogle's colleague Farzad Nazem, senior vice
president of Yahoo, each with about $1.2 billion worth.
</P>
<P>
   All told, 40 executives had at least $100 million worth of
unexercised option profits waiting for them at the end of last
year, compared with just 16 executives in the previous year's
survey.
</P>
<P>
   Ranking second to Siebel in total compensation last year was
Carleton S. Fiorina, president and chief executive of
Hewlett-Packard, the giant Palo Alto, Calif., computer
manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   Carly Fiorina, as she is commonly known, joined HP in July, and
was paid a total of $93.8 million for her half-year's service.
</P>
<P>
   Most of this came in the form of a $65.6 million
restricted-stock grant _ in essence a gift, not keyed to managerial
performance _ while the bulk of the rest came from stock-option
grants estimated to be worth $24.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   Restricted stock generally is used to ensure that prized
executives won't walk away from their companies. If they do so
before a specified period has elapsed, they lose the shares.
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard's proxy statement explains that the company had
to pay Fiorina a huge amount up front to lure her away from Lucent
Technologies, where she had served as a division head. In leaving
Lucent, she forfeited stock options roughly equal in value to the
restricted stock she got from HP.
</P>
<P>
   Some executive-compensation experts consider that deal
outrageous. They argue that Fiorina had no previous experience as a
chief executive or even chief operating officer, and that HP _ one
of the world's largest companies _ might have used the $65 million
in restricted stock to lure an established, world-class CEO.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why chase a candidate that is totally unproven and not
necessarily qualified for the job?'' says Matt Ward, head of
WestWard Pay Strategies in San Francisco. ``Her package is
mind-bogglingly stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   HP replies that it considered 300 candidates for the job,
including many people who served as CEOs elsewhere, and that
Fiorina was the best qualified.
</P>
<P>
   ``We looked at a lot of experienced CEOs who did not have the
core capabilities and competencies Carly had demonstrated,'' says
Debra Dunn, vice president for strategy and corporate operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were many things about her track record at Lucent _ her
ability to lead and inspire people to make major change, her
ability to handle a breadth of products, to understand technology
but be focused on the customer _ that fit quite perfectly with what
we wanted in an HP CEO.''
</P>
<P>
   Pay for Attendance
</P>
<P>
   Notwithstanding Fiorina's huge grant, restricted stock seems to
be going out of fashion in the Bay Area. Only 31 of the 286
executives in the survey received restricted stock last year _ down
from 46 in the previous year's survey. The median grant was
$440,000 _ down from $861,000.
</P>
<P>
   If restricted stock fades away, that will be just peachy with
many executive-compensation consultants.
</P>
<P>
   They ridicule restricted stock as ``pay for attendance'' _ as
distinguished from pay for performance. An executive merely needs
to come to work and stay alive for a specified period of time to
collect restricted shares.
</P>
<P>
   Marty Katz, an executive-compensation specialist with William
Mercer in San Francisco, notes that restricted stock ``tends to get
criticized as a giveaway, whereas with a stock option, you can
always argue that the executive's reward is precisely correlated
with the shareholders' reward.''
</P>
<P>
   Katz adds that companies also are shunning restricted stock
because it hurts the bottom line. He explains that under current
accounting regulations, restricted-stock grants have to be charged
against earnings, while stock options do not.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Arthur M. Louis at  &LR; alouis(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
