<SLUG> BC-YAHOO-SEARCH-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 GOOGLE IS YAHOO'S NEW SEARCH ENGINE  &HT;     By VERNE KOPYTOFF 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Internet portal Yahoo said Monday that it is
changing its search engine, replacing Inktomi with Google, a
fledging Web search service in Mountain View, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is a major victory for Google, which has gained respect
for the quality of its search results. The terms of the agreement
were not disclosed, but Sergey Brin, Google's president, said it is
his company's biggest contract since being founded two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Jeff Mallet, Yahoo's president, said his company
choose Google because ``they share our strong consumer focus.'' A
Yahoo spokeswoman said major contributing factors to the decision
included Google's ability to list search results by relevance and
requests by Yahoo users for the service.
</P>
<P>
   Google already offers its search engine to nearly 80 Web sites,
including Netscape and WashingtonPost.com. The company says it has
the Internet's most powerful search engine, drawing on content from
1 billion Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Danny Sullivan, editor of SearchEngineWatch.com, an Internet
news Web site, said Yahoo's deal with Google is probably based more
on money than quality. Because both Google and Inktomi offer good
search results, he said, the deciding factor for Yahoo may be that
Google was cheaper. ``It's like musical chairs when you deal with
these major portals,'' Sullivan said, adding that Yahoo has changed
search engines three times since it was founded in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Santa Clara, Calif.'s Yahoo, the third-most-popular Web
property, will begin using Google's search services in about a
month. Those search results will supplement Yahoo's own
human-edited directory of Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   In a consolation, Yahoo said yesterday that it will use
Inktomi's search engine in a new effort called Corporate Yahoo.
Yahoo is trying to sell customized versions of its service to other
companies for internal use.
</P>
<P>
   Inktomi, based in Foster City, Calif., offers its search engine
to nearly 125 Web sites including America Online and Microsoft.
Dick Pierce, Inktomi's chief operating officer, said that losing
Yahoo as a client is bothersome, but that the portal accounts for
only 2 percent of Inktomi's revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Inktomi stock fell sharply yesterday following the announcement.
Shares declined $25.31, nearly 18 percent, to $115.06. Yahoo's
stock dropped $6 to $119.31.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Verne Kopytoff at  &LR; verne(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
