<SLUG> BC-MONEYBAG-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 MONEYBAG: WHEN CHOOSING STOCK, WATCH THE PE RATIO  &HT;     By ARTHUR M. LOUIS 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I am interested in Qualcomm, the telecommunications company.
Its share price has been all over the place, from as low as $6 or
so to more than $170 last year. Recently, it has been in the $60s.
At what price would it be worth buying?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A: You have asked the $64,000 question _ not just about Qualcomm,
but about any stock.
</P>
<P>
   I prefer not to recommend the purchase or sale of specific
stocks, but let's discuss this in a general way, and maybe you can
arrive at your own answer.
</P>
<P>
   At a recent price of $68.25, Qualcomm was selling at more than
70 times its earnings per share for the latest 12 months, and at
more than 60 times its estimated per-share earnings for the fiscal
year that will end in September. At its peak last year, it was
selling for around 200 times earnings.
</P>
<P>
   As a rule, price-earnings ratios greater than 30 are considered
high. A company has to show promise of extraordinary earnings
growth to justify that kind of evaluation. To justify a PE of 60,
70 or (gasp) 200, a company's growth prospects must be nothing
short of explosive.
</P>
<P>
   Securities analysts surveyed by First Call predict that Qualcomm
will earn about $1.08 per share in the current fiscal year _ up a
rousing 80 percent from last year. But they expect the growth to
slow to somewhat more than 30 percent in fiscal 2001, with the
consensus earnings estimate pegged at $1.42 per share.
</P>
<P>
   Even 30 percent is strong growth _ but you have to ask yourself
how long Qualcomm can keep it up. At its current price, it still is
selling at nearly 50 times next year's expected earnings. Heaven
help the shareholders if the company reports an unexpectedly weak
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   That, in a nutshell, is the rational, fundamental approach to
stock evaluation.
</P>
<P>
   But it sometimes pays to be irrational. At the height of the
tech-stock mania late last year, you could have bought Qualcomm at
$100 per share and sold it for more than $170 in the space of a few
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the fundamentals, $100 was an outrageously high price
to pay. But at the time, tech-stock speculators were willing to pay
almost any price for almost any company with a seemingly bright
future.
</P>
<P>
   That's not the case right now _ but it could happen again, and
probably will. Just don't ask me when.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Investing With $50
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Q: My sister would like to make some kind of investment, but she
can afford to put in only $50 per month. Is there any investment
vehicle that will accommodate her?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A: Amy Arnott, a spokeswoman for Morningstar Inc., says that
several mutual-fund groups will let you buy shares in selected
funds for as little as $50 per month, under what are known as
automatic investment plans.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; Among the groups she cites are Columbia, (800) 547-1707;
Evergreen, (800) 343-2898; State Farm, (309) 766-2029; Strong,
(800) 368-1030; T. Rowe Price, (800) 638-5660; and USAA, (800)
382-8722.
</P>
<P>
   There may be others, so check with any particular funds that
interest you.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Estimated Payments
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Q: I plan to sell some stock at a large capital gain later this
year. This means I will have to make estimated tax payments in
September or January or both, because the tax my employer withholds
from my salary will be far below my expected tax liability for
2000. I didn't make estimated tax payments in April or June. How do
I figure the size of the payments that are coming due?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A: The law regarding estimated tax payments _ like much tax law _
is annoyingly complicated.
</P>
<P>
   You can find a thorough explanation of the procedures to follow
in Internal Revenue Service Publication 505, which you can download
from the IRS Web site at  &LR; www.irs.gov &LR; . You also can order it by
telephone at (800) 829-3676.
</P>
<P>
   Taxpayers generally don't have to make estimated tax payments
unless their withholding and credits for the current year are going
to be less than the smaller of the following benchmarks: 90 percent
of the current year's tax liability, or 100 percent of the previous
year's tax liability.
</P>
<P>
   If you do have to pay estimated tax, notes Internal Revenue
Service spokesman Jesse Weller, the total of your withholding,
credits and estimated tax payments does not have to exceed the
smaller of those benchmarks.
</P>
<P>
   Another consideration, Weller says, is that estimated tax
payments are required only if you are going to owe at least $1,000
more than the amount of your withholding and credits.
</P>
<P>
   (The calculation becomes more complicated if you are in a high
income bracket. Again, consult Publication 505.)
</P>
<P>
   Let's assume that you are indeed required to make estimated tax
payments this year.
</P>
<P>
   The next due date is September 15 _ the third payment date of
the current tax year. At that point, Weller says, you should make
certain that you have paid at least three-fourths of your estimated
tax. Figure your tax on Form 1040-ES, which also can be downloaded
or obtained by telephoning the IRS.
</P>
<P>
   The final payment deadline is January 16, and by then you should
have paid the full amount of your estimated tax.
</P>
<P>
   Failure to pay the correct amounts on time could subject you to
interest penalties.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Send questions about how to manage your money to
 &LR; moneybag(AT)sfgate.com &LR; , or to Arthur M. Louis, Moneybag column,
901 Mission St., San Francisco, CA 94103.
</P>
</TEXT>
