A5902 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-STORMS-SUPPRESSING-KA     06-27 1016
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STORMS-SUPPRESSING-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONCEPT OF SUPPRESSING TORNADOES DEBATED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN A. DVORAK  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Midwestern sky grows dark, radio and television carries news
of a tornado watch, and a menacing cloud that might contain a
twister begins to form.
</P>
<P>
   Into the air heads a fleet of airplanes, spreading particles in
a process called cloud seeding. They alter the way the storm acts,
defusing what might have developed into a tornado catastrophe.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like poppycock. Or at best a dream.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, but then again....
</P>
<P>
   Out on the Kansas plains, home to a 25-year-old program to study
ways to suppress hail and instigate rain, meteorologists last year
said they may have quelled a tornado near Dodge City.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Curt Smith, manager of the Western Kansas Weather
Modification Program, said weather experts ought to study tornado
prevention.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's a good chance you can disrupt the natural
forces that cause tornadoes,'' he said in a telephone interview
from his office in Lakin, Kan.
</P>
<P>
   It can't be done now, at least not in any big way, and perhaps
tornadoes will never be stopped entirely, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But someday, Smith said, defusing tornadoes may be reality.
</P>
<P>
   Others agree. It's not unusual for the National Severe Storms
Laboratory in Norman, Okla., to hear of tornado-stopping ideas.
</P>
<P>
   Some of them parallel the kind of cloud seeding Smith and his
pilots do. Others involve setting off explosions in the air.
</P>
<P>
   A few of the ideas fall into the absurd.
</P>
<P>
   Recognized tornado experts doubt all of them and dismiss any
claims that a tornado might have been quelled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Theoretically there may be ways to modify tornadoes,'' said
Jeff Kimpel, director of the storm laboratory. ``However, there's
no evidence to date of any known mechanism that will produce the
desired result.''
</P>
<P>
   Another longtime student of the weather, Edwin Kessler, was more
emphatic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's garbage,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   There is no documentation, said Kessler, a former director of
the severe storms laboratory, that tornadoes can be affected as the
cloud seeders suggest.
</P>
<P>
   ``The burden of proof is on them, and they can't prove
anything,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kessler said he sees no practical reason to study tornado
suppression. ``I wouldn't spend five minutes on it myself,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   No major studies of tornado prevention are known to be under
way.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the task would seem to be as huge as the sky itself.
</P>
<P>
   Tornadoes afflict Kansas, Missouri and many parts of the Great
Plains, and can occur almost anyplace.
</P>
<P>
   The violent storms consist of rotating air columns that stretch
from a thunderstorm to the ground. They're capable of winds up to
250 miles an hour. On average, about 800 occur each year.
</P>
<P>
   Human intervention looks microscopic, compared to the natural
forces at work in a tornado.
</P>
<P>
   Cloud seeding, like the Western Kansas Weather Modification
Program does to suppress hail, is done with one-engine or
two-engine airplanes. It involves flying to a selected area of a
thunderstorm. There, from containers on the planes, a substance
containing silver iodide is vaporized.
</P>
<P>
   If the airplanes get to the right part of a tornado-producing
thunderstorm and seed at the right time, they could change the
thunderstorm enough to kill a tornado or make it less damaging, say
advocates of cloud seeding.
</P>
<P>
   Last year they drew some support from an important advocate _
President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   While touring tornado devastation in Oklahoma, Clinton told a
crowd he wants ``to see what we can do not only to provide even
better warning, but perhaps to dilute the strength of some of these
very powerful tornadoes before they hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelvin Droegemeier, professor of meteorology at the University
of Oklahoma, said the statement provoked thought and conversation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It died down fairly quickly,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At Oklahoma, he said, no tornado prevention research is being
done. Droegemeier, who works with computer models of thunderstorms,
described stopping tornadoes as ``a very, very futuristic kind of
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``The kind of remark President Clinton made is easy to
make in conversation. To actually control the weather in some
measured way...we're not anywhere close to that.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue is fraught with controversy. How much money would be
spent? What parts of the country would be protected?
</P>
<P>
   One particularly troubling question: If tornadoes can be
suppressed, can they also be made worse?
</P>
<P>
   Just think of the possibilities, though.
</P>
<P>
   From 1950 to 1995, federal government statistics show, Kansas
averaged 11 strong to violent tornadoes a year. Missouri averaged
eight. There were 29 a year in Texas, the most anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Last year in Oklahoma, a spate of tornadoes injured 800 persons
and caused insured losses of around $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Suppressing just one or two tornadoes a year could produce
enormous savings.
</P>
<P>
   But in the weather industry, consensus doesn't exist.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is substantial division of opinion,'' said Larry Ruthi,
meteorologist in charge at the Dodge City office of the National
Weather Service.
</P>
<P>
   Ruthi, who's familiar with the Western Kansas Weather
Modification Program, doesn't dismiss the idea of someday
preventing tornadoes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it would be an interesting concept to explore,'' he
said. ``I would like to see an open mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith, the manager of the weather modification program, said his
cloud seeding pilots last June encountered a small twister while
working in a developing thunderstorm near Dodge City.
</P>
<P>
   The seeding, he said, may have weakened the thunderstorm enough
to also weaken the twister. Ultimately, the twister touched ground
briefly but did no damage.
</P>
<P>
   It is not uncommon for twisters to form in thunderstorms and
then fizzle out before reaching the earth or before doing any
damage.
</P>
<P>
   Smith questioned why universities or the federal government
don't undertake tornado suppression studies.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say it doesn't work,'' he said. ``Well, how do you
know?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-27-00 0043EDT &QL; 
