<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 00:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5903 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-NETWORTH-PENDER-SFCHR     06-27 1673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETWORTH-PENDER-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETWORTH: INVESTMENT-SAVVY PARENTS GET A BREAK WITH
COLLEGE  SAVINGS PLANS
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By KATHLEEN PENDER 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Starting Saturday, parents or grandparents who
want to save for a child's college expenses through the state's
ScholarShare program will have three new investment options, but
that still may not be enough for some people.
</P>
<P>
   The program, also known as a 529 plan, lets anyone contribute as
little as $25 or as much as six figures to a tax-deferred account
on behalf of a child. The money grows free of state and federal
taxes until it is withdrawn, when earnings are taxed at the child's
ordinary income tax rate, usually 15 percent. The money can be used
to pay for tuition and certain living expenses at virtually any
college or graduate school.
</P>
<P>
   The folks who run the 9-month-old ScholarShare program say some
parents were clamoring for a more aggressive investment option than
the only one now available, an age-based fund.
</P>
<P>
   That fund becomes progressively more conservative as a child
gets closer to college. For a child entering college in 17 or 18
years, the fund would be invested 80 percent in stocks and 20
percent in bonds. By the time the child enters college, the asset
mix would have shifted to 15 percent stocks, 35 percent bonds and
50 percent money market funds.
</P>
<P>
   That's not a bad strategy, but it's not surprising that some
parents might want even more growth potential.
</P>
<P>
   The equity portion of the age-based fund is not exactly a
shoot-out-the-lights portfolio. It's pegged to the Russell 3000
index, which includes all but the smallest U.S. stocks.
</P>
<P>
   The new choices are:
</P>
<P>
   -- A 100 percent Equity Option: This fund will invest in 80
percent U.S. stocks and 20 percent foreign stocks. The U.S. portion
will be ``benchmarked'' to the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index, but it
won't be a slave to the S&AMP;P like a pure index fund would.
</P>
<P>
   -- A 100 percent Social Choice Equity Option: This fund will be
very similar to the 100 percent Equity Option, except it won't
invest in companies that produce tobacco, alcohol, weapons, nuclear
power or pollution.
</P>
<P>
   -- A Guaranteed Option: This fixed-income investment is similar
to a savings bond. It promises that investors will get back at
least their principal plus 3 percent a year. The program expects to
pay an additional amount that will change each quarter. The total
return for the quarter starting Friday is expected to be 6.65
percent.
</P>
<P>
   While four funds are better than one, these four are not exactly
a smorgasbord of investment options. It's more like a choice of
beef, pork, chicken and potatoes.
</P>
<P>
   The guaranteed option is more conservative than the age-based
funds.
</P>
<P>
   The two new equity options are spicier than the age-based funds
because they'll remain fully invested in the stock market. But
they're not what you'd call aggressive growth funds, and the
performance of the two new funds will be very similar.
</P>
<P>
   The ScholarShare program probably won't be able to add more than
one more fund because the Internal Revenue Service has indicated it
will let 529 plans offer up to five options, says Christopher Lynch
of TIAA-CREF, the giant pension fund for college teachers that
manages the ScholarShare funds.
</P>
<P>
   The new funds were selected by TIAA-CREF and the ScholarShare
board, chaired by California Treasurer Phil Angelides.
</P>
<P>
   Angelides, whose staff oversees ScholarShare, has also been
pushing the state's big pension funds to use social criteria in
their investments.
</P>
<P>
   California parents were not exactly pounding the table for a
social fund. But Susan Baltake, executive director of ScholarShare,
says California will be the only state to offer a social option in
a 529 plan, and she hopes that will attract out-of-state investors.
</P>
<P>
   Forty-one states offer 529 plans, and parents can invest in
out-of-state plans, although they may miss out on some tax
advantages offered to in-state residents.
</P>
<P>
   (You can compare 529 plans and learn more about them, at
 &LR; www.savingforcollege.com &LR; , run by Joseph Hurley, an independent
expert on college savings.)
</P>
<P>
   California does not offer an extra incentive _ such as a state
tax deduction or credit _ for ScholarShare contributions, although
Angelides is pushing for one in AB2095. That measure would give
families earning less than $150,000 a tax credit of up to $500 for
ScholarShare contributions.
</P>
<P>
   The state hopes passage of that bill, plus the new options, will
jump start the program, which has attracted a modest $57 million.
New York's 529 plan has more than $300 million, but it also is a
year older than California's and offers a break on state taxes.
</P>
<P>
   New York's plan, however, offers only one investment option, an
age-based fund. And that will remain the best option for many
California investors.
</P>
<P>
   Once you put money into a fund in a 529 plan, it stays in that
fund until you withdraw money from the account. You can add new
money to a new fund, but you can't switch money from one fund to
another, like you can in a 401(k) plan.
</P>
<P>
   Most parents probably won't want all their money locked in
stocks because if the market is having a bad year when junior is
ready for college, they'd be forced to take withdrawals at
depressed prices.
</P>
<P>
   That's why most experts advise parents to gradually start moving
money from stocks to bonds or money market funds as their child
gets closer to college.
</P>
<P>
   You could accomplish this by carefully allocating some money to
ScholarShare's all-stock fund and some to the guaranteed option, or
you could do the same thing with less hassle by choosing the
age-based fund.
</P>
<P>
   You can get more details by going to  &LR; www.scholarshare.com &LR;  or
calling toll free 877-728-4338.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some of the salient facts.
</P>
<P>
   -- Contributions. Any adult can contribute to an account in one
or more states on behalf of a child.
</P>
<P>
   In California's plan, the maximum lifetime contribution for each
child _ from all sources combined, including money in other states'
529 plans ranges from $110,033 for kids born this year, to $158,146
for teens born before 1984.
</P>
<P>
   If your kid's a genius, consider this: Gov. Gray Davis is
sponsoring a plan to reward $1,000 scholarships to children who
rank in the top 10 percent of their school in STAR testing. If that
plan passes, the money will be put in a ScholarShare account and
count toward the lifetime maximum.
</P>
<P>
   The minimum contribution is $25, or $15 through payroll
deduction. You can also set up automatic investments from your
checking account.
</P>
<P>
   -- Fees. The only fee is 0.8 percent per year, or 80 cents per
$100 in account value.
</P>
<P>
   -- Withdrawals. If your child decides to skip college and get a
high-paying programming job, you can transfer the account to
another family member _ even a parent _ who can use it for his or
her ``qualified'' college expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Qualified expenses include tuition, room and board (including
off-campus housing costs up to $2,500 per year), books, and certain
supplies and equipment.
</P>
<P>
   -- Penalties. If you can't find anyone who can use the money for
college, you can withdraw it and pay taxes at your own rate plus a
10 percent penalty on the earnings.
</P>
<P>
   -- Advantages. Unlike most other college savings schemes, there
is no income limitation, so even the wealthiest parents can
participate. And the maximum contribution is far higher than with
other plans.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the most you can put in an Education individual
retirement account is $500 per year per child, and the accounts are
off-limits to couples making $150,000 or $160,000 and singles
earning $95,000 to $110,000.
</P>
<P>
   A grandparent or other wealthy patron can put up to $50,000 in a
child's account without triggering the federal gift tax, although
that will use up the donor's $10,000 annual gift-tax exclusion for
the next five years.
</P>
<P>
   In most cases, money in a ScholarShare account is considered the
parent's. That helps if you're applying for financial aid, because
parents are generally expected to contribute no more than 5.6
percent of their assets to college costs, while students are
expected to fork over 35 percent. But beware: Some private schools
consider 529 accounts as student assets, and other schools could
follow suit.
</P>
<P>
   -- Drawbacks. You cannot contribute to an Education IRA in the
same year you contribute to ScholarShare.
</P>
<P>
   -- Tax considerations. Most families are better off putting
money in ScholarShare than in a taxable account in the parent's
name. But some may be better off putting college money in a taxable
account in the child's name rather than ScholarShare.
</P>
<P>
   Here's why: Each year, a child can earn up to $700 in investment
income tax-free. The second $700 is taxed at the child's rate,
generally 15 percent. Everything over $1,400 is taxed at the
parent's rate if the child is under 14, or at the child's rate
starting in the year the child turns 14.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a 529 plan, you lose the $700 annual deduction,'' says Joe
Hurley, who also wrote the book, ``The Best Way to Save for
College.''
</P>
<P>
   You also lose the benefit of the lower tax rate on long-term
capital gains, because ScholarShare earnings are taxed as ordinary
income. The long-term capital gains rate for kids is only 10
percent, falling to 8 percent next year for assets held at least
five years.
</P>
<P>
   Which is best depends on the child's age and the parent's income
and tax rate.
</P>
<P>
   -- Control issues. In ScholarShare, the parent retains control
of the account. If you put the money in the child's name, the child
gains control at age 18 (or 21 if you specify) and could blow the
college money on a Mexican vacation.
</P>
<P>
   Thoroughly confused? You should be. You almost need a college
degree _ preferably a master's in accounting _ to choose a college
savings plan. And there's no right answer for everyone. The only
thing you can say for sure: Saving anything, anywhere, anyhow, is
better than saving nothing.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Kathleen Pender at  &LR; kpender(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
