<SLUG> BC-PROVIDIAN-SETTLE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 CREDIT CARD ISSUER TO SETTLE DECEPTIVE-MARKETING CHARGES  &HT;     By SAM ZUCKERMAN 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In a case that breaks new ground in consumer
protection law, credit card giant Providian Financial Corp. is
expected to settle, as early as Tuesday, charges that it
systematically used deceptive sales tactics, sources familiar with
the matter said.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement with the San Francisco district attorney's office
and federal bank regulators is worth more than $300 million and
will be one of the largest payouts in a consumer financial fraud
case.
</P>
<P>
   The case sets a new standard for what lenders may legally say
and do when pitching products to consumers, sources said. It carves
out a tougher stance and an expanded role for bank regulators in
curbing abusive credit practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Typically, the (regulatory) agencies have not used the
hammer,'' said Ed Mierzwinski of U.S. Public Interest Research
Group in Washington, D.C. ``It's a welcome departure.''
</P>
<P>
   In their yearlong probes of Providian, the district attorney's
office and the Office of the Comptroller of the Currency zeroed in
on direct mail and telephone marketing tactics that allegedly
resulted in thousands of sales to customers who didn't know what
they were buying.
</P>
<P>
   Investigating such complaints isn't unusual for the San
Francisco district attorney's office, which enforces California
laws for business practices.
</P>
<P>
   But the involvement of bank regulators in a case that focuses on
consumer deception ``could be a precedent,'' said James Rockett, an
attorney with the San Francisco law firm McCutchen, Doyle, Brown &AMP;
Enersen. ``That has never in the past been a focus of regulation.''
</P>
<P>
   One major area covered in the settlement is a Providian program
that guaranteed big, though undisclosed, savings to customers who
transferred balances from other card issuers, but actually lowered
interest rates by three-tenths of a percentage point or less.
</P>
<P>
   Another area involves sales of fee-based products, such as
credit protection, in which customers who thought they were only
requesting information were charged for purchases.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement requires the nation's sixth-largest bank credit
card issuer to halt such practices, pay a penalty and reimburse
victimized customers.
</P>
<P>
   The company is not admitting wrongdoing. But the combined weight
of local prosecutors and a key regulatory agency apparently forced
it to settle.
</P>
<P>
   After the district attorney's office began its investigation
last year, Providian carried out a cleanup of its sales methods.
The settlement forces the company to make further changes to ensure
customers understand what they are buying.
</P>
<P>
   Federal regulators began signaling a harder line more than a
year ago when they declared that the way lenders treat consumers is
a ``safety and soundness'' issue, traditionally their top concern.
</P>
<P>
   According to this reasoning, consumer abuse can harm a lender's
reputation and expose it to lawsuits, thereby threatening its
financial health.
</P>
<P>
   Providian insiders have complained that the company is a victim
of changing regulatory standards. They have said practices
previously considered lawful are no longer permitted.
</P>
<P>
   There is little sympathy for Providian in the banking and credit
card industries, where most rivals view the company as a predator.
</P>
<P>
   But the aggressive stance of regulators alarms lenders,
especially those like Providian, which target customers with
troubled credit records.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's now no mistaking that it's open season on subprime
lenders,'' said Kenneth Posner, an analyst with the brokerage firm
Morgan Stanley Dean Witter.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Sam Zuckerman at  &LR; szuckerman(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
