<HEADLINE>
LODUCA MYSTIFIED ABOUT DEMOTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In his mind, catcher Paul LoDuca did everything he
could to prove he should remain with the Los Angeles Dodgers when
catcher Todd Hundley returned from injury. LoDuca even told manager
Davey Johnson he'd play outfield, first or third base.
</P>
<P>
   But after hitting .346 in nine games, and throwing out a
team-high 28.5 percent of those trying to steal against him, LoDuca
was sent Monday to Triple-A Albuquerque to make room for Hundley.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers general manager Kevin Malone said LoDuca was a victim of
the dreaded numbers game, which meant little to LoDuca.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sort of dumbfounded right now, so I don't know what to
say,'' said LoDuca, who had two homers and five RBI. ``It's hard in
spring training, doing well there and getting sent down, but it's
even harder now with what I've done since I've been here. I just
don't know what I need to do to stay here.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm not wanted here, I want somebody to tell me that,
straight-up. If I'm still in the plans, I want to be here.''
</P>
<P>
   When LoDuca was sent to the minors during spring training, he
asked general manager Kevin Malone to trade him. Anaheim wanted to
trade for LoDuca, but the Dodgers didn't want to part with him
because he's an insurance policy, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   Last week's acquisition of Jim Leyritz rendered LoDuca
expendable at the major-league level once Hundley returned. Further
frustrating LoDuca is the situation at Albuquerque, where Angel
Pena is the No. 1 catcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up a Dodger and I want to be a Dodger, but if I'm not
in their plans . . .,'' LoDuca said. ``I've been a good person to
this organization and I hope they respect me, and I think that
should be enough to let me go where somebody wants me and I can
help out that organization. It's a really tough situation right
now. I don't understand it.''
</P>
<P>
   LoDuca said he would take most of the 72 hours afforded to him
to report to the Dukes if the Dodgers don't trade him.
</P>
<P>
   __ Suspension roster talk: The club wants depth at the starting
pitcher spot to compensate for possible suspensions, so rookie
right-hander Eric Gagne is expected to be recalled to start today
for the Dodgers, who bumped Darren Dreifort to Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson wanted Gagne back on the roster to give it depth for the
upcoming suspensions. The addition of Gagne means the Dodgers will
have, in theory, six starters to better handle the likely
suspensions stemming from last month's fight at Wrigley Field.
</P>
<P>
   Though Paul Beeston, chief operating officer for the
commissioner's office, is yet to announce his decisions on the
appeals of the 16 players, three coaches and one on-field
assistant, Dodgers officials are bracing for the news to come
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   To make room for Gagne, the Dodgers are expected to send reserve
outfielder Shawn Gilbert to the minors.
</P>
<P>
   __ Gywnn on DL: San Diego announced before the game that right
fielder Tony Gwynn will undergo arthroscopic surgery on his left
knee today, but it's uncertain whether it will end his season. That
won't be known until doctors can determine the degree of the
cartilage damage.
</P>
<P>
   __ Odds and ends: Center fielder Devon White hit left-handed off
a tee before the game, and team officials said the session went
well. The Dodgers will see how his left shoulder is today, and if
all is well White might hit right-handed off a tee. . . .
Right-hander Terry Adams had his sore right shoulder examined by
team physician Dr. Frank Jobe before the game. Adams was diagnosed
with tightness in the arm, but he said he didn't think it was
serious. . . . Jeff Shaw, removed from the closer's role recently,
said he didn't plan on going on the disabled list because he didn't
believe he was injured. . . . Lakers guard Kobe Bryant will throw
out the first pitch before tonight's game.
</P>
</TEXT>
