<HEADLINE>
UNVEILING OF THE MAP OF HUMAN DNA RAISES HOPES, QUESTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW SCHOFIELD  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the biggest scientific breakthrough of a generation _ and the
likely basis for the next century of medical research _ two rival
groups of scientists Monday announced a nearly completed map of
human DNA.
</P>
<P>
   The map, considered a ``rough draft'' of the human genome, is
the first step on a path that many scientists think could lead to
everything from designer babies to the reduction of human disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the biggest thing to happen in genetics since DNA was
discovered, and even that was simply setting the table for this
announcement,'' said Kelley Thomas, a University of Missouri-Kansas
City geneticist. ``It's not landing on the moon so much as Sputnik,
a shock to the system. I hope it will provide the same sort of kick
in the pants for this country....''
</P>
<P>
   The announcement was made jointly at the White House by Francis
Collins, director of the National Human Genome Research Institute,
and J. Craig Venter, president of Celera Genomics Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Both had been racing to be the first to sequence human DNA, and
experts see their cooperation as a way for both to eliminate the
enormous risk of finishing second.
</P>
<P>
   Human deoxyribonucleic acid, or DNA, is considered the blueprint
for what makes humans human. Human DNA consists of 6 billion
pieces, and is found in 3 billion base pairs that form a double
helix, or spiral staircase pattern. It controls everything that
goes into making an individual, from eye color to height to
likelihood of contracting cancer. Even so, the DNA of people as
seemingly different as Michael Jordan and Bill Clinton is thought
to be 99.9 percent similar.
</P>
<P>
   And so human genome sequencing is an effort to determine in what
order those 3 billion pairs arrange themselves to make us who we
are.
</P>
<P>
   A National Institutes of Health press release Monday said the
work covered 97 percent of the human DNA chain; the Celera work
covered 99 percent. That's why scientists call it a ``rough
draft.'' They won't consider the work finished until they've
rechecked the results at least four _ and possibly eight _ times.
 &LR; brk:A first edition
</P>
<P>
   Those in the field have known this day was coming for years.
That it came so soon is a testament to rapid advancements in
technology.
</P>
<P>
   The Human Genome Project can trace its roots to a late 1980s
California microbiology conference, where geneticists decided the
time had come to pursue the Holy Grail of their field.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, 16 research centers around the world _ including
some in China, England, France, Germany, Japan and the United
States _ signed on to take part in the sequencing effort. Among
those, there are five institutions including Washington University
in St. Louis, and they have accounted for about 80 percent of the
sequencing work.
</P>
<P>
   With the technology and techniques available in the early '80s,
the sequence would have taken 100 years to complete. By the early
'90s, 2010 was thought to be a more likely date. Three years ago,
the target was set on 2005.
</P>
<P>
   In May 1998, Venter announced he would head a new company and,
using a different method of sequencing, beat the Human Genome
Project to its goal. The race was on.
</P>
<P>
   John McPherson, co-director of the Genome Sequencing Center at
Washington University, said Monday that its researchers completed
the last 60 percent of the sequence in the past six months. He
attributed the increased speed to lowered standards, that is, much
of the data was original and yet to be re-checked.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we've got here is a rough draft of The Book of Life,'' he
said. ``We can read the book now, and generally understand what
it's all about.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we know there are typos that need to be corrected, and
there are probably some paragraphs that still need to be written,
and others that need to be re-arranged.''
</P>
<P>
   The final version of the completed DNA sequence is expected
sometime before 2003.
</P>
<P>
   McPherson said the reason the book was released before all the
mistakes were edited was simple: public demand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each night, we put what we've completed on the Web site, and
scientists were clamoring for more,'' he said. ``We had been moving
along fairly steadily, with a high degree of accuracy. But as more
information got out there, the scientists wanted more.''
</P>
<P>
   And scientists, he said, had been thankful for the information.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not exact, but it's close enough that they can see the
storyline and advance their own research,'' McPherson said. ``And
nobody wanted to wait another three years for a first glimpse.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Crawford, a professor of genetics and anthropology at
the University of Kansas, said breakthroughs of this magnitude
don't come along often.
</P>
<P>
   ``We discovered the nature of DNA, then we walked on the moon,
and now this,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything we do from here on out will be built upon this
information. ...Really, it doesn't get much bigger.''
</P>
<P>
   What would be built, he added, would come from the subspecialty
of genome diversity. If all men and all women are 99.9 percent
similar, then it is the 0.1 percent that accounts for all the
difference.
</P>
<P>
   Fully understanding that 0.1 percent means everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``Disease, appearance, behavior _ we'll understand it all, and
it will forever change biology, physiology, medicine,'' he said.
``Once a good sequence is done, we can get down to the world of
human variation.''  &LR; brk:Questions abound
</P>
<P>
   The breakthrough announced Monday is big. Kansas Citian M.C.
Sullivan won't deny that. And the advance arrived earlier than
expected.
</P>
<P>
   And that concerns Sullivan, the CEO of the Midwest Bioethics
Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many reasons to be excited here,'' she said.
``It's an exponential increase in our knowledge about ourselves at
a cellular level.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we've had years to prepare ourselves, and we've not yet
built any safeguards into our society.''
</P>
<P>
   First, she said, history had shown that there would be those _
the Hitlers and Stalins of the world _ who would seek to abuse
genetic advances.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, and more urgent perhaps, greed is a powerful
motivator. For instance, soon scientists may be able to identify
which genetic sequences mean a person is prone to cancer or heart
disease. If that produces advice on living well and possible
treatments, it's a boon for humanity.
</P>
<P>
   But if it means that insurance companies use the information to
determine who receives coverage and who is denied _ or even which
babies are born _ it could be bad news.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once this information is out there, anyone with access to a
drop of your blood will have access to volumes of extraordinarily
private information about you,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody knows when the raw information of a DNA sequence will be
turned into widespread and commercial applications. Recently,
Sullivan said, she heard that two of the world's most prominent
geneticists were discussing the possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first said certainly within 10 years we'd see work being
done,'' she said. ``The second laughed and said nothing would
happen in any of our lifetimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's safe to say that now that the sequencing is
virtually done, a lot of people will push this forward, and at a
faster rate than we now believe possible. I just hope we're ready
when it happens.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
