 DAVIS TO SIGN BILL PROTECTING RIGHTS OF GAY JURORS  &HT;     By GREG LUCAS 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ Gays and lesbians cannot be denied jury service
because of their sexual orientation under a bill to be signed
Tuesday by Gov. Gray Davis.
</P>
<P>
   The bill also forbids lawyers from excusing potential jurors
over a belief their sexual orientation makes them biased.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's wonderful the governor is going to affirm his support
that all people should participate equally in the jury selection
process,'' said the bill's author, Assemblywoman Carole Migden,
D-San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The bill is the first of several in the Legislature expanding
the rights of gays and lesbians that has reached Davis.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest bill, pending in the Assembly, increases the rights
of domestic partners to include inheriting property and making
medical decisions for an incapacitated partner.
</P>
<P>
   Davis has said he does not intend to sign any domestic partner
legislation this year.
</P>
<P>
   Migden's bill gives the Democratic governor a chance to sign a
modest measure benefiting gays and lesbians, giving him some
political cover if he vetoes future domestic partner bills.
</P>
<P>
   Migden's bill places in law previous federal and state court
decisions that say a person cannot be prevented from service on a
jury because of sexual orientation or dismissed by lawyers because
of a perceived bias based on that orientation.
</P>
<P>
   The law already contains a long list of factors that cannot be
used to exempt persons from jury service _ job, race, color,
religion, sex or nationality, among others.
</P>
<P>
   The new law mirrors a decision this year by the Fourth District
Court of Appeals in Orange County which said gays and lesbians
should be added to that group of people.
</P>
<P>
   The court said that gays and lesbians have a common perspective
and therefore represent a class of citizens that cannot be excluded
from jury service.
</P>
<P>
   But, the court said, sexual orientation should not be part of
questioning potential jurors.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one should be `outed' in order to take part in the civic
enterprise which is jury duty,'' the court wrote. ``The whole point
is that no one can be excluded because of sexual orientation. That
being the case, no one should be allowed to inquire about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Migden's bill, which would take effect January 1, also places
other court decisions in law that prevent lawyers from using
challenges to kick off potential jurors because of concern they are
biased because of their sexual orientation.
</P>
<P>
   Although the bill does not sharply expand the rights of gays and
lesbians, it was not without opposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gays, lesbians and bisexuals are a politically charged,
activist minority fighting to advance a sexual lifestyle that has
never been accepted in American history,'' wrote the Committee on
Moral Concerns in opposition to the bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bill's findings identify them as a group that might have a
chip on its shoulder,'' the group continued. ``That is exactly the
type of social segment that should be excluded from certain
trials.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the groups supporting the bill are the state Attorney
General`s Office, the Judicial Council and the American Civil
Liberties Union.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
