 SOLAR-POWERED HOT SEAT AHEAD?  &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The presidential race is heating up to the point
where experts now rate it as ``tepid,'' and random potshots are
giving way to issues of real substance.
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore announced a sweeping energy strategy, with tax
incentives to energy savers.
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush, not to be outdone, announced that he would offer
tax credits to Texas death-row inmates who sign up to use the
state's new solar-powered electric chair.
</P>
<P>
   IN COSMIC news, scientists last week discovered evidence of
water on Mars, raising the possibility that life could exist there.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Martian life forms came out of the closet and admitted
that they do exist. Then the Martians held a press conference to
announce that they are buying Earth and consolidating operations of
the two planets, a merger designed to cut costs, boost sales and
beef up defense against evil invaders from other solar systems.
</P>
<P>
   In related news, the Philip Morris /Nabisco merger will result
in the first adult cereal, Shredded Nic-a-Wheat.
</P>
<P>
   NO ITEM here goes uncorrected.
</P>
<P>
   Last week I noted that North Beach Playground assistant rec
director Dan Harrington first suggested naming the playground after
Joe DiMaggio a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But the idea first surfaced in '77. The playground is home field
of the softball dynasty Les Lapins Sauvages. Team member Chris
Sullivan, now retired from the SFPD but then ace investigator for
the sex crimes detail, suggested naming the field after Joe. A
campaign was launched and the supervisors voted the name change in
1980.
</P>
<P>
   Question: The Great DiMaggio had 19 years to register his
objection to the naming, so why did he wait until he was dead to
complain?
</P>
<P>
   JOE BACKLASH: DiMaggio's pal /attorney Morris Engelberg will be
happy to learn that Jim Brandt, owner of the Gold Coast, is
dismantling the restaurant's Joe DiMaggio photo gallery.
</P>
<P>
   The photos will be hung in the men's room, which will be
officially named the ``Morris Engelberg (off-color slang name for
rest room).''
</P>
<P>
   Supervisor Gavin Newsom says he'll be on hand July 13 to
dedicate the room.
</P>
<P>
   And Ultan O'Broin suggests that the burger joint under the
Doggie Diner head on Sloat be re-named the Joe DeDoggio Diner.
</P>
<P>
   THE STORY about the CEO of Catholic Charities putting cosmetic
surgery and lavish restaurant tabs on his expense account, on top
of his $172,000 salary, brought back fond memories for Ed Moose.
</P>
<P>
   In '61, Ed became PR director (read: fund-raiser) for Catholic
Charities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pay,'' Ed says, ``was a princely $6,000 per annum (note
Ed's fluent Latin), and neither dinner nor dermabrasion was a perk.
Where did I go wrong?''
</P>
<P>
   For starters, Ed, you had a lousy agent.
</P>
<P>
   And anyone knows it would be silly for a Moose to get a
face-lift.
</P>
<P>
   SPEED BUMPS: The property owner of the Westport Business Park in
Redwood Shores has installed a bunch of speed bumps because a bunch
of people were speeding.
</P>
<P>
   Workers are objecting. One said, ``It's a cop's job to enforce
the laws of the state, not a speed bump's job!''
</P>
<P>
   That's a good point, pal, because cops don't have enough to do
these days. Let's get 'em down there in your parking lot, riding
herd on self-important dot-commers.
</P>
<P>
   Kedar K. Adour read the story and notes: ``In Brazil, speed
bumps are called policias silenciosos _ silent policemen.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, why do you think God made BMW and Lexus SUVs?
</P>
<P>
   MAILBAG:
</P>
<P>
   -- In reference to a mention of how old-world hatters went crazy
from inhaling glue fumes: ``The hatters became crazed from the
lead, not the glue.'' (Ta Allan)
</P>
<P>
   Then why is that stuff called Krazy Glue?
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Why do you look constipated in your photo?'' (Anon.)
</P>
<P>
   Because I don't give a (bad word).
</P>
<P>
   -- In reference to my suggestion that beached-whale carcasses be
broken up not with dynamite, but by having Shaquille O'Neal shoot
free throws at 'em: ``What makes you think Shaq would be able to
hit the dead whales?'' (David Hicks).
</P>
<P>
   David, as Capt. Ahab said to Moby, ``You've got me stumped.''
</P>
