<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-PRIMARY-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 SUPREME COURT REJECTS CALIFORNIA'S PRIMARY LAW  &HT;     By MARC SANDALOW 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court struck down California's system
of ``blanket primaries'' Monday, ruling that political parties have
the right to exclude nonparty voters from the process of choosing
their candidates.
</P>
<P>
   The 7-to-2 decision invalidates state election rules _ in place
since 1998 _ that permitted voters, regardless of party
affiliation, to vote for candidates of any party.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Antonin Scalia, writing for the majority, said forcing
the parties to honor the votes of nonmembers amounted to a ``stark
repudiation of freedom of political association,'' and that
 &LR; violated a party's ability to control its own nominating process
and define its identity.
</P>
<P>
   As a legal matter, the ruling restores the state's closed
primary system, in which only registered Republicans can vote in
the Republican primary, and only registered Democrats can vote in
Democratic primaries. The decision also affects election laws in
Washington and Alaska, which are similar to California's.
</P>
<P>
   As a political matter, it is a setback for moderates hoping to
boost voter turnout and reward centrist candidates who appeal to
members of both parties. The state's primary rules had been
championed by officeholders from Gov. Gray Davis, a Democrat, to
Rep. Tom Campbell, R-Calif., to Secretary of State Bill Jones, and
Arizona Senator John McCain, all Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the blanket primary said they would try to find a
legally acceptable alternative in time for the 2002 election.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will do everything within my power to find a
constitutionally permissible way to ensure California voters
continue to have as many choices as possible in our primary
elections,'' Davis said in response to the decision.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell and Jones made similar pledges, each contending that
the new rules were responsible for huge increases in voter turnout
during the past two elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to let people participate as freely as they did in
2000,'' said Campbell, who is running for U.S. Senate. ``Some
change is needed.''
</P>
<P>
   The case pit the right of a state to determine its own election
laws against the right of political parties to select their
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Under California law, primary votes from party members were
given the same weight as those of nonparty members, setting up the
possibility that a Republican candidate might win the primary even
while losing a majority of Republican votes.
</P>
<P>
   Two Southern California assembly candidates assert that is
exactly what happened to them in March, and now they are expected
to go to court to overturn their election losses.
</P>
<P>
   In his majority opinion, Scalia disparaged a system that
``forces political parties to associate with (and) to have their
nominees, and hence the positions, determined by those who at best,
have refused to affiliate with the party, and at worst, have
expressly affiliated with a rival.
</P>
<P>
   ``Representative democracy ... is unimaginable without the
ability of citizens to band together in promoting among the
electorate candidates who espouse their political views,'' Scalia
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The justices said they were not deciding the constitutionality
of the more common open primary system used in another 20 states.
In most of those systems, voters choose on election day in which
party's primary they will participate.
</P>
<P>
   Parties have not objected to such rules and in many cases have
voluntarily opened up their primaries to nonparty voters, they may
stay with them in November.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic Party Chairman Art Torres said Monday he would
consider voluntarily opening California's Democratic primaries to
independents and voters who decline to state their preference.
</P>
<P>
   But Justice John Paul Stevens wrote in dissent that he believed
Monday's high court ruling endangered those primary systems, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is surely a danger that open primaries will fare no
better against a First Amendment challenge than blanket primaries
have,'' Stevens wrote in an opinion joined by Justice Ruth Bader
Ginsburg.
</P>
<P>
   In siding with the U.S. Court of Appeals in San Francisco, which
had voted to uphold the law earlier this year, Stevens acknowledged
the party's right to association, but said that states have special
rights to determine the nature of elections.
</P>
<P>
   Both general and primary elections ``are quintessential forms of
state action,'' Stevens wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a state acts not to limit democratic participation, but
to expand '' the ability of individuals to participate in the
democratic process, it is acting not as a foe of the First
Amendment but as a friend and ally.
</P>
<P>
   In pledging not to give up the fight in California, Campbell
said he thinks that by concentrating on the effect the state's
primary had on political parties, the overall ruling may provide a
road map for a possible replacement.
</P>
<P>
   Louisiana now uses a nonpartisan version of the blanket primary,
where the top two vote-getters, regardless of party affiliation,
move into the runoff election. Since that system doesn't affect the
parties, it would be legal in California, Campbell suggested.
</P>
<P>
   Allowing voters to register on election day, instead of cutting
off registration weeks earlier, also could boost voter turnout,
Campbell said.
</P>
<P>
   The blanket primary law was challenged by the Democratic,
Republican, Libertarian and Peace and Freedom parties, each of whom
applauded the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``This decision ... (will) help preserve the two-party system
which, for all its faults, is preferable to any of the known
alternatives.'' said Jim Nicholson, chairman of the Republican
National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear whether the ruling will affect the two Southern
California legislative races whose outcomes were directly affected
by the blanket primary rules. In both cases, the winning Republican
candidates failed to win a majority of Republican votes, winning on
the strength of nonparty voters.
</P>
<P>
   The losing candidates are expected to take their claim to court,
but it is unclear whether the cases can be heard in time for
November's election.
</P>
<P>
   (Chronicle Political Writer John Wildermuth contributed to this
report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-27-00 0105EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
