r a BC-SCOTUS-MIRANDA-SFCHRO     06-27 0975
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-MIRANDA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 MIRANDA WARNINGS UPHELD BY SUPREME COURT  &HT;     By HARRIET CHIANG 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Supreme Court upheld a legal and cultural icon of America's
justice system Monday by reaffirming the landmark Miranda warnings
that require police to advise suspects of their right to remain
silent.
</P>
<P>
   The 7-to-2 decision gives new momentum to a right, established
in 1966, that has become a cornerstone of criminal defense. The
ruling should also end the tactic, practiced by some police
officers, of ignoring the warnings during interrogations.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Miranda decision, once a suspect has been advised of
his or her right to remain silent and has requested a lawyer,
police can no longer continue questioning.
</P>
<P>
   In another victory for defendants, the high court left intact a
federal appeals court ruling allowing two Southern California
inmates, then suspects in separate cases, to sue police officers
for continuing to question them after the two invoked their Miranda
rights.
</P>
<P>
   In Monday's ruling, written by Chief Justice William Rehnquist,
the court said the Miranda warnings are a constitutional right that
only the court and not Congress can overturn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Miranda has become embedded in routine police practice to the
point where the warnings have become part of our national
culture,'' Rehnquist wrote. The court will overturn a prior
decision only under ``special circumstances,'' he said. ``We do not
think there is such justification for overruling Miranda.''
</P>
<P>
   In upholding Miranda, the high court reversed a decision last
year by a federal appeals court in Virginia that appeared to doom
the warnings. The appeals court, in a ruling that caught many legal
experts by surprise, held that police who fail to give Miranda
warnings can still use statements under an obscure 1968 law passed
by Congress. The law, which had been long ignored, sought to
replace Miranda with a general ``totality of circumstances'' test
to determine if a suspect made the statements voluntarily.
</P>
<P>
   Both defense lawyers and prosecutors in California say the high
court's actions may stop some police officers from deliberately
ignoring a suspect's Miranda rights, a practice taught to them at
state-approved courses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two cases together send a strong message to law
enforcement that Miranda is a constitutional rule and it has to be
obeyed,'' said Charles Weisselberg, a criminal law professor at the
University of California at Berkeley and one of the lawyers for the
two Southern California inmates who filed civil rights suits
against the police officers.
</P>
<P>
   Nathan Barankin, a spokesman for the state attorney general's
office, said the lawyers in the office were still reviewing the
court's decision. ``It does appear the court has attempted to
clarify the confusion associated with Miranda rights around the
country,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Hutchins, a deputy district attorney in Alameda County who
teaches courses on search and seizure as well as Miranda warnings,
insisted that Monday's rulings are not setbacks for law
enforcement. Without the Miranda warnings, ``it would be a mess,''
he said. ``Officers wouldn't have any way to determine what they
should do and what they shouldn't do.''
</P>
<P>
   The Miranda warnings have become a familiar part of police
procedures, based on the Fifth Amendment provision that no criminal
defendant ``shall be compelled in any criminal case to be a witness
against himself.''
</P>
<P>
   In its 1966 ruling, the high court established the Miranda
rights as an added protection against police brutality and coerced
confessions.
</P>
<P>
   Almost any television crime show will  &LR; includes in the script
``You have the right to remain silent. Anything you say can be used
against you.''
</P>
<P>
   But over the years, the Supreme Court has allowed several
exceptions to the rule. Police can, without first giving the
Miranda warnings, use a suspect's statements to challenge his or
her credibility. The rule can also be bypassed in emergencies when
law officers are trying to find a kidnap victim or a discarded
weapon.
</P>
<P>
   The high court also has ruled that in requesting a lawyer, a
suspect be clear and unequivocal.
</P>
<P>
   In the case decided Monday, Charles Dickerson of Maryland was
indicted on bank robbery charges but claimed that he had not
received his Miranda warnings when he was brought in for
questioning at an FBI office.
</P>
<P>
   A federal trial judge ruled in his favor, suppressing the
statements he made. But the federal appeals court reversed that
decision, based on Congress' 1968 law to replace Miranda.
</P>
<P>
   In his opinion, Rehnquist said exceptions made by the high court
were merely ``refinements'' made to a general constitutional rule.
Miranda, he stated clearly, is still the rule of the land.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Antonin Scalia, joined by Justice Clarence Thomas,
dissented, calling the Miranda decision a ``milestone of judicial
overreaching.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Southern California inmates case, two convicted killers
separately brought civil rights suits against police officers who
continued to question them after each had requested legal
representation.
</P>
<P>
   In one case, the defendant's statements were used against him
during cross-examination. In the second, the prosecutor relied on
the defendant's statements during sentencing.
</P>
<P>
   The federal appeals court in San Francisco ruled in November
that the police officers who deliberately ignored the defendants'
Miranda rights were not immune from lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   William Hadden, a lawyer who filed a brief on behalf of several
law enforcement groups, said ``it seems unfair that they would be
held personally liable,'' since they are trained to find ways to
circumvent the Miranda rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``This would be the perfect kind of case where a government
agency should pick up the cost for any damages assessed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
