<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 01:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5913 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-QUACKENBUSH-HEARINGS-     06-27 0928
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUACKENBUSH-HEARINGS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INSURANCE OFFICIAL SAYS QUACKENBUSH ORDERED SETTLEMENT TO PAY FOR 
 TV ADS
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By LYNDA GLEDHILL 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
SACRAMENTO _ In perhaps the most damaging testimony yet for
Insurance Commissioner Chuck Quackenbush, a senior Insurance
Department official told an investigating committee Monday he was
ordered to settle a case because Quackenbush needed money for
television commercials.
<P>
   The testimony, from senior department official Robert Hagadorn,
directly contradicts Quackenbush's previous assertion that he had
no knowledge of the controversial foundations used to settle claims
with insurance companies or that the money was spent on television
commercials in which he appeared.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hagadorn's testimony was very damaging to the commissioner's
claims that he was uninvolved,'' said Northridge Assemblyman Tom
McClintock, the senior-ranking Republican on the Assembly Insurance
Committee. ``It's imperative the commissioner categorically refute
the evidence presented to the committee ... or its going to lead to
action by the state Legislature.''
</P>
<P>
   Quackenbush has denied any wrongdoing. He is scheduled to appear
before the committee on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's hearing was part of the Assembly committee's continuing
investigation into the actions of the Department of Insurance.
</P>
<P>
   In a day of high drama, the committee ordered the arrest of one
witness who failed to appear, while three other key witnesses
exercised their Fifth Amendment privilege against
self-incrimination.
</P>
<P>
   Legislators are investigating allegations that Quackenbush
coerced insurance companies into paying $12 million to two
nonprofit foundations he created. The payments allegedly allowed
the insurers to avoid paying as much as $3.7 billion in fines for
improperly handling policyholders' claims after the 1994 Northridge
earthquake.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say the payments to the foundations were used to promote
the Republican commissioner's own political agenda and that none of
the money went to earthquake victims.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general's office also is conducting a civil and
criminal investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Hagadorn, head of the department's compliance bureau, said he
was involved in reaching a settlement with a title insurance
company when the department's chief counsel, Brian Soublet, told
him Quackenbush ``needed $4 million for a media buy.''
</P>
<P>
   At around the same time, Hagedorn said, the deputy commissioner
for finance, Norris Clark, told him that his settlement ought to be
at least $4 million.
</P>
<P>
   Hagedorn said he found the suggestion to be both reasonable and
suspicious.
</P>
<P>
   While he said he thought there should be a payment by the
company, he was suspicious about the amount because ``it was the
same number.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark is scheduled to testify on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Three witnesses took the Fifth Amendment Monday, including a
current Department of Insurance employee.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Lowder, a top aide to Quackenbush _ whose previous
testimony has been called into question _ refused to answer the
committee's questions.
</P>
<P>
   Also taking the Fifth was Courtney Sakai, an associate of Joe
Shumate, Quackenbush's political consultant. Sakai had been
expected to testify about why political questions were included in
a poll that was supposed to deal with earthquake issues.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, George Grays, the top aide to Quackenbush who
resigned when the growing scandal came to light, also took the
Fifth Amendment. Many witnesses have testified that Grays was
running the foundations out of his office, and at least one witness
testified that Grays may have forged his signature on checks.
</P>
<P>
   The committee issued an arrest warrant for B.T. Thompson of the
Skillz Athletic Foundation, which received $217,000 from one of the
foundations and ran a sports camp attended by Quackenbush's
children. Thompson failed to appear under subpoena, and the
committee ordered the sergeant-at-arms to arrest him and compel him
to testify.
</P>
<P>
   Also Monday, the whistleblower who first leaked key information
about Quackenbush said she was told to shred some documents.
</P>
<P>
   Cynthia Ossias, a San Francisco lawyer in the Department of
Insurance, said Lowder, the department's top enforcement officer,
told her and other department attorneys to destroy drafts of
documents containing potential penalties derived from department
audits of State Farm's handling of earthquake-related claims.
</P>
<P>
   She testified that the settlements derived from those claims
were far less than what should have been obtained and that some
contained unusual terms, including a finding that State Farm acted
in good faith in handling its claims.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was appalled,'' Ossias told the committee. ``I had been
involved in three of the examinations. ... I felt these exams
showed violations that were egregious and warranted hefty fines.''
</P>
<P>
   As first reported by The Chronicle, Ossias was granted immunity
for her testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Ossias also testified that she developed a number that she
considered to be a starting point for negotiations with the
insurance companies. This directly contradicts testimony of several
top Quackenbush aides, who said there were never any number
recommended by department lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   She said she was shocked by the $2.83 billion amount that was
presented as a fine for State Farm during meetings in March 1999.
During those meetings _ which were referred to in the department as
a ``Turkey Shoot'' _ members of the legal department were told to
put empty boxes in the room to intimidate insurance companies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
