<HEADLINE>
A SHORT NIGHT FOR HERSHISER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The quandary was about Carlos Perez for the first
month of the season. The Los Angeles Dodgers had him, but they
didn't know what to do with him. The dilemma remains, but the
subject has now changed from Perez to Orel Hershiser.
</P>
<P>
   They have tried everything and so far nothing has worked.
</P>
<P>
   Just when it looks like it won't get worse, the one-time prized
possession of the Dodgers shows this isn't 12 years ago. Or even
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Hershiser was unmercifully knocked around in an eight-run second
inning as the San Diego Padres extended the Dodgers' losing streak
to a season-high five games with a 9-5 win Monday in the opener of
a four-game series at Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   San Diego's Bret Boone had five RBI in the decisive second
inning, including a three-run homer. Brian Meadows (6-5) allowed
three runs in 7 innings for his second win since May 14.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers, who have dropped to fourth place in the National
League, got solo homers from Todd Hollandsworth and Alex Cora. It
was the first of Cora's career. They got a two-run double from
Shawn Gilbert in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   For Hershiser, it might be his lowest point of the season. He
allowed eight runs on six hits in 1 innings, hitting his 11th
batter in 24 innings of work.
</P>
<P>
   It might outdo his seven earned runs and four hit batters in 1
innings against Houston on April 19, or his five earned runs in
one-third of an inning in a May 9 relief appearance at Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   But one thing to consider in this latest debacle is that
Hershiser (1-5) was pitching on one day's rest. He threw 26 pitches
in 1 innings before rain interrupted his start Saturday in St.
Louis.
</P>
<P>
   This outing, atop what's been a messy season, again raises
questions about Hershiser's future and his role with the Dodgers.
When they signed him to a one-year, free-agent deal in the
offseason that guarantees him $2.5 million, a veteran pitcher with
a 13.14 ERA wasn't what they had in mind.
</P>
<P>
   It's possible Hershiser's spot in the rotation could go to
Perez, who didn't have the same problems pitching on the same days
as Hershiser.
</P>
<P>
   Just like in St. Louis, Perez pitched very well in place of
Hershiser. He allowed two hits in 4 innings scoreless, and
pressureless, innings. Perez allowed one run in 4 innings in relief
of Hershiser against the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   However, a decision on what to do with Hershiser could be put
off.
</P>
<P>
   One thing to consider is how much pitching two days after his
last start affected him. After rain stopped his last start,
pitching coach Claude Osteen and catcher Paul LoDuca said
Hershiser's stuff was wonderful and his command was strong.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers must also consider the suspension factor. Paul
Beeston, chief operating officer for the office of the
commissioner, is expected to rule this week on appeals of the 16
players suspended from last month's Wrigley Field melee.
</P>
<P>
   In Frank Robinson's May 24 ruling, starters Darren Dreifort,
Eric Gagne and Chan Ho Park were suspended three games each and
Perez was suspended five games. The Dodgers are hopeful those
suspensions are either wiped out or reduced, but contingency plans
are being made in case they hold up.
</P>
<P>
   Gagne is scheduled to be recalled from Triple-A Albuquerque to
start today against the Padres, but part of the thinking is to get
Gagne back on the roster and bump the pitching staff to 12. That
would also give the Dodgers six starters to mix and match over five
spots in the rotation, which could cover gaps created by the
pending suspensions.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't start out poorly for Hershiser. He got Ryan Klesko to
hit into a double play to end the first inning, but there was
nothing to help him in the second.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Nevin led off with a walk and Boone homered to put the
Padres ahead 2-1. Carlos Hernandez singled to left, Ruben Rivera
walked and Kevin Nicholson drove in a run with an RBI single.
</P>
<P>
   After a double steal and a strikeout of Meadows, Eric Owens'
infield single scored a run and Ed Sprague hit a sacrifice fly to
give the Padres a 5-1 lead. Klesko was hit with a pitch and Nevin
singled before Boone delivered a three-run double.
</P>
</TEXT>
