<SLUG> BC-CAL-PRIMARY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH COURT VOTES NO ON OPEN PRIMARY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICK ORLOV 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The U.S. Supreme Court handed political parties a
major victory Monday, throwing out California's blanket primary
system that let Democrats and Republicans vote for any candidate,
regardless of party affiliation.
</P>
<P>
   In the 7-2 ruling, the court said the state law, as well as
similar ones in Alaska, Washington and Louisiana, violate the First
Amendment provision for freedom of association because they prevent
political parties from determining their own candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the state law, overwhelmingly approved by voters
in 1996, vowed to submit a new measure to voters in 2002. The
blanket primary was designed to attract more voters and produce
more moderate nominees.
</P>
<P>
   Party leaders, however, said they will try to come up with an
alternative before 2002 that would give independent voters a say in
elections. One avenue, which the court upheld, is the practice of
allowing voters to register for a specific party ballot on the day
of the election.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we don't want is Democrats deciding Republican
candidates, and I'm sure the Democrats feel the same way about
us,'' said Mike Schroeder, former state chairman of the Republican
Party, who filed the initial lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``This wasn't an open primary as much as it was giving people a
chance to channel-surf for candidates. And the parties that were
really hurt were the minor parties that saw their members no longer
having any say in nominating their candidates.''
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Bill Jones, a Republican who supported the
blanket primary system, said he is not sure same-day registration
would be feasible in California.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not New Hampshire,'' Jones said, referring to a state
where a same-day registration is allowed. ``We have a lot more
voters out here, and I'm not sure it's practical.''
</P>
<P>
   The California system listed all candidates and allowed voters
to jump from one party to the next for any given office.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Antonin Scalia, writing for the majority, said the
California system was ``forcing political parties to associate with
those who do not share their beliefs, and it has done this at the
crucial juncture at which party members traditionally find their
collective voice and select their spokesman.''
</P>
<P>
   He said ``the burden (the California law) places on the rights
of political association is both severe and unnecessary.''
</P>
<P>
   His opinion was backed by Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist and
Justices Sandra Day O'Connor, Anthony M. Kennedy, David H. Souter,
Clarence Thomas and Stephen Breyer. Dissenting were Justices John
Paul Stevens and Ruth Bader Ginsburg.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit was pursued by the Democratic, Republican,
Libertarian and Peace and Freedom parties, whose leaders had
appealed after the state law was upheld by lower courts.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder and state Democratic Party Chairman Art Torres said
they would favor some method allowing independent voters to take
part in partisan primaries by declaring on primary election day in
which party they want to vote.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said it is too late to get an initiative petition
circulated and qualified for the November ballot, but that he was
looking at whether a legislator would consider authoring a measure.
</P>
<P>
   Nick Tobey of Californians to Protect the Open Primary said he
will seek to qualify a measure for the November 2002 election.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've done it before, and we'll do it again,'' Tobey said,
citing polls showing 72 percent of Californians support the blanket
primary.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Gray Davis expressed disappointment with the court
decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the first governor of California to be nominated in an open
primary, I believe this process is good for voters and good for
democracy,'' Davis said. ``In light of the court's decision, I will
do everything within my power to find a constitutionally
permissible way to ensure California voters continue to have as
many choices as possible in our primary elections.''
</P>
<P>
   The ruling will not affect this year's primary election results
or those in past years, said George Waters, a Sacramento attorney
whose firm serves as general counsel to the state Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   Former independent state Sen. Lucy Killea, one of the original
sponsors of the measure, said she was disappointed in the court
ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole idea was to try to reduce the influence of political
parties,'' said Killea, who said she left the Democratic Party
because of her disgust with partisanship in Sacramento. ``It's a
shame that now the parties will be able to again be so strong.''
</P>
</TEXT>
