r a BC-LA-NO-GUNS-LADN     06-27 0907
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LA-NO-GUNS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROPOSAL TO BAN JUNIOR ROTC RIFLES TRIGGERS DEBATE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HARRISON SHEPPARD 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Junior ROTC cadets in Los Angeles Unified could
find themselves training to be soldiers without one crucial element
_ mock guns and air rifles for drills and competition _ if a
proposed school board resolution passes.
</P>
<P>
   School board member Valerie Fields wants to ban the use of the
rifles by students in the Junior Reserve Officer Training Corps,
saying they are inconsistent with the board's zero- tolerance
policy on weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are sending out mixed messages to kids,'' Fields said.
``You come to school with a mock gun, a toy gun and you're
expelled. And yet we allow the ROTC kids to come in with disarmed
weapons and we glorify them.''
</P>
<P>
   She added that she respects the district's JROTC program and the
values it teaches, but just thinks ``they don't need to be that
militaristic.''
</P>
<P>
   Her resolution calls for the program's officials to come up with
an appropriate substitute for the use of rifles and report back to
the board. But JROTC cadets said getting rid of the mock rifles
would mean the end of their drill teams and competitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole competition is based on rifles,'' said Juan Marquez,
15, a cadet master sergeant in the Army JROTC program at Monroe
High School in suburban Sepulveda. ``If we don't have the rifles,
we don't have a competition.''
</P>
<P>
   Other students said performing drills with the mock rifles,
while only a small part of the program, is one of the more fun and
challenging elements, and also helps to recruit younger students.
</P>
<P>
   Egly Sanabria, 17, a North Hills senior and cadet lieutenant
colonel, said training with air rifles has taught him discipline
and concentration, two skills that are also useful in the school
environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're shooting you have to concentrate in everything you
do,'' said Sanabria, who plans to join the Army Reserve after
graduation. ``The slightest distraction and you won't shoot in the
middle (of the target). It also helps to make the stress go away.''
</P>
<P>
   Fields' resolution to ban the use of mock guns by JROTC was
supposed to come up for board discussion today. Instead it will be
assigned to the School Safety and Campus Environment Committee,
which will take it up July 20, to give people more time to comment
on the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, JROTC students on the drill teams and color guard use
mock rifles either a Springfield 1903 rifle that has been
``demilitarized,'' or stripped of its firing mechanism and its
barrel blocked, or fake rifles made of plastic. The demilitarized
weapons cannot be converted back into working guns, according to
JROTC officials.
</P>
<P>
   Students on the rifle team use air rifles, which fire small
pellets, for marksmanship training and competition.
</P>
<P>
   The students who use the rifles are a small percentage of the
overall JROTC program. At Monroe High School, out of almost 300
JROTC cadets, only five are on the air rifle team and 15 are on the
drill team.
</P>
<P>
   Districtwide, there are about 4,500 cadets.
</P>
<P>
   JROTC administrators said the use of weapons, even symbolic
ones, to guard the flag when it is presented during ceremonies has
been a long and important tradition in the military. Without the
use of rifles, serving on the color guard just won't be the same,
they argued.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you present the colors, it's a tradition that goes back
to the days of the Roman Empire,'' said Army Lt. Col Ted McDonald,
assistant director of the district's JROTC program. ``You protect
your banner, your flag. Back then they used swords and spears. In
modern times we use a sidearm.''
</P>
<P>
   If the mock rifles are not allowed, he said, they would consider
other options to guard the flag.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always been guarded. How we would guard it, I don't know.
Maybe we'd have to go to sabers.''
</P>
<P>
   But McDonald also said that ultimately the use of rifles is not
the most important element of the JROTC program and he would
cooperate with whatever decision the board makes.
</P>
<P>
   But not all board members agree with Fields.
</P>
<P>
   ``Zero tolerance is all about having weapons on campus that are
meant to do harm to other kids or teachers or anyone who happens to
be on the school site. That's not what ROTC weapons are about,''
said board member Caprice Young, who added she hasn't decided yet
how she'll vote on the resolution. ``They're used for drills,
They're used for honorary kinds of protocols. They're not used to
hurt people.''
</P>
<P>
   She added that the use of mock guns also symbolizes for students
that sometimes democracy has to be defended by the use of force.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to fight for this democracy, and we have to struggle
every day in a global community that doesn't necessarily support
democracy. Sometimes it's important to, symbolically through our
rituals, through our flag salutes, show we are willing to continue
to fight for democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   Member Julie Korenstein, who heads the safety committee and
helped craft the zero-tolerance policy, said she can see both
sides.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little disconcerting that it's OK to have guns for some
things yet not have guns for anything else,'' Korenstein said. ``At
the same time, I suspect if we're having ROTC on our campuses,
which is a form of premilitary training, there may be reason to
allow it. I'm still making my mind up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
