<SLUG> BC-GENOME-SOCAL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRUG FIRMS EYE GENOME MAPPING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JASON Z. COHEN 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ While the mapping of the human genome is
essentially complete, the work is really just beginning.
</P>
<P>
   For two area companies, the work that begins now is where the
opportunities lie.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people initially thought that the mapping was
completed, that was the end game. The fact is, it's kind of the
beginning game,'' said James Chamberlain, president and chief
executive officer of Biosource International, based in Camarillo in
neighboring Ventura County.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the sequence of the genetic makeup of all humans has
been uncovered, it is up to scientists to take those genes and make
sense of what they say.
</P>
<P>
   That's where a company such as Biosource stands to benefit.
</P>
<P>
   Biosource's products include strands of DNA as well as test kits
and proteins, all of which are used at every stage of biotechnology
research.
</P>
<P>
   Major universities, biotech companies and pharmaceutical
manufacturers all use Biosource's products in their research, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It opens up many more areas of research,'' Chamberlain said.
``It just fits right into our products. This should help us out a
lot even though we're not making the drugs ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   One company that is making the drugs is Thousand Oaks-based
biotechnology giant Amgen, also in Ventura County whose
billion-dollar drugs Epogen and Neupogen both are the result of
similar genetic research.
</P>
<P>
   Amgen has been engaged in genomic sequencing, but with the
ultimate goal of taking the information it discovers and creating
drugs.
</P>
<P>
   One of Amgen's current drug candidates, OPG, is the result of
such research, said Amgen spokesman David Kaye.
</P>
<P>
   Amgen scientists isolated a gene, then engineered mice that had
an overexpressed version of the gene and others that had an
underexpressed version.
</P>
<P>
   Those mice with the overexpressed gene had excessively dense
bones, while the other mice had brittle, weak bones. The
researchers then found the protein whose manufacture that gene
regulates and are testing it as a possible drug for osteoporosis.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important to remember that genes are not drugs,'' Kaye
said. ``There is a lot of work to be done. It's a really important
first step.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to its own genomics program, Amgen subscribes to
Celera's library of genetic information. The company already has
begun research based on the information Celera has decoded, Kaye
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a drug discovery company,'' Kaye said. ``What we hope to
do is develop important therapeutics that can make use of the human
genome.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
