r a BC-LA-NO-AMMO-LADN     06-27 0499
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LA-NO-AMMO-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAN ON AMMO SALES IN L.A. BACKED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ALEXA HAUSSLER 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Acknowledging that Los Angeles would be plunging
into a national legal debate, a City Council committee is
supporting banning the sale of ammunition in the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a problem in our society and a problem in our city,
and I think this is a remedy in trying to solve that problem,''
said Councilman Mike Hernandez, who proposed the measure to the
council's Public Safety Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The committee _ with two of its three members present _ approved
the proposal Monday and sent it to the full council for
consideration, despite threats by gun-control opponents to
challenge the measure immediately.
</P>
<P>
   ``Laws which do not have a rational basis are unconstitutional,
and I think you'll find that this law does have no rational
basis,'' said Randall Herrst, a gun advocate with the Center for
the Study of Crime. ``You are reducing the ability of people to
defend themselves much more than you are the ability of criminals
to commit crimes.''
</P>
<P>
   Chicago is the largest U.S. city with such a prohibition, said
supporters and critics of the plan.
</P>
<P>
   Council members said the city's approval of a ban would give Los
Angeles grounds to add its voice to a case now before a federal
appeals court. The U.S. 9th Circuit Court is considering whether
state law pre-empts a Los Angeles County ban on ammunition sales on
county property.
</P>
<P>
   The Board of Supervisors passed the ban in August, driving a
major gun show out of the county fairgrounds at Pomona. Arguments
in the case are scheduled to be heard Aug. 10 in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll give us a reason to engage in the current debate,'' said
Councilman Nick Pacheco, a committee member.
</P>
<P>
   In case the ban on ammunition sales is shot down in court, the
committee called for a contingency _ a proposal by Councilman Mike
Feuer to require yearly background checks for purchasers of
ammunition in the city.
</P>
<P>
   Roberta Schiller, executive director of Women Against Gun
Violence, urged the committee to approve the Feuer proposal, saying
other California cities likely would follow suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we need is to create a web of cities that can support
this middle-of-the road type of ammunition regulation.''
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Police Commission supported both measures late
last year. After the committee's approval Monday, the ban is
expected to be taken up by the City Council in about three weeks,
although no date has been set.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Michel, a Los Angeles attorney representing the National
Rifle Association, said his client would file a lawsuit if either
of the Los Angeles ordinances is adopted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Neither one of these ordinances is going to prevent one crime
from occurring because ammunition is available through the mail,''
he said. ``Anybody who wants ammunition will now just simply not
buy it through a dealer in L.A.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
