ready to begin writing off Japan's democracy as hopelessly
moribond, the huge advance made Sunday by an opposition party once
seen as hapless has awakened the country to the possibility of
political change. By Howard W. French.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NY-BRONX-DEVELOP (New York) _ A Special Report: The Banana Kelly
Community Improvement Association, a nonprofit group once praised
as a national model for local residents who want to reclaim lost
neighborhoods, is in trouble. Yet while employees were scrounging
to collect money to make the payroll, Yolanda Rivera, the chief
executive of Banana Kelly, and a few of her associates were
traveling, as part of an international venture the group
established several years ago. By Amy Waldman.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DRUGS-SPENDING _ Spending on prescription drugs increased a
record 17.4 percent last year, with elderly people experiencing the
largest cost increases, a new study by a drug benefits company
says. The study comes during a week in which the House is expected
to vote on proposals to help provide prescription drug coverage to
Medicare benificiaries. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FED (Washington) _ After a period of rip-roaring growth that
fueled fears of inflation, the economy is showing enough signs of
slowing that the Federal Reserve will most likely leave interest
rate policy unchanged when it meets on Tuesday and Wednesday,
economists and analysts say. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TAIWAN (Taipei, Taiwan) _ Ask Stan Shih about personal
computers, the Internet or his native Taiwan, and he holds forth
enthusiastically. Not for nothing is Shih, the voluble founder of
the computer maker Acer, regarded as the head cheerleader and
unofficial spokesman for corporate Taiwan. But ask Shih whether he
favors an independent Taiwan, and he turns monosyllabic. ``No,'' he
says, as his Cheshire-cat smile tightens. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   NABISCO (Undated) _ There are two big winners in the two-part
deal to sell off Nabisco: Philip Morris shareholders, who saw the
price of their stock rise nearly $4 Monday, and Carl Icahn, the
value investor whose betting against the market when he bought a
stake in Nabisco Group Holdings gave him a very large psychic and
financial victory. By Kenneth N. Gilpin.
</P>
<P>
   NABISCO-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The complex transaction by which
Philip Morris, the nation's largest cigarette company, will buy
Nabisco _ a company that used to be part of a company that owned
R.J. Reynolds, the No. 2 cigarette maker _ is a monument to the
fear that class-action suits will drive the tobacco companies into
bankruptcy. By Floyd Norris.
</P>
