<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FED-PREDICT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FED RATE BOOST UNLIKELY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS SIEROTY 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Former Federal Reserve Board Governor Robert
Heller said Monday that he believes the Fed is likely to leave
short-term interest rates unchanged when they meet today and
Wednesday in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Heller said the Federal Open Market Committee, the group within
the Federal Reserve that controls monetary policy, is likely to
leave rates alone so that they can analyze the effect of past rate
increases on the economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of sectors are beginning to turn soft,'' he said. ``You
are seeing a slowdown in auto sales, housing starts and sales of
existing homes, along with other interest-rate-sensitive sectors of
the economy.''
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve has raised short-term interest rates 1.75
percentage points over the past year in an effort slow inflation at
a time of record economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   When they last met in mid-May, the central bank's top
policy-makers raised overnight interest rates by a half-point to
6.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time to wait and see if a course correction has taken
place,'' added Heller. ``You don't want to overdo it.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond this week's meeting, the outlook for Fed policy is
uncertain. Fed policy-makers meet again Aug. 22. At that time, if
new data suggest a rebound in growth, they could raise rates by a
quarter of a percentage point, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have no clue what they are going to do in August,'' said
Heller.
</P>
<P>
   He said the everyday consumer has to understand that when ``you
walk into that room, there will be people that say we should be
raising rates. Then there are others who will say keep rates at
their current levels.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a consensus-building process and at the end, Fed
officials will take a vote,'' he said. Heller served as member of
the Board of Governors of the Federal Reserve from 1986 to 1989.
</P>
<P>
   The Board of Governors, a separate body from the FOMC, is the
Fed's equivalent of a corporate board of directors.
</P>
<P>
   Heller said at the end of this week's meeting, the FOMC should
have left interest rates unchanged, which will mean a slight
reprieve for consumers as far as their mortgages and other
interest-rate-sensitive loans are concerned.
</P>
<P>
   However, consumer confidence is still near an all-time high. The
economy will slow down, and Fed officials hope that their series of
rate increases will help sustain a growth rate close to 3 percent,
said Heller.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will be in a growing economy and a well-growing economy,
but not as we saw last year,'' said Heller, who is now an executive
vice president with Fair, Isaac and Co., a San Rafael-based
financial services firm.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Heller warned that an unexpected increase of
a quarter of a percentage point this week could send the stock
markets lower.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will have a negative reaction on the markets, because they
didn't have time to digest a 25-basis-point increase, when a rate
increase wasn't expected,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-27-00 0154EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
