r f BC-CAL-HOME-PRICES-LADN     06-27 0262
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAL-HOME-PRICES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSING SALES DEFY SLOWING U.S. ECONOMY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREGORY J. WILCOX 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Rising interest rates did not faze California home
buyers during May as both sales and prices hit record levels, a
trade group said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The median price statewide rose 11.8 percent on an annual basis
to $246,420, said the Los Angeles-based California Association of
Realtors. Prices have been at record levels for months, reflecting
huge appreciation gains in the Northern California market.
</P>
<P>
   Sales rose 7.2 percent last month, which would amount to 580,540
units if the market maintained May's level throughout the year.
</P>
<P>
   In Los Angeles county prices were weaker but sales stronger. The
median price rose 3 percent to $208,710, still well below the
record of $229,260 reached in May 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Sales increased 17.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter where you go in L.A. County, if you have good houses
with access to good schools. ... It's still a red-hot market,''
said Jack Kyser, chief economist for the Los Angeles County
Economic Development Corp.
</P>
<P>
   In Ventura County, the median price jumped 10.7 percent to
$288,780 and sales increased 3.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Sales remained robust in defiance or rising interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, 30-year fixed mortgage interest rates averaged 8.52
percent, up from 7.15 percent a year ago, according to the Federal
Home Loan Mortgage Corp. Adjustable rates averaged 7.07 percent, up
from 5.72 percent in May 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
