r s BC-BBN-DODGER2-LADN-(SLA     06-27 0707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGER2-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    WRITETHROUGH, WITH QUOTES... 
SHORT NIGHT FOR HERSHISER
</HEADLINE>
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ There was no illusion that this stop in Los
Angeles would be even close to the same as the first time around
for Orel Hershiser. No one thought a Cy Young was in store, but a
handful or more of wins and maybe a golden moment or two were
possible.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it has turned into a situation nobody wanted to think
about, or really cares to witness.
</P>
<P>
   Even when it looks like it won't get worse, or can't fall
further, the one-time prized possession of the Dodgers shows he is
very different these days.
</P>
<P>
   Hershiser was unmercifully knocked around in an eight-run second
inning as the San Diego Padres extended the Los Angeles Dodgers'
losing streak to a season-high five games with a 9-5 win Monday in
the opener of a four-game series at Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   San Diego's Bret Boone had five RBI in the decisive second
inning, including a two-run homer, and Brian Meadows (6-5) allowed
three runs in 7 innings for his second win since May 14, but this
was about Hershiser.
</P>
<P>
   And about his future.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had some sad days, but today really tugged at your
heartstrings to see Orel struggle like that,'' Dodgers manager
Davey Johnson said. ``I know he's frustrated about it. It's been
hard on him, but it's been just as tough on me because I think the
world of him and he's such a great pitcher and had such a good
career.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really tough seeing Orel struggle. It was not fun. He
doesn't have all his weapons working for him, he's struggling with
command. I've never seen him struggle. He's always been something
special. To see him struggle, that's tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson wouldn't address Hershiser's standing in the rotation
after the game. No doubt, it's something that will be discussed in
some high-power meetings during the next few days at Chavez Ravine.
</P>
<P>
   The choices are aplenty and only one is good for Hershiser. He
could stay in the rotation, but with Carlos Perez pitching
excellent relief for the second straight time (he threw 4 shutout
innings), the left-hander is likely to find his way back into the
rotation.
</P>
<P>
   There's a possible move to the bullpen, a release or a trade.
Hershiser tried the bullpen and that didn't work, and even tried a
minor-league stint to get his control back.
</P>
<P>
   But at 41, there's also the suggestion Hershiser could retire
and move into the Dodgers front office.
</P>
<P>
   ``He still feels he can pitch, and if he feels that way I feel
that way, too,'' Johnson said. ``It's a little lack of work. . . .
I don't have the answer. I wish I did.''
</P>
<P>
   Six weeks ago, Hershiser said retirement wasn't an option, and
following one of the worst outings of his career, he said that
remains his thinking.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a puzzle and I want to figure this puzzle out,'' said
Hershiser, 1-5 with a 13.14 ERA. ``I wouldn't (retire), and even if
I was I wouldn't even think about talking about it right now. After
a tough outing, it's not the time to think about that. I need to
work on it, and here, all in a sudden if there's not an
opportunity, then I need to think about other things.''
</P>
<P>
   He allowed eight runs on six hits in 1 innings, hitting his 11th
batter in 24 innings of work. It might out-yuck his seven earned
runs and four hit batters in 1 innings against Houston on April 19,
or his five earned runs in one-third of an inning in a May 9 relief
appearance at Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have a confidence problem, I have an execution
problem,'' said Hershiser, who threw 26 pitches in a Saturday start
in St. Louis. ``When you can only throw the ball somewhere between
83 and 87 miles per hour, pretty straight and not with much
movement, at least for a strike, big-league hitters are going to
catch onto that pretty quick. It can get ugly pretty quick, and it
did.''
</P>
<P>
   Boone gave the Padres a 2-1 lead with a two-run homer in the
second. He also capped the inning with a three-run double to give
the Padres an 8-1 lead and knock Hershiser out of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's had an awesome career,'' Boone said of Hershiser. ``He
can't have the stuff he had 10, 12 years ago.''
</P>
</TEXT>
