</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-LYCOS-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... in April.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the logic of Terra Lycos stems from the international growth
of the Internet, so does some of the controversy surrounding
Villalonga.
</P>
<P>
   The medium is gaining ground globally; by 2003, International
Data Corp. predicts, only 200 million of the Internet's 600 million
users will be in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The trend had been on Villalonga's mind since the former
management consultant was appointed to head Telefonica by his
boyhood friend, Spanish Prime Minister Jose Maria Aznar.
Telefonica's previous managers had bought up state-owned phone
companies in Argentina, Brazil, Peru and Mexico, and Villalonga
moved to spin off these companies as separate stocks, part of a
reorganziation to promote online businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Yet these actions prompted resistance from foreign investors in
some of the telephone companies. The investors complained that
Telefonica wasn't assigning them enough equity. ``It was a terrible
rip-off,'' says Mark Mobius, president of Templeton Emerging
Markets Funds.
</P>
<P>
   Mobius threatened to sue, and to settle the matter earlier this
year, Villalonga and Telefonica agreed to acquire some of their
minority shares from the miffed investors.
</P>
<P>
   The phone companies also served as a platform for Terra
Networks's expansion. In March, Terra said it had 389 million page
views a month in Brazil, for instance, and 116 million in Mexico. A
rival, StarMedia Network Inc., said it had about 140 million page
views a month in Brazil earlier this year, and about 266 million a
month in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Exact comparisons aren't available because the companies report
and audit their measurements differently. Yahoo Inc., doesn't break
out traffic figures for its Latin sites.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of hard numbers seems to make the competition bitter.
Fernando Espuelas, chief executive of StarMedia, in New York, says
Terra has little to show for its investments. ``They had to catch
up to us, and they didn't achieve it,'' Espuelas says. Nor does he
fear Terra Lycos, Espuelas said. ``We'll be gaining an unfocused
competitor,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nonsense, say Davis and Linares, who argue StarMedia is an
insignificant player next to AOL and Yahoo. ``I have plenty of
local competitors in Germany, Korea and Singapore. But as we map
out a strategy, we don't think about how we'll defeat them,'' Davis
said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Now, along with the foreign competitors, Villalonga must defeat
his challengers in Ma-drid.
</P>
<P>
   Spain's National Securities Market Commission is looking into
whether Villalonga acted improperly when he bought options on a
quarter-million shares in Telefonica in 1998, then sold them two
weeks later, around the time Telefonica began talks with WorldCom
Inc. about a potential alliance. The commission previously had
investigated the matter, and declined to act. Telefonica and
Villalonga deny wrongdoing and say they will cooperate with the
probe.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation follows a series of articles about the options
in El Mundo, a newspaper that supports Spain's center-right
government and once was a Villalonga ally. Observers say the paper
soured on him when Telefonica began talks with Prisa Group,
publisher of rival newspaper El Pais. Also, El Mundo reported on
Friday that Villalonga used a false identity for some stock
transactions. Telefonica called that charge ``absolutely false.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics also cite the divorced Villalonga's appearances with a
girlfriend in Miami, where Villalonga spends much of his time, and
the multimillion-dollar stock options Villalonga offered himself
and other Telefonica managers. News of these options cooled
relations between Villalonga and Prime Minister Aznar.
</P>
<P>
   Yet defenders point out Villalonga has survived plenty of
setbacks in the past. Short of leaving his company entirely,
Dresdner analyst Simon Edelsten in London imagines Villalonga could
just hand over the Telefonica reins and take on a bigger role at
Terra Lycos, helping Davis arrange deals.
</P>
<P>
   Davis calls that scenario ``unlikely'' and predicts Villalonga
will stay in his current job. But he's not central to the deal in
any case, Davis said. ``Our deal is with Bertelsmann and Terra,''
Davis said.
</P>
</TEXT>
