<HEADLINE>
FILTER CONCEPT GUIDES START-UPS INTO PRIME TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH HEALY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Can you trademark due diligence?
</P>
<P>
   One Boston law firm thinks so, and it's telling clients as much
in its bid to provide one-stop service for high-tech start-ups on
the road to venture funding.
</P>
<P>
   G+H Solutions, the new-technology services arm of Gadsby Hannah,
has trademarked its ``Due Diligence Filters,'' a detailed approach
to getting a business plan in shape for prime time.
</P>
<P>
   William Zucker, a partner at Gadsby Hannah and head of G+H, says
the filter concept evolved as the firm sought to help scores of
young companies sort through the intricacies of financial
forecasts, corporate structure, intellectual property and stock
allocations, among myriad other issues. The problem, he says, is
that some clients would pick and choose services (usually to save
money) but end up needing far more help than they thought.
</P>
<P>
   It's a bit like skipping the full $25 car wash in mid-winter _
undercarriage scrubbed, mats vacuumed, and exterior waxed _ and
skimping for the $5.99 quick wash.
</P>
<P>
   ``The `I've already done that' routine doesn't cut it when you
go to the funding stage,'' Zucker says. Now the tech group is
turning away the a la carte clients, because the firm thinks it
leaves clients believing they're ready for the next step when
they're not.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of one client, an online derivatives exchange,
Zucker says the owners weren't willing to buy all the services of
the filter. In particular, they didn't want to review their
ownership guidelines and what size stake they were willing to give
up in exchange for venture funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were pennywise and pound foolish,'' Zucker says. ``Fifty
percent of nothing is nothing _ even if you have a great concept.''
</P>
<P>
   And that wasn't the only trouble, he says. The company had only
a prototype of its product, not a working model. It had holes in
its management team and even in its technology crew.
</P>
<P>
   The firm didn't get the financing round it went on to seek,
Zucker says. And it hasn't yet.
</P>
<P>
   Another client, Lisa McGonagle, founder of ModernParent.com, a
Boston-based Web information and purchasing service, bought into
the filters without a big pitch. She says she needed all the
services the firm was offering, from revamping the financials to
replacing corporate partners that weren't working out. The lawyers
introduced her to United Asset Management Corp. financial chief
Julie Coyle, who's now on her board.
</P>
<P>
   McGonagle's done the friends-and-family money round. Now, she
says, ``We're talking to a big company for a first round.''
</P>
<P>
   Sounds great. But one thing to remember about VCs is they don't
think anybody else is smarter than they are. They trust people they
know, and they trust track records. That's about it. No stamp of
approval from some trademarked filter is going to get them excited.
</P>
<P>
   Says Andy McLane, a veteran of the business and a managing
director at Boston's TA Associates, ``I think the idea is wacky.''
He explains, ``It's the guys doing the investing that are doing the
due diligence.''
</P>
<P>
   Precisely. That's why G+H isn't trying to sell this model to the
venture capitalists, per se. Rather, it wants to convince start-up
clients that they need to book on for a full ride.
</P>
<P>
   What's it cost? That's where the firm hedges. Suffice it to say
you're talking thousands of dollars. How many thousands depends on
how much work the entrepreneur needs done. The question is whether
you can get enough out of the lawyers to make your idea more
valuable to the big investors.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, lots of lawyers will take some warrants in lieu of
cash. See how that figures into the filter.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Beth Healy is a member of the Globe staff. She can be reached by
e-mail at bhealy(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
