<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 LYCOS CHIEF SAYS TELEFONICA DEAL ON TRACK 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For Bob Davis, it's a case of bringing the new economy to the
Old World.
</P>
<P>
   That's the gulf that Davis, the chief executive of Lycos Inc.,
must bridge as he seeks to complete the trans-Atlantic sale of his
Internet portal in Waltham, Mass. to the Spanish telecommunications
giant Telefonica SA.
</P>
<P>
   The deal would combine Lycos with Telefonica's Internet unit to
create a global media player known as Terra Lycos. But even as
Telefonica's controversial chairman, Juan Villalonga, was embracing
Davis at a New York press conference last month, dissent was
brewing in Spain's business and political circles.
</P>
<P>
   Now the deal's prospects have been shaken by this Byzantine
establishment, where Villalonga has alienated many with his
aggressive management and high pay scales. Last week, his foes
helped convince Spanish regulators to reopen an insider-trading
investigation into Villalonga, raising concerns he could be ousted.
The renewed probe drove down share prices in Telefonica, its Terra
Networks unit, and Lycos on fears the merger itself could be at
risk, though Terra shares have recovered since.
</P>
<P>
   The news from Spain may be an unwelcome dose of deja vu for
Davis, who a year ago failed to complete another complex merger
between Lycos and USA Networks.
</P>
<P>
   This time around, Davis says he's got a better arrangement. He
would become chief executive of Terra Lycos, which would have $3.2
billion in cash to fund promotions and acquisitions. The company
also would have access to Telefonica's big telephone and
mobile-phone networks in Europe and Latin America. And it would
boast an alliance with German publisher Bertelsmann AG, whose
properties range from book publisher Random House to Germany's
Stern magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Davis insists the Terra Lycos deal is still on track. He calls
the Spanish government inquiry into the financial dealings of his
partner meritless and insignificant. ``This is just hardball
Spanish politics,'' Davis said. Villalonga has no plans to step
aside, but even if he were to leave the merger would go forward,
Davis said. Villalonga himself wasn't available for comment, a
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Davis's goal is to make it to September or so, when Lycos
submits the merger to a vote of its shareholders. The largest Lycos
holder is CMGI Inc. of Andover, Mass.; its chairman, David
Wetherell, has spoken favorably of the Terra deal but has not said
if he'll vote for it. Late last week, CMGI executives declined to
comment on the Villalonga inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Villalonga's challenge, meanwhile, is to fend off government
investigators and keep his Spanish supporters in line, including
the two banks that control 9 percent of his company. His fate may
be discussed at a board meeting set for Wednesday, said a company
executive.
</P>
<P>
   But if Villalonga and Davis can hang on, analysts say, they
would create a peer of the other online media giants being created
through mergers, such as AOL Time Warner and the combination
announced last week of France's Vivendi and movie studio-owner
Seagram.
</P>
<P>
   To succeed, team Terra Lycos says it must integrate assets
quickly _ heightening the risk from political disruption. Abel
Linares, the managing director of Terra Networks who is slated to
become Terra Lycos' chief operating officer, he's got a simpler
merger to manage than do his online rivals, with less overlap
between business divisions.
</P>
<P>
   By linking Bertelsmann's content with its portal sites
throughout North and South America, Europe and Asia, Terra Lycos
will have to undertake relatively little reorganization, he said.
That's crucial while the loyalties of so many Internet users are up
for grabs. Lycos and Terra, both nimble companies, may be able to
capitalize.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have very good content,'' Linares said of his rivals.
``But the battle will be them with their content or us with our
speed.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The origins of Terra Lycos date to last winter, when bankers
from Lazard Freres, representing Telefonica's Internet unit, called
on Davis to suggest a combination.
</P>
<P>
   With about 30 million unique visitors a month, Lycos was
trailing America Online, Yahoo Inc. and Microsoft's MSN, all of
which had far deeper pockets. Many worried Lycos investors expected
some agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Villalonga saw in Lycos an entry into the US Internet market,
still the world's largest. A merger would fit his ambitions for
Telefonica, a sleepy former state-owned monopoly he was named to
head in 1996. After privatizing it the next year, Villalonga has
been on an acquisitions tear that has sent the company's share
price soaring.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Davis wasn't ready to give away the company he'd built
from scratch. A Dorchester native and former computer salesman for
Wang Laboratories, Davis was brought in by investors in 1995 to
commercialize a search technology that had been developed at
Carnegie Mellon University in Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many online companies, Lycos has a solid business model
based around advertising sales and e-commerce. For the nine months
ended April 30, excluding merger costs, Lycos had net income of
$8.2 million on revenue of $203 million.
</P>
<P>
   Another reason for hesitation was the legacy of the failed USA
Networks deal, scrapped a year ago for lack of support from
shareholders. A central critic was Wetherell, who initially
supported the deal but then renounced it and quit the Lycos board
as the Lycos share price sank.
</P>
<P>
   Burned once, Davis picked up and continued Lycos's original
strategy of using many different brand names, from the Tripod
Website service to Wirednews.com, all with the goal of growing
faster than the Internet as a whole.
</P>
<P>
   So at first, Davis turned the bankers down. He was looking for
what he calls a ``transforming event'' for Lycos. By that he meant
a deal that would both broaden Lycos's audience and give it more
content to distribute in new ways.
</P>
<P>
   Villalonga and Telefonica returned in March with a more
appealing offer: the company would underwrite a stock offering to
raise $2 billion in cash, which Terra Lycos could use for
acquisitions. By April, Bertelsmann also was interested in joining
the arrangement. Bertelsmann had a partnership with America Online,
but it needed a new strategy after AOL announced plans to buy a
competing publisher, Time Warner Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Bertelsmann's agreements with AOL prevented it from buying an
Internet service like Lycos outright. But Bertelsmann would agree
to pay Terra Lycos $1 billion over five years to advertise and
distribute its own brands.
</P>
<P>
   On May 16, in New York, the companies announced the creation of
Terra Lycos, in a deal then worth $12.5 billion. Davis would direct
the operation from his current office in a Waltham office park,
where Lycos now has about 600 employees and plans to add several
hundred more by 2001. At 43, Davis said he's too old to learn
Spanish, but that he'll have plenty of fluent deputies.
</P>
<P>
   The company will have about 3,500 employees in all, spread
across 37 countries, including a major operation in Miami and a new
headquarters in Barcelona.
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts hope both the executives pull it off. ``I think
Telefonica would be crazy to abandon the deal with Lycos, even if
Villalonga left, because it's a fantastic trade,'' said Albert
Richards, a Solomon Smith Barney analyst.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's complicated, but it seems to be where the world is
headed, and it creates a well-funded company,'' said Chase H&AMP;Q
analyst Paul Noglows, who upped his rating on Lycos late last week
even after the renewed probe was announced.
</P>
<P>
   Noglows said he doubts the investigation will sink the deal, and
expects Lycos shareholders will support the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Terra shares rose $2.625 in Nasdaq trading Friday to close at
$40, making the merger worth about $9.5 billion at the end of last
week. Lycos shares fell 19 cents to close at $54.125. Lycos was
trading at $38 before sale rumors began to drive it up in April.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
