<HEADLINE>
SYSTEMS INTEGRATORS BLAMED FOR ONLINE RETAILERS' WOES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEPHANIE STOUGHTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Virgin Atlantic's Web site greets customers with error messages,
a seven-step buying process and distracting graphics that blink and
shimmy across the screen. Wal-Mart, the world's most powerful
retailer, takes its online shoppers on a confusing tour through
unmarked aisles and a slow check-out process.
</P>
<P>
   These companies are far from alone in their online woes. In the
last two years, consumers and investors have rebuked companies
sharply for lumbering online with poorly conceived e-commerce
sites. But a new report says the designers and builders of Web
sites _ the Internet services and consulting firms that have
sprouted around the country _ share much of the blame.
</P>
<P>
   ``These help providers have been working in a market flush with
demand,'' said Christine Overby, an analyst with Forrester
Research. ``There's little incentive for them to improve their
service offerings.''
</P>
<P>
   Dot-coms and established companies alike have come to rely
heavily on Web consulting and services firms to help them succeed
in the booming Internet marketplace. Last year, the industry racked
up $11 billion in revenues, and demand for big technology
consultants is so intense that many would-be customers cannot
afford to hire them.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts believe that the lackluster performance of the Web
services industry has contributed to the ailments of e-commerce
players.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is that it's hurting the new economy,'' said Phil
Terry, chief executive of Creative Good, a New York firm that helps
companies create e-commerce strategies. ``It's making it hard for
the few sites that are performing well to make their case to
investors, as well as the customer who goes to a bad Web site, gets
turned off and stops using the channel.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the year's biggest dot-com flops was Boo.com, a British
Internet apparel store that collapsed last month after burning
through much of its $135 million in start-up funding. Critics say
that Organic Inc. of San Francisco played a role in Boo.com's
downfall by creating a site that emphasized flashy features over
basic merchandising principles.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Organic chief executive Jonathan Nelson said he
was baffled by Forrester's report, which had his company tied for
the lowest position among 40 leading Web services firms. He could
not be reached to discuss Organic's involvement with Boo.com.
</P>
<P>
   For its report, Forrester surveyed 150 companies that help
design and build Web sites, whittling down the number to the top 40
firms. But even the best performers, it wrote, were inconsistent.
</P>
<P>
   Forrester noted that iXL Enterprises Inc. of Atlanta had done
significant work on Virgin Atlantic Airways's Web site, which now
suffers ``serious ills.''
</P>
<P>
   An iXL spokesman declined to comment, but Bill Danylko, the
airline's interactive marketing manager, said his company was happy
with the technology firm's work. He acknowledged, however, that the
site did not always function properly, frequently displaying errors
messages when online customers tried to navigate the Web pages.
</P>
<P>
   At the headquarters of Wal-Mart Stores Inc. in Bentonville,
Ark., executives are none too pleased with their Web site, which
Cambridge Technology Partners Inc. helped overhaul last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, we are not giving our online customers the level of
service that they deserve,'' said Melissa Berryhill, a Wal-Mart
spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Berryhill said she was unable to comment on the company's
relationship with Cambridge Technology. Industry sources say,
however, that Wal-Mart has dropped Cambridge Technology and is
working now with a competitor.
</P>
<P>
   In Forrester's report, few Web services firms escaped criticism.
Even Sapient Corp., a hot technology consultant in Cambridge,
Mass., had at least one displeased customer. The client, a heavy
equipment manufacturer, complained that Sapient built a Web site
that could not handle future growth.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Sapient received the highest grade from Forrester, which
praised its work on easy-to-peruse sites operated by United
Airlines, ETrade, and iWon.com.
</P>
<P>
   There were other bright spots as well. L.L. Bean's successful
site got a helping hand from Digitas Inc., a Boston firm. Another
local company, Zefer Corp., received kudos for building several
efficient e-commerce sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a good experience working with Zefer,'' said Mie-Yun
Lee, founder of Buyerzone.com, a Cambridge online marketplace for
small and midsize businesses. ``I wish they could have gotten up to
speed on our company faster _ but that's a challenge of any
consulting firm.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Web-site builders often face a daunting task in
integrating the various software systems needed to operate an
e-commerce site. And like many of their dot-com clients, they are
straining to retain bright technology workers in a fiercely
competitive job market. Cambridge Technology, for example, has
churned 1,000 employees in less than a year.
</P>
<P>
   Privately, Web services firms say it's not their fault if
customers ignore their suggestions and insist on building clunky
sites. In other cases, clients want to race to cyberspace, despite
warnings that their sites will not be as effective.
</P>
<P>
   A Sapient spokesman, for instance, said the client that griped
about its work in Forrester's report was told that it had two
options. It could wait for a site that would accommodate its
growth, or it could push ahead with a site that met its immediate
needs. The client picked the second option.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Forrester said we made bad choices, it wasn't our
choice,'' she said. ``It was the customer's choice.''
</P>
<P>
   In Wal-Mart's case, the retailer's size, time pressures, and the
number of players involved made the project more of a challenge,
said Peter Ward, Cambridge's director of e-business strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you need to understand is that there were a lot of chefs
in the kitchen,'' Ward said.
</P>
<P>
   The real problem is that those chefs don't always agree on
what's best for their customers, says consultant Phil Terry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
