<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-SUBMARINE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUN SILENT. RUN DEEP. RUN WIRELESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT WEISMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Navy submarines, those stealthy models of undersea technology,
finally have plumbed the Internet. The first e-mail originating
from a submerged sub, the USS Dolphin, was transmitted to shore
over Memorial Day weekend.
</P>
<P>
   It was tapped out and sent from a depth of 400 feet below the
surface of the Pacific Ocean, off California, using an advanced
acoustic modem developed by Benthos Inc. of North Falmouth, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an enabling technology,'' said John L. Coughlin, the
Benthos president and chief executive, who regards the May 26
e-mail as an historic breakthrough with military and commercial
potential. ``For the first time, we can get data out of the water
in real time.''
</P>
<P>
   The company's Benthos ATM 885 Telesonar Acoustic Modem is
roughly the size and shape of a tennis ball can. It is based on
commercial technology similar to that employed for cell phones.
</P>
<P>
   Using specialized software, it encodes data bits from a PC
inside the sub and turns them into acoustical pulses that are sent
out through the ocean. The pulses are received by another modem
mounted on a buoy floating on the surface; from there, they are
transmitted into the Internet as e-mail, first via radio and then
through a cell phone link.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, the Benthos modem can receive acoustical pulses
originating from bases on the shore and convert them back into data
bits that can be downloaded into a PC.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some tones will not propagate through certain types of
water,'' Couglin said. ``And that's really where our technology
comes in. The acoustic modem will actually interrogate the water to
see what's the best way to send the data. It is looking at the
water to determine the best coding and the best speed for
transmission.''
</P>
<P>
   The weather and the conditions of the sea are factors. It is
easier to shoot an e-mail from deep below the ocean to the surface,
for example, than to send it horizontally across the surface in
choppy water.
</P>
<P>
   Submarines already can communicate externally, of course, though
their need to avoid detection poses restrictions. One way they
transmit classified data is by emitting extremely low-frequency
radio waves that can be received only by a secure antennae in the
western United States.
</P>
<P>
   Navy engineers also have modified submarine sonar systems to
send encoded messages on an experimental basis. Subs are able to
talk to one another through UQC underwater telecommunications
systems, limited by range. And they can send data to shore through
conventional radio, but that requires them to stick an antennae
above the surface.
</P>
<P>
   While the Navy sent the e-mail as part of a series of tests
using the Benthos modem, the real purpose of last month's
experiments was to gauge the potential for linking undersea sensors
into a network that can sit on the bottom of the ocean.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're interested in the technology for . . . developing
underwater networking,'' said Joseph A. Rice, principal
investigator for acoustic communications at the Navy's Space and
Naval Warfare Systems Command center in San Diego. ``We'd like to
be able to build and buy underwater sensors that would enable us to
do surveillance of the underwater environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Benthos got into the acoustic communications program last year
when it acquired Datasonics in nearby Cataumet, a leader in
acoustic modems. It will join the Navy in August in another
experiment called Seaweb 2000, in which 32 modems will be set up in
an ocean network over several square miles near Buzzards Bay.
</P>
<P>
   The research that produced the Benthos modem was underwritten in
part by $1.6 million from SPAWAR, the Office of Naval Research and
the Navy's Small Business Innovative Research program, which
encourages contractors to commercialize technology.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy would use the modem and a network of underwater sensors
for military purposes, mainly tracking other countries' submarine
movements. But the technology could have civilian applications in
oil and gas drilling, oceanography and meteorological studies.
</P>
<P>
   The immediate future for undersea e-mailing is murky, however.
Rice said bandwidth constraints make it difficult to transmit
anything other than text, at least for now. And security
considerations would preclude widespread use, if not all use, of
e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time a submarine broadcasts anything, it's at an elevated
risk of exposing its position,'' Coughlin said. ``I don't think
you'll see submariners sending e-mail to their friends and families
any time soon.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
