<SLUG> BC-TECH-POLITICS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TECHNOLOGY LEADERS RELISHING ROLES IN POLITICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; PALO ALTO, CALIF. _ What's the new, new thing in Silicon
Valley? Politics.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, the political pulse of the Valley amounted to
little more than its voting activity _ that is, if harried
high-tech executives could spare the time to make it to the polling
booths.
</P>
<P>
   That's all changing, and technology poobahs are beginning to
relish their new roles as Washington kingmakers and policy pushers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot more fun than you would ever guess it to be,'' John
Kernan, chief executive of Lightspan Inc., said of his involvement
in politics in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   The political awakening of Silicon Valley can be traced back to
1997, when technology companies raised $35 million to fight a state
ballot proposal that would have allowed shareholders to sue
individual executives when their companies' stock prices start
falling. The measure was defeated.
</P>
<P>
   Stoked by their victory, industry chiefs, including Kernan,
decided to continue their political activities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We realized we had to be forceful advocates of issues that
have an impact on us,'' said Eric Benhamou, chairman and chief
executive of 3COM Corp. in San Jose. ``That meant we had to get
organized.''
</P>
<P>
   Benhamou, Kernan and a dozen other technology executives formed
TechNet, a bipartisan lobbying group. They stocked its board of
directors with cyber-luminaries, including John Doerr, a well-known
Silicon Valley venture capitalist; Jim Barksdale, former head of
Netscape Communications Corp.; John Chambers, chief executive of
Cisco Systems Inc.; and, the heads of E-Trade Inc., Genentech Inc.,
and Sun Microsystems Inc.
</P>
<P>
   As a sign of its growing maturity, TechNet earlier this year
hired Jeffrey A. Modisett, former attorney general of Indiana, to
be its Democratic general counsel. Aside from hosting fund-raisers,
TechNet offers ``Politics 101'' training courses for neophytes.
They learn everything from how to track issues and organize visits
to Capitol Hill to identifying key lawmakers for specific issues.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Silicon Valley is a critical stop on the campaign trail.
And local techies are stepping right up, playing host at
$1,000-a-plate fund-raisers and private meet-and-greet soirees.
Last week, both presidential candidates made pilgrimages to Silicon
Valley. George W. Bush was hosted at Chambers's home, while Vice
President Al Gore was feted at the home of Joel Hyatt, who teaches
entrepreneurship at Stanford University and is founder of Hyatt
Legal Services.
</P>
<P>
   Even local pols from other states are stopping by. Over the
weekend, Massachusetts Lieutenant Governor Jane Swift made the
rounds in San Jose to promote her policies on Internet privacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``This trip was an opportunity for me to speak with the best
minds on the issue of privacy,'' Swift said. ``We also want to make
sure that Governor Celucci and I remain on the cutting edge of that
(high-tech) industry so we can keep pace with public policy
initiatives that affect the new economy.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not just the money that brings candidates here. It's also
the desire to be associated with the movers and shakers of the
vaunted new economy.
</P>
<P>
   What candidates find here, however, is not politics as usual.
The Valley is ``aggressively bipartisan,'' in the words of Lezlee
Westine, vice president and Republican general counsel of TechNet.
Chambers, for example, supports both Bush, a Republican, and US
Senator Dianne Feinstein, a California Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   ``We look at the issues, not at the party line,'' said Benhamou.
He said he supports Gore because ``I am convinced he has a deep
understanding of the issues, and he is in broad agreement with the
issues we advocate.''
</P>
<P>
   Longtime technology executive Mitchell Kertzman, a well-known
political gadfly in Massachusetts until he moved to Silicon Valley
several years ago, believes the Valley's bipartisan bent is due to
the fact that both Republicans and Democrats have done a good job
tailoring their rhetoric to appeal to the cyber-elite.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both parties are saying the same things,'' said Kertzman, now
chief executive of Liberate Technologies Inc. in San Carlos, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   While politics is not an essential part of the business scene
yet, Kertzman says, that's is changing. ``Politics is a
relationship business as well as a money business, and you need to
be engaged long-term,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Alex Pham is a Globe reporter covering Silicon Valley. She can be
reached by e-mail at pham(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
