<DOCNO> NYT20000627.0053 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 10:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6014 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-CASTANEDA-COLUMN-ADV2     06-27 1595
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CASTANEDA-COLUMN-ADV26-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$ADV26 
 MEXICO'S OPPOSITION PARTIES HAVE SOWN THEIR OWN DEFEAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use Monday, May 26, and thereafter.)  
 ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's monthly CASTANEDA COLUMN. For more
information about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _
or becoming a client of the CASTANEDA COLUMN _ contact one of the
New York Times Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of
the text.) 
 By JORGE G. CASTANEDA  
 c.2000 New York Times Special Features  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although there will be many lessons to be learned from Mexico's
presidential election on July 2, we may have a notion of some of
them already.
</P>
<P>
   The most important is to recognize the consequences of last
year's failure of the two opposition parties to join forces. Their
reasons then were:
</P>
<P>
   1) An alliance wouldn't be possible.
</P>
<P>
   2) An alliance wouldn't guarantee victory.
</P>
<P>
   3) There were too many political differences dividing the two
parties.
</P>
<P>
   The first was unalterably true. But with the campaign's
evolution, the other two have since been disproved.
</P>
<P>
   Firstly, had there been one candidate representing an allied
opposition _ presumably Vicente Fox (PAN) since, according to
polls, he outgunned the PRD's Cuauhtemoc Cardenas by a ratio of
2-to-1 _ chances for a victory would have been enhanced.
</P>
<P>
   This is particularly so in a campaign where, right now, the two
frontrunners (Fox and the PRI's Francisco Labastida) are running
neck and neck. Had there been an opposition alliance where Cardenas
conceded to Fox as candidate, nobody today could deny that it would
have given Fox an overwhelming advantage and ultimately, victory.
</P>
<P>
   All the polls show the split vote is a committed one. But the
polls also show that the second choice for president among the
majority of those votes is Fox.
</P>
<P>
   This was also confirmed in a secret PRD internal survey
conducted between March and June, in which voters overwhelmingly
confirmed Fox, over Labastida, as their second choice. Over the
four-month period, the percentages for Fox increased concurrently
with the progress of the campaign, which would have eventually
given Fox a 5-point lead, and a sure win.
</P>
<P>
   The third reason _ political incompatibility _ has also been
disproved by evolving campaign events. Up till now _ and there is
no reason to expect any change in the last days before the election
_ the divergences between the two opponents have been personal: Fox
is a liar, Cardenas an anachronism; Fox is intolerant, Cardenas is
an egoist.
</P>
<P>
   Or historical: The Cristera War (a 1920s uprising against
government imposed anticlerical laws) vs. the Mexican Revolution;
for or against reforms implemented by former President Carlos
Salinas. But there has been nothing of substance or about
platforms, such as privatizing Pemex, legalizing abortion,
rescinding NAFTA, or re-establishing state ownership of Telmex, the
banking and steel industries, for example.
</P>
<P>
   Since none of these topics were debated, the difference between
the two candidates is moot, and so they failed to prove any
political incompatibility.
</P>
<P>
   Out of this political stumbling, emerges another, pivotal fact
that was highlighted by Cardenas' brief and belated skirmishes over
a second round of voting. If Mexico had a constitutional electoral
second balloting (as exists in most countries with presidents,
including the United States, through the primaries of the two big
parties) Fox would have a very strong possibility of defeating
Labastida in the final election.
</P>
<P>
   But why isn't there a second round vote? The PRI and the
government, supposedly, didn't want it; the PAN accepted the
decision without real conviction and only to please Fox, and the
PRD didn't say anything.
</P>
<P>
   There is, however, another version of truth behind these
suppositions.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, in November 1998, Giovanni Sartori, the eminent
political expert and professor emeritus at Columbia University, had
a two-hour discussion with President Ernesto Zedillo on the virtues
of second round balloting, particularly for a country like Mexico.
It would give the country stability, legitimacy and a soundness, he
apparently said, which would neutralize in the long run any
disadvantage it could have for the ruling party in the short run.
</P>
<P>
   An impressed Zedillo suggested he present his ideas to the
opposing parties and their probable candidates. But after doing so,
Sartori disclosed that the followers of Cardenas were absolutely
opposed to second balloting.
</P>
<P>
   As to why Zedillo didn't promote it, even if Cardenas was
opposed, the answer is simple: With the full approval of the two
opposition parties, Zedillo might have been able to push through a
constitutional amendment, imposing it on a reluctant PRI wary of
the probable defeat it would mean _ a party which was, and still
is, totally opposed to such second round balloting. Asking Zedillo
to act against his party's interests and without the total support
of the opposition was too much.
</P>
<P>
   If that is the true story, the ostensible reasons for Cardenas'
rejection of a second round are now known.
</P>
<P>
   In the first place, Cardenas' estimates were wrong: in 1998 he
thought he would be the forerunner in the 2000 presidential
campaign. So a second balloting might mean taking away his victory
of the first round. In the second place, he thought (once again
mistakenly) that if there were a second round, PAN and PRI would
unite in a conservative alliance and defeat him in the second
ballot. He clearly never thought of a third possibility: that he
might not be a candidate in the second round and might have to
throw his votes to one of the other two candidates.
</P>
<P>
   But another possible motive for his opposition to the measure
might have been based on an even worse possibility: What to do if
he had, in the end, to decide on the lesser of two evils, between
PRI and PAN, between Fox and Labastida?
</P>
<P>
   This third possibility was so awful that it could not be
considered. Or even better: avoid creating the conditions that put
him in such a position. At least this way the decision would be
taken in pectore, implemented in private, far from the startled
looks or autonomous voters.
</P>
<P>
   And, as a matter of fact, Cardenas actually made his decision in
the solitude of his introversion and with full fidelity to his
obsessions and roots. This happened probably in the first days of
March, and surely no later than the first week of April, when he
received the results of the secret polls, which showed that the
proportion of votes for Fox and Cardenas was still the same
(2-to-1).
</P>
<P>
   Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, a man of few decisions in his life, but all
of them transcendental, faced the terrible choice that history and
reality presented: He was not going to be president of Mexico. He
couldn't win this time, and there was no possibility of a new
attempt in 2006, when he would be 70. Nevertheless, he still had in
his hand the power to decide who would be Mexico's next president:
Labastida or Fox.
</P>
<P>
   There's no doubt in my mind that Cardenas, faced with the
Hamletian drama he was living, suffered horribly, argued with
himself, agonized and doubted, but finally opted for the road of
his phantoms. Over and above the animosity between himself and Fox,
and of the greater certitude offered by a deal _ tacit or explicit,
suggested or signed _ with Labastida, Cardenas chose the system and
the PRI. To do otherwise would mean, to him, betraying his father,
President Lazaro Cardenas, and his legacy _ the most noble and
glorious of Mexico's 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   Surely, Lazaro Cardenas would never have understood how his son
could anoint a ``reactionary,'' a ``counterrevolutionary'' for
president.
</P>
<P>
   So, understandably, it's not easy to blame Cardenas for his
decision. It is, without doubt, the most loyal to his true past, to
his life and to his refusal to betray an everlasting and crushing
icon of Mexican politics.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, by refusing to negotiate with Fox, he may have
led his party to imminent collective suicide. The PRD may still
have some chips to deal right now, but come July 3 they will have
lost their value.
</P>
<P>
   Worse than any historical mistake, it is a betrayal engendered
by historical blindness.
</P>
<P>
   (Jorge G. Castaneda is a political scientist, biographer and
chronicler of Mexican politics, economics and society. Castaneda is
the author of books including ``Companero: The Life and Death of
Che Guevara'' (1997), ``The Mexican Shock'' (1995) and ``Utopia
Unarmed'' (1993). He is a professor of political science at the
National Autonomous University of Mexico and at New York University
and lives in Mexico City and New York City. His essays and
commentaries have appeared in Foreign Affairs, The New York Times,
The Atlantic Monthly, Inter-American Dialogue and many other
publications.)
</P>
<P>
