<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SOLVING-CONFLICTS (Schenectady, N.Y.) _ For more than 120 years,
the Navajo and Hopi tribes have fought bitterly over 1.8 million
acres in the northeast corner of Arizona. Jamie Manygoats, a
Navajo, hopes to succeed where Congress and the courts have failed
by using an algebraic solution to end the long and deadly conflict.
By ANDREW BROWNSTEIN.
</P>
<P>
   NADER-CAMPAIGN (San Francisco) _ Fresh off the Green Party's
presidential nomination, Ralph Nader energetically ripped the
Republican and Democratic front-runners and said his record as a
corporate watchdog and political reformer should impress voters _
as long as he reached them. The consumer activist called his
candidacy a ``serious run,'' unlike his shoestring bid four years
ago. By DEMIAN BULWA.
</P>
<P>
   CHROMOSOME-18 (San Antonio) _ It took 16 years for Torrie Bryant
to realize she was not alone. Bryant, born with a chromosomal
abnormality that affected her hearing and muscle tone, grew up
without knowing there were children with similar problems. But
Bryant, now 20, said her life changed about four years ago when she
learned about the Chromosome 18 Registry and Research Society, a
one-of-a-kind organization that is headquartered in San Antonio. By
NICOLE FOY.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MAKEUP (San Francisco) _ Heads up, girls . . . the '50s have
returned. At least on the face. Makeup for fall is on the retro
side, concentrating on elegantly groomed and definitively sexy
eyebrows, smoked-up eyes and blood-red lips. By CYNTHIA ROBINS.
</P>
<P>
   TWISTED-GUIDEBOOK (San Francisco) _ The newly printed ``San
Francisco Bizarro: A Guide to Notorious Sights, Lusty Pursuits, and
Downright Freakiness in the City by the Bay'' contains no fewer
than 192 entries: from offbeat churches (John Coltrane's, Anton
Lavey's Church of Satan) to odd tours (of historic Black Panther
sites), newsworthy sites (where Rudolph Nuryev was busted for pot
and where Jonathan Winters wigged out) to off-the-beaten-path
tourist attractions (the Vibrator Museum, the Tattoo Hall of Fame.)
By JANE GANAHL.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   YAHOO-GOOGLE (San Francisco) _ In a marriage made in goofy name
heaven, Yahoo Inc. has tapped Google Inc. as its primary search
engine. Under the agreement, Google will provide an underlying Web
search engine to Yahoo's Web directory and navigational guide.
Yahoo expects to integrate the services within the next 30 days. By
ALAN T. SARACEVIC.
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE-GROCERS (San Francisco) _ The virtual aisles of the
online supermarket industry got larger with the purchase of
HomeGrocer.com Inc. by Webvan Group Inc., in a deal valued at more
than $1 billion. Two of the more successful _ but yet not
profitable _ online grocers decided to join forces rather than
compete for customers in the growing industry, with Webvan clearly
the dominant player. By VICTORIA COLLIVER.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BKN-TEENAGER (Undated)_ Five years after Kevin Garnett's giant
leap for teen-kind, another man-child heads for the promised land.
The critics have been muted, if not thoroughly silenced, because at
18, Darius Miles looks like a sure thing. No less an authority than
Michael Jordan, Washington's general manager in absentia, has said
that Miles deserves to be the No. 1 pick in Wednesday's NBA draft.
By GWEN KNAPP.
</P>
<P>
   FBC-SHRINE-GAME (San Francisco) _ A five-year agreement has been
reached to bring the East-West Shrine football game to Pacific Bell
Park, beginning Jan. 13, 2001, in a move designed to help
attendance. By DWIGHT CHAPIN.
</P>
