<HEADER>
A6046 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-MONEY-TALK0628-COX     06-27 0766
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEY-TALK0628-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Midyear's a good time for tax-lowering steps
 &HT;    By Hank Ezell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Making promises to reform the tax laws is often
harmless. Politicians do it all the time.
</P>
<P>
   Grouching about the iniquities of income tax is usually OK.
People do it on talk radio all the time.
</P>
<P>
   But cutting your tax bill requires more than just talk, and it
is something you have to do for yourself.
</P>
<P>
   Midyear is a good time to start. Some actions you should
initiate quickly. Others you can put off if you're willing to face
frantic scrambles at year's end.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some suggestions for a midsummer tax checkup:
</P>
<P>
   Check your withholding. If you get a big refund each year,
you're having too much withheld from each paycheck.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to make sure you're not lending your money to the
government,'' said Doug Liptak, a certified public accountant with
Frazier &AMP; Deeter. ``You won't get any interest, and you could have
used the money yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   At the other extreme, you may not be withholding enough to cover
your tax bill. If your underpayments are too large, you could be
hit with penalties.
</P>
<P>
   To get back to limits, ask your employer for the paperwork
required to complete a new W-4 form. You will also get a worksheet
to help figure it out.
</P>
<P>
   If your income changes substantially _ typically from
self-employment income, stock options or bonuses _ you may need to
consider making estimated tax payments throughout the year.
</P>
<P>
   Deduction bunching. This means packing as many deductible items
as you can into a single year.
</P>
<P>
   Certain itemized deductions have to exceed an established
threshold before you can claim them. For example, you can claim a
deduction only on medical expenses that exceed 7.5 percent of your
adjusted gross income. Looking ahead, you may find that you will
benefit from getting elective medical work done this year. That's
not something you want to leave until the holiday period.
</P>
<P>
   If possible, says tax analyst Mildred Carter of CCH Inc., ``You
should plan your deductions so you can claim them in the years when
you have the highest tax rate.''
</P>
<P>
   The Financial Planning Association, which represents certified
financial planners, warns that jiggering like this may make you
vulnerable to the alternative minimum tax.
</P>
<P>
   That's complex enough that you may want to take it up with an
expert. You won't be alone. More than half of individual taxpayers
hire a professional to do their taxes. Another alternative is to
check the resources below for detailed information.
</P>
<P>
   Retirement savings accounts. Individual retirement accounts and
401(k) plans can help cut your tax bill.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Brennan, a manager in KPMG's tax practice in Atlanta, points
out two reasons for maxing out a 401(k): You get to deduct your
contribution from your taxable income now, and you get to defer
taxes on the earnings your investments make.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're not contributing the maximum, you should consider
doing it,'' Brennan said. The maximum is 15 percent of your salary
but not more than $10,500 for the year.
</P>
<P>
   If you've topped out and still have more disposable income, he
suggests contributing to a traditional or Roth IRA.
</P>
<P>
   Review your investments. If you have sold winners and have
capital gains, you may want to offset that income by selling losers
that you have been meaning to sell anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Liptak suggests another precaution: checking how much of a tax
liability your mutual funds are likely to dump on you when they
make capital gains distributions at year-end. If it's big, you may
want to consider selling the shares before the distribution and
switching the money to more tax-efficient investments.
</P>
<P>
   Marriage plans. Two-income families have to worry about the
marriage penalty and may want to tie the knot after December.
</P>
<P>
   If only one spouse will work, it may be beneficial to marry
before the year is out.
</P>
<P>
   Charitable giving. If you plan to donate appreciated stocks,
Brennan thinks it may be a good idea to do it now.
</P>
<P>
   ``You may be better off, since stock prices are so erratic,'' he
said. ``You would do that if you think the value of the asset might
decrease.''
</P>
<P>
   You could also consider making non-cash charitable donations
before the holiday rush begins, Liptak suggested.
</P>
<P>
   Record keeping. Don't wait until next spring to organize your
tax records. If you've had trouble finding receipts for deductible
expenses, for example, the time to set up an organized storage plan
is now.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
