<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN0628-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sit back and relish the memories
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ Chairs have always been a significant part of
my life _ mainly, I guess, because I'm lazy and much prefer sitting
down to standing up. Somehow, my history seems defined by a
progression of chairs _ rather like reading the rings of an ancient
tree.
</P>
<P>
   The first chair in my life was a cane-seated rocker that came
with the suite (what the matching stuff was called back then) of
walnut furniture in my parents' room. There was a bed with a curved
footboard and a bed lamp on the headboard, a night table, a vanity
with a long mirror in the middle and two shorter ones on the sides
that swung back and forth so Mother could see all of her hair, a
caned bench, a chiffonier with Daddy's suits hanging in it and his
socks in the top drawer, a dresser with a mirror, one straight
chair, and the rocker.
</P>
<P>
   Mother didn't sing or tell stories, but she did rock. I remember
the rhythmic creaks, and because she was short, the tap of her toes
on the wood each time the chair rocked forward and her feet met the
floor.
</P>
<P>
   Daddy had an old Morris chair and footstool on one side of the
fireplace, right next to the GE radio with the green ``eye'' on the
front that showed when it was properly tuned. In 1941, that was
where he explained war to me _ as well as he could. He'd fought in
the first ``big one'' and was too old for this one.
</P>
<P>
   Every evening we shared his chair and listened to Gabriel
Heater's commentary on the news of the world brought to us by Kreml
hair tonic. It's where I first heard of men named MacArthur and
Nimitz, and strange places called Tulagi and
</P>
<P>
   Tarawa. And it's where I was told that Billy Kelly, the boy
across the street whose folks had been so proud of him when he
played ball for Ohio State, wouldn't be coming home any more to
play catch with us little kids.
</P>
<P>
   The ``hall chair'' was a green, plush-covered relic, retired
from an old Pullman car. My father bought it at auction and it took
three men to carry it to the upstairs hall.
</P>
<P>
   On school mornings, I'd pick up the clean dress mother had laid
on the chair arm for me, and put my brown teddy bear, raggedy from
too much love, in its place, ready for the next bedtime.
</P>
<P>
   It was the chair where my father waited for mother to finish my
bath, and for me to holler, ``Okay, Daddy. Come dry me!'' I
remember how he'd wrap me up and lift me onto his lap, reminding me
as he dried carefully between each toe that
</P>
<P>
   if I didn't always do that, they'd rust.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, Putsy the cat slept in the green chair. Once he got
sick on it. So did I, once. Then when I was 12, we moved and left
the green chair in the hall.
</P>
<P>
   When my son was born, I bought a bentwood rocker. He and I
giggled and rocked and sang until he no longer fit my lap. It's in
his old bedroom now _ maybe waiting to go live at his house when
it's needed.
</P>
<P>
   When he was 12, a flowered armchair and ottoman moved into his
room. There's a blue stain on one side of the seat cushion where a
ballpoint leaked when he sat on it. The old chair is so badly worn
now that the welting is hanging out. The upholsterer is coming for
it next week and I'm hoping none of the memories go with the old
cover.
</P>
<P>
   Chairs, I think, are like good friends, and over the years we
learn to cherish the comfort both give us. Occasionally, I even
wonder if maybe there's such a thing as a lifetime allotment for
chairs...and how many I still have to go.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison, Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or e-mail: eschuett(at)nwonline.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
