<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'Monday Night' QBs get _ what? Brains over brain damage?
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABC has made a horrible choice.
</P>
<P>
   That's what analysts said when the network introduced former
``Saturday Night Live'' regular Dennis Miller as the next Howard
Cosell.
</P>
<P>
   I must agree. Dennis Miller _ bright, articulate, funny and
apparently football-savvy _ is someone I'd watch.
</P>
<P>
   And that should disqualify him.
</P>
<P>
   The analysts know what demographic ``Monday Night Football''
most needs, and it's not me.
</P>
<P>
   It's the World Wrestling Federation crowd, the New World Order
crowd, the ``Monday Night Nitro'' crowd.
</P>
<P>
   The Rush Limbaugh crowd?
</P>
<P>
   This _ the Limbaugh-WWF connection _ is not one I'd have made
until the other day. Then I heard an ``entertainment analyst'' say
it: The pro wrestling crowd is what ``MNF'' might have had in mind
in auditioning Limbaugh, the toad king of the airwaves.
</P>
<P>
   The wrestling crowd accounts for much of the exodus from
one-time sky-high ``Monday Night Football'' ratings, said the
analyst. And, he suggested in advance of ABC's decision, Limbaugh
might be the vehicle to get those viewers back.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, I did not make this Rush-wrestling connection.
Granted, I associate Limbaugh with a certain raw-meat crowd. But it
dines selectively _ on the reputations of liberals and
Clintonistas, rather than ``any and all comers.'' (For instance,
when Republicans have sex scandals, soft-money scams or cushy
dealings with the Chinese, Rush napkins-up and excuses himself from
the table.)
</P>
<P>
   If what ``Monday Night Football'' needs back is the pro
wrestling crowd, it seems that the analyst in question may have
taken one too many pile drivers, noggin-wise. Rush Limbaugh? Dare I
say it? He's too urbane.
</P>
<P>
   If its aim was to pander to the wrestling crowd, seemingly all
ABC would have to do is get Stone-Cold Steve Austin, or a goon
named Goldberg, or silver-haired Dusty Rhodes. Any number of pro
wrestling stars would be willing to wax salivary at its microphone.
</P>
<P>
   One really wonders, when analysts say that programmers need to
start thinking like a pro wrestling crowd, if thought is what they
have in mind. Pro-wrestling is not about thought. It is more on a
glandular level. One would say that sports, particularly football,
is all about glands anyway. May be.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is, what analysts say now applies to sports commentary
(``any and all comers'') increasingly applies to such a thing as
governing. Obviously, that is what a plurality of Minnesota voters
decreed last general election when they made a pro wrestler
governor.
</P>
<P>
   In the weeks after his election, reactions to Jesse ``The Body''
Ventura alternated between ``what a terrible mistake'' and ``at
last, a truly candid, brutally honest politician.''
</P>
<P>
   To be brutally honest, the pendulum has swung back to position
A: ``terrible mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   But, you see, when the object is pandering to a crowd rather
than delivering thoughtful policies in a complex world, who better
than a pro wrestler to deliver?
</P>
<P>
   Back to ABC, which in its quest for someone nontraditional and
provocative has made a mistake. It's not that Dennis Miller isn't
great. He is. I will watch and listen with interest.
</P>
<P>
   That's the problem for ABC. I'm not the target audience it
wants. Listen to the masses it misses. The best man for the job was
one with some blood on his lapel.
</P>
<P>
   John Young is the Opinion page editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald
E-mail: jyoung(at)wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
