<TEXT>
<P>
   DISPATCHES FROM DREAMSVILLE: ``Eating out'' once meant an old
table under an apple tree
</P>
<P>
   (''Dispatches from Dreamsville'' is an occasional series in
which readers share with Cox Newspapers senior writer Joe Murray
their memories of growing up in small-town America. Back then, or
at least the way we remember it, life was like a dream.)
</P>
<P>
   By Dora Matthai
</P>
<P>
   Special to Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   It seems that everyone is eating out these days, either at
fast-food places, buffets, carry-outs or fancy restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   Sixty-five years ago, when I was a little girl growing up on a
108-acre farm outside Hillsboro, Ohio, life was nothing like it is
today.
</P>
<P>
   My parents, two sisters, a brother and I lived in a small
three-room house with no electricity, running water, bathrooms or
telephone.
</P>
<P>
   Dad promised to build a new house after he finished the barn.
But the money was never available, and he wouldn't buy anything
``on time,'' as credit was referred to in those days. Dad felt it
was a disgrace to owe money.
</P>
<P>
   But we did get to ``eat out'' occasionally, though our idea of
eating out was lunch on an old table under the apple tree in our
front yard.
</P>
<P>
   Our mom would spend the entire morning preparing lunch (we
called it dinner) while the rest of us worked in the fields.
</P>
<P>
   When we'd come in at noon, all hot and tired, she'd have fried
chicken, roasting ears, fresh green beans, cole slaw, mashed
potatoes and gravy, hot homemade bread, and lemonade or iced tea _
plus hot berry cobbler and homemade ice cream (hand-cranked) for
dessert. That was gourmet dining at its best.
</P>
<P>
   We would eat so much we'd try to sneak a little nap under a
shade tree somewhere, but dad would find us and then it was back to
the field we'd go.
</P>
<P>
   We also looked forward to occasional family trips into town in
our Model-A Ford to sell eggs, cash the milk check, buy the few
grocery items that we couldn't raise, and to visit our
grandparents, always bringing meat and fresh vegetables from the
farm.
</P>
<P>
   Since we didn't want to burden them by arriving at lunchtime, on
those special days we also ``ate out.''
</P>
<P>
   Mom would purchase a pound of old-fashioned red bologna and a
loaf of store-bought bread, rare treats for farm folks. Then dad
would drive us out to a big shade tree on the outskirts of town for
a picnic.
</P>
<P>
   That was our idea of fast food.
</P>
<P>
   All these years later, my sister and I can still taste those
wonderful red bologna sandwiches every time we pass the same old
shade tree on the way to the cemetery where mom and dad are buried.
</P>
<P>
   (Dora Matthai lives in Springfield, Ohio.)
</P>
<P>
   (If you have a story to share, send it to ``Dispatches from
Dreamsville,'' c/o Joe Murray, Cox Newspapers, P.O. Box 151108,
Lufkin, Texas, 75915; email, jmurray(at)txucom.net. If your article
is used, you will receive $25. For other Dreamsville stories, visit
http://www.coxnews.com/newsservice.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
