A6065 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-DANCE-PRIZES-NYT &LR;      06-27 0722
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DANCE-PRIZES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT BALLET COMPETITION, YOUTH AND ENERGY BUT NO GOLD MEDALS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JACK ANDERSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Three bronze medals and three silver medals were
awarded to young dancers on Sunday night at Alice Tully Hall at a
ceremony concluding the Sixth New York International Ballet
Competition. The competition attracted 48 dancers from 18
countries, and the gala was the culmination of a three-week period
during which all participants learned and were judged on an
identical repertory. They also had opportunities to show works
chosen on their own.
</P>
<P>
   A panel of dancers, teachers and choreographers awarded bronze
medals in the women's division to Hye Min Hwang (South Korea) and
Emi Hariyama (Japan). A men's bronze medal went to Rene Salazar
(Brazil). Sarah Lamb of the Boston Ballet received a women's silver
medal; Ilya Kozadayev and Mikhail Ilyin (both of Russia) won men's
silver medals.
</P>
<P>
   This year there were no gold medals for dancers. But an honorary
gold medal for lifetime achievement went to Arthur Mitchell, the
artistic director of Dance Theater of Harlem. The presentation was
made by Frederic Franklin, the former star of the Ballet Russe de
Monte Carlo, who for several decades has been an adviser to many
companies, including Mitchell's. Upon receiving the award,
Mitchell, quoting Martha Graham, said that ``dancers are angels of
God.''
</P>
<P>
   The competition was founded in 1984 by Igor Youskevitch, who
died in 1994, and Ilona Copen, who continues as executive director;
Eleanor D'Antuono serves as artistic director. To promote high
standards, its directors and judges have always been chary about
awarding gold medals. The competition has been held every three or
four years and, of the past five events, two were without
gold-medal presentations.
</P>
<P>
   The competition is open to dancers between the ages of 17 and
24. All must learn three assigned pieces of choreography, but those
works are not announced until the dancers arrive in New York.
</P>
<P>
   This year's selections were Balanchine's ``Tchaikovsky Pas de
Deux,'' coached by Deborah Wingert; the grand pas de deux from
Petipa's ``Sleeping Beauty,'' coached by Winthrop Corey, and the
``Giggling Rapids'' sequence from Alvin Ailey's ``River,'' coached
by Mucuy Bolles. Lupe Serrano, Stephen Pier and Luis Fuente taught
the dancers during the three-week period. Liliane Montevecchi, who
has been a star of Roland Petit's Ballets de Paris and of such
Broadway shows as ``Grand Hotel'' and ``Nine,'' served as master of
ceremonies. The awards ceremony was followed by a performance by
this year's winners, other finalists and some winners and finalists
from previous competitions. The dancers were eager and attractive,
yet several performances had rough edges. And some of the works
presented that were not part of the competition syllabus were
choreographically undistinguished.
</P>
<P>
   But Hariyama offered a delicate variation from ``The Sleeping
Beauty.'' Hwang was secure in a solo from ``Le Corsaire,'' although
her dancing could benefit from a greater sense of flow. Salazar and
Priscilla Yokoi, another Brazilian dancer, were gleeful in
``Giggling Rapids.''
</P>
<P>
   Lamb brought dignity and radiance to the ``Sleeping Beauty'' pas
de deux, for which her partner was Zack Grubbs, also of the Boston
Ballet.
</P>
<P>
   Partnering Mirai Noda of Japan, Ilyin looked at home in the
``Tchaikovsky Pas de Deux.'' Kozadayev leaped lightly througn a
solo from Petipa's ``Rest of the Cavalry.''
</P>
<P>
   Other finalists who danced were Marnie Shapiro, Emily Grizzell
and Joel Prouty (United States), Rosa Antuna (Brazil), Kenny Wang
(Taiwan), Neli Beliakaite (Lithuania), Cong Ma (China), Diana
Stetsura (Belarus), Eivar Sair (Venezuela) and Altanhuyag Dugarai
(Mongolia).
</P>
<P>
   Dancers from previous competitions who participated included
Christina Theryoung, Venti Petrov, David Kierce and four dancers
now with American Ballet Theater: Anna Liceica, Gillian Murphy,
Gennadi Saveliev and Carlos Molina.
</P>
<P>
   The performance by Liceica and Molina of the Black Swan adagio
from ``Swan Lake'' was especially notable for its elegance and
sense of drama.
</P>
<P>
   Competition judges were Cynthia Gregory, chairwoman, and Karen
Kain, Carla Fracci, Jean-Christophe Maillot, Julio Bocca, Boris
Eifman, Zhao Ruheng and Rudi van Dantzig.
</P>
</TEXT>
