<SLUG> BC-YAHOO-GOOGLE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     YAHOO ADDS NEW SEARCH ENGINE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ALAN T. SARACEVIC  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOUNTAIN VIEW, Calif. _ In a marriage made in goofy name heaven,
Yahoo Inc. has tapped Google Inc. as its primary search engine.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, Google will provide an underlying Web
search engine to Yahoo's Web directory and navigational guide.
Yahoo expects to integrate the services within the next 30 days.
</P>
<P>
   Financial terms of the multiyear agreement, announced Monday,
were not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yahoo selected Google because they share our strong consumer
focus,'' said Jeff Mallett, president and chief operating officer
of Yahoo. ``Google has clearly demonstrated its ability to scale
with the rapid growth of the Web, making it a particularly good
match for Yahoo as we continue to expand our global presence. We
are very pleased by this agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo had been using the search engine of Inktomi Corp. for
general Internet search queries. Yahoo officials said Monday they
would continue to use Inktomi for corporate search engine
applications.
</P>
<P>
   From Google's end of the deal, this was a match made three years
ago when the company's founders first met Yahoo co-founder David
Filo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been wanting to do this deal for a long time,'' Google
chief executive and co-founder Larry Page told a news conference at
the corporate headquarters in Mountain View. ``Filo actually
encouraged us to start this company three years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Google officials also released its new index of Web sites,
containing more than 1 billion site locations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
