<DOCNO> NYT20000627.0083 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 12:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6126 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-ANGOLANS-ACTIVISTS-AR     06-27 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANGOLANS-ACTIVISTS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (a and i coding)  
 ACTIVISTS WORRY ABOUT CRIME'S LURE FOR ANGOLANS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANCIE LATOUR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROCKTON, Mass. _ Looking at Eulidio Monteiro, it's hard to tell
where the Cape Verde in him ends and the Angola in him begins.
</P>
<P>
   His face burns caramel, part almond brown from his Cape Verdean
mother, part deep coffee from his Angolan father. His hair doesn't
so much coil as wave, weaving a story of two peoples whose shared
history is evident even worlds away, in a Brockton parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``We come because Cape Verdeans were here,'' said Monteiro, 22,
who left his parents behind and came to the United States in 1998
from the Angolan capital of Luanda. ``They say, `Come to Brockton,
it's nice.' So, we come.''
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of miles of African coastline separate the Cape Verde
Islands from Angola. But common culture has long united the former
Portuguese colonies, cemented by a huge migration of Cape Verdeans
to Angola in the 1950s. Now, a growing stream of Angolans, whose
homeland has been ravaged by civil war, has followed Cape Verdeans
to the United States seeking stability.
</P>
<P>
   But in the Boston area _ the largest hub for Cape Verdeans, and
now Angolans, in the United States _ activists in the midst of a
losing battle against Cape Verdean youth violence are driving a
major effort to keep young Angolan men from following some of their
cultural kin into a cycle of crime, prison, and deportation.
</P>
<P>
   The need for prevention was punctuated 11 days ago in Boston,
when five Cape Verdean teenagers allegedly chased down a Dorchester
teenager and one of them, a juvenile, shot him to death. The
shooting capped six months of increasing violence in Dorchester and
Roxbury, as well as Brockton, Randolph, and Rhode Island.
</P>
<P>
   So far, activists say, incidents among Angolans have remained
low, maybe a dozen in the past three years, when the flow of
Angolans to Massachusetts began in earnest.
</P>
<P>
   But the number of incidents is growing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want the number to stay small,'' said the Rev. Filipe
Teixeira, an activist whose background is part Angolan and Cape
Verdean. ``But we are already seeing some serious incidents
happening with Angolans, including the aggravated felonies and drug
charges that classify them to be deported.''
</P>
<P>
   Teixeira and other Cape Verdean community leaders as well as
police have stressed that the ongoing violence among Cape Verdeans
involves only a small group of feuding teens.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Immigration and Naturalization Service, six
Angolans were deported for criminal reasons from 1993 to 1997, the
latest years for which figures were available. About 75 Cape
Verdeans were deported in that period.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the INS office in Boston, Paula Grenier, said
it was unclear whether any Angolans were in detention awaiting
deportation.
</P>
<P>
   Among the most recent deportations of Angolans, Teixeira said,
was that of Bruno Edison, 21, of Brockton, whose court records show
that he began working as a salesman, then piled up misdemeanors
before being convicted on assault and firearms charges. He was
deported six months ago, according to Teixeira.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is so much activity going on with Cape Verdeans and guns
in the Brockton area,'' Teixeira said. ``This is where a lot of
Angolans are landing. They get there with no language, no housing,
nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   As they gravitate to Cape Verdeans for help with everything from
apartments to home-cooked hot sauce, Angolans are particularly
vulnerable to falling into violence, Teixeira and others say.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the new arrivals are men 16 to 30 years old. Almost all
come without their parents and with few language skills, banding
together to rent affordable apartments.
</P>
<P>
   Many are more than familiar with guns, having served in or
narrowly escaped serving in a 30-year-old civil conflict between
guerrilla groups and the government.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to give these kids support and really watch how they
are mixing with some of these Cape Verdean youth,'' said Herberto
Agostinho, owner of Angolan BBQ in New Bedford. ``We have to make
them aware of the laws in the US, to steer them away from
violence.''
</P>
<P>
   Agostinho, 31, of Fairhaven, is an elder of this young
community. He, his wife, Selma Agostinha, and Teixeira founded the
Angolan Association of the USA, which seeks to end war in Angola as
it shepherds Angolan youth who have left war behind. The group of
about 50 began meeting in April.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in his restaurant, Agostinho said that helping Angolan
youths is a delicate dance to avoid stereotypes between the two
close cultures.
</P>
<P>
   Agostinho and Teixeira have quietly encouraged Angolans to leave
Brockton and to find housing in New Bedford or other nearby areas.
At a meeting of the association last month, leaders went to pains
to explain how teens should avoid trouble without talking about the
trouble itself.
</P>
<P>
   Underlying the conversations about Cape Verdeans and crime, many
Angolans here say, is a longstanding belief that Cape Verdean
culture has tended more toward violence and drug abuse than Angolan
culture _ both at home and abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Mendes, 18, an Angolan who lives in New Bedford and works
at Agostinho's restaurant, said he has tried to draw a line between
himself and some Cape Verdean youths.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some are my friends, but some are always in trouble,'' he
said. ``They don't think what they could make by working hard is
enough. They want to make more. People in Angola are different.
Even at home, if you look at Cape Verdeans and Angolans in Portugal
or back home, we have never gone to this violence.''
</P>
<P>
   Monteiro, born of Cape Verdean and Angolan parents, said he
hopes the new association will be a uniting force to galvanize the
Angolan community _ something many say is missing among Cape
Verdeans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very sad,'' he said. ``We hear about Cape Verdeans who
come here and get into drugs. I don't know why. It's a thing I
don't like to think about, because they help us, too.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
