u a BC-SCI-QUESTIONS-BOS &LR;      06-27 0271
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-QUESTIONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY ISN'T THE MOON AS VISIBLE IN THE NORTH? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. Why is it that we never see the moon in the north as we do in
other sectors? R.N., Tempe, Ariz. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. It is a remarkable fact about our solar system that the Earth
and all the planets move in orbits that lie in almost the same
plane.
</P>
<P>
   The moon in its orbit around the Earth also lies in more or less
the same plane as the one that contains the Earth's orbit about the
sun, and the Earth itself rotates in a plane that is also about the
same.
</P>
<P>
   What all this means is that you could get a pretty good picture
of how everything in the solar system moves by imagining that
everything sits in one plane all the time, as if it were all
happening on a table top.
</P>
<P>
   When you're in the Northern Hemisphere, above the plane, you
sort of look ``down'' on the moon _ it appears to be in the South.
When you're in the Southern Hemisphere, you're below the plane and
you sort of look ``up'' at the moon, and you see it in the Northern
Hemisphere.
</P>
<P>
   The picture is a little more complicated if you're near the
equator, as the plane of the moon's orbit is really tilted by about
5 degrees, so within 5 degrees of latitude of the equator the moon
can appear a little North or South depending on where you are and
when you look.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail questions at drknowledge(at)globe.com; or send fax to:
617-929-9263, or a letter to Dr. Knowledge, in care of The Boston
Globe, Health/Science Section, P.O. Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107.
Please include your initials and hometown.
</P>
</TEXT>
