<HEADER>
A6128 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-SOC-GOLDCUP-CHASTAIN-     06-27 1109
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-GOLDCUP-CHASTAIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUCCESS HASN'T SPOILED BRANDI CHASTAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are times when it gets old, when every Mr. Original from
two blocks over yells ``Hey, Brandi!'' and yanks his shirt over his
head. What she did, she said, was temporary insanity. Brandi
Chastain won the World Cup with a penalty kick and that's how
soccer players celebrate big goals. They pull off their jerseys.
</P>
<P>
   ``It happened,'' she said, nearly a year after the exuberant
moment that put Chastain on the cover of Time, Newsweek, and Sports
Illustrated. ``I did it. I'm not unhappy I did it. I think it was a
liberating moment for myself. I think, hopefully, it was a
liberating moment for others, male or female.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't as if Chastain planned to put herself on center stage
with 40 million people watching. The coaches told her she was
kicking fifth and it happened that her kick was the deciding one.
What if Julie Foudy had been kicking fifth? What if Chastain had
been fourth?
</P>
<P>
   ``Who knows what I would have done if I had been fourth,'' said
Chastain. ``Maybe something as silly as I did. I don't know. I
don't think you can go back and say, what if I hadn't been? There's
no reason to.''
</P>
<P>
   What if Buzz Schneider hadn't come off early at Lake Placid in
1980 and Mike Eruzione hadn't come over the dasher to beat the
Soviets? Would there still have been a Miracle on Ice? Would
someone else have scored? ``All I know is, I was in the right place
at the right time,'' Eruzione would say. ``And I did the right
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Chastain is the female Eruzione, with one critical difference.
Eruzione never played another hockey game. Chastain is still lacing
up her boots, still playing friendlies against the likes of
Iceland, trying to make it back to Olympus this summer and pick up
another gold medal for the trophy case.
</P>
<P>
   It's all but certain that Chastain will be in Sydney in
September and highly likely that she'll be starting again on the
back line. But with a new coach (former teammate April Heinrichs)
shuffling new young faces in and out of the lineup, nothing is
assumed. Not in June.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every player needs that motivation to remind them that this is
something that is not a right,'' said Chastain. ``It's a privilege
to be on this team and you have to work hard every day to secure
your position. So it's good to not know whether it's going to be
the same 11 or not. Unknowing is really pushing us hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Chastain has been on the team, off the team, and back on again.
She has been moved from forward to defense. She is 31 and playing
on rebuilt knees. Chastain may be a household name with a couple of
million dollars' worth of endorsements, but if Heinrichs thinks she
can't help the team, she'll be watching the Games on TV, and
Chastain accepts that.
</P>
<P>
   She was on the inaugural Cup-winning team with Heinrichs, but
coach Tony DiCicco left her off the 1995 squad and Chastain watched
her former teammates lose in the semifinals from a sports bar in
Salt Lake City. When some players went on strike later that year
over Olympic bonus money, DiCicco invited Chastain back and she
ended up playing every minute of the Games.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't like Chastain was just another ponytail on last
summer's Cup squad, but for most of the tournament the spotlight
was focused elsewhere: on Mia Hamm, on Michelle Akers, on Briana
Scurry.
</P>
<P>
   And for a few horrifying minutes in the quarterfinal against
Germany, after Chastain crossed wires with Scurry and put the ball
into her own goal, it seemed that she'd be in the sports screwup
pantheon along with Bill Buckner, Wrong Way Riegels, and Roberto de
Vicenzo: Own-Goal Brandi.
</P>
<P>
   So there was a lovely symmetry to it when Chastain walked to the
spot on the floor of the Rose Bowl. ``Hollywood,'' her mates had
dubbed her, always ready for her close-up. She had posed nude for
Gear magazine, bantered with David Letterman. ``Do you want a
kick?'' assistant coach Lauren Gregg asked her, when she was making
out the list. ``Yeah,'' Chastain said. ``Do you think you can make
it?'' ``Yeah.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no way to know that Scurry would block China's third
attempt. No way to know that Chastain would be taking The Kick. And
no time to think about what making it would mean. Chastain simply
teed up the ball, swung her left foot and blasted a shot just
inside the right post that had lunging keeper Gao Hong reaching for
air.
</P>
<P>
   Chastain screamed in delight, ripped off her jersey, swung it
around her head _ and then the next half-dozen months became a
blur.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I slept very much,'' she said. ``I don't think I
ate very much. I think it was a pure adrenaline rush. It was just
working on overdrive.''
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, everybody wanted a piece of Ms. Sports Bra. Nike and
Volvo and Power Bar signed her to endorsement deals. There were TV
appearances, speaking engagements, an Air Bud movie to shoot. Tiger
Woods wanted to play nine holes with her.
</P>
<P>
   Some teammates admitted to a twinge of envy. ``We were asking,
`Why not me?' '' said Tiffeny Milbrett, who got little more than a
pat on the back for her goal against the Chinese that won the
Olympic gold medal.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't as if Chastain planned it that way. The jersey thing
was spontaneous.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just the event and the moment and it surprised
people,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   It could have been Foudy, it could have been any of them, and
the Girls of Summer have come to understand that. What they did
together was bigger than any one of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anybody minds now how much attention Brandi
gets, how much Mia gets, how much I get,'' said Milbrett. ``Now
we're all getting attention as a team.''
</P>
<P>
   Chastain just happened to be the woman on the big screen when
the fireworks went off. And maybe it was happy chance that she
doesn't mind being asked . . . and asked . . . and asked about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoy meeting new people,'' she said. ``I enjoy having an
opportunity to talk about this great game of soccer. Before, I used
to have to chain them to their chairs so they'd listen.''
</P>
<P>
   Chastain remembers coming home from China after winning the 1991
Cup and finding that most of her countrymen didn't even know
America had a women's team. She remembers NBC not showing the
Olympic gold-medal match four years ago. So if the world is going
to freeze-frame her forever in one celebratory moment, she won't
argue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still haven't watched the game from start to finish,''
Brandi Chastain says. ``I haven't had a chance. But I will one of
these days. Probably after the Olympics are over.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
