<DOCNO> NYT20000627.0088 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 13:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6132 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-SCI-GENOME-DECODE-BOS     06-27 1273
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-GENOME-DECODE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GENETIC CURES: THE BEGINNING OF A NEW SCIENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG AND RAJA MISHRA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the announcement that scientists have completed a rough
draft of the human genome, the race to the starting line is over.
</P>
<P>
   Now the post-genomic marathon officially begins cheered on by
high expectations for possible cures to major diseases, new drugs
for treating a host of problems such as depression and hypertension
based on a patients' individual genetic makeup, and new ways to
diagnose illnesses, perhaps even before symptoms arise.
</P>
<P>
   The speed with which these new products and therapies can be
tested and brought to market has just been accelerated, but they
still won't arrive overnight.
</P>
<P>
   The avalanche of human genome data being made available now
actually tells researchers relatively little, other than that
nature still has many secrets to reveal.
</P>
<P>
   Like someone who has found all the individual letters contained
in a copy of The Boston Sunday Globe, scientists cannot make sense
of the information until it is arranged in proper order. Merely
sequencing the genetic code does not tell us what all the genes do
or how the cells are formed. Nor does the genome reveal how
diseases begin or how we age. Before genetic drugs can be developed
to attack a specific disease, researchers must understand exactly
how that gene causes the disease in the first place. By
understanding how genes work and studying how they go awry,
scientists expect to develop new medical therapies that attack the
underlying causes of disease vs. many of today's drugs that only
treat the symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   And by offering better treatments than existing medications, the
makers of gene-based drugs expect to command premium prices. Even
when scientists know that a defect in a single gene is responsible
for a disease, such as Huntington's Disease, Duchenne muscular
dystrophy and cystic fibrosis, the complexity of determining how
they are linked to multiple genes scattered among 60,000 to 100,000
genes in the genome has made it difficult to find an effective
medical treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``In cystic fibrosis, where you are trying to restore a function
in the body that has been lost turns out to be more difficult than
in diseases where you want to replace something or slow down a
process that is out of control, such as in arthritis,'' said Josh
Boger, founder and chief executive of Vertex Pharmaceuticals Inc.
whose Cambridge, Mass. company has used genomic data to develop
several drugs now in clinical trials.
</P>
<P>
   Boger and others, however, predict the first series of
gene-targeting drugs will hit the market, in part, because of
discoveries from existing genetic code. These include therapies to
treat cancer, asthma, certain wounds and aging, where certain genes
have been identified as playing key roles in these conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just at the beginning of understanding how widely you
can scan through this information and extract the gold nuggets,''
said Kellie Watson, manager at Feinstein Kean Healthcare, a
Cambridge consulting company for biotech firms.
</P>
<P>
   Some of those chunks are stretches of genomic code linked to
particular diseases, such as diabetes, obesity, cancer tumors and
Alzheimer's disease.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Joel F. Habener, director of molecular endocrinology at
Massachusetts General Hospital, has located six genes involved in a
common form of diabetes. He suspects there are many other and
continues his search. Once he finds all the diabetes-related genes
in the genome, he can stop his search with confidence.
</P>
<P>
   This security _ which has never really existed _ is one of the
genome's biggest pluses.
</P>
<P>
   After identifying the genes, population tests will be conducted
to see how the genes mutate to cause diabetes, then on to the
development of drugs that can correct the genetic problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're several years away, maybe five, from bringing a
drug to market,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And the genome assures that the drugs will be safe. Take
Rezulin, which Habener calls a ``miracle'' diabetes drug. It was
recently taken off the market because several hundred people had
serious reactions to it. This was simply because something in their
genetic makeup clashed with the drug. Having the genome map will
allow tests to be developed to catch such side effects in advance.
</P>
<P>
   On the flip side, drugs work better on some people because of
their genetic makeup. So, drugs can be tailored to work best with a
particular person's physiology _ so-called designer drugs. Genetic
diagnostics could provide scientific confirmation that one drug
will work better than another, thereby organizating and
accelerating the process of matching drugs for all sorts of disease
with appropriate patients or groups of patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now its pretty much trial and error with drug
efficacy,'' Habener said. ``But it's astonishing how fast this
field is developing.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, knowing how individuals react to specific medicines and
what these drugs might do to prevent future illnesses will change
the practice of medicine. Already there are chips the size of
quarters that will be able to screen for 6,000 genetic conditions
in a single person. The chips will eventually hold a person's
entire genetic code and will be able to reveal at the molecular
level whether particular genes are turned on or off.
</P>
<P>
   Later this year a personalized genetic test to predict whether
skin cancer will spread in a person recovering from the disease
will be launched by Millennium Pharmaceuticals Inc. of Cambridge
and Becton Dickinson Co. It is the first of seven cancer diagnostic
tests the two companies plan to develop.
</P>
<P>
   But learning which genetic diseases and defects an individual
faces raises some profound ethical, legal and social concerns.
</P>
<P>
   For example, who protects the privacy of people who submit their
genetic information to scientists and doctors? And, if doctors spot
certain defects or genetic predisposition to diseases through
interpretation of a patient's genetic makeup, will they be
obligated to inform the patients, their families, their employers
or insurance company?
</P>
<P>
   Last year, federal legislation called the Genetic Information
Nondiscrimination in Health Insurance Act was introduced but the
bill has not been acted on.
</P>
<P>
   Medical ethicists have questioned whether health-care providers
should be required to obtain written informed consent before
proceeding with a genetic test. Similarly, should testing
laboratories be required to obtain an assurance that informed
consent has been obtained before providing test services?
</P>
<P>
   There also are fears that employers might disqualify an
individual from certain jobs. Genetic tests can reveal whether a
person is a disease carrier as well as the likelihood of passing on
a genetic condition to their children. The Americans For
Disabilities Act, however, offers some protection from workplace
discrimination for people with genetic predispositions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The gene has become more than a piece of information, it has
become a cultural icon, a symbol, almost a magical force,'' George
J. Annas, chairman of the health law department at the Boston
University School of Public Health, stated in his recent book
``Some Choice: Law, Medicine and the Market.''
</P>
<P>
   ``To the extent that we accord special status to our genes and
what they reveal,'' he wrote, ``genetic information is uniquely
powerful and uniquely personal and thus merits unique privacy
protection.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Globe staff reporter Richard Saltus contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
