<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 13:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6136 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MUSIC-METALLICA-BOS &LR;      06-27 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-METALLICA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METALLICA, ON HIATUS, COULDN'T PASS UP THE CALL OF THE ROAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM SULLIVAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The summer is here and Metallica _ the world's most popular and
progressive-minded heavy metal band _ was supposed to be on
vacation, part of a yearlong plan to Not Be Rock Stars and, then,
eventually, work up some new material come 2001.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't quite work out that way. Instead, Metallica headlines
a multiband bill that includes Korn and Kid Rock, called the
``Summer Sanitarium'' tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured out the difference between a year on and a year off
is that when you're off they come to you versus you having to go to
them,'' says drummer and de facto band spokesman Lars Ulrich.
``Whoever they may be. So, we're sitting there in March and we get
a phone call from somebody who was very interested in putting
Metallica out on the road for a couple of weeks this summer.
Initially, we weren't all that keen on it, but we sat down and
realized that in some way the essence of this band is going out and
playing live, sweating, acting, all that stuff. And what appealed
to us was to go out and play a short run of dates. The days of
going on the road for four years at a time are not that appealing
anymore.'' (This tour runs just three weeks, and all shows are
outdoor events _ some at stadiums, some at racetracks.)
</P>
<P>
   The guys in Metallica _ singer-guitarist James Hetfield,
guitarist Kirk Hammett, bassist Jason Newsted and Ulrich _
discussed what bands they should bring along and opted, says
Ulrich, ``for people that we care about, have respect for, and find
musically intriguing. It wasn't so much about `Let's put this great
big package together.' It was more about `We're going on the road,
and let's see who wants to join us.' Then, all of a sudden, you get
the two biggest other rock entities, Korn and Kid Rock, who want to
come along for the fun, and all of a sudden it became a different
thing. Which is cool because we haven't really done this thing for
a while.'' Last time: A tour with Guns N' Roses (remember them?)
that hit Foxborough in September of 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once in a while, you have to step up to this level,''
continues Ulrich. ``I think the buzz on this thing is enormous.
Without putting too much of a `selling hat' on, this really is an
opportunity, if not of a lifetime, then at least to see three or
four of the biggest bands in the country all play together.'' Note:
This tour needs no promotional help. It's sold out. And Metallica
has had a big airplay hit with ``I Disappear,'' from the ``Mission:
Impossible 2'' soundtrack.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the great thing about being in a band like Metallica,''
Ulrich says of the 18-year-old San Francisco-based band. ``We can
go from playing stadiums to arenas to clubs to your neighbor's lawn
all in the space of a week.''
</P>
<P>
   Another buzz has involved Metallica's stand against Napster,
which enables people to easily download music from the Internet for
free. ``I am sort of surprised the way this whole thing blew up
over the past eight weeks,'' Ulrich says, adding that a supposed
``backlash'' toward the band, the most vocal of many Napster
critics, hasn't occurred.
</P>
<P>
   The group has had but two personnel changes over the years: They
sacked guitarist Dave Mustaine, who went on to form Megadeth, early
in the game. And Newsted replaced founding bassist-writer Cliff
Burton, who died in a van crash in September 1986. The band
snatched up Newsted from the group Flotsam and Jetsam.
</P>
<P>
   The show will, as usual, feature some pyrotechnics. One of the
highlights of a Metallica show has been a ferocious strobe-lit and
smoke-filled rendition of ``One,'' the antiwar song based on Dalton
Trumbo's book. ``People know when they see Metallica they're going
to get their money's worth,'' says Ulrich. ``You know you'll get
something visually to complement what we're doing _ without it
being crass and without it taking away from what we're doing.
There's not going be landings of a space shuttle inside Foxboro
Stadium or anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Metallica is not a band for the meek. And neither are the others
on the bill, which includes Powerman 5000 and System of a Down.
Might it get rough out in the crowd? ``I guess it could,'' says
Ulrich, ``but it can get rough at political rallies. It gets rough
outside abortion clinics. Anytime you put 50,000 people together
and you turn the temperature up to 90, you have the potential for _
whatever. But I think it's unfair to just throw that in the
direction of `That only happens at a Metallica-Korn show.' ''
</P>
<P>
   After the tour ends, Ulrich says the band members will chill _
Hetfield may hunt in Argentina, Ulrich plans to take his son to the
park in Santa Barbara a lot _ and reconvene in January ``to get
back to ultimately doing what this is really all about, which is
creating and formulating new music and new ideas.'' On their
downtime, Ulrich says the band members don't socialize much,
although he and his kid did participate in an Easter egg hunt at
the Hetfield home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of us still being together is the fact that we all give
each other some space,'' says Ulrich. ``If we didn't, I think this
band would have collapsed quite awhile ago.'' And whatever tension
is there within the band, Ulrich says, tends to benefit the music.
</P>
<P>
   Metallica can be a serious band _ it tackles knotty subjects,
both personal and political. It recorded ``S &AMP; M,'' a tremendous
live album last year, with accompaniment by the San Francisco
Orchestra. Still, the band members know about living it up and
pushing the extreme, onstage and off. It nicknamed itself
Alcoholica in the early days, but Ulrich says, ``as opposed to your
Boston boys up there (Aerosmith) we were just fortunate enough to
never have personalities that went too far. We never had addictive
personalities to the point it affected what else we were doing.
It's all about balance. You know what your limits are and you find
an awareness and understanding of those and you're OK. . . .
There's nobody here that goes to AA meetings or anything yet. We
still have our moments. We can still hang in there with some of
these younger kids.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
