<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLUMN-POP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNPOLLUTED HIP-HOP A REFRESHING NEW RAP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With their back-in-the-day precision scratching and classic
rhymescapes recalling such rap luminaries as A Tribe Called Quest,
EPMD, De La Soul, and Cold Crush Brothers, it's tempting to call
Jurassic 5 and Dilated Peoples old-school hip-hop.
</P>
<P>
   And many already have. The Source calls Jurassic 5 an
``old-school styled hip-hop group,'' while the Miami Herald noted
that even the cover art _ a Los Angeles subway station _ for
Dilated Peoples' major-label debut, ``The Platform,'' ``evokes a
New York rap album from a previous decade.'' Certainly, both ``The
Platform'' and Jurassic 5's ``Quality Control'' are reminiscent of
sounds that might have spilled from a boombox in the late 1980s and
early 1990s, when hip-hop had moved from novelty to the new Sound
of Young America.
</P>
<P>
   The old-school tag immediately places them in the lofty company
of The Roots, Fugees (will Wyclef, Lauryn Hill, and Pras ever make
another record together?), Common, Mos Def, and the Black Eyed
Peas. But I've never much cared for the label, which makes such
groups seem more like imitators instead of innovators. Whether
intended or not, it implies hip-hop groups like Dilated Peoples
(DP) and Jurassic 5 (J5) are just throwbacks repackaging history
with no sense of the present or flava for the future.
</P>
<P>
   It's an undermining distinction that all but says ``This is your
grandfather's hip-hop,'' as pristine and quaint as a parlor game _
and it ignores the fact that DP and J5 have produced two of the
best hip-hop CDs of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, you won't find either group on magazine covers or
see their videos in heavy rotation. They won't be chatting with
Carson Daly on MTV's ``Total Request Live,'' and you won't hear
kids from Boston to Berkeley sprouting such tunes as DP's ``Ear
Drums Pop,'' or J5's ``Dop Woo.'' And while both albums have been
available for several weeks and have received enthusiastic reviews,
they haven't made much of a splash on the charts yet.
</P>
<P>
   That may be because of what DP and J5 are not _ namely, members
of the fool-school of hip-hop where rappers waste their breath and
our time talking about fast cars and even faster women, or spinning
nonsense about the ice dangling from their skinny necks, and the
gold and platinum in their ragged mouths.
</P>
<P>
   Nor do these groups have anything to do with the increasingly
cruel-school of hip-hop where murder, misogyny, and mayhem rule.
They don't subscribe to the brutality that mars way too many rap
albums, where rappers pathetically boost their manhood and record
sales by dogging women, boy bands, and gay folks.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they weave rhymes that incorporate such disparate
images as the Harlem Renaissance and cultural figures like David
Lynch and Randy Newman. These are CDs for hip-hop heads who refuse
to acquiesce to the incessant pollution of their music by those who
see only dollar signs in controversy.
</P>
<P>
   Both DP _ DJ Babu and rappers Rakaa and Evidence _ and J5 _ DJs
Nu-Mark and Cut Chemist, and rap masters Akil, Zaakir, Marc 7even,
and Chali 2na (yes, J5 has six members) _ hail from Los Angeles,
and have been underground heroes of the West Coast hip-hop scene
for years. Like fellow Left Coast rappers, the Pharcyde, DP and J5
steer clear of all those hometown cliches about guns, hos, 40s,
low-rider Chevys. Instead of old-school _ and what could be older
at this point than spewing all that mess about bullets and blunts _
both groups talk about the state of the world in a way that is
sparkling, fresh, and new, quite unlike anything else in hip-hop
these days.
</P>
<P>
   On ``Doo Wop,'' the hip-wiggling first cut off ``Quality
Control,'' J5 lets the world know what they are _ and aren't _ all
about:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(poetry style &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A lot of these kids think that commercial
</P>
<P>
   Is rocking fly suits and jewelry
</P>
<P>
   But we can rock shows with no rehearsal
</P>
<P>
   With the rebels of rhythm and unity
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's a declaration that could apply to both DP and J5, who have
the talent, honesty, and savvy to continue to forge hopeful, smart,
positive directions in rap. Frankly, that's not old-school at all _
that's true-school hip-hop.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Renee Graham covers the pop scene for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-27-00 1310EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
