<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIVE IT UP FOR YOUR RED SOX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It is June 27, the sixth day of summer, and the
baseball season in Boston is already over. The Red Sox are not
going to the playoffs. If you want to see a real postseason team
around here, you'll have to wait for Rick Pitino's young and
exciting Celtics to begin their season in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Why did it take me so long to figure this out?
</P>
<P>
   The Sox are clearly the worst team in the American League. They
have only 91 games remaining, and I don't know if that's enough
time to make up the massive 2 1/2-game gap that separates them from
the first-place Toronto Blue Jays. Excuse me. The
(itals)mighty(unitals) Toronto Blue Jays.
</P>
<P>
   I wish I lived in Toronto so I could see the Jays play every
day. Not only do they play well, they play in a lovely,
retractable-roof stadium that looks as if it is related to the Mir
Space Station. The place is carpeted with lush artificial turf.
It's paradise. The sorry Sox play in an antiquated, 88-year-old
park. It has a manual scoreboard, natural grass, a towering green
wall in left, and, on clear nights, views of MIT and Beacon Hill.
Isn't that terrible? That's fitting, because the Sox are terrible,
too.
</P>
<P>
   Since May 1, the Sox have lost 12 games by one run. They have
played 50 games in that time, so that means they are currently in a
rut in which they lose by a run every four days. They have won two
one-run games since the first of May. If they had come up with a
single in half of those 12 one-run losses, they would be sitting
atop the AL East this morning. They aren't. It should be obvious,
then, that Dan Duquette has done a poor job of constructing this
team.
</P>
<P>
   Duquette claims he went to Amherst College, but there are some
alums there who swear he is behaving like one of the Ephs of hated
rival Williams. Do you realize that Duquette traded Carl Pavano and
Tony Armas Jr. for Pedro Martinez? What an awful deal for the Sox!
Pavano and Armas have combined for 142 innings and 10 wins.
Martinez has thrown 106 innings and produced nine wins. In the last
couple weeks, his ERA has soared from 0.99 to 1.44.
</P>
<P>
   The guy is a 21st century Teddy Higuera. You remember Higuera,
the talented Brewers pitcher who was always hurt. Martinez is the
same way. He's overrated.
</P>
<P>
   He has a sore oblique muscle now and has given up a total of
nine home runs this season, six in his last two starts. He gave up
26 homers in 1998, when he had an ulcerlike condition; he won 19
games that year. He had a sore back in October, barely held the
Cleveland Indians scoreless and hitless in six innings of playoff
relief, and baffled the Yankees in Game 3 of the American League
Championship Series.
</P>
<P>
   (If the guy were really as good as everyone says, why did he
have to pitch in relief?)
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Martinez is hurt again should prove that he is too
small to have a long career. He is only 5 feet 11 inches and 175
pounds. His slight build is directly related to his current
problem. And don't tell me that a big man _ 6-4, 205-pound pitcher
Steve Avery _ was once troubled by the same injury; that
information contradicts my Martinez-is-too-small harangue.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Dr. Timothy Kremchek said that common remedies for sore
side muscles include stretching and rest. Kremchek is the team
doctor for the Cincinnati Reds, one of Avery's former employers.
Stretching and rest doesn't sound as scary as, say, Tommy John
surgery. But do you want to trust this Kremchek character? I mean,
he's only an orthopedic surgeon.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez insists that he is not hurt. When the oblique muscle is
sore, twisting and turning, which are the staples of a pitcher's
delivery, can become painful. Symptoms are a loss of velocity and
control.
</P>
<P>
   But on Sunday, Martinez suggested that some folks have become
entangled in overanalysis. Today, it is not unusual when someone
hits a home run. Baseballs stripe stadium skies like moonlets.
Martinez happened to give up three moonlets Sunday in Toronto,
including one that tied the game.
</P>
<P>
   You ever see John Wasdin do that?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad that I gave up those five runs, so you don't think
I'm a robot,'' Martinez said Sunday. ``It's almost relaxing for me,
so you think I am normal.''
</P>
<P>
   He is normal. And it is completely miserable in New England.
Forget about the playoffs. Forget about the street festival
atmosphere in Kenmore Square. Forget about the bunting lining the
ancient walls of Fenway. The Sox won't be playing in mid-October.
</P>
<P>
   They are too weak. Nomar Garciaparra could hit .370 and Carl
Everett could hit 40 homers. Pedro Martinez could miss a start and
still have his win total in the high teens. Ramon Martinez could
win 14 games and Derek Lowe could save 35 games. Jose Offerman and
Troy O'Leary and Brian Daubach could remember how to hit again.
</P>
<P>
   It won't be enough.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Jays are too good. The Yankees appear to be
unstoppable. In the National League, the Atlanta Braves are
nonpareil. Their closer, John Rocker, is a compassionate man known
for speaking out on injustice. When he rides the No. 7 train in New
York, he doesn't discriminate. He also likes Times Square.
</P>
<P>
   Other cities have fun. There is no fun here. It's not the Fourth
of July and the season is done. Do you know how hard it is to make
up 2 1/2 games? It could take an entire week. Maybe even two.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Michael Holley is a Globe columnist. He can be reached by e-mail
at holley(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-27-00 1312EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
