<HEADER>
A6139 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-AUTHOR-FEIGEN-BOS &LR;      06-27 1902
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHOR-FEIGEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RENOWNED ART DEALER FEIGEN RELISHES BAD-BOY IMAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK FEENEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``There's so much money out there,'' Richard Feigen
says, ``and there are very few objects.'' As one of the world's
foremost dealers in Old Master painters and drawings, few people
are in a better position to know either fact than Feigen is.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Milken thought highly enough of him to propose a $200
million junk bond offering in the mid-'80s to finance his operation
(Feigen declined). Works sold by his firm, Richard L. Feigen &AMP; Co.,
hang in 106 museums, and among his private clients is the financier
Saul Steinberg, who is currently selling 60 works in his
collection, worth an estimated $52 million, through Feigen
(pronounced FIE-ghen).
</P>
<P>
   ``He certainly cuts a figure in the New York and international
art world, as great a figure as anyone,'' says Ivan Gaskell,
Margaret S. Winthrop curator of the department of paintings,
sculpture, and decorative arts at Harvard's Fogg Art Museum.
</P>
<P>
   Feigen also cuts a figure in the world of transatlantic
aviation, and that fact (or, rather, what underlies it: a sense of
command and unwillingness to take no for an answer) helps explain
his singular status _ part grandee, part bad boy _ in the upper
reaches of the art world.
</P>
<P>
   This fact comes to light while Feigen's sitting in his office
(oak paneling, inlaid floor, Turkish carpet, floor-to-ceiling
bookcases with oversized shelf space to accommodate his many art
books _ and, just so no one confuses it with a Regency gentleman's
library, an iMac and espresso machine, too), which sits atop the
chateau-style townhouse on the Upper East Side where his gallery is
located. Feigen's delivering outrageous opinions and scandalous
stories: both the on-the-record kind to be found in his new book,
``Tales From the Art Crypt,'' and some off-the-record ones only
marginally more outrageous and scandalous.
</P>
<P>
   An assistant pokes her head in to ask about getting a painting
to a client. Its size means shipping might be a problem. Feigen
knows what to do. Find a big-enough case, he tells her. ``Bring me
the case, put it in, then I will tell you if you can bully it onto
an airplane.''
</P>
<P>
   He uses the verb so matter-of-factly a visitor almost laughs.
Presumably Feigen has bullied a few pictures onto planes in his
time?
</P>
<P>
   ``You bet,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once I had a great early Italian painting, worth $8.5 million.
I knew I'd have a problem getting it on the plane in Paris, so I
took the Concorde. Although the Concorde is a small airplane, the
crew is very attentive to passengers. So I figured I'd be better
off, talking this on, than with a bigger plane. Well, it did work.
But the painting wouldn't fit _ literally wouldn't fit _ in the
cabin, so the pilot took it up in the cockpit.''
</P>
<P>
   Feigen turns 70 in August, but it doesn't show. ``Very
dynamic,'' is how he's described by Jack Kilgore, the president of
Jack Kilgore &AMP; Co., a New York gallery specializing in Dutch and
Flemish Old Masters. ``There's no one like him. There's a certain
kind of charisma he has.''
</P>
<P>
   Kilgore, who used to work for Feigen, recalls the time his
then-boss ``had a director and a curator in his office _ from the
Kimbell and Met, I think _ looking at a painting by Claude Lorrain,
and there was Richard screaming at his Porsche mechanic over the
phone. They were listening to this and would start to leave, and
he'd motion for them to stay. It was very funny. He's always doing
two or three things at the same time. You watch it and think, `How
can he do that?' But he does.''
</P>
<P>
   Feigen has craggy-handsome looks somewhere between those of
Charlton Heston and Elizabeth Taylor's onetime husband, US Sen.
John Warner. Neither the Hollywood nor Washington reference is
gratuitous. Feigen was in a movie (Michael Douglas outbids him for
a $2 million painting in Oliver Stone's ``Wall Street'') and he has
family on Capitol Hill (Sen. Carl Levin and Rep. Sander Levin, the
Michigan Democrats, are his cousins).
</P>
<P>
   Politics comes naturally to Feigen. He worked behind the scenes
to get Jane Alexander appointed head of the National Endowment for
the Arts, in 1993, and was active in the campaigns of John Lindsay,
Eugene McCarthy, and George McGovern. Feigen's liberal politics _
and brusque manner _ earned him the rare, if unenviable,
distinction of being filleted by Tom Wolfe in ``Radical Chic'':
``somehow Radical Chic reaches its highest, purest state . . . as
Richard Feigen, in his tuxedo, breaks in to ask (a Black Panther
leader), from the bottom of his heart, `Who do you call to give a
party?' ''
</P>
<P>
   (Thirty years later, the question has switched to ``Who do you
call for a blurb?'' The answer _ surprise _ is Tom Wolfe, a glowing
paragraph from whom adorns the dustjacket of ``Tales From the Art
Crypt.'')
</P>
<P>
   Feigen lives with his second wife and twin stepchildren in a
Fifth Avenue duplex and Westchester County estate. (He also has two
grown children from his first marriage.) In residences, as in
trade, he's in the heart of the heart of the New York swirl. Yet
he's a native Midwesterner who very much remains a Chicago guy:
tough, no-nonsense, a little full of himself, not afraid to swagger
a bit, profane as well as polished.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know every block of that city,'' he says with pride. ``If I
get tied up in traffic getting in from the airport, I know exactly
how to go to duck it! That's my hometown, and I'll always feel that
way. I'd rather live in Chicago than New York. I feel much more
like a Chicagoan than a New Yorker, but I couldn't do what I do in
Chicago.''
</P>
<P>
   It was in Chicago that Feigen began to collect art. He was all
of 10 years old. ``You know, quite honestly, at the very beginning
I don't think it was loving art. It was business, it was trading.
The attachment to the objects came early, but gradually, not at the
very beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   Feigen comes from a prosperous, cultivated background _ he
remembers going to hear Rachmaninoff play his Second Piano Concerto
with the Chicago Symphony _ and went to Yale, then Harvard Business
School. He worked for an insurance company in Los Angeles, then for
a trading house on Wall Street. All the while, though, it was art
that interested him, and in 1957 he sold his seat on the New York
Stock Exchange and returned to Chicago to open a gallery.
</P>
<P>
   Originally, Feigen specialized in Expressionist art (he
considers Max Beckmann the greatest painter of the 20th century).
However, as both dealer and collector, he began to focus on earlier
work. And with New York increasingly becoming the art capital of
not just the United States but the world, Feigen saw what he had to
do. While maintaining his Chicago operation, he moved to New York
in the mid-'60s. In so doing, he guaranteed himself a footnote in
any history of art-world real estate: His was the first gallery in
SoHo.
</P>
<P>
   The move to New York was inevitable, Feigen says. ``In New York
you have a plutocracy,'' and such a density of wealth _ and
ambition _ guarantees a seller's market for art, for there's no
quicker way to buy prestige than by owning the right pictures.
``There's so much money around that it's hard to gain power simply
with wealth _ or, put it this way, the ante keeps rising.''
</P>
<P>
   In a milieu where politesse and good form are de rigueur,
Feigen's willingness to throw around words like ``plutocracy'' and
``ante'' make him unusual _ and talked about. ``I try not merely to
curse the darkness but also light candles,'' he says with a shrug,
``and candles give off heat as well as light.''
</P>
<P>
   Seen in those terms, ``Tales From the Art Crypt'' qualifies as
enough candelabra to illuminate _ and heat up _ several museums'
worth of space. There is, for example, a scathing account of the
shenanigans several years ago at the Barnes Foundation, the fabled
museum outside Philadelphia, when trustees attempted to sell off
holdings in violation of its founder's will _ an attempt Feigen all
but single-handedly scotched. Or there's his comparing the
exhibitions policy at New York's Metropolitan Museum, with its
``random mixture of box-office frivolity with serious art,'' to ``a
nice girl of good family who just once in a while goes out and
turns tricks for some pocket change.''
</P>
<P>
   As such a statement suggests, Feigen is very much of the old
school about art (old school in beliefs, that is, not expression).
For him, the museum is about edification not entertainment, fine
art not fashion. The Metropolitan's director, Philippe de
Montebello, recently chided Feigen at a party for what he had to
say about his museum; and Malcolm Rogers, director of the Museum of
Fine Arts, is no likelier to approve of what Feigen has to say
about the MFA (see accompanying story).
</P>
<P>
   Feigen believes that connoisseurship, not commerce, should be
the supreme value in the art world. That's not exactly an opinion
one expects from a dealer, but Feigen doesn't see himself primarily
as a dealer. ``I really am a collector,'' he says. ``That's what I
really like to do. I love to buy. I don't like as much to sell.''
Artists in his collection include Poussin, Fra Angelico,
Domenichino Turner, and (of course) Beckmann. Feigen also owns
three of the 60 known works by Orazio Gentileschi.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, he sees art dealing as ``a dying business. I don't
know whether it'll still exist in 50 years.'' Asked why that is,
Feigen is quick to note that the art market consists of various
submarkets _ the problems he faces at Feigen Contemporary, his
gallery in New York's Chelsea district, which specializes in the
work of emerging artists, are considerably different from those he
faces selling Old Masters on the Upper East Side _ and then gives
some reasons. Old collections have been dispersed. The supply of
objects is finite, and the supply of available objects contracting.
Most European countries have sharpened export restrictions. The
number of museums has vastly increased (which means works that
might previously have gone on the market are now likelier to be
bequeathed to an institution, the resultant tax break oftentimes
making a donor as much of a financial gain as a sale would).
</P>
<P>
   Feigen cites the difficulties with characteristic, if
incongruous, gusto _ and why not? Selling Old Masters may be in
peril as a business, but you wouldn't know it by looking at such
items he has for sale from the Steinberg Collection as Titian's
``Salome With the Head of John the Baptist'' (estimated worth $12
million) or Jacob Jordaens' ``A Twelfth Night Feast'' (estimated
worth $7 million). And all else failing, he can always fall back on
his acting career.
</P>
<P>
   Feigen barks out a laugh at the suggestion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoyed it,'' he says. ``I still get residuals (for `Wall
Street'). A check will come in the mail for $34, $32. The best of
it was I had one of those trailers. It was out there on Park
Avenue, with my name on the window. It was great. There were only,
let's see: Michael (Douglas) had a trailer, Darryl (Hannah) had a
trailer, Oliver Stone had a trailer, and I had a trailer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm annoyed with a friend of mine, Leonard Goldberg, who
produced this movie called `Double Jeopardy.' There's an art dealer
in the movie, and after it came out I said to him, `Leonard, how
can you do this? I haven't had any work since `Wall Street!' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-27-00 1313EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
