<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 13:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6141 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-EVERYDAY-ETHICS-COLUM     06-27 0848
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EVERYDAY-ETHICS-COLUMN-ADV02-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$ADV02 
 EVERYDAY ETHICS 
 FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 2, AND THEREAFTER.
</HEADLINE>
  (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's EVERYDAY ETHICS column. For more information
about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of the EVERYDAY ETHICS column _ contact one of the New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the
text.) 
 By RANDY COHEN 
 c.2000 Randy Cohen 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A VOTARY VOTES
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am a Lutheran pastor living in a parsonage. Our school
district is debating a building project to be funded by increased
property taxes, a proposition I support (although I do not have any
children enrolled in the system). As the parsonage is exempt from
property tax, is it right for me to vote in the election,
considering that should the project be approved, my portion of its
taxation is passed on to neighbors?
</P>
<P>
   _ Douglas S. Larson-Sell, Lonsdale, Minn.
</P>
<P>
   A: Your exemption from property taxes is not germane. Many
people own no property and hence pay no property taxes; they still
get to vote. The United States long ago abandoned owning land as a
prerequisite for voting. (And I understand that in many states
women have been granted the franchise.) As a citizen, you should
vote on all ballot issues, even those that don't seem to affect you
directly. Otherwise, only motorists would vote on highway bills,
only backpackers (or bears) on funds for national parks. But these
issues concern the entire society. For instance, the bill you
describe finances school construction, and even those without
children have a stake in an educated populace. Democracy works best
when civic life is strong, when people have a broad sense of
community, shared experiences and mutual responsibility. Although I
must say, why church property like your house is exempt from taxes
is a mystery to me.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My city will haul away only trash inside the bins. When a
garden project left more trimmings than fit into the bin, my
neighbor suggested I offer the trash collector $10 or $20 to take
the excess. Isn't this as bad as offering a policeman money to
avoid a ticket? Where do you draw the line between outright bribery
and a little ``lubrication,'' like slipping the maitre d' 10 bucks
for a better table?
</P>
<P>
   _ R.T., Los Angeles
</P>
<P>
   A: Here's one place to draw the line: when you pay someone to
break the law, as you contemplate here, it's a bribe. One reason
some people dislike tipping is because of the ambiguity you
describe. Are you showing appreciation for a job well done or
inducing someone to do something he otherwise would not? That is,
are you rewarding the maitre d' for attentive service or enticing
him to give you a table deserved by someone else?
</P>
<P>
   There is something to be said for clear responsibilities, decent
paychecks and hauling your own excess weeds to the dump.
Alternatively, you could simply stash your trash out back until
next week's pickup when there's room in the bin. As subtle as the
distinction between a bribe and a tip can be, it is lucidity itself
compared to this murky imponderable: what is the difference between
a bribe and a campaign contribution _ particularly when an interest
group donates to both candidates in a race? Science is baffled.
</P>
<P>
   Q: When we stay at motels, I bring the unused, wrapped soaps and
shampoos home to be passed on to a shelter for the homeless. My
husband maintains I'm stealing. I consider the cost of these items
to be built into the charge for the room and that they are ours to
do with what we wish. What is your opinion?
</P>
<P>
   _ R.S. Schenectady, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   A: What you're doing isn't exactly stealing, but it is taking
advantage. While you're at the motel, you may wash yourself as
lavishly as you like, but you may not back a truck up to the supply
room or, for that matter, empty out the shelf above the sink. That
the motel budgets for such things is neither here nor there; they
budget for fire insurance, but you really ought not torch the
place. If you want to donate to a homeless shelter, do so out of
your pocket, not someone else's.
</P>
<P>
   Do you have ethical questions that you need answered? Send them
to ethicist &LR; nytimes.com, or Everyday Ethics, New York Times
Syndicate, 122 East 42nd St., 14th floor, New York, N.Y. 10168.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on EVERYDAY
ETHICS and other features. &QL;
</P>
