<SLUG> BC-RESIDENCY-BURNOUT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOSPITALS REASSESSING HOURS WORKED BY INTERNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE BARNARD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   At a time of increasing concern about medical errors and young
doctors' long working hours, the number of hospitals being cited
for overworking their interns and residents is on the rise,
according to the group that sets standards for doctor training.
</P>
<P>
   Sensing that this long-term, high burnout problem is reaching
crisis levels, teaching hospitals from Massachusetts to California
are reassessing their residency programs.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 86 teaching hospitals reviewed last year by the private
organization that accredits residency training programs, 17 _
nearly one in five _ were cited for violating the organization's
work-hour standards.
</P>
<P>
   The standards don't purport to keep medical training from being
grueling: They call for one day off out of seven; overnight
hospital duty no more than once every three nights; and workweeks
of 80 hours or more, depending on the specialty. Still, the group
found violations in 28 of 92 training programs in internal medicine
and 25 of 69 general surgery programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The citations related to work hours and working conditions are
more frequent now than they have been in past years,'' said Dr.
David Leach, president of the evaluating group, the Accreditation
Council for Graduate Medical Education. The group does not disclose
which hospitals are cited.
</P>
<P>
   There are many possible reasons for the increase, doctors and
administrators said. A budget crunch has forced teaching hospitals
to lay off support staff and rely on residents for routine tasks.
An increased array of medical options gives residents more to learn
and more to do.
</P>
<P>
   The accreditation council and other medical groups have renewed
their interest in the problem of exhausted doctors, particularly in
the seven months since a National Academy of Sciences report, ``To
Err is Human,'' said that more Americans die each year from medical
errors than from car accidents.
</P>
<P>
   Physician training programs across the country, from
Massachusetts General Hospital to the University of California at
San Francisco School of Medicine, are reassessing the way they use
residents, in a flurry of activity not seen since 1989.
</P>
<P>
   That year, New York became the only state to regulate residents'
hours, responding to the 1984 death of 18-year-old Libby Zion,
whose father, a prominent journalist, blamed overworked,
unsupervised residents. Massachusetts hospitals headed off such
legislation by adopting voluntary guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's distressing to see the number of citations and the number
of programs that are not in compliance when this is a 10-year-old
issue,'' said Dr. Michael Whitcomb, vice president of the American
Association of Medical Colleges.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, he said, some programs are now finding
innovative solutions to a longstanding problem _ how to reduce
hours while still providing intense training in the first three to
five years after medical school. That is one of the questions to be
tackled by a new task force to make medical institutions more
accountable for doctors' training.
</P>
<P>
   Outside forces may spur more hospitals to focus on the issue.
Last year, the National Labor Relations Board upheld a union
representing interns and residents at Boston Medical Center, ruling
that they are primarily employees, not students, and have a right
to organize.
</P>
<P>
   Some doctors, including Bertrand Bell, the author of New York's
regulations, say the council should publicize its list of violators
to create more public pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``It should be known to the patients, it should be known to the
residents who are about to start,'' said Josh Sharfstein, a
pediatrics fellow at Boston Medical Center who has written about
the issue for The New Republic.
</P>
<P>
   But Leach, head of the ACGME, said the group does not want its
members to ``waste time and energy dealing with the public fallout
that could be spent on improving the situation internally.'' He
said the group is not afraid to cite prestigious hospitals and even
remove their accreditation _ a step that is public _ if they do not
improve.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Hasan Bazari, director of internal medicine residency
programs at Massachusetts General Hospital, said that when his
program received a citation several years ago, it helped speed
changes doctors wanted to make anyway.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, he said, there were no caps on the number of patients
an intern could admit to the hospital in a night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't atypical for an intern to admit 14 or 15,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Now it is in line with ACGME guidelines, which limit that number
to five. In addition, he said, internal medicine interns are on
``call'' _ all-night duty _ every four or even five nights, rather
than every three.
</P>
<P>
   Accomplishing that was expensive, and not every hospital can do
it, especially when the American Association of Medical Colleges
estimates that Medicare cuts will cost the average teaching
hospital $43 million by 2002. Bazari credits the leadership of
chief of medicine Dennis Ausiello. In two years, he said, MGH has
hired an additional 17 interns and residents, bringing the total to
119, without increasing the workload.
</P>
<P>
   It has also added a ``night float'' rotation, a 9 p.m. to 7 a.m.
shift that reduces the need for shifts that stretch to 36 hours. It
has shunted some tasks to doctors who have completed their training
so residents spend more time learning. That involved assigning nine
doctors _ five newly hired from other hospitals _ to focus on
caring for inpatients.
</P>
<P>
   Bazari said today's interns and residents need more time for
each patient than in his day because of the growing amount of
available treatments and an increase in acute ailments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, we took care of a lot of patients, but we needed to know
less and we had less to offer them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Brigham and Women's Hospital and Massachusetts General in Boston
have both transferred some duties to physician's assistants and
other aides, said Debra Weinstein, director of graduate medical
education for Partners, which includes both hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the University of California at San Francisco's
School of Medicine created a task force to reduce residents' hours,
partly to head off a San Francisco ballot initiative and a bill in
the state Legislature that would have imposed New York-style
regulations after a fourth-year medical student drew media
attention to the issue. The school has withdrawn its residents from
some hospitals where they were spread too thin, said David Irby,
vice dean for education.
</P>
<P>
   One of only two Boston-area hospitals with unionized residents
and interns, Boston Medical Center has seen working conditions
improve under chief medical officer John Chessare, said Sandy Shea,
organizer of the union there.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Ruth Potee, an intern and union member, said that in some
rotations, such as surgery or obstetrics, she works 100 to 110
hours a week. She said she often takes patients in neighborhood
clinics after being up all night.
</P>
<P>
   Potee said that she would ask for help if she feared she would
injure a patient. But she has had other mishaps, including two
minor car accidents from ``being exhausted and backing into things
I shouldn't have hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucian Leape, a surgeon and adjunct professor at the Harvard
School of Public Health who was one of the authors of the medical
errors report, said many medical leaders still have not embraced
reducing resident hours, arguing it will cause mistakes when one
doctor hands off a patient to another.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's disingenous,'' he said. ``Senior physicians can
go home at 5 p.m. We have ways of making sure people don't fall
between the cracks.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, `We have opened up a dialogue.. . .I bet in five
years this won't be an issue.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
