<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TRADE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME FEAR CHINA TRADE BILL IS UNRAVELING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ More than a month after the US House approved a
sweeping trade agreement with China, the bill has been unexpectedly
delayed in the Senate, causing growing anxiety among business
officials who believed the political battle was won weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Senate leaders have not yet scheduled a vote on permanent
normalization of trade relations with China, or PNTR. Several
senators are now threatening to add amendments to the bill, which
would force the House to vote again on the revised measure. And
with time running out on the legislative calendar, business leaders
eager to tap into the sprawling Chinese marketplace are
increasingly worried that the deal could be postponed until next
year.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement is of special interest in Massachusetts, where
business analysts believe expanded trade could add billions of
dollars to the technology and financial services industries. Yet
because the delay appears to be the result of internal Capitol Hill
squabbling, some industry leaders said they felt powerless to speed
up the process, especially after expending so much time and effort
on the fierce battle in the House last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``This should be done and over with,'' said Bruce Holbein, vice
president for public policy at the Massachusetts Software &AMP;
Internet Council.
</P>
<P>
   ``The longer we wait, the more it gets embroiled in
election-year politics,'' said Greg Garcia, director of
governmental affairs for the networking firm 3Com, whose New
England headquarters is in Marlborough. ``The longer we wait, the
danger increases that it will be put off until the following
year.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill, which would require China to lower its tariffs and
barriers in exchange for permanent normal trade status with the
United States, was always expected to face stiff opposition in the
House, where many Democrats are allied with powerful labor unions.
Labor believes the trade deal will endanger US jobs while doing
little to force China to treat its own workers with dignity.
Opponents also say China has an abysmal human rights record.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, eager to secure a major policy victory in his
final year in office, took on normalization as a personal crusade.
When it passed the House on May 24 by a vote of 237-197, Clinton
called it ``a historic step toward continued prosperity in America,
reform in China, and peace in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate passage was supposed to be a breeze. Currently, 75 of the
Senate's 100 members, including the two Democrats from
Massachusetts and most of the New England delegation, are expected
to vote in favor of PNTR. But for unrelated political reasons,
Senate majority leader Trent Lott has not yet taken the crucial
first step of putting the bill on the calendar for a vote.
</P>
<P>
   Lott says he is waiting for his Senate colleagues to present a
so-called ``clean bill'' _ one identical to the House version, in
order to remove several procedural steps and clear its path to the
White House for Clinton to sign it into law.
</P>
<P>
   Lott also says he wants the Senate to handle several
appropriations bills first, to avoid an embarrassing struggle late
in an election year. But many political aides see partisan
maneuvering at work. One Republican aide said he believed Senate
GOP leaders are trying to draw out what is an uncomfortable issue
for many Democrats, dividing their loyalties between labor unions
and businesses. Senator John F. Kerry of Massachusetts said there
is a widespread fear that the bill is ``being taken political
hostage.''
</P>
<P>
   Lott insists he wants to schedule the vote before the summer
recess begins July 28. ``It is clearly my intent to call it up
before the August recess,'' Lott said last week.
</P>
<P>
   But he also conceded, ``It might not be as easy done as said.''
And after so many weeks of stalling, PNTR advocates overjoyed by
the House vote four weeks ago are beginning to fear that momentum
is starting to wane.
</P>
<P>
   They see troubling signs. US Commerce Secretary William Daley,
who guided the bill adroitly thus far, is leaving his job in
mid-July to take over the presidential campaign of Vice President
Al Gore. The following month, thousands of demonstrators are
planning to descend on the Democratic convention in Los Angeles to
protest, among other global issues, PNTR.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some on the Republican side would like to push this past the
conventions,'' Senator Max Baucus, a Democrat of Montana, said this
week in the Capitol Hill newspaper Roll Call. ``If that were to
happen, I see this vote losing. If anything like what happened in
Seattle happened in Los Angeles, then I think a number of senators
would be unlikely to vote for it.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Senator Fred Thompson, a Tennessee Republican,
is promoting a bill to establish an annual review of China's
nuclear weapons capacity _ a major change to the existing PNTR bill
that would force a new vote in the House. Under the rules of
Congress, both houses must vote on exactly the same bill before it
can be sent to the White House. With elections this fall, Congress
will be more or less on hold after July, making it extremely
difficult to get anything done.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, concerned about such procedural obstacles, summoned
nearly a dozen pro-PNTR senators to the White House earlier this
week to try to work out a strategy. Kerry was among them. ``The
president was resolute and clear about the need to achieve this,''
Kerry said. ``Our hope is the president is going to engage very
directly with the leadership on the Republican side, and we are all
going to engage with our colleagues, to see if we can get a date
certain to proceed.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the delay has worried many business leaders.
Especially in the technology industry, which has only recently
begun to interact with the government, this inside-the-Beltway
wrangling appears unnecessary and confusing. ``The dot-com
community already has this disdain for government,'' said one
Republican Senate aide. Political haggling of this kind, he said,
is likely to make things worse.
</P>
<P>
   While the slow action in the Senate is unsettling to business
interests, the procedural delay has had few practical effects thus
far. The effects of PNTR will not be felt in full until China
enters the World Trade Organization later this year or in early
2001.
</P>
<P>
   In effect, PNTR is a preventive measure: Under the rules of the
WTO, the United States is not allowed to make unilateral decisions
about how it trades with other countries, as it does with China
now. Without PNTR, China would have the right, under WTO
guidelines, to keep its high tariffs in place for US companies as
punishment for the annual trade vote now required on China in the
Congress. That vote, conditioned on a review of human rights
behavior, is galling to the Chinese; PNTR would do away with it.
</P>
<P>
   With PNTR, which makes China's trade status permanent, the
tariff playing field is leveled.
</P>
<P>
   Labor unions believe the deal would harm US workers by
encouraging American companies to move abroad. But that argument
has been largely dismissed in the Senate, in part because so many
states' economies stand to benefit from the deal. Hundreds of
Massachusetts companies, especially those that sell technological
equipment and provide financial and insurance services, hope they
will be able to move swiftly into the giant marketplace, providing
products that are currently forbidden or highly taxed by the
Chinese government.
</P>
<P>
   The uncertainty, said Garcia, the lobbyist for 3Com, is
preventing some companies from laying out new China business plans.
And, several business officials said, it is not winning any votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Washington, it's a political hot potato,'' said Chris
Anderson, the government liaison for the Massachusetts Hi-Tech
Council. ``From the perspective of those of us outside the Beltway,
it looks absurd.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
