<SLUG> BC-JORDAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS A VOTE FOR NADER A VOTE FOR BUSH? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT A. JORDAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; He may not do as well as Ross Perot did as a third party
candidate, but consumer advocate Ralph Nader and the Green Party
which endorsed him Sunday may have as much impact on the
presidential election as did Perot's Reform Party.
</P>
<P>
   As Perot did in the 1992 election when he criticized both George
Bush and Bill Clinton as having no real differences between them,
Nader is now saying essentially the same about Texas Governor
George W. Bush and Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   However, as some political analysts have suggested, Perot drew
more votes from people who might have voted for Bush, and thus may
have helped Clinton win the White House that year.
</P>
<P>
   And Nader is using his strong opposition to the current China
free trade bill, as Perot used the NAFTA (North American Free Trade
Agreement), to attract organized labor.
</P>
<P>
   Nader has drawn much praise from labor, including the United
Auto Workers and the International Teamsters, with his strong
argument that NAFTA has _ and the bill which grants China permanent
normal trade relations status will _ hurt US workers by exporting
hundreds of thousands of jobs overseas.
</P>
<P>
   There are at least two reasons why Teamsters president James
Hoffa Jr. attended the Green Party's endorsement of Nader. Although
he did not indicate whether he would endorse Nader's presidential
bid, he praised Nader for his stance on the trade bill, and
criticized Gore for supporting the China free trade bill. Hoffa
also said he expected Bush to support the trade bill, suggesting
that endorsing Bush is not high on the Teamsters' list of
possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffa and several other union presidents critical of Gore's
stance on the China free trade bill argue that they are openly
challenging the belief among some Democrats that organized labor,
which has been essential to the election of Clinton and members of
Congress, has nowhere to go but to Gore. If the Teamsters and the
UAW, and other large unions, decide to endorse Nader over Gore,
that could pose problems for organized labor and for Gore. Although
the national AFL-CIO and the CWA (Communications Workers of
America) endorsed Gore early in the campaign, a split in organized
labor over Gore and Nader could seriously weaken Gore's election
chances.
</P>
<P>
   To add to Gore's problem with Nader, some polls have shown that
Bush currently is in a virtual dead heat with Gore for rank and
file support of US workers. If anything, this support for Bush
suggests that organized labor has a lot of work ahead in educating
working families about what a Bush presidency, as opposed to a Gore
presiency, would mean to them.
</P>
<P>
   The bigger problem right now for Gore and labor is the
``bounce'' Nader will receive from the endorsement he received from
the Green Party.
</P>
<P>
   Some polls have Nader at 4 percent nationally, and about 9
percent in California, a state crucial to Gore's election bid.
</P>
<P>
   But there's another percentage on which Nader and the Green
Party is focused _ the 15 percent Nader and other presidential
candidates are required to reach in the polls to be eligible for
participation in the presidential debates, which begin Oct. 3 in
Boston. Both Nader and Pat Buchanan, the Reform Party's expected
presidential candidate, are legally challenging this 15 percent
threshold.
</P>
<P>
   If Nader and Buchanan, a former member of the Republican Party,
are able to participate in the debates, Nader could pose more of a
problem for Gore than Buchanan. Even if Nader is kept out of the
debates, that move could generate more positive publicity for the
consumer advocate. Either way, the Green Party's endorsement of
Nader gives him a higher profile that can't be ignored.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if his candidacy could take votes from Gore and
result in Bush's election in November, Nader brushed the question
aside by saying there was no real difference between Bush and Gore.
Of course, beyond the China free trade bill, there are clear
differences between Gore and Bush _ particularly on issues that
matter to organized labor.
</P>
<P>
   Nader knows it, and organized labor knows it. Before November,
organized labor will have to decide whether, in reality, that a
vote for Nader will, in the end, be a vote for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Robert A. Jordan is a Boston Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
