<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NET PIONEER'S IPO TOWERS OVER OTHERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Who knew a contract to hook together a handful of computers
could lead to this?
</P>
<P>
   The event is this week's initial public stock offering of
Genuity Inc., which traces its corporate roots to the pioneering
days of the Internet and manages Web access for millions of
computer users today. It's a stock deal that towers over other
Massachusetts IPOs in size and complexity.
</P>
<P>
   The Burlington, Mass. company expects to raise about $2.3
billion for stock scheduled to begin trading Wednesday. Genuity
will probably hit the market with a total stock valuation of $13
billion or more, exceeded by just eight companies in Massachusetts
at the moment.
</P>
<P>
   Whether this is the kind of stock market inclined to swallow
millions of new shares in an Internet company up to its routers in
red ink is a serious debate. The early line: Genuity is a big
player with natural appeal to investors, but its stock sale is
being aggressively priced by underwriters who estimate a range of
$12 to $15 per share by the time the deal wraps up.
</P>
<P>
   The timing is being driven by factors beyond stock market
sentiment. Regulatory approval for the $65 billion merger between
Genuity's parent, GTE Corp., and Bell Atlantic Corp. is contingent
upon the public stock offering. That means it goes now.
</P>
<P>
   Genuity used to be called GTE Internetworking. The business was
built on GTE's acquisition of Bolt Beranek &AMP; Newman, a Cambridge
firm purchased for $616 million in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Bolt Beranek was a technology consulting firm with an expertise
in acoustics when it won a government contract in 1969 to connect
computers located across the country for Pentagon research projects
_ a system that eventually evolved into the Internet. BBN delivered
the world's first electronic mail message and pioneered the use of
the ``(at)'' symbol now used in all e-mail addresses.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Genuity operates one of the nation's largest Tier 1
Internet ``backbones,'' more than 17,000 miles of fiber-optic
cables routing and carrying Internet traffic around the world.
Among the millions of people who dial into America Online Inc. to
reach the Web, one of every three is connected along Genuity's
backbone.
</P>
<P>
   Genuity is also building Internet hosting services and ``virtual
private networks,'' for secure data transmission by corporate
clients.
</P>
<P>
   Genuity is no Internet seedling, having generated more than $700
million in revenue last year. It's on target to exceed $1 billion
in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The flip side: Genuity sure loses money like a young Web company
as it continues to pour cash into technology. It lost $647 million
last year, a figure that matched 92 cents of every sales dollar in
1999. More losses are in the future, and Genuity talks about
capital expeditures of as much as $13 billion over the next five
years.
</P>
<P>
   Genuity pulls down most of its revenue from Internet access
charges. One customer, AOL, accounted for 52 percent of all sales
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the company's biggest access competitors, all operating
their own Tier 1 backbones, are connected with giant
telecommunciations companies like Worldcom's UUNet unit.
</P>
<P>
   Genuity's business of hosting Web sites and connecting Internet
visitors to them is growing, but accounted for only 7 percent of
revenue last year. Other developing businesses account for an even
smaller slice of the pie.
</P>
<P>
   Placing a value on Genuity becomes complicated because the
company operates in several businesses that command different
levels of interest among investors.
</P>
<P>
   Genuity's IPO appears to be valued at somewhere between
five-and-a-half and seven times the revenue forecast for 2001. But
other free-standing access companies, such as PSINet Inc., trade at
about three times next year's projected sales.
</P>
<P>
   Leading competitors in the hot hosting business command much
higher stock valuations, as much as 15 times revenue.
</P>
<P>
   So how do you come up with a value for Genuity? To buy the IPO
price, it helps to have faith that the company can grow its hosting
services to become as much as 20 percent of the business.
</P>
<P>
   Another unanswered question: Who will own how much of Geunity?
This is where it really gets complicated.
</P>
<P>
   Shareholders buying Genuity stock at the IPO appear to be
acquiring 90.5 percent of the company, but a twist in the offering
will likely turn control back to the seller before long.
</P>
<P>
   The combined GTE and Bell Atlantic, which will be called
Verizon, agreed to spin off most of its ownership in Genuity only
to satisfy federal regulators.
</P>
<P>
   But Verizon will be allowed to convert its interest back into an
82 percent stake of Genuity later, at modest expense.
</P>
<P>
   The catch: Local telephone service in all the states covered by
Bell Atlantic must be successfully opened to competition.
</P>
<P>
   That process has to be accomplished state by state, but
investors are treating the Genuity IPO as if Verizon will in fact
become an 82 percent owner. It could take place over five years or
longer, but analysts suggested the conversion will take place
within three years and perhaps as quickly as 20 months.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
