<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 13:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6146 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-NBA-DRAFT-BOS &LR;      06-27 1747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NBA-DRAFT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBA DRAFT PROSPECTS NOT AS FOREIGN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHIRA SPRINGER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With his West Virginia twang in full effect, Celtics general
manager Chris Wallace gave a quick lesson in Eastern European
history Monday. He talked about the dissolution of the Soviet Union
and the breakup of Yugoslavia. He rattled off the names of places
such as Serbia, Croatia, and Montenegro, stressing each exotic
syllable.
</P>
<P>
   The ever-changing borders of Eastern Europe provided context for
one of Wallace's biggest concerns: the evaluation of foreign talent
available for Wednesday's NBA Draft. As the physical and political
landscapes of countries are transformed, professional scouts assess
the talents of foreign players who may be capable of altering the
NBA landscape.
</P>
<P>
   While the NBA has shown serious interest in international talent
for more than a decade, the stateside performances of such players
has been mixed. Players such as Toni Kukoc, Vlade Divac, and Drazen
Petrovic legitimized overseas interest. But the return of Sasha
Danilovic and others to European leagues, the nine-year wait for
Arvydas Sabonis, and a disputed deal involving Sarunas Marciulionis
gave NBA teams pause about pursuing foreign talent. So far, more
international players have been forgotten than have made a name for
themselves in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   But not so long ago, when familiarity with international players
increased and the number of rounds in the drafts decreased, the
calculus involved changed. Scouts, player personnel directors, and
coaches developed a better understanding of what international
players need to succeed. Now the risks are fewer, the upside
greater, and the talent pool larger and better prepared.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what's happened now is we've been through a
decade-plus with a growing global tint to the NBA,'' said Wallace.
``Towards the end of the decade, we actually saw the arrival of
some bona fide European stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody doubts anymore in the NBA that European players can
perform and succeed in the league. That notion has been knocked
down. I don't know whether you call it xenophobia or whatever. That
doesn't exist anymore in the league.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, 38 foreign-born players declared themselves eligible
for the draft, including 18 early-entry candidates (12 of the
early-entry candidates subsequently withdrew). The majority of
these players have spent their entire careers playing for European
teams, while 10 attended US colleges and one (Soumaila Samake)
played in the IBL.
</P>
<P>
   Some mock drafts have as many as five international, non-college
players being selected in the first round _ three more than were
selected last year (Frederic Weis, 15th by the Knicks; Andrei
Kirilenko, 24th by Utah) and a far cry from the days when Europeans
were seldom considered worth an early pick.
</P>
<P>
   Although Portland chose Sabonis with the final first-round pick
in 1986, the slots of Petrovic (third round, 60th overall to
Portland in 1986), Alexander Volkov (sixth round, 134th overall to
Atlanta in 1986), and Valerie Tikhonenko (seventh round, 157th
overall to Atlanta in 1986) were far more typical. Even the highly
touted Kukoc was not selected by Chicago until the second round in
1990.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important thing that has changed is we now have a
formal process for having them apply for the draft, which means we
get to watch them a lot, talk to them a lot,'' said Stan Kasten,
president of the Atlanta Hawks and one of the first talent
evaluators to look overseas. ``Everything is wide open now and
there's an easier method for comparing them to the other players in
the draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back then, everything was somewhat cloak and dagger and
shrouded in mystery. You could not be sure of what you were
getting. You hadn't seen them play against this kind of
competition. You didn't know if they wanted to come over here.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're always reluctant to waste a No. 1 pick. Now, you're not
worrying about wasting a pick. You know the player's available and
is going to play and you have a much better handle on how well
he'll be able to play.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, the European leagues produce fundamentally
sound shooters accustomed to a level of play less intense than the
NBA, especially regarding man-to-man defense. While the American
system rewards athleticism, European practices consist of
repetitive drills that break down each facet of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign players must adjust their game and lifestyle once they
reach the NBA. And that takes time and patience on the part of
their teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``You usually can throw away the first year because it's just
such a learning experience,'' said Wallace.
</P>
<P>
   Marc Fleisher, president of Entersport and an agent for such
European stars as Divac and former Celtic Dino Radja, said, ``It's
difficult in the first year, and (the transition) depends on the
team and coaching staff. Every player is different with different
personalities. I remember one player came over here and didn't know
how to work his refrigerator. He called and I explained what to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a full-service job, more so when you're representing
European players.''
</P>
<P>
   Petrovic and Dallas forward Dirk Nowitzki are examples of the
virtues of patience and the importance of finding the right fit.
</P>
<P>
   Before Petrovic died in a 1993 car accident, he was starting to
excel in the NBA. Portland tired of waiting for him to develop, but
after he was traded to New Jersey, he improved dramatically. In his
first year with the Nets ('91-92) he more than doubled his scoring
average and recorded career-highs in assists (252) and steals
(105). In his final NBA season, Petrovic averaged 22.3 points.
</P>
<P>
   Nowitzki had a similarly steep success rate this past season,
his second in the NBA. Playing in all 82 of the Mavericks' games,
he more than doubled his scoring average to 17.5 points, quadrupled
his assists (203), more than doubled his steals (29), and grabbed
three more rebounds a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hard to begin from zero,'' said Radja of his own
adjustment period. ``You have a certain name when you are in
Europe, then you come to the US and you have to earn every second
on the court.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As foreign players become more prevalent in the NBA, teams
experience their own learning curve, improving the way
international talent is developed. Minnesota center Radoslav
Nesterovic benefited from the failure of Lithuanian forward
Virginius Praskevicius, a gifted athlete who was physically ready
to play in the NBA but had problems because of the language.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Praskevicius) could barely communicate when he first came
here,'' said Rob Babcock, the Timberwolves' director of player
personnel. ``He was just constantly so far behind. Once you get
going into the season, the coaches didn't have time to spend to
develop him. Logistically, it's a very difficult thing to do, and
he didn't make it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really learned that the player not only has to have the
character and language base to be able to get going and make
continual progress, but they've also got to be good enough as a
basketball player that they're going to be able to get into your
rotation fairly quick.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're used to playing a lot. They're generally a star back
home. Though they're realistic in most cases and realize they're
playing in the best league in the world, they still want to play.
If you see you're earning more minutes and you're progressing, then
you have some motivation to stay here. If you don't, then you get
unhappy really fast.''
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota knew Nesterovic would remain with Virtus Roma for one
year after being selected with the 17th pick in the 1998 draft, but
the Timberwolves were willing to wait for young 7-footer from
Slovenia. They brought Nesterovic over just before the 1999
playoffs, after his European season finished. He played five games,
gaining a feel for the NBA, the organization, his new home, his
teammates, and his coaches.
</P>
<P>
   When injuries on the team forced coach Flip Saunders to make
Nesterovic the starting center this past season, the Minnesota
staff stayed patient. Nesterovic showed his commitment, practicing
extra hours. He averaged 5.7 points in 82 regular-season games,
then got significant minutes in four playoff contests.
</P>
<P>
   The coaches didn't put a lot of pressure on Nesterovic; they
didn't run plays directly at the young center and tried to keep up
his confidence by using him in the right matchups. After all,
Nesterovic represented a prized NBA commodity: a skilled true
center.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   International big men benefit from excellent teaching in the
European leagues and arrive fundamentally sound. Recently, there
has been a shortage of quality big men coming through the American
system.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you took away all the foreign-born players at the center
position in the NBA, we'd really be struggling,'' said Wallace.
</P>
<P>
   Of the top foreign-born players being considered in this year's
draft, the majority are centers, including 7-foot-2-inch Iakovos
Tsakalidis and 6-10 Olumide Oyedeji, who have piqued the Celtics'
interest. But in Tsakalidis's case, unresolved contract issues with
his European team, AEK Athens, have made his future unclear.
</P>
<P>
   ``NBA teams still look at signing a foreign players as a big
undertaking,'' said Fleisher. In addition to all the concerns about
adjustments, organizations interested in foreign talent must worry
about binding contracts and buyouts.
</P>
<P>
   Washington-based lawyer Lon Babby made his first foray into the
foreign market this year, adding Oyedeji and Hidayet Turkoglu to a
list of NBA clients that includes Tim Duncan and Grant Hill. Babby
figures foreign players are going to be an increasingly prominent
part of the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   Turkoglu is under contract to Efes Pilsen in his native Turkey,
so he would have to be bought out.
</P>
<P>
   But ultimately, it's up to each international player what he
makes of his NBA experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I try to emphasize to all my players, European and
non-European, is that the draft is really just the beginning of the
process,'' said Babby. ``Wherever they go, that's just the
beginning of their career. The draft doesn't determine the outcome
of your career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think (foreign) players in particular know that what they do
over the next few years and how they develop and what their
attitude is and what their work ethic is will determine how
successful they are.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
