<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 13:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6149 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u t BC-TRAVEL-VERMONT-ART-BO     06-27 0891
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-VERMONT-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 VISITING CHEESEMAKERS A FLAVORFUL WAY TO SEE THE REAL VERMONT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILLIAM A. DAVIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRATTLEBORO, Vt. _ Henry Tewksbury, known around here as ``Henry
the Cheeseman,'' boasts that he stocks more than 470 cheeses from
around the world in his shop at the Brattleboro Food Cooperative.
</P>
<P>
   But in a cooler case separate from the others, Tewksbury proudly
displays his personal favorites: the 100 or so distinctive cheeses
made in Vermont, most by small, family-run cheesemaking operations
using traditional methods and milk from their own herds. ``All the
Vermont cheeses are good, but some are now world class,'' he says.
``High quality farmstead cheeses are helping save the Vermont
family farm and preserve the Vermont landscape.''
</P>
<P>
   A dozen cheese makers, scattered around the state, welcome
visitors to their farms or creameries and to the ``caves'' where
cheeses are carefully aged, just like fine wines. And, as at
wineries, cheeses can usually be both sampled and bought. A trip
along this Vermont Cheese Trail is both a flavorful experience and
a scenic journey into the bucolic heart of New England's most
agricultural state.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vermont has 25 farmstead cheesemakers, more than any other
state,'' says Tewksbury. Farmstead, or farmhouse, cheese is made at
a farm from the milk of animals _ cows, goats, or sheep _ that are
also raised and milked there. This means the cheese has a unique
flavor with subtle seasonal and annual differences, just like wine
from the same vineyard.
</P>
<P>
   Cheesemaking is an old Vermont tradition. Crowley Cheese of
Healdville, which makes a creamier version of cheddar commonly
called Colby (but in Vermont often referred to as ``Crowley'') was
founded in 1882 and claims to be the oldest continuously operated
cheese factory in the country. The Cabot Creamery in Cabot, a
farmers' cooperative founded in 1919, has a large modern plant that
produces more than 12 million pounds of cheese, mostly cheddar, a
year.
</P>
<P>
   Farmstead cheesemaking operations, however, tend to be
relatively new and small in scale. Some get milk from as few as
four cows. They also generally make gourmet _ and pricey _ cheeses
such as blue, chevre, feta, and European-style sheep cheeses.
``There was plenty of cheddar out there, so we decided to go for a
niche cheese market,'' says Kate Wright, who with her husband ,Jon,
runs Taylor Farm in Londonderry.
</P>
<P>
   Last year the Wrights began making Gouda, a cheese that
originated in Holland and is made from the milk of Holstein cows
and traditionally aged in a red wax covering. `The nice thing about
Gouda is that it ages fast and you can sell it after two months,''
Kate Wright says.`` Now we also make a maple smoked Gouda and are
working on an aged Gouda. It isn't as creamy as the regular cheese
but has a different flavor and costs more.''
</P>
<P>
   Farmstead cheeses like the Wrights' Gouda are handcrafted
products and priced accordingly, says Tewksbury, noting that the
best Vermont farmstead cheeses retail for as much as $17 a pound.
``They're not cheap,'' he allows.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Wrights are transplants to Vermont; he grew up in
Manhattan and she in the Boston suburb of Sudbury. Cheesemaking is
only one of the sidelines the couple have developed in order to
make a living and continue farming. They offer sleigh rides in the
winter and run a farm stand that sells vegetables, baked goods and,
now, cheese. ``We love it here and don't want to live anywhere
else,'' Kate Wright says.
</P>
<P>
   For some farmers, becoming cheesemakers has enabled them to keep
their animals after other uses became uneconomical. ``When my
father suggested that we milk our sheep instead of just raising
them for wool and meat, we thought it was a ridiculous idea at
first,'' says Cindy Major, ``but then we realized that cheeses like
Roquefort and mozzarella are made from sheep's milk.''
</P>
<P>
   Cynthia and David Major, both in their 30s, are the founders of
Vermont Shepherd of Putney, which makes French Pyrenees-style sheep
cheeses sold in gourmet food shops around the country. ``The first
cheese we made was so bad that we decided to go to France and see
how cheesemakers in the Basque country did it,'' says Cindy. That
was a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Vermont Shepherd's country style cheese, made with
unpasteurized milk from sheep that graze on fresh grass and wild
herbs, is prized for its rustic rind, grassy aroma, and nutty tang.
``I think it's better than anything from France,'' says Tewksbury.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to milking their own sheep, the Majors also buy
young cheese, made to their specifications, from other local
farmers, and age it in their large cave. They also now make some
cows' milk cheeses as well.
</P>
<P>
   The Vermont Shepherd cave, where the sampling room is located,
is an impressive sight. Its shelves are covered with wheels of
cheese ranging in shade from pale yellow to golden brown. For four
to eight months, each wheel is carefully turned and brushed every
other day so it will cure evenly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We baby them,'' says Brad Lussier, the cave's ``affineur'' or
cheese ager, ``that's how you make good cheese.''
</P>
</TEXT>
