<HEADLINE>
GOOD REASONS TO HEAD TO EUROPE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Europe: It's the place to be this year. Not only are there some
great happenings but the dollar is strong, which means the trip
could cost less than expected.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest savings will be found in countries that have adopted
the euro such as France, Germany, Ireland, Italy, and Belgium. The
dollar has been running almost 23 percent more against the euro.
While travelers may not see savings in everything, there are
bargains out there that could allow you to travel a little bit
better. For example, last year a room at the luxurious Hotel Adlon
in Berlin started at $283 a night; this year that same room costs
$205.
</P>
<P>
   Even without the savings, Europe is festive this year. It is
celebrating with the first world fair of the century in Hannover,
Germany. Nearly 200 nations are participating in the fair, which
runs through October. Also in Germany is the Oberammergau Passion
Play, held once every 10 years. In Rome, it is a Jubilee Year for
Christians. In London, visitors can ride the London Eye, a
450-foot-tall Ferris wheel.
</P>
<P>
   Other events to note: On July 1, the longest combined
rail/road/tunnel crossing in the world will open between Denmark
and Sweden. The Oresund Bridge is 10 miles long and has two decks,
with cars driving on the upper and trains on the lower. It cost $3
billion to build and will cost you about $30 to drive it one way.
For more information, go to www.oeresundsbron.com.
</P>
<P>
   In Wales, the first national botanic garden, and the first to be
created in Britain for more than 200 years, is open. The National
Botanic Garden of Wales cost $65 million and took 10 years of
planning. The garden is located about an hour by car from Cardiff
and costs about $9.50 to view. To learn more go to
www.gardenofwales.org.uk.
</P>
<P>
   Since both of these attractions are best visited by car, look
into renting a vehicle. Avis International has a Personally Yours
collection of free and unique preprinted itineraries for popular
driving tours in Europe. Each tour covers historic, cultural, and
scenic highlights based on recent drives. The tours make travel in
Europe all the more interesting. Travelers do need to book their
car 21 days in advance of the trip to obtain the Personally Yours
driving tour. Ask also about the 25 percent discount of the Avis
Super Value rate. And booking before you go is another way to save,
because all you can buy in the United States before heading to
Europe guarantees your price, can be less costly, and you don't
have to worry about exchange rates. For Avis, call 800-331-1084 or
see a travel agent. For a discount, mention AWD N917201.
</P>
<P>
   With the strength of the dollar against the franc, a visit to
Nice and Cannes on the French Riviera is a great value. The two
resort cities have a lineup of folk festivals and special
celebrations throughout the summer. For information on Nice, call
(+33) 493.928.291 or visit www.nice-coteazur.org; for Cannes, call
(+33) 492.993.135 or visit www.cannes-on-line.com.
</P>
<P>
   And, if you are in Denmark on July 4, you won't miss America's
birthday _ the largest July 4 celebration outside the United States
is held in Rebild National Park, 12 miles south of Aalborg, North
Jutland. The event, complete with bands, singing, and speeches by
prominent Americans and Danes has taken place every year since
1912, except for during the two world wars. The park was presented
to Denmark by Danish Americans in 1912.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Sculpture 2000
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some of the finest sculptors from countries as diverse as
Israel, India, Morocco and Colombia will unite for Sculpture 2000
International, an outdoor invitational exhibition in the shoreline
city of New London, Conn. The free exhibit, spearheaded by Mitchell
College, continues through Aug. 22. Several artists will be
creating new pieces for the event that will become permanent gifts
to the community. During the showings there will be seminars and
workshops with the artists, and walking tours of the sculptures.
New London will also be the site of the tall ship celebration,
Opsail 2000, July 12-15.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Montreal jazz
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Montreal becomes soul heaven from Thursday through July 9 when
music lovers flock to the 21st Montreal International Jazz
Festival. City streets become the world's largest stage for 400
concerts, 300 of which are free.
</P>
<P>
   Among the performers will be Sting, Ray Charles, Manhattan
Transfer, Herbie Hancock, and Patti Smith. This year's edition pays
tribute to the legacy of Louis Armstrong on the 100th anniversary
of his birth. For information on packages, hotel rates, and more,
call the Info-Jazz Bell line at 888-515-0515 or visit
www.montrealjazzfest.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Stone houses
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The 50th annual Stone House Day in Hurley, N.Y., is July 8.
Eleven of the country's oldest homes will be open for viewing
between 10 a.m. and 4 p.m. For more information, call 914-338-2283.
</P>
</TEXT>
