<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONLINE-GROCERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     ONLINE GROCERS UNITE IN BID TO CHANGE SHOPPING PATTERNS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By VICTORIA COLLIVER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The planned merger of two of the more successful
on-line grocers is intended to strengthen the virtual supermarket
industry that so far has not been able to turn a profit.
</P>
<P>
   Webvan Group Inc. announced Monday it was buying HomeGrocer.com
Inc. in a deal valued at more than $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``This may be the biggest deal done yet in e-commerce,'' said
Shawn Milne, senior electronic commerce research analyst for
EOffering Corp. in San Francisco. ``These are two well-funded
companies realizing one-plus-one can be three, not two.''
</P>
<P>
   It is still uncertain whether shoppers will switch from the
checkout lane to the keyboard in sufficient numbers to make the
industry profitable. Indeed, the two companies and several others
that are either in the home-delivery grocery business or are
experimenting with it have only a tiny presence in the market.
</P>
<P>
   Still, George Shaheen, the chief executive of Webvan, sounded
confident in a conference call with analysts.
</P>
<P>
   ``This merger will allow us to tighten our focus on changing
customer behavior,'' he said, ``by replacing a trip to the store
with giving them back their most precious commodity _ time.''
</P>
<P>
   The industry is in its early stages. Kirkland, Wash.-based
HomeGrocer began delivering to customers in the Seattle area in
June 1998, and now serves six markets. Webvan, of Foster City,
Calif., started in the San Francisco area a year ago and has
expanded into three markets.
</P>
<P>
   But compared with the total $440 billion in supermarket sales,
on-line grocery buying accounted for less than 0.1 percent, or $340
million, of those sales last year, according to the Boston
Consulting Group.
</P>
<P>
   The research group predicts sales for this year will reach $860
million, or 0.2 percent of the market.
</P>
<P>
   ``What matters more for the on-line grocery business is the
percentage of an individual city they have,'' said James Vogtle,
Boston Consulting's e-commerce research director.
</P>
<P>
   The grocery business is typically a low-margin business, with
on-line deliveries of perishable items considered a logistical
nightmare. But according to analysts, an on-line grocer only needs
2 to 4 percent of the customers in a particular market to make
money.
</P>
<P>
   Webvan declined to provide market penetration figures.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of both companies plunged after the merger announcement.
Webvan, which went public last November, fell $1.41, or 16.1
percent, to $7.31 per share. Shares of HomeGrocer, which went
public in March, dropped $1.22, or 15.1 percent, to $6.88 on the
Nasdaq.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts chalked up the stock price drop to some concerns over
merging the companies. But they were generally bullish on the
merger, primarily over the size of the combined company's war
chest: about $650 million in cash at the end of May this year.
</P>
<P>
   Although Webvan is the acquiring company, it is a little smaller
than HomeGrocer, with $16.3 million in revenues at the end of the
first quarter, compared with Home Grocer's $21.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   HomeGrocer has more than 100,000 customers at the end of the
quarter compared with 87,000 for Webvan in fewer markets. But
Webvan Group Inc., the name of the combined company, accounts for
most of the cash reserves.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got a lot of money in the bank so this could play out
for a couple of years,'' Vogtle said. ``They've got the time to
weather this out.''
</P>
<P>
   The merger also keeps the companies from overlapping in what
could have been as many as nine of 15 markets by the end of next
year. Webvan currently serves the San Francisco Bay Area and
Sacramento and the greater Atlanta area, with plans to expand to
Chicago in August.
</P>
<P>
   HomeGrocer already serves six markets: Dallas; Los Angeles,
Orange County and San Diego in California; Portland, Ore.; and
Seattle. The combined company plans to be in 13 metropolitan
markets by the end of this year and in 15 markets by this time next
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very positive deal,'' said Peter Swan, an analyst who
follows Webvan for Pacific Growth Equities in San Francisco.
``They're able to pool the capital and . . . they won't be laying
parallel track, to use railroad terminology.''
</P>
<P>
   As part of the deal, former Netscape Communications chief
executive Jim Barksdale will join the Webvan board of directors. He
was formerly on the board of HomeGrocer.
</P>
</TEXT>
