<HEADLINE>
A MOVING LOOK AT THE HOLOCAUST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Faces and voices. More than anything else, they tell of the
horror of the Holocaust in a new, ex tensive, and moving exhibit at
our Museum of the Month, London's Imperial War Museum.
</P>
<P>
   The 4,000-square-foot Holocaust Exhibition covers two floors and
uses original artifacts, documents, photos, and film to tell of the
Nazis' unrelenting program of genocide. The main focus is the
persecution of Jews in Europe, but other groups are included, such
as Gypsies, Poles, Soviet prisoners of war, disabled people,
homosexuals, and prisoners of conscience. In developing the
exhibition, staff members visited other Holocaust displays and
memorials (including Boston's) around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Among the many items are a funeral cart, a section of a rail car
used for deportation, and a dissection table. But it is the people,
captured in period photos, letters, and survivors' filmed
testimony, who will move visitors the most. Included are:
</P>
<P>
   --Photos of Jewish families smiling, celebrating, playing, or
posing for formal portraits. Within a short time, few members of
those families would be alive.
</P>
<P>
   --The words of a 13-year-old, recalling his first day as a
refugee in Britain: ``I spent most of that day in and out of the
toilet so that no one could see the tears rolling down my cheeks.''
</P>
<P>
   --A survivor, her voice breaking, remembering ``the screams from
the mothers who are separated from their children, from the boys,
their sons, from their husbands; it was just terrible.''
</P>
<P>
   --A photo of an 8-year-old girl in a First Communion dress. She
was actually a Jew, taken in by a Catholic family, and the photo
was displayed to fool her persecutors.
</P>
<P>
   --Another survivor, asking a question that perhaps has no
answer: ``How can you forgive the unforgivable?''
</P>
<P>
   The Holocaust Exhibition was opened this month by Queen
Elizabeth and is the final stage in redeveloping the Lambeth Road
building that was once the Bethlehem Royal Hospital for the Insane,
better known as Bedlam. The museum stresses that it is more about
social history than tanks, guns, and planes. But you will find
those, too, including such items as a massive V-2 rocket, twin
cannons at the entrance, and planes flown by both sides in World
War I and II. There are galleries of war art and interactive
exhibits that show what it was like to fight in a trench or
experience the bombing of Britain from a shelter.
</P>
<P>
   Prices are about $9 for adults, $7.50 for students, and free for
children. The Holocaust Exhibition is not recommended for younger
children, however. For more information, call 44-20-7416-5320 or
visit www.iwm.org.uk. For information on all London attractions,
call 800-462-2748 or visit www.londontown.com. A new Web site is
www.londonelite.com. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Meanwhile, in Raleigh: ``One Voice: From the Pen of Anne Frank'' is
the newest exhibit at Exploris, an interactive museum in Raleigh,
N.C. Displays and video clips help convey the family's experience
in hiding in Holland during World War II and the hope for a better
future that Anne expressed in her famous diary. For more
information, call 919-834-4040 or visit www.exploris.org. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Travel Trivia: Which is farther north _ the American side of
Niagara Falls or Canada's Horsehoe Falls? (Answer at end of
column.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
In a name: The Canary Islands were named by the Romans after the
wild dogs (canariae) that lived there. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Attention, TV addicts: Bathrooms in the new and luxurious Park
Hyatt Chicago have TVs with 7-inch liquid crystal display screens
mounted on walls near the tubs. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Quotable: ``A good part of all longing to travel consists in a
yearning for people one has never seen, a lust for the new _ to
look into strange eyes, strange faces, to rejoice in unknown human
types and manners'' _ Thomas Mann, German novelist.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Today's loopy law: North Dakota forbids serving beer and pretzels
at the same time in any bar or restaurant. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Royal indeed: The Royal Suite at the Churchill Inter-Continental is
London's largest hotel suite, at 885 square feet, and possibly its
most lavish. It has four bedrooms (each with a marble bathroom), a
dining room for up to 10 guests, a lounge, study, and kitchen. The
two master bedrooms have private balconies, and one of the bedrooms
converts into a well-equipped gym, with a personal trainer on call.
The cost: about $5,600 a night. For more information, call
44-0-7486-5800, fax 44-0-20-7486-1255, or e-mail churchill(at)
</P>
<P>
   interconti.com. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Or your money back: Biztravel.com is guaranteeing the on-time
performance of five airlines _ American, Continental, US Airways,
British Airways, and Air France _ or the Web company will give the
following refunds: Any flight arriving at the gate more than 30
minutes late, $100; more than an hour, $200; more than two hours, a
full refund. There are also refunds for flight cancellations, seat
assignments that are not honored, requested meals that are not
available, and lost baggage. For details, visit www.biztravel.com. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Did you guess it? The American side. (With thanks to faithful
contributor Mike Schuster of Foxborough, Mass., who cites the AAA
Ontario Tourbook map.)
</P>
