<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 13:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6158 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k BC-MONTINI-AZR &LR;      06-27 0580
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-AZR </SLUG>
  
 BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    BARBECUED SHRIMP ON STATE'S MENU(a) 
 &HT;    (Moving in ``K'' category) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By E.J. MONTINI(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In this era of dot-coms, cellular phones and the designated
hitter, one of the many primitive skills to be cultivated and
refined by civilized men and women is the art of the human
sacrifice. Particularly children.
</P>
<P>
   During the past three weeks, members of the Arizona Legislature
have been offering up one child per day to the gods of
stubbornness, self-importance, pride and stupidity.
</P>
<P>
   It began earlier this month, when Gov. Jane Hull called
lawmakers into special session to address the state's growing
education crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone agreed that something had to be done. Schools statewide
are in dire need of repair. There is a shortage of qualified
teachers, due in large part to the shortage of decent wages.
</P>
<P>
   A new testing system called AIMS was implemented before some of
the standards it requires were introduced in the classroom. And, in
just about every education survey conducted by just about every
public policy organization, Arizona ranks somewhere near the
bottom.
</P>
<P>
   When faced with such an obvious disaster, the governor and
legislators sprang into action.
</P>
<P>
   They compiled all the available statistics. They consulted with
educators and administrators. They spoke to financial and
governmental experts. They accumulated mounds of input from
interested members of the public. They had their staffs take all
this material, combine it, condense it and forge it into a workable
legislative package.
</P>
<P>
   Then, they ignored it.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Jeff Groscost didn't like the governor's proposal
to increase the sales tax. He decided the best position he could
take was one that had him facing Hull's office, sticking out his
tongue. The governor, in turn, sent out such lackeys as Lisa Graham
Keegan, state superintendent of public instruction, to call
Groscost's counterproposal a ``joke.''
</P>
<P>
   On and on it went.
</P>
<P>
   The governor blamed Groscost for stalling. The speaker blamed
the governor for not lining up the support she needed for her plan
before the session started.
</P>
<P>
   The cost to taxpayers for a single day of the special session is
reported to be $5,200.
</P>
<P>
   In most Arizona school districts, that's more than it costs to
educate one child for a year.
</P>
<P>
   Each passing day, it was as if lawmakers stuck a skewer through
one of Arizona's school-age shrimp and tossed him on the barbie.
</P>
<P>
   During the past three weeks, one kid per day has been sacrificed
while Maricopa County lawmakers collect $35 a day in expenses and
those from outside the county get $60.
</P>
<P>
   One boy or girl per day has become a burnt offering while
grown-ups claiming to have the interests of children at heart
continue pointing fingers at one another.
</P>
<P>
   More than five grand a day has gone up in smoke while
legislators bicker over how to put out the fire.
</P>
<P>
   And in the end, it won't matter a bit because the folks at the
Capitol are going to pass the buck. Because their lack of brains is
matched only by their lack of guts, our elected officials will
refer the final education proposal to the November ballot.
</P>
<P>
   That way, the people who spent the past three weeks sacrificing
one child per day will give you the chance to burn them all at
once.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
