<DOCNO> NYT20000627.0110 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 13:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6160 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-TUTU-AZR &LR;      06-27 0438
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TUTU-AZR </SLUG>
  
 BC-TUTU-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    TUTU URGES REVERING, NOT JUST RESPECTING, EACH OTHER(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By MAUREEN JENKINS(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   .
</P>
<P>
   ``Ethnicity, skin color, all these are total irrelevancies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that invests all of us with a value that can't be
(measured) is that each of us is created in the image of God.''
</P>
<P>
   South African Archbishop and Nobel Peace Prize winner Desmond
Tutu brought a message of unity, tolerance and respect to a crowd
of more than 1,000 at the Arizona Biltmore on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   The members of the crowd at the $250-per-plate benefit for
Catholic Charities' Foundation for Senior Living and Catholic
Social Service were more diverse in age, race and background than
those typically seen at major fund-raisers.
</P>
<P>
   Prominent community leaders were plentiful. But thanks to
anonymous and corporate donors who provided free and discounted
tickets, young people and non-famous folks got the chance to
witness living history in their hometown. And a multiracial mass
choir, which marched in carrying candles and singing a South
African religious tune, set the stage for the archbishop's speech.
</P>
<P>
   Next to Nelson Mandela, 68-year-old Tutu probably served as the
world's most enduring symbol of hope during South Africa's
apartheid regime. More recently, the cleric has headed his nation's
Truth and Reconciliation Commission, helping heal the scars left by
decades of institutional racism and discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   To Phoenix, Tutu brought a message as relevant to 21st-century
America as to his post-apartheid homeland. But despite the often
political nature of Tutu's message, he ultimately sounded like a
man of God.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fantastic thing is that each of us is a God-carrier. We
shouldn't just respect each other - we should revere each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Tutu will soon return to South Africa. His Phoenix visit
followed a two-year visiting professorship at Emory University's
Chandler School of Theology in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   But in hopes of extending Tutu's message of tolerance and
justice beyond Monday's speech, the city of Scottsdale's Office of
Diversity &AMP; Dialogue will host a regional youth Town Hall meeting
on Aug. 12. A videotape of Tutu's speech also will be made
available to Valley schools.
</P>
<P>
   During his speech, in fact, Tutu saluted the youth in the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``God has this wonderful characteristic of wanting to use young
people,'' Tutu said. ``God regards you as some of God's best
partners. So go for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Reach the reporter at Maureen.Jenkins(a)ArizonaRepublic.com or
(602) 444-8307.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-27-00 1344EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
