<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 13:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6161 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-PSYCHOLOGY-TODAY25-CO     06-27 0487
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PSYCHOLOGY-TODAY25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Obsessive people hiding anxiety
 &HT;    By Hap LeCrone
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``This traffic at lunch time is getting unbearable,'' he
thought, as he drove to his favorite restaurant for lunch. ``Those
dimwits at City Hall don't even try to coordinate the traffic
lights to speed things up.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, sliding into a booth at the restaurant, he noticed that
someone had spilled ketchup at some point in the past all over the
menu, and it needed to be replaced. As the waitress annoyingly
popped her gum while taking his order he noticed the man in the
next booth crudely applying his toothpick to his teeth like a
crowbar. ``I might as well write this lunch time off as another bit
of evidence that the world is full of idiots and imbeciles and I
need to move to another planet.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time he returned to work he had a pounding headache,
which became more severe that afternoon when his secretary
misspelled several words and asked to leave work early.
</P>
<P>
   Most of us pay lip service to the fact that the world is
unpredictable and imperfect _ but that's as far as it goes for
many. For the obsessive personality, life's main goal is to remedy
the uncertainties, injustices and imperfections that stand between
them and a safe and happy passage through life.
</P>
<P>
   High blood pressure, frequent indigestion, insomnia and bad
moods are but but some of the inevitable and necessary scars that
they feel must be endured along the way through life.
</P>
<P>
   The core of obsessiveness is the need for control. The finely
honed and sharpened tools of conscientiousness, thoroughness and
attention to detail are rewarded in our society by recognition in
the forms of material wealth, power and bountiful accolades. After
all, who wants a sloppy accountant, an irresponsible physician or a
mediocre minister? Words like balance, moderation, compromise and
flexibility conjure up images of weakness, inadequacy and even
disgust to the obsessive.
</P>
<P>
   If the need for control is the fuel that drives the obsessive,
then what is the source of the fuel? Like the magma that lies just
beneath the outer crust of the earth, unbridled anxiety directs the
need for control. Our obsessive is a thinly armored bowl of
quivering Jell-O. Fear that loss of control will result in such
horrible experiences as embarrassment, demotion, defeat or failure,
the obsessive makes focusing on reducing uncertainty and
imperfection the top priority.
</P>
<P>
   If you are an obsessive and want to begin changing, recognize
that the process of change is usually slow. I will return to this
topic again in future columns.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Hap LeCrone is a clinical psychologist. If you have
questions or topics you would like Dr. LeCrone to discuss, write
him at 4555 Lake Shore Drive, Waco 76710 or e-mail him at
hlecrone(at)aol.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
