<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 14:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6193 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r p BC-NADER-CAMPAIGN-HNS &LR;      06-27 0585
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NADER-CAMPAIGN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     NADER TARGETS GORE, BUSH; SEEKS SPOT IN NATIONAL DEBATES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DEMIAN BULWA  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Green Party presidential candidate Ralph Nader
energetically ripped the Republican and Democratic front-runners
and said his record as a corporate watchdog and political reformer
should impress voters.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing in San Francisco and Oakland on Monday, the consumer
activist called his candidacy a ``serious run,'' unlike his
shoestring bid four years ago. He deflected reports that his
campaign's biggest impact could be to steal votes from Vice
President Al Gore, the presumptive Democratic nominee, especially
in liberal Northern California. Texas Gov. George W. Bush is a
shoo-in for the Republican nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were worried about hurting Al Gore's campaign, I wouldn't
be running for president against Al Gore and George W. Bush,''
Nader said. He added his votes would come from blue-collar workers,
the poor, the young and the old, among others.
</P>
<P>
   Nader, 66, said he would raise $5 million for the current
campaign, compared with $5,000 in 1996, when he garnered just
700,000 votes nationwide. An aide said Nader had about $900,000 as
of Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``That $5 million will be the equivalent of $15 million when you
compare it to the other candidates' profligate spending,'' Nader
said, lacing nearly every sentence with blasts of the major
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Nader spoke at the Ariba Juntos job-training center in San
Francisco. Later, he greeted hundreds of supporters in an Oakland
ballroom with U.S. Senate candidate Medea Benjamin and Oakland City
Council hopeful Rebecca Kaplan, Green Party candidates who echoed
Nader's belief that voters want to see strong third options.
</P>
<P>
   A national consumer advocate for more than 30 years, Nader was
nominated Sunday at the Green Party's convention in Denver. Members
of the 16-year-old, grass-roots organization say he has championed
many of their core values, and also view him as a vehicle for party
legitimacy.
</P>
<P>
   If he can win 5 percent of the vote in the fall election, the
party could qualify for federal matching campaign funds in the 2004
presidential race. Polls in recent months have given Nader up to 7
percent popularity nationally, and up to 9 percent in the West.
</P>
<P>
   Nader said he would spend his campaign pushing for publicly
financed elections _ he is accepting only individual contributions
of up to $2,000_ universal health care and more protections for
laborers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wants to make change, and I think (his campaign) will go a
significant way toward changing the consciousness of Americans,''
said Rose Ann DeMoro, executive director of the California Nurses
Association, which has endorsed Nader. ``When Al Gore starts
talking like Ralph Nader, I think Ralph Nader will feel like he has
been massively successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Nader said his campaign would get a major boost in this year's
race if he could confront the front-runners on national television.
The major debates, though, are limited to those winning at least 15
percent popularity in polls. Nader proposed lowering the figure to
5 percent or including candidates with a ``demonstrated record.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's when the focus of the public is most intense. . . . We
have to break through on this,'' said Nader, whose running mate is
American Indian activist Winona LaDuke. ``Americans are going to
fall asleep watching these debates.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
