<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Wednesday, June 28:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CUBA-U.S. (Washington) _ After five hours of negotiations,
Republican leaders in the House of Representatives agreed early
Tuesday to allow sales of U.S.-grown food and medicine to Cuba,
thereby relaxing the sanctions that Washington invoked against the
communist regime in Havana 38 years ago. By Lizette Alvarez.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT1.
</P>
<P>
   (See also CUBAN-BOY and CUBAN-BOY-LOBBY, below)
</P>
<P>
   ZIMBABWE-ELECTIONS (Harare) _ Developments on the parliamentary
elections held over the weekend. By Rachel L. Swarns.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE-HUMAN-RIGHTS (Warsaw, Poland) _ In another slap at the
United States, France said Tuesday that it would not endorse a
Warsaw Declaration supporting universal concepts of human rights,
drawn up at a U.S.-organized conference of 108 democracies. By Jane
Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE-EUROPE (Berlin) _ French President Jacques Chirac called
Tuesday for a core group of European Union countries to lead the
way to greater European integration, and for a European
constitution. By Suzanne Daley.
</P>
<P>
   SYRIA-POLITICS (Beirut, Lebanon) _ A look at the succession of
Bashar Assad, who was anointed by Parliament Tuesday as the sole
presidential candidate in a July 10 referendum. By John Kifner.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-BELARUS (Moscow) _ Russian parliamentary leaders said
Tuesday that they are making an appeal to the Belarussian
president, Alexsander Lukashenko _ who supports a Belarus-Russia
union _ to allow the country's opposition parties to participate in
all aspects of elections this fall. By Patrick E. Tyler.
</P>
<P>
   SWISS-MONEY-LAUNDERING (Geneva) _ Switzerland reported Tuesday
that there had been a five-fold increase in a year-long period in
funds frozen for suspected money laundering and said the rise
demonstrated a determination to get tough on criminals. By
Elizabeth Olson.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-BRITAIN (Beijing) _ China condemned the British government
Tuesday for allowing Taiwan's former president, Lee Teng-hui, to
visit Britain, calling him a ``troublemaker'' who continues to work
for Taiwan's independence from the mainland. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   POPE-JEWS (Rome) _ Jewish groups are mounting a campaign against
the beatification of Pius IX, the 19th-century pope who kidnapped a
Jewish child and raised him as a Catholic. By Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-MIRANDA-ASSESS (Washington) _ The reaffirmation of the
Miranda decision says as much about the Supreme Court and what its
focus is as it does about the rights of criminal suspects. A news
analysis by Steven Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-RENO (Washington) _ Attorney General Janet Reno testifies
before the Senate Judiciary Comittee about campaign finance
investigation. By David Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-SPEND (Washington) _ It seemed simple at first. The
Clinton administration had proposed a $5 billion emergency spending
bill to cover, among other things, money to Colombia to fight drug
trafficking. But the aid package is mired in turf battles and even
abortion politics. By Steven A. Holmes.
</P>
<P>
   ARMY-RECRUITING (Washington) _ The Army is to announce new
recruiting strategies, which are expected to include the naming of
an advertising agency to handle the Army account. By Steven Lee
Myers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN-BOY (Dateline to come) _ Elian Gonzalez could return to
his native Cuba as early as Wednesday if the Supreme Court rules
against the last attempt by his U.S. relatives to keep him in the
United States, an appeal filed on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN-BOY-LOBBY (Washington) _ The Cuban-American Foundation,
expecting Elian Gonzalez to leave America this week, has announced
an ad campaign against members of Congress who favor easing
sanctions. By Christopher Marquis.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-SCHOOL-UNIFORMS (Undated) _ San Diego, Calif., is the only
major U.S. city where all children are required to wear school
uniforms. By James Sterngold.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (``p'' code)
</P>
<P>
   GORE (Dateline to ku, Pa.) _ Vice President Al Gore lays out his
plans for the environment and the nation's energy policy. By Frank
Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-WELFARE (Wayne, Mich.) _ George W. Bush talks about welfare
to work programs. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS (Undated) _ Political news and notes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-AFRICA-AIDS (Undated) _ An estimated 19 million people have
been killed and a further 34 million infected _ 5 million last year
_ by the AIDS virus, which is wreaking social and economic
devastation in the most stricken African nations. A U.N. report
paints an almost unremittingly grim picture; in some countries in
southern Africa, it predicts, half or more of people now under 15
will succumb to the disease. By Lawrence K. Altman.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT2, and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   FDA-OVER-THE-COUNTER (Washington) _ Spurred by two
pharmaceutical companies that want to take their
cholesterol-lowering medications over the counter, the Food and
Drug Administration is taking a broad look at whether many more
medicines _ from antibiotics to birth control pills _ should be
made available without a doctor's prescription. Beginning with
public hearings Wednesday and Thursday, the agency will launch a
reexamination of the way it regulates over-the-counter drugs, the
first such policy review in nearly three decades. The last one, in
1972, prompted the agency to move more than 600 drugs from
prescription to non-prescription status. By Sheryl Gay Stolberg.
(1300 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT4.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-COASTAL-EROSION (Undated) _ In a report to Congress, the
Federal Emergency Management Agency says a quarter or more of
houses within 500 feet of the Atlantic and Gulf coasts will be lost
to erosion in the next 60 years, putting an intolerable strain on
the nation's flood insurance program. The agency recommends
extensive mapping of erosion hazards and alterations of the
insurance program's rate structure to reflect erosion risk. Coastal
scientists praise the report; representatives of some coastal towns
call it an unwarranted federal attempt to force people off the
beach. By Cornelia Dean.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT3, and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   WORLDCOM-SPRINT (Undated) _ The Justice Department has filed
suit to block the proposed merger of WorldCom and Sprint, the
nation's second- and third-largest phone companies, on grounds it
would increase prices for millions of consumers. By Seth Schiesel
and David Leonhardt.
</P>
<P>
   GENOME-PATENTS (Undated) _ Long before scientists had completed
the task of reading the human genome, parts of it had already been
claimed for commerce. In what has often been compared to a land
grab, companies and universities have filed for patents on hundreds
of thousands of genes and gene fragments. Amid concerns that such
patents are being granted too liberally and that they could hinder
innovation, the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office is about to
implement new guidelines that will make it harder to patent genes.
But critics say the new rules are still too lax. By Andrew Pollack.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   GENOME-INVESTORS (Undated) _ The sequencing of the human genome
is often described as a triumph akin to landing on the moon. For
investors, that might not be the most comforting analogy: Three
decades after Apollo 11, no one has yet made a profit on going to
the moon. A similar business challenge faces Celera Genomics. By
Andrew Pollack.
</P>
<P>
   ACCOUNTING-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The column: The Securities
and Exchange Commission will disclose proposed rules on the kinds
of consulting services that accounting firms may offer. By Floyd
Norris.
</P>
<P>
   MEDIAMETRIX-JUPITER (Undated) _ In a transaction that would
combine two prominent Internet research concerns, Media Metrix
agreed to buy Jupiter Communications for about $414 million in
stock. By Barnaby J. Feder.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS-TRAVEL (Undated) _ The business travel column. By Nancy
Sharkey.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-U.S.-BANK (Tokyo) _ An investment group led by Wilbur L.
Ross, the U.S. corporate turnaround specialist, has won a bid to
take over Tokyo Sowa Bank Ltd., a once-thriving regional Japanese
bank seized by the government a year ago because of bad loans. The
takeover is the second Japanese bank acquired by Ross and only the
third to be purchased by any foreigner. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MANAGEMENT PAGE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ACCOUNTING-EDUC (Undated) _ Competing for the smallest pool of
college graduates of accounting programs in more than a decade,
many of the nation's largest accounting firms and associations have
begun promoting their profession in high schools. With scholarships
and internships in hand, they are hoping to resuscitate a field
that is rapidly losing recruits to the wonders of technology and
the glamour of being entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
   WORLDLYINVESTOR (Undated) _ Lewis Gersh, the 32-year-old chief
executive of worldlyinvestor.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  (``k'' code)
</P>
<P>
   Paul Krugman's ``Reckonings.''
</P>
<P>
   Maureen Dowd is on vacation.
