<P>
   RENO-GORE _ Coverage of Janet Reno's appearance before a Senate
subcommittee looking into possible wrongdoing by Vice President Al
Gore. (Foskett, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 25.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH - The end is finally in sight for the Bush fund-raising
effort that has shattered records by collecting more than $92
million. It will shut down in mid-July as the campaign shifts into
a federally funded operation after the GOP convention. But Bush
isn't done yet. A fund-raising letter in the mail this week seeks
to milk another $100 to $150 out of donors who have not hit the
$1,000 maximum. Bush says he needs it for TV ads. (Herman, Austin
American-Statesman). 25.
</P>
<P>
   EROSION _ WASHINGTON _ The Federal Emergency Managment Agency
releases a five-year study of the nation's coastal erosion problem.
(O'Dell, Cox Nnews Service). 18.
</P>
<P>
   EVERGLADES _ WASHINGTON _ Sen. Bob Smith, chairman of the
Environment and Publics Works Comittee and Sens. Bob Graham and
Connie Mack release details of the Everglades restoration bill they
will vote on tomorrow in the committee. (Lipman, Cox News Service).
18.
</P>
<P>
   EDUCATORS-COMPUTING _ ATLANTA _ At the National Educational
Computing Conference in Atlanta this week, such heavyweights as
U.S. Education Secretary Richard Riley and Intel CEO Craig Barrett
have preached the value of technology in the classroom. At the
periphery, though, is a lone voice of caution: that of William
Rukeyser, head of an anti-technology group called Learning in the
Real World. He says that research hasn't proven that technology
improves learning, and he says it's too expensive for cash-strapped
schools. ``Everybody loves to play with new toys,'' he says. ``But
the fact is, when it comes to technology in schools, there is no
Santa Claus.'' His is not a popular view at the technology
conference this week. WITH PHOTO (Rukeyser). (Judd, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 12.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-CHILDHEALTH _ The first time Carla Savannah applied for
Medicaid she was pregnant. She got a lecture, but no health
coverage. ``My son's now 1 and I'm still not covered,'' said
Savannah, 18, of Austin. ``I just have bills.'' Despite three or
four tries, Savannah has not successfully navigated the complex
Medicaid system, dominated by poor women and children entitled by
federal law to health care. Although Medicaid is intended as a
safety net for the state's most vulnerable residents, the poorest
children in Texas have the hardest time getting covered. Texas
maintains some of the nation's most stringent Medicaid rules. The
restrictions are in sharp contrast to Texas' new Children's Health
Insurance Program, which serves the working poor whose incomes
generally are higher than Medicaid families. Insurance Commissioner
Jose Montemayor plans Tuesday to present the results of a survey of
Texas health insurance carriers that offer coverage to children.
(Roser, Austin American-Statesman). 35. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   POL-TICKER _ A brief roundup of the day's campaign events,
pulled from Cox staff and wire reports. (Cox News Service) ETA: 6
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   US-CUBA _ WASHINGTON _ A bill partially lifting sanctions
against communist Cuba may have officially hit the fast track
Tuesday, after House leaders agreed on a structuring of the
legislation. The bill now heads to a conference committee with a
Senate that has already indicated its approval, and could wind up
with a pact by week's end. President Clinton has also said that he
would sign the bill in its current form. Developing. (Deans, Cox
News Service). 20.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-CARDENAS _ MEXICO CITY _ To some he's the hero of
Mexico's impoverished and oppressed. To others he's in danger of
becoming the spoiler of an historic opportunity for democratic
change. Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, the spiritual leader of Mexico's left,
is running in third place as Mexicans prepare to elect a new
president on Sunday, according to most pre-election opinion
surveys. This is the third time Cardenas has tried to oust the PRI,
Mexico's ruling party. This time, however, Cardenas' underdog
campaign has been eclipsed by Vicente Fox, a conservative
opposition candidate whom polls show stands a credible chance of
defeating the PRI. Fox has alternately insulted and tried to woo
Cardenas to join his campaign. But at a huge rally here Sunday
Cardenas made it clear no 11th-hour deal will be cut. He bitterly
spurned Fox's latest public plea at his own rally the night before
to join him, and thus guarantee the PRI's defeat. (Ferris, Cox News
Service). 30.
</P>
<P>
   OPED/EDITORIAL
</P>
<P>
   EDITORIAL-GORE _ The Atlanta Constitution's lead editorial for
Wednesday will be on Vice President Al Gore. (The Atlanta
Constitution). 12.
</P>
<P>
   EDITORIAL-ELIAN _ Anticipating the Supreme Court will reject the
relative's bid to keeo Elian here, we say a fond farewell to the
6-year-old boy and this whole mess. (The Atlanta Constitution). 9.
</P>
<P>
   EDITORIAL-MIRANDA _ With a touch of black-robed drama seldom
seen in the U.S. Supreme Court chambers, Chief Justice William
Rehnquist took center stage with an aplomb for which he will long
be remembered. (The Atlanta Constitution). 8.
</P>
<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ Two matters that had seemed among the Great
Immutables of American life are showing distinct signs of wobble.
It is unclear where the startlingly sudden conversation about the
death penalty is headed, but the drift in what is loosely called
gay rights seems fairly clear. The surprise there is that the
momentum is accumulating so quickly. (Teepen, Cox News Service.)
MOVED MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ Ever noticed how many things you buy have a
price tag that ends in 9? The reason, of course, is the psychology
of marketing to make things seem less expensive than theyactually
are. Howard Kleinberg wonders why consumers don't seem to want to
do anything about it. (Kleinberg, Cox News Service.) MOVED MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   SCHUETT-COLUMN _ GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ Chairs have always been a
significant part of my life _ mainly, I guess, because I'm lazy and
much prefer sitting down to standing up. Somehow, my history seems
defined by a progression of chairs _ rather like reading the rings
of an ancient tree. (Schuett, Cox News Service). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   JOEMURRAY-COLUMN28 _ Column from Dreamsville: In the ``old''
days on a farm in Ohio, eating out used to mean a home-cooked meal
on a table under an apple tree in the yard. (Joe Murray, Cox
Newspapers senior writer).
</P>
<P>
   YOUNG-COLUMN _ ABC, which in its quest for someone
nontraditional and provocative has made a mistake. It's not that
Dennis Miller isn't great. He is. I will watch and listen with
interest. That's the problem. I'm not the target audience it wants.
The best man for the job was one with some blood on his lapel.
(Young, Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS
</P>
<P>
   CABLE-SETTOPBOXES _ July 1 is the deadline for makers of cable
set top boxes to come out with a box that can be sold directly to
consumers in stores like Cirbuit City. This is government mandated
to try to foster competition in a market dominated by just two
players: Scientific Atlanta and General Instruments. But nobody
thinks consumers really want to buy set top boxes through retail
stores. (Brister, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 16.
</P>
<P>
   MONEYTALK _ Personal finance advice. This week: tax lowering
steps. (Ezell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   SALVATION-ARMY _ ATLANTA _ They wear uniforms and have military
rank. But this is no regular army. They don't carry weapons, but
Bibles, and they fight for Jesus. Members of the Salvation Army
will be spending a week in Atlanta, praying and planning for the
future of their organization. We capture what they are up to on
their first day in Atlanta. (GWhite, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
25. WITH PHOTOS.
