<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 14:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6216 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-ANGOLANS-ACTIVISTS-AR     06-27 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANGOLANS-ACTIVISTS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (a and i coding)  
 ACTIVISTS WORRY ABOUT CRIME'S LURE FOR ANGOLANS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANCIE LATOUR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROCKTON, Mass. _ Looking at Eulidio Monteiro, it's hard to tell
where the Cape Verde in him ends and the Angola in him begins.
</P>
<P>
   His face burns caramel, part almond brown from his Cape Verdean
mother, part deep coffee from his Angolan father. His hair doesn't
so much coil as wave, weaving a story of two peoples whose shared
history is evident even worlds away, in a Brockton parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``We come because Cape Verdeans were here,'' said Monteiro, 22,
who left his parents behind and came to the United States in 1998
from the Angolan capital of Luanda. ``They say, `Come to Brockton,
it's nice.' So, we come.''
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of miles of African coastline separate the Cape Verde
Islands from Angola. But common culture has long united the former
Portuguese colonies, cemented by a huge migration of Cape Verdeans
to Angola in the 1950s. Now, a growing stream of Angolans, whose
homeland has been ravaged by civil war, has followed Cape Verdeans
to the United States seeking stability.
</P>
<P>
   But in the Boston area _ the largest hub for Cape Verdeans, and
now Angolans, in the United States _ activists in the midst of a
losing battle against Cape Verdean youth violence are driving a
major effort to keep young Angolan men from following some of their
cultural kin into a cycle of crime, prison, and deportation.
</P>
<P>
   The need for prevention was punctuated 11 days ago in Boston,
when five Cape Verdean teenagers allegedly chased down a Dorchester
teenager and one of them, a juvenile, shot him to death. The
shooting capped six months of increasing violence in Dorchester and
Roxbury, as well as Brockton, Randolph, and Rhode Island.
</P>
<P>
   So far, activists say, incidents among Angolans have remained
low, maybe a dozen in the past three years, when the flow of
Angolans to Massachusetts began in earnest.
</P>
<P>
   But the number of incidents is growing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want the number to stay small,'' said the Rev. Filipe
Teixeira, an activist whose background is part Angolan and Cape
Verdean. ``But we are already seeing some serious incidents
happening with Angolans, including the aggravated felonies and drug
charges that classify them to be deported.''
</P>
<P>
   Teixeira and other Cape Verdean community leaders as well as
police have stressed that the ongoing violence among Cape Verdeans
involves only a small group of feuding teens.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Immigration and Naturalization Service, six
Angolans were deported for criminal reasons from 1993 to 1997, the
latest years for which figures were available. About 75 Cape
Verdeans were deported in that period.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the INS office in Boston, Paula Grenier, said
it was unclear whether any Angolans were in detention awaiting
deportation.
</P>
<P>
   Among the most recent deportations of Angolans, Teixeira said,
was that of Bruno Edison, 21, of Brockton, whose court records show
that he began working as a salesman, then piled up misdemeanors
before being convicted on assault and firearms charges. He was
deported six months ago, according to Teixeira.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is so much activity going on with Cape Verdeans and guns
in the Brockton area,'' Teixeira said. ``This is where a lot of
Angolans are landing. They get there with no language, no housing,
nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   As they gravitate to Cape Verdeans for help with everything from
apartments to home-cooked hot sauce, Angolans are particularly
vulnerable to falling into violence, Teixeira and others say.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the new arrivals are men 16 to 30 years old. Almost all
come without their parents and with few language skills, banding
together to rent affordable apartments.
</P>
<P>
   Many are more than familiar with guns, having served in or
narrowly escaped serving in a 30-year-old civil conflict between
guerrilla groups and the government.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to give these kids support and really watch how they
are mixing with some of these Cape Verdean youth,'' said Herberto
Agostinho, owner of Angolan BBQ in New Bedford. ``We have to make
them aware of the laws in the US, to steer them away from
violence.''
</P>
<P>
   Agostinho, 31, of Fairhaven, is an elder of this young
community. He, his wife, Selma Agostinha, and Teixeira founded the
Angolan Association of the USA, which seeks to end war in Angola as
it shepherds Angolan youth who have left war behind. The group of
about 50 began meeting in April.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in his restaurant, Agostinho said that helping Angolan
youths is a delicate dance to avoid stereotypes between the two
close cultures.
</P>
<P>
   Agostinho and Teixeira have quietly encouraged Angolans to leave
Brockton and to find housing in New Bedford or other nearby areas.
At a meeting of the association last month, leaders went to pains
to explain how teens should avoid trouble without talking about the
trouble itself.
</P>
<P>
   Underlying the conversations about Cape Verdeans and crime, many
Angolans here say, is a longstanding belief that Cape Verdean
culture has tended more toward violence and drug abuse than Angolan
culture _ both at home and abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Mendes, 18, an Angolan who lives in New Bedford and works
at Agostinho's restaurant, said he has tried to draw a line between
himself and some Cape Verdean youths.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some are my friends, but some are always in trouble,'' he
said. ``They don't think what they could make by working hard is
enough. They want to make more. People in Angola are different.
Even at home, if you look at Cape Verdeans and Angolans in Portugal
or back home, we have never gone to this violence.''
</P>
<P>
   Monteiro, born of Cape Verdean and Angolan parents, said he
hopes the new association will be a uniting force to galvanize the
Angolan community _ something many say is missing among Cape
Verdeans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very sad,'' he said. ``We hear about Cape Verdeans who
come here and get into drugs. I don't know why. It's a thing I
don't like to think about, because they help us, too.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-27-00 1452EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000627.0122 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 14:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6222 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-IMMIGRATION-RACISM-BO     06-27 1471
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMMIGRATION-RACISM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMMIGRATION LAW CRITICIZED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES A. RADIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tough new US immigration policies have triggered a wave of
deportations that are disproportionately affecting people of color
and refugees from countries whose relations with the United States
have soured, according to immigration activists and attorneys.
</P>
<P>
   The legal changes, which are based on two bills passed in 1996,
have made it easier for the US Immigration and Naturalization
Service to deport a broad range of people.
</P>
<P>
   INS officials say they are applying the law fairly, but
activists say cases are piling up that indicate that some races,
and people from unpopular nations, are routinely deported, while
others who commit similar offenses are not vigorously pursued.
</P>
<P>
   There are no definitive statistics. But consider: The number of
deportations in the Boston INS district rose 22 percent between
1996 and 1999. Deportations of Cape Verdeans rose 100 percent, and
of Jamaicans, 66 percent. The percentage of Britons and Russians
deported did not change at all.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, the number of deportations to Mexico have tripled,
to 150,000 last year; deportations to Latin American countries have
doubled, to between 3,000 and 4,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, authorities deported 32 people from Ireland and 86
from Russia _ nations that are widely recognized as having large
numbers of undocumented immigrants in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a general lack of evenhandedness'' in the application
of immigration law, ``and it is based on race and on politics,''
said Daniel Kanstroom, director of the Immigration and Asylum
Project at Boston College Law School. A prime example, he said, is
that authorities ``have not sought to target or infiltrate the
Irish as they have the Cape Verdeans. There are clearly as many
illegal Irish.''
</P>
<P>
   Sister Lena Deevy, director of Boston's Irish Immigration
Center, which works with diverse groups of immigrants, contends
that how the law is applied ``depends on the political relationship
between the US government and the country of origin. . . . It has
little to do with human rights. `Give me your tired, your poor' is
fine as long as it fits in with what (the leadership of) this
country wants.''
</P>
<P>
   Armando Baptista, Mahnaz Samadi, and Jezdimir Topic are
individuals whose cases illustrate what is happening.
</P>
<P>
   Baptista, 25, came from the West African nation of Cape Verde as
a young boy, had several brushes with the law, and was on his way
to a career as a street thug in Boston until, at the urging of a
priest, he turned himself in, got a job, and started helping other
youths. But today he faces deportation. His offense: A barroom
brawl.
</P>
<P>
   Samadi came to the United States six years ago with the resume
of a hero: prisoner of the fundamentalist Muslim rulers of Iran,
torture victim, freedom fighter, refugee. But she could be thrown
out soon, wearing a very different label. She has been branded a
terrorist because years ago she was a member of the resistance to
Iran's fundamentalist Muslim regime.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is Topic. The ethnic Serb served as a guard at a camp
in Bosnia where women and girls were imprisoned and abused for
being Muslim. He committed the same technical offense as Samadi _
not disclosing a military affiliation to the INS. But while Samadi
and Baptista were jailed immediately for their alleged offenses,
Topic continues to live quietly in Everett, more than a year after
his past was revealed.
</P>
<P>
   When Samadi entered the country, she did not disclose on her
immigration forms that she was a member of Iran's National Council
of Resistance. If she had, she almost certainly would still have
been granted asylum, for she did state on the forms that she was
involved in efforts to overthrow the fundamentalists, a goal with
which the US government was sympathetic.
</P>
<P>
   Samadi became widely known in North America as a human rights
activist. But when she returned to the United States from a trip to
Canada on April 3, she was arrested on charges that she had
obtained asylum fraudulently, by not disclosing her membership in
the Iranian group.
</P>
<P>
   Years after Samadi left the council, and at a time when the
United States was attempting to court purported moderates in Iran's
ruling circles, the State Department declared the council a
terrorist organization. Now it considers Samadi deportable for not
having disclosed her association.
</P>
<P>
   Since her arrest, Samadi has been held in jails in New York,
Georgia, Alabama, and Virginia, often in remote locations where her
attorneys and supporters could not readily contact her.
</P>
<P>
   Her treatment at the hands of immigration authorities contrasts
with that of Topic, the Serb prison camp guard.
</P>
<P>
   Three former prisoners identified Topic as a guard on the basis
of photos taken of him at the door of his home, and the immigration
service promised to investigate. Steven Farquharson, regional
director of the immigration service, said Topic's file had no
indication that he had disclosed his military service.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he did not divulge'' such associations to immigration
officers overseas, ``it would be a very serious, major
consideration in revoking his refugee status and resulting in his
removal from the United States,'' Farquharson said. ``If all of
this is verified, this gentleman is going to face the serious
prospect of having his refugee status revoked.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, 16 months after Topic's past was disclosed, he remains
free, while Samadi is shuffled among rural Southern jails and is
denied bond while the case against her is processed.
</P>
<P>
   In response to inquiries about Topic, Farquharson said he
contacted immigration service headquarters and ``asked if they
could give me an update on what was going on and where the
investigation stood,'' but he received no response.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, I had tried to get a response long before this,'' he
said, ``and I did not get one.''
</P>
<P>
   Karen Kraushaar, a spokeswoman at immigration service
headquarters in Washington, first said she would not comment on
details of the cases, then said the reason for the difference in
treatment ``is really very simple. Any member of a known and
recognized terrorist organization is not eligible for admission.''
</P>
<P>
   The organization to which Samadi belonged ``is among those
groups that are recognized by the State Department'' as terrorist,
``so this is a national security issue.''
</P>
<P>
   She said it did not matter whether a refugee was a member of a
group only before that group was listed as terrorist because ``the
law is retroactive.''
</P>
<P>
   The US Constitution bars Congress from passing laws that
penalize behavior that occurred before the law was passed, but the
Supreme Court has ruled that the prohibition does not apply to
civil matters such as immigration cases, and that deportation is
not a punishment under the terms of the Constitution. Those rulings
facilitated deportations of Chinese laborers in the late 19th
century and of alleged communists during the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   These days, the targets of the State Department and immigration
service are more often immigrants and refugees from the Middle East
and Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Baptista is one of scores of Cape Verdeans targeted for
deportation in recent years, many for serious offenses, but many
others for relatively mild infractions that, under the 1996 laws,
were classified as ``aggravated felonies.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the guidance of a priest, the Rev. Filipe Teixeira,
Baptista turned himself in last year and was placed on probation
after, in legal parlance, he ``admitted to sufficient facts''
related to the assault charges against him. The admission was urged
by a lawyer despite Baptista's insistence that he was the victim of
an attack; the attorney subsequently said he did not know that the
admission could subject his client to mandatory deportation.
</P>
<P>
   Baptista got a job, adhered to the terms of his probation, and
began helping Teixeira reach out to other youths in trouble. But,
in February, he was arrested, jailed, and scheduled for deportation
hearings by the immigration service, which said it was acting on
information provided by a law enforcement agency it would not name.
</P>
<P>
   On June 16, Dorchester (Mass.) District Court Judge Sydney
Hanlon allowed Baptista to withdraw his admission, clearing the way
for a trial. If he is found not guilty, the grounds for deportation
will disappear. But it is unclear whether that trial can be
completed before his deportation hearing, which is scheduled for
July 25.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does seem to me that justice may not have been done,''
Hanlon said, explaining her reason for allowing the withdrawal.
``It seems justice may not be done in the future, but that is not
the issue before me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
