<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 14:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6228 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-SOLVING-CONFLICTS-HNS     06-27 1020
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOLVING-CONFLICTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     NUMBERS MAY ADD UP TO PEACE BETWEEN ARIZONA INDIAN TRIBES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ANDREW BROWNSTEIN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCHENECTADY, N.Y. _ For more than 120 years, the Navajo and Hopi
tribes have fought bitterly over 1.8 million acres in the northeast
corner of Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   To settle the dispute, they tried guns. They tried litigation.
But math?
</P>
<P>
   Meet Jamie Manygoats. A Navajo at Union College in Schenectady,
she hopes to succeed where Congress and the courts have failed.
</P>
<P>
   Using a formula patented by a Union professor, Manygoats's
senior thesis has sparked the interest of both sides with her
algebraic solution to the long and deadly conflict.
</P>
<P>
   It was an unlikely project for Manygoats, who despite growing up
in the ``Four Corners'' region of the Southwest was sheltered from
the dispute that had caused more forced relocation than the
internment of Japanese-Americans during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, I would drive with my father and we would see
abandoned houses,'' Manygoats recalled. ``I'd say `What a nice
house. Why aren't there any people there?'''
</P>
<P>
   During her junior year at Union, she became entranced by the
voila logic of Union mathematician Alan Taylor. Taylor's formula,
called ``adjusted winner,'' holds the promise of settling disputes
ranging from divorce to the religious unrest in the Middle East
with the simple application of high school algebra.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor took to Manygoats' idea of applying his work in conflict
resolution to the turmoil in her homeland. Convincing the leaders
of the Navajo and Hopi nations was another matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't take to it well,'' acknowledged Manygoats. ``For
most people, the idea of using math to solve a problem, especially
one with so many deep feelings, doesn't make sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Manygoats' thesis completed a historical arc begun by another
Union College student after he graduated more than 150 years ago:
Chester Arthur, the future president of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   It was Arthur, with hope of preventing Navajo incursions against
the Hopi, who set aside 2.5 million acres in Northeastern Arizona
for the Hopi in 1882. However, he also protected ``other Indians''
who might be settled there, a vagary that set off more than a
century of conflict between the village-dwelling Hopis and
scattered Navajo sheepherders who also occupied the land.
</P>
<P>
   In 1974, Congress sought a precise, geometric solution to the
problem. They split the area, inhabited almost entirely by Navajos,
into two equal sides. Those on the ``wrong side'' would be
relocated.
</P>
<P>
   In the decades since, about 13,900 Navajos and 100 Hopis have
been relocated at a total cost expected to exceed $500 million.
</P>
<P>
   The toll in human misery, of course, is much harder to quantify.
Some of the Navajos, who called themselves Dine (``The People''),
refused to leave the isolated, haunting land of towering mesas and
multicolored canyons.
</P>
<P>
   It is a conflict that Manygoats seems to have understood in her
blood.
</P>
<P>
   Even her name is tinged with the sad history of U.S. policy
toward American Indians. Her great-great grandfather herded more
goats than sheep, so that is the name the government gave him. Her
true name, she explained, is barely translatable into English, a
secret only to be shared with the man she marries.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is their homeland and they'll do anything to save it,''
Manygoats said. ``They've used guns. They have stayed on the ground
and refused to budge.''
</P>
<P>
   In completing her thesis for graduation, the test for Manygoats
was to keep her Navajo biases at bay. Of course, that was the major
appeal of using math to solve the problem: Both sides would have to
put aside their shared history and emotions in pursuit of an
objective goal.
</P>
<P>
   In the ``Win-Win Solution: Guaranteeing Fair Shares to
Everybody,'' Taylor and New York University Professor Steven Brams
expound on the mathematical process that landed them in the
Encyclopedia Brittanica.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of ``adjusted winner'' is to settle disputes in a
manner that is equitable, efficient and envy-free. In a two-person
dispute, for example, the sides would divvy up 100 points each on a
host of contested items. The player who assigns the highest value
to a particular item ``wins'' that object or issue.
</P>
<P>
   After the trading and splitting of some items, the two sides
would have the same number of points, both getting more than
one-half of what they wanted.
</P>
<P>
   In her thesis, Manygoats identified 16 items of contention
between the Hopi and the Dine. Based on research and interviews
with leaders of both parties, she assigned values to each item. The
Hopi won out on two of their highest values: getting 500,000 acres
of land from the federal government and $15 million based on
assessments made in various lawsuits. The Dine won the right to use
Hopi land to bury their dead, one of their biggest wishes.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides chose the duration of the Dine lease on Hopi land _
now 75 years _ as their top priority. But the Dine placed more of
their points on it, so the issue went to them.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, after trading and splitting, both sides walked away
with 58.41 of their own points.
</P>
<P>
   For her thesis, Manygoats won Union's Eugene W. Hellmich
Mathematics Prize, which goes to a student preparing for a career
in teaching math. The daughter of teachers, she plans to study at
Columbia University and return to the Navajo nation to teach.
</P>
<P>
   ``All in all, it was a great application of the theory,'' said
Taylor, her mentor. ``To my knowledge, this is the first time it
has actually been put on the table in a live dispute.''
</P>
<P>
   Amazingly, when presented with Manygoats' thesis, leaders of
both nations agreed with her assessment of the issues and their
value.
</P>
<P>
   One might have assumed that the hard part was over, but real
life is seldom so easy. This summer, she plans to promote the idea
among tribal leaders. She describes herself as a cautious optimist.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a huge dispute,'' she said. ``It's going to take a lot
more than my thesis to resolve it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
