<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 15:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6234 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-TWISTED-GUIDEBOOK-HNS     06-27 0611
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TWISTED-GUIDEBOOK-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GUIDE TAKES A LOOK AT THE BIZARRE SIDE OF SAN FRANCISCO 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JANE GANAHL  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ ``The mouse is inside out!''
</P>
<P>
   Not an exclamation one would normally hear at a book-release
party, but this one was different. This party celebrated the newly
printed ``San Francisco Bizarro: A Guide to Notorious Sights, Lusty
Pursuits, and Downright Freakiness in the City by the Bay.''
</P>
<P>
   It included, among other things, a demonstration of mouse
taxidermy by Jeanie M. _ who is featured in the book _ complete
with projection screen so the packed house at Edinburgh Castle bar
could catch every grisly second of her dissection and reassembly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think because I grew up on a ranch in Montana I've always
been unnaturally attracted to animals,'' said Jack Boulware,
chronicler of the city's strangest goings-on. A longtime aficionado
of all things sick and twisted, Boulware inspects one of the mice,
declaring, ``I think he looks rather happy!''
</P>
<P>
   It's true. Jeanie M. has positioned this one standing, front
legs stretched out rather like a mouse cheerleader. Jeanie M.
apparently takes orders for stuffed mice and will do them up in
costume if you like _ including the ever-popular Catholic icon
series.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a full-service kind of organization,'' Boulware said
wryly.
</P>
<P>
   His book, released in paperback by St. Martin's Press, contains
no fewer than 192 entries: from offbeat churches (John Coltrane's,
Anton Lavey's Church of Satan) to odd tours (of historic Black
Panther sites), newsworthy sites (where Rudolph Nuryev was busted
for pot and where Jonathan Winters wigged out) to
off-the-beaten-path tourist attractions (the Vibrator Museum, the
Tattoo Hall of Fame.)
</P>
<P>
   It is written with a strong ironic tone by the oft-hilarious
Boulware, whose last offering, ``Sex American Style'' (1997), also
caused a stir.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly enough, the book is being marketed as a tourist guide. One
very satisfied Amazon.com reader calls it ``a guide for the VERY
intrepid'' visitor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone thinks of San Francisco as this dream city with a
weird undercurrent, but no one has ever done a book about that side
of it,'' said Boulware, who covered ``that side of it'' for 10
years for the SF Weekly before moving on to Salon and other
national magazines. ``So I thought, let's put it together in a
funny way, and it will be something the whole family can enjoy. Hey
kids, there's the house where the Jefferson Airplane lived!''
</P>
<P>
   Once again, he's being ironic. Don't take this book home for
your pre-teens to read unless you want them to get an early
education in the more sordid angles of Baghdad by the Bay. There
are also entries for porn palaces like the Mitchell Brothers and
for strange practices, including a diaper-wearing sex cult.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, that was one of my personal favorites,'' Boulware said.
``You see, there's something for every interest.''
</P>
<P>
   Displayed on the wall behind Boulware at the party were examples
of memorabilia from the book, including some beautiful blotter-acid
art. A band that plays guitars made entirely of toilet seats was
also scheduled to play, but the mouse taxidermy demonstration was
all anyone can talk about. Of course, watching it gives rise to all
kinds of bad jokes from Boulware's literary pals.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is pretty appropriate, really, since book sales are
mouse-driven these days,'' said the humorist Ian Shoales.
</P>
<P>
   Scottish scribe Alan Black defended the display's questionable
taste. ``Hey, we sell fish and chips don't we? Rodents deserve a
presence here, too.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
