<HEADER>
A6242 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-COX-EROSION28-COX     06-27 0572
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-EROSION28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COASTAL EROSION WILL TAKE MANY BUILDINGS, REPORT WARNS
 &HT;    By ROB O'DELL
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ One-fourth of the homes within 500 feet of the U.S.
shoreline will be overtaken by erosion within the next 60 years,
the Federal Emergency Management Agency warned Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The hardest-hit areas will along the Atlantic and Gulf of Mexico
coasts, magnets for residential development where some areas are
losing several feet of shoreline every year, said a five-year study
issued by FEMA.
</P>
<P>
   ``More and more people are moving and building in high-risk
coastal areas, approximately 3,600 people a day, which equals an
additional 27 million people moving to these areas in the next 15
years,'' said James Lee Witt, director of FEMA.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need Congress to pass legislation to require the cost of
erosion to be included when setting flood insurance rates, and to
fund FEMA's preparation of erosion maps to determine safe areas
along the coast in which to build,'' Witt said.
</P>
<P>
   The report, which also examined the Great Lakes and Pacific
regions, predicted that rising water levels, storms and currents
would claim 87,000 buildings by 2060, including 53,000 on the
Atlantic coast and 13,000 near the Gulf of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   The report did not describe erosion rates for every coastal
location, but singled out a few areas with severe problems.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, it said, Galveston and Brazoria counties are losing
shoreline at the rate of 5 to 6 feet per year. In Florida,
shoreline areas of Brevard and Lee counties are shrinking by an
average of one foot a year.
</P>
<P>
   The hazardous effects of erosion are illustrated by the Cape
Hatteras lighthouse in North Carolina, the report said. When it was
built in 1870, the lighthouse was 1,500 feet from shore, but by the
late 1980s it was only 160 feet from the water and was in danger of
collapsing. In 1999, the National Park Service successfully moved
the lighthouse 2,900 feet from shore at the cost of $9.8 million.
</P>
<P>
   The FEMA report was ordered by Congress and prepared by the H.
John Heinz III Center for Science, Economics and the Environment, a
non-profit institution dedicated to improving the scientific and
economic foundation for environmental policy.
</P>
<P>
   It recommended two steps:
</P>
<P>
   _ Congress should provide funds to FEMA to prepare coastal
erosion maps, similar to flood plain maps now in use, to determine
safe areas along the coast for housing and other construction. It
said such mapping would cost $44 million to start up and $5 million
a year to maintain.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cost of this effort ... pales in comparison to the $530
million annual cost of erosion in the United States,'' said William
Merrell, president of the Heinz Center.
</P>
<P>
   _ Congress should require FEMA to include the anticipated cost
of erosion when setting flood insurance rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Federal Flood Insurance Program is not currently permitted
to take into account expected losses from coastal erosion,'' Witt
said. ``However, flood insurance for some coastal areas is often as
much as 50 percent lower than it should be.''
</P>
<P>
   The American Coastal Coalition, which represents governments,
businesses and residents in coastal areas, disagreed with much of
theoastalcoalition.org
</P>
<P>
   Rob O'Dell's e-mail address is rodell(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
