<P>
   BASIL (Undated) _ The summer our grandmother, a ninth-generation
Manhattanite, moved down South to live nearer to the family, she
brought with her a truckload of sleek, blond mid-century furniture,
a closetful of spike heels and a tattered, handwritten recipe for
pesto genovese. The year was 1982, and we had never tasted anything
like it. Shining through the richness of Parmesan, pine nuts and
garlic was the sunny, uplifting flavor of fresh basil, an epiphany
we would forever associate with summer and urban sophistication. By
Matt Lee and Ted Lee.
</P>
<P>
   With recipes.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT6.
</P>
