<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-BELARUS-490&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN POLITICIANS ASK BELARUS LEADER TO ENSURE DEMOCRATIC
ELECTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By PATRICK E. TYLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Russian parliamentary leaders said Tuesday that they
are appealing to Belarus' autocratic president to allow the
country's opposition parties to take part in all aspects of
elections this fall.
</P>
<P>
   The appeal adds significant political weight to the message,
already delivered by European leaders, that Russia shares concerns
that the future of democracy is under threat in Belarus as
repression rises. Over the past year, some opposition leaders have
disappeared, fled or been jailed on political charges, newspapers
have been shutdown and journalists harassed.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, a delegation of the European Parliament admonished
the president of Belarus, Alexander Lukashenko, who has led the
country of 10 million since his election in 1994, to open talks
with opposition parties. European leaders have threatened to
withhold sending observers to Belarus this fall unless Lukashenko
allows opposition party members to join the electoral commission
that will supervise elections and gives opposition candidates
access to the state-controlled news media.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are taking our obligation seriously to do everything in our
power to democratize the electoral process in Belarus,'' said Oleg
Naumov, a member of Russia's parliament from the reformist Union of
Right Forces Party. ``We are trying to avoid any ultimatum because
an ultimatum could only lead to the strengthening of the Lukashenko
regime. That is the same thing that happened with Milosevic in
Yugoslavia.''
</P>
<P>
   The final draft of the appeal, which was coordinated with but
not openly endorsed by the Kremlin, will carry the signatures of
Yevgeny Primakov, head of the Fatherland-All Russia Party; Boris
Gryzlov, leader of the Unity Party, which is most closely aligned
with President Vladimir Putin; and the leaders of the Yabloko and
Union of Right Forces parties.
</P>
<P>
   By Tuesday evening, only the Communist Party leader, Gennadi
Zyuganov, had not signed the appeal, but organizers said the
Communists might yet sign the document before it is sent to Minsk,
the Belarussian capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are convinced that the legislation for elections to the
Belarussian parliament must meet international standards, and the
vote should be democratic and fair,'' the appeal says. The document
calls on Lukashenko to form electoral commissions across the
country with the participation of all registered parties and to
grant them equal access to the state-run media.
</P>
<P>
   Lukashenko was in Moscow Tuesday to meet with Putin in a
gathering of the Supreme State Council of the Union of Belarus and
Russia. The union was sealed last December by Lukashenko and former
President Boris Yeltsin, and though it leaves both countries
independent it provides for integration of economic and security
policies.
</P>
<P>
   Putin and Lukashenko made no public comments Tuesday about the
looming confrontation over the elections in Belarus.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In Minsk, Yuri Khodyko, deputy chairman of the opposition
People's Front, told reporters that it makes sense to take part in
elections that really give voters the right to choose. But based on
Lukashenko's statements thus far, he said, the opposition fears
that he is planning to hold a farce, not elections.
</P>
<P>
   Belarussian opposition leaders came to Moscow last week to seek
assistance from liberal party leaders to put pressure on
Lukashenko. ``This is our first step in giving assistance to the
democratic forces in Belarus,'' said Naumov of the Union of Right
Forces, ``and we thought it was very important that this appeal to
Lukashenko not come only from two parties but from all nine
factions in the Russian legislative body.''
</P>
</TEXT>
