<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 15:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6278 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      06-27 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     WEIGHING IN ON A SENSITIVE SUBJECT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARIANNE MEANS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Even Jane Fonda, who made millions by selling
videotapes promoting exercise as the way to slim down and catch a
man, now says she regrets their implied message that happiness
depends upon being thin.
</P>
<P>
   Hooray, it is finally happening. It is occurring to people that
maybe we aren't what we eat after all. Instead, we are what we
think. Our heads and hearts are more important than our size.
</P>
<P>
   Among government and private nutritionists, women's magazine
writers and the owners of pleasingly plump figures, a backlash is
beginning against the bag-of-bones look popularized by models and
female television stars.
</P>
<P>
   How far this will go is anyone's guess. Fashion designers who
prefer to drape fabrics over a toothpick on legs have yet to be
heard from. But their influence is waning in a world in which
substantial cleavage increasingly competes for attention with a
wasp waist.
</P>
<P>
   We are a nation obsessed with our weight, forking over millions
every year for fad diets, liposuction, pills, treadmills, anything
that promises a flat belly by tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   But there is plenty of evidence that this is a never-ending
struggle. Is the time and energy expended worth it, to say nothing
of the grumbles from an unfulfilled stomach? Can we find a
middle-weight ground here?
</P>
<P>
   Few of us are naturally thin with the busy metabolism that
allows us to be as lazy and eat and drink as much as we want and
never gain a pound. And the argument has raged for years over which
body weight is best for which person and why.
</P>
<P>
   The food frenzy has escalated in recent months. Newsweek moans
this week that our kids are too fat, for the same reasons adults
are overweight _ too much to eat and too little exercise to work
off the calories.
</P>
<P>
   Several women's magazines have begun questioning the health of
stars so skinny that their heads look like lollipops on stick
bodies. If they are anorexic, they are truly sick from an eating
disorder. But of course the lollipops all deny it and insist they
are thin through clean living.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble is that young girls searching for love or fame look
up to these impossibly thin women and want to be like them.
</P>
<P>
   People magazine earlier this month surveyed competing celebrity
diets and concluded that despite the hype it isn't easy sticking to
them or keeping the weight off.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest success story seems to be Sarah Ferguson, the
duchess of York, who is a paid Weight Watchers shill and takes her
role seriously, slimming down from a size 14 to a size 10. Monica
Lewinsky, alas, was not such a great role model for Jenny Craig and
was dropped as a spokeswoman after failing to meet her pound-loss
criteria.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors are also speaking out against the obsession with being
skinny. A month ago, the British Medical Association officially
blamed the media clamor over the superwaifs of fashion for a
pattern of health problems in British girls trying to imitate them.
Last year, the American Medical Association issued a report urging
the television, movie and magazine industries to employ models and
actresses whose poundage could be described as healthy, not
underweight.
</P>
<P>
   In May, the Board of Supervisors in San Francisco, a socially
pioneering city, passed an ordinance making it illegal to
discriminate against a person based on physical size, a category
left somewhat vague. It was clearly a strike for fat acceptance, at
least in principle.
</P>
<P>
   It might come as a shock to think that as a nation we could
admire thickened waistlines and middle-aged paunches as badges of
honor, not ugly signs of overindulgence. But one survey shows that
62 percent of American women wear at least a size 12. Such a large
majority is hard to ignore, let alone put down. A few retail stores
and female-oriented magazines are beginning to promote larger sizes
and use what are delicately called full-figured models.
</P>
<P>
   Rubens lovingly painted women whose bodily curves, hills and
valleys concealed those sharp-angled bones that are now in fashion.
His models looked pretty sexy in paint.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble for modern young women is that such lushness doesn't
look sexy on television; it looks tubby. But we'd be better off
getting used to it.
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached at the e-mail address means(at)
hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
