<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIMPLE-COOKING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAST KIMCHI IN HOT TIMES 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARK BITTMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like so many fermented products _ cheese, wine and pickles, for
example _ kimchi began as a way of preserving a bounty that would
otherwise go bad. Anyone who has seen the huge piles of cabbage
harvested annually in Korea knows that it cannot all be eaten in
the next days or weeks. Pickling allows the cabbage to be kept for
months.
</P>
<P>
   There is also a tradition of making kimchi for immediate
consumption, although even that might be more work than most people
would want on a weeknight. But it is easy enough to take the basic
ingredients and flavors of kimchi and create a fast cabbage salad
that puts ordinary coleslaw to shame. Use this as a bed for grilled
beef _ or anything else that has the flavor to stand up to it _ and
you have a great summer dish.
</P>
<P>
   Quick kimchi takes very little work, but the cabbage is best if
salted and allowed to sit for an hour or longer, drawing out excess
water and making the cabbage ultracrisp. Skip that step if you're
pressed for time; the salad will taste just as good.
</P>
<P>
   All kimchi packs a punch, thanks to plenty of garlic and chili
peppers, and I have included appropriate quantities of those here.
You can increase the amounts if you like, though many people will
find these proportions strong enough.
</P>
<P>
   If you can get to a Korean market, buy some of the ground chili
powder labeled co chu karo, which is hot but also flavorful.
Otherwise substitute any good ground chilies or crushed red pepper
flakes. Fish sauce is traditional (in truth, dried oysters or dried
shrimp are traditional, but fish sauce has the same character),
although you can use soy sauce if you prefer.
</P>
<P>
   I grill the flank steak with nothing but salt and pepper; a
drizzle of the salad dressing on top gives it plenty of additional
flavor. Grilled pork, shrimp, tuna or chicken (legs, for best
flavor) would also be good.
</P>
<P>
   GRILLED FLANK STEAK WITH KIMCHI-STYLE COLESLAW
</P>
<P>
   Time: About an hour, plus at least one hour's resting
</P>
<P>
   1 small head Napa or Savoy cabbage, about 1{ pounds
</P>
<P>
   Coarse salt
</P>
<P>
   3 spring onions or 6 large scallions, trimmed and chopped
</P>
<P>
   3 cloves garlic, minced, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon co chu karo or crushed red pepper flakes, or to
taste
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon peeled and minced ginger
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons fish sauce or soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons rice wine or other vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 flank steak, about 1{ pounds
</P>
<P>
   Ground black pepper.
</P>
<P>
   1. Remove tough exterior leaves of cabbage; core it by cutting a
cone-shape wedge out of the stem end. Shred cabbage into thin
strips, and separate the strips by hand. Put in a colander, and
toss with about 1 tablespoon salt and the onions or scallions. Let
sit for at least an hour, preferably two, tossing occasionally,
until cabbage wilts.
</P>
<P>
   2. Meanwhile, prepare a grill. Combine garlic, co chu karo,
ginger, fish sauce and vinegar in a bowl. Grill steak for about 4
minutes to a side for medium rare (more time or less according to
the degree of doneness you prefer), turning once. Sprinkle steak
with salt and pepper as it cooks.
</P>
<P>
   3. Remove steak from grill, and let it rest. Squeeze as much
liquid as you can out of the cabbage, and toss it with dressing. To
serve, carve steak. Place a portion of cabbage on a plate, and top
with slices of steak. Spoon a little dressing over steak, and
serve.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
