A6294 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-KITCHEN-WARES-NYT &LR;      06-27 0233
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KITCHEN-WARES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROOF THAT THERE'S NOTHING THAT CAN'T BE IMPROVED 
</HEADLINE>
   By AMANDA HESSER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Measuring spoons have a clear purpose and a simple design that
you would think should be foolproof. And yet, aside from the food
processor with all of its parts, there may be no other tool that
can be more of a pain in the neck to use and clean. There are those
bound by an inseparable ring, so that every time you use one, you
must clean them all. There are others with seams that catch specks
of flour or grease, and those that inevitably spill their contents
when set down on a counter.
</P>
<P>
   CuisiPro, in New Castle, Del., did something about these
problems. Its spoon set is held together by a ring with a separable
joint. Each spoon is made of a single piece of stainless steel, so
there are no seams, and has a long, narrow head to fit into all
sorts of bottles and jars. The most innovative feature, though, is
a handle that curves downward at the end, so when you put a spoon
down, it sits level.
</P>
<P>
   The spoons also have gentle curves and a nice heft. Why not have
something that's pleasurable to hold as you dutifully measure
something down to the last eighth of a teaspoon?
</P>
<P>
   CuisiPro measuring spoons are $6.98 at Zabar's, 2245 Broadway
(80th Street), New York, (212) 787-2000. Call CuisiPro for
locations of other stores: (302) 326-4802.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
