<HEADER>
A6306 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-TURKEY-RAKI-NYT &LR;      06-27 0961
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURKEY-RAKI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANISE DISTILLED INTO THE SOUL OF TURKEY 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEPHEN KINZER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISTANBUL, Turkey _ Besides being an accomplished architect,
Aydin Boysan is perhaps Turkey's most famous bon vivant. That
means, inevitably, that he is a passionate drinker of raki.
</P>
<P>
   ``Raki civilizes society,'' Boysan said between sips on a recent
evening. ``That's very important here, because Turkey is such a
huge mess that if we didn't have something like raki, we'd probably
become hopeless and all commit suicide. Raki is our only
consolation.''
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult to imagine Turkey without raki. More than simply
the national drink, it is a potent, anise-flavored distillation of
the Turkish soul. It accompanies much of the best after-dark
conversation and is woven inextricably into the country's social
fabric.
</P>
<P>
   Boysan took his first drink of raki when he was 18 and now, 61
years later, describes it as ``my lawfully wedded wife.'' He
worries that two evils imported from the West, bars and cocktail
parties, are eroding the raki tradition.
</P>
<P>
   As long as Turks love life as much as he does, however, it seems
in no danger of disappearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to drink it like a gentleman, which of course means
never drinking too much,'' he said earnestly. ``All the senses are
involved. First you watch the water being poured into the glass and
mixing with the raki. Then you pick up the glass and inhale the
aroma. When you drink it, you take a small sip, feel the pleasure
of it flowing down your throat, take another small sip, then put
the glass down.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best part is feeling it go down your throat. A giraffe _
that's an animal ideally made to appreciate raki.''
</P>
<P>
   Raki is clear when poured out of the bottle, usually into tall
glasses. The glass is filled about one-third with the liquor. Water
is then added, turning the liquid translucently white. That
appearance gives it the widely used nickname lion's milk.
</P>
<P>
   It is unusual to see raki being consumed without food. Most
often it is served with the small appetizers called mezes that have
been a mainstay of Mediterranean cooking since time immemorial.
Most connoisseurs agree that the ideal dish is seafood.
</P>
<P>
   Records of raki production go back to the early 17th century.
Though it is one of Turkey's great passions, in Central Asia, where
Turkic tribes originated, there is no tradition of anise-flavored
liquor. That tradition is Mediterranean, and Turks adopted it
during Ottoman rule over Greece and nearby lands. To this day,
Greeks and Turks argue over the relative merits of raki and its
Greek counterpart, ouzo.
</P>
<P>
   Turks claim that the process for making classic raki is more
complex. It involves two distillations in traditional copper vats,
one using a concentrate made from seedless grapes and the other a
special variety of anise. Raki's alcohol content is 45 percent.
</P>
<P>
   There are three grades, but even drinkers who could easily
afford the small premium for the highest grade, Altinbas, say the
basic Yeni raki is best. It is cheaper because it is made partly
with pure alcohol, while Altinbas and the mid-grade Kulup are made
with fermented grapes only.
</P>
<P>
   The government liquor and cigarette monopoly, Tekel, is the only
legal producer of raki. In the countryside there are still
producers of bathtub raki, but the relatively low price of the
legal stuff _ about $5.75 for a 70-centiliter bottle of Yeni raki _
makes bootlegging a small-scale labor of love rather than a serious
business.
</P>
<P>
   Raki makes its way to the United States, much of it served in
Turkish restaurants. In New York a 750-milliliter bottle is sold at
Sherry Lehmann in Manhattan for $17.95.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly the most famous of all raki drinkers was Mustafa Kemal
Ataturk, the founder of the Turkish Republic, who was born and
raised in what is now the Greek city of Thessaloniki. Ataturk died
of cirrhosis in 1938 at the age of 58, and there are countless
stories about his fondness for raki.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the Republic was founded, most members of Parliament were
very conservative religious figures, and alcohol was illegal,''
said Ali Gok, a manager of Tekel. ``Ataturk used to serve it to his
friends at home. They would say to him, `Pasha, it's great that we
can drink when we're with you, but why don't you make raki legal so
we can drink it in our own homes?' That made sense to him, and
after a while the ban was lifted.''
</P>
<P>
   According to a new biography of Ataturk, he once asked a dinner
guest what goes best with raki. ``Leblebi,'' the guest answered,
referring to a dish made from roasted chickpeas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wrong,'' replied the great man. ``The best accompaniment to
raki is good conversation.''
</P>
<P>
   Drinking raki is a social thing, not something you do alone.
``It's also a macho thing,'' said Warren Winkler, an American-born
physician who has lived in Turkey for nearly 40 years. ``A lot of
foreign women who live here develop a taste for it, but not many
Turkish women do. You'll see six or eight or 10 or 20 guys sitting
around a table drinking without a woman in sight.''
</P>
<P>
   Although it is quite common to see working-class men drinking
raki, many intellectuals also consider it essential to provocative
discussion and debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the 1950s and '60s, educated people didn't want to
drink raki because it was considered too folksy and rural,'' said
Ilter Turan, a political scientist who is rector of Bilgi
University in Istanbul. ``It was considered more sophisticated to
drink wine or whiskey. But that didn't last long. Raki has been
reinstated as our national drink. It's a sign that Turkey is
becoming more comfortable with itself, a recognition that something
from our own tradition is not negation of the modernity we're
seeking.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-27-00 1620EDT &QL; 
