<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLEEP-DOWNSIDE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLEEPING EVERY AFTERNOON MAY HAVE A DOWNSIDE  
 &HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (The following ``separate buy'' article from HealthScout, the
authoritative online health- and medical-news Web site, is
available from the New York Times Syndicate. Please contact
syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 BY JENNIFER THOMAS  
 c.2000 HealthScout.com  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by The New York Times Syndicate) &LR;  &QL;
<P>
   Taking a daily siesta is a Latin tradition many sleep-deprived
Americans would love to adopt, but snoozing every afternoon could
increase your chances of a heart attack, new research has found.
</P>
<P>
   About 1,000 Costa Ricans were surveyed recently, and those who
took a siesta every day had a 50 percent greater chance of having a
heart attack, says a study in the International Journal of
Epidemiology. Those who napped less than four times a week showed
no increased risk for heart attacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the research on heart disease has been carried on in
Western countries, not in tropical areas or the developing world,''
says Hannia Campos, lead author of the study and an assistant
professor of nutrition at Harvard University School of Public
Health. ``Heart disease has become the major cause of death in many
developing countries. We were interested in the siesta because it's
a behavior that's common in tropical regions, but it's different
from U.S. or Northern European behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   And previous studies have shown heart attacks are most common
when people wake up in the morning, says Dr. Robert Kloner,
professor of medicine at the University of Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors suspect it is due to the release of catecholamines,
adrenaline-like neurotransmitters that gear your body up for the
day by stimulating the nervous system. In turn, this increases your
heart rate and force of heart contractions while raising blood
pressure.
</P>
<P>
   In people with atherosclerosis, or build-up of plaque in the
arteries, these changes can cause clots and heart attacks, Kloner
says.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have long known that cardiac events tend to occur more in
the morning, and within the first two to three hours of waking,''
Kloner says. ``These include angina, silent ischaemia (low blood
flow to the heart that does not cause pain), heart attacks, sudden
cardiac death, arrhythmia and even stroke.''
</P>
<P>
   That may be exactly what happens after waking up from a siesta,
Campos says. Heart disease is the leading cause of death in the
United States. It has more recently become the leading cause of
death in Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   The origin of the siesta goes back hundreds of years, Campos
said. Traditionally, about 80 percent of Costa Ricans have been
involved in agriculture. Coffee farmers got up early, worked hard
for several hours, and rested during the hottest part of the day.
</P>
<P>
   But in recent decades, Costa Rica has become more urbanized.
Only 18 percent in the control group were involved in agriculture,
and only 13 percent in the group that had heart attacks worked in
agriculture. About half in both groups were overweight.
</P>
<P>
   ``The siesta may not have been a problem when the people were
very physically active, but now people are becoming more sedentary
and developing more heart disease,'' Campos says.
</P>
<P>
   Campos and her colleagues studied 522 Costa Ricans who had
survived heart attacks and 505 who had never had a heart attack.
Among those who napped daily, the average length was almost two
hours. Among those who napped six days a week or less, the average
duration was 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Determining the likely times of day for heart attacks could help
doctors target the best times for giving heart drugs, Kloner says:
``If you can decrease the triggers for cardiac events, you can
decrease the total number of events.''
</P>
<P>
   Kloner also suggests waking up slowly, and waking to soft music.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm all for naps,'' he says, adding his suggestions about
waking slowly have not been tested. ``The bottom line is you can't
get away from this phenomenon. You have to sleep and you have to
wake up.''
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
