<HEADER>
A6325 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-BASIL-ART-3TAKES-NYT &LR;      06-27 0886
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BASIL-ART-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXOTIC BASILS, THE QUINTESSENCE OF SUMMER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Conn., Wash.)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT6 has been sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(Editors: 700 words of recipes appear in 2nd take.) 
 By MATT LEE and TED LEE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The summer our grandmother, a ninth-generation
Manhattanite, moved down South to live nearer to the family, she
brought with her a truckload of sleek, blond mid-century furniture,
a closetful of spike heels and a tattered, handwritten recipe for
pesto Genovese. The year was 1982, and we had never tasted anything
like it. Shining through the richness of Parmesan, pine nuts and
garlic was the sunny, uplifting flavor of fresh basil, an epiphany
we would forever associate with summer and urban sophistication.
</P>
<P>
   Basil is still the quintessence of summer for us, but over the
years it has lost its cosmopolitan credentials; every other
restaurant in America, it seems, is turning out some pale version
of fresh pesto, slathered over grilled chicken or salmon or pizza.
</P>
<P>
   Then, on a recent spring day at the Union Square Greenmarket, we
came across a stall with 11 varieties of basil, with alluring,
exotic names: Thai Siam Queen, Purple Ruffles, Burns' lemon basil,
and lime, cinnamon and holy basils. There were bushy plants with
dainty, teardrop-shaped leaves and the pale tone of pea soup
standing beside a lanky variety with razor-toothed leaves shot
through with purple veins. One basil had the saturated color of
inky zinfandel, and broad leaves that were ridiculously frilly at
the edges.
</P>
<P>
   We sampled them all, beneath the wary gaze of the grower, and
each bite brought on the excitement and thrill of the new.
Suddenly, basil was once again a culinary adventure.
</P>
<P>
   These basils really are different from the varieties available
year-round. Besides the familiar sweet basil flavor, they have
other beguiling flavors and aromas, like warm cinnamon toast, lemon
zest, bay leaf, ripe berries, tobacco and clove, to name a few.
These are delicate nuances, no matter how pronounced the flavors
may be. When you cook with an exotic basil, you have to think about
it differently and handle it differently or its distinctive essence
will vanish.
</P>
<P>
   That day at the market, we bought one of each plant, put them in
our Harlem community garden plot and bought even more plants
expressly for cooking.
</P>
<P>
   The 11 varieties we found represent only a fraction of the
number of basils. Eileen Boyle, the director of horticulture at the
New York Botanical Garden in the Bronx, ventures that there are
several hundred basil varieties among 60 or 70 species in the genus
Ocimum, native to India, Africa and Asia.
</P>
<P>
   A cook can divide them into four flavor categories: the citrusy
basils, like lemon, lime or Mexican basil, all as intense as a
lollipop and perfect for perfuming sauces. Then, there are the
anise or licorice varieties _ less assertive than the citrus
basils, but more complex than the standard sweet basils. These
include Thai, Armenian and Holly's Painted basil.
</P>
<P>
   The spicy basils, like cinnamon, clove or chocolate basil, tend
to have flavors that are fleeting, and need to be eaten fresh.
Finally, there are the lustrous purple and opal basils. They are
generally muted versions of the basic sweet Italian basil; they can
add visual spice to a plate, but not a whole lot of flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Cooking with exotic basils is about preserving the herb's heady,
aromatic oils. The vibrancy of these oils makes them seem
invincible, but sustained heat will reduce even Burns' lemon basil
to a shadow of her outrageously lemony self. We had resolved to
keep heat to a minimum and still we slipped up. We coated two
small, whole red snappers with a generous rub of kosher salt,
ground black pepper and minced lemon basil, then wrapped the fish
in a nest of basil sprigs, hoping that a brief blast of heat on the
grill wouldn't dent the intense lemon perfume. After just five
minutes on the grill, it had faded into dark oblivion.
</P>
<P>
   So we tried a lemon basil beurre blanc, with a half-cup of
chopped leaves blended into the sauce once the pan was safely off
the flame. It was perfect for the fish, the lemony essence of the
basil deftly parting the richness of sauce and fish.
</P>
<P>
   We also learned that simply substituting a lemon basil or a
licorice basil in recipes that call for the standard Genovese won't
always work. Flattering their distinctive flavors can be a
challenge.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, cinnamon basil pesto sounded great, but lacked the
piney, peppery kick of good pesto; the bold synergy of herb, cheese
and nut collapsed. Using both basils, in a proportion of one to
one, added the mysterious note of cinnamon and sandalwood we were
after without upsetting the balance.
</P>
<P>
   With the most potent basils, like Burns' lemon basil or holy
basil, merely rubbing a leaf across a surface _ say, of a crisp
bruschetta or a fresh fig _ will release enough aroma and flavor to
set off visions of lush mountain meadows.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, we also discovered that a discreet twist of
lemon peel, a tablespoon of diced fennel or a cinnamon stick can
reinforce the character of the herbs without selling them short.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE) nn
</P>
<P>
   One sure bet with all basils is to let them shine on their own,
in salads: insalata Caprese, the rustic salad of sliced tomato,
fresh mozarella and basil, is a classic formula that can stand up
to a zinger, like holy basil. Any green salad can be intensified
with a handful of whole basil leaves thrown in.
</P>
<P>
   Our favorite recipe came about from free-association. Our lime
basil made us think of a favorite summer nibble: Cuban grilled
corn, lightly brushed with homemade mayonnaise and sprinkled with
lime juice and queso fresco. We set out to simulate that balance of
corn, lime and cheese flavors in a dish that would be a light
summer meal. A sweet corn risotto seemed perfect, with a dusting of
grated Parmesan and 40 dime-size leaves of lime basil folded in
just before serving.
</P>
<P>
   Basil's tarragonlike, herbal tendencies make it indispensable in
savory dishes, but its mint, cinnamon and anise qualities point
toward dessert. So we dunked strawberries into a pint of
store-bought creme fraiche that we had blended with chopped
cinnamon basil. Strawberries and cinnamon? Strawberries and basil?
Sounds odd, but it was delicious, easy, and it performed double
duty as a crudite dip when we added salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   We also made more ambitious desserts, after consulting Jerry
Traunfeld, the executive chef of the Herbfarm Restaurant in Fall
City, Wash., which has acres of kitchen gardens. His book, ``The
Herbfarm Cookbook'' (Scribner), was published this spring. The
popularity of Genovese basil among his clientele inspired the Basil
Banquet, nine courses with different varieties of basil, including
cinnamon, licorice and lemon.
</P>
<P>
   Traunfeld uses whole leaves in salads and sauces, and with
grilled fruit. He drops battered leaves into hot oil for basil
tempura, and smokes salmon with ``basil wood,'' the dried stems of
basil plants. But the real fireworks are in desserts, like licorice
basil and apricot sorbet and cinnamon basil and blueberry
shortcake, that use herb-infused simple syrups and creams.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you infuse,'' Traunfeld told us, ``you get that wonderful
spice flavor and strain out the green vegetal flavors.''
</P>
<P>
   Following his advice, we plunged whole leaves of basil into a
bath of hot cream, steeping them for half an hour. Once the cream
was suffused with the herb's flavor, we threw out the leaves and
made a superb lime basil and coconut ice cream, and a cinnamon
basil chocolate mousse. Chocolate and basil _ perhaps against one's
better instincts _ go well together. Note that the Michelin
three-star restaurant Arpege in Paris pairs a basil ice cream with
chocolate.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the enthusiasm these basils inspire in chefs and
culinary tinkerers like us, they're decidedly underexposed in
American markets.
</P>
<P>
   They're less durable than supermarket varieties, said Susan Blew
of Oak Grove Plantation, a specialist in organic herbs in
Pittsfield, N.J., which sells exotic basils at the Union Square
Greenmarket all summer long. Blew begins her basil crop in her
greenhouse right after New Year's Day. She scrutinizes January
forecasts for a stretch of three days of full sun to allow seeding.
If the weather report is wrong, she'll start over again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basil's like kids,'' she told us. ``They don't like cold and
they don't like wet feet.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the matter of distribution. Quincy Horan, a
Connecticut grower of organic heirloom produce, won't take the
chance of shipping bunches of the nine varieties of basil he grows
out of Litchfield County.
</P>
<P>
   The exotics wilt quickly after picking, so they're more often
sold as plants, roots and all, in garden markets rather than in
supermarkets. ``If Dean &AMP; DeLuca is out of Thai basil,'' one
shopper observed, ``I go to Home Depot.''
</P>
<P>
   When you find the exotic basils it's wise to preserve them.
Washed and dried leaves freeze well in a sealed plastic container
or in a tightly sealed freezer bag. Then, defrost and use them.
</P>
<P>
   But we prefer to pack basil tightly in a small jar, like those
used for baby food or spices, with olive oil and a layer of rock
salt at the neck of the jar. Store the jars in the refrigerator
and, after each use, top off the jar with a little more rock salt.
Leaves near the top may discolor, but will not lose flavor.
Vegetable oil is equally suited to preserving basil, but we find
the olive oil becomes infused with the essence of the herbs and is
superb _ especially in the first gray days of autumn _ when a
drizzle on a slice of apple will transport you back to a warm, slow
afternoon. Not a drop gets wasted. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (MORE) nn
</P>
<P>
   LIME BASIL RISOTTO  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 45 minutes  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   3 cups chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   2 cups corn kernels (from about three ears)
</P>
<P>
   1{ cups chopped lime basil leaves, loosely packed
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   { cup chopped onion
</P>
<P>
   2 cups arborio rice
</P>
<P>
   } cup white wine
</P>
<P>
   Juice of one small lime
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Grated Parmesan to taste.
</P>
<P>
   1. Bring chicken broth and 3 cups water to a simmer. Puree 1 cup
of corn with } cup basil leaves, and reserve.
</P>
<P>
   2. Melt butter in a large saucepan over medium heat. Add onion;
stir until translucent. Add rice to pan and stir. Add wine and
continue stirring until liquid is absorbed by rice, about a minute.
</P>
<P>
   3. Add hot chicken broth 1 cup at a time, stirring continuously,
until 4 cups of broth are absorbed, about 15 minutes. Stir in
corn-basil puree and { cup broth and stir about 10 minutes, until
rice is tender. Add more broth as necessary to keep mixture from
scorching.
</P>
<P>
   4. When rice is done, stir in remaining cup of corn kernels,
lime juice and remaining } cup chopped basil leaves. Add salt,
pepper and Parmesan to taste.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   CINNAMON BASIL CHOCOLATE MOUSSE  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 15 minutes, plus 3 hours' refrigeration  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2 ounces unsweetened chocolate
</P>
<P>
   { cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 eggs, separated
</P>
<P>
   2 cups cinnamon basil whipped cream (see recipe).
</P>
<P>
   1. In a saucepan, melt chocolate with \ cup sugar and \ cup hot
water, stirring until smooth. Beat egg yolks and stir into
chocolate. Remove saucepan from heat.
</P>
<P>
   2. Beat egg whites, gradually adding remaining \ cup sugar,
until peaks form. Fold egg whites into chocolate. Fold 1\ cups
cinnamon basil whipped cream into chocolate. Pour mixture into
ramekins or glasses and chill for 3 hours. Top with remaining
whipped cream and serve. Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   CINNAMON BASIL-INFUSED WHIPPED CREAM  &QL; 
Adapted from ``The Herbfarm Cookbook'' &QL; 
Time: 45 minutes, plus 6 hours' refrigeration  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   24 leaves cinnamon basil
</P>
<P>
   2 cups heavy cream, preferably not ultra-pasteurized
</P>
<P>
   1 2-inch cinnamon stick
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons sugar.
</P>
<P>
   1. Wrap basil leaves in a towel and roll a rolling pin over them
once or twice to bruise them slightly. Heat cream over medium-high
heat until it begins to boil, stirring constantly so cream does not
scald. Add basil leaves and cinnamon stick, submerging them in
cream. Turn off heat.
</P>
<P>
   2. Cover tightly and let sit for a half-hour. Strain, pressing
out juice in leaves. Refrigerate until very cold, about 6 hours.
Place cold cream and sugar in a mixer and whip until it forms
peaks. Yield: 3{ to 4 cups. BASIL CREME FRAICHE  &QL; 
Time: 5 minutes  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons chopped cinnamon basil
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces creme fraiche
</P>
<P>
   Sugar to taste
</P>
<P>
   Fresh berries.
</P>
<P>
   1. In a blender, puree basil with cream. (Or mince basil and
mash in a mortar and pestle with cream and a couple pinches of
sugar.) 2. With a spoon, blend mixture thoroughly into creme
fraiche. Add sugar to taste. Serve in a bowl, with fresh berries
alongside for dipping.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   GRILLED SNAPPER WITH LEMON BASIL BEURRE BLANC  &QL; 
Time: 30 minutes  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   { cup lemon basil leaves
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   5 tablespoons white wine
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons white wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons minced onion
</P>
<P>
   8 tablespoons unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   Salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   2 small whole red snappers, cleaned and scaled
</P>
<P>
   Olive oil.
</P>
<P>
   1. Puree basil leaves and heavy cream in a blender and reserve.
In a medium saucepan, bring wine, vinegar, lemon juice and minced
onion to a simmer, uncovered. When liquid has been reduced to \ its
original volume (about 5 to 10 minutes), turn off heat and whisk in
the cream and basil mixture, being sure to spoon in all basil
shreds.
</P>
<P>
   2. Add butter to mixture one tablespoon at a time, whisking
continuously, until all is used. Return pot to low heat for a few
seconds, if necessary, so last butter pats melt. Strain sauce, salt
to taste; set aside.
</P>
<P>
   3. Prepare a hot grill. Brush the snapper with olive oil. Grill
5 minutes a side, until skin is crispy. Lift meat from bones and
place on plates. Drizzle with beurre blanc and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
