<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 16:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6330 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-MOUSE-GENOME-HNS &LR;      06-27 0856
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOUSE-GENOME-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     NEXT GENETIC MILESTONE: BETTER UNDERSTANDING THE MOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By SYLVIA WOOD  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ With scientists making astonishing breakthroughs
in understanding the genetic makeup of humans, researchers also are
keeping an eye on the mapping of the mouse genome.
</P>
<P>
   Without the mouse genome, experts say the information gathered
from the human genome is just that _ information. But a genetic map
of the most widely used lab animal in the world would give
scientists a way to manipulate and interpret those findings and aid
in the understanding of human diseases.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the mouse genome, scientists are going to be able to
answer more questions about the human condition,'' said Lorraine
Flaherty, director of the Genomics Institute at the New York
Department of Health's Wadsworth Center.
</P>
<P>
   Although a draft copy of the entire mouse genome is still years
away, its potential is already causing excitement in both the
business and scientific communities.
</P>
<P>
   The genome is essentially an instruction manual for creating and
sustaining living things. On Monday, scientists announced that they
had completed a rough draft of the human genome after 10 years of
work.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, a rough draft of the entire human DNA sequence
seemed impossible. For years, scientists were limited to studying
genes a few at a time, a task that was cumbersome and not very
enlightening. Flaherty likens it to trying to understand
Beethoven's Fifth Symphony from a handful of notes.
</P>
<P>
   Today, with the help of technology, researchers can look at
thousands of human genes all at once. The potential impact is
boggling. Imagine going from having a few pages of a book to having
access to an entire library.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the geneticist's trip to the moon,'' Flaherty said.
``It's that kind of accomplishment.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet scientists are just beginning to understand all of the
information at their fingertips. And that's where the mouse genome
comes in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mice and humans get many of the same diseases,'' said Carol
Bult, an assistant staff scientist at the Jackson Laboratory in Bar
Harbor, Maine. ``Comparing the two will help us identify genes we
wouldn't be able to pick up any other way.''
</P>
<P>
   The mouse will also give researchers a way to make those
comparisons, since most genetic experiments would be considered
unethical in humans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mice, on the other hand, don't have to sign consent forms,''
said Paulette McCormick, a professor of biological sciences and
co-director of the Center for the Study of Comparative Functional
Genomics at the State University of New York at Albany.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mouse is going to be the key,'' Flaherty said. ``We can do
things in mice we can't do in humans.''
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, on a genetic scale, there isn't too much of a
difference between humans and mice. The two genomes are thought to
be about the same size, with 3 billion chemical bases, or letters
of DNA.
</P>
<P>
   And about 95 percent of human genes are also found in the mouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having both genomes, we'll be able to answer the question,
`how many genes away are we?''' Bult said.
</P>
<P>
   More importantly, researchers say the mouse genome will open the
door to a better understanding of human disease.
</P>
<P>
   Within the next decade, specialists predict that people will be
able to have their individual genetic profiles done to make sure
they get the best, most effective treatment for diseases.
</P>
<P>
   This fall, SUNY-Albany is setting up a Transgenic Mouse Facility
at its East Greenbush campus, a project that is being done in
cooperation with the Albany Medical Center, a teaching and research
hospital, and Taconic Farms, a breeder of laboratory animals based
in Germantown, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   The facility will start designing mice to over-express or lack
certain genes believed to be linked to specific illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   On a wider scale, Taconic Farms will act as a sort of storage
center for such mutant mice, freezing embryos for distribution to
scientists across the country.
</P>
<P>
   At the New York Health Department, Flaherty has already been
using genetically altered mice to better understand how genes may
control certain fear and risk-taking behaviors in the rodents.
</P>
<P>
   The implications for humans could be significant, especially in
dealing with certain anxiety or addiction problems. ``If we can
understand how this operates, we may be able to use drugs,
behavioral modification or environmental conditioning to help,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Her research has already indicated that there may be some
genetic underpinnings for mice to seek novelty, and she hopes to
have a specific location for the gene within a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because the mouse genome is progressing at such a rapid rate,
we can go from mapping to identifying at a much faster (pace),''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   But the completion of the human genome, as well as the eventual
completion of the mouse genome, are just the first steps of a long
scientific journey.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is giving you the clues to the problem, but you still
have to follow up on the clues,'' Flaherty said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-27-00 1650EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
