r a BC-TEXASATLARGE-CHAPMAN-     06-27 0638
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXASATLARGE-CHAPMAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG LAKE SEEKS TO JOIN PUSH FOR TEXAS TOURISM DOLLARS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Big Lake Mayor J.R. Dunn announced this month that he wants
Big Lake's dry lake filled with water, there was guffawing all over
the state.
</P>
<P>
   Dunn wants the state's largest natural dry lake pumped full of
water to draw tourists and boost the town's dwindling economy. He
figures it will take about 50 to 100 wells.
</P>
<P>
   Big Lake, in Reagan County, is about 280 miles southwest of Fort
Worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not Don Quixote; we're realists out here,'' the mayor
told reporters. ``We have the largest natural dry lake in the state
of Texas, and the state's second-largest industry is tourism. We
feel like if we could take advantage of that, we could develop that
and we could create jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Just how much money is at stake can be seen in the latest
Scripps Howard Texas Poll on vacations, which indicates that 57
percent of Texas' 20 million people will travel this summer, and
that almost a third of them will stay in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   They'll drop between $500 and a $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   Tourism is generally considered the third-largest industry in
the state, not the second; nevertheless, it creates $34.6 billion
in local and state revenues.
</P>
<P>
   That's why state tourism officials spent more than a
half-million dollars last month to show off the Lone Star State's
attractions to hundreds of foreign travel professionals meeting in
Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   It also has an awful lot to do with why the city of Fort Worth
drives a handful of longhorn steers about three blocks, and back,
every day. It's why Big Lake's lake needs water.
</P>
<P>
   Texas cities like to show off because it is profitable.
</P>
<P>
   The Scripps Howard Texas Poll indicates that the high price of
gasoline isn't going to stop the locals from traveling around the
state.
</P>
<P>
   Sixty-three percent of all vacationers plan to travel by car, 26
percent by airplane, and 1 percent each by boat or bus.
</P>
<P>
   The poll shows that most of the vacationers won't be gone too
long. Fifty-four percent plan to return home in a week or less.
About 34 percent will stay away for a week to two weeks, and 8
percent get to luxuriate for three weeks or more.
</P>
<P>
   The categories don't add up to 100 percent because there are
always the undecided.
</P>
<P>
   There is no question which city draws the most people. With the
Alamo as the primary backdrop, San Antonio's SeaWorld and Six Flags
Fiesta Texas draw thousands of visitors, along with the River Walk,
the San Antonio Zoo and the Institute of Texan Cultures.
</P>
<P>
   San Antonio was the most visited place among Texans who
vacationed in the state last summer, and it is projected to lead
the pack again with about 16 percent of the travelers, down from 25
percent last summer.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest gainer this year seems to be Galveston. Last summer,
Galveston got 6 percent of instate vacationers. This year it
figures to get 9 percent, knocking Corpus Christi out of second
place.
</P>
<P>
   Fort Worth remained steady at about 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Austin will get 8 percent; Dallas and Houston both figure at 7
percent.
</P>
<P>
   But there is room for improvement. The poll shows that nearly
half (46 percent) of the vacationing Texans will shamelessly visit
another state this summer. An additional 11 percent will travel to
another country.
</P>
<P>
   The poll was conducted between May 22 and June 16. One thousand
adult Texans were randomly surveyed by telephone. The margin of
error is plus or minus 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   No decision has been made on whether or not to fill Big Lake's
lake.
</P>
<P>
   (Art Chapman writes a weekly column on things Texan. You can
call him at (817) 390-7422, or e-mail: artc(at)star-telegram.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
