<P>
   CUBA-U.S. (Washington) _ House Republican leaders agreed Tuesday
to end 40 years of trade sanctions on food and medicine to Cuba, in
a compromise that carried great political significance but may be
of only symbolic economic value, at least in the short term. House
Republicans had long opposed any weakening of the embargo against
Cuba, arguing that Fidel Castro had done little to institute
democratic reforms. But an intense lobbying campaign from
agribusiness and the U.S. Chamber of Commerce softened their
resolve. Cuban-American lawmakers succeeded in placing serious
restrictions on the bill. Both the federal government and U.S.
banks would be barred from providing any financing for Cuba, making
it difficult for Cuba, which is cash-starved and credit-poor, to
buy goods. By Lizette Alvarez.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT1.
</P>
<P>
   ZIMBABWE-ELECTIONS (Harare, Zimbabwe) _ President Robert Mugabe
urged reconciliation Tuesday after a polarized nation gave his
governing party a narrow majority in parliamentary elections,
saying ``the results do bind us all.'' The opposition, which
previously had three seats in the 150-member parliament, won 57,
enough to block constitutional amendments. (Summary from wires) By
Rachel Swarns.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE-HUMAN-RIGHTS (Warsaw, Poland) _ In another slap at the
United States, France said Tuesday that it would not endorse a
Warsaw Declaration supporting universal concepts of human rights,
drawn up at a U.S.-organized conference of 108 democracies. By Jane
Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-MIRANDA-ASSESS (Washington) _ Timing, in constitutional
law no less than in life or love, can mean everything, and when it
came to timing, the opponents of the Miranda decision who finally
managed to push the Supreme Court into revisiting the case after 34
years turned out to have been spectacularly unlucky. A news
analysis by Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
