<SLUG> BC-TASTINGS-PROSECCO-WINE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROSECO, SLIM, STYLISH AND SPARKLING 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: a list of recommended wines appears at end of story.) 
 By ERIC ASIMOV   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Of all the seasons, summer demands the most of its
beverages, requiring refreshment as well as lightness and balance.
You could drink a heavy Chateauneuf-du-Pape or a tannic cabernet
sauvignon with a hearty roast, but who would want to? The first
rule of summer drinking is not to work up a sweat doing it. That's
where prosecco comes in.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecco, a crisp, light-bodied sparkling wine produced in the
Veneto region of northeast Italy, is a perfect summer aperitif.
It's winsome and light in alcohol, generally around 11 percent, as
slim and stylish as an Italian motor scooter. You might not want
prosecco at a wedding or on New Year's Eve; it doesn't have the
depth of Champagne. But freed from the burden of heavy expectations
and pretensions _ and price, for that matter _ it exists simply to
please.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecco is produced from the white prosecco grape, which is
also used to make still wines, though you rarely see them in the
United States. Most of the sparkling varieties are labeled Prosecco
di Valdobbiadene or Prosecco di Conegliano, two of the prime
prosecco areas in Veneto. A small percentage of prosecco is called
frizzante, meaning it is lightly sparkling with a soft texture,
which I find particularly attractive. But most proseccos are
spumante, or fully sparkling, positively frothing compared with the
frizzante wines. Incidentally, the more famous Asti Spumanti, the
sweet sparkling wines from the Asti region, are made from the
muscat grape, not from prosecco.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, not all proseccos are created equal. It's easy to
find insipid versions that are either too sweet or too dull. But
the following proseccos, all nonvintage and spumanti unless labeled
otherwise, are just right for relaxed summer evenings, when the
world is your hammock and the most difficult problem is deciding
whether to roll over.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BELLENDA VITTORIO , COL DE LUNA , FRIZZANTE $10 &QL; 
Bready aroma, zesty, lightly fizzy and delightful.  &QL; 
RUGGERI &AMP; C., PROSECCO DI VALDOBBIADENE $14 &QL; 
Aromas of lemons, apples and anise; crisp and fresh. &QL; 
 &QL; 
BISOL DESIDERIO &AMP; FIGLI , PROSECCO DI VALDOBBIADENE , CREDE $16 &QL; 
Aromas of peaches and peppermint; off-dry yet refreshing.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
COLLALBRIGO BRUT , PROSECCO DI CONEGLIANO $15 &QL; 
Lively apple and lime aromas; light dry apple flavor. &QL; 
 &QL; 
ZARDETTO , PROSECCO DI CONEGLIANO $14 &QL; 
Apple and anise aromas; fruity with a slight yeastiness. &QL; 
 &QL; 
MIONETTO , PROSECCO DI VALDOBBIADENE , FRIZZANTE $11.60 &QL; 
Dry, lightly fruity and pleasant. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Listed in order of preference. Prices are those paid in various
Manhattan wine shops.  &QR;
</P>
</TEXT>
