<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWISS-MONEY-LAUNDERING-1STLD-WRITETHRU-350&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWISS REPORT INCREASE IN FUNDS FROZEN BECAUSE OF SUSPECTED MONEY
LAUNDERING 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS first graf after optional end to CORRECT 23 to 33.)  
 By ELIZABETH OLSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA _ Swiss authorities froze nearly $1 billion in suspicious
money over the past year _ five times as much as the previous year,
when the country began cracking down on money laundering to enhance
its international banking reputation, a monitoring agency reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Money Laundering Reporting Office, part of the federal
police department, said Swiss banks had blocked dubious funds
involved in 370 reports of suspicious transactions, mostly in the
financial centers of Geneva and Zurich. This compares with 160 the
previous year, and only about 40 before reporting became mandatory.
</P>
<P>
   The Swiss figures, which covered the 12 months through March,
came a day after the Organization for Economic Cooperation and
Development issued a list of 35 places that have lenient laws for
tax evaders and a week after an international task force unveiled
its list of 15 countries accused of failing to curb money
laundering.
</P>
<P>
   Switzerland, which was not on either list but whose banking
industry is estimated to manage as much as one-third of the world's
offshore wealth, began its reporting system two years ago to clean
up its banking image. That is part of a plan to step up its fight
against organized and financial crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``The figures show money launderers are no longer able to carry
on their activity without risk of detection,'' said Daniel
Thelesklaf, a lawyer who heads the reporting office.
</P>
<P>
   The higher figures for the past year were in part the result of
the discovery of funds linked to the former Nigerian dictator Sani
Abacha, who died in 1998, and his family, Thelesklaf said.
</P>
<P>
   More than 50 tips involved some $485 million in funds linked to
the Abacha cases; overall $670 million was uncovered in related
cases in 17 Swiss banks.
</P>
<P>
   Another 23 reports involved $12 million connected with the Bank
of New York, where some employees are accused of involvement in the
apparent laundering of billions of dollars from Russia. Last
September, Swiss authorities froze $16.8 million in bank accounts
linked to the investigation.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   An additional 33 reports involved bank accounts with Russian
owners but have not been tied to the Bank of New York
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Thelesklaf said the growing number of tipoffs is beginning to
approach what might be expected in a financial center of
Switzerland's importance.
</P>
<P>
   Suspicion of wrongdoing can be based on many factors, such as
transactions involving money that cannot be traced to a logical
owner.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know how much money is laundered,'' he said. ``This
is part of the iceberg, but whether it is the tip or not, we don't
know.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost 79 percent of the reports, covering the vast bulk of the
suspicious money, showed evidence of sufficient wrongdoing to be
referred to legal authorities. Prosecutors are still investigating
the cases, a lengthy process because it almost always involves
other countries. Meanwhile, funds are usually kept frozen.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the 370 tips came from banks as opposed to asset
managers, lawyers and others who handle large sums of money,
Thelesklaf said. An April 1998 law requires banks and asset
managers to report suspicious fund activity to the government. He
said the non-banking entities were lagging behind in reporting.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't won the money laundering fight yet,'' Thelesklaf
said, ``At the end of the day, we need convictions and asset
seizures to succeed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
