<SLUG> BC-TRIXIE-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TRIXIE' MISSING A FEW CLUES
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
Our rating: 1 star 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the endurance test disguised as a detective movie spoof
called ``Trixie,'' Emily Watson speaks exclusively in malapropisms,
Nick Nolte voices nothing but hot air and everybody else says
exactly what you'd expect them to at any given moment.
</P>
<P>
   Watson's title Trixie is a security guard who, despite evident
mental limitations, is determined to prove herself as a private
eye. Via her new assignment at an upstate casino, she has ample
opportunity to encounter suspicious characters, including Nolte's
windbag politician, Dermot Mulroney's klutzy ladykiller, Nathan
Lane's ex-con entertainer and two women of fluid morals and
uncertain self-worth, played by Lesley Ann Warren and Brittany
Murphy.
</P>
<P>
   There's a runaway, some beatings, a mysterious death. Believing
that it's time to fish or get off the pot, Trixie is going to grab
the bull by the tail and look him in the eye, then get her man by
hook or ladder.
</P>
<P>
   Really. She says so _ endlessly.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine two hours of dialogue like that. No, not dialogue, just
setups for Watson to mangle more aphorisms.
</P>
<P>
   When she's not snapping gum.
</P>
<P>
   Which is irritating, too.
</P>
<P>
   The movie was co-written and directed by Alan Rudolph and
produced by Robert Altman, and it exhibits the worst tendencies of
both filmmakers: Rudolph's to stroke a precious conceit to inflamed
rawness (``Welcome to L.A.,'' last year's ``Breakfast of
Champions''), Altman's to permit actors to indulge themselves well
beyond the point of watchability (``Popeye,'' ``Kansas City,''
roughly half of ``Short Cuts'').
</P>
<P>
   These two are, of course, also first-class filmmakers whose
movies are, more often than not, truly special. The same can be
said of the general run of work the fine ensemble members can
claim.
</P>
<P>
   But everything about ``Trixie'' _ comic timing, plot structure,
basic premise _ is so off that not all the talent in the world can
set it on the right track. If you need proof, you can see a good
chunk of it trying to and failing here.
</P>
<P>
   But take my word for it: You don't need proof that badly.
</P>
<P>
   The film: ``Trixie'' (R; sex, nudity, language, violence). &QL; 
The stars: Emily Watson, Dermot Mulroney, Nick Nolte, Nathan Lane,
Lesley Ann Warren, Brittany Murphy. &QL; 
Behind the scenes: Directed by Alan Rudolph. Written by Rudolph and
John Binder. Produced by Robert Altman. Released by Sony Pictures
Classics. &QL; 
Running time: One hour, 57 minutes. &QL; 
Our rating: 1 star
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-27-00 1703EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000627.0173 </DOCNO>
