<TEXT>
<P>
   ARTICHOKE-DILL &QL; 
POTATO SALAD WITH CHICKEN &QL; 
3 pounds whole tiny new potatoes &QL; 
Water &QL; 
1 cup light mayonnaise OR salad dressing &QL; 
1/2 cup chopped onion &QL; 
2 tablespoons chopped dill pickle &QL; 
2 tablespoons wine vinegar &QL; 
2 tablespoons Dijon-style mustard &QL; 
1 tablespoon snipped fresh dill OR 1 1/2 teaspoons dried dill weed &QL; 
1 1/2 teaspoons lemon-pepper seasoning &QL; 
2 cups chopped, cooked chicken (10 ounces) &QL; 
2 (6-ounce) jars marinated artichoke hearts, drained and cut up &QL; 
2 hard-cooked eggs, peeled and chopped &QL; 
Cook potatoes, covered, in boiling, lightly salted water 20
minutes, just until tender. Drain. Cool potatoes; cut into
bite-size pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in a very large bowl, stir together mayonnaise,
onion, dill pickle, vinegar, mustard, dill and lemon-pepper
seasoning. Gently fold in potatoes, chicken, artichoke hearts and
eggs. Cover and chill 4 to 24 hours. Stir gently before serving.
Makes 8 to 10 servings.
</P>
<P>
   From ``Better Homes and Gardens Fresh and Simple Quick-Toss
Salad Meals.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   COUNTRY HAM POTATO SALAD &QL; 
DRESSING: &QL; 
3/4 cup mayonnaise &QL; 
1/4 cup Dijon mustard &QL; 
2 tablespoons cider vinegar &QL; 
1 tablespoon minced fresh chile pepper &QL; 
1 teaspoon grated lemon peel &QL; 
1 teaspoon ground cumin &QL; 
1/2 teaspoon salt &QL; 
Freshly ground black pepper to taste &QL; 
SALAD: &QL; 
2 pounds boiling potatoes, peeled and cut into 1-inch cubes &QL; 
Water &QL; 
6 ounces baked ham, cut into 1/2-inch chunks &QL; 
1 cup diced red onion &QL; 
1 cup cubed (1/2-inch) peeled jicama &QL; 
Snipped fresh chives for garnish &QL; 
Make Dressing by combining all dressing ingredients in a small
bowl; stir until smooth.
</P>
<P>
   For Salad, place potatoes in a medium-size saucepan and cover
with cold water. Bring to a boil, then reduce heat and simmer until
tender, about 10 minutes. Drain, rinse under cold water and drain
again.
</P>
<P>
   In a large bowl, toss potatoes, ham, red onion and jicama with
dressing. Season with salt and pepper, sprinkle on chives. Makes 6
to 8 servings.
</P>
<P>
   From ``The New Basics Cookbook,'' by Julee Rosso and Sheila
Lukins, Workman Publishing. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AMERICAN-STYLE POTATO SALAD &QL; 
WITH EGGS AND SWEET PICKLES &QL; 
2 pounds red OR new potatoes, boiled, peeled, if desired and cut
into 3/4-inch cubes &QL; 
2 tablespoons red wine vinegar &QL; 
1 teaspoon kosher salt OR 1/2 teaspoon table salt &QL; 
1/2 teaspoon ground black pepper &QL; 
3 hard-cooked eggs, cut into small dice &QL; 
2 to 3 green onions, sliced thin (about 1/2 cup) &QL; 
1 small celery stalk, cut into small dice (about 1/2 cup) &QL; 
1/4 cup small diced sweet pickle (not relish) &QL; 
1/2 cup mayonnaise &QL; 
2 tablespoons Dijon-style mustard &QL; 
1/4 cup minced fresh parsley &QL; 
Layer warm potato cubes in a medium bowl. Sprinkle with vinegar,
seasoning with salt and pepper as you go.
</P>
<P>
   Mix in remaining ingredients. Refrigerate until ready to serve.
Adjust seasonings and serve chilled. Makes 6 to 8 servings.
</P>
<P>
   From ``The Perfect Recipe,'' by Pam Anderson, Houghton Mifflin. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GERMAN-STYLE POTATO SALAD &QL; 
WITH BACON AND BALSAMIC VINEGAR &QL; 
For German-style salads, the smaller new potatoes are more
attractive because the slices tend not to break up as they do with
bigger potatoes. Balsamic vinegar gives this salad an appealing
sweet/sour flavor. &QL; 
2 pounds red OR new potatoes, boiled, peeled, if desired and cut
into 1/4-inch-thick slices &QL; 
1/4 cup balsamic OR cider vinegar &QL; 
1 teaspoon kosher salt OR 1/2 teaspoon table salt &QL; 
1/2 teaspoon ground black pepper &QL; 
4 to 5 thick slices (about 4 ounces) slab bacon, cut crosswise into
1/4-inch strips &QL; 
1 medium onion, cut into medium dice &QL; 
2 tablespoons vegetable oil &QL; 
1/2 cup beef broth &QL; 
1/4 cup minced fresh parsley &QL; 
Layer warm potato slices in a medium bowl. Sprinkle with 2
tablespoons vinegar, seasoning with salt and pepper as you go.
</P>
<P>
   Fry bacon in a medium skillet over medium heat until bacon is
brown and crisp and fat is rendered, 7 to 10 minutes. Transfer with
a slotted spoon to potatoes. Add onion to bacon drippings. Saute
until softened, 4 to 5 minutes. Add up to 2 tablespoons vegetable
oil to yield 2 tablespoons unabsorbed fat. (If bacon is fairly
lean, onion will absorb most of drippings.)
</P>
<P>
   Add beef broth and bring to a boil; add remaining 2 tablespoons
vinegar. Pour broth-onion mixture over potatoes. Add parsley; toss
gently to coat. Adjust seasonings; serve warm or at room
temperature. Makes 6 servings.
</P>
<P>
   From ``The Perfect Recipe,'' by Pam Anderson, Houghton Mifflin. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
