<P>
   FAVORITE SOUR CREAM POTATO SALAD &QL; 
This is my rendition of the potato salad I grew up made with sour
cream. &QL; 
1 1/2 cups dairy sour cream &QL; 
3 to 4 tablespoons red wine vinegar &QL; 
1 tablespoon dill pickle juice &QL; 
1 tablespoon prepared mustard &QL; 
1/2 teaspoon seasoned salt &QL; 
1/2 teaspoon garlic pepper &QL; 
1 1/2 teaspoons dried dill weed OR 3 tablespoons chopped fresh
dill &QL; 
4 medium dill pickles chopped &QL; 
2 pounds medium red potatoes, cooked until tender, chilled and cut
into 1-inch cubes &QL; 
Mix together sour cream, red wine vinegar, pickle juice, mustard,
salt, garlic pepper and dill weed. Combine in a large bowl with
pickles and cold potatoes, tossing gently until well mixed. Chill
several hours or overnight. Makes 6 or more servings. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN YOGURT POTATO SALAD &QL; 
Often I like to make potato salad this way, dressed with yogurt. &QL; 
1 carton (8 ounces) plain non-fat yogurt &QL; 
2 tablespoons EACH prepared mustard and red wine vinegar &QL; 
1/4 cup sweet pickle relish OR dill pickle relish &QL; 
1/2 teaspoon (OR more to taste) seasoned salt &QL; 
Garlic pepper to taste &QL; 
1 green bell pepper, chopped &QL; 
2 stalks celery, chopped &QL; 
1/3 to 1/2 cup chopped green onions &QL; 
1 large OR 2 medium tomatoes, chopped &QL; 
6 medium potatoes, cooked until tender, peeled and diced &QL; 
In a large bowl mix together all ingredients except potatoes. Add
potatoes and toss to blend well. Cover and chill several hours.
Garnish with hard-cooked egg slices and paprika if desired. Makes 6
servings. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   COTTAGE CHEESE AND POTATO SALAD &QL; 
Trim calories per serving by using low-fat cottage cheese and
reduced-calorie mayonnaise or salad dressing. &QL; 
6 medium potatoes (about 2 pounds) OR 2 pounds whole tiny new
potatoes &QL; 
Water &QL; 
1 cup sliced celery &QL; 
1/4 cup chopped green OR red bell pepper &QL; 
1 cup cream-style cottage cheese &QL; 
1/2 cup reduced-calories mayonnaise OR salad dressing &QL; 
Milk &QL; 
1 tablespoon coarse-grain brown mustard OR prepared yellow mustard &QL; 
1/2 teaspoon salt &QL; 
1/2 teaspoon dried dill weed OR basil, crushed, OR celery seeds &QL; 
In a large saucepan, cook potatoes, covered, in a small amount of
lightly salted boiling water until just tender. (Allow 20 to 25
minutes for medium potatoes or 15 to 20 minutes for new potatoes.)
Drain potatoes well. Peel and cube potatoes or quarter new
potatoes.
</P>
<P>
   In a mixing bowl, combine celery, green pepper and onion. Add
cooked potatoes. Toss to mix.
</P>
<P>
   For dressing, in a blender container or food processor bowl,
combine cottage cheese, mayonnaise, 2 tablespoons milk, mustard and
salt. Cover and blend or process until mixture is smooth. Add to
potato mixture. Add dill. Toss to combine all ingredients. Cover
and chill at least 5 hours. If salad seems dry after chilling, stir
in 1 to 2 tablespoons milk to moisten. Makes 6 to 8 servings.
</P>
<P>
   From ``Better Homes and Gardens Comfort Food,'' Meredith Corp. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TRUE BLUE IOWA POTATO SALAD &QL; 
Some of the finest blue cheese in the world is made in Iowa at
Maytag Dairy Farms in Newton. No one will argue after tasting the
creamy blue cheese dressing that coats the following potato and
cucumber salad. &QL; 
4 medium baking potatoes (about 2 pounds) &QL; 
Water &QL; 
6 tablespoons olive oil &QL; 
2 tablespoons finely chopped green onions &QL; 
2 tablespoons chopped fresh basil OR 1 teaspoon dried &QL; 
2 tablespoons chopped fresh parsley &QL; 
1 large clove garlic, crushed &QL; 
1/2 teaspoon salt &QL; 
1 teaspoon Dijon mustard &QL; 
6 ounces creamy blue cheese (such as Maytag OR Blue Castello), at
room temperature &QL; 
2 tablespoons red wine vinegar &QL; 
2/3 cup heavy whipping cream &QL; 
2 small cucumbers (about 4 ounces EACH), peeled, seeded and minced &QL; 
Cook potatoes, unpeeled, in boiling water until just barely tender,
about 20 minutes. Rinse under cold running water and drain.
</P>
<P>
   Peel potatoes while warm. Cut in half lengthwise. Cut each half
into 1/4- inch-thick slices. Combine with oil, green onions, basil
and parsley in a large bowl. Let stand, covered, 1 hour.
</P>
<P>
   Mash garlic with salt in a small bowl until a paste is formed.
Whisk in mustard. Remove any rind from cheese and add to garlic
mixture in small pieces. Beat until smooth. Whisk in vinegar and
cream.
</P>
<P>
   Sprinkle minced cucumbers over potato mixture. Pour dressing
over top of cucumbers. Gently toss to mix. Serve at room
temperature. Makes 4 to 6 servings.
</P>
<P>
   From ``As American As Apple Pie,'' by Phillip Stephen Schulz;
Simon and Schuster. &QL;
</P>
