<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 17:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6355 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-JAPAN-U.S.-BANK-NYT &LR;      06-27 0776
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-U.S.-BANK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEEING OPPORTUNITIES IN JAPAN, U.S. FINANCIER BUYS TOKYO SOWA
BANK 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ The Japanese government said Tuesday that it would sell
the bankrupt Tokyo Sowa Bank to an investment fund led by Wilbur
Ross, a specialist in corporate rescues who has made a name for
himself through investing in financially distressed companies in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Ross' fund, the Asia Recovery Fund, will pay 35 billion yen, or
about $331 million at Tuesday's exchange rates, for Tokyo Sowa, the
second Japanese bank it has purchased. Last month, the government
sold the fund the failed Kofuku Bank, which operates mainly in
Osaka, Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Tokyo Sowa is the third bank the government has sold to
foreigners and the sixth nationalized bank it has returned to the
private sector since it began overhauling the country's shaky
financial system two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   By the time it hands Tokyo Sowa over to Ross, the government
will have spent 70 billion yen, or about $673 million, cleaning it
up.
</P>
<P>
   Ross has been one of the most serious foreign investors in Asia
since the financial crisis that gripped much of the region in 1997.
A bankruptcy specialist in the United States, he has promoted the
idea of ``vulture investing'' here, or purchasing distressed
businesses that can be salvaged for profit.
</P>
<P>
   Ross has said he sees vast opportunities in the Japanese banking
industry, which has been riddled with bad loans as a legacy of the
speculative bubble economy of the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   By melding the two troubled Japanese banks he is purchasing,
Ross plans to create a network of 200 branches offering services to
individuals and small and mid-sized companies in and around Tokyo
and Osaka, Japan's two largest cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will give us critical mass, making critical investments
in information technology and marketing more affordable,'' Ross
said.
</P>
<P>
   Tokyo Sowa is smaller than Kofuku, but has several strengths
that Ross said he hopes will enhance the investment. The Tokyo bank
is known for having one of the best automated teller machine
networks in Japan, distinguishing itself by offering a broad range
of 24-hour services, still relatively rare here.
</P>
<P>
   It also issues credit cards, a business that Kofuku abandoned
but would now like to re-enter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We now will have a big distribution system through which we
can offer money management, insurance and other products that
generate fees,'' Ross said. ``Increasing sales of fee-based
products is key for Japanese banks. Interest rates are too low here
to make a good rate of return with your balance sheet alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Japanese interest rates have been near zero for more than a year
because of Japan's weak economy. The low rates have helped banks by
keeping their own borrowing costs down. But the low rates also mean
the banks have little reason to loan more money and must find other
ways to be profitable.
</P>
<P>
   Ross has been making a name for himself in Asia, at a time when
many private equity investors are complaining about what they call
the difficulty of finding attractive deals.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Ross' investment firm, W.L. Ross &AMP; Co., joined with
the American International Group Inc., a leading American insurer,
to invest $800 million in a mutual fund company that is part of
South Korea's giant Hyundai conglomerate. Ross' firm also owns a
life insurance company in South Korea and is managing the
resolution of some defaulted loans for the South Korean government.
</P>
<P>
   In Japan, Ross has invested in a bankrupt auto parts
manufacturer and the two banks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's baloney to say there aren't opportunities in this
region,'' Ross said. ``You just have to be prepared to do things
differently than the way we do them in the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   In the bidding for Tokyo Sowa, Ross beat out Shinsei Bank,
formerly known as Long-Term Credit Bank, which is owned by a group
of investors led by Ripplewood Holdings LLC, a Wall Street
investment firm, and H.I.S., a travel agency that specializes in
selling discount tickets.
</P>
<P>
   The government said the deal with Ross' group was the best for
Japanese taxpayers. But officials at the Financial Reconstruction
Commission, the agency overseeing the restructuring of the
financial sector, also may be irritated with Shinsei and
disinclined to do business with it.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of Ripplewood's purchase of Shinsei, the bank is
not responsible for a broad category of loans that go bad _ the
government must pay them instead.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the government have said such an arrangement is
unfairly generous to Shinsei and victimizes Japanese taxpayers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-27-00 1710EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
