<DOCNO> NYT20000627.0179 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 17:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6361 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-PATRIOT-FILM-$ADV2-2T     06-27 1234
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATRIOT-FILM-$ADV2-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE REVOLUTIONARY WAR IS LOST ON HOLLYWOOD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 2)  
 By JAMIE MALANOWSKI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like fireworks _ loud, dazzling, pleasing and scary to the most
impressionable _ ``The Patriot,'' the new movie starring Mel
Gibson, will prove to many a satisfying way to spend a summer
evening. It's got big battles and wrenching hand-to-hand combat, a
courageous but conflicted hero and a dastardly and totally
guilt-free villain, thrills, tenderness, sorrow, rage and a little
bit of kissing. There is just enough brain bran to keep the
postfilm discussions from being dominated by people who want to
focus on how cool it was when Mel hit that guy with the hatchet.
Why, some may think it's the best Revolutionary War movie ever
made.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us to our point: It is also one of the very few
Revolutionary War movies ever made, most of which are not all that
good. Disney's ``Johnny Tremain'' (1957) is shallow and childish,
hardly a fair representation of Esther Forbes' flinty and
hardheaded novel; it even features a cringe-inducing moment when
smiling Sons of Liberty stroll the streets of Boston singing a kind
of fight song. John Ford's ``Drums Along the Mohawk'' (1939) just
transplants the Ford formula and stock company from Monument Valley
in 1876 to the Mohawk Valley in 1776. There the simple, amiable,
good-hearted and altogether too cute rustics turn ferocious when
their settlements are threatened by Indians; the British are nearly
invisible, represented almost entirely by a vulpine, eye-patched
John Carradine, who incites the Indians to commit their atrocities.
</P>
<P>
   ``1776'' (1972) is a pretty good parlor trick; not all that
great a musical, and not all that great a drama about declaring
independence, it's an engaging melding of the two. It now seems to
have found a niche as an educational tool for fifth-graders getting
their first exposure to U.S. history. Hugh Hudson's ``Revolution''
(1985), starring Al Pacino, is dark, murky and poorly plotted; its
box office toxicity warned future filmmakers with head-on-a-pike
firmness to stay away from this theme. Which may explain why the
sluggish ``Jefferson in Paris'' (1995) takes place entirely after
the Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   There is also ``The Devil's Disciple'' (1959), a pretty good
adaptation of Shaw's play set during the Revolution, and Robert
Stack as ``John Paul Jones'' (1959), George Arliss in ``Alexander
Hamilton'' (1931), a bad 1940 Cary Grant movie called ``The Howards
of Virginia,'' and ``Funky Phantom,'' which according to the
Internet Movie Data Base (www.imdb.com) is a 1971 movie about
``three teens and the ghost of a patriot from the American
Revolution who set across the country to uphold justice and fight
for freedom.'' This isn't an exhaustive list _ it omits a few
silents and some minor talkies _ but it does appear we've managed
to pick out the biggest chunks.
</P>
<P>
   Think for a moment about what isn't there. Where's that George
Washington biopic starring Gary Cooper? The quiet, iconic
action-loving movie star would have done a good job playing the
quiet, iconic, action-loving father of his country. Errol Flynn
portrayed everybody from the Earl of Essex to Jeb Stuart, went
everywhere from the Crimea in ``The Charge of the Light Brigade''
to the Little Big Horn in ``They Died With Their Boots On'';
where's his Paul Revere? (Granted, while Flynn seems perfect for
the midnight ride part, he might not have been up to the
silversmithing aspect of the gig.)
</P>
<P>
   Burt Lancaster, Kirk Douglas, Gregory Peck _ any of them would
have done a good job besting the libertine Gen. Johnny Burgoyne
(Laurence Harvey, maybe, or Dirk Bogarde) at Saratoga, the turning
point of the war (and wouldn't John Wayne have been perfect as Col.
Daniel Morgan, the big heroic rifleman who once took 500 lashes for
slugging a British officer?). Did no one think to connect the
rebels of '76 with the rebellious kids of the '60s: Consider a
Boston Tea Party with Peter Fonda, Dennis Hopper, Christopher Jones
and Yvette Mimieux, Richard Lester directing. What about the dark
story of Benedict Arnold _ hero of the revolution, general of the
army _ who betrays the cause when he falls for the beautiful Tory
debutante Peggy Shippen; Jack Nicholson and Bob Rafelson would
surely have done something interesting with this tale of
self-destruction on a historic scale. Instead, ``Funky Phantom.''
We cast about for explanations.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my 50 years of making motion pictures,'' said David Brown,
the dean of Hollywood producers, ``when it came to stories about
American history, particularly stories about the American
Revolution, the prevailing opinion, beginning with the studio
moguls like Zanuck and Selznick, was that the box office would be
bad. Jack Warner had a classic rule. `I don't want any pictures,'
he would say, `where they write with a feather.'''
</P>
<P>
   But obviously the old-time moguls allowed a lot of
feather-writers to make it to the screen _ Queen Elizabeth and the
Armada, Lady Caroline and Admiral Nelson, Napoleon and Josephine,
and multiple versions of ``The Scarlet Pimpernel,'' ``A Tale of Two
Cities'' and ``War and Peace.'' There was even the Spencer Tracy
movie about the French and Indian War, ``Northwest Passage''
(which, in combination with Michael Mann's splendid ``Last of the
Mohicans,'' means there have been more good movies about that
conflict than about the War for Independence.) It's not period
pieces the moguls didn't like; it's the American Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to remember,'' said Brown, who himself has tried to
develop the story of George Washington, ``that a lot of these men
came from Eastern Europe, and they were Anglophiles. A lot of us
had the sense that through these movies they somehow wanted to
endear themselves to the aristocrats who threw them out.''
</P>
<P>
   The film historian David Thomson also points to their
Anglophilia, as well as the extent to which the moguls were keeping
an eye on the passions of their own times. ``They were very against
the idea of revolution and revolutionary views. They saw it in
Europe, and they were afraid of it happening in America.''
</P>
<P>
   Along these lines, perhaps it was not entirely irrelevant to
their thinking that America's enemy in the Revolution just happened
to have been our ally in two world wars and a Cold War. Why go out
of your way to dredge up some long-reconciled misunderstandings
when they was a globe full of German, Japanese and Russian enemies
to conquer before the credits roll?
</P>
<P>
   Mogul psychology notwithstanding, some people _ historians _ who
would love to see more Revolutionary War movies are nonetheless
sympathetic to the view that the Revolutionary era is not easy for
modern audiences to understand.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of us have trouble at first perceiving those people as
real,'' said the historian David McCullough, whose biography of
John Adams will be published next year. ``Because of their
clothing, and the wigs, and their mannered way of speaking, they
are like characters in a costume pageant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Also, we're handicapped because they don't appear in
photographs. One reason we find the Civil War more accessible, and
why there have been more movies about it, is that we've seen the
Civil War soldiers, and we identify with them much more readily
than we do with those in the Revolution.''
</P>
<P>
   (MORE) nn
</P>
<P>
   Joseph J. Ellis, whose 1997 biography of Thomas Jefferson,
``American Sphinx,'' won the National Book Award, said: ``The lack
of realistic images means that all we see are paintings and
iconographic renderings that all have a celebratory, patriotic,
posed quality. Because the movies are realistic, they have a hard
time measuring up. It's like when I was a kid, and I loved
listening to the Lone Ranger on the radio. When I finally saw him
on TV, I was disappointed.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellis also sees the big differences between the eras as a
factor.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are, despite what Tom Brokaw says, really our greatest
generation, but they are also kind of a lost generation. Remember,
they are pre-modern _ pre-Marx, pre-Freud, pre-Darwin,
pre-Stravinsky, pre-Keynes, and they are covered with this
patriotic haze. They are sufficiently different from us that it
really requires a willingness on our part to put ourselves back to
a time that is really lost.''
</P>
<P>
   They are also different from us on the crucial matter of
slavery; as William Hallahan, author of ``The Day the American
Revolution Began,'' pointed out: ``It's very hard for today's
audiences to root for a slaveholder. We're very quick to spot
hypocrisy in our current politicians, and these guys, even the
non-slaveholders, though great and brilliant men, all have feet of
clay.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellis said: ``Coming to terms with your father is always a
tricky thing. One is never really capable of seeing them with
complete detachment, and these men are our political fathers. We
are still living with their institutions.''
</P>
<P>
   As ``The Patriot'' shows, however, the challenge of creating
characters that can be understood by modern audiences is hardly
insuperable. Mel Gibson's Benjamin Martin is pretty modern: devoted
to his family, wracked by guilt, and possessed of a Bob Vila-esque
interest in furniture-making. Although he is a South Carolina
planter, he is not a slave owner but an employer of freed blacks, a
circumstance that the film's advisers, from the Smithsonian
Institution, found completely credible. (It helped that the Martin
plantation is in the back country, not the low country, where
slavery was prevalent.) Martin does not seem to possess the hip,
edgy, self-referential sense of humor of many moderns; but then,
he's better with a flintlock.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Patriot'' screenwriter, Robert Rodat, who also wrote the
screenplay for ``Saving Private Ryan,'' saw the connective tissue
early on in his research phase, when he read the letters and
journals of the colonists. ``I was struck by how immediate they
felt,'' he said. ``They were very much like the letters and
journals I read for `Saving Private Ryan.' Their concerns were
identical: duty and family.''
</P>
<P>
   Roland Emmerich, director of ``The Patriot,'' said: ``I'm always
skeptical about historical dramas. But I could see that these were
characters I could relate to, and they were engaged in a conflict
that had a significant outcome _ the creation of the first modern
democratic government.'' It does not come as much of a surprise to
hear that the first thing Emmerich did after reading the
screenplay, which he liked immediately, was to thumb through a film
guide, looking to see if this kind of film had been done before,
wondering why it hadn't. It's encouraging that the studio, Sony,
showed no a priori aversion to the subject.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope this movie is a good one,'' said McCullough, who would
like to see the film spark interest in the Revolution the way
``Saving Private Ryan'' rekindled interest in World War II. ``The
importance of what those people accomplished cannot be overstated,
and under those costumes and wigs they were as vivid and as capable
as any generation in our history. To fight and get shot and to die
like that, to suffer disease and hunger and really horrible
conditions, to be poorly clothed, poorly fed, and poorly led, and
to still fight on? They were as strong as any characters! To have
been in Philadelphia in the first days of July in 1776, knowing
that the British had just landed 32,000 troops _ a force larger
than the population of Philadelphia _ in Staten Island, just a day
and a half's march away, and to still declare independence? These
are characters! These are stories!''
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of what they wrote with.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
