<DOCNO> NYT20000627.0186 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 17:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6370 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-SLUG-REVIEW-LADN &LR;      06-27 1039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLUG-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HISTORY ASIDE, `PATRIOT' A SPECTACLE TO BEHOLD
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
Our rating: 3 stars 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When they make films about the birth of our nation that try to
be thoughtful, like ``Revolution'' and ``Jefferson in Paris,'' the
results tend to be very bad. So now they've made one where thinking
is a secondary consideration, if even that, and the outcome is, if
not really better, at least rather fun.
</P>
<P>
   The key image in Roland Emmerich's long, unwieldy and resolutely
superficial ``The Patriot'' is not of Mel Gibson waving various
early combinations of red, white and blue, nor even of his face
covered in crimson blood to evoke fond memories of the Pictish
warpaint he wore in the just as dumb but cooler ``Braveheart.'' No,
the telling shot here is of a Continental soldier's head getting
knocked off by a British cannonball. It nicely encapsulates the
film's anything-for-an-effect ethos and, of course, symbolically
comments on the filmmaker's opinion of the picture's perfect
audience (right before the decapitation, there's a subjective shot
of the projectile barreling right at us). &QL; 
The rest of the movie is more subtle, if only incrementally. But
Emmerich, whose gift for action staging and visual splendor
counterbalances his tendencies to simplify and pander, often sweeps
us along with pure spectacle. ``The Patriot'' is a gorgeous film _
just, like too many pretty things, more emptier than it aspires to
be.
</P>
<P>
   Gibson's Benjamin Martin is a South Carolina widower with seven
children and _ in a flagrant attempt to avoid anything resembling
honest or, God forbid, complicated social history _ a plantation
worked by ``free'' blacks. Of course, Frances Marion, the
Revolutionary figure Martin is clearly based on, was as fervently
committed to slavery as he was to killing redcoats, an attitude
likely shared by most of his fellow Southern landowners in the 18th
Century.
</P>
<P>
   But that's a different, contradictory movie, and the last thing
a filmmaker like Germany's Emmerich _ whose usual speed is pop
culture pastiches like ``Independence Day'' and the ``Godzilla''
remake _ wants to do is challenge anyone's complacency. So Martin
is not only incredibly ahead of his time, racial
enlightenment-wise, he's also All About Family.
</P>
<P>
   Which we all know is really important. Maybe the most important
thing. Along with, maybe, freedom and stuff. And paying fewer
taxes.
</P>
<P>
   See, even though he was a holy terror in the French and Indian
Wars, Martin is reluctant to join the rebellion for the sake of his
children. He's also, it's bludgeoningly hinted, a little worried
about turning back into the brutal killer he became in the earlier
conflict. Indeed, it's the same psychic no-man's-land Clint
Eastwood explored so brilliantly against the backdrop of frontier
capitalism in ``Unforgiven,'' and it would have been very
interesting to examine how that kind of violent nature fit into the
idealistic struggle to create the first modern democratic republic.
</P>
<P>
   But nah, Martin only goes Mad Max when despicable Brits
terrorize his kids, which essentially lets him off any ethical
hook. With his Cherokee tomahawk and ragtag band of backwater
militia, Martin essentially invents modern guerrilla warfare and
harasses an uncomprehending Cornwallis (Tom Wilkinson,
self-parodying stuffiness with a deft intelligence that comes from
a whole other movie) all the way from Charleston to Yorktown.
During downtimes between ambushes, of which there are plenty,
Martin bonds with his oldest son/second-in-command Gabriel (Heath
Ledger, another Aussie), makes tentative passes at his just-waiting
sister-in-law (Joely Richardson, who is English) and tries to get
his mute youngest daughter to say she loves Daddy (I think the girl
who plays her might actually be American).
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to well-meaning, slightly psychotic family man
Martin, the main British villain, Reinhard Heydrich ... er, that
is, dragoon Col.William Tavington (Jason Isaacs), likes to ride
around the countryside slaughtering entire communities at a time.
While such depredations have certainly accompanied military actions
from Carthage through Mongol invasions to the Thirty Years War,
you'd think that if such Nazi-like atrocities had occurred during
our war of independence, they might have made their way into the
national lore before now. Really makes you dislike Tavington,
though, which, it could safely be argued, was the point.
</P>
<P>
   So, you wonder, what on Earth is right about ``The Patriot''?
Good gory battle scenes, first and foremost (the raid Martin takes
two of his youngest sons _ the only allies around who can handle
muskets _ on is particularly chilling). Though not quite as
visceral as ``Braveheart's'' best, nor as appallingly wasteful as
the point blank exchanges in the Civil War drama ``Glory,'' they
convincingly evoke the futility of fighting superior forces with
conventional methods. Conversely, we're given a clear understanding
of how imagination and surprise can be a general's greatest
weapons. Plus, all those blue and red uniforms blood-up real
pretty.
</P>
<P>
   There's also a nice ration of sly humor to counterpoint the grim
and sentimental goings-on. ``Patriot's'' script is credited to
Robert Rodat, whose screenplay for ``Saving Private Ryan'' had its
share of detractors, but compared to this melodrama, it clearly
stands out as a rigorous and complex study of men fighting the good
fight despite what it does to them.
</P>
<P>
   But if ``The Patriot'' is cartoon history, at least it's full of
color and motion like a good cartoon should be. Enjoy the
spectacle, let the cheap emotions touch you if they can ... but
don't forget to duck that cannonball. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The film: ``The Patriot'' (R; violence, language, children in
jeopardy.) &QL; 
The stars: Mel Gibson, Heath Ledger, Jason Isaacs, Tom Wilkinson,
Joely Richardson, Chris Cooper, Tcheky Karyo. &QL; 
Behind the scenes: Directed by Roland Emmerich. Written by Robert
Rodat. Produced by Dean Devlin, Mark Gordon and Gary Levinsohn.
Released by Columbia Pictures. &QL; 
Running time: 2 hours, 38 minutes. &QL; 
Playing: Citywide. &QL; 
Our rating: 3 stars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-27-00 1729EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000627.0187 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 17:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6374 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e BC-FILM-PATRIOT-SPI &LR;      06-27 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-PATRIOT-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PATRIOT': VISUAL FIREWORKS, DUD OF A PLOT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 Our Grade: B  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hollywood's new Revolutionary War drama ``The Patriot'' has so
much going for it in terms of production design, believable battle
sequences and Mel Gibson's star power that it's actually painful to
gradually discover that it has a flag-waving dumbness at its core.
</P>
<P>
   With a gut-wrenching revenge theme that's similar to
``Gladiator,'' its fellow historical epic in this summer's movie
sweepstakes, it's likely to be every bit as popular with young
moviegoers and further re-establish this long dormant movie genre
as the hottest box-office prospect of the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
   But, unfortunately, it isn't nearly as smart as ``Gladiator''
and ends up being something of a missed opportunity. What could
have been Hollywood's greatest examination of our War of
Independence is finally a movie so intent on being ``Saving Private
Ryan: the Prequel'' that it clumsily distorts history.
</P>
<P>
   Suggested by the life of Gen. Francis Marion, the famous ``Swamp
Fox,'' it's the story of a wealthy South Carolina farmer (Gibson)
who _ remembering the horrors of the French and Indian War _
refuses to join the Colonies' rebellion against Britain.
</P>
<P>
   But when the nastiest British general this side of Jack the
Ripper (Jason Isaacs) murders his young son, he sees the errors of
his pacific ways and joins the cause with both barrels blazing,
forming an intrepid band of South Carolina irregulars that harasses
General Cornwallis and Co. with Viet Cong-like guerrilla tactics.
</P>
<P>
   Visually, it's a gorgeous movie. Production designer Kirk
Petruccelli and cinematographer Caleb Deschanel _ arguably
Hollywood's finest cameraman _ have created what could well stand
as the movies' most splendid evocation of Colonial America, and
have done it in a rather subtle way, without showy effects that
call attention to themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Director Roland Emmerich (``Independence Day,'' ``Godzilla'')
also shines _ and boosts the film to the level of a satisfying
combat epic _ with some extraordinary battle scenes that recall
both star Gibson's work in ``Braveheart'' and Stanley Kubrick's
horrifyingly formal Napoleonic exchanges in his 1975 ``Barry
Lyndon.''
</P>
<P>
   The supporting performances _ Heath Ledger as Gibson's oldest
son, Tom Wilkinson as Cornwallis and especially Tcheky Karyo as a
Lafayette-like French adviser _ are all enjoyable, and Gibson
himself is terrific. His explosive power and personal charm fairly
light up the screen and, like Warren Beatty, he's learned that the
more flawed his character, the more the audience likes him.
</P>
<P>
   But, while ``Gladiator'' was a bona fide historical epic in the
tradition of ``Ben-Hur,'' ``Spartacus'' and ``Lawrence of Arabia''
that used Russell Crowe's star-power as one element of its complex
palette, ``The Patriot'' is very much a Mel Gibson star vehicle: a
movie in which every element is designed to showcase his
personality.
</P>
<P>
   So he's thoroughly sympathetic and politically correct (he's the
one big landowner in South Carolina who doesn't own slaves), and
often super-human _ as when he single-handedly takes on 20 armed
Redcoats, Douglas Fairbanks-style, and vanquishes them all with a
tomahawk. By the end of the movie, it's clear we owe our
independence to him personally.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, while it's understandable that Robert Rodat's
script might want to duplicate his ``Saving Private Ryan'' success,
and even admirable that he wants the film to be a similar tribute
to the sacrifices of our Revolutionary War servicemen, it's
disappointing that the only way Rodat can think to do this is to
turn the British into crypto-Nazis.
</P>
<P>
   The historically complex Revolutionary War is, like ``Ryan,''
depicted here as a battle between good and evil, between
peace-loving Americans and slobbering, fiendish brutes who hang and
shoot small children, and _ at one point _ burn an entire village
of men, women and children to death in a boarded-up church.
</P>
<P>
   It's too bad. With a slightly lighter hand, a bit more
intelligence and a healthy dash of moral ambiguity in the script,
this might have been a classic _ a truly memorable movie about the
American Revolution _ instead of a stunning-looking, undeniably
compelling but empty-headed shoot 'em up.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriot. Directed by Roland Emmerich. Written by Robert
Rodat. Cast: Mel Gibson, Heath Ledger, Joely Richardson, Jason
Isaacs, Chris Cooper, Tcheky Karyo, Tom Wilkinson. Columbia. 158
minutes. Rated R for violence.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
