<HEADER>
A6377 &Cx1f; tad-z
r w BC-EVERGLADES-0628-COX     06-27 1476
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EVERGLADES-0628-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    RESTORING ``CROWN JEWEL'' GETS BIPARTISAN LOOK
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON - With key administration officials looking on, a
bipartisan group of senators Tuesday unveiled a bill authorizing a
$7.8 billion, 30-plus year restoration of the Everglades.
</P>
<P>
   Calling the Everglades a ``crown jewel'' of America's
environment on the scale of the Grand Tetons or Yellowstone
National Park, Sen. Bob Smith, R-N.H., said ``it is our moral
obligation to restore this for the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith chairs the Senate Environment and Public Works Committee
which today will vote on the restoration plan _ which is similar to
the administration plan commonly known as the ``restudy.''
</P>
<P>
   The plan establishes a science-based process of reversing more
than a century of efforts to drain and control the Everglades by
restoring the sheetflow of water across much of South Florida. The
bill provides assurances that most of the additional water will be
used for environmental purposes while giving the state greater
authority to determine how the water will be allocated.
</P>
<P>
   The bill authorizes 10 of the 68 projects included in the plan
at an initial cost of $1 billion to be split evenly between the
federal and state governments. The other projects are expected to
be authorized as they are ready for construction.
</P>
<P>
   Also included are four pilot projects, costing $69 million,
designed to test new technologies that might be used later in the
restoration.
</P>
<P>
   Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt, who attended a news conference
unveiling the bill, called it a ``template for environmental
restoration'' and hailed it as the most important environmental
legislation in a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Babbitt noted that the legislation attempts to save the dying
Everglades National Park by restoring an ecosystem stretching from
Orlando to Florida Bay. The bill coordinates the responsibilities
of numerous federal agencies and sets up an equal partnership
between the federal and state governments over the project's
future.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the hefty price tag, Smith _ one of the most
conservative members of the Senate _ said he felt it necessary for
the federal government to spend the money.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the right thing to do for everybody, especially for a
conservative,'' Smith said. ``I don't believe it is
anti-conservative to be pro-environment.''
</P>
<P>
   ---STORY COULD TRIM HERE---
</P>
<P>
   Environmental groups hailed the bill as a goal they have long
sought, but said they wanted an even stronger assurance that clean
water would be supplied to the natural areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``This legislation is a bipartisan starting point from which
</P>
<P>
   the Congress and the administration can work to conserve a
critical
</P>
<P>
   natural system on which both people and wildlife depend. It's a
</P>
<P>
   tremendous opportunity for Congress to demonstrate its
commitment to conserve and protect an irreplaceable national
treasure,'' said Michael Bauer, director of the National Wildlife
Federation's Everglades Project.
</P>
<P>
   Today's committee action could produce fireworks over the future
of Homestead Air Force Base, which is being considered for
conversion to a cargo airport.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. George Voinovich, R-Ohio, said he supports the restoration
bill but will offer an amendment asking that the airport's final
use be determined by the secretary of the Army in consultation with
the secretary of Interior and the head of the Environmental
Protection Agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``My personal opinion is that I would rather see anything other
than a large cargo airport right next to the Everglades,''
Voinovich said.
</P>
<P>
   Florida Sens. Bob Graham, a Democrat, and Connie Mack, a
Republican, indicated they would oppose the amendment. Graham is a
member of the committee.
</P>
<P>
   Both noted that Homestead's use has been studied once since 1994
and a second environmental impact study is nearing completion.
</P>
<P>
   Graham, who as Florida's governor launched the ``Save the
Everglades'' program in 1983, said the restoration bill would go a
long way toward his goal of ``rolling back the calendar'' and
making the area look more like it did in the 1880s than in the
1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Graham noted that there were no differences between the projects
recommended by the Army Corps of Engineers' restudy and this bill,
but there are some differences in the relationships between the
federal agencies and between the federal and state governments.
</P>
<P>
   Mack, who is retiring from Congress this year after 18 years,
said an Everglades restoration bill would be a fitting parting
gift.
</P>
<P>
   Carol Browner, a Miami native and administrator of the
Environmental Protection Agency, said the restoration plan was
important not only to protect the environment but also to provide
an assured supply of clean water to South Florida's 6.5 million
people, a number expected to double within 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is good news for the state's $14 billion tourism
industry, it's good news for the state's agriculture industry and
it's good news for future generations of Floridians,'' Browner
said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On the web:
</P>
<P>
   Senate Environment &AMP; Public Works Committee:
www.senate.gov/(tilde)epw bjects and skills that will prepare them
for work, higher education and independent living.
</P>
<P>
   Many local experiments have shown that disabled students who
help shape their own education are far more likely to graduate, get
into college or support themselves.
</P>
<P>
   But a federal compliance audit issued this year said that at
least 44 states fail to enforce that policy, which is supposed to
be a condition of receiving federal funds for education of students
with disabilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The feds have written some very pretty laws,'' said Laurel
Lawson, a 20-year-old junior at Georgia Tech who said she left the
public schools in order to obtain an education that allowed her to
enter a selective university. ``However, until the lasaid. ``As a
result, plans are made _ sometimes by a computer program, rather
than by people discussing an individual _ which may not provide the
student with the same education that non-disabled peers are
receiving, and certainly lack some of the plans and accommodations
that address a student's needs adequately.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Web:
</P>
<P>
   Progress Report on Disabilities:
www.ncd.gov/newsroom/publications/policy98-99.html
</P>
<P>
   Back to School on Civil Rights:
ww.ncd.gov/newsroom/publications/backtoschool(underscore)1.html
</P>
<P>
   Presidential Task Force on Employment of Adults with
Disabilities:
www.dol.gov/dol/(underscore)sec/public/programs/ptfead/main.htm
</P>
