<HEADER>
A6379 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MEXICO-CARDENAS-0628-     06-27 1176
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-CARDENAS-0628-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MEXICO'S CARDENAS: DEMOCRATIC HERO OR SPOILER?
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ To supporters he's the only true hero of Mexican
democracy and the impoverished.
</P>
<P>
   To others Cuauhtemoc Cardenas is in danger of going down in
history as a spoiler, the man who foiled a historic opportunity to
end 71 years of one-party rule in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   At 66, Cardenas is the spiritual leader of Mexico's left and the
son of one of this country's most beloved, nationalistic
presidents. In his third attempt at the presidency, polls are
showing that Cardenas is lagging in third place as Mexicans prepare
for the most competitive presidential election ever on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   With all campaigning to stop by law on Wednesday, Cardenas has
rejected 11th-hour appeals to withdraw and unite with a stronger
opposition candidate, conservative Vicente Fox Quesada. A
withdrawal by Cardenas _ analysts agree _ would greatly enhance
Fox's chances of toppling Mexico's Institutional Revolutionary
Party, the PRI, and forming what he promises would be a plural
``transitional'' government.
</P>
<P>
   In most opinion surveys of likely voters, Fox is in a virtual
tie with the PRI's candidate _ averaging out to around 40 percent
each _ while Cardenas ranges from 12-to-20 percent support. These
same polls also show that as much as 20 percent of the electorate
is undecided.
</P>
<P>
   ``Understand, Cuauhtemoc: To unite forces is what's best for the
country and for your people. We would share the government and the
responsibility of a transition,'' Fox said in a speech Saturday
night before an estimated 200,000 supporters here.
</P>
<P>
   But at his own equally huge rally the next day, Cardenas
bitterly spurned Fox, who has alternately insulted Cardenas and
tried to woo him and his party, the Democratic Revolutionary Party,
or PRD.
</P>
<P>
   ``His mournful cries are those of one who knows he will lose,''
Cardenas, the former mayor of Mexico City, said, attacking Fox in
his speech with as much vigor as he attacked the PRI.
</P>
<P>
   ``If (Fox) really had, as he claims, 40, 46 or 48 percent of all
votes, would he be calling me,'' Cardenas asked. ``Would he be so
desperately begging for the votes of the PRD?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody here is looking for work from him,'' Cardenas
continued, prompting cries of support from those gathered in the
main square in Mexico City, where the PRD is strong. ``To think
that Fox would share power would be to believe in another one of
his lies.''
</P>
<P>
   The PRD and Fox's party, the pro-free-market National Action
Party, the PAN, tried unsuccessfully last year to form an alliance
to select one candidate. Despite their ideological differences, the
parties have backed mutual candidates for several governors' races.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Cardenas' position on Sunday was that the PAN and the PRD
are basically enemies: ``Our political proposals, our styles of
government and our way of life are diametrically opposed.''
</P>
<P>
   Although many Mexicans who voted for Cardenas in the past have
thrown their support to Fox, the crowd at Cardenas' rally relished
his words. For hard-core Cardenas supporters voting for the PRI and
the PAN are the same sin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to kick out Bismarck so I can put Hitler into
office,'' said Jorge Martinez, 53, a university professor who wore
a yellow PRD scarf on his head at Cardenas' rally.
</P>
<P>
   But Fox, who has fought to overcome his party's stuffy image,
has picked up significant backing from some leftist leaders whose
priority is to defeat the PRI.
</P>
<P>
   Two former top Cardenas advisors, Jorge Castaneda, a leading
writer, and Adolfo Aguilar Zinzer, an independent senator, are on
Fox's team. Porfirio Munoz Ledo, a PRD co-founder who broke from
the party for his own presidential bid, dropped out of the race
recently to support Fox.
</P>
<P>
   Fox held a meeting Monday with other leftists who chastised
Cardenas for refusing to step aside.
</P>
<P>
   ``If (PRI candidate) Francisco Labastida wins, it will be in
good part the fault of Cardenas, who, in spite of Vicente Fox's
repeated calls for unity, has acted with extreme stubbornness,''
said Indian community leader Julian Jimenez Garcia.
</P>
<P>
   For Cardenas, this will most likely be his last run at the
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   For more than a dozen years he has been at the forefront of the
fight to make Mexico a more democratic, less economically polarized
nation. Although Mexico is the world's fifth-largest oil-producing
nation, half of its population lives in poverty.
</P>
<P>
   Cardenas co-founded the PRD, which accuses the PRI of having
abandoned the ideals of the Mexican Revolution _ land and tools for
peasant farmers, free education at all levels and government
protection of national industries.
</P>
<P>
   Cardenas' father, Lazaro, nationalized foreign-owned oil
industries in Mexico in the 1930s and distributed land, built dams
and other infrastructure to benefit the countryside. Lazaro named
his son after the last Aztec king.
</P>
<P>
   Fox last month called Cardenas ``jealous and ``a traitor to
democracy,'' as well as ``obsessed'' with becoming president, like
his father.
</P>
<P>
   Cardenas accused Fox of ``not having the pants,'' or courage, to
make such remarks to his face.
</P>
<P>
   Cardenas was a member of the PRI, like his father, but he broke
with the party to run in 1988 as presidential candidate of a
leftist coalition. The election was widely viewed as stolen from
Cardenas by Carlos Salinas de Gortari _ burned ballots were found
and suspicious computer crashes occurred. After that, Cardenas
emerged as a tireless critic of PRI corruption and free-market
economic reforms led by President Salinas.
</P>
<P>
   Cardenas lost a second run at the presidency in 1994, when
Mexicans were gripped by fear after a spate of political
assassinations, including PRI presidential candidate Luis Donaldo
Colosio.
</P>
<P>
   When the peso crashed in December 1994 and revelations of
corruption and mismanagement during the Salinas administration
began to come out, ision stations widely viewed as biased in favor
of the PRI.
</P>
<P>
   ``People had very high expectations, too, for what Cardenas
would be able to accomplish as mayor,'' said Mexican political
analyst Jose Antonio Crespo.
</P>
<P>
   But Cardenas can still draw crowds of adoring supporters. And
analysts believe he could still beat both Fox and Labastida in
Mexico City, home to more than 6 million voters and 10 percent of
the electorate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ever since 1988, I've voted for Cardenas. He would be the only
real change in Mexico,'' said Norma Bonilla, 44, an administrative
worker at the Mexico City's Polytechnic Institute. ``The strength
of Cardenas is even if he doesn't win the presidency, the PRD will
continue to win in the Congress. The party will go on.''
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Ferriss' e-mail address is: susanf(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information:
</P>
<P>
   www.cardenas2000.org
</P>
<P>
   www.wola.org (Washington Office on Latin America)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
