<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 17:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6380 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-BKN-TEENAGER-HNS &LR;      06-27 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-TEENAGER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SMILES FOR DARIUS MILES AT NBA DRAFT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By GWEN KNAPP  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Five years after Kevin Garnett's giant leap for
teen-kind, another man-child heads for the promised land. The
critics have been muted, if not thoroughly silenced, because at 18,
Darius Miles looks like a sure thing.
</P>
<P>
   No less an authority than Michael Jordan, Washington's general
manager in absentia, has said that Miles deserves to be the No. 1
pick in Wednesday's NBA draft.
</P>
<P>
   Everything about Miles' entry into the league seems like a
feel-good story. He grew up in East St. Louis, Ill., one of
America's most blighted cities, and he should be a millionaire
before the year's out.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't have to worry that general managers will be shy about
drafting a high schooler. He can thank Kevin and Kobe for that.
They have vaulted into the elite of the NBA without benefit of
tutelage from the Kryzewski, Thompson &AMP; Tarkanian branch of the
basketball-industrial complex.
</P>
<P>
   What team wants to be known as the one that took Joe Smith first
in the '95 draft, when Garnett was available? What teams wants to
be known as the one that took Todd Fuller ahead of Kobe Bryant in
1996? What team, in other words, wants to be known as the Warriors?
</P>
<P>
   Well, perhaps that's too easy. Consider that other, saner
franchises, took Antoine Walker, Kerry Kittles and Samaki Walker
over Bryant. And that Philadelphia and Denver have to live down
choosing Jerry Stackhouse and Antonio McDyess over Garnett.
</P>
<P>
   Miles presents an even easier decision. Since so many collegians
have started bailing out as freshmen and sophomores, Miles isn't
competing for draft position with eminently safer picks. He is
competing against players almost as young as he is, or those who
were never sure things and, therefore, had to stay in school.
</P>
<P>
   So is it time to drop the fight against the kiddie pool turning
pro? Sure _ if you're talking about a sure thing.
</P>
<P>
   But for every pundit who mocks the choice of Joe Smith over
Garnett, there should be an advocate for another Smith kid, the one
who fell hard on the leap from high school to NBA.
</P>
<P>
   Leon Smith's promised land turned out to be a mirage. Drafted at
the bottom of the first round last year, he ended up in a psych
ward, recovering from a suicide attempt, less than six months after
he was picked.
</P>
<P>
   Smith had been reared in group homes, and then he went to Dallas
to play for Don Nelson (no one has ever confused him with Father
Flanagan). When Smith couldn't make it there, the Mavericks pointed
him toward a European league for more seasoning. He rebelled. Then
he imploded.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA's role in Smith's self-destruction is highly debatable.
Its need for a minor-league system, directly accountable to the big
clubs, is not.
</P>
<P>
   In baseball, the minors are the ``farm''; the majors are the
``parent club.'' Being sent to the triple-A affiliate does not feel
like excommunication. Stars go down to the minors when they get
hurt. Young stars-in-waiting go down on the farm, or start there,
without fear that the major-league club has given up on them.
</P>
<P>
   Not so in the NBA. A player ends up in the CBA one way and one
way only. He has to be cut.
</P>
<P>
   And what of the players who don't fall between the cracks, but
get caught in limbo? They're not Kobe or Kevin, but they're not
Leon Smith, either. They're Jermaine O'Neal, sitting on the bench,
waiting when they should be playing.
</P>
<P>
   With a minor league, they could put their games in order, play
40 minutes a night. Over the long term, who knows how much money
these kids might lose because their skills never matured?
</P>
<P>
   The NBA says it wants to fix this problem, because the league
will lose in the long term, too. It already has, in the quality of
play, and in the public-relations disaster that followed Leon
Smith's horrific crash.
</P>
<P>
   But so far, the plans for a minor league have yielded nothing.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, hype surrounding Kobe and Kevin has reached dangerous
proportions. Nike ran ludicrous ads during the NBA playoffs, with a
whiney disc jockey asking why Garnett's choice had been so
vehemently criticized. Nobody rants about baseball, hockey and
tennis players skipping college, the DJ points out softly _ and
disingenuously.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball and hockey have the minors. Tennis is an individual
sport, without coaches to limit playing time, without lineups that
are dictated by front-office politics.
</P>
<P>
   But what can we expect from Nike? The same ad series showed a
bunch of women athletes _ ``our sisters,'' the DJ says _ and asked
why they weren't paid as much as men. Does Nike pay its female
endorsers as much as it pays men? Scott Reames, senior
public-relations manager, concedes: ``No, we don't.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Nike just wanted to raise provocative questions, to make
people think. Problem is, with the Garnett ad, the company made
people think that the issue was ``To go to college or not to go.''
</P>
<P>
   The real question is more complicated. It's not about the Kevin
Garnetts. It's not about Darius Miles. It's about kids like Leon
Smith, about kids who don't have shoe deals, the ones on the fringe
of the pros. These youngsters _ heaven help them _ make less money
than some female stars. They have less clout. If there's a better
sign of their dire circumstances, I don't know what it is.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-27-00 1736EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
