<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 17:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6385 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-RENO-GORE-HNS &LR;      06-27 0901
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RENO-GORE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     RENO REFUSES TO TALK ABOUT GORE INVESTIGATION 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (Eds: FILED in the ``w'' and ``p'' categories.)
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARK HELM  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Warning against investigations conducted ``in
headlines,'' Attorney General Janet Reno refused Tuesday to say
whether she will appoint a special counsel to investigate Vice
President Al Gore's 1996 fund-raising activities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not think it proper for me to comment on pending
investigations and pending prosecutions,'' Reno told a Senate panel
looking into possible 1996 campaign fund-raising abuses.
</P>
<P>
   Resisting calls by Republican senators for a special counsel in
Gore's case, Reno said that publicly discussing it could taint the
probe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sound bites and quick conclusions are not conducive to
thorough analysis,'' she said. ``I think those matters should be
handled properly and professionally, not in headlines but in
courtrooms.''
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., insisted that the evidence showed
that the vice president ``may have lied'' to federal prosecutors
and that the attorney general should turn the investigation over to
an outside counsel.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Department of Justice should not be investigating the vice
president,'' he said, adding that ``there is a conflict of
interest.''
</P>
<P>
   Judiciary Committee Chairman Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, complained
that the Justice Department's probe of 1996 campaign finance
irregularities has taken too long and yielded too little.
</P>
<P>
   ``We now find ourselves on the threshold of a new election with
many old questions still unanswered ... It is now time to make a
decision and be held accountable for it,'' Hatch said.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Specter, who has been holding hearings into campaign
finance abuses, announced that the head of the Justice Department's
campaign finance unit had recommended that Reno appoint a special
counsel to investigate Gore. According to Specter, Robert J. Conrad
Jr. told Reno that during an interview that he and two FBI agents
conducted two months ago with Gore, questions arose about the vice
president's truthfulness. Conrad reportedly said the questions came
when they asked Gore about a 1996 luncheon he attended at the Hsi
Lai Buddhist Temple in Hacienda Heights, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Reno refused to comment on her discussions with Conrad about the
investigation, but she told the committee that she listens to a
``wide variety'' of advisers and that they often disagree with one
another and with her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like `yes' people,'' she said. ``I also don't count up
the votes, with the majority winning.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Robert Torricelli, D-N.J., defended Reno, pointing out that
she has appointed seven independent counsels _ the most by any
attorney general _ to investigate members of the Clinton
administration, including the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is inconceivable that Ms. Reno can be criticized on her
independence or her willingness to appoint independent counsels,''
he said. ``The facts simply aren't there.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who was previously questioned four times by campaign
finance investigators, was interrogated for four hours by Conrad
and two FBI agents on April 18. Gore has said that he was unaware
that the luncheon, attended by saffron-robed nuns and monks, was a
fund-raiser, although he has acknowledged that he knew it was
``finance-related.'' The event, which lacked the conventional
trappings of a fund-raiser such as expressions of thanks for
contributions, nonetheless raised $140,000 for the Democratic
National Committee. Much of the money was later returned when
questions arose about the donors. Longtime Gore fund-raiser Maria
Hsia was convicted this year of campaign finance violations, which
included disguising the true source of donations given by the
temple's nuns and monks. Last Friday, after Specter announced
Conrad's recommendation, Gore released a transcript of his
interview with the federal investigator and the FBI agents.
</P>
<P>
   The transcript showed Gore heatedly denying under oath any
wrongdoing about his role at the Buddhist temple.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sure as hell don't recall having _ I sure as hell did not
have any conversations with anyone saying this is a fund-raising
event,'' Gore testified. ``As to whether or not I had any follow-up
conversations that said, were we able to set up this event or not,
I don't think I did. But I may have ... ''
</P>
<P>
   Gore advisers have suggested that Conrad's recommendation was
leaked in an attempt to force Reno to name a special counsel during
the presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Specter bristled at that suggestion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not take lightly the comments of the vice president's
surrogates accusing me of working with the Bush campaign on this,''
he said. ``That is a matter I will take up personally with the vice
president to see if it was authorized.''
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general has been strongly criticized by Republicans
for her past refusals to seek an independent investigation of the
Democrats' fund-raising. Justice officials insist that the
department's campaign finance unit, set up shortly after the 1996
presidential election, has ``vigorously'' pursued all leads and has
succeeded in winning 17 convictions. Conrad was appointed by Reno
six months ago to head the unit.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
