<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 17:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6388 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-ACCOUNTANTS-EDUC-NYT &LR;      06-27 1161
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ACCOUNTANTS-EDUC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACCOUNTING FIRMS TARGETING HIGH SCHOOLS TO SNARE RECRUITS 
</HEADLINE>
   By GREG WINTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When jobs are plentiful but applicants scarce, where do
accountants go to drum up enthusiasm for a profession whose very
name evokes images of number-crunching nerds with pen-holders in
their shirt pockets?
</P>
<P>
   As it turns out, they now go to the one place where hostility to
all things uncool burns hottest: high school.
</P>
<P>
   Competing for the smallest pool of college graduates of
accounting programs in more than a decade, many of the nation's
largest accounting firms and associations have begun seeking talent
at secondary schools, the latest battlefield in an industrywide
recruitment war. With scholarships and internships in hand, they
are hoping to resuscitate a field that is rapidly losing devotees
to the wonders of technology and the glamor of being an
entrepreneur.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're making big investments in the development of a high
school pipeline,'' said James Hayes, a partner at
PricewaterhouseCoopers who oversees recruitment efforts to about
3,000 schools a year. ``High school may almost be too late, and at
some point we have to start looking at middle schools.''
</P>
<P>
   This is not to say that the Big Five accounting firms _ Arthur
Andersen, Deloitte &AMP; Touche, Ernst &AMP; Young, KPMG and
PricewaterhouseCoopers _ have stopped their hiring efforts on
college campuses. In fact, driven by a boom in business, they are
crafting ever-wilder ways of grabbing college students' attention
and winning their loyalty. Ernst &AMP; Young now sends its interns to
Disney World, while Arthur Andersen sponsors a national tax
Olympics every year that awards the winning school $20,000 in
scholarships.
</P>
<P>
   But a 23 percent drop in enrollment in college accounting
programs since 1996 has prompted many in the industry to focus on
students before they are whisked away by other fields. The goal is
not to pluck recruits fresh from high school, but to plant the
corporate flag and push college-bound students into the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``One objective is to get them exposed to careers in
accounting,'' said Allen Boston, a recruiter with Ernst &AMP; Young,
which offers college scholarships to high school students in 15
states. ``The other is to get them to know Ernst &AMP; Young.''
</P>
<P>
   Leading the charge is the profession's primary association, the
American Institute of Certified Public Accountants, which will send
an accounting curriculum to about 10,000 high schools this fall.
</P>
<P>
   As much public relations as instruction, the institute's lessons
promote accounting across the disciplines, from physics to social
studies: history becomes a class on how sleuthing accountants
caught Al Capone; chemistry becomes a chance to set the price of an
electric car. Anything, in fact, to topple the stereotype of the
humorless drone in a back room.
</P>
<P>
   Some high school students are buying it. Lindsey Whitneck, who
graduated from Bristol Central High School in Connecticut in June,
said distaste for study had, at first, soured her on going to
college. But after taking classes with one of the accounting
curriculum's designers, she took an after-school bookkeeping job
last fall and has now enrolled in Central Connecticut State
University to major in accounting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like accounting saved me,'' Whitneck said, although she
added: ``Everyone in my family thinks it's only a bunch of numbers
on paper. They just don't understand.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, such converts remain rare, college professors say.
The profession holds a certain appeal in tough economic times: When
jobs are scarce, a certified public accountant is nearly assured
employment. In an economy that promises young people fun and riches
elsewhere, however, the profession must double its recruiting
efforts.
</P>
<P>
   College students ``don't want to dedicate themselves to the work
it takes to get a technical degree,'' said Sally Jones, an
accounting professor at the University of Virginia, where
accounting majors have dropped more than 50 percent since 1992,
despite rising applications to the business school. ``There's such
a demand for business students that they are going to work in
start-ups, finance, everything but accounting.''
</P>
<P>
   Making matters worse, almost all states now require an extra
year of college courses before students can take exams to get a
license in accounting. The new rules, adopted at the accounting
institute's urging in the late 1980s, only recently went into
effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``The timing was unfortunate,'' said Bea Sanders, the
institute's academic director. ``Ten years ago, no one imagined
that there would be a whole new economy drawing on the pool.''
</P>
<P>
   The number of first-time takers of CPA exams has fallen 13
percent since 1992, the institute said. And with fewer accountants
to choose from, many firms have taken to raiding one another for
talent, or simply buying smaller practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's just nobody left to employ,'' said Kim Fantaci,
director of the National Association of Certified Public Accounting
Firms, an association of 47 small to mid-size practices.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the shortage has been a boon to salaries. In
an April survey of 70 academic disciplines at more than 120
schools, the National Association of Colleges and Employers
reported an 8.8 percent increase in starting pay _ now about
$37,000 _ for accounting graduates, second only to the gain for
information-systems majors.
</P>
<P>
   But accounting salaries still lag behind those in technology,
and accounting firms have proved reluctant to offer stock options,
the Holy Grail of many job seekers these days.
</P>
<P>
   ``People feel that they are covering their bets better by
getting a broader business degree,'' said Jane Rubin, an
accreditation specialist at the International Association for
Management Education.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin said she supports efforts to arouse teen-age curiosity,
though she thinks programs so far are insufficient. ``There's going
to have to be a much more comprehensive master P-R plan than even
what's been envisioned so far,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe so, but the Big Five firms still stand to benefit from the
early exposure of their profession to young people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eventually these kids are going to be adults with businesses
who are going to use their services,'' said Sanders, the accounting
institute's academic director.
</P>
<P>
   The accounting firms themselves seem to have no illusions about
their high-school expeditions. Easily distracted, convinced their
careers are eons away, teen-agers are moving targets, difficult to
track through college and beyond, they acknowledge.
</P>
<P>
   But, they add, they have no choice but to take aim at them.
</P>
<P>
   ``As difficult as it is, given the number of high schools that
are out there, we need to do more,'' said William Nickey, New York
recruiting director for Deloitte &AMP; Touche. ``Even if the economy
slows down, we're always going to need more accountants than we're
currently producing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-27-00 1741EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
