<SLUG> BC-SPOT-BJT28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 UPDATE &HT;    UPDATE
 &HT;    CoxNet Cox News Service budget
 &HT;    FOR WEDNESDAY, June 28, 2000
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   For questions, please call 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   Eds. Deletes: CAR-JARRETT, NORMAN, DAVIDIAN, PRESCRIPTIONS,
TURNER, WORLDCOM, PUBLIC-PRIVATE
</P>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   RENO-GORE _ Coverage of Janet Reno's appearance before a Senate
subcommittee looking into possible wrongdoing by Vice President Al
Gore. (Foskett, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 25.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH _ The end is finally in sight for the Bush fund-raising
effort that has shattered records by collecting more than $92
million. It will shut down in mid-July as the campaign shifts into
a federally funded operation after the GOP convention. But Bush
isn't done yet. A fund-raising letter in the mail this week seeks
to milk another $100 to $150 out of donors who have not hit the
$1,000 maximum. Bush says he needs it for TV ads. (Herman, Austin
American-Statesman). 25.
</P>
<P>
   PRESCRIPTIONS _ WASHINGTON _ Elderly rural Americans are most
likely to need prescription drugs and least likely to be able to
obtain them, according to a new study released Tuesday.
Administration officials say the study bolster's their argument
that a Republican drug plan scheduled for a House vote Wednesday
won't help many seniors. (Lipman, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   DAVIDIAN _Davidians' wrongful death lawsuit trial continues with
more testimony from survivors of the fire and a California man who
offered up armored firefighting equipment to the FBI. (England,
Waco Tribune-Herald). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EROSION _ WASHINGTON _ The Federal Emergency Managment Agency
releases a five-year study of the nation's coastal erosion problem.
(O'Dell, Cox Nnews Service). 18.
</P>
<P>
   WAN location Atlanta, category National, subcategory
Environment.
</P>
<P>
   EVERGLADES _ WASHINGTON _ Sen. Bob Smith, chairman of the
Environment and Publics Works Comittee and Sens. Bob Graham and
Connie Mack release details of the Everglades restoration bill they
will vote on tomorrow in the committee. (Lipman, Cox News Service).
18.
</P>
<P>
   EDUCATORS-COMPUTING _ ATLANTA _ At the National Educational
Computing Conference in Atlanta this week, such heavyweights as
U.S. Education Secretary Richard Riley and Intel CEO Craig Barrett
have preached the value of technology in the classroom. At the
periphery, though, is a lone voice of caution: that of William
Rukeyser, head of an anti-technology group called Learning in the
Real World. He says that research hasn't proven that technology
improves learning, and he says it's too expensive for cash-strapped
schools. ``Everybody loves to play with new toys,'' he says. ``But
the fact is, when it comes to technology in schools, there is no
Santa Claus.'' His is not a popular view at the technology
conference this week. WITH PHOTO (Rukeyser). (Judd, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 12.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-CHILDHEALTH _ The first time Carla Savannah applied for
Medicaid she was pregnant. She got a lecture, but no health
coverage. ``My son's now 1 and I'm still not covered,'' said
Savannah, 18, of Austin. ``I just have bills.'' Despite three or
four tries, Savannah has not successfully navigated the complex
Medicaid system, dominated by poor women and children entitled by
federal law to health care. Although Medicaid is intended as a
safety net for the state's most vulnerable residents, the poorest
children in Texas have the hardest time getting covered. Texas
maintains some of the nation's most stringent Medicaid rules. The
restrictions are in sharp contrast to Texas' new Children's Health
Insurance Program, which serves the working poor whose incomes
generally are higher than Medicaid families. Insurance Commissioner
Jose Montemayor plans Tuesday to present the results of a survey of
Texas health insurance carriers that offer coverage to children.
(Roser, Austin American-Statesman). 35. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   POL-TICKER _ A brief roundup of the day's campaign events,
pulled from Cox staff and wire reports. (Cox News Service) ETA: 6
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLIC-PRIVATE _First comes love. Then comes marriage. Then
comes a newborn shown off live on the World Wide Web before its
powdered bottom ever graces a baby carriage. That's the basic
premise behind a Baby Huey-ish new company that's already signed up
more than 75 hospitals nationwide and which could be coming to the
metro Atlanta area by the end of this summer. The company lets new
parents conduct live-action ``netcasts'' right from the hospital,
meaning relatives scattered around the country and co-workers stuck
back at the office don't have to miss witnessing Junior's first
gurgles and coos. And why would they want to, having perhaps
already spent months tracking the pregnancy via the parents-to-be's
personal web page _ and, even before that, keeping up with their
wedding plans on yet another web page. Remember when experts warned
us about the possible isolating effects of the Internet? (Vejnoska,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   US-CUBA _ WASHINGTON _ A bill partially lifting sanctions
against communist Cuba may have officially hit the fast track
Tuesday, after House leaders agreed on a structuring of the
legislation. The bill now heads to a conference committee with a
Senate that has already indicated its approval, and could wind up
with a pact by week's end. President Clinton has also said that he
would sign the bill in its current form. Developing. (Deans, Cox
News Service). 20.
</P>
<P>
   WAN: Location, Atlanta; Category, International; Subcategory,
Other.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Expected to move by 5 p.m. EDT on the NYT Wire in (i)
International and (w) Washington categories.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-CARDENAS _ MEXICO CITY _ To some he's the hero of
Mexico's impoverished and oppressed. To others he's in danger of
becoming the spoiler of an historic opportunity for democratic
change. Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, the spiritual leader of Mexico's left,
is running in third place as Mexicans prepare to elect a new
president on Sunday, according to most pre-election opinion
surveys. This is the third time Cardenas has tried to oust the PRI,
Mexico's ruling party. This time, however, Cardenas' underdog
campaign has been eclipsed by Vicente Fox, a conservative
opposition candidate whom polls show stands a credible chance of
defeating the PRI. Fox has altthe Supreme Court will reject the
relative's bid to keeo Elian here, we say a fond farewell to the
6-year-old boy and this whole mess. (The Atlanta Constitution). 9.
</P>
<P>
   EDITORIAL-MIRANDA _ With a touch of black-robed drama seldom
seen in the U.S. Supreme Court chambers, Chief Justice William
Rehnquist took center stage with an aplomb for which he will long
be remembered. (The Atlanta Constitution). 8.
</P>
<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ Two matters that had seemed among the Great
Immutables of American life are showing distinct signs of wobble.
It is unclear where the startlingly sudden conversation about the
death penalty is headed, but the drift in what is loosely called
gay rights seems fairly clear. The surprise there is that the
momentum is accumulating so quickly. (Teepen, Cox News Service.)
MOVED MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ Ever noticed how many things you buy have a
price tag that ends in 9? The reason, of course, is the psychology
of marketing to make things seem less expensive than theyactually
are. Howard Kleinberg wonders why consumers don't seem to want to
do anything about it. (Kleinberg, Cox News Service.) MOVED MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   SCHUETT-COLUMN _ GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ Chairs have always been a
significant part of my life _ mainly, I guess, because I'm lazy and
much prefer sitting down to standing up. Somehow, my history seems
defined by a progression of chairs _ rather like reading the rings
of an ancient tree. (Schuett, Cox News Service). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   JOEMURRAY-COLUMN28 _ Column from Dreamsville: In the ``old''
days on a farm in Ohio, eating out used to mean a home-cooked meal
on a table under an apple tree in the yard. (Joe Murray, Cox
Newspapers senior writer).
</P>
<P>
   YOUNG-COLUMN _ ABC, which in its quest for someone
nontraditional and provocative has made a mistake. It's not that
Dennis Miller isn't great. He is. I will watch and listen with
interest. That's the problem. I'm not the target audience it wants.
The best man for the job was one with some blood on his lapel.
(Young, Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS
</P>
<P>
   CABLE-SETTOPBOXES _ July 1 is the deadline for makers of cable
set top boxes to come out with a box that can be sold directly to
consumers in stores like Circuit City. This is government mandated
to try to foster competition in a market dominated by just two
players: Scientific Atlanta and General Instruments. But nobody
thinks consumers really want to buy set top boxes through retail
stores. (Brister, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 16.
</P>
<P>
   WORLDCOM _ The Justice Department filed a suit to block the
proposed $129 billion merger of WorldCom and Sprint, the nation's
second- and third-largest phone companies, on grounds it would
increase prices for millions of consumers. The companies almost
immediately withdrew their merger notification filed with the
European Commission, citing Justice Department opposition. (Kanell,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   TURNER _ Turner Broadcasting System today announced plans for
$1.2 billion in new construction projects for Downtown and Midtown
Atlanta. The expansion will include office and hotel towers, and
new buildings at the company's Techwood campus. Turner says CNN.com
is a primary reason for the additional space. We take a look at how
they are fueling Turner's growth. Kempner(Kempner, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   MONEYTALK _ Personal finance advice. This week: tax lowering
steps. (Ezell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   SALVATION-ARMY _ ATLANTA _ They wear uniforms and have military
rank. But this is no regular army. They don't carry weapons, but
Bibles, and they fight for Jesus. Members of the Salvation Army
will be spending a week in Atlanta, praying and planning for the
future of their organization. We capture what they are up to on
their first day in Atlanta. (GWhite, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
25. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   SALARMY-FACTS _ ATLANTA _ A rail of fun facts about the
salvation army _ cost of uniforms, ranking system for members, most
recognized tunes played by the Army's brass bands. (Henry, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   LECRONE-PSYCHOLOGY _ Dr. Hap LeCrone's weekly psychology column.
This week: Obsessive personality(LeCrone, Waco Tribune-Herald)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT-ARTS
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-PATRIOT _ Movie review: ``The Patriot,'' filmed partially
in South Carolina with Mel Gibson as sort of Revolutionary
Braveheart. It's a movie made by Hollywood committee, at times
overtly bloodthirsty and overblown. There are a couple of moments
of cinematic beauty (especially a nighttime battle in a plantation
front-yard that's both beautiful to look at and frightening. Grade:
C+. (StMurray, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 27.
</P>
<P>
   SURVIVOR-SEQUEL _ CBS is already planning the sequel to mega-hot
hit ``Survivor,'' but Phil Kloer has some tongue-in-chek
suggestions on how a sequel might work. (Kloer, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 20.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD
</P>
<P>
   SANGRIA _ Sangria is not merely a quintessential summer
refresher. It also mocks snobbish wine rules that try to tell us we
should not drink cheap wine, we shouldn't mix wine with other stuff
and shouldn't ever pour it over ice. Sangria does all of those
things proudly, unabashedly, exuberantly. (Dayton Daily News). 20.
WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   SANGRIA-RECIPES _ Four Sangria recipes to go with main story.
(Dayton Daily News). 15.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS
</P>
<P>
   TENNIS
</P>
<P>
   TEN-WIMBLEDON-AGASSI _ WIMBLEDON _ Andre Agassi makes his debut
at Wimbledon vs. Taylor Dent. (Clarke, Palm Beach Post). 18.
</P>
<P>
   NBA DRAFT
</P>
<P>
   BKN-DRAFT-MAIN _ ATLANTA _ Overall advance of NBA Draft. The New
Jersey Nets are expected to take Kenyon Martin of Cincinnati with
the No. 1 overall choice. Iowa State forward Marcus Fizer and Texas
center Chris Mihm are also expected to be among those selected
early in the first round. Orlando has three of the top 13 picks
unless they trade. (Bunn, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 20.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-DRAFT-PREVIEW _ AUSTIN _ General preview on Wednesday's NBA
draft. (Rosner, Austin American-Statesman). 10-15.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   BKN-DRAFT-MIHM _ AUSTIN _ Before his freshman year at the
University of Texas, Chris Mihm got an opportunity not afforded
most young basketball players. In July of 1997, the recent graduate
of Westlake High School spent two days in San Antonio, working out
with David Robinson. When they were done, by way of farewell, the
San Antonio Spurs' all-star
</P>
<P>
   center left Mihm with a few words that, three years later, are
prophetic. Maybe he was just being polite or maybe he meant it, but
Robinson told the young 7-footer that he some day expected to see
him in the NBA. ``I remember David telling me that Chris impressed
him on the court and off the court,'' said Jeff Austin, the
Washington, D.C.-based agent who represents both Mihm and Robinson.
``And that was three years ago.'' Robinson was right. Chris Mihm's
time has come. (Riggs, Austin American-Statesman). 28.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-DRAFT-TEXASPREPS _ AUSTIN _ Texas, long known for football,
isn't getting the respect it should for its basketball talent. On
Wednesday, Chris Mihm of Texas and Kenyon Martin of Cincinnati will
be among the top five selections in the NBA draft. Both played high
school basketball in Texas Mihm is a graduate of Westlake. Martin
attended Dallas Bryan Adams. They aren't the first first-round
picks who played high school basketball in Texas. In the 1990s,
Larry Johnson (Dallas Skyline), Lance Blanks (Conroe) LaBradord
Smith of Bay City in 1991, Shaq O'Neal (San Antonio Cole) and
Oliver Miller (Fort Worth Southwest), no one in 1993, BJ Tyler
(Port Athur Lincoln) in 1994, Kurt Thomas (Dallas Hillcrest) and
Mario Bennett (Denton High) and Greg Ostertag (Duncanville); No one
1996; Tony Battise (Dallas South Oak Cliff) in 1997, no one in
1998; Brian Skinner (Temple High) and 2000 with Mihm and Martin.
(Golden, Austin American-Statesman). 15.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-DRAFT-HAWKS _ ATLANTA _ Advance of the NBA draft from a
Hawks perspective. Who will they choose with the No. 6 overall
pick? It might be Cincinnati's DeMarr Johnson, high school
All-American Darius Miles or Florida's Mike Miller. (Denberg,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 18.
</P>
<P>
   GOLF
</P>
<P>
   NORMAN _ Greg Norman will have surgery on his hip and miss about
eight weeks, including the British Open. (Dolch, Palm Beach Post)
</P>
