<HEADLINE>
CLAIRE ESSENTIALS  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by clients of ``HIGH STYLE AND MORE.''
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 (One color slide is available.) 
 By JESSICA KERWIN  
 From W magazine 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Claire Forlani isn't one to bottle up her emotions. One moment,
her raucous laugh is ricocheting off the walls in the quiet SoHo
Grand lobby, where the 28-year-old actress sits sipping tea; the
next, her big eyes are welling up with tears.
 &HT;    Only two days ago, Forlani was shooting a film in Vancouver.
Last night she hit a movie premiere and the alarm clock got her out
of bed half an hour ago, at noon.
 &HT;    ``It's been a very surreal few days for me,'' she says.
``Usually I have at least a week once I've finished a film to say
goodbye. I'm on an emotional roller coaster, and I just feel like I
could burst into tears at any moment.''
 &HT;    Fortunately all those feelings will be put to good use when the
next role comes along.
 &HT;    ``You relate to different things at different times in your
life,'' she says seriously, ``and you can give yourself to roles
purely because of what you need to experience or what you have
experienced.''
 &HT;    A second later, Forlani laughs out loud. ``I feel like I'm in a
therapy session,'' she says.
 &HT;    Not a moment too soon, either, to judge by the somber quality of
most of her major roles to date. She was Neal Cassidy's suicidal
girlfriend in ``The Last Time I Committed Suicide,'' the betrayed
girlfriend in ``Basquiat,'' and in ``Meet Joe Black,'' Forlani
hooked up with Death himself, in the form of Brad Pitt.
 &HT;    If those characters showed off her dark side, however, Forlani's
upcoming films will be a good deal sunnier. In ``Boys and Girls,''
she is a bouncy, wide-eyed college babe, and in ``Antitrust,''
slated for a fall release, she plays the techno-thriller's sole
Luddite.
 &HT;    ``My character's the one who puts a plant next to the computer
to absorb the negative energy,'' she explains.
 &HT;    Off-screen, Forlani's relationship with the press has also
seemed a bit gloomy, but she's given her attitude an overhaul as
well.
 &HT;    ``I was really bumming everybody out,'' she says of her
reluctance to publicize herself and her films. ``It was so deeply
depressing to me that I had to do those photo shoots, but you don't
want to not enjoy your day, and you don't want to destroy anyone
else's day. I'm finding ways to be less of a pain in the ass.''
 &HT;    As much as she may despise the pop of flashbulbs, Forlani loves
working her magic on the set.
 &HT;    ``I always ask for more takes,'' she says. ``I'm like a junkie.
Every director allocates me the amount I can have.''
 &HT;    Her addiction to acting began early, when, at age 11, Forlani
enrolled in the Arts Educational School in London. Later she moved
to San Francisco with her parents and then on to Los Angeles.
 &HT;    ``It's the same old story,'' Forlani insists. ``It was escapism.
My reality seemed gray, but the second I landed in L.A. _ it sounds
sick and twisted _ but when my feet hit the tarmac, I felt like I
went into Technicolor. My first years there were truly
intoxicating, even when nothing was happening and I was driving
around to pick up scripts in my shitty car. The air intoxicated me.
It's a bizarre feeling and an embarrassing one to admit to.''
 &HT;    It wasn't long before Forlani had bagged the coveted ``Meet Joe
Black'' role, opposite Pitt. Despite a decidedly negative critical
response to the otherworldly romance, Forlani was singled out for
praise.
 &HT;    Nevertheless, following that experience, she took a break from
movie making. ``I checked out,'' she says, looking into her tea.
``My mom was very sick, and I just went to be with her for a year.
No regrets.''
 &HT;    Forlani has been wary of the press since then, it's probably due
in part to a tabloid rumor that she and Pitt were involved in an
on-set romance. Was there anything to it?
 &HT;    ``I've answered the question so many times,'' she sighs,
exasperated. ``Is it still a question?''
 &HT;    With perfect timing, Forlani's 14-year-old goddaughter, Kyra,
who is visiting from England, appears beside her and takes a seat.
 &HT;    ``She's asking the Brad question,'' Forlani says.
 &HT;    ``The answer's no, isn't it?'' Kyra asks.
 &HT;    That's enough to get the actress laughing again. ``Thanks,
Kyra,'' she says. The two are looking forward to a day spent
wandering SoHo's boutiques.
 &HT;    ``Kyra's got the best taste of anyone I know,'' says Forlani,
who insists that she knows nothing about fashion. ``She loves to
shop, and I hate to shop, so Kyra dresses me.''
 &HT;    A few minutes later, the two bounce toward the door. Forlani
looks back over her shoulder.
 &HT;    ``I swear,'' she says, ``Kyra wasn't a ploy!''
 c.2000 Fairchild Publications 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Jessica Kerwin is a writer for Fairchild Publications.)
</P>
