<HEADLINE>
EYE SCOOPS!  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by clients of ``HIGH STYLE AND MORE.''
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 (Color art is available.) 
 From W magazine, WWD and DNR 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    
 WILD CHILD  
 &HT;    When ``Beverly Hills 90210'' actress Jennie Garth told InStyle
magazine that her favorite fragrance is an obscure scent called
Child that she buys at Fred Segal Apothia in Los Angeles, readers
scrambled for their phones.
 &HT;    The Apothia staff was overwhelmed with calls and owner Ron
Robinson had to hire someone just to handle the inquiries.
 &HT;    In the past four months, he has sold ``nearly six figures''
worth of the obscure indie scent, which he has quietly carried for
the past decade.
 &HT;    Robinson doesn't think Garth's plug had much to do with the
frenzy. After all, celebrity endorsements are commonplace these
days. Rather, it was the fact that Garth said Child drives men
wild.
 &HT;    ``Everyone who calls asks if it really has that effect on men,''
he noted.
 &HT;    -----
 BRITS TEE OFF ON CAMILLA'S COUTURE  
 &HT;    LONDON _ Poor Camilla. Her new look has bombed.
 &HT;    The British press has almost universally attacked the Versace
gown Parker Bowles wore to the gala dinner on June 20 to celebrate
the opening of the new headquarters of Prince Charles' The Prince's
Foundation.
 &HT;    The V-necked, pink gown with diamante swirls was a major fashion
statement by Parker Bowles, who previously has opted for low-key
dresses and suits by such designers as Valentino or Anthony Price.
Her new style included more blonde highlights in her hair and a
touch more makeup than usual.
 &HT;    But Camilla's makeover left fashion critics snarling.
 &HT;    ``So was this a dress too far?'' columnist Lesley Garner wrote
in The Daily Mail.
 &HT;    Garner contended Charles and his advisers were pushing Camilla
into the limelight too fast. Parker Bowles' choice of Versace was,
even unintentionally, identifying her with the late Diana, Princess
of Wales, who regularly wore dresses by the designer. Her dress was
also reminiscent of ones worn by the queen, Garner said, which
``might explain why Charles liked it.''
 &HT;    ``Can't they understand _ whoever they are _ that Camilla in her
normal black dress, or even her hunting jacket, had more integrity,
and thus earned much more sympathy, than this wholly manufactured
creature?''
 &HT;    The Times of London claimed Charles chose the bright-pink color
of the dress but not the design and either paid for the dress
himself or donated its value to one of Donatella Versace's favorite
charities. But whether Versace was the correct choice was clearly a
matter for debate even among Charles' advisers, the Times
indicated.
 &HT;    ``Camilla is never going to fit into the sort of slinky sheath
of the sort you would find on a Versace model,'' one royal source
said. ``She hasn't got a bad figure for a woman of that age. But I
suspect her outfits will hint at the curves instead of highlighting
them.''
 &HT;    The Evening Standard claimed Parker Bowles' choice was simply a
reflection of current society.
 &HT;    ``Donatella Versace dressing Camilla Parker Bowles _ in a frock
chosen by the Prince of Wales _ symbolizes the closing of a great
gulf, between city and county, aspirational chic and assured
frumpishness, youth (in spirit) and age,'' Melanie McDonagh wrote.
``It would be too much to call it a meeting of minds _ intellect
not being the distinguished feature of either set _ but it's
something like social and behavioral cross-dressing.''
 &HT;    But McDonagh went on to bewail the choice of Versace. Friends
and supporters of Parker Bowles have always claimed she's the type
of woman who would gladly leap off a horse and right into a
ballgown. Her appearance, though, left them wondering whether that
were still the case.
 &HT;    ``Camilla used to be the archetype of rural womanhood, if you
exclude the queen, and now the Prince of Wales has gone and spoiled
it,'' McDonagh wrote.
 &HT;    -----
 NAOMI'S MODEL SCENT  
 &HT;    NEW YORK _ As a hairstylist, makeup artist, publicist and
photographer hovered expectantly in a 33rd floor suite at the Four
Seasons Hotel on June 14, it was clear that supermodel Naomi
Campbell was in the house.
 &HT;    But as Campbell herself sauntered into the elegantly appointed
sitting room in a girlish cream top and floral pleated skirt, it
definitely wasn't a leave-it-to-diva scene.
 &HT;    Instead, Campbell was upbeat, discussing her eponymous new
fragrance, which is making its American debut at Sephora. Sephora
will have a U.S. store exclusive on the fragrance until September,
and it will retain the Web exclusive indefinitely.
 &HT;    By year-end, the scent is expected to be in about 200 department
store doors, including Macy's and Dillard's.
 &HT;    Campbell signed an agreement with Cosmopolitan Cosmetics _ the
fragrance arm of the German beauty giant Wella _ to produce the
fragrance, which started rolling out last fall and is now available
in several global markets, including Germany, Japan, Australia and
the United Arab Emirates.
 &HT;    Campbell said that the decision to do a fragrance wasn't one she
took lightly.
 &HT;    ``I didn't want to just put my name on something, like I did
with the Fashion Cafe,'' said Campbell of the ill-fated New York
theme restaurant she was once a partner in. ``I wanted to be
involved with my fragrance every step of the way, and that meant
committing myself in every way _ to the promotion, to the
formulation of the scent, to everything.''
 &HT;    It's been a successful association thus far: ``The people at
Cosmopolitan are wonderful people to work with,'' Campbell said.
``They're experienced fragrance marketers, and since they also
market the Gucci and Anna Sui fragrances, I'm certainly in great
company.''
 &HT;    Naomi Campbell is slated to be the first in a series of Campbell
fragrances. Campbell, in fact, is ready to go with a second _
Naomagic _ which launches in Germany in September. It doesn't have
a firm U.S. release date yet.
 &HT;    Nor is Campbell limiting herself to fragrance. She plans a full
beauty range, including color cosmetics _ already in the planning
stages _ scented candles, incense and possibly skin care. Whether
they'll be produced by Cosmopolitan has yet to be determined,
although ``they've been so great, I can't imagine going
elsewhere,'' Campbell said.
 &HT;    When asked if she's an aspiring Estee Lauder, Campbell chooses
her words carefully.
 &HT;    ``I admire Estee Lauder a great deal and to reach that level of
success would be incredible. But I'm taking this all one day at a
time. I'm not doing this line because I am being forced to
financially _ instead, I'm doing it because it touches me. It makes
a statement about my sense of smell to the world.''
 &HT;    -----
 VOGUE AND VH1 REUNITE  
 &HT;    This year, suspense is promised. And it's bigger. The second
installment of the ``Vogue/VH1 Fashion Awards'' will take place
Friday, Oct. 20, and has moved from the 69th Regiment Armory to a
venue twice the size at The Theater at Madison Square Garden. It
will be shown live on VH1 and repeated again that night and several
times later in the month.
 &HT;    Richard Beckman, vice president and publisher of Vogue, and Jeff
Gaspin, executive vice president of programming at VH1, said
they're determined to work out the kinks and make the show livelier
than a year ago.
 &HT;    The biggest kink of all last December: Everyone knew the winners
in advance. Although the evening appeared to run smoothly and came
in under two hours, the suspense was missing, as December issues of
Vogue were mistakenly sent out to subscribers early and the winners
were widely reported the day before the event.
 &HT;    This year, three awards will be voted upon online by Vogue
readers and VH1 viewers: designer of the year, most stylish video
and breakthrough video. Seven other categories will be determined
by a style council, composed of designers, models, stylists and
journalists.
 &HT;    Last year, Vogue bought into VH1's annual fusion of rock and
fashion, and the two became 50-50 financial partners in the event.
VH1 will once again reap TV revenues, and Vogue will take the
magazine's revenues from ads surrounding the November awards issue,
which will profile the winners.
 &HT;    -----
 LATIFAH CASTS HER VOTE  
 &HT;    Lane Bryant, whose past spokeswomen have included Camryn
Manheim, Anna Nicole Smith and Mia Tyler, is going the hip-hop
route.
 &HT;    The plus-size retailer, along with election.com, an online
election firm, is joining forces with Queen Latifah, recording
artist and TV host, in a national in-store campaign for fall to
encourage women to register to vote.
 &HT;    The campaign features Latifah in a fake mink vest and leather
jeans. She and Smith will also do the catwalk at the company's
Venezia Jeans fashion show on Sept. 6 in Manhattan.
 &HT;    ``Lane Bryant has some cool stuff, and it's affordable,''
Latifah said. ``I also like their positive outlook. I'm not ashamed
of who I am. And that's what they are all about.''
