<HEADER>
A6409 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-FBC-SHRINE-GAME-HNS &LR;      06-27 0381
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-SHRINE-GAME-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     NEW GIANTS STADIUM TO HOST SHRINE GAMES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DWIGHT CHAPIN  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A five-year agreement has been reached to bring
the East-West Shrine football game to Pacific Bell Park, beginning
Jan. 13, 2001.
</P>
<P>
   To accommodate the 76th annual event, the San Francisco Giants'
new baseball park will be converted into a gridiron for the first
time.
</P>
<P>
   The East-West Game has been played for the last 25 years at
Stanford Stadium, after an earlier history that included a 40-year
stop at Kezar Stadium, as well as much shorter stays at long-gone
Ewing Field (for its first year, in 1925), Candlestick Park and the
Oakland Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   Attendance for the college all-star game at Stanford Stadium,
which seats 80,000, had fallen off markedly in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers hope to rekindle interest, in a facility that seats
about half as many spectators.
</P>
<P>
   There won't be much room to maneuver for players or fans in a
baseball-park-turned-football-stadium, but the setting should help
to improve the game's intimacy _ and perhaps boost its popularity.
</P>
<P>
   And the Giants, in signing a contract to bring in the historic
contest, will get a financial boost in paying off the costs of
building Pac Bell Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are extremely excited about returning the Shrine Game to
the city of its origin, San Francisco,'' said Jeffrey Foster, the
game's executive vice president. ``Given its intimate size and
convenient location, Pacific Bell Park is the perfect setting to
hold this type of event.
</P>
<P>
   ``By moving to Pacific Bell Park, we will create a more exciting
experience for our fans and athletes, and will further our goal of
providing national exposure for the Shriners Hospitals for
Children.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, the game has raised more than $14 million for
the 22 Shriners hospitals located throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Tickets to the 2001 game will be offered first to Giants
charter seat and season ticketholders, prior to going on sale to
the general public shortly after Labor Day. Those interested in
adding their name to a priority waiting list should contact
BASS/Tickets.com at 510-762-2277, or on line at www.tickets.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
