<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 17:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6411 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-CHROMOSOME-18-1STLD-W     06-27 0734
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHROMOSOME-18-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GROUP OFFERS HOPE FOR PEOPLE WITH CHROMOSOME DISORDER 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (EDS: SUBS 8thgraf, Bryant, to add home town)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By NICOLE FOY  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ It took 16 years for Torrie Bryant to realize she
was not alone. Born with a chromosomal abnormality that affected
her hearing and muscle tone, Bryant grew up without knowing there
were children with similar problems.
</P>
<P>
   Her doctors did not fully understand the disorder, and for years
they treated her symptoms without attributing them to the genetic
syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   But Bryant, now 20, said her life changed about four years ago
when she learned about the Chromosome 18 Registry and Research
Society, a one-of-a-kind organization that is based in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   The nonprofit group provides a support network for families with
children who have chromosome 18 abnormalities.
</P>
<P>
   It also helps fund research at the University of Texas Health
Science Center aimed at unlocking the genetic mysteries behind the
disorder.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really amazing finding out there were other people like
me out there,'' Bryant said. ``It made me feel not so alone.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Bryant joined about 35 children who have chromosome
18 abnormalities at the registry society's annual conference. The
seventh annual meeting, held at a resort near Boerne, Texas,
attracted families from as far as Scotland, Australia, Costa Rica,
Canada and Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant, of Marion, Mass., has a syndrome known as 18q-, which
means she is missing a piece from the ``long arm'' of chromosome
18. When she was born, in addition to suffering from poor muscle
control and hearing difficulties, Bryant also had a clubfoot.
</P>
<P>
   Each of those difficulties since has been corrected, and Bryant,
now a college student, considers herself fortunate. Some children
with chromosome 18 abnormalities suffer more severely, with common
effects being stunted growth, developmental delays, congenital
defects and mental disabilities.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to 18q-, other syndromes of the disorder include
trisomy 18, where there are three copies of the chromosome rather
than the usual two; 18p-, where a piece is missing from the ``short
arm'' of the chromosome; Ring 18, in which one of the copies of the
chromosome forms a ring; and tetrasomy 18p, where an extra
chromosome is present.
</P>
<P>
   Trisomy 18 can be the most severe of the syndromes. The chances
of being born with the disorder are about 1 in 5,000, and about
half of the children survive to 6 months of age. Only 10 percent
might live through the first year.
</P>
<P>
   The overall outlook for children with chromosome 18 defects is
unknown, said Jannine Cody, a health science center geneticist who
is president of the registry and research society. Since the
disorder easily can be misdiagnosed or missed, it has been hard to
track the life spans of those afflicted, she said.
</P>
<P>
   There have been reports, however, of adults with chromosome 18
deletions living into their 30s and 40s, Cody said.
</P>
<P>
   Cody and Robin Leach, an associate professor of pediatrics, have
spearheaded the research effort at University of Texas Health
Science Center. They are involved in a project testing the effects
of human growth hormone on children with 18q-.
</P>
<P>
   The two also are searching for the specific genes that are
missing or altered in children with the disorder. To that end, they
have been intensely interested in the international effort to
sequence the entire human genome.
</P>
<P>
   Monique Mansoura, a policy analyst with the National Human
Genome Institute, spoke at the conference and noted the historic
achievement announced Monday by President Clinton and British Prime
Minister Tony Blair regarding the human genome.
</P>
<P>
   The two leaders praised the international team of scientists
that completed a rough draft of the human blueprint after 10 years
of work.
</P>
<P>
   The project provides a map that researchers such as Cody and
Leach will use to try and unlock the mysteries of chromosome 18
defects.
</P>
<P>
   ``To a certain extent, we'll be able to treat some of the
symptoms of things like chromosome 18 just by understanding them,''
Mansoura said. ``The mapping effort gave us a parts list, and now
we need to go and say, `OK, how do we fix it?'''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Contact Nicole Foy by e-mail at nfoy(at)express-news.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
