<P>
   BKN-DRAFT-MIHM _ AUSTIN _ Before his freshman year at the
University of Texas, Chris Mihm got an opportunity not afforded
most young basketball players. In July of 1997, the recent graduate
of Westlake High School spent two days in San Antonio, working out
with David Robinson. When they were done, by way of farewell, the
San Antonio Spurs' all-star
</P>
<P>
   center left Mihm with a few words that, three years later, are
prophetic. Maybe he was just being polite or maybe he meant it, but
Robinson told the young 7-footer that he some day expected to see
him in the NBA. ``I remember David telling me that Chris impressed
him on the court and off the court,'' said Jeff Austin, the
Washington, D.C.-based agent who represents both Mihm and Robinson.
``And that was three years ago.'' Robinson was right. Chris Mihm's
time has come. (Riggs, Austin American-Statesman). 28.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-DRAFT-TEXASPREPS _ AUSTIN _ Texas, long known for football,
isn't getting the respect it should for its basketball talent. On
Wednesday, Chris Mihm of Texas and Kenyon Martin of Cincinnati will
be among the top five selections in the NBA draft. Both played high
school basketball in Texas Mihm is a graduate of Westlake. Martin
attended Dallas Bryan Adams. They aren't the first first-round
picks who played high school basketball in Texas. In the 1990s,
Larry Johnson (Dallas Skyline), Lance Blanks (Conroe) LaBradord
Smith of Bay City in 1991, Shaq O'Neal (San Antonio Cole) and
Oliver Miller (Fort Worth Southwest), no one in 1993, BJ Tyler
(Port Athur Lincoln) in 1994, Kurt Thomas (Dallas Hillcrest) and
Mario Bennett (Denton High) and Greg Ostertag (Duncanville); No one
1996; Tony Battise (Dallas South Oak Cliff) in 1997, no one in
1998; Brian Skinner (Temple High) and 2000 with Mihm and Martin.
(Golden, Austin American-Statesman). 15.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-DRAFT-HAWKS _ ATLANTA _ Advance of the NBA draft from a
Hawks perspective. Who will they choose with the No. 6 overall
pick? It might be Cincinnati's DeMarr Johnson, high school
All-American Darius Miles or Florida's Mike Miller. (Denberg,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 18.
</P>
<P>
   GOLF
</P>
<P>
   NORMAN _ Greg Norman will have surgery on his hip and miss about
eight weeks, including the British Open. (Dolch, Palm Beach Post)
</P>
