<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOTBALL-COSELL-FANTASY-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOWARD COSELL, SPEAKING OF SPORTS ...  
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to correct 12 rounds to 15 in 8th graf, bgng `I have
not...')   By RICHARD SANDOMIR    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hello again, everyone, this is Howard Cosell speaking of sports.
</P>
<P>
   Crude, vulgar, obnoxious, truculent, verbose, condescending, a
wiseacre.
</P>
<P>
   There is no question that Dennis Miller is all of these things.
</P>
<P>
   Much has been written by print reporters, that seedy lot of
hangers-on, about Miller, in essence, replacing me on ABC's
``Monday Night Football.''
</P>
<P>
   What a tribute to my palpable impact and how right I was for my
times that I have been irreplaceable for 16 seasons. Would that
young Dennis handle my halftime highlights, a historic
demonstration of ad-libbing proficiency.
</P>
<P>
   Young Dennis is quite the mischievous monkey on his weekly HBO
program. I watched it Friday night and I have rarely in my
illustrious career, with my full knowledge of constitutional law,
listened to somebody in greater need of a First Amendment defense
lawyer. I don't blush easily, but young Dennis articulated
vulgarities 18 times in a mere 30 minutes. Young Dennis informed
viewers that ``golly'' will be his ``Monday Night'' code for a
famous epithet.
</P>
<P>
   Not even the Danderoo ever took such reckless verbal risks.
</P>
<P>
   I have not been so appalled _ so horrified, so assaulted _ since
Nov. 26, 1982 _ the Houston Astrodome _ when Larry Holmes
brutalized _ even destroyed _ a defenseless and desperately
untalented Randall ``Tex'' Cobb for 15 dehumanizing rounds.
</P>
<P>
   It is unsurprising to this reporter that Don Ohlmeyer, a man I
greatly respect, turned to young Dennis to save ``Monday Night
Football.'' But he doubtlessly got the idea from yours truly: In
1985, I wrote, with characteristic perspicacity, that the show
needed a star, like Bill Cosby.
</P>
<P>
   We're dealing with football, an entertainment, not the
canonization of a saint. I believe young Dennis and I share much,
yet not enough. To his detriment.
</P>
<P>
   We each suffer from bad hair. For no apparent reason, he calls
attention to his slovenly tresses by nervously running his hand
through them. I dared not touch what I had, lest it move into
unsuitable and unstylish hairlines.
</P>
<P>
   Young Dennis and I are alumni of ``Saturday Night Live.'' My
version, on ABC, started before NBC's, yet it lasted but 22 weeks.
You are indisputably aware of its auspicious start: the American
debut of the Bay City Rollers.
</P>
<P>
   When I appeared as a guest on the NBC show, I dressed up as a
relative of Ed Grimley, the transcendent nerd created by Martin
Short. Dennis Miller merely emceed ``Weekend Update'' on that
program, replacing, in essence, Chevy Chase.
</P>
<P>
   I, of course, never replaced anyone.
</P>
<P>
   I was, and continue to be, an original.
</P>
<P>
   To his credit, this young scamp works assiduously at being
unlikable.
</P>
<P>
   I never toiled at it, such a skill coming naturally.
</P>
<P>
   He employs words like weaponry as I wielded words and thoughts
like the jabs Ali threw before the U.S. government stripped him of
his right to work.
</P>
<P>
   Young Dennis's intelligence is eclectic, even catholic, like
mine. I can envision him hosting a show like my ``Speaking of
Everything.'' His potty-mouthed show on Friday ranged from
commentary on Bill Gates and the execution of the convicted Texas
murderer Gary Graham to security leaks at Los Alamos.
</P>
<P>
   I confess to a modicum of shame at laughing when he remarked,
``It's always nice to know the doomsday machine is hooked up to a
Clapper.''
</P>
<P>
   I also confess that this lad is quite the communicator. Like me,
he possesses a rapport with young people, the type of skill that
told me I was the right person to report to America that John
Lennon had been assassinated.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, as someone for whom ``Monday Night'' is a distant and bad
memory, I am concerned about whether young Dennis's penchant for
baroque similes will work for an audience weaned on pedestrian
analyses of X's and O's and an overdependence on scribbling with
the Telestrator.
</P>
<P>
   Can a tackle by the insouciant defensive end Bruce Smith, long
of the Buffalo Bills, now with the suddenly renascent Washington
Redskins, be rightly compared to a ``choice between walking and
hitching a ride with a bisexual trucker''? Will there be
credibility to young Dennis describing the muddied nose of an
offensive tackle as if it had ``inhaled Bob Marley feet first''?
</P>
<P>
   In the booth with Alfalfa Michaels, with whom I once called
``Monday Night Baseball,'' and Dan Fouts _ the newest recruit of
manifest ordinariness from the Jockocracy, a substratum of ex-jocks
and ex-coaches that does not respect the training required to be an
effective broadcaster _ Miller will divide viewers between those
who admire and those who abhor him.
</P>
<P>
   I have considerable expertise in this field, having once been
voted the most loved and hated sportscaster, simultaneously, in a
TV Guide poll.
</P>
<P>
   I made ``Monday Night.'' I was the one who gave it moment. Those
who succeeded me _ Joe Willie Namath, The Juice, Dan Dierdorf,
Boomer Esiason _ had their moments, too, but they occurred during
the time of William of Orange.
</P>
<P>
   Yet I harbor some hope for young Dennis. He has none of my
experience, yet if he can make viewers hate him, and organize
screen-bashing keg parties to protest his most grotesque
utterances, ratings will ascend accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   Many years ago, Jim Brown described Howard Cosell as a warrior,
whose career could be measured by the caliber of his enemies.
</P>
<P>
   Young Dennis has much to shoot for.
</P>
<P>
   This is Howard Cosell.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
