<SLUG> BC-LOUIMA-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFICERS SENTENCED FOR ROLES IN LOUIMA ATTACK AND COVER-UP 
</HEADLINE>
   By JULIAN E. BARNES and ALAN FEUER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A federal judge on Tuesday sentenced a former
Brooklyn police officer to 15 years and eight months in prison for
attacking Abner Louima and then trying to cover up the assault.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Eugene H. Nickerson of U.S. District Court also ordered
the defendant, Charles Schwarz, to pay $277,495 in restitution to
Louima. Schwarz had faced a maximum sentence of life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Two other police officers, Thomas Bruder and Thomas Wiese, who
were convicted along with Schwarz in the cover-up scheme, were
sentenced Tuesday to five years in prison each.
</P>
<P>
   Schwarz has steadfastly maintained his innocence through two
convictions. The first conviction came in June 1999 for holding
down Louima as he was sodomized by another officer, Justin A.
Volpe, and the second in March for concocting a story to minimize
his involvement.
</P>
<P>
   In a lengthy statement to the court before he was sentenced
Tuesday, Schwarz told Nickerson that he would not ask for leniency
because he is an innocent man.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no doubt in my mind that you will give me a harsh
sentence,'' Schwarz said. ``I refuse to demean myself and beg for
mercy for a crime I did not commit. I have already spent 384 days
in jail, isolated in a six-by-nine cell, 23 hours a day, and it's
384 days too many.''
</P>
<P>
   Schwarz, who has been held in jail without bail since his first
conviction, was taken from the courtroom Tuesday by federal
marshals after the verdict.
</P>
<P>
   The two other defendants received the maximum sentences they
faced for their role in covering up the attack. Bruder and Wiese
were found guilty of conspiracy to obstruct justice by making up a
story to cover up Schwarz's role in the attack. The officers were
acquitted in June 1999 of beating Louima while he was in a squad
car.
</P>
<P>
   Both Bruder and Wiese were allowed to remain free after the
verdict but must surrender to federal authorities within 45 days.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the courtroom, Louima thanked the federal prosecutors
and the police officers who came forward to tell federal
investigators what happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``Justice is served,'' Louima said. ``I hope that this sentence
sends the message that no one is above the law.''
</P>
<P>
   During the first trial, prosecutors argued, and a jury agreed,
that Schwarz held down Louima while Volpe sodomized him. Volpe
confessed to the attack and was sentenced to 30 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Volpe has said that Schwarz was not involved, and instead said
the second officer in the bathroom was Wiese. Prosecutors have
contended that Volpe was not telling the truth.
</P>
<P>
   At Schwarz's sentencing Tuesday, Nickerson said it was clear
that Volpe bore the greater culpability. The judge also cited
Schwarz's military service and the fact that he had cared for a
disabled brother in handing down a sentence far shorter than the
maximum.
</P>
<P>
   ``But for Volpe's extraordinary brutality, it is unlikely
Schwarz would now face a sentence for a sexual assault carried out
with such force,'' Nickerson said. ``Volpe and not Schwarz wielded
the stick.''
</P>
<P>
   The attack on Louima, an immigrant from Haiti, focused public
attention on police brutality. And the prosecution of Schwarz,
Wiese and Bruder was held up as an attempt to erode the code of
silence among the police, commonly referred to as the Blue Wall of
Silence.
</P>
<P>
   But to Schwarz, the case against him was an example of
overzealous prosecution. He attacked federal prosecutors for being
unwilling to admit they made a mistake, and revise their story in
light of Volpe's testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Schwarz's lawyer, Ronald Fichetti, said he would continue to
appeal the conviction and seek to have Schwarz released.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not the end of the Schwarz case; this is the
beginning,'' he said. ``This court house has a black stain on it.
</P>
<P>
   Schwarz's wife, Andra, called the sentencing Tuesday ``the worst
day of our lives.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But we will get over it,'' she said. ``We expect him to be
totally vindicated.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruder and Wiese also told the judge they were innocent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stand before this court wrongfully accused, tried and
convicted,'' Wiese said. ``I never did anything wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Loretta E. Lynch, the U.S. attorney for the Eastern District of
New York, said instead of helping Louima, they decided to protect
their fellow officers who committed the attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``They chose instead self interest and to protect one of their
own,'' she told reporters after the sentencing. `When they did that
they turned their back on their oath and abdicated their
responsibilities.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside the courthouse, the Rev. Al Sharpton, standing next to
Louima, also criticized the claims by the former officers. He said
although he wished Schwarz had been given a life sentence, the
conviction and sentences had helped to breach the New York Police
Department's so-called wall of silence.
</P>
<P>
   ``These policemen are the first policemen to be crushed on the
blue wall of silence in a federal court,'' Sharpton said. ``The
courts have reaffirmed his guilt. Mr. Schwarz is where he should be
today, in jail.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
