<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADA-MURAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MURAL NUDITY BRINGS OUTCRY FROM PROVINCE'S INDIAN LEADERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLIN NICKERSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ Does a woman's naked breast constitute a racial slur?
</P>
<P>
   Indian leaders in British Columbia say so, decrying a painting
depicting several topless native women at work as ``highly
offensive.'' They have launched an angry campaign to force the
government to remove the mural and other historic artwork from the
provincial legislature.
</P>
<P>
   ``The images are hateful, like putting a swastika on a public
building,'' said Edward John, grand chief of the British Columbia
First Nations Summit, which represents 140 tribal bands in Canada's
westernmost province.
</P>
<P>
   He said it is degrading to show Indian women with their breasts
bared since white women of the same era would not be portrayed
similarly unswathed, at least not on the walls of a provincial
capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``The paintings reflect racist attitudes,'' John said. ``We've
got to get rid of these relics of ugly history.''
</P>
<P>
   The painting, which has decorated the rotunda of the legislature
in Victoria for more than 60 years, is one of four adjacent murals
depicting colonial life in British Columbia. The artwork shows
several bare-breasted Indian women carrying baskets of fish to
white colonists during construction of a fortified trading post in
1843. Scantily clad native women also lug logs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It portrays aboriginal women as sluts,'' said Bill Wilson, a
British Columbia chief. ``Our women never exposed their breasts to
anyone other than to the man to whom they were married.''
</P>
<P>
   Historians are not sure Wilson is correct. But those reached
Tuesday were very sure they did not want to comment publicly on an
issue that has far more to do with raw racial politics than
historic verisimilitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ideas of modesty varied among tribes,'' said one academic
specialists on the Indians of the Pacific Northwest. ``Suffice it
to say that bare breasts were more of a European preoccupation than
something native people fretted on.''
</P>
<P>
   Indian activists have set a deadline of July 31 for the
government to get rid of two of the murals. If officials don't act,
the activists threatened to take matters into their own hands,
perhaps stealing or defacing the murals.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are aboriginal people willing to remove the murals,''
Wilson said. ``These paintings have been highly offensive to us for
decades.''
</P>
<P>
   Indian activists also object to a scene in another mural that
shows a dejected Indian miscreant apppearing in court before a
stern magistrate. Each of the four paintings bears a title
reflecting virtues needed to build civilization: Labor, Courage,
Enterprise, and Justice.
</P>
<P>
   Commissioned by the province in 1932, the murals are the work of
English-born painter George Southwell, who died in 1961. The works
are viewed by thousands of visitors to the imposing legislative
structure every year.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians were quick to attack the sensibilities of the dead
white painter. But not so quick to promise that the murals will
come down.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a distortion, a fanciful impression, based more on the
South Pacific than the west coast of British Columbia,'' Dale
Lovick, minister of aboriginal affairs, said of the artwork.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, argued Lovick, who is white, the paintings should
not be destroyed but instead preserved as testimony to the
insensitivity of those who are not Native Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are a total distortion of what First Nations were
about,'' said Lovick, using the term by which some Canadian
aboriginals prefer to be known. ``I don't defend them as art, I
don't defend them as history. But I defend them as part of our
culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an ugly, unhappy part of our history,'' he said. ``So
you use it as an example of a world you want to do better than.''
</P>
<P>
   Responded Chief John: ``Bizarre.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, British Columbia Attorney General Andrew Potter
promised to launch an investigation into the Indian complaint.
``Depictions of a people and their cultural representation within a
government building are important,'' he said. ``If there are
concerns that the pictures are inaccurate or demeaning, I take
those concerns seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   But ridding the rotunda of the murals would be a major
undertaking. Artist Southwell, scorning canvas, painted his art
directly on to the wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``They will have to chisel them off because they are right on
the plaster,'' Marc-Andre Ouelette, director of legislature
protocol, told the Vancouver Sun. ``It's not like something is hung
there that you can just remove.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
