<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-BRITAIN-410&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA CHIDES BRITAIN FOR VISIT BY FORMER PRESIDENT OF TAIWAN 
</HEADLINE>
   By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ China condemned the British government Tuesday for
allowing Taiwan's former president, Lee Teng-hui, to visit Britain,
calling him a ``troublemaker'' who continues to work for Taiwan's
independence from the mainland.
</P>
<P>
   Lee left Tuesday for his first trip abroad since he stepped down
in May after 12 years as president. His stated reason was to attend
the high school graduation of a granddaughter, though he is also
expected to be honored by an academic society in Manchester.
British diplomats said they had been assured that the trip was
private in nature.
</P>
<P>
   But a Chinese spokesman said that Lee ``goes to the United
Kingdom with clear political motives'' and that China is ``strongly
opposed'' to the trip. China has lodged formal objections in both
London and Beijing, said the spokesman, Zhu Bangzao, at a regularly
scheduled foreign ministry news conference Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   As part of its campaign to isolate Taiwan diplomatically and
force it to reunify with the mainland, China pressures other
countries not to give Taiwan diplomatic recognition or to allow
high-level official exchanges.
</P>
<P>
   A decision by the United States in 1995 to allow Lee to give a
speech at Cornell University, where he received a doctorate in
agricultural economics, caused severe tensions and may have
prompted China to test missiles near Taiwan in an attempt to
intimidate Taiwan's voters before a presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   China on Tuesday did not indicate any specific actions it would
take against Britain. But Zhu made clear that although Lee is now
formally a private citizen, heading a think tank in Taipei, China
did not consider him so and would continue trying to hem in the man
the Chinese leaders loathe as a wily advocate of Taiwan's separate
international identity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lee is by no means an ordinary person,'' Zhu said. ``Though he
has stepped down, he stubbornly sticks to the idea of Taiwanese
independence, continues his activity in splitting China and tries
every means to organize separatist activities in the international
community.''
</P>
<P>
   China officially is maintaining a wait and see policy toward
Lee's successor, Chen Shui-bian, who has called for dialogue with
China. Beijing is wary because Chen has a history of calling for
independence and now, though he says such a declaration is
unnecessary, he has refused to embrace Beijing's ``one China''
principle.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Since Lee no longer holds office, his unofficial travels would
appear to be something of a sideshow, but China remains extremely
prickly on the subject.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement that in a way confirms China's fears, The Liberty
Times, a Taiwan newspaper with close ties to the former president,
said Tuesday morning that Lee's success in gaining entry to Britain
only one month after departing office ``of course goes beyond the
significance of a simple private trip.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
