<HEADLINE>
NEW REPORT DETAILS WORSENING AIDS EPIDEMIC IN AFRICA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE LAURIA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ UN AIDS experts issued a grim report on the
global epidemic Tuesday, saying that no one could predict when the
plague would be contained in Africa and that half of all 15 year
olds in South Africa and Zimbabwe would die from the disease.
</P>
<P>
   Issuing the first full UN report on the worldwide AIDS crisis in
two years, Peter Piot, head of the UN Joint Program on HIV/AIDS,
warned Tuesday that the human toll ``is only going to get worse
over the next years even if today, by some miracle, all HIV
transmission would stop.''
</P>
<P>
   Attempts a few years ago to forecast when the AIDS crisis in
Africa would peak have failed miserably, Piot said, adding that no
one could predict when the plague would be contained.
</P>
<P>
   Its extent is staggering. Last year alone, 4 million sub-Saharan
Africans were infected. In 16 African countries, more than 10
percent of adults now have the virus and in seven southern Africa
nations one adult in five is living with AIDS, the study said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a whole generation which is being taken out,'' Piot
said.
</P>
<P>
   Worldwide, the virus has killed 19 million people and infected
34 million more, including 5.4 million last year alone. The
Caribbean, Eastern Europe, and Asia face catastrophe if effective
measures are not taken, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But for now Africa remains the center of the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Botswana has been the hardest hit country in the world.
Thirty-five percent of all adults are infected and two-thirds of
all 15 year olds will die from the disease, the 135-page study
said.
</P>
<P>
   Young women are especially vulnerable in Africa, where their
infection rates are three times higher than in men, the study said.
</P>
<P>
   Over 13 million African children under the age of 15 have been
orphaned since the crisis began.
</P>
<P>
   ``The epidemic is undermining basic education in many parts of
African,'' Piot said. ``It's killing off teachers well before
retirement age and households are spending too much money on health
care and have less money for school fees.''
</P>
<P>
   In Zambia there are as many teachers dying from AIDS as are
being trained, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are only at the beginning of the impact on society of
AIDS,'' Piot said in a telephone news conference from Geneva.
``There are examples of the impact on agriculture, business, the
health sector, skilled labor and professionals who are dying.''
</P>
<P>
   The disease is bankrupting businesses throughout Africa, the
report says.
</P>
<P>
   The UN report has some good news. It shows that young people are
beginning to use preventative measures. There is evidence they are
delaying their first sexual encounters, are having fewer casual
partners and are using condoms more often. Infections of girls in
Zambia have dropped by half over the past six years.
</P>
<P>
   The news is better in other parts of the developing world, Piot
said. In Brazil, in particular, ``condom use for first sexual
intercourse is now becoming the norm, as it is here in Switzerland,
where it is used 50 to 70 percent of the time,'' Piot said.
</P>
<P>
   In Cambodia, the most infected nation in Asia, a program aimed
at achieving universal use of condoms is starting to take effect,
the study said.
</P>
<P>
   The improved treatment that has led to a dramatic decrease in
AIDS deaths in Western countries is starting to appear in parts of
Latin America, but not in Africa ``where even care for the simplest
infections does not exist.''
</P>
<P>
   The report also dealt with developed countries. The United
States remains the industrial country with the highest rate of
infection, with 1.7 percent of the population carrying the AIDS
virus. Spain has the most cases in Europe, and in Britain last
year, for the first time, heterosexual intercourse became the most
common way AIDS was transmitted.
</P>
</TEXT>
