<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 18:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6422 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-MIRANDA28-C     06-27 0396
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-MIRANDA28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Don't remain silent, praise high court
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   With a touch of drama seldom seen in the U.S. Supreme Court
chambers, Chief Justice William Rehnquist took center stage with an
aplomb for which he will long be remembered. He read aloud the
familiar Miranda warnings before declaring that they are indeed
constitutionally necessary:
</P>
<P>
   You have the right to remain silent. Anything you say may be
used against you in a court of law. You have a right to the
presence of an attorney. If you cannot afford an attorney, one will
be appointed for you.
</P>
<P>
   Those warnings, he stated boldly, guarantee that no individual
should ever be forced by the state to confess to something he
didn't do. Rehnquist's words were all the more dramatic because he
had questioned the Miranda decision several times earlier in his
career. Now, Rehnquist will be remembered for placing the
conservative stamp of approval on Miranda, a 34-year-old ruling
that conservatives have long labeled as a ``liberal'' decision of
the era of Chief Justice Earl Warren.
</P>
<P>
   After Miranda was handed down, a conservative Congress tried to
legislate an end run, passing a law defining exceptions when such
warnings aren't necessary. It was that long-dormant law, recently
upheld at the appellate level, that the high court rightfully
struck down. In so doing, the majority confirmed two other key
principles: the Supreme Court, not the Congress, interprets the
Constitution, and the court's prior interpretations will not be
easily disregarded.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Antonin Scalia, who dissented (along with Justice
Clarence Thomas) will also be remembered for his courtroom drama _
rolling his eyes while the chief justice spoke, as if to make light
of a constitutionally protected right against self incrimination.
But as Yale law professor Peter Brooks said, the decision wasn't
about a conservative or liberal court; it was about limiting state
power, a principle conservatives should rush to embrace.
</P>
<P>
   The warnings have become a cultural symbol at home and abroad
that in America, individuals have guaranteed rights and that they
will be informed of those rights before giving them up. Thanks to
the chief justice for saying so _ with a flourish.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
