u a BC-SKAKEL-CHARACTERS-BOS     06-27 1213
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKAKEL-CHARACTERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SKAKEL HEARING A BIZARRE DISPLAY OF CHARACTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MACQUARRIE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   STAMFORD, Conn. _ The stakes are enormous, the subject is
murder, but the cast of characters in the drama unfolding at a
scruffy courtroom here seem better suited to the theater of the
bizarre.
</P>
<P>
   A troubled Kennedy castoff, a wise-cracking defense lawyer, a
prosecution witness who calls prison his home, and a Maine school
where students beat one another have all taken the stage.
</P>
<P>
   Now playing at Stamford Juvenile Court: The State of Connecticut
v. Michael Skakel.
</P>
<P>
   Preparations for the production, which resumes Wednesday, have
been nearly 25 years in the making, or ever since Greenwich
teenager Martha Moxley was discovered bludgeoned to death on her
leafy estate in the most-exclusive neighborhood in one of the
richest towns in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But until Skakel's indictment in January, the prospects for a
trial seemed improbable and a gruesome slaying seemed destined to
remain a frustrating, tantalizing mystery.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the ``reasonable cause'' hearing to determine whether
Skakel will stand trial is seen as a fascinating prelude to an
irresistable examination of the confluence of money, power, sex,
and murder.
</P>
<P>
   Key witnesses in this hearing seem as damaged as the defendant,
and inflammatory figures such as Mark Fuhrman and the controversial
owner of a Maine school for troubled youths are hovering around the
periphery.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of those cases where it will only get weirder and
weirder, and it's because of the characters involved,'' said
Timothy Dumas, a former Greenwich reporter whose book ``A Wealth of
Evil'' helped opened the literary floodgates on the Moxley case.
</P>
<P>
   Take Skakel as Exhibit A of the pastiche of players. At his
arraignment in March, the stocky 39-year-old nephew of Ethel
Kennedy had the chutzpah, or courage, to greet the mother of the
woman he is accused of killing with the words: ``I feel your
pain.''
</P>
<P>
   Skakel would appear to be well-acquainted with pain. His mother
died of cancer when he was 13; his father generally left his
children unsupervised, a friend testified; and Michael Skakel
reportedly wrote in a book proposal that he became a ``full-blown''
alcoholic by his early teens.
</P>
<P>
   He was also a close friend of his cousin, Michael Kennedy, who
died in 1997 in a freak skiing accident in Colorado. However,
Skakel had seriously damaged relations with the Kennedys when he
answered questions from a Massachusetts district attorney about
allegations that Michael Kennedy had sexual relations with an
underage baby sitter.
</P>
<P>
   During this hearing, scheduled to resume Wednesday, Skakel has
been generally composed. But, as has been characteristic of his
severely troubled life, Skakel also has been stunningly
unpredictable.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, he reportedly mouthed an obscenity at a former
classmate during his testimony that Skakel confessed to Moxley's
slaying. And when Skakel left the courtroom shortly afterward, his
chest heaved with effort as he broke down in tears.
</P>
<P>
   But, as he left the court at day's end, Skakel held his head
high, walked slowly, and calmly entered a waiting car as a horde of
jostling media strained to capture a hint of guilt or innocence in
his face.
</P>
<P>
   Such were the stage directions of the tanned Michael ``Mickey''
Sherman, a ferociously ambitious defense lawyer who brazenly cracks
jokes during cross-examination, counts singer Michael Bolton as his
best friend, and once walked into a hunting-violation case with
rubber duck feet protruding from his briefcase.
</P>
<P>
   Sherman, 53, told reporters that John Higgins, a key prosecution
witness, is a ``moron''; termed his testimony ``garbage''; and
tried to impugn his credibility by impersonating millionaire-maker
Regis Philbin with the sarcastic question: ``Is that your final
answer?''
</P>
<P>
   The case's reach extends far beyond Connecticut's Gold Coast.
</P>
<P>
   Higgins and Gregory Coleman, two prosecution witnesses who
attended the Elan School with Skakel, have added disturbing context
to the harrowing efforts at ``rehabilitation'' that the trio
experienced as teenagers.
</P>
<P>
   The Elan School in Poland Spring, Maine, ``was a place to hide
your kids if they bothered you,'' Higgins testified. Beatings of
fellow students with paddles and open fists were sanctioned by
school staff and owner Joseph Ricci, Coleman testified.
</P>
<P>
   Ricci, himself, is a controversial bit player in Maine life who
has twice run for governor, publicly called Governor Angus King a
``pimp'' and ``prostitute,'' and been fined for using the
public-address system at Scarborough Downs, which he owns, to curse
out a state harness-racing official in the stands.
</P>
<P>
   Even Ricci's attorney has had problems lately. The Maine lawyer
might face charges on allegations that he left his 4-month-old baby
unattended in a car for hours.
</P>
<P>
   Ricci, for his part, contends that Coleman and Higgins are lying
and interested in reward money and that he never heard Skakel
confess.
</P>
<P>
   The Skakel witnesses _ particularly Coleman, whose son's mother
died at the hand of a serial killer _ have pasts that separate them
from the general public.
</P>
<P>
   Coleman, who testified that Skakel boasted he would ``get away
with murder'' because ``I'm a Kennedy,'' is serving an eight-month
sentence in a New York state prison for criminal trespass against
his wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm an alcoholic and a drug addict. I've seen all sorts of
people,'' Coleman, 38, said from the witness stand. And, of all the
people Coleman has seen, Skakel apparently made an indelible
impression.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was one of the residents who had a problem with Michael
Skakel's attitude,'' Coleman said. ``Arrogant, cocky,
self-serving.''
</P>
<P>
   As a member of the school's ``goon'' or ``gorilla squad,''
Coleman said, his job was to keep escape-minded students like
Skakel in line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was involved in the rituals of the house,'' Coleman said,
which included attitude-adjustment unpleasantries known
euphemistically as ``haircuts'' and ``general meetings.'' These
measures were designed to break down fellow students through group
hostility _ both verbal and physical.
</P>
<P>
   Surrounding the case, as well, is the work of Fuhrman, the
bad-boy detective in the O. J. Simpson case whose book ``Murder in
Greenwich'' kept the public spotlight focused on Moxley's death.
Fuhrman fingered Michael Skakel as the likely killer, rather than
his brother Thomas, whom police had long considered the top
suspect.
</P>
<P>
   Fuhrman was directed to the case by Dominick Dunne, the novelist
who was a fixture at the Simpson trial and whose fictional account
of the Moxley slaying, ``A Season in Purgatory,'' preceded
Fuhrman's true-crime analysis.
</P>
<P>
   Dunne has been an intent observer at the Skakel hearing,
watching the proceedings from an uncomfortable seat at the side of
the tiny courtroom, taking notes on dialogue and atmosphere with a
flowing hand as he gathers material for a Vanity Fair article.
</P>
<P>
   To Dunne, who lost a child to murder, Fuhrman ``found
redemption'' through his investigative work that led to Skakel. In
a story whose ending will not be known for months _ if ever _
stranger things are bound to happen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
