<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 18:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6425 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-FRANCE-EUROPE-600&AMP;ADD     06-27 0770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRANCE-EUROPE-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHIRAC URGES FASTER INTEGRATION FOR SOME EUROPEAN UNION COUNTRIES 
</HEADLINE>
   By SUZANNE DALEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ President Jacques Chirac of France urged Germany
Tuesday to join France in spearheading a core group of European
Union countries that would move faster than others toward political
and economic union.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those countries that want to proceed further with integration,
on a voluntary basis and in specific areas, must be allowed to do
so without being held back by those who, with every right, do not
want to proceed as quickly,'' Chirac said in a speech to the German
parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Chirac cited the new European currency, the euro, as an example
of a success achieved with only 11 of the 15 European Union members
taking part.
</P>
<P>
   Chirac's speech was intended to be the high point of a two-day
visit here proving that the French-German ``motor'' was still
vigorous despite what has seemed like a cooling of the relationship
in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   But his speech was seen here as the beginning of what is likely
to be a long and heated debate about the future of the European
Union. Last month, Germany's foreign minister, Joschka Fischer,
suggested that a European federation with a directly elected
president and a parliament sharing real executive and legislative
powers was needed for the union to function effectively.
</P>
<P>
   Fischer's plan, put forward as his personal opinion, brought a
harsh reaction from the French interior minister, Jean-Pierre
Chevenement. At first, Chevenement said the proposal showed that
Germany had not yet recovered from the ``derailment'' of Nazism and
still wanted to restore a sort of Germanic Holy Roman Empire. He
later apologized for some of his remarks.
</P>
<P>
   But the fact that Fischer spoke out at all was widely applauded
in some quarters. As the European Union is poised to take in a
dozen new members in the next few years, there is a wide consensus
that its institutions must be overhauled or face paralysis. But
there has been little public discussion.
</P>
<P>
   Even at the most recent summit meeting of European leaders, last
weekend, the subject apparently was not discussed, and the minutiae
of certain tax policies and other smaller issues seemed to grab all
the attention. Chirac's speech was therefore eagerly awaited.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Chirac hinted at his position when he told reporters
that he hoped for a ``united Europe of states rather than a United
States of Europe.'' In his speech at the Reichstag Tuesday, the
first by a foreign head of state since its renovation, Chirac
maintained that theme.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our nations are the source of our identities and of our roots,
'' he said, ``the diversity of our political traditions, cultures
and languages is one of the strengths of the union. In the future,
our nations will stay the first reference point for our people.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Chirac conceded that much work needed to be done to
ensure that the union continued to function and grow. He called for
lines of authority to be clarified, for allowing majority voting
instead of unanimity on most issues, and he endorsed the weighting
of member states' votes.
</P>
<P>
   Chirac also endorsed the drafting of a European constitution.
</P>
<P>
   He emphasized, however, that he did not believe that there was
any need for a new treaty. And he said that nation states had to
remain the core of the union; envisaging their abolition was
``absurd,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Neither you nor we envisage the creation of a European
superstate that would take the place of our nation states and end
their role as actors on the international stage,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Chirac's idea of letting some union countries go ahead with
reforms that others are not inclined to or ready for is a
controversial one. Some countries fear that a two-tier system could
result, with some nations' having second-class status.
</P>
<P>
   France is to take over the rotating presidency of the European
Union this weekend, and has set an ambitious agenda, including
agreement on many of these reforms by December. Germany has
expressed support for this aim. But Germany wants a second
intergovernmental conference before 2004 over the power-sharing
issue, a move that some experts believe could lead to foot-dragging
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Chirac was warmly applauded at the Reichstag, particularly when
he evoked the five decades of friendship between France and Germany
since the end of World War II. Several members of parliament said
they welcomed his ideas because now the debate will really begin.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
