<DOCNO> NYT20000627.0221 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 18:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6433 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-SANGRIA-COX     06-27 0775
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SANGRIA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rrefreshing drink tastefully breaks all the rules
 &HT;    By Mark Fisher
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A few years back, Napa Valley winemaker R. Michael Mondavi was
searching for a dramatic way to make his point that the wine
industry needs to remove the mystery and inject some fun into its
products. In front of a symposium audience of wine trade veterans,
he uncorked a bottle of his sophisticated, pricey cabernet
sauvignon and held it alongside a large tumbler filled with ice,
then poured the regal red into the glass.
</P>
<P>
   Audience members gasped in dismay.
</P>
<P>
   What they should've done instead was run to the kitchen and cut
up some citrus fruits, and perhaps look for some club soda and
brandy, and maybe a pinch of sugar. Sangria! Let the party begin!
Hey, Mike _ dude _ how many more bottles of that cabernet did you
bring?
</P>
<P>
   Sangria is not merely a quintessential summer refresher. It also
mocks snobbish wine rules that try to tell us we should not drink
cheap wine, we shouldn't mix wine with other stuff and shouldn't
ever pour it over ice. Sangria does all of those things proudly,
unabashedly and exuberantly. It's perfect for a long holiday
weekend of potlucks, picnics and cookouts.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Castro knows a thing or two about sangria. The image of his
restaurant, El Meson in West Carrollton, is inextricably linked to
the large, frosty pitchers of red and white sangria that pour out
of his kitchens to complement the Central American, South American
and other specialties.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really seems to give a signature stamp to our restaurant,''
Castro said. ``When people come in, they order a pitcher of sangria
before they even look at a menu.''
</P>
<P>
   Making sangria is simple, and that's a good thing because Castro
and other sangria aficionados strongly recommend that sangria is at
its best made fresh, not days in advance or out of a bottle
(remember Y'ago? Shudder...). But finding much consistency among
sangria recipes is anything but simple. All call for wine and
citrus fruits, and most include some sort of brandy, but beyond
that, no two recipes are alike. Other ingredients might include
cinnamon sticks, fresh mint, plums, nectarines or starfruit.
</P>
<P>
   Castro is happy to discuss the ingredients in El Meson's
sangrias, but he won't reveal the exact proportions. It's a family
recipe, handed down from generation to generation, he says.
</P>
<P>
   He uses wine, cut-up fruit (``cut an orange in half, and squeeze
half of it into the pitcher...''), brandy (not flavored, just
regular), sugar and club soda or sparkling water. The brandy
``gives it a little kick,'' while the club soda adds some body and
effervescence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Using a dry wine is the key,'' Castro said. ``Where people
fail in making sangria is they'll start with a sweet wine, then add
all these things to it and wonder why it doesn't taste right. ...
Some people will use Lambrusco and come back and say, `It was
horrible.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to start off with a good wine,'' perhaps a Spanish
wine from Rioja or the Penedes region (Torres is a widely available
Penedes winemaker) in the $6-10 range, Castro said.
</P>
<P>
   A Dayton Daily News tasting panel didn't fully agree with the El
Meson proprietor, enthusiastically endorsing a white sangria made
from a semi-sweet Gewurtztraminer and taking a shine to a red
sangria that called for inexpensive California ``Hearty
Burgundy''-style wine that costs about half of what a Spanish wine
from Penedes typically costs.
</P>
<P>
   We sampled four recipes, two white and two red, on a Sunday
afternoon. For snacking purposes, we nibbled on cheese, pate and
crackers, chips and guacamole. The research was grueling. (The
recipes are included on page 4C). Here were some of the comments:
</P>
<P>
   _ Sparkling Fruit Wine: The consensus favorite. Zippy, zingy,
very refreshing, not too sweet. The blackberries are a surprising
and welcome addition. This is sangria for a party.
</P>
<P>
   _ White Sangria: Sweet, light and fruity, with a delayed kick.
Some tasters wanted a bit more flavor and a bit more oomph. The
fruit was great to nibble on, though.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ruby Red Sangria: Intense red-wine flavor; robust if a bit
simple. Not a sangria to guzzle. Those who already like red wine
will find it delicious; those who don't like red wine may not be as
enthusiastic. The consensus favorite among the two red sangrias.
</P>
<P>
   _ Red Sangria: The cherry brandy made this one taste a bit like
Kool-Aid to some tasters. More suitable for those who are not big
fans of red wine.
</P>
<P>
   Contact Mark Fisher at markfisher(at)coxohio.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-27-00 1814EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000627.0222 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 18:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6434 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-SANGRIA-RECIPES-COX     06-27 0722
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SANGRIA-RECIPES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Eds. RUNS WITH SANGRIA
 &HT;    Chill out with these sangria offerings
 &HT;    By Mark Fisher
 &HT;    and Pat Thomas
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The surprise hit of our informal sangria tasting was this
sparkly, fruit-filled concoction featuring Gewurztraminer wine and
champagne or sparkling wine. Look for the driest sparkling wine you
can find, but remember, it's sangria _ don't spend more than $6 or
$7 on it.
</P>
<P>
   SPARKLING FRUIT WINE
</P>
<P>
   Makes 12 servings
</P>
<P>
   1 bottle (3 cups) Gewurztraminer, chilled
</P>
<P>
   2 cups peach nectar, chilled
</P>
<P>
   2 limes cut into thin slices
</P>
<P>
   2 peaches or nectarines, halved, pitted and cut into small
wedges
</P>
<P>
   2 plums, halved, pitted and cut into small wedges
</P>
<P>
   1 cup blackberries
</P>
<P>
   1 bottle (3 cups) chilled champagne or sparkling wine
</P>
<P>
   Ice cubes (optional)
</P>
<P>
   In a large pitcher, stir together the Gewurztraminer and peach
juice. Reserve some lime slices for garnish and add the remaining
lime slices, peach or nectarine wedges, plum wedges and
blackberries to the pitcher. Chill for 1 hour.
</P>
<P>
   Just before serving, stir in the champagne or sparkling wine.
Add ice cubes, if desired. Pour into glasses, distributing some
fruit into each glass. Garnish with a slice of lime on the rim of
each glass and serve well-chilled.
</P>
<P>
   In three trips to area stores, we could not find anything
labeled ``peach nectar.'' We substituted natural peach juice
drained from a large can of peaches (do not use the kind packed in
heavy syrup), and it tasted just fine. Cut back on the peach juice
for a less-sweet version.
</P>
<P>
   _ Adapted from Summer: Recipes Inspired by Nature's Bounty by
Joanne Weir (Time-Life Books, $24.95).
</P>
<P>
   This is a classic white sangria, cool and pretty. We've been
making it for 20 years, since the recipe appeared in Dayton Daily
News food editor Ann Heller's book It's Simple!, published in 1980
by The Journal Herald. Here it is, word for word, and as Heller
originally wrote, ``Just be sure to have ingredients on hand for
seconds, because it goes down easy.''
</P>
<P>
   WHITE SANGRIA
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 to 6 servings
</P>
<P>
   1 fifth dry white wine, chilled
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup Cointreau
</P>
<P>
   1 10-ounce bottle club soda, chilled
</P>
<P>
   1 unpeeled orange, sliced
</P>
<P>
   1 unpeeled lemon, sliced
</P>
<P>
   2 limes, cut in wedges
</P>
<P>
   1 unpeeled green apple, cut in wedges
</P>
<P>
   Green grapes
</P>
<P>
   Just before serving, combine the wine and Cointreau in a large
glass pitcher. Stir in ice cubes, soda and fruit and pour.
</P>
<P>
   Use an inexpensive California jug wine. To keep the cost down,
substitute the cheaper Triple Sec for Cointreau. And feel free to
use any other fruit you think looks pretty at the market.
</P>
<P>
   This recipe, courtesy of the San Francisco Chronicle, is elegant
and simple _ no brandy, no soda, just red wine, a bit of sugar and
lots of fruit. You can substitute inexpensive Spanish or Chilean
wine (the Spanish Tinto Zamora, at $6-$7 for a one-liter bottle, is
a good bet) for the California Burgundy.
</P>
<P>
   RUBY RED SANGRIA
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 to 8 servings
</P>
<P>
   1 Valencia orange, unpeeled, cut into 1/2-inch dice
</P>
<P>
   1 Granny Smith apple, cored and cut into 1/2-inch dice
</P>
<P>
   1 lemon, unpeeled, cut into 1/2-inch dice
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   3 bottles (750 ml each) California Burgundy wine, preferably
Taylor Hearty Burgundy
</P>
<P>
   Divide the fruit and sugar between 2 pitchers. Add the wine and
stir until the sugar dissolves. Chill well before serving.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a sturdy, reliable red-wine sangria that uses the classic
ingredients of jug wine and club soda, but adds a kick with
brandy-marinated fruit. If you make a vat of this to tote to the
next potluck barbecue, you will be assured of a return invitation.
Warning: The brandy infused fruit packs a punch.
</P>
<P>
   RED SANGRIA
</P>
<P>
   Makes 12 servings
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup cherry brandy
</P>
<P>
   2 unpeeled oranges, sliced
</P>
<P>
   2 cups of any single or combination of pitted cherries, red or
green grapes or apple slices
</P>
<P>
   1 jug of inexpensive red wine (a ``mountain burgundy'' works
well)
</P>
<P>
   110-ounce bottle of club soda, chilled
</P>
<P>
   Mix brandy and fruit in medium bowl and refrigerate for 1 hour.
</P>
<P>
   Combine red wine and club soda, add fruit and brandy. Stir well
and serve chilled.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
