<DOCNO> NYT20000627.0224 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 18:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6439 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d BC-SUMMERFRUIT-SFCHRON &LR;      06-27 2984
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUMMERFRUIT-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;      
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 Glorious Fruit: Veteran pastry chef whips up a parade of
desserts  for the holiday weekend  By Janet Fletcher 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; For almost 20 years, making irresistible desserts
has been pastry chef Mary Jo Thoresen's daily challenge.
Fortunately, summer comes every year, bearing peaches, nectarines,
plums, apricots, cherries, melons and berries in fragrant
profusion.
<P>
   ``It really does make (my job) easy,'' says Thoresen, co-owner
of the 6-month-old Jojo in Oakland and a former pastry chef at Chez
Panisse. Armed with the impeccable summer fruit that she shops for
daily, Thoresen can make the sorbets, fruit tarts, fruit jellies
and compotes that she enjoys eating at the end of a meal. They're
also great finales for Fourth of July barbecues _ the seasonality
and colors are perfect _ as well as for other celebratory summer
meals.
</P>
<P>
   ``In general, with fruit desserts, the least amount of fussing
the better,'' Thoresen says. Some of her favorite summer desserts
call for cooking the fruit just barely, or not at all, to preserve
the fruit's flavor. Starting with juicy, aromatic, intensely
flavored fruit is a must for these recipes where it has nothing to
hide behind.
</P>
<P>
   Like several chefs, Thoresen can go behind the scenes at
Berkeley's Monterey Market, where she often shops, and taste the
fruit she is considering buying. But she uses her eyes and nose as
much as her palate to determine quality.
</P>
<P>
   ``I smell everything,'' she says. ``If it doesn't smell like a
peach, it's not going to taste like one.''
</P>
<P>
   Thoresen upends berry baskets to inspect for crushed or moldy
berries, and sniffs melons to find the ripest. She suggests asking
for help if you're unsure and can't sample; most produce managers
can point you to the most flavorful fruit. But, resist the impulse
to squeeze the peaches or snitch berries, she cautions; it isn't
fair to the store or other shoppers.
</P>
<P>
   At home or back in her restaurant, Thoresen arranges the fruit
on parchment-lined baking sheets, making sure that there's space
between each fruit. Berries are refrigerated uncovered. Stone
fruits are left at room temperature, stem-side down, until they
give to gentle pressure on the shoulders, then refrigerated. At
Chez Panisse, one of Thoresen's jobs was to check the fruit once a
day _ twice a day in hot weather _ so it would be used at its peak.
</P>
<P>
   When Thoresen finds exceptional fruit, she buys it in quantity.
She freezes extra berries on parchment-lined baking sheets, then
transfers them to freezer bags for later use in tarts, pies or
other cooked desserts. Even Chez Panisse freezes berries, she says,
when the pastry department gets more great fruit than it can use.
</P>
<P>
   Thoresen also frequently preserves a particularly delicious
batch of fruit by converting it into a sorbet base _ basically,
sweetened fruit puree. She freezes the base and thaws it as needed;
an ice-cream machine transforms the thawed puree into a creamy
sorbet. Home cooks can freeze peach, nectarine or strawberry puree
in batches just large enough for a dinner party, then thaw and
transfer the puree to an ice-cream machine on the afternoon of the
dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Thoresen keeps sugar to a minimum in fruit desserts unless the
fruit is less than perfect. A little extra sugar can ``help push
the flavor forward'' in slightly underripe fruit, she says. Vanilla
extract also heightens flavor. The peaches for her peach galette
always get a few drops.
</P>
<P>
   Thoresen washes strawberries in a strainer just before using,
laying them out on towels to dry. She advises against washing
fragile bush berries such as raspberries, blackberries and
olallieberries. ``Once you get bush berries wet, they really start
to decline,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   As a general rule, the fruit near the end of its season is
sweeter and tastes better than the early harvest. It's often less
expensive, too. That's why Thoresen advises against rushing to buy
the season's first peaches or plums. Wait for warm weather to
develop the flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Thoresen's knack for pastry and her considerable knowledge have
been gained entirely on the job. She had no professional kitchen
experience when a childhood friend who worked at Chez Panisse
called her _ she was working at an insurance company in Michigan _
and invited her to come help. The restaurant had just opened the
upstairs cafe and needed more hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically they were looking for someone who would work for
free,'' Thoresen says. ``I'm not a risk-taker, but this just felt
like something I shouldn't pass up.'' After about three months of
volunteer work, she was put on the payroll and stayed in the pastry
department for 12 years. She then spent three years running the
cafe at the California College of Arts and Crafts in Oakland and a
couple of years as executive pastry chef for the group that owned
Enrico's, Tavolino and U.S. Restaurant in San Francisco. Last year,
she opened Jojo with partner Curt Clingman.
</P>
<P>
   Today, she makes the pastry at Jojo in a small corner of the
restaurant's small open kitchen. The following desserts will likely
appear on her menu over the summer, nature willing.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_  &UR; Champagne Gelee with Mixed Berries. &LR;  ``It's really cold and
fresh and spectacular-looking, especially in a nice, clear glass,''
says Thoresen of this grown-up version of Jell-O.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the clean, clear taste of Champagne, seeing the golden
color of the jelly and all those deep, bright berries.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Peaches in Red Wine Raspberry Compote. &LR;  ``We used to make red
wine-raspberry sorbet at Chez Panisse, and I've always liked the
red wine and peaches thing,'' says Thoresen, referring to a
European tradition of slicing peaches into sweetened red wine. She
warms the wine just enough to dissolve the sugar, pours the warm
mixture over raspberries and lets them infuse, then presses the
berries through a strainer into the syrup.
</P>
<P>
   The peaches are peeled without blanching to preserve their
texture, then sliced and marinated in the light wine syrup. ``They
lose something when they're cooked,'' she says. ``Even just
blanched, they get that layer of translucency and they absorb the
wine differently.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Nectarines with Beaumes de Venise Sabayon. &LR;  Thoresen pairs
unpeeled nectarines with this billowy sabayon flavored with French
Muscat wine. Apricots, strawberries, bush berries or a mixture of
fruit would be equally appealing.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Melon Sorbet. &LR;  To preserve the fresh melon flavor, Thoresen
dissolves the sugar over heat in just enough melon puree to moisten
it, then stirs that puree back into the main base. She uses the
same proportion of 1 quart fruit puree to 1 cup sugar for most
summer fruit sorbets, although extra-sweet melons may need some
lime juice for balance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've monkeyed around with it, but with more or less sugar, it
doesn't freeze as nicely,'' she says. ``More sugar makes it syrupy;
less makes it icy.''
</P>
<P>
   With melon, strawberry, peach, nectarine and plum, she uses
straight sugar in her sorbets, believing that sugar syrup dilutes
the fruit flavor too much. With the more intense raspberries and
blackberries, she uses sugar syrup.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Santa Rosa Plum Galette with Vanilla Ice Cream.  &LR; ``If I was
stranded on an island with only one dessert, this would be the
one,'' Thoresen says, although in her dreams, it would arrive with
bitter almond ice cream. The dough is one she learned when Jacques
Pepin cooked for a week at Chez Panisse and used it for an apple
galette. ``We essentially abandoned all other dough recipes after
that,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Thoresen uses the same dough and method to make galettes of many
kinds _ apricot with cherry, peach, apple, pear, rhubarb. ``One
customer who comes in about once a week has two slices every
time,'' she says. ``She says she is not usually a dessert eater,
but these fruit tarts have been an epiphany.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
BEGIN SIDEBAR &QL; 
 &QL; 
TIPS FOR BUYING &AMP; STORING FRUIT
</P>
<P>
   Here are some tips from pastry chef Mary Jo Thoresen for buying
and storing fruit for those perfect fruit desserts.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Buy the ripest fruit possible.  &LR; Fruit in its prime should
smell sweet and true to its nature. If the produce manager allows,
ask to taste the fruit before you buy. Also ask the produce manager
to help you pick the best of the bin.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Inspect fruit carefully.  &LR; Be sure there are no bruised,
withered or moldy spots. But resist the temptation to squeeze the
fruit in the market. Turn baskets of berries over to be sure there
is no mold on the bottom.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Store fruit properly.  &LR; Spread out fruit on a parchment-lined
baking sheet, making sure there is space between each piece to
allow air to circulate. Stone fruit should be placed stem-end down
on the parchment and left at room temperature until it yields to
gentle pressure on the shoulders. Berries _ don't wash them, don't
cover them _ should be refrigerated.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Buy fruit later in the season.  &LR; Early-season fruit generally
isn't as full flavored as late-season fruit. It also is more
expensive.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Don't be afraid to buy fruit in quantity when it is at its &LR; 
 &UR; best.  &LR; Freeze extra berries and turn other fruit into sweetened
fruit purees _ try the proportion of 1 quart of fruit puree to 1
cup of sugar, then freeze the puree.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; CHAMPAGNE GELEE WITH MIXED BERRIES
</P>
<P>
   A light and refreshing dessert for a hot summer night.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   2 cups good-quality nonvintage Champagne
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup cold water
</P>
<P>
   1 package unflavored gelatin
</P>
<P>
   11/2 cups mixed berries: strawberries, raspberries,
boysenberries, olallieberries, blueberries
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Pour the Champagne into a 1-quart glass loaf pan. Add the sugar
and stir occasionally until the sugar dissolves.
</P>
<P>
   Pour the cold water into a small saucepan and sprinkle the
gelatin over the water slowly and evenly so it will absorb without
clumps. Let sit for 5 minutes. Warm the gelatin mixture over low
heat just until the gelatin melts. Slowly pour the dissolved
gelatin into the Champagne, stirring constantly. Cover with plastic
wrap and refrigerate overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Wash, hull and slice the strawberries, if using.
</P>
<P>
   Remove the gelee from the refrigerator and draw a knife through
it in a cross pattern just to break it up a bit. Spoon some gelee
into the bottom of a balloon wine glass or other wide-mouthed
glass, then place a layer of berries on top. Repeat until the glass
is 2/3 to 3/4 full. At this point you can cover each glass with
plastic and return it to the refrigerator until you are ready to
serve it.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 220 calories, &LR;   &LR; 2 g protein, 33 g carbohydrate,
0 &LR;   &LR; fat, 0 cholesterol, 11 mg sodium, 2 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
PEACHES IN RED WINE RASPBERRY SYRUP
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   2 cups Beaujolais
</P>
<P>
   1 cup water
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup sugar, or more to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 cup fresh raspberries + raspberries for garnish
</P>
<P>
   4 large unblemished freestone peaches
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Combine the wine, water and sugar in a nonreactive saucepan and
warm, stirring, until sugar dissolves.
</P>
<P>
   Put 1 cup raspberries in a glass or ceramic bowl and pour the
warmed wine mixture over them. Let macerate until cool, or
refrigerate overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Pass this mixture through a food mill or fine strainer to get
all the raspberry juice into the wine, leaving the seeds behind.
Taste for sweetness; add a little more sugar, if desired.
</P>
<P>
   A few hours before serving, cut the peaches in half and
carefully peel them, being careful to preserve their beautiful
shape. Slice each half thickly, yielding 4 to 5 slices per half.
Place the slices in the chilled syrup and refrigerate until just
before serving.
</P>
<P>
   To serve, divide the peaches among compote dishes and ladle
enough of the syrup into each dish to partially cover the peaches.
Garnish with a few fresh raspberries.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 8.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 150 calories, &LR;   &LR; 1 g protein, 29 g carbohydrate,
0 &LR;   &LR; fat, 0 cholesterol, 4 mg sodium, 2 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NECTARINES WITH BEAUMES DE VENISE SABAYON
</P>
<P>
   Muscat de Beaumes de Venise is a sweet wine from Southern
France. If you can't find it, substitute another sweet Muscat.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   7 egg yolks, preferably organic
</P>
<P>
   1 cup + 2 tablespoons Muscat de Beaumes de Venise
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 cup heavy cream, whipped to firm peaks
</P>
<P>
   4 ripe nectarines with unblemished skins
</P>
<P>
   Toasted sliced almonds for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Using an electric mixer, whip the egg yolks until very light and
lemon colored.
</P>
<P>
   While the yolks whip, combine the wine and sugar in a heavy
stainless-steel saucepan. Place over moderate heat. When the wine
comes to a boil, add it gradually to the yolks, whipping
constantly. Return the mixture to the pot and place over moderate
heat. Whisk furiously until the mixture begins to thicken and the
bubbles created become smaller. Do not overcook.
</P>
<P>
   Remove from heat and strain through a fine sieve into a large
stainless-steel bowl set over ice. Gently fold the sabayon to
hasten its cooling.
</P>
<P>
   When the sabayon is cool, fold in the whipped cream. Refrigerate
until ready to use. Sabayon may be made up to a day ahead.
</P>
<P>
   To serve, halve and slice the nectarines and arrange on dessert
plates. Spoon sabayon alongside the fruit and garnish with toasted
almonds.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 8.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 275 calories, &LR;   &LR; 4 g protein, 21 g carbohydrate, &LR; 
 &LR; 16 g fat (8 g saturated), 225 mg cholesterol, 21 mg sodium, 1 g &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
MELON SORBET
</P>
<P>
   Use any fragrant melons for this sorbet: cantaloupe, honeydew,
Charentais, Canary melons or whatever variety smells and tastes
best. Because melons vary greatly in size, this recipe is written
to accommodate any choice. Serve with butter cookies.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   Melons, best available
</P>
<P>
   Sugar
</P>
<P>
   Lime juice (optional)
</P>
<P>
   Melon balls or strawberries for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Halve the melons and remove the seeds. Cut the halves into 4
lengthwise slices and remove the rind. Chop into pieces that will
fit in your food processor or blender. Puree in batches until
smooth. If it is not completely smooth, pass the puree through a
strainer.
</P>
<P>
   Measure the puree. For each cup of puree, measure out 1/4 cup
sugar (use slightly less if the melon is very sweet). Place the
sugar in a stainless-steel saucepan. Add enough melon puree to
moisten the sugar. Place over moderate heat just long enough to
melt the sugar. Test with your fingers; if you feel no grains of
sugar, it has melted. Pour this mixture back into the melon puree.
Chill thoroughly.
</P>
<P>
   Taste the mixture and add a few drops of lime juice if the puree
is too sweet. Freeze according to the directions for your ice-cream
maker.
</P>
<P>
   Serve in chilled glasses or bowls. Garnish with fresh melon
balls or strawberries. It's nice to use green-fleshed melon for
garnish if your sorbet is orange, and vice versa.
</P>
<P>
   Yield depends on size of melon used. One 4-pound melon yields
about 6 cups puree.
</P>
<P>
   Due to general nature of recipe, no nutritional analysis is
included.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; SANTA ROSA PLUM GALETTE
</P>
<P>
   ``If I was stranded on an island with only one dessert, this
would be the one,'` says Thoresen. Although she pairs warm wedges
of this homey tart with bitter almond ice cream, it goes equally
well with French vanilla.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   The Dough
</P>
<P>
   1 cup all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   4 to 6 ounces cold unsalted butter (see note)
</P>
<P>
   Ice water
</P>
<P>
   The Filling
</P>
<P>
   8 to 10 firm-ripe Santa Rosa plums
</P>
<P>
   2 to 3 tablespoons flour
</P>
<P>
   5 tablespoons sugar, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   To Finish
</P>
<P>
   Melted butter for brushing
</P>
<P>
   Sugar for sprinkling on crust
</P>
<P>
   French vanilla ice cream
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;   &UR; To make the dough:  &LR; Combine the flour and salt in a mixing
bowl. Cut the butter into small pieces and add to the flour. Work
in the butter with a mixer or by hand until the pieces are the size
of tiny peas. Add ice water 1 tablespoon at a time, tossing and
mixing gently by hand until the dough is moist but not sticky. Wrap
the dough in plastic and flatten into a disk. Refrigerate at least
1 hour, but preferably overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Roll out the dough to a 12-inch-diameter circle on a floured
surface. Don't worry if it's not perfectly round; the tart is
beautiful no matter what shape it is. Transfer the dough to a
parchment-lined pizza pan or baking sheet. Cover with plastic and
refrigerate.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To finish the galette:  &LR; Preheat oven to 400 degrees. Halve and
pit the plums. Cut each into 5 or 6 slices.
</P>
<P>
   Remove the dough from the refrigerator. Leaving a 2-inch border,
sprinkle the surface of the dough with 2 to 3 tablespoons flour and
1 tablespoon of the sugar. Place the plum slices on the dough. You
can arrange them artfully or place them helter-skelter; either way,
it will look lovely.
</P>
<P>
   Carefully draw up the dough from the sides and fold it over to
form the rim. Make sure there are no cracks where juices can run
out during baking.
</P>
<P>
   Brush the rim of the dough with melted butter and sprinkle
generously with sugar. Then sprinkle the plums with the remaining 4
tablespoons sugar, or more, depending on sweetness of plums.
</P>
<P>
   Bake until well-browned and bubbly, about 40 minutes, rotating
as needed so the tart browns evenly.
</P>
<P>
   Transfer to a cooling rack so the bottom crust doesn't get
soggy. Use a pastry brush to dab the plums with plum juice to glaze
them while still hot.
</P>
<P>
   Serve the galette warm with a scoop of vanilla ice cream.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 8.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Note:  &LR; When we tested this recipe, we used 6 ounces of butter
to make the pastry. Although the finished crust was rich, flaky,
buttery and totally delicious, it was difficult to roll out and had
a tendency to tear. Using 4 ounces of butter produces dough that is
easier to work with, although it is not quite as rich.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 230 calories, &LR;   &LR; 2 g protein, 29 g carbohydrate, &LR; 
 &LR; 12 g fat (7 g saturated), 31 mg cholesterol, 136 mg sodium, 1 g &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
