<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRESCRIPTIONS28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    STUDY CITES DRUG COVERAGE GAP FOR RURAL RESIDENTS
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Elderly rural Americans are more likely to need
prescription drugs and less likely to to obtain them than urban
Medicare beneficiaries, according to a recent study.
</P>
<P>
   The study by the administration's National Economic Council and
the Democratic Policy Council found that 28 percent of rural
elderly are in poor health, compared to 26 percent in urban areas.
</P>
<P>
   But 43 percent of rural elderly lack any prescription drug
coverage for an entire year, compared to 27 percent of urban
elderly who lack coverage.
</P>
<P>
   The study also noted that rural elderly are generally poorer
than their urban counterparts, but pay substantially more for
prescription drugs.
</P>
<P>
   About 20 percent of rural elderly have incomes below the federal
poverty level, compared to 16 percent for urban elderly. But rural
elderly pay an average of $375 a year in out-of-pocket costs for
prescriptions, compared to $300 for urban beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
   The study was highlighted Tuesday by Sens. Byron Dorgan, D-N.D.,
and Max Baucus, D-Mont., at a briefing for reporters on the eve of
House consideration of a Republican plan to offer an
insurance-based prescription drug plan for Medicare beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
   Gene Sperling, the administration's chief economic adviser, used
the briefing to criticize the GOP plan and reiterate Clinton's
willingness to accept a tax cut for married couples in exchange for
a Medicare-based prescription drug benefit.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP plan is designed to encourage insurance companies to
offer a drug benefit by giving them subsidies, and by helping to
pay premiums for low-income beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
   Sperling called the GOP bill a ``false promise'' because it
would not require insurers to offer policies in rural communities
nor guarantee that policies would be affordable there if offered.
</P>
<P>
   ``It fundamentally would not fix the basic problem _ there are
gaps that exist right now in rural America,'' Sperling said.
</P>
<P>
   The study noted that rural elderly are slightly more likely to
purchase supplemental ``medigap'' policies offering prescription
drug coverage _ 13 percent for rural elderly, 11 percent for urban
_ but it noted that such policies increase in price as people get
older.
</P>
<P>
   ``Medigap is such a poor option for seniors . ... I'm surprised
there is a market at all,'' Sperling said, noting that some elderly
pay about $2,000 a year for such coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Dorgan called the GOP plan ``an illusion'' because insurance
companies have expressed reluctance to provide the type of coverage
the plan envisions, particularly in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
   Baucus said offering competing insurance plans would make it
even more difficult for seniors to understand the complexities of
the health care system and warned that insurers would seek out only
the healthiest seniors to cover.
</P>
<P>
   Dorgan predicted a prescription drug plan closer to the one
Clinton has proposed _ offering a 50 percent subsidy for drug costs
up to $2,000 and full coverage for out-of-pocket spending in excess
of $4,000 _ would likely to part of a ``big puzzle'' of legislation
to be hammered out before the election.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Lipman's e-mail address is larryl(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
