<SLUG> BC-WALKHAYES-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;      
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITOR'S NOTE: This is the latest installment of a bi-weekly series
of Food Lovers' Walks that cover neighborhoods in San Francisco and
other Bay Area cities where a casual stroll turns up culinary
treasures. &HT;     
 Food Lovers' Walks: Chic Neighborhood Rises From Ashes  By Andy Lax  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; Hayes Valley, formerly one of the city's rougher
neighborhoods, has become a chic center for fashion, style and
food.
<P>
   For years the shadow of the central freeway had separated the
east and west sides of Hayes Valley. The east was home to the new,
trendy businesses, while the west was plagued with crime. But after
the freeway was knocked down following the Loma Prieta Earthquake
in 1989, the neighborhood took off.
</P>
<P>
   At Hayes and Franklin, a large sign proclaims, ``Welcome to
Hayes Valley.'' That welcome is extended at  &UR; Nuts About You &LR; , an
anachronistic card and candy shop that offers a wide selection of
teas and coffee drinks. The store carries more than 30 varieties of
black licorice, ranging from salty Dutch to soft, chewy Australian.
</P>
<P>
   Just up the street is  &UR; Richard Hilkert, Bookseller, Ltd &LR; , which
resembles a cluttered personal library. Although the focus of the
store is on architecture and design, near the back is a slender
shelf and coffee table stacked with cookbooks. Owner Richard
Hilkert knows a gem when he sees it. Interspersed with the new,
popular titles are such culinary relics as ``Everyday Foods in War
Time,'' published in 1918. Sitting under a photograph of the late
M.F.K. Fischer (who used to visit the store) Hilkert is ready to
make suggestions or share his opinion on the development of Hayes
Valley, where he set up shop in 1981. ``We had an image problem,''
he says, likening Hayes Valley in those years to ``an early Grant
Avenue.''
</P>
<P>
   The close proximity of Hayes Valley to the opera, theater and
symphony has made securing a table for a preshow dinner something
of a challenge. During the day, however, tables are plentiful and
offer a welcome break from shopping.
</P>
<P>
   The menu at  &UR; Moishe's Pippic  &LR; would make a Jewish grandma proud
_ knishes, kishke, rugalach and deli sandwiches like the New Yorker
(corned beef, coleslaw and Russian dressing on rye), ranging from
$4.75 to $6.95. For a few dollars less you can opt for a hot dog
with a variety of condiments.
</P>
<P>
   If it's soul food you're hankering for, walk down the street to
 &UR; Powell's Place &LR;  for a real stick-to-your-ribs meal. Daily specials
range from BBQ beef ribs to smothered pork chops to award-winning
fried chicken, all served with sides like candied yams and corn
muffins oozing with butter. If that's not enough, order a wedge of
sweet potato pie, sit back, loosen your belt and marvel at what you
just ate for $10.
</P>
<P>
   The space previously occupied by Mad Magda's Russian Tea Room
now houses  &UR; Frjtz &LR; , with a menu of crepes, salads, sandwiches and
Belgian fries, with the most expensive item (a green salad with
smoked salmon, mangoes, macadamias, avocado and red onion) at
$6.75. The rear courtyard surrounded by flowering trees is a
perfect place to eat.
</P>
<P>
   If you're in a hurry,  &UR; Arlequin &LR;  offers salads, soups and
sandwiches to go. Like its parent restaurant,  &UR; Absinthe Brasserie &LR; 
 &UR; and Bar &LR; , the menu is French-inspired with offerings like a lentil
salad with roasted beets, and a sandwich of salami, grilled
asparagus and fontina cheese, all in the $5- to $6-range.
</P>
<P>
   Sandwich prices range from $5 to $6, while salads run from $2 to
$5.50. House-made ice creams and sorbets offer respite from the
summer heat.
</P>
<P>
   A quick sandwich for around $5 also can be found at  &UR; Parco &LR; 
 &UR; Coffee and Tea &LR; , this time with an Asian skew. Standards like
turkey and egg salad share the menu with udon noodles and edamame.
</P>
<P>
   For a more leisurely lunch, try Absinthe, with an appetizer of
ricotta dumplings and a Mediterranean salad of grilled prawns,
fennel, pickled salicornia and steamed potatoes in mustard
vinaigrette.
</P>
<P>
   To ensure that your own table is as stylish as those of the
restaurants, Hayes Street has home furnishing stores and galleries
that combine the latest styles from around the world with antiques
revived in contemporary settings. That global array is the focus at
 &UR; Worldware &LR;  with an inventory from 48 countries _ Parisian
flatware, Venetian plates and Romanian glassware.
</P>
<P>
   The antiques at  &UR; F Dorian &LR;  offer a stark contrast to more modern
wares. Along with items like Japanese condiment holders, you can
find cocktail, wine and martini glasses to spruce up your bar. At
 &UR; Pomp Home &LR; , colorful coffee cups from Poland share the shelf with
Thai table settings and a wide variety of elegant chopsticks.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Buu &LR;  offers another round-the-world houseware tour, focusing on
German and Japanese products such as sleek espresso cups and
thermal carafes and modern tetsubin-style teapots, fashioned after
traditional cast-iron designs. A glass case in the middle of the
store displays art deco corkscrews and Japanese Brieto knives as
though they were fine  &LR; objets d'art &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   If you want to end the day with a glass of wine, slip into the
plush back room of &UR; Hayes and Vine &LR; . Reclining on the purple velvet
cushions is an ideal way to sample the wine flights, which change
weekly. If you prefer to take your wine with you, visit
 &UR; Amphora &LR;   &UR; Wine Merchant &LR; , which carries wines from a number of
small producers.
</P>
<P>
   Once the plates from lunch have been cleared, the perfect place
mats purchased and the final drops of wine drained from your glass,
there is only one thing left to do on a Hayes Valley tour: check
out the menus displayed outside the restaurants and make your plans
for dinner.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
HAYES VALLEY
</P>
<P>
   The area code for the following businesses is (415).
</P>
<P>
   STORES
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Amphora Wine Merchant &LR; , &UR;  &LR; 384A Hayes St. (at Gough); 863-1104
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Buu &LR; , 506 Hayes St. (at Octavia); 626-1503
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ F Dorian &LR; , 388 Hayes St. (at Gough); 861-3191
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Nuts About You &LR; , 325 Hayes St. (at Franklin); 864-6887
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Pomp Home &LR; , 516 Hayes St.; 864-1830
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Richard Hilkert Bookseller, Ltd &LR; , 333 Hayes St. (at
Franklin); 863-3339
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Worldware &LR; , 336 Hayes St. (at Franklin); 487-9030
</P>
<P>
   RESTAURANTS
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; _ Absinthe Brasserie and Bar &LR; , 398 Hayes St. (at Gough); 551-1590
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Arlequin &LR;  384B Hayes St. (at Gough); 626-1211
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Frjtz &LR; , 579 Hayes St. (at Laguna); 864-7654
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Hayes and Vine &LR; , 377 Hayes St. (at Gough); 626-5301
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Moishe's Pippic &LR; , 425A Hayes St. (at Gough); 431-2440
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Parco Coffee and Tea &LR; , 350 Hayes St. (at Gough); 621-1348
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Powell's Place &LR; , 511 Hayes St. (at Octavia); 863-1404
</P>
