<HEADER>
A6443 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d BC-LEARN-PASTA-SFCHRON &LR;      06-27 0707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEARN-PASTA-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;      
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Every other week, The Chronicle features ``Learning
to Cook'' by Marion Cunningham, a cooking teacher and cookbook
author best known for her revisions of the Fannie Farmer cookbooks.
This column is intended for novices in the kitchen. &HT;     
 Learning To Cook: Let the Guests Design Their Own Pasta  By Marion Cunningham  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; Pasta has been high on the list of America's
favorite foods for quite a few years. Quick and easy to fix and
hard to ruin, pasta can be prepared and on the table 30 minutes
after you come in the front door. In other words, it's ideal for
today's faster-busier lifestyle.
<P>
   However, the one fault with many pastas is that they are
smothered in sauce. Too much sauce destroys pasta's texture and
taste. But I have a solution and, I think, a very pleasant way of
serving pasta so each diner can create his favorite style.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of the cook preparing everyone's dish of pasta, let each
diner prepare his own. Here's how to do it:
</P>
<P>
   _ Have a big pot of cooked pasta, in its cooking water, on the
stove. This can be done ahead of time. Pasta will stay hot in its
cooking water for 15 to 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   If the water cools down, the pasta may be reheated. Simply bring
the water back to a boil, then turn off the heat. Don't drain the
pasta until just before serving. The past must be hot for this
trick to work.
</P>
<P>
   _ Have bowls of chopped ingredients on the table: garlic, fresh
chives, watercress, oregano and ripe tomatoes. You'll want a
separate bowl for each ingredient. Add a bowl of freshly grated
Parmesan or, even better, a chunk of Parmesan and a cheese grater,
a cruet of fine olive oil, and salt and pepper grinders.
</P>
<P>
   _ Provide your guests with heated pasta bowls and let each
person take what he wants from the vegetables, then top with the
hot pasta. The heat from the pasta will lightly wilt the herbs and
tomatoes, warming the ingredients just enough to release their
juices, flavors and aromas.
</P>
<P>
   _ A quick toss with a fork, and the custom-made pastas are ready
to garnish with a little olive oil and freshly grated cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Serve with warm rolls or heated sourdough bread, and for
dessert, fresh fruit and cookies.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
PASTA TO PLEASE
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   6 large garlic cloves, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 bunch chives, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 bunch oregano (leaves only), chopped
</P>
<P>
   4 ripe tomatoes, cored and roughly chopped
</P>
<P>
   6 quarts water
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons salt + salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 pound linguine
</P>
<P>
   Olive oil, as needed
</P>
<P>
   1/2-pound chunk Parmesan cheese
</P>
<P>
   Pepper, to taste
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   You can chop the garlic, chives, oregano and tomatoes early the
day you plan to serve this. Put each chopped ingredient in a small
bowl. Shake a little cold water over the chives and oregano, cover
the dishes with plastic wrap and put in the refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   Combine the water and 2 tablespoons salt in a large pot. Place
over high heat and stir to dissolve the salt. When the water begins
to boil, add the linguine. Use a fork to stir and separate the
pasta strands so they don't stick together. Cook for 12 to 16
minutes (test at 12 minutes by spearing a strand or two with a fork
and tasting it. If the pasta is still firm, cook for a few minutes
longer, testing frequently).
</P>
<P>
   If you are not ready to serve the pasta, let it remain in its
cooking water. If the water cools before you can serve the pasta,
place the pot back over high heat. As soon as the water boils,
drain the pasta and serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Have the small bowls of ingredients _ the garlic, chives,
oregano, tomatoes _ on the table. Also, place a small pitcher of
olive oil, the Parmesan and a cheese grater, plus salt and pepper
mills on the table.
</P>
<P>
   Let each diner add ingredients to his pasta bowl (if possible,
warm the bowls) before forking in the hot pasta. The heat of the
pasta will wilt and warm the ingredients, and the flavors and
juices will be released into the pasta.
</P>
<P>
   Pass the cheese and its grater, and the olive oil at the table.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 500 calories, &LR;   &LR; 20 g protein, 93 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 5 g fat (2 g saturated), 8 mg cholesterol, 204 mg
sodium, 2 g &LR;   &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-27-00 1829EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000627.0229 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 18:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6444 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d BC-TASTE-CHIPS-SFCHRON &LR;      06-27 0483
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TASTE-CHIPS-SF </SLUG>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Each week, The San Francisco Chronicle's panel of
professional tasters tries a different product available in
supermarkets.  
 
 Taster's Choice : English-Style Chips Lack Clear Winner 
 
By  Robin Davis 
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
 
SAN FRANCISCO _ In honor of the Independence Day, today's panel
tasted one of the lingering remnants of the English colonization:
malt vinegar, but in the form of salt and vinegar potato chips, or
``crisps'' as they're called across the ``pond.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   The panel tasted eight brands, but there was no consensus on a
favorite. Opinions varied dramatically, which produced muddled
rankings.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Tim's Cascade &LR;  (six ounces, $1.89 at Albertson's) received the
highest ranking, but only two panelists considered it their
favorite. Three liked the thickness and crunchiness, but one
thought it was too thick. Some liked the balance of flavor, but one
thought it tasted of bad oil. Three would buy it; two would not.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Lay's &LR;  (71/2 ounces, $1.99 at Safeway) came in second. One
panelist described it as ``the best,'' and another praised the
salty-tart flavor. But others thought the chips were too pallid and
oily and lacked vinegar flavor. Two would buy it, one might buy it,
and two would not.
</P>
<P>
   Third place went to  &UR; Kettle &LR;  (five ounces, $1.69 at Whole
Foods). Two panelists liked the tartness but wanted more salt for
balance. Two others didn't care for the dark brown color, which
they thought lent a burnt flavor. Three might buy it; two would
not.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Trader Joe's &LR;  (seven ounces, $1.39 at Trader Joe's) came in
fourth. Most of the panelists thought these tasted too strongly of
vinegar. Others disliked the dark brown color and slightly burnt
taste. But one panelist said she ``loved the crunch.'' One would
buy it, two might buy it, and two would not.
</P>
<P>
   Fifth place went to  &UR; Cape Cod  &LR; (51/2 ounces, 99 cents at
Albertson's). One panelist thought the flavor was too mild, but
most of the others thought this chip tasted too strongly of
vinegar. Another also thought it was much too salty. Two panelists
commented on the oiliness; one characterized the chip as ``almost
chewy.'' Two might buy it; three would not.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Boulder &LR;  came in sixth (five ounces, $2.29 at Andronico's). Two
panelists objected to the sweet taste of these chips; others
thought they tasted stale (packages were opened minutes before the
tasting). However, some panelists liked the crunch. One would buy
it, one might buy it and three would not.
</P>
<P>
   Panelists also tasted Terra and Pringles but they ranked too
low.
</P>
<P>
   Panelists were John P. Carroll, cookbook author; Marc Halperin,
culinary director, Center for Culinary Development; Patricia Hart,
food writer and consultant; Donna Katzl, chef-owner, Cafe For All
Seasons, San Francisco; and Kirk Webber, chef-owner, Cafe Kati, San
Francisco. All products are tasted blind. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-27-00 1830EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
