<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 18:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6445 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d BC-SECRET-SALAD-SFCHRON &LR;      06-27 0515
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SECRET-SALAD-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;      
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Each week, The Chronicle offers readers the recipe
for an outstanding dish at a Bay Area restaurant, plus the chef's
secrets for making it a success. Tips and recipe follow in optional
trim. 
 
 Secrets Of Success: Mazzini's Simple Salad: Celery, cheese and 
 walnuts combine for ideal party fare  By Michael Bauer  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; You would think this simple, sensational blend was
right out of Italy: marinated mozzarella, toasted walnuts and thin
slices of celery in a simple dressing studded with hot red pepper
flakes.
<P>
   The tangy cheese, crunchy nuts, and cooling celery create a
dynamic mix of flavors that's a perfect way to kick-start a dinner
party.
</P>
<P>
   The recipe has an Italian flair, which is no surprise since it
was created by Carol Field, the author of several impressive
Italian cookbooks including ``Italy in Small Bites.''
</P>
<P>
   Field is a consultant to Mazzini in Berkeley, which was opened
in 1998 by Jim and Laura Maser. The Masers also own Picante Cocina
Mexicana and are part owners of Cafe Fanny with Alice Waters.
However, the connections go even deeper. Laura Maser is Alice
Waters' sister.
</P>
<P>
   At Mazzini, which feels like an upscale trattoria with a comfy
bar and partly open kitchen, simplicity is the key. In the end, it
does feel just like Italy.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Mazzini, 2826 Telegraph Ave. (near Stuart Street), Berkeley; &LR; 
 &LR; (510) 848-5599. Lunch and dinner daily. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SECRETS OF SUCCESS
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Heating the marinade. &LR;  Gently heating the oil used to
marinate the mozzarella releases the flavor of the garlic and red
pepper flakes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Resting at room temperature. &LR;  Allowing the salad to stand at
room temperature before serving also helps marry the flavors.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
MARINATED MOZZARELLA, WALNUT &AMP; CELERY SALAD
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 garlic cloves, minced
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon hot red pepper flakes
</P>
<P>
   20 grinds of black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 pound fresh mozzarella, cut into 1-inch cubes
</P>
<P>
   6 celery ribs, thinly sliced on the diagonal
</P>
<P>
   6 to 8 ounces walnut pieces, toasted
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Heat the olive oil in a small saute pan over low heat. Add the
garlic, red pepper flakes and black pepper. Cook for 5 minutes to
blend flavors. Let cool. Stir in the salt.
</P>
<P>
   Put the cheese in a medium-size bowl and pour the marinade over
it. Toss to coat well. Cover and refrigerate at least overnight or
up to several days. For a quicker turnaround, the mozzarella may be
marinated at room temperature for several hours.
</P>
<P>
   Remove the cheese from the marinade. Reserve the marinade.
Combine the mozzarella, celery and walnuts in a large bowl. Add
enough of the reserved marinade to make the mixture glisten. Season
with more salt and marinade, if desired.
</P>
<P>
   Let stand at room temperature for 1 hour before serving.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6 to 8.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING (including 2 tablespoons marinade): &LR;   &LR; 420
calories, &LR;   &LR; 14 g protein, 6 g carbohydrate, 38 g fat (11 g
saturated), 44 &LR;   &LR; mg cholesterol, 307 mg sodium, 2 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-27-00 1830EDT &QL; 
