<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Wednesday, June 28, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A wavering front separating sultry air over the Southeast and
southern Plains from cooler and less humid conditions farther north
will be focus for abundant clouds and clusters of thunderstorms.
Late Wednesday and Thursday, repeated heavy showers will raise the
risk of local flooding from the Tennessee Valley to parts of the
Middle Atlantic states.
</P>
<P>
   Cooler air and lower humidity will spread from the Midwest to
the interior Northeast. A mixture of clouds and sun will cover most
of these regions as a jet stream disturbance passes overhead. A
broken area of showers will dampen parts of the Great Lakes and
northern Mississippi Valley, especially in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Unseasonable heat will persist in much of the Northwest.
Moisture lingering over the Southwest will fuel afternoon
thunderstorms in the mountains.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: UNCOMMON EXTREMES
</P>
<P>
   Exposed to prevailing winds off the cool waters of the Pacific,
most locations along the immediate West Coast have an equable
climate. The large swings that often characterize daily and
interseasonal temperatures at most places across the nation are
uncommon. On Monday and Tuesday, the mercury soared to the
record-setting 80s at several coastal towns in Washington and
Oregon where temperatures are usually in the 50s and 60s for most
of the year. Wednesday, sea breezes will return to cool the
Northwest coast while a heat wave persists in the interior. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
