<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 18:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6451 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-ARMY-RECRUITING-HNS &LR;      06-27 0548
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARMY-RECRUITING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     ARMY MAKES PUSH FOR MINORITY RECRUITS, BEGINS NEW CAMPAIGN 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Army Secretary Louis Caldera announced Tuesday a
major recruiting drive to boost the service's sagging ranks by
embarking on a $380 million advertising campaign, geared in large
part toward attracting minorities.
</P>
<P>
   Caldera also said the Army was dropping the ad agency that
helped popularize the venerable ``Be All That You Can Be'' slogan.
</P>
<P>
   Caldera said the Army has hired a new advertising agency _ Leo
Burnett Worldwide Inc., based in Chicago _ to produce commercials
and advertisements for print and broadcast media.
</P>
<P>
   Burnett will work with two minority-owned partners: Cartel
Creativo, of San Antonio, which specializes in Hispanic-American
advertising, and Images USA, of Atlanta, which specializes in
marketing to African Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Presently, about 30 percent of Army recruits are African
American and 8 percent are Hispanic American. While the Army will
target both groups, Caldera said the Hispanic community is
``potentially a growing market'' for the Army.
</P>
<P>
   The Army is having difficulty getting recruits. As of June, its
recruiting rate will put the service about 3,600 enlistees shy of
its goal of 80,000 recruits for the year, Caldera said. Last year
was the worst for Army recruiting in nearly two decades _ the
service ended up short 6,300 recruits short of its target of 74,500
new soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   The other military services have faired better. The Navy last
year exceeded its recruiting goal of 52,500 enlistees by 100
recruits, while the Marine Corps met its target of 33,700 new
troops. The Air Force was 1,700 short of its goal of 33,800. All
told, the Pentagon needs about 200,000 new recruits each year for
the active duty forces.
</P>
<P>
   A Pentagon report to Congress this year said that recruiting
problems were caused by ``a robust job market, coupled with an
increased propensity among high school graduates to go on to
college.''
</P>
<P>
   The contract between the Army and Leo Burnett is structured to
give the company additional financial rewards if the recruiting
goals are met. Some of the firm's other clients include McDonalds,
Coca-Cola, Walt Disney and Nintendo.
</P>
<P>
   Young &AMP; Rubicam Inc. of New York, which has held the advertising
account since 1987, opted not to compete for the contract, Caldera
said.
</P>
<P>
   Young &AMP; Rubicam took over the Army's advertising in 1987 after
the New York agency N. W. Ayer devised the ``Be All That You Can
Be'' jingle, which has been the cornerstone of recruitment efforts
since 1981.
</P>
<P>
   Caldera has made it known that he thinks the slogan is
``dated,'' although he has resisted discarding it all together
because of its popularity. The slogan has been de-emphasized in
recent Army ads.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Wolf, Leo Burnett's chief executive officer, told the
Pentagon news conference that no decision has been made on whether
to scrap the slogan, which Advertising Age magazine has ranked 18th
among the 20th century's 100 top ad campaigns. She said that new
Army ads will be unveiled by the fall. &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Eric Rosenberg can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address eric &LR; hearstdc.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
