<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 18:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6453 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-US-CUBA-0628-COX     06-27 0907
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-CUBA-0628-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.S. CONGRESS MOVES TO EASE CUBAN EMBARGO
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Congress is poised to ease four decades of
sanctions against Cuba as early as this week, after House
Republicans reached agreement Tuesday over legislation that would
allow American farm goods to be sold to the struggling Caribbean
nation.
</P>
<P>
   The measure would clear the way, immediately upon passage, for
U.S. farmers to begin annually exporting millions of dollars worth
of food to Cuba. It has been the target of a U.S. economic embargo
since communist revolutionary Fidel Castro consolidated control
over the tiny country, with the help of his Soviet patrons, in
1960.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents of the change, led by Rep. George Nethercutt,
R-Wash., were reviewing the possibility of attaching the
implementing legislation to some broader measure expected to be
passed by both the House and Senate before lawmakers break for the
July 4 weekend.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said President Clinton
supports the main thrust of the measure. Clinton has reservations,
however, about a provision that would prevent future presidents
from restricting U.S. food or medicine exports as part of punitive
sanctions against other nations.
</P>
<P>
   That provision, Lockhart told reporters, threatens to tie
presidents' hands in the formulation of foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``In theory, we don't have a problem if aid goes directly to the
Cuban people for the benefit of the Cuban people,'' Lockhart told
reporters at the White House. ``But the President also needs
</P>
<P>
   the flexibility, as the steward of our foreign policy, to
implement the policy. And we oppose anything that restricts that.''
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart said, though, that lifting the U.S. embargo on food
exports was not a first step toward an overall easing of 40 years
of sanctions against Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Political repression and human rights violations under Castro,
said Lockhart, still call for sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The President has made clear we can provide aid, whether it be
food or medicine, to the people, but we don't believe it's time to
provide any kind of aid that helps the Cuban government,'' Lockhart
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Nethercutt provisions are formally called the Trade
Sanctions Reform and Export Enhancement portion of the $14.4
billion agriculture appropriations bill for 2001. That bill _ one
of 13 spending measures the Congress seeks to pass before the end
of the current fiscal year on Sept. 30 _ has been held up since May
amid negotiations over the proposed trade sanctions changes.
</P>
<P>
   In essence, the Nethercutt provisions terminate existing
sanctions, and prohibit future options, that restrict the export of
U.S. farm products and drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Cuba is the main country affected. The U.S. State Department
opened farm exports to Iran, Sudan and Libya _ countries the U.S.
regards as official supporters of terrorism _ as the result of an
April 1999 White House directive. U.S. exports of medicine to Cuba
have been permitted since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Experts agreed the shift in Cuba policy would be largely
symbolic and result in only a small amount of sales at first.
Extensive prohibitions against U.S.-Cuban commerce would remain in
place, as would restrictions on U.S. investment, banking and
tourism in Cuba. Imports into the United States of Cuban cigars,
for example, and other Cuban products would remain forbidden.
</P>
<P>
   And, in a concession to the powerful Cuban-American lobby, House
Republicans required that Cuba pay in hard cash _ American dollars
_ for any purchases the country makes from the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Ordinarily, such purchases are aided by a system of financing
from American banks, credits to individual countries and loans
backed by the U.S. government to help facilitate overseas trade.
</P>
<P>
   Castro opponents, such as Rep. Lincoln Diaz-Balart, R-Fla., who
was born in Cuba, said the financing restrictions would make it
difficult for Cuba to increase its purchase of U.S. goods in any
appreciable way.
</P>
<P>
   He also cast the legislation as a step toward tightening the
economic noose around Cuba . The legislation agreed to by House
Republicans would strip the White House of its authority to ease
restrictionson any American wanting to travel to Cuba. The House
measure would require instead that any such loosening first receive
Congressional approval.
</P>
<P>
   Diaz-Balart hailed that provision as a victory for Castro's
opponents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Closing off Clinton's tourism option for Castro is our most
important achievement in years,'' Diaz-Balart said in a prepared
statement. ``We are extremely pleased.''
</P>
<P>
   Cuba gave a tepid greeting to the proposal, saying it was
''symbolic'' and left most existing U.S. sanctions in place.
</P>
<P>
   Late Tuesday, Nethercutt and his Congressional colleagues were
reviewing a number of options for securing passage of the measure.
House leaders were weighing whether to keep the bill as part of the
agriculture bill or to attach it as an amendment to some other
legislative vehicle _ the supplemental budget for emergency
spending has been mentioned in the Senate _ considered certain to
pass.
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Deans' E-mail address is: bobdeans(at) coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.cubatrade.org
</P>
<P>
   http://www.canf.org/
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
