<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Wednesday, June 28 Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   CUBA-U.S. (Washington) _ House Republican leaders agreed Tuesday
to end 40 years of trade sanctions on food and medicine to Cuba, in
a compromise that carried great political significance but may be
of only symbolic economic value, at least in the short term. By
Lizette Alvarez.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT1.
</P>
<P>
   WORLDCOM-SPRINT (Undated) _ The Justice Department sought to
curb the headlong consolidation of the telecommunications industry
on Tuesday by moving to block WorldCom Inc.'s proposed $115 billion
acquisition of the Sprint Corporation. In seeking an injunction
against the deal in federal court, the Justice Department cited
concerns that the combined company would stifle competition on the
Internet and in the long-distance telephone industry. By Seth
Schiesel and David Leonhardt.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-AFRICA-AIDS (Undated) _ At least half of all 15-year-olds in
the African countries worst affected by AIDS will die of the
disease even if the rates drop substantially in the next few years,
the United Nations reported Tuesday. And if infection rates remain
high, the odds are that more than two-thirds of 15-year-olds will
die from AIDS in countries like Botswana, according to projections
from Unaids, a joint U.N.'s program in Geneva. By Lawrence K.
Altman. 1,300 words.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT2, and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   FDA-OVER-THE-COUNTER (Washington) _ Spurred by two
pharmaceutical companies that want to take their
cholesterol-lowering medications over the counter, the FDA is
considering whether many more medicines _ from antibiotics to birth
control pills _ should be made available without a doctor's
prescription. Beginning with public hearings on Wednesday and
Thursday, the drug agency will begin a re-examination of the way it
regulates over-the-counter drugs, the first such review in nearly
three decades. The last one, in 1972, created a new system for
approving over-the-counter drugs that enabled more than 600 drugs
to switch from prescription to nonprescription status. By Sheryl
Gay Stolberg. 1,500 words.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT4.
</P>
<P>
   DRUGS-LOBBY (Washington) _ With a congressional debate planned
for this week on competing Republican and Democratic Medicare drug
proposals, a look at the intense lobbying effort against the
Clinton plan. By John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-UNREST (Jakarta, Indonesia) _ A terrifying surge of
communal violence, apparently fueled by anti-government agitators
in Jakarta, is tearing apart the remote and beautiful islands of
Maluku, once known as the Spice Islands, raising fears of
destabilization throughout Indonesia's ailing archipelago. More
than 200 people have reportedly been killed in the past week in
village massacres and in street fighting in the small city of
Ambon, pushing the death toll during the last 18 months to more
than 2,500. By Seth Mydans. 1,400 words.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-MIRANDA-ASSESS (Washington) _ Timing, in constitutional
law no less than in life or love, can mean everything, and when it
came to timing, the opponents of the Miranda decision who finally
managed to push the Supreme Court into revisiting the case after 34
years turned out to have been spectacularly unlucky. A news
analysis by Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-27-00 1838EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000627.0239 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6455 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-KING-CLAPTON-NYTR &LR;      06-27 0529
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KING-CLAPTON-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLAPTON AND KING MAKE MAGIC 
</HEADLINE>
   By BILL DEAN   
 The Ledger, Lakeland, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The defining visual moment on the new album by guitarists B.B.
King and Eric Clapton is a black-and-white photograph from the
1960s. In it, the two sit with crossed legs on matching Fender
amps, presumably trading licks with the aplomb afforded masters, of
the instrument.
</P>
<P>
   King, ever the gentleman-blues herder in dark suit and ankle
boots, and Clapton _ in his mid-1960s, Cream-era Afro and jeans _
couldn't have come to the blues as more polar opposites.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, there they are: Sitting in marked contrast but playing in
shared devotion. Though it has taken 30-plus years for it to
happen, such a meeting seems to have whetted their appetites to
record an album together.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the album, ``Riding With the King,'' is a reality, its
defining musical moments could be any of eight cuts on the 12-song
disc. That's enough to make it a success by any standard. Simply
put: Plug this sucker in, turn the lights down and turn your living
room into a smokey blues club.
</P>
<P>
   The best songs here range from slow, growling blues (``Three
O'Clock Blues,'' ``When My Heart Beats Like a Hammer'') and uptempo
house-rockers (``Days of Old'') to unique hybrids (``Marry You'')
that flawlessly marry the commercially adept Clapton and the
soulful King.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marry You,'' for example, is a smoky cool synthesis of King's
reverential approach and Clapton's contemporary pop-blues sound.
The same could be said of ``Help the Poor,'' though this time the
pairing results in a vintage, 1950s sound that could have sparked a
Screamin' Jay Hawkins record.
</P>
<P>
   The strength of ``Riding With The King'' is King's unrivaled
blues vocalizing, which runs from sweet as honey to raw and
growling. The 72-year-old Riley King received his nickname _ B.B.
for ``Blues Boy'' _ while working as a Memphis disc jockey in the
1950s. On this disc, he provides five classic songs and sounds
particularly energized to be playing with one of his most devoted
disciples.
</P>
<P>
   On two seven-minute-plus, slow-blues workouts, King and Clapton
trade signature guitar licks that could have come straight from
that 1960s photograph.
</P>
<P>
   If anything threatens to mar this blues lovefest, it's Clapton's
vocals, which trade off with King's on 10 of the 12 cuts and all
too often sound thin and blown out of the water when paired with
the master.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the songs, one is a flop _ Johnny Mercer's ``Come Rain or
Come Shine,'' with strings that make it a parody. One is
unnecessary _ an acoustic retooling of Big Bill Broonzy's ``Key to
the Highway,'' which Clapton did much better on Derek and the
Dominos' ``Layla'' album.
</P>
<P>
   Two others are a tossup: a slow take on the Sam &AMP; Dave hit
``Hold On I'm Coming,'' and the lead-off, title cut, which is a
self-conscious, weak composition to start the album.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, though, ``Riding With the King'' melts Mentor
and Student together in a satisfying set that, despite the few
flaws, is worth the wait.
</P>
<P>
   (The Ledger in Lakeland, Fla., is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-27-00 1840EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000627.0240 </DOCNO>
