<DOCNO> NYT20000627.0241 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 18:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6457 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER28-COX-UPDA     06-27 1548
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER28-COX-UPDATE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: Fixes missing grafs.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Oh yeah? so's your old man
 &HT;    (A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from Cox
staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Al Gore campaign denounced new Republican hearings into 1996
Democratic fund-raising. Gore spokesman Chris Lehane charged Sen.
Arlen Specter (R-Pa.) of ``engaging in McCarthy-like tactics''and
said the Republican Party had turned Congress into a
``scandal-industrial complex''with George W. Bush as its ``CEO.''
The Bush camp, meanwhile, blamed Gore for high gasoline prices.
Said a Bush press release: ``Mr. Gore, who has been a part of the
anti-American-oil-production policies, wants voters to think
falsely of Governor Bush as a ``big oil'' man. What about Mr.
Gore's ``big oil'' interests?'' That last reference was to Gore
family stock holdings in Occidental Oil.
</P>
<P>
   COULD USE SOME TELEPROMPTER TECHNOLOGY, TOO
</P>
<P>
   Squinting into a punishing Philadelphia sun today with his back
to natural-gas pipelines and smokeless stacks of Trigen, a
cleaner-burning power plant, Al Gore delivered what his campaign
billed as a major address on energy policy: a call for $75 billion
in tax incentives for fuel-efficient technologies. His TelePrompTer
malfunctioned and was removed just before Gore took the stage to
the tune of Steve Winwood's ``Higher Love.'' Often criticized as a
halting speaker, Gore has recently begun to use the machine for
daily policy speeches in these weeks leading up to his crucial
address at the convention in mid-August.
</P>
<P>
   PERSONALITY OVER POLITICS, PART I
</P>
<P>
   Battling over personality rather than policies, GOP Rep. Merrill
Cook struggled to overcome allegations of erratic behavior and win
his party's nomination today for a third term in Utah. Cook is
considered to be one of the most vulnerable House members in the
country. Two years ago, Cook was briefly banned from state GOP
headquarters after a foul-mouthed tirade days before the November
election. Soon after winning his second term, he fired chief of
staff Janet Jenson, who accused him of delusional behavior. Cook's
primary opponent is millionaire computer company founder Derek
Smith.
</P>
<P>
   PERSONALITY OVER POLITICS, PART II
</P>
<P>
   Voters in South Carolina today were deciding between an
estranged husband and wife vying for a state legislative seat.
Domestic discord led to a bitter race between two-term Republican
state Rep. Shirley Hinson and her estranged husband, retired school
principal Jimmy Hinson. The election was steeped in the details of
their troubled marriage, including allegations of death threats and
infidelity. Mrs. Hinson said her husband was simply seeking
revenge; he said he could do a better job. The winner is assured of
the seat because there is no Democratic opposition.
</P>
<P>
   JUST PERSONAL _ NO POLITICS INVOLVED
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bill Thomas of California wrote an open letter to
constituents denying any conflict of interest after the Bakersfield
Californian reported he had an ``intensely personal'' relationship
with a health care lobbyist, Deborah Steelman. The 11-term
Republican is head of the subcommittee governing health care and a
key player in the Medicare prescription drug debate. Thomas, who is
married, didn't deny the relationship. But he said he has ``never
let my public decisions be influenced by any factor other than what
I thought was best and right on your behalf.'' Thomas won nearly 80
percent of the vote in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH PULLING AWAY IN THE BACKSTRETCH
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush is widening his lead over Al Gore in polling
among likely voters with a little more than four months to go, a
new survey suggests. Bush racked up a 52-39 percent lead in a new
CNN-USA Today-Gallup poll. The same poll (5 percentage point margin
of error) taken the week of June 5 showed Bush ahead 48-44 percent.
It was 49-42 for Bush in the same poll late last month.
</P>
<P>
   CHECKS KEEP COMING IN
</P>
<P>
   Big money continues to roll into the Republican Party. New
Federal Election Commission reports show that in May the party and
its committees raised $12.2 million in soft money. That brought the
party's fund-raising total for the 2000 election to $106 million.
The Democratic soft-money totals have not yet arrived at the FEC,
but figures that include some of May's fund-raising has the
Democratic soft-money total at $86.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   SQUEEZING DOLLARS OUT OF WOMEN
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats are pursuing more than women's votes this year;
they're after their pocketbooks as well. From informal coffees to
major fund-raising dinners with President Clinton, the party is
targeting the nation's women who have been rising to more powerful
jobs but still give less than one-quarter of political donations.
``That's certainly a way to bring in new money.'' said Janice
Griffin, a Democratic lobbyist. ``And we think it's a new pool of
money.'' But the number of female donors is growing slowly. A study
last year found that 23 percent of contributors to congressional
campaigns in 1996 were women, up slightly from 17 percent in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   FIRST THE MONEY, THEN THE REWARD
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Nancy Pelosi of California, campaigning to become majority
whip if Democrats win control of the House, said she's raised more
than $1 million to help Democratic candidates win seats this
November. That puts Pelosi well ahead of her closest rival for the
No. 3 leadership post in the House, Rep. Steny Hoyer of Maryland,
who has raised $460,000 for Democratic candidates. The Democrats
must take six more seats to regain control of the House.
</P>
<P>
   BEING BLACK AND A REPUBLICAN
</P>
<P>
   Joan Johnson, who jumped into the race for Rick Lazio's Long
Island House seat when he decided to challenge Hillary Clinton for
the Senate, is insulted when people ask why she's a Republican.
``This is a question that's never asked of a white person. It says
to me that in America, the majority race thinks that blacks are
assigned to one party, and that's an insult,'' she says. ``Because
people can get off the boat from China, Vietnam or any place and be
anything they want to be. But if I'm black in America, I'm supposed
to be a Democrat.'' So why, then? ``Because I believe that many of
the principles of the Republican Party empower our people.''
Johnson, 66, is town clerk of Islip.
</P>
<P>
   DIFFERENT KIND OF VACATION FUN
</P>
<P>
   School's out, so Chelsea Clinton made her debut on the campaign
trail with her mother, New York Senate candidate Hillary Clinton,
and said she expects to be on the stump ``on and off'' this summer.
``You'll be seeing some of me,'' said the 20-year-old Stanford
student outside New York City Hall. Her mother said it is entirely
Chelsea's choice how big a role she takes. At this point, it's
unclear whether she'll make speeches.
</P>
<P>
   CHILDREN, NOT CORPORATE WELFARE
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Nader made his first appearance as the Green Party's
presidential nominee surrounded by children at a Los Angeles
housing project, where he blasted the two major party candidates
for ignoring the growth in child poverty amid the booming economy.
Nader said greater spending on education, a higher minimum wage and
expanded child care are needed to combat child poverty. He accused
politicians of failing to use the benefits of a growing economy to
invest in programs for children, spending it instead on ``corporate
welfare'' such as corporate tax cuts and subsidies.
</P>
<P>
   WEARING THE FOREIGN POLICY HAT
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore told Iraqi opposition leaders in a Washington meeting
that Saddam Hussein stands in the way of Middle East peace and
``must be removed from power.'' Gore was showcasing his foreign
policy responsibilities as vice president to representatives of
forces trying to topple the Iraqi president _ experience his
campaign says makes him better prepared to be president than George
W. Bush. Immediately afterward, Gore shifted gears for talks and an
official dinner with Armenian President Robert Kocharyan.
</P>
<P>
   THIRD PARTIES SIGNING UP IN ILLINOIS
</P>
<P>
   Third-party presidential hopefuls Pat Buchanan and Ralph Nader
filed petitions for a spot on the Illinois ballot. Buchanan, who
hopes to win the Reform Party nod, filed his petition personally.
He said he had collected more than 67,000 signatures from
supporters; only 25,000 were needed. The Green Party filed
petitions to place consumer activist Nader on the ballot, and the
Libertarian Party filed to reserve a spot for its yet-to-be
determined nominee.
</P>
<P>
   ALL DEPENDS ON THE AUDIENCE
</P>
<P>
   To help the Democrats pick up one of the six seats they need to
regain control of the House, Denver Mayor Wellington Webb sent out
a fund-raising letter on behalf of Colorado businessman Ken Toltz,
the Democrat challenging Republican Rep. Thomas Tancredo. But
Webb's letter, which characterized Tancredo as ``a right-wing
extremist'' and said ``this race could decide the majority in
Congress,'' has been turned against Toltz. Tancredo mailed the same
letter to Republican loyalists and raised $50,000 with it.
</P>
<P>
   _ Compiled by Ernie Freda.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
