<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 19:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6464 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-SURPLUS-BOS     06-27 0415
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-SURPLUS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE UNINSURED AND THE SURPLUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   President Clinton, Vice President Al Gore, and Governor George
W. Bush are busy hatching plans to spend a projected surplus, which
may not exist in 10 years, on long-term programs that will generate
short-term political gain. In this time of prosperity, they ought
to focus instead on solutions to a limited number of major problems
and make sure there is money to pay for them.
</P>
<P>
   One ought to be the long-festering problem of providing health
insurance coverage for all Americans. More than 44 million (16.3
percent of the population) are uninsured, according to 1998 Census
Bureau figures, the latest available. Massachusetts has a 10.3
percent rate, but, unlike many other states, it makes a special
effort to place the uninsured into government health programs.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Gore nor Bush makes mention of their plight in their
campaigns, even though Bush's home state, Texas, has the highest
percentage of the uninsured, 24.5 percent. Hispanic-Americans and
young people are helping to fuel an economic boom there, yet they
are disportionately without health insurance. Gore's home state,
Tennesee, has a 13 percent rate.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, both parties are eagerly anticipating massive
budget surpluses during the next decade. The Republicans would use
them for huge tax cuts. Clinton and Gore would safeguard Social
Security and Medicare and add a significant drug benefit for the
elderly. Covering the uninsured ought to be on the agenda as well.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic Representative Pete Stark of California and
Republican Dick Armey of Texas, the House majority leader, tried to
start a bipartisan dialogue last year on the uninsured. ``We think
Congress should create a new refundable tax credit to enable all
Americans to buy decent health coverage,'' they wrote. Nothing has
come of their plan.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and the Republicans are treating the surpluses as though
they were set in stone. They may be far less than now projected,
and it would be unwise to make the financing of new or old programs
depend solely on future budget windfalls.
</P>
<P>
   When Stark and Armey wrote their article a year ago, the Census
Bureau reported that 43 million were uninsured. The latest figure _
44.3 million _ shows that prosperity is not enough by itself to
guarantee that all Americans will be protected against the
financial consequences of illness.
</P>
</TEXT>
