<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-BEIJING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEIJING BOOMERANG? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   During her visit to Beijing last week, Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright and her Chinese interlocutors said US-China
relations are finally recovering from the deep chill that followed
the inadvertent American bombing of the Chinese embassy in
Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   To foster this spirit of renewed amiability, the two sides
highlighted their exchanges about the recent groundbreaking summit
between the leaders of North and South Korea. What the officials
did not emphasize was a crucial source of discord _ China's
persisting proliferation of missile know-how and missile components
to Pakistan and Iran.
</P>
<P>
   This is a very serious matter, threatening not only relations
between the United States and China but also geopolitical stability
in a large part of the world. Paradoxically, continued Chinese
peddling of missiles to Iran and Pakistan is almost certain to have
a boomerang effect against China.
</P>
<P>
   The more India feels forced into an arms race with Pakistan in
nuclear weapons and missile delivery systems, the more pressure
there will be on China to divert great sums to modernize and
enlarge China's nuclear arsenal.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Beijing's feckless supplying of guidance systems for
Iranian missiles and China's help for the Iranians in their missile
test flights only stoke the fears of American defense specialists
who are considering the need for an antimissile defense against
ballistic missiles from rogue states.
</P>
<P>
   If one day it becomes technologically feasible, an American
missile shield would nullify completely China's small deterrent
force of some two dozen ICBMs. Also, an American missile defense
might protect Taiwan against the missiles Beijing has assembled
across the Taiwan Strait.
</P>
<P>
   Until this week, Senator Fred Thompson had been holding up the
Senate's debate on Permanent Normal Trade Relations with China by
linking it to a China Nonproliferation Act he had introduced.
Wisely, Republican leaders in the Senate delinked the two by
promising to debate Thompson's sanctions bill as ``free-standing''
legislation during the week of July 10.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson has good reason to seek a means of compelling China to
cease transferring missiles and missile technology to Iran and
Pakistan. But Thompson's effort to legislate sanctions against
Chinese companies and China's government is not the right
prescription _ at least not yet.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese leaders are much more likely to respond to arguments and
threats that affect China's national security. They do not want
Taiwan to have certain advanced weapons; they do not want India,
their regional rival, to gain a qualitative edge over China in
military technology; and they certainly do not want to see Japan
become a military giant again, much less a nuclear power.
</P>
<P>
   US officials have been journeying to Beijing to make the US case
against China's export of missile technology and components to Iran
and Pakistan. For now, this is the proper way to dissuade the
Chinese rulers. They should be made to understand that the security
they are threatening is their own.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
