<HEADLINE>
ATT TO OPEN NETWORKS TO ONLINE PROVIDERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A planned November ballot question that would require
``open access'' to high-speed cable Internet access in
Massachusetts _ and was expected to trigger a $10 million
advertising blitz _ was dropped Tuesday after open access
proponents reached a compromise with AT&AMP;T, the measure's leading
foe.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T earlier this month took over MediaOne Group to become the
state's dominant provider of high-speed residential Internet access
over cable systems. Tuesday it agreed in principle to open up its
Bay State networks to providers such as America OnLine and
Shore.Net by mid-2002.
</P>
<P>
   In return, a group of open access proponents headed by Boston
Net venture capitalist J. Christopher Grace agreed to abandon their
proposed November initiative petition mandating open access across
the state, which had been expected to ignite an epic summerlong
TV-ad war between AOL, AT&AMP;T, and other deep-pocketed Net giants.
</P>
<P>
   What impact the deal has on Massachusetts Internet users will
depend on whether AT&AMP;T can actually come to terms with Net
providers such as Shore.Net, HarvardNet, AOL and MindSpring to let
those service providers resell access to their portals over
$40-a-month high-speed cable connections now affiliated with
RoadRunner.
</P>
<P>
   If the deal works out as promised, the more than 130,000 Bay
State homeowners who now have RoadRunner service from AT&AMP;T/MediaOne
would be able to sign up with another ISP _ and get access to its
array of services _ while still enjoying the 1.5-megabit-per-second
download speeds of cable modems.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel very gratified that these agreements have been worked
out,'' said Grace. ``Our mission has been accomplished without the
need to proceed all the way to the ballot box.''
</P>
<P>
   Open access advocates had portrayed their cause as an effort to
ensure AT&AMP;T does not use its control over high-speed access to
dominate what users can see on the World Wide Web, and to allow
ISPs the same access to the publicly sanctioned cable monopolies as
phone companies get to Bell Atlantic lines.
</P>
<P>
   But AT&AMP;T and some sympathetic state and federal regulators said
a government mandate for open access, rather than freely negotiated
deals in the marketplace, would chill investment in cable franchise
upgrades.
</P>
<P>
   Grace's past business dealings with AOL, to which he sold a
small company in 1996, and ownership of AOL stock had exposed him
to charges he was carrying water in the ballot fight for AOL.
</P>
<P>
   Facing potentially huge defections among its 20 million mostly
dial-up customers to cable and DSL services up to 50 times faster,
AOL had been clamoring for access to cable modem services. But then
in January AOL announced a $175 billion bid to take over Time
Warner _ meaning it would own those cable modem services and have
to share with rivals.
</P>
<P>
   AOL never formally endorsed the Massachusetts ballot question,
but was widely seen in the industry as losing its heart for the
battle once it made its move on Time Warner.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, what looked last year like an accelerating bandwagon
for ``open access'' laws and local ordinances has stalled,
especially after last week's ruling by a federal appeals court
overturning a Portland, Oregon, bylaw requiring open access.
</P>
<P>
   Four Massachusetts communities that tried this spring to impose
open access requirements as a condition of transferring MediaOne
franchises to AT&AMP;T were rebuffed by the state Department of
Telecommunications and Energy, which said they had no legal
authority to do so.
</P>
<P>
   And Federal Communications Commission chairman William E.
Kennard has repeatedly expressed skepticism over whether open
access laws are necessary or would do more good than harm.
</P>
<P>
   Under a memorandum of agreement signed by Grace and AT&AMP;T general
counsel James W. Cicconi, AT&AMP;T agreed to begin technical trials of
open access in one to three Bay State communities by November 2001
and implement an ISP choice policy in its franchises with Net
service by July 2002.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T has already agreed to conduct similar trials in Colorado to
investigate how easily it can configure its systems to allow access
to 5 or 10 or more internet service providers.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T spokesman Richard D. Jenkinson said officials there
concluded that rather than pouring millions of dollars into TV and
newspaper ads opposing the ballot question, ``These dollars would
be better spent upgrading and facilitating the rollout of broadband
services. We wanted to get this off the table and move forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Jenkinson said the agreement ``is very clear that we will not
discriminate'' against non-AT&AMP;T-affiliated Net service providers in
offering them wholesale access through AT&AMP;T cable systems to
subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   But he acknowledged that ``the devil's in the details no matter
which way you go'' in terms of AT&AMP;T actually reaching deals with
ISPs to use its broadband Net systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is that consumers will have this choice a lot
faster than if we had had the government telling us what to do,''
Jenkinson said _ or if open access had been mandated by a ballot
question that surely would have faced years of litigation.
</P>
<P>
   US Representative Edward J. Markey, a Massaachusetts Democrat
and ranking member on the House telecommunications subcommittee,
praised Grace and his coalition for achieving ``the best voluntary
open access agreement to date anywhere in the country.'' Markey
called open access key to opening ``all telecommunications markets
to competition, innovation and customer choice.''
</P>
<P>
   When its pending acquisition of Cablevision franchises in
Boston, Brookline, Framingham and 36 other suburbs is complete,
AT&AMP;T will control cable franchises in 212 of the 351 Bay State
cities and towns, although currently fewer than two-thirds of those
offer high-speed Net access. AT&AMP;T has 155,000 RoadRunner customers
in Massachusetts and southern New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   Grace's group also reached an open access commitment with Time
Warner, which swapped most of its Massachusetts franchises to
MediaOne two years ago but still has franchises in 5 Massachusetts
communities that are slated to get RoadRunner service.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T had had an agreement in principle to take over Charter
Communications' 53 Worcester-area franchises as part of a swap of
US franchises. But some industry analysts think that deal is dead
because AT&AMP;T did not want to give up MediaOne franchises in Los
Angeles to get the Worcester County franchises.
</P>
<P>
   The only other major cable provider in the state is Adelphia
Communications, which has franchises in 36 cities and towns, four
of which it has outfitted so far for cable modem service with about
a dozen more coming on line this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
