<HEADLINE>
EVEN TEXTBOOKS DON'T GET GENOME DESCRIPTION RIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. CHANDLER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Confused about the exact meaning behind this week's reports on
the human genome project? Don't bother consulting a biology
textbook to clear things up. It won't help.
</P>
<P>
   According to a new study of 10 widely-used current high school
biology textbooks, not a single one of them is acceptable overall.
``At their best, the textbooks are a collection of missed
opportunities,'' according to Jo Ellen Roseman, director of the
study, which was carried out for the nonprofit American Association
for the Advancement of Science, publishers of the journal Science.
</P>
<P>
   The textbooks are so bad, the study's authors say, that the best
advice they can offer to schools faced with a decision about buying
new biology books is this: Don't.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our advice to school districts if they're about to buy biology
books is not to,'' said George Nelson, director of the AAAS's
``Project 2061'' aimed at fostering better science and math
education.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead, spend the money on professional development,'' Nelson
said, to help teachers supplement existing textbooks and add
activities that will help students understand fundamental concepts
such as natural selection and how a cell works. The books uniformly
fail to do this, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They present the content in a disconnected way,'' Nelson said,
and they ``camouflage the important ideas with details and
trivia.'' It is as though, he said, a textbook on cars explained
details of carburetors, fuel injectors and universal joints,
instead of stressing that a car can provide transportation because
power is produced by the engine and conveyed to the wheels through
a transmission.
</P>
<P>
   The 24 educators and biologists who conducted the study spent an
average of 400 hours on each book, evaluating how they handled four
different areas of biology _ cell structure and function, matter
and energy transformations, the molecular basis of heredity, and
natural selection and evolution.
</P>
<P>
   Their evaluations were condensed into four sets of 19 scores for
each book, and a detailed analysis will be published in a few
months.
</P>
<P>
   In general, the books focus too much on the details and pay
scant attention to the overall concepts that unify these details
into an understandable picture, Roseman said.
</P>
<P>
   Not one of the books got any scores of ``excellent'' for any of
the 19 areas there were graded on. And of the 190 total grades
assigned to the 10 books, an overwhelming 167 _ or 88 percent _
were the lowest grade, ``poor'', equivalent to an F.
</P>
<P>
   ``They do pretty uniformly flunk,'' Roseman said in an
interview.
</P>
<P>
   One of the glaring failings of the books, Roseman and Nelson
said, was that they fail to consider recent research into students'
ideas and misconceptions about biology, or about how learning works
most effectively.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, in discussing evolution, one book says that a
species ``has become adapted,'' without making clear that
adaptation has nothing to do with individual animals adapting to
their environments; rather, the species adapts over many
generations. Biologists have understood that for well over a
century, but students commonly misunderstand the concept.
</P>
<P>
   The report suggests that the failings of the books have nothing
to do with the much-publicized political wrangling in some states
over the teaching of evolution. In fact, of the four areas of
biology that were analyzed, it was ``evolution and natural
selection'' in which the textbooks actually achieved their best
scores.
</P>
<P>
   Andrea Bowden, chief of the office for science and math programs
for Baltimore public schools, said the new study points out
``significant flaws'' in the available textbooks, despite years of
widespread attempts to promote better science education. ``I'm
frustrated that 15 years after the call for reform, we still don't
have acceptable materials,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Alberts, president of the National Academy of Sciences and
a cell biologist, commented that in today's society, ``every
citizen needs a basic understanding of the major concepts of
biology.'' But the new study shows, its authors say, that biology
textbooks are not conveying even enough information to allow
students to understand the key concepts in a newspaper story on
biology.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of things like the human genome project, we don't
think the books do a good job of enabling students to read the
newspaper, to participate in our society, or to understand how to
make good decisions,'' Roseman of the AAAS said.
</P>
<P>
   She said that good textbook writing involves an intensive
process of testing and rewriting to find out what really works,
such as trying out different analogies to see which ones help
clarify student understanding. ``Textbook companies really don't do
that kind of research and development,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think we can be very helpful to publishers,'' she added,
``if they'll listen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
