<HEADER>
A6474 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-WORLDCOM27-COX     06-27 0865
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLDCOM27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Justice Department files suit to halt Sprint-WorldCom deal
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - A reinvigorated U.S. Justice Department has taken up
Sherman's antitrust march to the scene of a mega-merger again, this
time moving to thwart WorldCom's $129 billion purchase of Sprint.
</P>
<P>
   Flush from its legal victory over Microsoft, the department
filed suit Tuesday to block the WorldCom merger, arguing that the
massive deal combining the two companies would undercut efforts to
spur competition, especially in long-distance service and transport
of Internet data.
</P>
<P>
   ``If WorldCom were allowed to acquire Sprint, large and small
businesses and millions of individual consumers would have to pay
higher prices and accept lower service quality and less
innovation,'' said Assistant Attorney General Joel Klein.
</P>
<P>
   The department is wielding powers provided by the 1890 Sherman
Act, named for Ohio Sen. John Sherman, younger brother of the Civil
War general who burned Atlanta. The law is meant to protect
consumers and companies alike by blocking corporate domination of
markets and is not often invoked, said Benjamin Wolff, a specialist
in telecommunications law and a partner in the Portland, Ore.,
office of Davis Wright Tremaine. ``Justice is looking at reduced
competition in the market place, the effect of the merger. The
number of times you see them actually raise an issue is
infinitesimal.''
</P>
<P>
   Within moments of the Justice Department suit, WorldCom withdrew
its merger filing with the European Commission. A revised filing is
possible, but the commission's antitrust chief said that ``only
under exceptional circumstances'' could the companies modify plans
to make the merger acceptable.
</P>
<P>
   Most analysts expect the apparent collapse of the deal to mean
that someone _ presumably more acceptable to regulators _ will make
a bid for Sprint. The failed deal also raises the specter of a
big-ticket bid for WorldCom. Among ambitious outsiders with cash to
spare are Deutsche Telekom, France Telecom and Japan's NTT.
</P>
<P>
   But many eyes also turned to BellSouth, the Atlanta-based
regional telecom company that in October offered $100 billion in an
eleventh-hour effort to buy Sprint. While falling short, the bid
proved BellSouth's willingness to gamble and its desire to grow.
</P>
<P>
   But that was then. BellSouth looks a bit different now.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the company has announced creation of a tracking
stock that will value its surging Latin American investments.
BellSouth also announced plans to deliver digital television via
satellite throughout the Southeast. Most tellingly, BellSouth's
nascent joint venture with SBC Communications will create a nearly
national wireless company, virtually eliminating the need to bid
for Sprint's wireless unit.
</P>
<P>
   Still, BellSouth could be interested in some other pieces of
Sprint.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Sprint's long-distance business would give
BellSouth _ or any company _ instant muscle in the national market.
But BellSouth is not expected to have federal approval to offer
long-distance for months, so such a deal could be stymied by
regulators.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint is also a sizeable carrier of high-speed data, the
Internet ``backbone'' that is considered crucial to competing
globally _ and something that BellSouth lacks. Sprint too has
national presence as a provider of telecom services, while
BellSouth is a regional player.
</P>
<P>
   After all, the industry has been moving toward a world of much
bigger companies that offer a range of services to clients around
the world. The regulatory roadblock to WorldCom-Sprint probably
does not mean an end to the trend _ only a signal that regulators
will accept only so much concentration of market power in any
market.
</P>
<P>
   Together, WorldCom _ which previously swallowed MCI _ and Sprint
have about 27 percent of the residential long-distance market. That
is half of AT&AMP;T's share, but it would mean the market would have
just two big competitors. And WorldCom and Sprint have greater than
30 percent of international long-distance.
</P>
<P>
   The picture is in some ways more imposing in Internet backbone
service, where WorldCom leads with 37 percent of the market and
Sprint is second with 16 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In the four years since passage of the Telecommunications Act,
federal regulators have permitted a string of ever-larger mergers.
No large combination had been rejected, although a few _ like an
AT&AMP;T-SBC Communications marriage _ have been headed off when they
were still under discussion. Yet regulators have grown increasingly
willing to set conditions and restrictions, but had shown no sign
of just where the line of unacceptability lay _ until Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We finally got an answer to the question, how big is too
big?'' said Jeffrey Kagan, Atlanta-based telecom analyst. ``Long
term there will be several global telecom supercarriers who are
going to be measured in the hundreds of billions of dollars. Short
term however is apparently a different story.''
</P>
<P>
   And short-term, the name Sherman can still bring some heat to
bear..
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
