<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBA-FOOD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE OK'S US TRADE IN FOOD, MEDICINES, WITH CUBA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN DONNELLY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House Republican leaders agreed Tuesday to allow
the sale of US-grown food and medicines to Cuba, signalling the
first substantial relaxing of 38-year-old sanctions against the
island nation's Communist government.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement, which was shepherded by House Speaker J. Dennis
Hastert, an Illinois Republican, represents a small opening in
practical terms, but it represented a historic moment in opening
US-Cuban business again.
</P>
<P>
   But the deal, which is set to be slipped into a conference
committee proceeding that would not allow for any debate or vote,
also included a setback for those favoring open relations: It
blocks future tourism to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   It would essentially make law the status quo: allowing cultural
and education exchanges, as well as restricted family-to-family
visits, but no other travel. That takes the matter out of the hands
of the Clinton administration, which had been widely expected to
loosen restrictions on tourism with Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   The impetus for opening up food and medicine sales didn't arise
so much from political factors, although the Elian Gonzalez custody
case appears over the last several months to have greatly hurt the
pro-sanctions Cuban-American lobby. Rather, the push came from
economic interests, namely farmers who want another market to sell
their wheat, soy, rice and powdered milk.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a historic development because it is the result of the
changing views toward Cuba, particularly of Midwestern
conservatives, who are now more interested in selling grain than in
beating Castro over the head,'' said Alfred Padula, professor
emeritus at the University of South Maine, who began analyzing
Cuban issues for the State Department in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   The compromise, which included imput from two Cuban-American
representatives from South Florida as well as farm-state lawmakers,
calls for cash-only sales and won't allow for US government credits
or American bank loans to subsidize the agriculture sales, which is
a common practice.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Ileana Ross-Lehtinen, a Miami Republican, said
the legislation would ``make it as difficult as possible'' for such
sales to take place.
</P>
<P>
   The provision also included a strong anti-sanctions message,
prohibiting the president from using food and medicine in future
embargoes without Congress' approval.
</P>
<P>
   The deal also could open sales to other countries with which the
US has imposed embargoes, including Iran, Libya, North Korea and
Sudan. One exemption would be Iraq, because the United Nations has
imposed the sanctions, with the US as the strongest backer.
</P>
<P>
   The use of food and medicine in sanctions has come under
increasing attack from US allies and United Nations leaders,
including Secretary-General Kofi Annan, who has called repeatedly
this year for the use of ``smart sanctions'' rather than
broad-based ones. Such sanctions would target specific leaders,
rather than nations, imposing travel restrictions and freezing bank
accounts, for instance.
</P>
<P>
   The White House reacted cautiously to the agreement, which is
now expected to be attached to the conference committee
deliberations on either the military-construction bill or the
agricultural appropriations legislation. Once those measures come
out of committee, the entire package will be considered in a
yes-or-no vote, with no amendments allowed. It then would go to the
president.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not opposed to allowing things like food and medicine
to go to Cuba as long as it is for the benefit for the people, not
the benefit of the Castro government,'' said White House spokesman
Joe Lockhart.
</P>
<P>
   But Lockhart said if a provision is included to restrict the
president's ability to manage embargoes, ``those are concerns we
will have to try to work out.''
</P>
<P>
   Cuba favors lifting the food and medicine embargo because it
would help improve nutrition to many people and make available many
new prescription drugs, which are currently unavailable because
they are made by US companies.
</P>
<P>
   The food-and-medicine portion of the deal would generate only an
estimated $25 million to $45 million in the first year, said John
S. Kavulich II, president of the US-Cuba Trade and Economic
Council, which provides information on Cuba for American
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Cuba spent an estimated $750 million on bulk food
commodities, but almost all of that was done with foreign
government credit. Kavulich said that even though the US sales at
first may seem small, he projects the sale to grow over the years.
In any case, he said, the sales would have a major impact to some
farmers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a family farmer in Iowa, now sells to Cuba, say, $800,000 a
year and that is an 8 percent increase of annual revenues to the
farmer, which nets a $1,000 extra in profit, well, that might be
the difference between sending a child to state college and a local
college,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Padula said that the symbolism of the deal is most
important, especially if the US Supreme Court releases Elian
Gonzalez to the custody of his father and the two return to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   ``That means there could really be a double blow for the exiles,
and to a certain extent that means the diminishing of the power of
the Cuban exile community,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the exiles' power still was apparent with the freezing of
the travel restrictions, said Representative James P. McGovern, a
Massachusetts Democrat who was angry after learning that the
measure may not come up for House debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``While we are making some progress in food and medicine, it
seems to be going in the wrong direction when it comes to relaxing
travel restrictions,'' McGovern said. ``We need to be encouraging
more exchanges. More people-to-people dialogue is a good thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The irony here is that these (Cuban-American representatives)
have the nerve to get up and talk on the floor and about democracy
and we don't have the right to practice democracy on the House
floor by allowing a vote on this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
