<HEADER>
A6502 &Cx1f; tab-z
u l BC-BREAKTHROUGH-BRIEFS-D     06-27 1551
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BREAKTHROUGH-BRIEFS-DISCOVER-$ADV27-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BREAKTHROUGH BRIEFS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use Tue., June 27, 2000, or anytime thereafter.) 
 &HT;    
 ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by DISCOVER NEWS SERVICE clients.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 (Color art is available.) 
 By THE EDITORS OF DISCOVER MAGAZINE 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    
 UNDER T.REX'S TOES  
 &HT;    Stephen Hasiotis was clambering around near Lake Powell, Utah,
in 1996 when he spied striking white structures jutting out of the
purple clay.
 &HT;    In the years since, he and his colleague Robert Wellner have
uncovered 100 more of the formations and identified them as
fossilized burrows dug by some of our mammalian ancestors 150
million years ago.
 &HT;    Back then, mammals had to compete against much larger dinosaurs.
 &HT;    ``If you were on the ground, you could be eaten or squashed. The
trees probably weren't very safe either. So, our best bet was
probably in the ground,'' says Hasiotis, a biogeologist at Indiana
State University.
 &HT;    The burrows have complex forms similar to today's mammal
hideouts. Each has several openings, spiral ramps, and three or
four chambers that may have served as living room, pantry, birthing
room and bathroom.
 &HT;    Based on the burrows' shapes, Hasiotis suspects the animals
looked like prairie dogs but with longer tails and extended snouts
for hunting insects.
 &HT;    So far, the researchers haven't found any fossils of the mammals
themselves, but Hasiotis plans to hunt for them this summer. To
uncover bones or teeth, he'll use hydrochloric acid to dissolve the
calcium carbonate deposits that have filled the once-empty burrows.
 &HT;    Soon, he predicts, we'll be looking at the actual remains of the
timid diggers who eventually took over from the dinosaurs.
 &HT;    
 HOMO INTOXICATUS  
 &HT;    Getting sloshed on a Saturday night may seem a uniquely human
tradition, but not if physiologist Robert Dudley is to be believed.
 &HT;    Dudley, a biologist at the University of Texas at Austin, claims
the taste for alcohol runs deep in animal evolution and is shared
with our close primate relatives: chimps, gorillas, and orangutans,
which have a known weakness for overripe fruit.
 &HT;    Ripe or rotting rain-forest fruits contain alcohol
concentrations as high as 5 percent, Dudley says. The odor attracts
birds, bats, butterflies and elephants.
 &HT;    Chimps and gorillas _ from which our hominid ancestors split
between 5 million and 7 million years ago _ will roam for miles
through tangled trees and creepers in search of fermenting fruit.
Sugar and alcohol provide primates with precious calories, and the
fruit in turn spreads its seeds far and wide.
 &HT;    Genes for alcohol addiction may have persisted in the human line
for the same reason that those for fat accumulation have, according
to Dudley's theory.
 &HT;    Modest amounts of alcohol are known to decrease heart disease
risk and may lengthen life. Animals predisposed to a little nip
would be better survivors, more likely to pass their DNA to the
next generation. That genetic heritage may no longer be helpful now
that alcohol, like high-fat food, is available on every corner.
 &HT;    ``Alcoholism is not just another addiction,'' Dudley says. ``It
is a by-product of our ancestral nutritional physiology. Once we
better understand the mechanism, we'll have a better shot at a
cure.
 &HT;    -----
 FRESH-SQUEEZED  
 &HT;    The blandness of canned orange juice is an unfortunate side
effect of the high heat and chemical preservatives needed to
prevent food poisoning. Now microbiologist Martin Cole of Food
Science Australia and others have developed a way to kill germs
without killing flavor.
 &HT;    Cole applies pressures of up to 100,000 pounds per square inch
to wipe out disease-causing bacteria _ including E. coli,
Salmonella, and Listeria _ in fruits, juices, fish and other foods.
 &HT;    The smothering pressure ruptures the outer membranes of bacteria
and breaks apart crucial proteins. The process also unravels animal
proteins, making raw meat look pale and cooked.
 &HT;    ``But people are looking at using the process to extend the
shelf life of meats that are already cooked and sliced,'' Cole
says.
 &HT;    Because of their rigid walls, plant cells suffer little damage
under intense pressure. Fruits maintain their texture, shape, and
taste, and juices taste fresh-squeezed after compression.
 &HT;    Flow International, a manufacturer in Kent, Wash., is readying a
commercial version of the technology. Pressure-preserved strawberry
jam, now on sale in Japan, proves the gastronomic benefits.
 &HT;    ``When you eat the jam, it is just like eating fresh
strawberries,'' Cole says.
 &HT;    -----
 ROBOT WATCH: THE BUCKSHOT BRIGADE  
 &HT;    A group of robots now roaming the University of Minnesota campus
can come to the rescue nearly as fast as a speeding bullet.
 &HT;    Richard Voyles and his colleagues at the university devised two
miniature rovers that can be shot en masse out of grenade
launchers.
 &HT;    One of them, called a Scout, is a wheeled cylinder that rolls
along like a soda can but has a spring-loaded ``foot'' to fling it
up stairs or over small obstacles.
 &HT;    A second rover, the TerminatorBot, has arms that unfold so they
can drag the rover along or pick up objects _ ideal for exploring
loose wreckage for survivors after an earthquake, Voyles believes.
 &HT;    -----
 POET OF THE PILL  
 &HT;    Working at Syntex, a private company in Mexico City, chemist
Carl Djerassi created norethindrone, a synthetic form of the
hormone progesterone, in 1951.
 &HT;    Soon after, norethindrone became an active ingredient in an oral
contraceptive _ famously known as ``the pill.''
 &HT;    In the 1980s, after years of biochemical research at Stanford
University, Djerassi switched gears and began writing about
scientific issues in fictional settings. He has published five
novels, including ``Cantor's Dilemma'' and ``Menachem's Seed.''
 &HT;    The first installment in a planned trilogy of plays, ``An
Immaculate Misconception,'' was broadcast on May 6 and 7 on the BBC
World Service and will soon be available on video from GlobalStage.
 &HT;    Josie Glausiusz talked to Djerassi about his dual life.
 &HT;     Q:  Why do you write fiction?
 &HT;     A:  I am trying to smuggle important scientific ideas out to
the general public. The vast majority of legislators haven't got
the foggiest idea about science or technology, and yet many of the
decisions they make are based on these things.
 &HT;     Q:  What are the key ideas in ``An Immaculate Misconception''?
 &HT;     A:  It deals with the ethical dilemmas we face as sex and
reproduction become increasingly separate. With in vitro
fertilization you can analyze the embryo and screen for all kinds
of diseases _ such as Down's syndrome or sickle-cell anemia _
before you put it back into the woman. But this is an expensive
procedure, and the only people who can afford it are affluent
people in affluent countries. We're creating another gulf between
the haves and the have-nots.
 &HT;     Q:  What will be the impact of a split between sex and
reproduction?
 &HT;     A:  It will change the power relationship between men and
women. Sexual reproduction was overwhelmingly in favor of the man,
who ran the show. But this reduces a man to what he really is: the
donor of a single sperm. That sperm a woman can now get without
sexual intercourse.
 &HT;     Q:  How will contraception change in the new century?
 &HT;     A:  I think that practically nothing will happen. I am
extremely dubious that we will have a male pill in the next 10 or
20 years, because the pharmaceutical industry is not interested. A
contraceptive vaccine is of least interest because there is no
money in it. The better such a vaccine is, the fewer times you use
it.
 &HT;     Q:  What about mifepristone (RU-486), the abortion pill now
available in some European countries?
 &HT;     A:  Scientifically it's one of the few, perhaps the only, real
major advances beyond the pill. Right now, nearly 50 million women
in the world have an abortion each year, and I think it behooves us
to give women various choices as to how to have an abortion, just
as we give people choices on what kind of contraception to use.
 &HT;     Q:  What is your greatest love?
 &HT;     A:  Curiosity. That's probably what keeps me young and active,
always wanting to get into new areas. That's why I want to become a
playwright. There aren't too many people who start writing plays at
age 75.
 &HT;    ----
 c.2000 Discover magazine 
