<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPED-ZIMBABWE-RIEFF-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZIMBABWE'S COURAGE, FAR FROM CONQUERED 
</HEADLINE>
   (New York Times OpEd for Wednesday, June 28, and thereafter.)  
 ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's OPED news service. For more information
about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of the OPED news service _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.) 
 By DAVID RIEFF    
 c.2000 New York Times    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even though the democratic forces lost _ and may have had the
election stolen from them, at that _ the result of this week's
voting in Zimbabwe represents some of the best news from
sub-Saharan Africa in recent memory. What it has shown, as the
Movement for Democratic Change came close to winning a
parliamentary majority in the face of violence and intimidation, is
the strength of the popular desire for a fair and decent
government.
</P>
<P>
   This was an election that President Robert Mugabe and his ruling
party were committed to winning at any cost. Some opposition party
candidates were killed. The so-called war veterans _ men who were
little more than bands of thugs loyal to Mugabe _ were deployed to
make a show of force and to help curry the votes of impoverished
farmers through an attempted expropriation of white-owned land.
Moreover, U.N. officials were prevented from acting as monitors.
European Union observers have refused to certify the vote as free
and fair, blaming the government and its security forces for the
widespread irregularities.
</P>
<P>
   Even under these circumstances, the opposition party won handily
in the cities and made powerful inroads in rural areas, which have
been Mugabe's base of support since independence. Much of the
credit for this moral victory goes to the civil society groups that
trained 24,000 local poll watchers.
</P>
<P>
   This election in Zimbabwe is a salutary reminder that the
situation in sub-Saharan Africa, though desperate, is not hopeless.
All across the continent, the desire for reform continues to grow.
</P>
<P>
   Zimbabwe itself has exemplified both the promise and tragedy of
post-colonial Africa. Mugabe has been gradually transformed from an
idealistic guerrilla commander fighting for an end to British rule
into a tyrant.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the deep wounds from colonialism, both Zimbabweans
and foreigners have been reluctant to face the truth about him, and
he has been a master at turning attention away from his own
destructive conduct by harking back to the evils of colonial days.
As the president of the opposition party, Morgan Tsvangirai, has
put it, Mugabe specialized in the ``unethical use of legitimacy of
the past in order to rationalize the plundering of the present.''
</P>
<P>
   By now, Mugabe's indifference to the welfare of his citizens has
been matched only by his willingness to shed blood or provoke
political crises.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after he came to power, he used troops trained by North
Korea to unleash a campaign of terror in the province of
Matabeleland that some human rights activists have described as
genocidal. More recently, he has embroiled his country in a war in
the Democratic Republic of the Congo that benefits business and
mining interests linked to him and his close associates. At home,
he has presided over the ruination of the economy and the
evisceration of basic services from public health to road
maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the fact that Mugabe has managed, however
tenuously, to hold onto power means that the next few months will
be dangerous. Before the election, the opposition activists worried
that, as one put it, ``we will need a landslide victory to handle
Mugabe and his thugs.''
</P>
<P>
   They didn't get one, or, at least, if they did, voting
irregularities make the question of how people really voted all but
moot. What is clear is that the people of Zimbabwe have done their
part to try to rid themselves of Mugabe. Now the question is
whether the rest of the world will help them or abandon them to a
dictatorial government's determination to stay entrenched, as we
did the Chinese students in Tiananmen Square.
</P>
<P>
   (David Rieff is the author of ``Slaughterhouse: Bosnia and the
Failure of the West.'')
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
