<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Turner Broadcasting to spend $1.2 billion on construction
 &HT;    By Tony Wilbert
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - Turner Broadcasting System left little doubt Tuesday
that it is in Atlanta to stay.
</P>
<P>
   The news-and-entertainment subsidiary of Time Warner said it
will spend $1.2 billion on construction projects downtown and in
Midtown during the next five years to accommodate a projected 63
percent increase in local employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``The project is gigantic for little old Turner Broadcasting,''
said Terence McGuirk, chairman and chief executive. ``When you come
to CNN Center in the future, you're going to be very impressed.''
</P>
<P>
   The plans call for adding a 25-story, 600,000-square-foot office
tower atop the parking garage at Techwood Drive and Marietta Street
and a 24-story hotel tower that will adjoin the existing Omni Hotel
at CNN Center. The 593-room hotel expansion will be developed in
partnership with Omni Hotels.
</P>
<P>
   The $140 million office building, Turner Tower, ``will
accommodate employees temporarily relocated from CNN Center to
Centennial Tower,'' according to TBS.
</P>
<P>
   At its Techwood Campus at Techwood and 10th Street, Turner said
it will construct two buildings in addition to the pair it has
under construction. Buildings C and D will house additional
facilities for future networks and business units of Turner
Entertainment Group. Building D will be completed in early 2003 at
a cost of $45 million. At a cost of $95 million, Building C will be
finished in early 2005.
</P>
<P>
   ``Could you get a better hat trick than that?'' said Ken
Bleakly, president of COPA Inc., a nonprofit group that promotes
development around Centennial Olympic Park. ``That looks like a
tremendous project and really validates all we've been trying to do
around the park.''
</P>
<P>
   The project will be one of the largest capital investments ever
in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fun to build things, and it's fun to grow,'' McGuirk
said. ``We're going to be here for a very long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Turner has 6,000 employees in metro Atlanta and expects to add
3,800 during the next five years. The projects announced Tuesday
should erase any concern that Time Warner's merger with America
Online would jeopardize TBS jobs in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``Turner has not forgotten where it got its start _ right here
in Atlanta,'' Gov. Roy Barnes said.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Mayor Bill Campbell applauded Time Warner Vice Chairman
Ted Turner: ``His commitment to downtown has been unwavering.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
