<P>
   (NYT12) GAITHERSBURG, Md. -- June 27, 2000 -- GENOME-INVESTORS
-- The sequencing of the human genome is often described as a
triumph akin to landing on the moon. For investors, that might not
be the most comforting analogy. Three decades after Apollo 11, no
one has yet made a profit going to the moon. A similar business
challenge faces Celera Genomics. At the Celera Genomics
Corporation's command center, from left, Tony White, head of the
Perkin Elmer Corporation, Celera's sister company; Hamilton Smith,
who won the Nobel Prize for his work on restriction enzymes and
currently is a scientist at Celera; and J. Craig Venter, chief
executive officer of Celera. The group was watching human genome
data being assembled in early January. (Marty Katz/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) KAMPALA, Uganda -- June 27, 2000 -- UGANDA-VOTE-3 --
Once there were few places in Africa as grim as Uganda, now there
are few as hopeful. And the man who claims the credit, President
Yoweri Museveni, is campaigning hard for voters to reward him in
perhaps an odd way: He wants them to admit that Uganda is still
backward and not yet ready to open up to political parties. A
security guard with Museveni's entourage, urges supporters of a
multi-party system, and who oppose Museveni, to keep quiet during a
rally supporting Museveni on Sunday. Several young protesters were
arrested. (Tyler Hicks/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) KAMPALA, Uganda -- June 27, 2000 -- UGANDA-VOTE-2 --
Once there were few places in Africa as grim as Uganda, now there
are few as hopeful. And the man who claims the credit, President
Yoweri Museveni, is campaigning hard for voters to reward him in
perhaps an odd way: He wants them to admit that Uganda is still
backward and not yet ready to open up to political parties.
Museveni speaks to supporters from the back of his Land Rover on
