<P>
   (NYT7) BALTIMORE -- June 27, 2000 -- BALTIMORE-SANDWICH -- Pit
beef is Baltimore's version of barbecue: beef grilled crusty on the
outside, rare and juicy inside and heaped high on a sandwich.
Several things make it distinctive in the realm of American
barbecue. Brian Shafer with a pit beef sandwich at his Big Fat
Daddy restaurant. (Marty Katz/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) UNDATED -- June 27, 2000 -- BASIL -- Some are discovering
that basil is a culinary adventure. Cinnamon basil chocolate mousse
with cinnamon basil garnish and cinnamon sticks. (Susan B.
Markisz/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) WASHINGTON -- June 27, 2000 -- CLINTON-RUBIN-PORTRAIT --
President Clinton, former Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin and
Treasury Secretary Larry Summers, right, took turns ribbing each
other during the unveiling ceremony of Rubin's official portait in
the halls of the Treasury department, Tuesday. Each treasury
secretary has a painted portrait hung in the halls of the
department to honor his tenure. (Stephen Crowley/The New York
Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- June 27, 2000 -- FDA-OVER-THE-COUNTER -- The
Food and Drug Administration is taking a broad look at whether some
medicines, from antibiotics to birth control pills, should be made
available without a doctor's prescription. Beginning with public
hearings Wednesday and Thursday, the agency will launch a
reexamination of the way it regulates over-the-counter drugs, the
first such policy review in nearly three decades. (Marilynn K.
Yee/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) SOUTHHAMPTON, N.Y. -- June 27, 2000 --
SCI-COASTAL-EROSION -- In a report to Congress, the Federal
Emergency Management Agency says a quarter of more of houses within
500 feet of the Atlantic and Gulf coasts will be lost to erosion in
the next 60 years, putting intolerable strain on the nation's flood
insurance program. (Lois Raimondo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW TAFARA, Zimbabwe -- June 27, 2000 -- SCI-AFRICA-AIDS
-- An estimated 19 million people have been killed and a further 34
million infected by the AIDS virus, which is wreaking social and
economic devastation in the most stricken African nations, with the
worst still to come, according to a report issued Tuesday by the
U.N. Program on HIV/AIDS. Esther Daiton holds her niece Manyara,
who is HIV-positive, in October, 1999. Daiton also takes care of
eight other children who have lost their parents to AIDS. (Dominic
Chavez/Boston Globe Photo) LITE
</P>
