<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 19:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6526 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-MOVIES-PATRIOT28-COX     06-27 1001
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-PATRIOT28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Patriot' long on jingoism, and just plain long
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mel Gibson single-handedly wins the American Revolution, among
other historical revisions in ``The Patriot.'' As cliched as it is
long (very), the latest from Roland Emmerich takes the jingoistic
spirit of his ``Independence Day'' and amps it to a feverish,
flag-waving pitch. The movie is beautiful on the eye and crafted
with great care. But it relies on oversimplification, cheap
sentiment and a villain so two-dimensionally nasty even Satan
wouldn't claim him.
</P>
<P>
   It will be an enormous hit.
</P>
<P>
   Think of ``Braveheart'' in knee breeches (though that was the
far better movie). As in that Oscar-winner, Gibson is battling evil
Brits. He can't be very welcome in London these days.
</P>
<P>
   He plays Benjamin Martin, loosely based on the historic ``Swamp
Fox,'' Francis Marion (only with Marion's alleged ickier traits,
like racism and rape, expunged). Single father of seven, he's a
stern South Carolina farmer who initially resists his neighbors'
talk of raising arms against the British. It's 1776.
</P>
<P>
   A hero of the French and Indian War, Martin changes his pacifist
ideals after his home is engulfed one night in a skirmish between
Brits and Yanks. The scene fills the dusky farmyard with flashes of
gunpowder and scurrying figures. There's a spooky, mesmerizing
grandeur to this scene, and it's one of the very few in the movie
that ends too soon.
</P>
<P>
   Converting his house into a makeshift clinic for the wounded,
Martin the next day encounters the movie's uber-cad, British Col.
Tavington (Jason Isaacs), whose ruthless sneer is matched only by
his butchery of Americans _ soldiers, women, even children.
</P>
<P>
   Watch out, Tav, 'cause the Revolution just got personal.
</P>
<P>
   A virtual one-man Brit-buster, Martin begins a campaign against
the enemy, starting with one of the movie's most riveting, morally
complex scenes. He arms two of his young sons, barely taller than
the rifles he hands them, and ambushes a company of British
soldiers in the woods. The carnage thrills one boy, traumatizes the
other; he shrinks from this newly revealed, bloodthirsty version of
his father.
</P>
<P>
   The script flirts with, then abandons, its most interesting
idea: that Martin's skills as a killer and strategist threaten to
lose him the love of the family he's trying to save. His soul might
be lost as well. His youngest girl refuses even to speak to him
(but in typical fashion, that conflict is resolved in a teary burst
of sentiment).
</P>
<P>
   For the record, Gibson is very good, a convincing man of action
with a dangerous streak. But his role gets more cartoonish as the
movie continues to stack the deck. Bad things happen to Martin's
family and friends, in order to justify his vengeance, and to make
us feel safe about rooting for his vigilante bloodlust. ``The
Patriot'' is less ``Braveheart'' than a revenge fantasy in costume.
Think of Charles Bronson with a ponytail, and you're on the right
track.
</P>
<P>
   The screenplay saddles Martin with a dark secret, letting Gibson
deliver a somber monologue much like Robert Shaw's USS Indianapolis
speech from ``Jaws.'' We also watch him handle some slapstick with
a chair, a bit meant to make Martin goofy and endearing. And
there's not one but two tepid romances to appeal to couples
watching the flick on a date night.
</P>
<P>
   Like the movie he's in, Martin's character is cobbled together
from time-tested, profitable bits and pieces. You can almost hear
the committee of Screenwriting 101 script docs, shouting
instructions to writer Robert Rodat, who stuffs the film with
elements designed to please as many demographics as possible.
</P>
<P>
   This is a reconstructed South where the black figures are noble
freedmen or slaves who so love the little blond children they tend,
they don't seem to have much interest in liberty. The exception is
a token slave fighting with the militia to secure his freedom; he
exists mainly to widen audience appeal. The women characters exist
only to hector the men into action, or, in the case of Joely
Richardson as Gibson's comely sister-in-law, to gaze at the star
longingly with her blond hair back-lit like honey.
</P>
<P>
   The battle scenes are undeniably rousing. Emmerich enjoys the
tight confusion of conflict, the point-of-view shots as a
cannonball rips off a solder's head. And there's a courteously
tense battle of wills between Martin and Gen. Cornwallis (Tom
Wilkinson, in a slow-burn performance) as the soldier negotiates
the release of his captured fellow militiamen. The scene ends with
a zinger of a punchline, though it makes you wonder how this
rag-tag band of fighters has the resources and time to manufacture
the objects used in their prank. (Don't worry, I won't give it
away.)
</P>
<P>
   Breathtaking scenes
</P>
<P>
   What makes the script's tired manipulations even more
frustrating is the great care that's been brought to the movie's
visuals. Cinematographer Caleb Deschanel (``Anna and the King'')
shoots many scenes at magic hour, the golden times of sunset and
sunrise; some of his images, such as the endless lines of soldiers
advancing on each other in the sunlight, are breathtaking. (The
film was shot on location, in South Carolina.) Another asset is
Australian actor Heath Ledger as Martin's headstrong son Gabriel,
blending thoughtfulness and idealism (and covering the teen
audience demo).
</P>
<P>
   In the end, ``The Patriot'' packages history like a luxe
consumer product, reducing the Revolution to mano-a-mano melodrama
less complicated than a Batman movie. Did I mention that it will be
a hit?
</P>
<P>
   ``The Patriot''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C +
</P>
<P>
   Starring Mel Gibson, Heath Ledger, Jason Isaacs. Rated R for
strong war violence.2 hours, 44 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A rousing but depressingly heavy-handed retelling
of the American Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
