<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 19:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6527 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-SURVIVOR-SEQUEL28-COX     06-27 0730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SURVIVOR-SEQUEL28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Survivor' mania: Some sequels we would like to see
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Your lawn is on life support, it costs a month's mortgage to
fill up your gas tank, the dot.coms (and your portfolio) are
self-destructing.
</P>
<P>
   But how will you remember the summer of 2000?
</P>
<P>
   As the summer of ``Survivor.'' The CBS
pseudo-sort-of-not-really-reality show has a hammerlock on the
nation's limited attention span as we tune in in ever-increasing
millions at 8 p.m. Wednesdays to see the scrappy little teams of
castaways whack yet another of their own (last week's edition was
the No. 1 show in the nation).
</P>
<P>
   Consider it ``The Sopranos'' without the ziti.
</P>
<P>
   Age discrimination, roasted rat, hanky-panky, sour grapes,
tribal councils, silly challenges _ what a bizarre recipe for a
runaway hit. Whatever happened to the tried-and-true old formulas
for breakout television, like giving Regis Philbin a trivia show?
</P>
<P>
   CBS already is planning ``Survivor II: The Australian Outback''
for early next year. But what's unclear is whether ``Survivor'' is
a show that can roll on endlessly with minor tweaking, much like
``60 Minutes,'' or whether it's one of those fads we briefly
embrace and then toss aside, like the hula hoop, Rubik's Cube or
Sen. John McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe what CBS needs to do is up the ante for the next round of
``Survivor.'' Maybe it needs to take unsolicited advice from TV
columnists. Or maybe not. Here are some suggestions anyway.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Celebrity Survivor'' _ The best week ever of ``Who Wants to
Be a Millionaire'' was when the celebrities played during the May
sweeps period. ``Celebrity Survivor'' would have some logistical
problems, but the money it would make would overcome all obstacles.
Guarantee the celebs $10 mill apiece for charity; CBS would still
make money like Minute Maid makes orange juice.
</P>
<P>
   The trick, of course, is to bypass B-list celebs (sorry, Craig
Kilborn) and go big. And controversial. And sexy. And
confrontational. And egotistical. And a mix. Like this:
</P>
<P>
   The guys: Pete Rose, Ted Turner, Eminem, Slobodan Milosevic,
Johnnie Cochran, Jerry Seinfeld, Tom Green and Snoop Dogg.
</P>
<P>
   The gals: Marisleysis Gonzalez, Ellen DeGeneres, Christiane
Amanpour, Kathie Lee Gifford, Jennifer Lopez, Julia Child, Sarah
Michelle Gellar and Rosie O'Donnell.
</P>
<P>
   Now that's entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Presidential Survivor'' _ Every four years, more people
repeat the cliche ``Is this any way to pick a president?'' than
actually vote. ``Presidential Survivor'' at least gives us a new
approach.
</P>
<P>
   In the 2000 version, Al Gore, George W. Bush and Pat Buchanan
are all sent to a deserted island. Tempting as it may be to just
leave them there and not even bother making a TV show, each
candidate is instead given a team to whip into shape. Can Gore's
group make a bonfire? Can Bush's bunch catch a fish? Can Buchanan
stop sputtering when he finds out his team is all recent
immigrants?
</P>
<P>
   When it's over, America votes via 900 number. It's up to CBS to
work through the inevitable nitpickers who say it's
unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Suburban Survivor'' _ Sixteen hardy souls are set up in
homes in Alpharetta. Each is given three young children, two of
whom have swimming lessons at different pools at exactly the same
time; a baby sitter who's as trustworthy as a Bill Clinton
deposition; a major, road-hoggin' sport-utility vehicle with
one-sixteenth of a tank of gas left; and a magnificent, lush lawn
that must be maintained with a single garden hose amid neighbors on
the lookout for watering violators.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Nicotine Survivor'' _ You want to see folks acting like
eight wet cats in a burlap sack? You want to see people put forth
absurd effort to win a single challenge? This version would be the
same ``Survivor'' as the current one, except everyone on the island
is a pack-a-day smoker marooned without cigarettes. All of the
challenges are for cartons of Marlboros and Zippo lighters.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``NRA Survivor'' _ ``Survivor'' originally was a Swedish TV
show called ``Expedition Robinson.'' If we're going to take these
shows and Americanize them, let's do it right. Arm all the
participants to the teeth. ``Survivor'' would stay No. 1 _ with a
bullet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Survivor''
</P>
<P>
   8 p.m. CBS (1515)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
