<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6528 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-SALARMY-FACTS28-COX     06-27 0646
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALARMY-FACTS28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Little known facts about the army
 &HT;    By Derrick Henry
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  The red shield: Dates from 1896 and serves as the trademark
for the army's social services. It represents ``a fight on the
spiritual battlefield which must last as long as life itself.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Salvation Army flag is the only flag, other than the U.S.
flag, to have flown on the moon.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The red kettle: The Christmas kettle debuted in San Francisco
in 1891 in the guise of a crab pot. A depression had thrown many
out of work, including hundreds of seamen and longshoremen. The
campaign proved so successful that by 1900 it was imitated
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Uniforms: The uniform identifies its wearer as a member
(soldier) of the army who is available and approachable by anyone
in need. The original uniforms were modeled on the British army.
The uniform consists of navy blue serge woolen pants or skirt, a
navy blue serge tunic, white cotton shirt or blouse, and tie (there
are several choices). Made exclusively by and for Salvation Army
soldiers, they cost about $300. They are worn to work and to
official or service functions. In warmer countries, the uniforms
tend to be lighter, including tan, beige and white. In the early
days, women wore high collars and bonnets and skirts down to the
ankles; now skirts are several inches below the knees. Bonnets went
out in the 1970s, replaced by caps (left).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Strike up the band: Around 1884 a young Salvation Army woman
conducting open-air services in Salisbury, England, had to cope
with tomatoes and rocks thrown by unappreciative onlookers. Taking
pity, a non-Salvationist man and his three sons brought their brass
instruments, surrounded her and accompanied her as she sang hymns.
Soon the idea spread to army street meetings elsewhere. Bands would
perform religious songs set to secular tunes, among them ``Marching
to Georgia.'' The army now has the largest catalog of sacred
instrumental music in the world, with 10,000 titles of brass band
music, many symphonic in scope. There are about 2,500 Salvation
Army brass bands worldwide. Some are very good, but, says Lt. Col.
Tom Jones of national headquarters in Alexandria, Va.,``In all
candor, we also have some of the worst.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Rose Bowl Parade: Since the 1920s, a Salvation Army brass band
from Southern California has marched in the Rose Bowl Parade. It
always performs ``Onward, Christian Soldiers.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Famous composers: John Philip Sousa wrote ``The Salvation Army
March'' in 1930. British composer Ralph Vaughan Williams wrote
``Prelude on Three Welsh Hymn Tunes'' for the army in 1955.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Recordings: Bands have made hundreds of recordings. After July
10, call 1-800-786-7372 for a catalog. Or visit the army store,
1424 N.E. Expressway, 9 a.m.-4 p.m. weekdays. Or go to
www.musosmedia.com/au/salvatio.htm.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Stars: Philip Smith (left), the New York Philharmonic's
principal trumpeter, also performs every Sunday in his army church
in Montclair, N.J.; Charles Baker, principal trombonist of the New
Jersey Symphony; and Mark Ridenour, assistant principal trumpeter
of the Chicago Symphony.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Dallas Cowboys running back Emmitt Smith (right) learned to
play at an army community center in Florida. Basketball star ``Dr.
J'' Julius Erving learned basketball at a Salvation Army camp.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Movies: Actors Clark Gable, Cary Grant, Frank Sinatra, Marlon
Brando, Mae West and Joan Crawford have appeared in movies with
army characters. The best known is the 1955 film version of the
Broadway musical ``Guys and Dolls.'' Brando has a romance with a
female officer (Jean Simmons), modeled on a real New York crusader,
Rheba Crawford, the ``Angel of Broadway.''
</P>
<P>
   _Derrick Henry writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
