<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Tuesday, 06/27/00. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   The following photos have moved with the latest installment of
the New York Times series on race relations slugged: RACE-PAPER:
</P>
<P>
   (NYT110) AKRON, Ohio -- June 27, 2000 -- RACE-PAPER-1 -- Carl
Chancellor, left, and Bob Dyer were part of a team of reporters for
The Akron Beacon Journal that had explored the racial attitudes of
this city of 215,000 people. Their series earned the paper
journalism's big award, the Pulitzer Prize. (Stephen Crowley/The
New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT111) AKRON, Ohio -- June 27, 2000 -- RACE-PAPER-2 -- John L.
Dotson Jr., and Charles L. Knight, current and early publishers of
the Akron Beacon Journal. Dotson is part of a pioneering generation
of black journalists who covered the Detroit race riots in the
1960's and worked for The Philadelphia Inquirer and Newsweek.
(Stephen Crowley/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT112) AKRON, Ohio -- June 27, 2000 -- RACE-PAPER-3 -- Carl
Chancellor and Bob Dyer were part of a team of reporters for The
Akron Beacon Journal that had explored the racial attitudes of this
city of 215,000 people. Their series earned the paper journalism's
big award, the Pulitzer Prize. The paper's Pulitzer, surrounded by
series front pages, occupies a place of honor in the news room.
(Stephen Crowley/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT113) AKRON, Ohio -- June 27, 2000 -- RACE-PAPER-4 -- Bob
Dyer, with his family outside his home, and Carl Chancellor, were
part of a team of reporters for The Akron Beacon Journal that had
explored the racial attitudes of this city of 215,000 people. Their
series earned the paper journalism's big award, the Pulitzer Prize.
Dyer with his wife Becky and daughters Kimmie, 10, left, and
Carrie, 12. (Stephen Crowley/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT114) AKRON, Ohio -- June 27, 2000 -- RACE-PAPER-5 -- Carl
Chancellor, with his family outside his home, and Bob Dyer, were
part of a team of reporters for The Akron Beacon Journal that had
explored the racial attitudes of this city of 215,000 people. Their
series earned the paper journalism's big award, the Pulitzer Prize.
Chancellor with his wife Sheila Williams son son Tyler, 7. (Stephen
Crowley/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT115) AKRON, Ohio -- June 27, 2000 -- RACE-PAPER-6 -- Seven
years after The Beacon Journal race series appeared, Akron still
feels its effects. The mainly black Arlington Church of God and the
mainly white Chapel, which began uniting services after the series,
recently gathered to participate in a foot-washing ritual. (Stephen
Crowley/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT116) AKRON, Ohio -- June 27, 2000 -- RACE-PAPER-7 -- Bob
Dyer, top, Carl Chancellor, were part of a team of reporters for
The Akron Beacon Journal that had explored the racial attitudes of
this city of 215,000 people. Their series earned the paper
journalism's big award, the Pulitzer Prize. (Stephen Crowley/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   Our report tonight also includes:
</P>
<P>
