<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6530 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-SALVATION-ARMY28-COX     06-27 0922
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALVATION-ARMY28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Salvation Army ventures into new territory with conference and
parade in Atlanta
 &HT;    By Gayle White and Derrick Henry
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Some 136 years after a certain Northern army left
Atlanta charred, the city is under invasion again. But the only
blaze this bunch hopes to ignite is the flame of the Holy Spirit.
</P>
<P>
   About the time Gen. William Tecumseh Sherman and his troops were
marching through Georgia, Gen. William Booth and his wife,
Catherine, were marshaling forces to attack sin in London. Booth's
brigades became the Salvation Army, now 1 million strong in 107
countries.
</P>
<P>
   Today more than 20,000 soldiers and officers of Booth's army are
gathering at the Georgia World Congress Center and Philips Arena
for the first International Congress of the Salvation Army to be
held outside headquarters in Great Britain. On Friday, they will
march down Peachtree Street beginning at noon.
</P>
<P>
   Already military sounds are wafting through the city. In the CNN
Center at noon on Tuesday, the Hendon Band of London, one of the
army's premier brass bands, played to a lunchtime crowd. Other army
bands will play there at noon today and Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they're excellent, just excellent,'' said Earl Blauer
of Hays, Kan., who is in town with his wife, Roann, attending a
computer convention for educators. Blauer knows his music. He's a
former high school band director.
</P>
<P>
   The performers make their way through the old hymn ``This Is My
Story'' with a bit of a Latin beat, raise the rafters with the
``William Tell Overture'' and move into another number named for
some people a bit less famous than William Tell _ outside Salvation
Army circles, that is. It's called ``The Gowans and Larson
Overture, Too,'' and it's made up of some of the greatest hits of
the 10 musicals written by the army's present leader, Gen. John
Gowans, and his second-in-command, John Larson.
</P>
<P>
   Gowans writes the lyrics, Larson the tunes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's Sullivan. I'm definitely Gilbert,'' said Gowans. Gowans
was at the Marriott Marquis Tuesday afternoon, giving a speech on
behalf of the metro Atlanta army. His talk focused on the women of
the army, and he quoted founder Booth, who reportedly said, ``Some
of my best men are women.''
</P>
<P>
   The congress in Atlanta gives army personnel a chance to
celebrate and to refocus on the basics of their faith, Gowans said.
And just pulling off the meeting is a ``miracle,'' he said. The
army in wealthier parts of the world helps subsidize or completely
fund the travel of people from impoverished areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good investment,'' said the general. ``If the
Salvationists go home with a clearer idea of what they're doing and
a better idea of how to do it, the whole world benefits.''
</P>
<P>
   Out on the streets of Atlanta and in its hotel lobbies, the
world was already mingling. Female Indian Salvationists in navy
saris with white blouses underneath stand at the top of an
escalator at the Marriott Marquis near other Salvationist women
with the Western version of the uniform _ navy skirts a few inches
below the knee with their white blouses.
</P>
<P>
   In the same hotel, Lt. Col. Amos Makina, 52, is stylishly
dressed in full regalia in his country's tan Army outfit. Makina,
who is heading a contingent of 150 Salvationists from Zimbabwe,
grew up in a non-Christian family, but went to live with his uncle,
a soldier of the Salvation Army, when he was 12. He was drawn in by
the music, he says. Now, he's executive chaplain of 50 Territorial
Songsters from Africa who will perform at various congress events.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone in uniform is a Salvationist.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is this Salvation Army?'' asks Lt. Yozo Matkovich,
walking downtown with half a dozen white-uniformed men. Matkovich
is a Croatian naval officer who has been in Athens, Ga., for
training.
</P>
<P>
   Out in Centennial Olympic Park, Gary Noland from Warren, Mich.,
kept an eye on some friends' children playing in the fountain and
served as an unofficial, informal greeting committee for other
Salvationists headed through the park on their way to register for
the congress.
</P>
<P>
   In shorts and a purple T-shirt with sleeves rolled up, he
presented a contrast to Lt. Klilliqui Sackie and David Bainda of
Liberia, in dark pants, dark shoes and white shirts with the
epaullets of the army on their shoulders. As an officer, or ordaine
a good ministry there.''
</P>
<P>
   The congress is also a family affair for Capt. Hildegard Anthun
Orsnes of Bergen, Norway. She's here with her husband, two
children, her father, mother and mother-in-law. But social worker
Orsnes, 38, treats the whole army as kinfolks.
</P>
<P>
   Every few seconds, she greets someone in German, French,
Norwegian, English or French Creole (she served seven years in the
Caribbean).
</P>
<P>
   ``Here, you really experience the Salvation Army as an
international organization,'' she says. ``Whether you are from a
tiny church in Haiti or a big place like Atlanta, this feels like
family.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  To hear a portion of ``The Salvation Army March,'' composed by
John Philip Sousa for a Salvation Army congress in New York in
1930, and performed by the Victor Band under Rosario Bourdon, dial
404-222-1500.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : The International Millennial Congress of the
Salvation Army: www.salvationarmy.org/webmain.nsf/sub
</P>
<P>
   /internationalmillennialcongress
</P>
<P>
   Gayle White and Derrick Henry writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
