<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 19:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6532 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-BRAZIL-MEDIA-INVEST-N     06-27 0882
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAZIL-MEDIA-INVEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAZIL'S MEDIA ANTICIPATE DEREGULATION, EYEING INVESTMENT,
EXPANSION 
</HEADLINE>
   By JENNIFER L. RICH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAO PAULO, Brazil _ Brazil's Congress is scheduled to vote
Wednesday on a constitutional amendment that would allow foreigners
to invest in the country's media companies, ending a prohibition
that has lasted for 66 years.
</P>
<P>
   If the amendment is passed, Brazil's media companies may be one
step closer to the financing they need to keep up with
technological advances that are revolutionizing print and broadcast
businesses elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are investments that will make the growth and
development of the whole industry possible,'' said Paulo Machado de
Carvalho Neto, vice president of the Brazilian Association of Radio
and Television Broadcasters.
</P>
<P>
   The amendment, which has been circulating in Congress for the
last two years, has broad-based support.
</P>
<P>
   It would allow foreigners to own up to 30 percent of radio and
television stations, newspaper and magazine publishers. Opposition
groups, including unions and leftist parties that are normally
against foreign investment in important Brazilian industries, have
been largely mollified by the relatively low investment that will
be permitted and a clause that prevents foreigners from assuming
any control over editorial content.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the amendment would let Brazilian companies for the first
time own 30 percent of radio and television stations and 100
percent of publishing houses. The current wording of the
constitution allows only Brazilian-born private citizens to own
media outlets.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil's media regulations date to 1934, when post-World War I
nationalism spurred the government to enact laws that would protect
the country from what was then considered undue influence by
foreign powers. A succession of military leaders kept the
legislation in place through the 1970s and 1980s. By the time
Brazil's government and economy started loosening controls on
business in the 1990s, privately owned media businesses were
already hampered by high lending rates and large debts, with
nowhere to turn except to other wealthy individuals.
</P>
<P>
   Since media groups are all privately owned, the exact
indebtedness of the industry is unknown, but the information that
has found its way into the market suggests deep-seated financial
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``In many cases, companies have a high level of indebtedness,
outstanding debts with the government and with the social security
system,'' said Haroldo de Britto, an economist at Goes &AMP;
Consultores, a consulting firm in Brasilia. ``In some cases, they
are almost buried.''
</P>
<P>
   Although there was some concern about whether Congress would
have enough members on the floor this week to vote on the amendment
winter recess looms, there was little doubt that it would
eventually be passed. Media companies are already starting to
navigate through a breach in the law by selling off interests in
their online publishing ventures.
</P>
<P>
   Organizacoes Globo, the leading Brazilian media company,
recently sold a 30 percent stake in its online news portal
Globo.com to Telecom Italia for $810 million, while Universo
Online, an internet news and entertainment portal owned by
publishing companies Folha Group and Editora Abril, is planning an
initial public offering.
</P>
<P>
   Essentially betting that the amendment will pass, the country's
media giants are preparing for the future.
</P>
<P>
   Editora Abril, which publishes more than 200 magazines,
including the world's fourth-largest news weekly, Veja, already
audits its finances as if it were a public company in preparation
for the opening of the market.
</P>
<P>
   Globo, which, along with the Folha Group, started the country's
second national business newspaper, Valor Economico, earlier this
year with an initial investment of $50 million, has already
announced that it is actively seeking foreign partners to bring
content and capital to the publication. Globo also has plans to
launch an initial public offering as early as next year.
</P>
<P>
   The country's smaller media outlets are likely to gain the most
from changes in the law. Brazil has more than 3,000 radio stations,
most of them independent and suffering from a shortage of funding.
With the help of the new legislation, the radio stations are
expected to consolidate into chains that would have stronger
financial potential to improve technology and offer wider coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have seen this development in the United States and
elsewhere,'' said Machado de Carvalho Neto of the broadcasters
association. ``If you begin to value the industry, it winds up
creating a positive situation for the businesses, the investors,
and principally, the public.''
</P>
<P>
   Smaller television networks, which see advertising revenue and
credit availability suffer under the shadow of the TV Globo empire,
will also gain more access to capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need technological know-how to be able to accompany the
process of digitalization that will reach us in three or four
years,'' said Flavio Cavalcante Jr., director at SBT Television,
one of the major national network channels. ``This demands a huge
amount of resources. We want to have the option to form a
partnership with an international company at some time in the
future.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
