<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ZIMBABWE-GENERATION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW GENERATION SHOWS STRENGTH IN ELECTION RESULTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KURT SHILLINGER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARARE, Zimbabwe _ Desperate for jobs and fed up with
state-sanctioned violence, the people of Zimbabwe voted in a new
democratic era in last weekend's parliamentary election, breaking
President Robert Mugabe's 20-year lock on power with a clear demand
for more accountable government, election results showed Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Zimbabwe African National Union (Patriotic Front), which
ruled virtually unopposed since independence in 1980, lost nearly
half of its elected seats and saw its senior ranks plundered. More
than 10 ministers and deputy ministers, half of whom formed
Mugabe's innermost circle, were tossed out.
</P>
<P>
   The party won 62 seats, just five more than the 57 taken by an
upstart opposition movement formed only nine months ago. A tiny
third party captured one seat.
</P>
<P>
   In a stark measure of the change that has taken place, Mugabe's
party held 147 of 150 seats in the previous parliament. Now, even
with its cushion of 30 unelected seats, the ruling party no longer
holds a two-thirds majority. For the first time, Mugabe will not be
able to amend the constitution without bipartisan support.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the beginning of serious politics _ serious democratic
politics _ in this country,'' said Washington Sansole, a former
High Court judge. ``The message to the ruling party is, `Your time
is up.' The young generations do not accept the status quo.''
</P>
<P>
   The opposition Movement for Democratic Change planned to contest
the results in at least 20 districts where, it alleged, severe
political violence prevented its candidates from campaigning
freely. But political analysts expressed hope that the roughly
balanced outcome would dampen prospects for post-election violence
from either side.
</P>
<P>
   Addressing the nation Tuesday night, Mugabe made no reference to
the results, observing only that ``our next parliament is certainly
destined to prove very lively.''
</P>
<P>
   On a continent marred by decades of stolen elections, military
coups d'etat, and autocratic rule, Zimbabwe's election posted a
rare triumph of the ballot box over brutality. A new generation,
removed from their parent's struggle against colonialism, defied
widespread violence and voiced its anger over corruption and
economic mismanagement.
</P>
<P>
   The election was marred by four months of intimidation as
pro-government thugs invaded white-owned farms and beat black
farmworkers they suspected of supporting the opposition. At least
30 people died in the violence. Every candidate from the rival
party faced attack; one fled the country for safety, others were
hospitalized. The European Union's election monitoring team
concluded the elections could not be free and fair, given the
pre-ballot atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   But the two days of voting proceeded smoothly. Nearly 65 percent
of the 5 million registered voters cast ballots. And international
observers cited few serious flaws in the counting process.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking in Poland after the results were announced Tuesday, UN
Secretary General Kofi Annan praised the Zimbabwean people for
their calm. ``I think the election in Zimbabwe was very closely
fought,'' he said in Warsaw. ``The people have spoken. We must
accept their will and I rejoice with them.''
</P>
<P>
   In London, British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook urged Mugabe to
discuss with the opposition ``how, in light of this vote, they can
work together for the people of Zimbabwe.''
</P>
<P>
   The campaign was Zimbabwe's first real contest between competing
ideals. Mugabe exploited the racially imbalanced issue of land
ownership, the crux of the 1970s bush war against colonialism.
Roughly 4,500 white farmers own most of the best agricultural land,
while much of the black majority subsists on scrappy communal
plots. The president lashed out at the British government _
Zimbabwe's former colonial power _ for failing to finance land
reform, and encouraged veterans of the liberation war to invade
white-owned farms.
</P>
<P>
   More than 1,300 farms were raided, but neither land nor race
appeared to swing voters. All but one white opposition candidate,
most of whom ran in urban districts, won seats, including a white
farmer in a rural district near the border with Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition, meanwhile, focused on the economy, railing
against corruption and Zimbabwe's misery index _ inflation,
unemployment, and interest rates all soar above 50 percent. The
party also tapped discontent over Mugabe's military adventures in
Congo, where for nearly two years he has been spending millions of
dollars every month to maintain 11,000 troops in defense of
President Laurent Kabila. That initiative, economists say, has
drained foreign exchange reserves in Zimbabwe, precipitating acute
fuel shortages across the country.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition swept the urban vote, where better educated
voters were isolated from the farm attacks.
</P>
<P>
   But violence almost certainly prevented the ruling party from
losing more seats than it did, political analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   The election offered some surprises. Opposition leader Morgan
Tsvangirai, the fiery trade-unionist, lost in his attempt to win a
seat in parliament. Brushing off the defeat, he said his ability to
campaign throughout the district was frustrated by violence, and
that in any event he remained leader of the party and would now
concentrate on the 2002 presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   Significantly, eight of the opposition's 10 women candidates
emerged victorious.
</P>
<P>
   In a sharp rebuke of the ruling party, Justice Minister Emmerson
Mnangagwa, the man often tipped to be Mugabe's eventual successor,
was trounced. Chenjerai Hunzvi, the controversial leader of the war
veterans who masterminded the farm violence ahead of the elections,
won his district.
</P>
<P>
   Noting the ruling party's losses, Hunzvi called Tuesday for
internal reforms. ``Clearly there is a revolution taking place. The
party has to rejuvenate. To meet the challenge we need an overhaul
from the grassroots to the top,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond establishing the first two-party legislature in
Zimbabwe's history, the election immediately set up a fierce battle
for the presidency in two years. The opposition does not have
enough seats to impeach Mugabe. But the simple vote split _ 51
percent for the ruling party, 48 percent for the opposition _ has
shown that the president is vulnerable, and could set off a panic
inside the ruling party.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the night opposition supporters erupted into
spontaneous celebrations, dancing in the streets of Harare and
tooting car horns with each set of updated results. When newspapers
hit the streets Tuesday morning, huge crowds swarmed to read the
news.
</P>
<P>
   But by midday, the mood in the capital, a new stronghold of the
opposition, had sobered. People wanted better. ``I'm not happy. My
party didn't have enough time to campaign because of the
violence,'' said Golden Ndlovu, an opposition supporter, looking up
from his checkers board in Freedom Square. ``Soldiers in Congo?
What for? The people are suffering, but Mugabe doesn't care.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sort of happy,'' said Richard Musware, a mechanic. ``We
now have an opposition in the country. The ruling party should wake
up and change the way it is running things.''
</P>
<P>
   As the two parties now settle into the unfamiliar task of
sharing power, those comments reveal the new expectations they will
face.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any country that goes through a nationalist struggle goes
through a battle between the liberation loyalties and governance,''
said Strive Masiyiwe, a prominent young businessman who has fought
actively against government corruption. ``Mugabe was kept in power
by what he achieved during the liberation struggle. Now, the basis
of power will be performance.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
