<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 19:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6537 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-RENO-GORE-COX     06-27 0631
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RENO-GORE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reno stands by her role in Gore investigation
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Attorney General Janet Reno on Tuesday once again
defended her handling of the Justice Department's campaign finance
investigation of Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Reno appeared before a Senate subcommittee to face largely
skeptical questions from Republican Senators who called on her to
name an outside prosecutor in the department's investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Reno refused to say whether she would make such an appointment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't do things based on polls. I do things based on the
law,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The panel's Democratic members, led by Sen. Robert Torricelli
(D-N.J.) defended both Reno and Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vice president may have made some mistakes of judgment,''
Torricelli said. ``I do not believe he made mistakes of law.''
</P>
<P>
   The committee's hearing came as a new CNN/USA Today/Gallup of
560 likely voters found Gore trailing Gov. George W. Bush of Texas
52 to 39 percent. A similar CNN poll taken earlier this month
showed Bush leading 48 to 44 percent. The poll's margin of error
was five percent.
</P>
<P>
   Under the now expired independent counsel statute, Reno twice
refused to recommend an independent counsel to investigate alleged
abuses of the Clinton-Gore campaign fund-raising tactics in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Reno is considering another staff recommendation to appoint a
special counsel, this time under internal Justice Department
procedures. Gore's truthfulness in the earlier investigations is
one of the legal issues under review.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate subcommittee was chaired by Sen. Arlen Specter
(R-Pa.), who first disclosed the pending recommendation before Reno
at a news conference last week.
</P>
<P>
   Specter's disclosure prompted Gore to release a 123-page
transcript of an interview conducted April 18 by the head of the
Justice Department's campaign finance task force.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Chris Lehane, Gore's campaign spokesman, released a
caustic statement criticizing Specter for ``McCarthy-like''
tactics.
</P>
<P>
   Lehane accused Specter and his Republican allies of turning
Congress ``into a scandal industrial complex designed to
manufacture and create partisan scandals and inflict political
damage on the vice president a mere four months before voters go to
the polls.''
</P>
<P>
   Specter reacted angrily to the comments during the committee,
saying he planned to take them up personally with Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Specter urged Reno to name an outside counsel to lay the
campaign finance scandal to rest, but even he conceded that it was
probably too late to do so now.
</P>
<P>
   Specter said it was unrealistic to assume that an outside
prosecutor could be put in place before the Democratic National
Convention in August, much less conclude an investigation before
the November elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be that the only alternative America has at this point
in this election is to leave it to the political process,'' Specter
said.
</P>
<P>
   Reno declined to say why Justice investigators waited until
April 18 to quiz the vice president about the two most
controversial aspects of the fund-raising scandals, the White House
coffees and a fund-raiser attended by Gore at a Buddhist temple in
California in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Gore was interviewed four times before, but never about the
White House coffees, which were attended by Democratic donors, or
the temple fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't discuss the timing because I think that would be
inconsistent with my duties,'' Reno said.
</P>
<P>
   Reno repeatedly urged senators not to jump to conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can tell me I'm wrong,'' she said. ``But I will have
greater confidence in your telling me I'm wrong when you have all
the facts.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
