s e BC-U.S.-EUROPE-MUSIC-1     06-27 1110
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.S.-EUROPE-MUSIC-1,070(2TAKES)-$ADV02-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR SINGERS, A NEW AMERICAN WAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, July 2) 
 By ANNE MIDGETTE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The book is called ``Kein' Angst, Baby!'' (``Don't Worry,
Kid!''), and it has a voluptuous Valkyrie sizzling on the cover.
Written for opera singers by opera singers and first published in
1992 by the New York Opera Newsletter, it is a guide to auditioning
in Germany. American singers long regarded the German audition tour
as a useful _ indeed, essential _ career move, and this book helped
the uninitiated negotiate everything from writing a letter to a
German agent to dealing with German telephones and money matters.
</P>
<P>
   But things have changed. International telephoning and banking
have been facilitated by calling cards and automated tellers.
German theaters are not hiring singers as they used to. And both of
the authors of ``Kein' Angst, Baby!,'' Dorothy Maddison and Gail
Sullivan, are back, training in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hegemony of the American singer in Germany is over,'' said
Peter Russell, the director of the Young Artist Development Program
at the Metropolitan Opera.
</P>
<P>
   There are no official statistics on the numbers of American
singers who used to go to Germany for the fall audition season. But
in the mid-1980s it was reported to have been a couple of thousand.
</P>
<P>
   The promise of steady work was a powerful lure. More opera is
performed in the German-speaking world on any given night than in
the entire rest of the world. The former West Germany had more than
80 opera houses, supported by state subsidies. Each employed its
own singers, who received year-round salaries (with an extra
month's pay as a Christmas bonus), four to six weeks of vacation
and full benefits.
</P>
<P>
   In America, by contrast, work was and is irregular. ``In the
States, most of the companies still do four productions a year, and
they do that production four times,'' said Pamela Rosenberg, the
artistic director of the Stuttgart Opera, who is to become the
general manager of the San Francisco Opera next year. In Germany,
most houses adopted the repertory system, playing a different work
from one night to the next, like the Met. But the average German
house has a far longer season than the Met, with its seven and a
half months, the longest season of any opera house in America. No
company in the United States can give a singer a full-time job.
</P>
<P>
   German theater directors, moreover, have a decided prejudice in
favor of American-trained singers, who arrive with a level of stage
experience that most German conservatories don't offer. ``The
training is absolutely better,'' said Klaus Schulz, director of the
Stadttheater am Gaertnerplatz in Munich, who makes regular trips to
America to scout new talent.
</P>
<P>
   And the results of this preference are still in evidence.
``Every German opera house still has about 50 percent Americans,''
Rosenberg said. ``They'd have to shut every house in Germany if
Americans didn't come.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the picture has gradually been changing. In the 1960s, ``If
you could speak some German and sing all right, you could probably
get a job,'' said Frederic Mayer, a retired tenor. But by the 1980s
it was a lot harder to get a foot in the door.
</P>
<P>
   Mayer sang in the ensemble at Gaertnerplatz for more than 30
years. He was also choir director at the English-speaking Church of
the Ascension in Munich, which used to be an unofficial meeting
place for auditioning singers. (It is recommended in ``Kein' Angst,
Baby!'')
</P>
<P>
   ``I see quite a few kids coming through and auditioning, but not
masses, the way we used to in the '80s,'' Mayer said. ``Where we
used to get 15 or 20 new singers every year, I probably see 3.''
</P>
<P>
   There are a couple of reasons for the falloff in young
Americans. One is the opening of the former Soviet Union in the
early 1990s, which released a huge wave of eager young singers from
Eastern Europe who were willing to work for a lot less money than
anyone else.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the first five years, one could get the East bloc singers
strikingly cheap,'' said Schulz of the Gaertnerplatz. Even today,
the Vienna State Opera has been known to alternate a highly paid
superstar soprano in the same role with a young Eastern European
singer who receives a mere fraction of the better-known singer's
salary.
</P>
<P>
   At the entry level, the pay may not be as much an issue.
``Americans will also sing for not much money,'' said Inge
Tennigkeit, an opera agent in Dusseldorf. ``They'll also sing in
small theaters.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, there is no question that the Eastern Europeans have
changed the playing field. ``I hear fewer Americans, because I can
only hear 25 or 30 people, maximum, at each audition,'' said
Karl-Erich Haase of Munich's venerable Stoll agency, who, as all
the agents used to do in the 1980s, holds auditions once a week.
``You can only hear so many. And there are more Eastern Europeans
now. The middle level of American singer has fewer chances.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there is German reunification. As the once wealthy nation
stretched its resources to cover the costs of five impoverished new
states, cultural subsidies suffered, and the budgets of opera
houses _ along with those of museums, theaters and dance companies
_ were frozen or slashed. A few smaller opera houses had to close.
The effects have extended even to such major houses as those in
Frankfurt and Hamburg, which have reduced their numbers of
performances appreciably.
</P>
<P>
   With tighter budgets has come a tendency not to replace singers
who retire or move to another house. In lieu of the year-round
contracts that used to be the norm, theaters have been offering
more and more part-time contracts and guest stints. From 1990 to
1997, the number of singers employed in German ensembles fell by
about 20 percent. People who have ensemble jobs have tended to keep
them, so there are fewer jobs free for incoming singers.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, as Germany tightens its belt, the American opera
scene is expanding as never before: another reason fewer singers
are crossing the Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 114 professional opera companies registered with the
service organization Opera America, Mark Scorca, the group's
president, reports, half have started since 1970. And 70 companies
have some sort of training program. In the three years since its
inception, Opera America's singer services program has grown
threefold, to more than 1,300 members. ``I think it's much easier
for American singers to make careers without going to Europe,''
said Diana Hossack, who directs singer services.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Russell, of the Met's young artist program, elaborated: ``What I
find frightening is that there are now so many different
opportunities for young American singers in the States that a lot
of us are vying for the best singers.''
</P>
<P>
   There are no rules about how to launch a singing career, and
there have always been singers who have built fine careers at home.
Amy Burton, a soprano who often appears at the New York City Opera,
started out singing in regional companies around America.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some years I was traveling 10 months a year,'' she said. ``I
was still in the phase of, `I can't believe they're paying me to
sing: I'm having such a good time.' I was learning an amazing
amount of repertoire.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, she sang in Europe but not on a full-time basis and not
in Germany. ``I did consider a contract somewhere, and that was
never very appealing to me,'' she said. ``I didn't want to live in
Germany, for one thing.'' What she has created instead, she added,
is ``not only an American career but one of the most New York-based
careers that I know.''
</P>
<P>
   Dean Elzinga, a bass-baritone from California, has also started
out along a peripatetic American-based path. ``I'm hardly ever at
home,'' he said from a hotel room in Portland, Ore., during a
recent run of ``The Mikado,'' before flying to New York for an
acclaimed appearance with the Eos Chamber Orchestra in Peter
Maxwell Davies' ``Eight Songs for a Mad King.'' Elzinga is spending
three months at the Glimmerglass Opera, in Cooperstown, N.Y., this
summer, after a season that carried him from Arizona to Alberta.
</P>
<P>
   This kind of nomadic life is fine for some; for others, it is
enough to drive them away. ``I was really sick of being a secretary
and then flying out to the Fort Lauderdale Opera for $600 and doing
the rehearsal period for nothing,'' said Susan Davis Holmes, a
soprano. ``Or the Bronx Opera for $350 for three months' work,
hoping someone would see me from the New York City Opera. The
pitiful thing was that people envied my career. I just couldn't
handle the traveling and being uprooted all the time, and the
uncertainty and no money. I said: `I'll go to Germany, and I'll go
twice. I'll go into debt. If I don't get a job somewhere, I'm
quitting.'''
</P>
<P>
   But there are still jobs in Germany, and Holmes got one. She
spent four years in the ensemble of the small theater in Pforzheim,
which she describes as ``a factory.'' A notorious risk of the
German ensemble system is that singers work so much they wear out
their voices; then the theater discards them. ``Once you're in a
small house for longer than two years,'' Holmes said, ``people
start not taking you seriously anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   But she landed an ensemble contract at a larger house, in
Freiburg, and she has started making more prestigious guest
appearances at theaters like the Stuttgart Opera: a textbook
example of a young singer climbing the ensemble ladder. ``I have no
interest in going back to the States,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Some young singers in the American opera loop do better
financially than Holmes did in the tough New York market. While
some American houses offer more prestige than pay _ Glimmerglass,
the Opera Theater of St. Louis or the Virginia Opera, for example _
others are well financed, even in relatively unexpected places like
Salt Lake City, New Orleans and Tulsa, Okla.
</P>
<P>
   ``At a lot of regional houses, I expect to make somewhere
between $1,000 and $3,000'' per performance, Elzinga said.
</P>
<P>
   Both fees and opinions vary. ``You can't make a good living
singing only in America,'' said Richard Harrell, the director of
the San Francisco Opera Center. ``The fees just aren't high
enough.'' At the same time, Rosenberg, struggling to hire singers
in Stuttgart, is shocked to learn that the Tulsa Opera, in a
production of ``Aida,'' offers its Amneris $6,000 a night. ``We pay
much less than they pay in the States,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   And she labors under another disadvantage, because a change in
German laws has driven taxes, even for foreign artists, so high
that given a comparable choice they prefer to sing elsewhere.
``It's tougher for us to get a certain level of American singers to
commit,'' she said. In recent months, the strong dollar has only
contributed to the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Elzinga said that when he recently auditioned for London agents
who might represent him in Europe, he was told that German fees had
declined. ``You have less money to take home. But there are still
really important houses and artists there if you can survive on
what they pay you.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, plenty of people would still recommend a stint in
Germany. ``I say to every American singer that they should get
themselves over here and get a house position,'' Rosenberg said.
``You will do a role 20 or 30 times. You will be working at your
profession much more.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Harrell, based in San Francisco, emphasizes that opera ``is
essentially a European art form performed in European languages.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important for someone who's going to make a career of it
to go and spend some time there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans getting jobs in Germany now seem to be coming in
at a higher level of professionalism. ``Many Americans come over
with managers now,'' said Haase of the Stoll agency. ``It's easier
for me when I simply talk to an agent and he brings me 10 good
people.''
</P>
<P>
   But at least one agent feels that the overall level of Americans
has declined drastically. ``First, not so many Americans are
coming,'' Tennigkeit said. ``Second, they're not as well trained.
The singers present themselves well, but in terms of pure vocal
technique, they don't compare to those 10 years ago. The difference
is absolutely blatant. Today, they're often the ones who have sung
for a couple of years in America, and it didn't work over there, so
they thought they'd try it in Germany.''
</P>
<P>
   In America, by contrast, Harrell, who hears some 600 entry-level
singers a year, says that ``the people I'm hearing are getting
better: better trained, more high-quality singers.'' Even allowing
for personal tastes, one could infer, from these contrasting
opinions, that young American talent today is more likely to
audition for the San Francisco program than for a German agent.
</P>
<P>
   For those who do find work in the German-speaking world, it is
an open question exactly what that contract translates into in
terms of a larger career. Elzinga spent seven months at the Vienna
Volksoper doing major roles: Escamillo in ``Carmen,'' Figaro in
``Le Nozze fi Figaro,'' Mephistopheles in ``Faust.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it would lead to something, but it didn't,'' Elzinga
said. ``I know a woman who worked in Germany for a long time who
said it was quite a struggle to come back. She'd been out of the
loop. If you're at the important but not star level in Europe and
you want to break into the States, it's hard.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
