<SLUG> BC-FORECAST-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: AD SPENDING FORECAST SIGNALS CONTINUING BOOM 
</HEADLINE>
   By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A leading forecaster of advertising spending has
raised his estimates for 2000, citing economic conditions that are
more robust than he expected as well as strong spending so far this
year by marketers in major categories from automobiles to computers
to drugs.
</P>
<P>
   And in a sign that the sustained boom on Madison Avenue shows
little likelihood of slowing down _ dot-coms or not-coms _ a
preliminary prognostication for 2001 was similarly upbeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think these good trends will continue,'' said Robert Coen,
senior vice president and forecasting director at Universal McCann,
who presented his predictions Tuesday at the University Club in
Manhattan. ``There is continued strong demand for media time and
space.''
</P>
<P>
   Ad spending is considered a sensitive barometer of the economy,
particularly the willingness of consumers to continue shopping as
enthusiastically as they have. Though the Conference Board reported
Tuesday that consumer confidence fell this month from a record in
May, the data for the second quarter was the second best ever. That
suggested the consumer spending spree is unlikely to slow
significantly.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are legs to the story'' of continued sustained ad
spending growth, said Karen Ficker, a managing director at ING
Barings in New York who attended Coen's presentation.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the categories cited by Coen, which also included
alcoholic beverages, brokers and mutual funds, restaurants and
resorts, Ficker said she expected big increases in ad spending in
``emerging categories'' like wireless and hand-held devices that
``are going to need to brand themselves to differentiate
themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   In his presentation, which Coen makes twice a year, he predicted
that ad spending this year in the United States would total a
record $235.6 billion, up 9.4 percent from a revised figure of
$215.3 billion spent in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The 1999 figure represented an increase of 6.8 percent from the
$201.6 billion spent in 1998 _ ``very good for an odd-numbered
year,'' Coen said, without the stimulative effects of elections and
the Olympics, which are of course adding to the projected increases
for 2000, along with special campaigns with millennium themes.
</P>
<P>
   An increase of 9.4 percent for 2000 would be the largest in
percentage terms since 1984 _ also a year of Olympics and elections
_ when ad spending climbed 15.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The estimate Tuesday marked the second time that Coen, who has
been following ad spending trends since 1948, had raised his
forecast for 2000. His first prediction, made in June 1999, was for
an increase of 7.5 percent, to $230 billion. Six months later, he
revised his outlook to an increase of 8.3 percent to $232 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The economic expectations are considerably brighter for 2000
than they were in December,'' Coen said, primarily because numerous
advertisers ``are posting phenomenal increases'' in ad spending.
</P>
<P>
   National ad spending this year is now expected to rise 11.1
percent, to $141.9 billion, compared with Coen's estimate in
December of 9.1 percent to $139.2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Local ad spending, however, is now expected to rise 7 percent,
to $93.8 billion, rather than 7.1 percent, to $93.9 billion. Coen
attributed the slight decrease in his estimate to ``a weak
performance in retail'' advertising in newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   If Coen's latest estimates for 2000 prove right, ad spending as
a percentage of gross domestic product would reach a record 2.4
percent, compared with 2.33 percent in 1999 and 2.3 percent in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   That pleased another analyst attending the presentation, Leland
Westerfield from PaineWebber in New York, who has theorized that ad
spending may be breaking out from historic norms. Until now,
Westerfield said, when ad spending reached or exceeded 2.3 percent
of gross domestic product, it would then grow more slowly than
gross domestic product.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no one else who can bring 50-plus years of economic
observations to his forecasts,'' Westerfield said, ``which provides
a large measure of credibility when Bob says advertising can
outpace GDP growth.''
</P>
<P>
   If advertisers cooperate with Coen's initial estimate for 2001 _
$251 billion, an increase of 6.5 percent from his adjusted forecast
for 2000 _ ad spending next year would amount to 2.42 percent of
projected gross domestic product.
</P>
<P>
   Turning to ad spending abroad, Coen was also optimistic, citing
expected gains in several countries that account for about
two-thirds of all spending outside the United States, among them
Canada, France, Germany and Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Spending overseas should total $229.2 billion for 2000, Coen
said, an increase of 7.2 percent from a final total of $213.8
billion for 1999, which has been adjusted downward from earlier
estimates of $216.3 billion. The revised total for 1999 marked a
gain of 4.2 percent from $205.2 billion spent abroad in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   For 2000, then, Coen's worldwide total estimate is $464.8
billion, up 8.3 percent from his final figure of $429.1 billion for
1999. That would be the biggest one-year percentage increase since
1995, when worldwide ad spending rose 11.5 percent. The final 1999
figure represented an increase of 5.5 percent from the $205.2
billion spent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Looking ahead to 2001, Coen said that ad spending abroad would
reach $247 billion, up 7.8 percent from his revised forecast for
2000; that would also be the biggest one-year percentage increase
since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   So Coen's worldwide total estimate for 2001 is $498 billion, an
increase of 7.1 percent from his projected total for 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't quite juggle those percentages to get to $500
billion, half a trillion,'' Coen said, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   One member of the audience at the presentation suggested with a
smile that if Coen was ``worried about getting to $500 billion,''
he should raise his estimate for online ad spending in 2000 of $3.4
billion, up 75 percent from 1999. (Actually, Coen had; the figure
he projected in December was $3.2 billion.)
</P>
<P>
   As for dot-com spending in the traditional media, which may
decline if more e-commerce companies close or conserve cash to
remain afloat, Coen was sanguine.
</P>
<P>
   ``If two of these companies lose their ability to buy
traditional media,'' he said, ``10 more can fly in to replace
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Universal McCann, where Coen works, is the media services
division of McCann-Erickson Worldwide Advertising. That agency is
part of the McCann-Erickson World Group, owned by the Interpublic
Group of Companies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
