<P>
   CUBA-U.S. (Washington) _ House Republican leaders agree to end
40 years of sanctions on sales of food to Cuba, in a compromise
that carries great political significance but may be of only
symbolic economic value. The deal would in principle allow U.S.
farmers and agricultural corporations to sell their goods directly
to Cuba for the first time since 1961. The agreement also echoes
existing policy allowing the sale of medicine and medical products
to Cuba. But Cuban-American lawmakers succeeded in placing severe
restrictions on the bill. By Lizette Alvarez. (Eds.: an early
version of this story has moved; the 1stLd-Writethru is scheduled
to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT1.
