Clinton plan. By John M. Broder. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in
``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   FDA-OVER-THE-COUNTER (Washington) _ Spurred by two
pharmaceutical companies that want to take their
cholesterol-lowering medications over the counter, the FDA is
considering whether many more medicines should be made available
without a doctor's prescription. Beginning with public hearings on
Wednesday and Thursday, the drug agency will begin a re-examination
of the way it regulates over-the-counter drugs, the first such
review in nearly three decades. The last one, in 1972, created a
new system for approving over-the-counter drugs that enabled more
than 600 drugs to switch from prescription to nonprescription
status. By Sheryl Gay Stolberg. (Scheduled to move by 8:45 p.m. ET
in ``w'' news file.) 1,500 words.
