<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 20:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6547 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-SUPREMES-MUSIC-$ADV2-     06-27 1170
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUPREMES-MUSIC-$ADV2-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFINING TWO ROLES:   DIVA AND SOUL SURVIVOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 2)  
 By DAVID A. KEEPS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For a teen-ager living in the suburbs of Detroit in 1964, the
royals of AM radio were alarmingly obvious: the Beatles were the
imported kings of rock 'n' roll and Aretha was the native Queen of
Soul. Then along came the pop princess Diana and her ladies in
waiting, the Supremes. With a voice as pure and sweet as an ebony
virgin locked in an ivory tower _ and the glamour and vanity to
match _ Diana Ross led the Motown trio to the top of the charts 10
times in less than three years. In 1967 she became the headliner,
and three years later, Diana Ross and the Supremes made their
farewell appearance at the Frontier in Las Vegas, singing their
final No. 1 hit. It was an end-of-the-affair, gospel-styled swan
song filled with regret and hope and titled ``Someday We'll Be
Together.'' No one, least of all Diana Ross, suspected that
``someday'' would ever come to pass.
</P>
<P>
   Now it has. With a few minor caveats: never mind that the Diana
Ross and the Supremes tour, which comes to Madison Square Garden on
Thursday and Jones Beach on Saturday, does not feature the founding
members Florence Ballard (who died, pretty much destitute, in 1967)
and Mary Wilson. Forget that Ross never even sang with the
latter-day Supremes Lynda Laurence (1971-73) and Scherrie Payne
(1973-76). Ignore the obvious irony of a show titled ``Return to
Love''; in the 30 years since Ross left the most successful female
vocal group in history, it has become clear that there was no love
lost.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly why Ross, a savvy multimillionaire performer and
television and film producer, has decided that now is the time to
relive the glories of her first 10 years in show business is
anyone's guess. With no new record to promote, this would appear to
be more of an upscale golden-oldies show for baby boomers than a
response to the kind of nostalgic zeitgeist that precipitated the
disco and new wave revivals of the last decade. It would also
appear to be one serious case of superstar hubris: at prices of up
to $250, ticket sales have been less than robust.
</P>
<P>
   Possessed of a pure pop instrument _ a girlish voice with crisp
enunciation that is equally suited to the task of telegraphing joy
and heartache, often within a single song _ Ross has reached out
and touched generations. She has also tried the public's patience
with an ego befitting the term diva long before it became a
fashionable, if overused, sobriquet for songstresses ranging from
Whitney Houston to Faith Hill. Long before Bruce Springsteen
punched in at the hit factory, Ross grandly declared herself the
Boss, taking the name from the title of her 1979 hit. ``Many people
view ambition as a negative quality in an individual,'' she has
said. ``It's just my life force, who I am. I cannot stop.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago at a party following the Grammy Awards, I had an
audience with Miss Ross. I had my photograph taken with her and,
afterward, asked what records she had been listening to lately.
``What is this?'' she snapped imperiously. ``An interview?'' It was
her way of saying that if it was, it was now over.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the answer to my question seems clear enough. In the last
few years, a new soul sisterhood of girl groups has taken center
stage alongside R-and-B-loving boy bands like 'N Sync and teen
sirens like Britney Spears. Some of these female combos, like TLC,
who trade in street-smart rap and cautionary ballads like
``Waterfalls,'' have been evolving since the early '90s. Others,
including Destiny's Child, 702 and the TLC protegees Blaque, have
recently climbed the charts. Their songs update the Supremes' sonic
blend of uptempo percussion and smartly deployed harmonies while
transforming the Supremes' once-timely advice for the lovelorn into
a modern message of female self-sufficiency. Perhaps Ross believes
that her time, a time of almost-quaint, yearning love songs, has
come again.
</P>
<P>
   Four decades ago, Diane Ernestine Ross was no different from any
member of Destiny's Child or even from Christina Aguilera. A young
sparrow who longed to be an international songbird, Diane sang
hymns in the church, Etta James tunes in front of her bedroom
mirror and rhythm-and-blues on the stoops of the Brewster housing
projects in Detroit. Back then there were no market strategists,
fashion stylists, video directors or music television channels to
speed her passage.
</P>
<P>
   There was, however, a local recording impresario named Berry
Gordy, who was melding the exuberance of gospel and the raunch of
ghetto blues with the smooth production values of pop to create a
new hybrid of rhythm-and-blues called soul.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr., Gordy had a dream. His
fledgling label, Motown, pronounced itself ``the sound of young
America'' _ a statement of both empowerment and assimilation _ and
the company's stock-in-trade was impeccably dressed harmony groups
that could transcend the marginalization of R-and-B music and claim
their rightful place in the pop charts.
</P>
<P>
   Diana Ross began her career in 1959 with the Primettes, a group
founded by Florence Ballard, whose roof-raising vocals made her an
ideal lead singer. after signing them and renaming them the
Supremes in 1961 and releasing six consecutive flops in the next
two years, Gordy began to have second thoughts. The Shirelles, a
quartet from Passaic, N.J., had already become the first black
female group to reach No. 1 with the wrenching ballad ``Will You
Love Me Tomorrow?'' A few years later, in New York, Brill Building
composers (including Carole King) and studio wizards like Phil
Spector were shaping a new sound. Most of these girl groups,
teen-ager puppets molded into disposable, interchangeable pop
entities, were about to be washed away in the flood of the British
Invasion that began in 1964. The Supremes, Gordy determined, would
not suffer that fate.
</P>
<P>
   By then, Diane Ross had rechristened herself Diana, goddess of
the hunt. Promoted as the star of the group, her high-pitched coo
of innocence and burgeoning sexuality was the icing on a string of
five consecutive No. 1 hits (including ``Baby Love'' and ``Stop in
the Name of Love'') in 1964 and 1965.
</P>
<P>
   Gordy was quick to capitalize on the Diana charm, casting her
and the Supremes as a sort of prom queen and court complete with
couture gowns, etiquette lessons (taught in Motown's ``artist
development'' finishing school) and empire-building aspirations.
Within three years, the Supremes had their faces plastered on a
signature line of baked goods (The Supremes White Bread) and
recorded an album of British Invasion tunes and a collection of
country-and-western, tribute LP's to Sam Cooke and Rodgers &AMP; Hart
and a version of the Broadway hit ``Funny Girl.'' They appeared at
the Copa in New York, and performed a moving rendition of
``Somewhere'' on the ``Tonight Show'' the day after King's
assassination.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   After leaving the Supremes, Ross channeled the spirit of the
jazz giant Billie Holiday, winning a 1971 Academy Award nomination
for her screen debut in ``Lady Sings the Blues.'' But her acting
career slowed down with the camp classic ``Mahogany'' (the story of
a ghetto girl gone high fashion, for which Ross designed her own
costumes) and the film version of the Broadway hit ``The Wiz.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite these film flops and a reputation for exasperating,
embarrassing behavior (she once berated her sound crew in front of
800,000 concertgoers in Central Park), Ross, 56, has endured,
navigating the changing currents of pop music with ease. Working
with the best songwriters and producers, she has scored hits with
schmaltzy soundtrack ballads (``Do You Know Where You're Going
To,'' 1975), post-disco gay anthems (``I'm Coming Out,'' 1980) and
Euro-disco workouts (``Take Me Higher,'' 1995).
</P>
<P>
   This April, she became the first recording artist to be honored
with a tribute concert broadcast as part of VH1's indefatigable
``Divas'' franchise. As an excuse to introduce the new Supremes
(complete with six male dancers) and thus promote the current tour,
it was rather transparent, but as is usually the case with legends,
there was a compelling back story. In the last year, Ross has
outdone herself: one week she was all over the tabloids for
hassling a security guard who patted her down at Heathrow Airport
in London, the next week she was feeling rapper L'il Kim's breast
at an awards show.
</P>
<P>
   Ross' turn on ``VH1 Divas 2000'' was equally baffling. Her voice
was ragged, she flubbed and flattened notes or didn't even try to
reach her trademark high ones, rendering pop classics into a
shorthand that approached improvisational jazz. She strutted and
staggered, giggled and poked a little fun at Mariah Carey's
miniskirts, shook the fringed hem of her own dress, watching it
like a girl fascinated by the rustle of her first crinoline and
showered the audience with a stream of ``Thank-you's'' and ``I love
you's.'' It was a riveting, unpredictable performance, filled with
bravura, like watching an aged figure skater go for a triple toe
loop and manage to land it.
</P>
<P>
   It defines the magic behind the madness of the diva complex. For
just when her narcissism (the gowns! the hair! the nails!)
threatens to bring the curtain down, Diana Ross cuts loose with a
fragile trill that soars like a wounded bird.
</P>
<P>
   We are, to paraphrase one of the Supremes' superb hits, back in
her arms again, so satisfied.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
