<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 20:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6551 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-MONKEES-REVIEW-NYT     06-27 0796
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-MONKEES-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DAYDREAM BELIEVERS': FAKERS WHO REALIZE THAT THEY'RE THE REAL
THING 
</HEADLINE>
  (Broadcast notes at end of review. Time, channel are for New York
area. Check local listings.) 
 By DAVID DeWITT    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The scene prompts amused, head-shaking, eye-blinking wonder: The
Beatles, the Fab Four themselves, sharing heart-to-hearts with the
Monkees, the Prefab Four, about the perils of fame and the burdens
of talent.
</P>
<P>
   That actually happened. The inventive American entertainment
machine sculptured four strangers into a band that parodied the
Beatles but ultimately shared their pop universe. ``Daydream
Believers: The Monkees Story,'' a smart and cheerful movie on VH1
Wednesday night, dramatizes the wildly improbable ride of this
manufactured band.
</P>
<P>
   The Monkees were conceived in 1965 as a gimmick: Take the madcap
style of the Beatles' film ``A Hard Day's Night,'' adapt it for
television and mix in talents like the filmmakers Bob Rafelson and
Paul Mazursky, all designed to tap into the nation's Beatlemania.
``You give me a free hand,'' the pop impresario Don Kirshner says
in the film, ``and I'll have 'em outselling the Beatles in six
months.''
</P>
<P>
   Who would have expected this idea to yield chart-topping hits, a
movie written by Jack Nicholson and audiences with the Beatles? Not
even the Monkees themselves. At first they seem delighted just to
have jobs. Yet ``Daydream Believers'' makes clear how this puppet
group gained its own life, thanks to the unlikely chemistry of its
members.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Nesmith (Jeff Geddis) and Peter Tork (L.B. Fisher) are
budding musicians; Micky Dolenz (Aaron Lohr) and Davy Jones (George
Stanchev) are workmanlike actors. All four need an opportunity and
respond to the open casting call for a proposed television comedy
titled ``The Monkees.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Daydream Believers'' makes the series the brainchild of a
somewhat composite character, Van Foreman (Colin Ferguson in an
intelligent performance), using the musical guidance of Kirshner
(Wallace Langham, who makes the role far more biting than Paul
Shaffer's familiar ``Saturday Night Live'' caricature). Kirshner is
promised total creative control of the Monkees' sound, well before
the band members are cast.
</P>
<P>
   That control doesn't sit well with Mike, who chafes at
Kirshner's use of studio musicians for the band's songs. ``Daydream
Believers'' portrays Mike as arrogant but somewhat innocent in his
belief that the Monkees can transcend the marketing forces that
made them.
</P>
<P>
   And in their desire for respect as a band, the Monkees seem to
dismiss a large part of their success: Their Emmy Award-winning
comic ensemble and the appealing personalities it offered, all
based on the performers themselves and bearing their real names. By
movie's end, with their television series canceled, the Monkees
seem to appreciate what they achieved, too late.
</P>
<P>
   ``Daydream Believers'' has cast the Monkees with look-alikes
(aside from Lohr's Micky) who give subtle honesty to what could
have been rote performances. Fisher makes the intriguing Peter both
sweet and compellingly earnest; Geddis captures Mike's style with
relaxed clarity; and Lohr makes a likable individual of Micky, the
television show's broadest talent but the television film's least
developed Monkee.
</P>
<P>
   Stanchev's Davy is the center of this story. He clearly portrays
Davy's growing isolation from the other Monkees, who embrace the
rock 'n' roll life while he struggles to remain an actor though he
has become a phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   The film's strong acting and thematic focus trump its sometimes
sketchy and formulaic dialogue. Nonetheless, the boldest moment of
``Daydream Believers'' is the script's: An opening scene in which a
contemporary man tries to sell a laptop-obsessed executive on the
``cutting edge'' idea of a show about a band, a scene that segues
into the series' 1965 pitch. The scene's apparent aim is to
introduce the Monkees to an audience familiar with today's
Backstreet Boys and similar manufactured acts.
</P>
<P>
   There's a big difference, however, between then and now. Can
anyone imagine the Backstreet Boys as stars of a weekly comedy
series? The Monkees may not have been the Beatles, but as
``Daydream'' seems to believe, they honestly earned their places in
pop history.
</P>
<P>
   BROADCAST NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `DAYDREAM BELIEVERS':
</P>
<P>
   The Monkees Story
</P>
<P>
   9 p.m. Wednesday on VH1.
</P>
<P>
   Written by Ron McGee; Susan Murdoch, producer; Neill Fearnley,
director; Joanne Jackson, production manager; Marie-Claude Harnois,
production coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: George Stanchev (Davy), Aaron Lohr (Micky), Jeff Geddis
(Mike), L.B. Fisher (Peter), Colin Ferguson (Van Foreman), Stephen
Bogaert (Harris Green) and Wallace Langham (Don Kirshner).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-27-00 2006EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
