<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 20:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6556 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-NY-MENUS-NYT &LR;      06-27 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MENUS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MENU WINKS, AND CATCHES THE EYE 
</HEADLINE>
   By AMANDA HESSER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On the menu at Blue Hill, a new restaurant on
Washington Place, there's a dish that might give diners pause. It's
called ``Not Another Roast Chicken.'' Dan Barber, one of the chefs,
said he wants diners to know that this isn't the cliched dish found
in every restaurant. It's a free-range organic chicken from a
small, obscure farm, roasted in a fancy high-tech oven imported
from Austria.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're inviting interaction,'' Barber said. He wants to provoke
a reaction, so his waiters can have a chance to explain how it's
different.
</P>
<P>
   This is also Barber's way of using the menu as one more way of
communicating with the customer. In New York these days the
traditional serious menu is being upstaged by menus that try to
make some personal comment: funny, ironic, intriguing, sometimes
just sophomoric.
</P>
<P>
   Personality is beginning to emerge somewhere between the entree
and the price, offering small glimpses of the chefs tucked away in
the kitchen. They're not just dutifully cranking out dinners; they
have ideas about food and eating that they want to express to their
customers. The menu is the first chance to communicate those ideas.
</P>
<P>
   When this is done well and with restraint, it's refreshing, even
charming. For instance, on the Lobster Club's menu, you'll come
across ``Creamed Spinach With Almost No Fat?'' You have to think
about it for a second. It's a tease. There is no such thing as
creamed spinach without fat.
</P>
<P>
   When it's not done so well, as in the references to ``Seizure
Salad'' at Greenwich Village Bistro and ``Chocolate Salami'' at
Revel, it can leave you worrying about who's behind that swinging
door.
</P>
<P>
   The other, serious, school of menu writing lists all the
ingredients and their sources like film credits. As reading
material, this ranks in excitement with a dental equipment catalog:
By the end, you are dizzy and exhausted from the whirl of words,
and so bored you could cry.
</P>
<P>
   Anne Rosenzweig's menus at the Lobster Club are a reaction to
these styles. ``I've always felt that a menu was an opportunity for
chefs to have fun and poke a little fun at themselves,'' she said,
``because I think chefs take themselves too seriously and menus are
too serious.''
</P>
<P>
   Her ``Sexy Grits,'' ``Voluptuous Cauliflower'' and ``He-Man
Salad,'' appearing periodically on the menu, may not be ha-ha
funny, but they are surprising. ``When we're devising dishes in the
kitchen, it's exactly how I talk about food,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Keller, the chef at the French Laundry in the Napa
Valley, is famously irreverent on his menu. Two of his classic
dishes are ``Macaroni and Cheese'' and ``Tongue in Cheek.'' Of
course, the macaroni and cheese is made with lobster, mascarpone
and orzo. The tongue in cheek is braised veal tongue and beef
cheeks.
</P>
<P>
   There is a fine line, however, between clever and cloying.
</P>
<P>
   ``Flantastico'' at Patria, for instance, feels more like an
entry in the Zagat guide describing a flan shop. ``Fusilli Aum!
Aum!'' _ Neapolitan for ``Fusilli Yum! Yum!'' _ at La Locanda is
cute, but when the moment comes to order it, who is actually going
to say the words?
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately some chefs realize when they've crossed the line. At
Atlas, the desserts called ``Rumpledinger's Ice-Cargots'' and
``Vacherin `A Liberal Interpretation''' have been reconsidered.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people just didn't get it,'' said James Danos, the
chef. Now, the ice-cargots is called ``Rumpledinger's Ice Cream and
Sorbet.'' The vacherin has been retired.
</P>
<P>
   Danos did, however, keep the ``Baked Black Truffle Mutton
Button,'' a cheese course of sheep's milk cheese and truffles that
is nothing more than a delicious little treat.
</P>
<P>
   At Blue Hill, Barber, 30, and his partner, Alex Urena, 29, are
new to running a restaurant. He admitted that they have had second
thoughts about the commentary they have added to their menu. ``I
wonder if saying `Not Another Roast Chicken' is a little too early
for us,'' he said. Someone like Keller, he pointed out, has the
pedigree and the cooking skills to back it up.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Barber and Urena are both shy about going out into the
dining room. To them, a menu with bits of their personalities _
they also offer ``Real Slow Cooked Salmon'' and ``Spring'' (a
salad) _ is a way to step out of the kitchen without actually
speaking to people.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, when you invite communication, you may actually get
it. Not long ago, one diner sent the roast chicken back to the
kitchen with a message for the chef: It was just another roast
chicken.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
