<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6558 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-FLIGHT-POSTERS-$ADV02     06-27 0997
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLIGHT-POSTERS-$ADV02-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAPTURING,   AND SELLING,   THE GLAMOUR   OF FLIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: R.I., Va., N.C., Calif., France, Germany, Egypt)  (For release Sunday, July 2) 
 By RITA REIF   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Posters helped sell aviation to the world a century
ago, though not until five years after Orville and Wilbur Wright
flew a heavier-than-air machine for the first time at Kitty Hawk,
N.C., in 1903.
</P>
<P>
   Even then, public interest in flying surged first not in the
United States but in Europe, when Wilbur Wright brought the
brothers' biplane to Le Mans, in western France, introducing it at
a race course and stunning the audience with its superior
performance. After that demonstration, aviation became a spectator
sport.
</P>
<P>
   European airplane producers promptly adapted various aspects of
the Wrights' technology to their monoplanes and biplanes. French
and German pilots demonstrated the improvements in their aircraft
at air meets that proliferated, becoming monthly events in cities
throughout Europe and North Africa like Frankfurt; Reims, France,
and Heliopolis, Egypt; they became as popular as rock 'n' roll
concerts are today. Meanwhile, poster production, which was far
more advanced on the Continent than in the United States, boomed,
awakening the public to every aspect of flying. And as flight
posters became increasingly colorful and diverse, they advertised
more than air meets. Some promoted the planes favored by the most
famous pilots, while others sold glamour, in consumer products that
ranged from Champagne to furs.
</P>
<P>
   The little-known role of posters in popularizing flight in the
early 20th century is the focus of ``Looping the Loop: Posters of
Early Flight,'' the first museum exhibition on the subject in this
country, on view at the National Air and Space Museum here through
next Sunday. The show was organized by the museum, along with the
owner of the 32 posters on view, the Allen Airways Flying Museum of
El Cajon, Calif., and the Smithsonian Institution Traveling
Exhibition Service. The show, which will travel through 2002, moves
next to the Thames Science Center in Newport, R.I. (July 22 to Oct.
8), and then to the Virginia Air and Space Center in Hampton (Oct.
29 to Jan. 7, 2001).
</P>
<P>
   ``The period covered in the show, the 1880s to 1915, represents
the beginning of the consumer society,'' said Joanna Gernstein
London, the curator of the exhibition. ``The public expected to
participate, even if it just meant watching.''
</P>
<P>
   The story of flight as depicted in these posters is frequently
meant to attract viewers, if not as fliers, then as buyers of
whatever the poster is selling. The message was sometimes obvious,
as in the earliest poster in the show, a French image from the
1880's, ``Ballon Captif,'' which depicts a tethered hot-air balloon
in a fairground. The image invites the public to inspect the
balloon and to float aloft in it; apparently the ploy worked,
increasing attendance at the fair.
</P>
<P>
   Posters in the early 20th century continued to show balloons,
but by then they were seen as upstaged by dirigibles and airplanes,
which were depicted soaring or floating past the spires of Gothic
cathedrals. With daredevil pilots demonstrating flying as a sport
and entertainment, poster artists depicted flight as a fantasy,
even a comedy. These conceptions would soon be replaced by darker
images, of airplanes as tools of war.
</P>
<P>
   In 1909, poster artists usually opted for the lighthearted
approach. In a Belle Epoque poster announcing an air meet in Monte
Carlo, a dapper aviator in cap, ascot, boutonniere and yellow
gloves is shown at the stick of an open-air Wright biplane, a lady
in red at his side looking as if she is flying through the air on
an earthbound swing, not in an aircraft high above the Riviera.
</P>
<P>
   That year, too, the Frenchman Louis Bleriot crossed the English
Channel in a monoplane in the first such powered flight, going from
Calais to Dover in a record 37 minutes, which made him a national
hero. The victory was advertised in a powerful poster by Gabriel
Borel, a Paris producer of the acetylene lamps on Bleriot's
aircraft, which is shown flying at night, its lamps illuminating
the white cliffs of Dover just before landing.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1913 poster, the mood quickens in a depiction of the French
pilot Adolphe Pegoud making aviation history by flying upside-down
and by doing an aerial somersault over a racetrack in Hanover,
Germany. Onlookers feared that his blood-tingling exhibition would
be suicidal, but the thrilling feats he performed were later cited
as the precursors of the combat tactics pilots mastered during
World War I.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition's debt to two passionate collectors of
aeronautical material is clearly stated in the wall labels. The
rich cultural history used in the descriptions of the posters was
the work of Henry Serrano Villard, an American diplomat and writer
from a prominent New York publishing family. He was introduced to
aviation at age 9, when he was taken up in a plane during an air
tournament at Belmont Park on Long Island. Two years later, when he
moved with his family to France, he joined the Societe Generale
Aeronautique and attended many of the meets celebrated in these
posters, and he collected aeronautical memorabilia for the rest of
his life. Villard, who became the first American ambassador to
Libya in 1952 and later was ambassador to Senegal and Mauritania,
retired from foreign service in 1961 and wrote several books on
early aviation. The last of these bears the same title as the show,
and was published by Kales Press ($40) of Carlsbad, Calif., after
his death at 95 in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The posters in the exhibition and the book were assembled by
Willis M. Allen Jr., who showed a bit of daring when he ignored a
warning printed on the Monte Carlo poster, a piece of ephemera that
was never meant to be owned privately. It says, ``Anyone found in
possession of this poster will be prosecuted.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-27-00 2011EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
