<DOCNO> NYT20000627.0317 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6560 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-BOS &LR;      06-27 0705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UPSTART IS FINISHED OFF QUICKLY AT WIMBLEDON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The bird fluttered around Centre Court, briefly
interrupting the proceedings at the All England Lawn Tennis &AMP;
Croquet Club, before Lleyton Hewitt contemptuously shooed it away.
He didn't need any help. He'd already mastered the role of pigeon.
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, Hewitt's shocking 6-3, 6-2, 7-5 first-round
Wimbledon caging by 56th-ranked Jan-Michael Gambill Tuesday offered
evidence that Pete Sampras's imprimatur may be a tad premature.
</P>
<P>
   Tennis's current ruler had anointed the 19-year-old Australian
``the future of the game'' _ and that was even before Hewitt
toppled Sampras in the Stella Artois final at Queen's Club 10 days
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday Gambill turned him into a thing of the past, at least
for the present.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just had one of those days, really,'' said Hewitt, who
couldn't even take consolation in the victory of his girlfriend Kim
Clijsters over Nathalie Tauziat earlier in the afternoon. ``I
struggled off the ground the whole day. The court I found very
slippery out there. It didn't suit my game at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, there was a lot more than landscaping to it. Sampras
proclaimed that Hewitt, ranked seventh in the world and seeded
seventh here, has all the tools to dominate tennis in a very short
while. Tuesday he brought equipment that was ideal for surviving
for a very short while. All the weapons were working in his
self-destructive arsenal: errant serving (eight double faults, 38
percent accuracy), an inability to sustain firepower in a
two-fisted baseline slugfest (two volley winners), and a lingering
lethargy that seemed to overtake him for the first two sets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wasn't much to get pumped up about,'' Hewitt said. ``I tried
as much as possible out there. I really had very little chances,
particularly on his serve the first two sets. He just served bombs
the whole time.''
</P>
<P>
   Funny, that's supposed to be one of Hewitt's calling cards. But
he was the victim against Gambill, who nailed 15 aces, including
seven in the third set, when Hewitt finally seemed to be emerging
from his ennui.
</P>
<P>
   He appeared energized when he broke Gambill for a 3-1 lead,
pumping his fist and exhorting himself with a cry of ``Come on!''
</P>
<P>
   He did, for a spell. But after building a 5-2 lead _ and visions
of a valorous comeback _ he collapsed, failing to win another game.
Gambill weathered six deuces on his next serve to stay alive at
5-3, broke Hewitt to 5-4, broke his spirit to go up, 6-5, and put
him away on the first match point, a serve that Hewitt plopped into
the net, along with his reputation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole time, I still felt that I had a chance at winning,''
said Hewitt. ``I never doubted myself until it was over today.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps this defeat was in the making well before it started,
with the great expectations that have become as much part of Hewitt
as his bushy ponytail that matches Clijsters's hairstyle. Maybe
Sampras and his fellow Hewitt worshipers were the real culprits.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, not at all,'' Hewitt said. ``I think I'm used to that,
living in Australia, playing the Australian summer, doing very well
in the Australian summer every year.''
</P>
<P>
   He'll have extra time to prepare for the Australian summer this
year, while Gambill basks in the gloomy London weather.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think playing a match like that is very helpful to me
confidencewise,'' said Gambill.
</P>
<P>
   The 23-year-old Spokane, Wash., native is in fact no slouch, as
evidenced by his victory over Hewitt in the Scottsdale, Ariz.,
final last year. Hewitt got some revenge with a win over Gambill in
Miami this season, but he was trumped with a vengeance Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had some big results every year,'' said Gambill, ``but
not enough of them to really create and confirm the interest.''
</P>
<P>
   That's exactly what Hewitt's destiny is presumed to be. But
perhaps he has a better perspective of his place in the
constellation than do his admirers. Asked yet again about his
potential, he pointed out, ``I haven't made a quarterfinal of a
Grand Slam.''
</P>
<P>
   He would have settled for the second round of this one.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
