<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6566 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-STAR-TV-$ADV02-2TAKES     06-27 1195
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAR-TV-$ADV02-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MODEST CREATOR   WITH A GIFT FOR GLOSS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Md., Calif.)  (For release Sunday, July 2)  
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It is both a Hollywood legend and a fact that the
people who create glamorous films and television shows are often
not especially glamorous. Take the case of Darren Star: the son of
an orthodontist from Potomac, Md., a boy who used his bar mitzvah
money to buy a subscription to Variety, a quiet, friendly and
modest 38-year-old writer and producer who eschews fancy clothes,
clubs and trappings and somehow seems unlikely to have been
involved in the hugely successful and unmistakably flashy shows
``Beverly Hills 90210'' and ``Melrose Place,'' as well as HBO's
acclaimed ``Sex and the City.''
</P>
<P>
   Star, who also helped create two new television shows for the
fall, the WB network's ``Grosse Pointe'' and Fox's ``The Street,''
admitted that his shows are tinged with glamour and fantasy. ``I
enjoy bringing a slightly larger-than-life quality to characters in
fairly ordinary circumstances,'' he said while eating scrambled
eggs in a Santa Monica hotel coffee shop overlooking the beach.
``There's a gloss that draws in audiences and allows me to tell the
stories I want to tell.''
</P>
<P>
   He shrugged. ``It also happens to be the train I'm on,'' he
said. ``And, for the moment, there's no reason to get off it.''
</P>
<P>
   Why should he? Star is not only one of the most successful
writer-producers on television, but also one of the most prolific.
By the fall season, he will have three shows on the air: ``Sex and
the City,'' the hit comedy series that seeks to offer a candid view
of sex and relationships among some (what else?) beautiful women in
Manhattan; ``The Street,'' about successful and, yes, handsome
young turks on Wall Street; and the suddenly controversial ``Grosse
Pointe,'' which is Star's tongue-in-cheek look at a teen-age
television soap opera that's very much like ``Beverly Hills
90210.'' The fact that the soap opera actors are not only depicted
as shallow and silly but actually resemble some real-life
counterparts has already stirred problems for Star.
</P>
<P>
   The powerful television producer Aaron Spelling, who has a
complicated relationship with Star as both a mentor and a
competitor, has complained that his daughter, Tori Spelling, is
being lampooned on ``Grosse Pointe.'' Spelling was one of the stars
of ``Beverly Hills 90210''; a ``Grosse Pointe'' character, Marcy
Sternfeld, is an actress with family connections that got her a job
on the fictional series. Star said that, under pressure from WB, he
had changed the hair color of the actress, Lindsay Sloane, who
plays Marcy Sternfeld, and deleted a scene in which the actress
becomes sick because of an eating disorder.
</P>
<P>
   But Star said he has fought Spelling's efforts to influence the
network, particularly in regard to the show's nepotism plot line.
``This is not Tori Spelling,'' Star insisted. ``I'm not out to hurt
anyone's feelings. I've made some minor changes.'' But Star said
that he would seriously object were the WB network to ask him for
weekly changes in the character. Spelling did not respond to a
request for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Star has plainly made an effort to move beyond the teen and
20-something genre that, in many ways, he helped create. After
moving to New York in 1995 _ he still has a home in the Hollywood
Hills _ Star created ``Central Park West'' for CBS. The glitzy soap
opera about rich and beautiful people in New York, which starred,
among others, Mariel Hemingway, Raquel Welch, Ron Liebman and
Lauren Hutton, flopped. Star said he believed the series failed
because CBS, with its older audience, was the wrong network for a
show initially designed for young professionals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was looking for a lover of one of the younger women on the
show and I got this call from CBS saying that they really wanted
Gerald McRaney, and I realized the show was really going to have to
change,'' Star said. McRaney, in his 50s, had been the star of the
CBS series ``Major Dad.''
</P>
<P>
   At that point Star optioned the book ``Sex and the City,'' by
Candace Bushnell. ``I did this show because I was sick of network
television,'' Star said. ``I did `Melrose Place,' which had a huge
audience but no respect. I wanted respect. I couldn't really tell
stories in my voice. I couldn't really tell stories that I, myself,
wanted to see. And I felt the idea of a comedy about sex was
something I really wanted to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Star, who produces the show with Michael Patrick King, brushed
aside the criticism that its sex-obsessed women are perhaps too
one-dimensional and verge on caricature. ```Seinfeld' was
sex-obsessed too _ that show wasn't about his job,'' Star said.
``Most shows about single guys are about sex too. The difference is
we don't veil it under double-entendres here, because it's HBO.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Albrecht, HBO's president of original programming, said
that Star's success on television rested in part on his ability to
deal with real issues: high-schoolers coping with teen-age angst
and sexuality (``Beverly Hills 90210''), young people struggling to
forge careers (``Melrose Place'') and successful women in their
30's searching for happiness (``Sex and the City''). But Star then
places his characters in a glamorous _ sometimes improbably
glamorous _ setting.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got relatability and you've got fantasy, and this makes
people want to watch these shows week after week,'' Albrecht said.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Grushow, chairman of the Fox Television Entertainment
Group, has known Star since the early days of ``Beverly Hills
90210.'' ``Darren has an uncanny ability to understand what the
public wants,'' he said. ``He has his finger on the pulse of what's
going on, what people are talking about. And he captures it and
executes it brilliantly.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Sarah Jessica Parker, who plays the New York sex columnist who
narrates ``Sex and the City,'' and is also a producer of the
series, said that Star's writing was deceptive. ``It's often
appropriately glib and surfacey, the characters are colorful, but
then in the last three minutes he can turn the knife and kill
you,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Often the shows end on an unexpectedly poignant or believable
note, Parker said. As a result, she said, women relate to it and
men are engaged by it. ``When I walk down the street what people
most often say to me is, `This is my life,''' she said. ``They
relate to the hunt, the journey, the disappointments, the hurts,
the ridiculousness, the whims and the vulgarity of looking for
love. It just resonates with people.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Apart from indulging his taste for fancy restaurants in New York
and Los Angeles, Star, who is single, lives his life almost
entirely around his work. Several years ago he met with Madonna to
discuss a film project. ``She invited me to attend the Independent
Film Awards in New York,'' he said. ``It was something I was
excited to do. I'm a huge Madonna fan. But I was working. I showed
up an hour late. She wasn't happy.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.) (MORE)  &QL; 
 &QL; 
</P>
<P>
   Growing up in Potomac, a suburb of Washington, Star was taking
screenwriting courses at American University while still in high
school. At the University of Southern California and UCLA, he
majored in creative writing. After graduation, he worked as a
waiter at a Hamburger Hamlet and as an assistant to a publicist. At
24, he sold his first screenplay, ``Doin' Time on Planet Earth.''
The movie quickly disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, he was living in an apartment complex in West
Hollywood (the inspiration for ``Melrose Place''), and his
unproduced screenplays soon won him a reputation as someone who
could write dialogue for teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Diller, then chairman of Fox, came up with the idea of a
television series set in a high school. Spelling was brought in to
produce, and Star, who was 28, was asked to write the pilot. The
series began in the fall of 1990, and ended in May after 10 years.
Star's involvement with the show lasted five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, the kids were beautiful and rich, for the most part, but
that wasn't the reason for the success of the show,'' he said. ``It
was about the power of friendship. And there was a universal appeal
for that show, I think, because parents did not come in and solve
their kids' problems, as in most shows about teen-agers. This was a
show in which kids solved their own problems. And that appealed to
a lot of people because that's what adolescence is about.''
</P>
<P>
   Star said that although he is often offered movie jobs, the fast
pace of television suits him better and, he said, so does New York:
``L.A. was too insular for me, too myopic, and I really love New
York. I'm doing the Wall Street show because I was surrounded by
Wall Street culture. And even I, like everyone else, was starting
to watch CNBC. And then I got a call from my broker in New York, a
guy I had never actually met. And I met him for drinks. And I
expected, like, my father to walk into the room. And this
26-year-old kid came in.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I'm like, `This is the guy I'm trusting all my money
with?' It was scary. And then it got me thinking. I began thinking
that this could make a very interesting show.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
