<DOCNO> NYT20000627.0328 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 20:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6571 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-INDIAN-PRINCESS-ART-$     06-27 1345
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIAN-PRINCESS-ART-$ADV02-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE THREE FACES, ALL OF THEM FEMALE, OF LIBERTY 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, July 2) 
 By SARAH BAYLISS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Long before the Greco-Roman specter of Lady Liberty arrived in
New York Harbor in 1886, another woman symbolized the United
States, one long forgotten by most Americans. Sometimes known as
L'Amerique, or the Indian Princess, she was a Native American
figure who first appeared on maps in the 16th century. Wearing a
feather headdress, accompanied by a parrot and perched on an
alligatorlike reptile, she represented continental America
alongside female allegories of Europe, Asia and Africa.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's big, naked and exotic, portrayed with the plants and
animals of the New World,'' said Rayna Green, director of the
American Indian Program at the Smithsonian Institution's National
Museum of American History. ``She is America, which is rich,
powerful, opulent and perilous.''
</P>
<P>
   This early character, along with Liberty and the lesser-known
Columbia, is the subject of ``The Changing Face of Liberty: Female
Allegories of America,'' at the New-York Historical Society through
Sept. 3. Featuring political cartoons, maps, prints and advertising
ephemera by Paul Revere, Jean-Honore Fragonard, Nathan Currier and
others, the small but illuminating show reveals how these figures
have symbolized this country for more than four centuries.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition comes at a time when two real native women have
seen renewed popularity. Sacagawea, the Shoshone woman who guided
Lewis and Clark, appears on the widely promoted new dollar coin, a
billion of which will be issued by the end of the year. And Disney
recently adapted the story of Pocahontas, the 17th-century
Algonquin who saved the British adventurer John Smith from
execution by her father, Powhatan, in a highly successful animated
film. Like these real heroines, the early Indian figure symbolized
bravery and compassion in the New World _ even if her actions might
have put her in opposition to her own people.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the earliest cartoons of this persona were by British
caricaturists who supported the colonies' struggle for
independence. During Revolutionary times, she was decked out in
feathers, but she was slimmer than the cartographers' figure.
Wielding a bow and arrow, she often appeared as Britannia's
rebellious daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Able Doctor, or America Swallowing the Bitter Draught,'' a
violent 1774 engraving first published in London Magazine after the
Boston Tea Party, portrays a native woman, stripped to the waist,
being pinned to the ground by wigged Britons. (Paul Revere copied
this picture for publication in America.) The figure of Britannia
looks away in despair as one man forces the supine princess to
swallow the Boston Port Bill, in the form of tea, which she
defiantly spits back in his face. Another man, Lord Sandwich, peers
up her skirt. (The peeping Lord Sandwich ``was known to be an old
lech,'' said the exhibition's curator, Ann Weissmann.)
</P>
<P>
   Most images depict the native woman more favorably. In ``Liberty
Triumphant; or the Downfall of Oppression,'' a 1774 engraving by an
American caricaturist, she leads the colonists, who are wearing
feathered headgear and armed with bows and arrows, into battle with
the British. The devil accompanies the British Army, while the
goddess of liberty, holding a liberty pole and cap _ the latter
adapted from the Phrygian cap, worn by freed Roman slaves to cover
their shaved heads _ hovers over the Americans. As with other
broadsides, illustrations like these, with balloon texts, expressed
editorial views for those who could read and those who could not.
</P>
<P>
   The Indian Princess started looking more Anglo-European as the
colonies matured. ``She becomes white and neo-classical,'' Green
said. ``She wears the white robes that symbolize innocence and the
democracy of Greece and Rome, which people are talking about in
colonial rhetoric. She might have Columbia's Wonder Woman crown of
stars or Liberty's cap.'' In the exhibition, Charles Lemire Sr.'s
19th-century etching ``L'Amerique'' shows the white-robed woman
looking distinctly like Roman aristocracy. As Green sees it,
``ultimately, we get the Princess Pocahontas'' as the figure
evolves into a beauty-queen persona not unlike Disney's
interpretation of the Algonquin girl. ``She is the idealized
princess who saves America from her bad brothers and fathers,''
Green said.
</P>
<P>
   If the native figure represented America's rebellious spirit,
the goddesslike Columbia, with her shield and starred tiara,
signified American strength after the Revolution, with the threat
of Britain still in recent memory. ``The Indian Princess started
disappearing because America wanted a more dominant image _ more
powerful, aggressive,'' Weissmann said. ``Columbia represented the
mature, stable, independent colonies. She was the older daughter of
Britannia, while the Indian Princess was the younger one.''
</P>
<P>
   Columbia and Liberty are often interchangeable star-spangled
figures in the exhibition's 19th- and early 20th-century political
cartoons, posters and advertisements. John Goater's 1861
wood-engraved cartoon ``Little Bo-Peep and her Foolish Sheep''
shows a worried Liberty posing as a shepherdess and representing
the Union, watching as her sheep, standing for the seceding
Southern states, run away. Columbia is the more warriorlike.
``Columbia is usually armed,'' says Wendy Shadwell, curator of
prints at the New-York Historical Society. By contrast, the Statue
of Liberty ``just stands there with a tablet and a lamp.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Frederic-Auguste Bartholdi's Roman-size monument, with
her spiked crown and book of law, is closer to European versions of
Liberty than American ones, and has ``no relation'' to Columbia or
the Indian figure, said Jeff Dosik, a librarian at the Statue of
Liberty National Monument. A gift to the United States from France,
the continental Liberty symbolized ``the Enlightenment ideas that
our founding fathers borrowed from French philosophers _ about
political freedom for all mankind, and human rights for all men,''
Dosik said.
</P>
<P>
   Caricaturists quickly adopted the statue as the prevailing image
of America, even before it arrived in New York. Thomas Nast's 1881
engraving for Harper's Weekly, ``A Warning Light,'' made when a
rash of deadly epidemics seized New York, shows a skeletal Liberty
with an upside-down torch and the caption ``Leave All Hope Ye That
Enter Here.'' A reproduction of an 1885 wood engraving by Frederick
Burr Opper, published in Puck, parodies the way in which the statue
was exploited by advertisers even before it took up residence:
wearing sunglasses, she's plastered with ads urging people to
``smoke `suredeath' cigarettes'' and buy from ``G.O.G.G.L.E.S.
opticians.''
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition's contemporary section includes some patriotic
knickknacks that, while amusing, don't shed a lot of new light on
these figures.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most revealing and contradictory symbol of America
is Thomas Crawford's 1863 Statue of Freedom atop the U.S. capitol,
illustrated in the exhibition by a modern copy of an 1867 engraving
Crawford made for Harper's Weekly. Erected during the Civil War
under Abraham Lincoln's supervision, the sculpture is a hybrid of
Liberty, Columbia and the Indian Princess. The original design
featured the liberty cap, but Jefferson Davis, then the secretary
of war and later the president of the Confederacy, insisted that
the headpiece _ and its associations with emancipation _ be
replaced. Crawford revised it to the current starry helmet and
feathers. Philip Reed, a slave, supervised the statue's casting.
</P>
<P>
   When the Statue of Freedom was taken down to ground level for
cleaning a few years ago, Green recalled, ``she was repeatedly
visited by Indians who came to pay her homage.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was quite interesting to see this pilgrimage,'' she said.
``Indians recognized her as their girl. It would cause a revolution
if people remembered that Freedom was originally an Indian woman.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
