</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRANCE-HUMAN-RIGHTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRANCE WITHHOLDS SUPPORT FOR DOCUMENT AT DEMOCRACY FORUM 
</HEADLINE>
   By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WARSAW, Poland _ To ensure that its disapproval of the
conference on democracy organized here by the United States was
officially noticed, France declined Tuesday to accept the document
summarizing the principles and signed by other participants.
</P>
<P>
   In a tart one-page statement, the French government said the
document, agreed to by more than 100 nations, should not be
interpreted as a ``political commitment'' for the participants to
act as a group to further democracy.
</P>
<P>
   The disavowal came one day after the French foreign minister,
Hubert Vedrine, discussed his philosophy about democracy with
American reporters and suggested it was misguided to believe that
democracy could be imposed.
</P>
<P>
   Democracy, Vedrine said, was most often a slow-growing process
that grew from within a country.
</P>
<P>
   Elaborating on Vedrine's discussion, the statement issued
Tuesday by the French Embassy said that spreading democracy was
``not a matter which allows sweeping generalizations,'' adding that
``The specifics of each case should be taken into consideration.''
</P>
<P>
   The statement threw faint praise on the exercise, a gathering of
foreign ministers and some well-known human rights figures
orchestrated by the U.S. State Department. The statement said the
conference had provided a ``good exchange of ideas.'' But the
French insisted that the meeting should be regarded as the
``beginning for such an exchange, not as a program for action.''
</P>
<P>
   For France, the conference presented a perfect opportunity to
take a shot at the United States, whom Vedrine has called the
``hyper-power.''
</P>
<P>
   In terms of democratic values, France has taken a much tougher
line than the Clinton administration against Moscow's actions in
Chechyna and criticized the new Russian president, Vladimir Putin,
for his pursuit of the war there.
</P>
<P>
   For their more aggressive stance on Chechyna, the French have
been scorned by Putin, who made his first European visit to Germany
earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. delegation, headed by Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright, was taken aback by the French objections.
</P>
<P>
   By taking exception to the democracy conference, Vedrine,
purposely or not, was taking aim at the heart of what Albright
possibly hopes will be a large part of her legacy. The conference
was conceived by one of Albright's senior aides, Morton Halperin,
as a way of highlighting the spread of democracy since the end of
of the Cold War and enshrining the United States as its leading
light.
</P>
<P>
   A few hours after Vedrine spoke to American reporters on Monday,
the American Embassy called the French Embassy asking for a
transcript of the foreign minister's remarks. Since Vedrine had
spoken informally, a transcript was not available, a French
official said.
</P>
<P>
   State Department officials made clear in the days before the
conference that the countries represented here had made their
attendance contingent on accepting the democracy document, known as
the Warsaw Declaration.
</P>
<P>
   The wording of the declaration was circulated to invitees well
before the meeting, they said.
</P>
<P>
   The document says that democratic governments may vary in many
respects but are the same in important respects. The common aspects
include free and fair elections, citizens are treated equally under
the law, respect for religion and the press, and freedom from
torture and arbitrary arrest. The document notes that opposition
political parties and trade unions have the right to organize.
</P>
<P>
   France's official disavowal of the declaration was organized
quietly between the French government and the Poles, who were the
hosts. Some days ago, the French government asked the Polish
foreign minister, Bronislaw Geremek, not to include France among
the countries who agreed to the declaration, a French official
said.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, at the final session at the Polish Parliament,
delegates found a piece of paper on their desks naming the
countries that had signed the Warsaw Declaration.
</P>
<P>
   France was conspicuously absent.
</P>
<P>
   State Department officials said the French podition was based on
a misconception. The conference, they said, was not intended to
start a movement to convert nondemocratic countries, rather to
strengthen democratic practices where they exist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
