<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLDLY-INVEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG ON PEAKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Lewis David Gersh is chief executive of Worldly Information
Network, an online financial information company, and
worldlyinvestor.com; this was written with DAVID LEONHARDT.) 
 By LEWIS DAVID GERSH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After high school, I moved to Santa Cruz, Calif., to go to
college. This was before the big earthquake, and before the city
was rebuilt, and Santa Cruz had a very dark underside.
</P>
<P>
   I got into racing motorcycles there, which will be news to my
mother when she reads this. In my sophomore year, I moved to San
Diego and promptly got into a motorcycle accident down there.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors told me I had two choices. I could ride a bike every day
to rebuild my knee, or I could go under the knife. That was an easy
decision. At the time, I was doing the typical college partying. I
was smoking and was pretty overweight. But my mom said no to the
surgery. She said, ``We're sending out the old Schwinn from the
garage in New Jersey.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't funny at the time.
</P>
<P>
   So, I just started riding it every day. I didn't realize how far
I was going, and I slowly built up strength. My folks got me a
better bike because I decided to try doing some racing.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, there was a mini-triathlon down in Mexico, and I
gave it a shot. Within a few months, I wanted to do a half-Ironman
triathlon: 1.2 miles swimming, 56 miles biking and 13 miles
running. So, I went to a meeting of the triathlon club at school,
San Diego State University. I learned later that people were
laughing at me.
</P>
<P>
   They said, ``A guy who smokes is going to do a half-Ironman?''
</P>
<P>
   It turned out to be 109 degrees on the day of the event _ they
were handing out painters' hats full of ice _ but I finished, and
my time was even decent.
</P>
<P>
   After that, I set my sights on a full Ironman.
</P>
<P>
   I was hooked.
</P>
<P>
   After college, I moved to New Zealand and then Australia to
train and compete. One day, we were all racing down a mountain, and
the next thing I knew we were all sprawled out on the pavement. I
had to fly back to New York for knee surgery. I remember looking at
myself in a mirror before I left and thinking, ``I'll never be in
as good shape as I am right now.''
</P>
<P>
   It was an amazing experience to know you have just peaked, to
know you may never be that happy again. I had had that feeling once
before, after my junior year of high school, when I'd had so much
fun with my friends and my girlfriend and my classes. But it was so
beautiful in Australia, and I was so happy. I'd gotten to a higher
peak.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, I couldn't really train.
</P>
<P>
   I interviewed with personnel agencies for a few jobs _ and got a
few dates with the women at the agencies but didn't get any jobs.
</P>
<P>
   I ended up managing a bar on the Upper West Side and then went
to law school. Afterward, I came back to New York, ran two
companies and eventually founded worldlyinvestor.com, a Web site
that offers international investment advice.
</P>
<P>
   Even when I was in Australia training, I thought I would move
back to New York at some point. I figured I'd gain back some of the
weight I lost and end up smoking again. And, yeah, I've gained back
some weight, and I smoke, occasionally, at parties. But for me,
it's a consequence of being in the 24/7 Internet life.
</P>
<P>
   What I'm doing comes with a lot more stress than I imagined, but
I can honestly say I'm having a blast. There are so many twists and
turns. But I have not yet looked in the mirror and thought, ``This
is not going to get any better.'' I don't think it's at a peak yet
at all.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
