<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 20:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6574 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-BKN-DRAFT-MIHM-COX     06-27 1185
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-DRAFT-MIHM-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NBA's Robinson saw star quality in Texas' Mihm
 &HT;    By Randy Riggs
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas - Before his freshman year at the University of
Texas, Chris Mihm got an opportunity not afforded most young
basketball players.
</P>
<P>
   The recent graduate of Westlake High School spent two days in
San Antonio in July 1997, working out with David Robinson. When
they were done, by way of farewell, the San Antonio Spurs' all-star
center left Mihm with a few words that, three years later, are
prophetic.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe he was just being polite or maybe he meant it, but
Robinson told the young 7-footer that he someday expected to see
him in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember David telling me that Chris impressed him on the
court and off the court,'' said Jeff Austin, the Washington, D.C.,
agent who represents both Mihm and Robinson. ``And that was three
years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever he meant, Robinson was right. Chris Mihm's time has
come.
</P>
<P>
   The Longhorns' first-ever Associated Press first-team
All-American, Mihm will hear his name called early in tonight's
National Basketball Association draft in Minneapolis. If he is one
of the top four picks _ a distinct possibility _he'll be chosen
higher than any UT player in history.
</P>
<P>
   It will be the latest milestone in the relatively brief
basketball career of the ``gentle giant'' who didn't make the
Westlake High School varsity until his junior season. But in five
short years of full-time basketball, Mihm, 20, has transformed
himself into one of the top players ever produced in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   ``A player can't judge his own legacy,'' Mihm said. ``That's for
others. I've just tried to be one of the best players in Texas
history and be recognized for that. But it's not up to me to make
that decision.''
</P>
<P>
   UT's basketball history isn't exactly full of players who
succeeded in the NBA. At the end of last season, no former
Longhorns played in the league. The school has produced only four
first-round picks.
</P>
<P>
   The highest to go was center LaSalle Thompson. Like Mihm,
Thompson left after his junior season, in 1982, in the aftermath of
Abe Lemons' controversial dismissal as coach. Thompson was taken by
the Kansas City Kings with the fifth pick.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson's 15-year NBA career as primarily a journeyman began
well before UT's other three first-rounders were taken _ and ended
after they were gone. Guards Travis Mays and Lance Blanks were
selected with the 14th and 26th picks of the 1990 draft, and guard
B.J. Tyler went with the 20th pick of the 1994 draft. None was in
the league for long _ Mays and Blanks lasted three years, Tyler
two.
</P>
<P>
   Mihm has all the physical tools required for a long professional
career, including key traits often overlooked by the casual fan.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got good footwork and great hands,'' said Rick Barnes,
who coached Mihm as a sophomore and junior at Texas. ``He's like a
vacuum with his hands, and that's important because great players
catch bad passes. He had his share of those, and he saved us a lot
of turnovers.''
</P>
<P>
   Mihm's athleticism comes from his parents, Gary and Nina Mihm,
who both played tennis at Marquette University.
</P>
<P>
   Mihm played basketball informally at an early age but was more
renowned for swimming and tennis. He was formidable in swimming _
``I was real good at the breaststroke and butterfly'' _ and earned
a state ranking for his age group in tennis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd have loved to be his doubles partner,'' said Westlake High
basketball coach Clifton McNeely. ``Can you imagine him at the
net?''
</P>
<P>
   McNeely got the opportunity to have Mihm around a different net.
McNeely arrived at Westlake before Mihm's junior year, the time
Mihm decided to concentrate on basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved all sports growing up. Tennis, swimming, baseball,
soccer, whatever,'' Mihm said. ``I've always believed in setting
goals, and my goal in basketball was to be a high school
All-American. I knew if that was going to happen, I had to dedicate
myself to basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Mihm had been playing basketball long before he began
sprouting toward seven feet. Buried in a box somewhere, former
Longhorns assistant coach Vic Trilli has a photograph of a young
Mihm flanked by UT basketball players Locksley Collie and Guillermo
Myers at a 1991 UT summer camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was probably about 6-2 then,'' said Trilli, now head coach
at the University of North Texas. ``But he was mature in ways most
kids are not at that age. He just seemed to have an idea of what he
wanted to do with his life, even then.''
</P>
<P>
   Mihm and his Westlake teammate, Luke Axtell, committed to the
Longhorns before their junior seasons in high school. Axtell, who
transferred to Kansas two years ago, was the more highly regarded
prospect at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Even then, despite his lack of experience, Mihm caught flak from
critics who didn't believe he was posting the kinds of numbers that
a big man should produce. Then as now, his intensity, desire and
passion for the game were questioned, and Trilli has the proof in
the boxes still unpacked from his move to Denton two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still have letters around here somewhere from fans saying
we'd made a big mistake in signing him at UT,'' Trilli said.
``People said he was soft and questioned his toughness, but I don't
know how they could say that. Nobody knew. He was just starting to
develop.''
</P>
<P>
   The questions about his toughness and dedication to basketball
continue to dog him, despite the fact that Mihm is the first person
in UT history to record more than 1,100 points, 800 rebounds and
200 blocks for his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``It amuses me. I take some hits for that, but I've grown
accustomed to it,'' he said. ``Playing a lot of individual sports
taught me to have an inner fire and drive from within. You're not
going to be yelling in a pool or on a tennis court.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hear so much that I don't love the game that it makes me
laugh. If I didn't love it, I wouldn't be doing it. People who
haven't been around me and haven't seen me practice don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Wendlandt does, because he has. A Texas forward in the
early 1980s, the Austin businessman is also a Westlake High product
and longtime friend of Mihm. Wendlandt coached Mihm's peewee
basketball teams in the Western Hills Youth Association when Mihm
was in elementary school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm telling you right now, if you think Chris is soft, go
guard him for about 30 minutes and then tell me that,'' said
Wendlandt. ``He'll beat your butt and punish you physically. You'll
go away thinking you've been in a 20-round boxing match. I've been
guarding the kid for 10 years. I know.''
</P>
<P>
   To hear Mihm talk, he's eager to begin proving himself, all over
again, at the ultimate level of his profession.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love competition. And the competitiveness of basketball is
something that really appeals to me,'' he said. ``Growing up in
sports, I know what it takes. I think my background has given me an
inner drive to be good.''
</P>
<P>
   So David Robinson noticed, three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
