<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 20:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6577 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-SCI-AFRICA-AIDS-ART-N     06-27 1228
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-AFRICA-AIDS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. REPORT PAINTS DEVASTATING PICTURE OF AIDS EPIDEMIC IN AFRICA 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients. Photo _
NYT 2 _ is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers can
purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By LAWRENCE K. ALTMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   At least half of all 15-year-olds in the African countries worst
affected by AIDS will die of the disease even if the infection
rates drop substantially in the next few years, the United Nations
reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   And if rates remain high, the odds are that more than two-thirds
of the 15-year-olds will die from AIDS in countries like Botswana,
according to projections from UNAIDS, a joint U.N. program based in
Geneva, Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world has never before experienced death rates of this
magnitude among young adults of both sexes across all social
strata,'' UNAIDS said in a report it released ahead of the 13th
International AIDS Conference, which begins on July 9 in Durban,
South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   It is UNAIDS' second comprehensive report on the global epidemic
of AIDS. The first report was published two years ago in
conjunction with the last international AIDS conference, in Geneva.
That report painted a bleak picture of AIDS, showing one in four
people were infected in some parts of Africa.
</P>
<P>
   The new report brings this picture into a sharper, grimmer
focus. More new infections are occurring through heterosexual sex
simply because the chances of an uninfected individual encountering
an infected partner have become higher, UNAIDS said.
</P>
<P>
   But the report contained glimmers of hope. It said that
infection rates have fallen in a small number of places, showing
that health officials are not powerless in stopping the epidemic.
</P>
<P>
   In the new report, UNAIDS calculated for the first time the
impact of AIDS on young people, the very individuals who are most
often infected by HIV, the virus that causes AIDS. HIV, which has
been spread primarily through heterosexual sex in Africa, is wiping
out many households, devastating national economies and killing off
so many teachers that it is undermining the delivery of basic
education, Dr. Peter Piot, the head of UNAIDS, said in a telephone
news conference from Geneva.
</P>
<P>
   But most people with HIV do not know they are infected because
testing for the virus is not widely available in Africa, said Dr.
Noerine Kaleeba, a Ugandan who is a UNAIDS official.
</P>
<P>
   HIV infection rates are more than five times as high among
African teen-age girls as among teen-age boys, largely because
young girls have sex with older men, who are more likely to be
infected. Also, girls are much more likely to be infected during
vaginal intercourse with an infected partner than are the boys. As
men age, their infection rate approaches that of women.
</P>
<P>
   The infection rates in sub-Saharan Africa are far greater than
any expert or computer model had predicted 10 years ago, Piot said.
</P>
<P>
   The result is an unusual demographic pattern in which a
country's population includes as many 60-year-olds as 40-year-olds
instead of the usual pattern of fewer older people. The U.S. Census
Bureau predicts that in Botswana, there will be more adults in
their 60s and 70s than in their 40s and 50s, assuming that H.I.V.
infection rates do not change.
</P>
<P>
   The ferocity of the AIDS epidemic in Africa is such that its
ravages thus far will seem minor compared with what lies ahead
unless affected countries make AIDS control programs a national
priority and other nations contribute much more money for
prevention and care, UNAIDS said.
</P>
<P>
   The estimated $300 million in international support this year
pales compared with the $2 billion needed each year in sub-Saharan
Africa alone, Piot said. He also said, ``It's time we make the
connection between debt relief and epidemic relief, because one
reason that many developing countries cannot invest enough in AIDS
prevention is that they have to pay such a high proportion of their
national budget'' for debt.
</P>
<P>
   On an encouraging note, Piot said that 19 years of experience
with AIDS has generated important insights into how to reduce the
impact of the AIDS epidemic. More young people are delaying first
sexual intercourse, decreasing the number of partners and using
condoms more often, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Uganda has dropped off the list of the top 16 infected countries
because its government, which was the first in Africa to recognize
the danger of AIDS to national development, has promoted broader
education and use of such measures to lower its infection rate to 8
percent, from 14 percent in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Zambia may follow Uganda's lead. Its infection rates have fallen
in recent years in its capital, Lusaka, where far fewer young women
were having sex before marriage in 1996 than in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Senegal has stabilized its HIV infection rate at less than 2
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Protecting another generation of young people from premature
illness and death is the greatest leadership challenge for many
countries. That requires a nationally driven agenda ``with the
persistent engagement of the highest levels of government,'' Piot
said. Although more countries are showing such political will, it
is lacking in many others, he said.
</P>
<P>
   While the HIV rate has stabilized in the United States and other
developed countries at a fraction of 1 percent, it exceeds 10
percent in 16 African countries. Among developed countries,
Portugal's rate of 0.7 percent and the United States' rate of 0.6
percent are the highest, said Dr. Bernhard Schwartlander, a
principal author of the UNAIDS report.
</P>
<P>
   In virtually any country where 15 percent or more of all adults
are currently infected with HIV, at least 35 percent of
15-year-olds will eventually die of AIDS, UNAIDS said.
</P>
<P>
   The 16 African countries are: Botswana (35.8 percent), Swaziland
(25.25 percent), Zimbabwe (25.06 percent), Lesotho (23.57 percent),
Zambia (19.95 percent), South Africa (19.94 percent), Namibia
(19.54 percent), Malawi (15.96 percent), Kenya (13.95 percent),
Central African Republic (13.84 percent), Mozambique (13.2
percent), Djibouti (11.75 percent), Burundi (11.32 percent), Rwanda
(11.21 percent), Ivory Coast (10.76 percent), and Ethiopia (10.63
percent).
</P>
<P>
   In South Africa, the country with the largest number of people
(4.2 million) living with HIV, the infection rate has jumped to
19.9 percent from 12.9 in the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   Infection rates are creeping up in West Africa. In addition to
Ivory Coast, which is 15th highest, Nigeria, the most populous
country in sub-Saharan Africa, has reached a 5 percent rate.
</P>
<P>
   Two countries in the Caribbean _ Haiti and the Bahamas _ have
worse epidemics than any other country outside of Africa. In Haiti,
more than 5 percent of adults are infected and in the Bahamas, the
rate is more than 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   AIDS has made inroads in Asia, but it is not clear whether rates
will explode to rival those in Africa and when that might occur,
UNAIDS said.
</P>
<P>
   In India, where only 7 adults in 1,000 are infected, 3.7 million
people were living with HIV at the beginning of this year. The
total number in India is second largest in the world, behind South
Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Since AIDS was first recognized in 1981, HIV has infected or
killed more than 53 million people around the world.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
