<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 20:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6578 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-DONLEAVY-GINGERMAN-NY     06-27 1285
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DONLEAVY-GINGERMAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE GINGERMAN,' THE CLASSIC WITH A PORNOGRAPHIC PEDIGREE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ireland, France)   By MEL GUSSOW   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It was on Thanksgiving Day in Dublin in 1949 that
J.P. Donleavy had the idea for the novel that would change his
life. He and his friends, many of them Americans studying at
Trinity College on the GI Bill, were leaving the school. They were
all headed in different directions, professionally as well as
geographically.
</P>
<P>
   As he recalled during a recent visit to New York from his home
in Ireland, he suddenly realized, ``This is all over: Trinity and
the world that we knew in Dublin,'' a world that he has described
as ``celebratory, boisterous and resolutely careless mayhem.'' He
decided to memorialize the high and rough times in print. At the
center was a fellow American, Gainor Stephen Crist, who became the
model for Sebastian Dangerfield, the title character in his novel,
``The Ginger Man.''
</P>
<P>
   In a later book, ``The History of the Ginger Man,'' Donleavy
called Crist ``a pagan sensualist,'' while making it clear that he
also always expressed moral values. His motto was, ``Do no evil.''
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, he has to be regarded as a saint _ as simple as that,''
Donleavy said. ``I'm hoping that the tourist board in Ireland will,
at some future date, say, `Saint Gainor Stephen Crist, guide to all
tourists in Ireland.'''
</P>
<P>
   When Maurice Girodias published ``The Ginger Man'' in Paris in
1955, adding it to his list of erotic books, it became a scandalous
event. But the novel was subsequently acclaimed, especially by
other writers. Dorothy Parker called it ``a rigadoon of rascality,
a bawled-out comic song of sex.'' Capturing the rebellious spirit
of its time, along with ``The Catcher in the Rye'' it was taken up
by students as a kind of monument to iconoclasm. Eventually it
became an international best seller. ``The Ginger Man'' has sold
more than 10 million copies and has never been out of print.
</P>
<P>
   Donleavy's play based on the novel has had numerous productions,
although the current revival at the Irish Arts Center, performed by
a company of actors from Dublin, is the first New York production
since it was done off Broadway in 1963. Donleavy, 74, was in New
York for the revival, one of his periodic returns to the city of
his birth.
</P>
<P>
   The perfect personification of a dignified country squire _ the
opposite of the pub-crawling young men in his book _ and wearing
his customary tweeds, he looked as if he had just come from a walk
in the Irish countryside. Since 1967 he has been an Irish citizen.
For almost 30 years he has lived on a 180-acre estate called
Levington Park in Mullingar, Ireland _ a working farm where he
raises cattle and also has a soccer field and an indoor swimming
pool.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, when the Modern Library named the 100 best novels
in the English language in the 20th century, ``The Ginger Man'' was
99th, just ahead of ``The Magnificent Ambersons'' by Booth
Tarkington. No. 1 was James Joyce's ``Ulysses.''
</P>
<P>
   Donleavy greeted that lowly position without rancor, while
saying, ``Some of my friends were outraged that I was at the
bottom.'' In common with many others on the list, ``The Ginger
Man'' is generally accepted as a contemporary classic.
</P>
<P>
   The novel brought the author fame and, at first, a certain
degree of misfortune. After it was rejected by scores of publishers
in the United States and England _ the number varies from 35 to 45
_ Donleavy left New York for Ireland, where his parents lived
before coming to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Back in Dublin, he was at a loss as to what to do with the
novel. A friend, the playwright Brendan Behan, read the manuscript
and filled it with a profusion of mostly helpful editorial comments
and corrections. He suggested that Donleavy send it to Girodias,
head of the Olympia Press in Paris. Behan had himself tried to
write a pornographic novel for Olympia and been turned down. He
thought Donleavy might have better luck _ and he did, in a manner
of speaking.
</P>
<P>
   To Donleavy's dismay, the book was published by Girodias (in
paperback) in the Traveler's Companion series of pornographic,
mostly pseudonymous novels. In the back of the first edition, it
was listed alongside such titles as ``White Thighs'' and ``The
Sexual Life of Robinson Crusoe.''
</P>
<P>
   Donleavy said that Girodias published his novel ``to cloak his
dealings as a pornographer _ he never thought the book would ever
make a penny.'' Because of the imprint, ``The Ginger Man'' was
regarded as something illegitimate.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was basically the end of my career,'' he said. ``I was `a
dirty book writer' out of Paris.''
</P>
<P>
   He vowed to take revenge on his publisher and to regain control
of his book. Through more than 20 years of litigation, Girodias
tied up the rights, one reason the novel was not filmed despite
interest from movie companies. (In recent years, Donleavy's son
Philip has been trying to put together a film production of the
novel.) Largely as a result of his conflict with the publisher,
Donleavy became a legal expert and began drawing up his own
contracts. Not only did he win his case, but he also ended up
buying Olympia at auction. In a final twist, the original edition
of the book is a valuable collector's item.
</P>
<P>
   The turning point in the novel's reputation came, the author
said, when in an interview John Osborne welcomed Donleavy as an
American cousin of Britain's Angry Young Men. As Donleavy later
discovered, Osborne had apparently read ``The Ginger Man'' before
he wrote ``Look Back in Anger.'' Despite differences in the works,
both Dangerfield and Osborne's Jimmy Porter are rebels thumbing
their noses at accepted behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking about his first novel, he remembered his friend Gainor
Crist, who died in the early 1960s. With Crist, he said, he can't
``separate fiction from reality,'' but whenever he and their mutual
friend George Roy Hill, the film director, would get together they
would swap stories about the charismatic Crist. Irrepressibly
convivial, Crist would talk to anyone in a bar or on the street
and, in hindsight, turn that person into ``an incredible
individual.''
</P>
<P>
   Crist read parts of ``The Ginger Man'' as it was written. ``He
was very much impressed by it but never thought it had much to do
with him,'' Donleavy said. He did, however, recognize a few events,
including the farcical scene in which the ceiling of his apartment
collapsed. For a while Crist taught English in Spain, and later he
worked for an airline in New York. Welcoming foreign dignitaries,
he ran up an astronomical bar bill. The name Dangerfield was a
tribute to Crist: it was his favorite name for an Englishman.
</P>
<P>
   At first, Donleavy called the novel ``SB'' or ``Sebastian
Dangerfield,'' but he changed the title at the request of Girodias,
who also rejected his other choice, ``His Hands Refuse to Labor.''
</P>
<P>
   Donleavy, who said he had never suffered from writer's block,
went on to write more than a dozen novels (his latest in 1998) and
several plays, as well as nonfiction. He has written sequels to
other books, but ``The Ginger Man'' is singular: ``I guess that it
had a degree of finality about it in this period and time.'' The
end of the book is the end of Dangerfield's story:
</P>
<P>
   God's mercy
</P>
<P>
   On the Wild
</P>
<P>
   Ginger Man.
</P>
<P>
   Although he has always retained his independence from anything
resembling a literary movement, Donleavy is well aware that in
recent years Ireland has become a far more hospitable place for
writers. ``Ireland has gone mad with authors,'' he said, and with
the mischievousness of Dangerfield, he added, ``I think they should
all go out and get decent jobs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-27-00 2028EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000627.0336 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 20:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6579 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-INDONESIA-UNREST-ART-     06-27 0912
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-UNREST-ART-2TAKES-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRAIL INDONESIA FEELS TREMORS FROM A POCKET OF VIOLENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ A terrifying surge of communal violence,
apparently fueled by anti-government agitators in Jakarta, is
tearing apart the remote and beautiful islands of Maluku, raising
fears of destabilization throughout Indonesia's ailing archipelago.
</P>
<P>
   More than 200 people have reportedly been killed in the past
week in village massacres and in street fighting in the small city
of Ambon, pushing the death toll during the last 18 months to more
than 2,500.
</P>
<P>
   The unchecked fighting in the province of Maluku, once known as
the Spice Islands, has become one of the main challenges to the
political control of President Abdurrahman Wahid, who faces a
possible vote of no confidence in a parliamentary assembly in
August.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has become a very serious issue,'' said Umar Juoro, a
former presidential aide who heads an Islamic policy institute.
``Now when you go to the mosque or you go to church you are hearing
about the killing of Muslims and the killing of Christians. This is
getting into our daily lives around Indonesia.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is much more serious for Indonesia than East Timor
because it involves a conflict of elites in Jakarta,'' Juoro said
of the former Portuguese colony that broke away in August and was
never an integral part of national affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts suggest an array of disaffected groups that may be
involved: loyalists or family members of Suharto who fear
punishment by the government; extremist Islamic groups seeking to
create a less moderate regime in this largely Muslim nation;
elements of the military who oppose the downgrading of their
political role in Indonesia, and powerful economic interests
seeking to maintain their control.
</P>
<P>
   While Wahid has sought to foster good will, his nine months in
office have seen repeated outbreaks of religious violence, many
apparently provoked by unidentified agitators, including attacks on
mosques and churches as well as communal fighting.
</P>
<P>
   The government's inability to curb the violence is adding to a
perception among some Indonesians that Wahid is unable to control
an array of powerful and vengeful forces that were disenfranchised
with the overthrow of President Suharto two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Wahid continues to command widespread respect for his liberal
and democratic goals. But the quality of his leadership has also
come into question from a series of financial scandals, political
missteps and seemingly intemperate comments.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say he has been slow to act on the Maluku fighting as
well as on other pressing issues. His defenders say that the
deep-rooted problems he faces defy aggressive solutions. In this
case, the situation has only spiraled further out of control.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   When Wahid announced a state of emergency in Maluku on Monday
and vowed to disarm the combatants, he drew an anguished reaction
from local residents reached by telephone, who said they feared the
military as much as the local religious gangs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The military is no longer capable of stopping the conflict,''
said Joseph Tethool, the Roman Catholic bishop of Ambon, who sent a
letter this weekend to the United Nations pleading for
international help. ``Many soldiers have taken sides.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Sammy Titaley, who heads the Protestant churches in
Ambon, said the fighting had escalated to include mortars,
automatic weapons and even small armored vehicles, a sign of
organized military involvement.
</P>
<P>
   In a scene reminiscent of the violence last year in East Timor,
the local military appears to have run out of control, arming
civilian combatants and, according to witnesses, sometimes leading
the attacks.
</P>
<P>
   But in East Timor, the rogue military groups were clearly better
organized and commanded from above. In Maluku, the chain of command
appears to have broken down more thoroughly as Muslim soldiers join
the Muslim side and Christian soldiers join with Christian
fighters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even the commanders cannot control their men,'' said Umelto
Labetubun, a student who lives on the Christian side of the
now-divided town. ``One Christian soldier stopped by my house, a
first lieutenant, and he said, `Some of my men are on the other
side and they are now shooting at us.'''
</P>
<P>
   But the problem goes well beyond a breakdown of military
command.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is that the government of Abdurrahman Wahid is
weak,'' said Salim Said, a political scientist. ``If you do not
have a strong government in this country you cannot overcome the
many problems that are the legacy of the old government. The old
government was put down but not destroyed. It is still very
strong.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   One of the most obvious signs of trouble has been the influx in
recent weeks of 2,200 white-robed Muslim fighters calling
themselves the Laskar Jihad, who were mostly organized and trained
at a camp near Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Minister Juwono Sudarsonso, in a recent interview, said
that there was no way to stop them from boarding interisland
ferries and traveling to the area, where they then received weapons
from unknown sources.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Local residents said they believed that these fighters were
involved in a horrific massacre a week ago at the village of Duma
on the island of Halmahera, where church workers said 206 Christian
villagers were killed in an attack that lasted just one hour.
</P>
<P>
   Members of Laskar Jihad have said they are engaged in
``self-defense'' and the attack on Duma was described as a revenge
attack. Last December, hundreds of Muslims were killed on Halmahera
by Christian gangs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a very complicated, very big problem, because national
politics is involved,'' the Maluku governor, Saleh Latuconsina,
told a Dutch journalist last month. ``The Laskar Jihad is connected
to some political elite, because they can come to Ambon without
anyone stopping them. Maybe it's from the people of the status quo
. . . well, Suharto.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor, himself a Muslim, said he believed that ``not more
than 10 percent'' of the people of either religion wanted to fight.
</P>
<P>
   A European political scientist who has lived in Maluku, said the
most disturbing thing was that villagers could be so easily
provoked to go to war with each other.
</P>
<P>
   More than 90 percent of Indonesia's 210 million people are
Muslim, making this the world's largest Muslim nation. But they
have traditionally lived in harmony with religious minorities.
Maluku is one of the few areas where Christians and Muslims live in
nearly equal numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The areas in Ambon and Halmahera where the killings are going
on are places I worked 10 years ago, and I found them to be some of
the more peaceful and beautiful places I have visited anywhere in
the world,'' said the scholar. ``It does not bear thinking what
would happen if groups in other parts of Indonesia begin attacking
their fellow Indonesians for religious reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month more than 120 people were killed and thousands of
people were driven from their homes when Muslims fought Christians
for several days on the island of Sulawesi in eastern Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   In Maluku, the divisions have spread to the military in a way
they have not done elsewhere in the country. When a national police
barracks in Ambon was burned down last week, Labetubun said, some
of the attackers were wearing police uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   Told of the president's imposition of a state of emergency, he
only laughed in despair.
</P>
<P>
   ``The military is just making it worse,'' he said. ``I am crying
because I cannot stand it any more. The military is shooting at us
so how can we trust the military? We cannot trust anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Ambon, the regional center, is now ``a dead city'' where
banks have closed and food and fuel are becoming scarce. ``The day
time is just like the night time,'' he said. ``No one goes out of
the house. You hear no sound, no car. Then you hear the shooting
and explosions.''
</P>
</TEXT>
