<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 20:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6582 &Cx1f; tth-z
u w BC-CUBA-TRADE-SPI &LR;      06-27 1167
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBA-TRADE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE AGREES ON DEAL TO ALLOW CUBA TO BUY FOOD, MEDICINE FROM
U.S. 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CHARLES POPE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With the House reaching a hard-won agreement
yesterday allowing Cuba to buy food and medicine from the United
States, Washington state farmer Cary Janson and Rep. George
Nethercutt are among those with good reason to look forward to the
fall harvest.
</P>
<P>
   For Janson, partially lifting long-standing trade sanctions
against Cuba and four other nations means he'll be able to sell his
crops _ peas, lentils and wheat _ to five large and hungry markets.
</P>
<P>
   Before the sanctions were imposed in 1961, Cuba was a huge
market for Washington state crops. The state's pea and lentil
growers in particular have mourned the loss of Cuba as a trading
partner, because it had been the largest importer of those
commodities in the late 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   Reopening that market could boost the price of peas and lentils
enough to turn a loss for the year into a small profit, Janson
believes.
</P>
<P>
   For Nethercutt, the harvest could mean the difference between
profit and loss in political terms. The Washington Republican is
hoping farmers will reward him with their votes this fall in what
promises to be a tight election for a fourth term. Farmers and
their lobbyists in Washington have been pushing hard to open those
markets.
</P>
<P>
   All of this potential took root Tuesday as Nethercutt and other
farm-state lawmakers reached agreement at 2 a.m. after more than
five hours of bruising negotiations. The session climaxed six weeks
of talks between Nethercutt and Republican leaders who opposed any
relaxation of trade barriers with Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Easy passage is expected in the full House. The Senate also is
expected to approve it. Although the White House has reservations,
President Clinton is expected to sign the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I began this process guided by the principle that the United
States is never justified in using unilateral food and medicine
sanctions as weapons in foreign policy,'' an elated Nethercutt
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This agreement accomplishes exactly what I first set out to
do: upon enactment, American farmers will have access to all five
unilaterally sanctioned markets. It's not a perfect agreement ...
but that's the nature of negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a fundamental shift in American foreign policy and a
new day for American agriculture.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, sales of food and medicine to Cuba, Sudan,
North Korea, Libya and Iran would have to be ``cash only'' with
additional restrictions to guarantee that the U.S. government or
banks do not finance any of the purchases by Cuba. Cuba initially
would be able to purchase only $45 million worth of U.S. farm
goods, according to an estimate by the U.S.-Cuba Trade and Economic
Council. That compares to $400 million if the country could use
U.S. financing.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Wahl, director of Washington State University's
International Marketing Project for Agricultural Commodities and
Trade, said Cuba is too small to provide much help to struggling
farmers. But, he added, ``this is good news for farmers because
it's been a long time since they've had any good news.''
</P>
<P>
   Wahl believes a more significant change is the requirement that
Congress approve future sanctions. That, he said, is likely to
result in fewer sanctions which will help farmers who suffer when
markets are closed.
</P>
<P>
   Nethercutt and his allies, however, said the agreement was the
first step in a larger effort to liberalize trade with Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line for me ... was we want to open markets for us
to sell products to them. Even though it will be a little more
difficult in Cuba (to finance purchases), I think it can be done,''
Nethercutt said. ``This is a first step.''
</P>
<P>
   Arkansas Rep. Jay Dickey, who worked with Nethercutt, said: ``To
those people who say we didn't go far enough or we didn't make a
good enough bargain, we're getting our foot in the door. It's not
perfect; we're trying to do as much as we can right now. The
resistance was unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   The measure must now be approved by the Senate, which in the
past has overwhelmingly endorsed lifting sanctions on food and
medicine to Cuba. Sanctions against the five countries would be
lifted 120 days after the bill becomes law.
</P>
<P>
   If all of that happens before Congress leaves for the July 4
recess _ as Nethercutt hopes _ some of the harvest from U.S. fields
could be on dinner tables in Cuba as early as this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Still, opposition remains.
</P>
<P>
   The White House is concerned that the agreement would require a
president to get congressional approval before imposing future
embargoes on food and medicine to other countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not opposed to allowing things like food and medicine
to go to Cuba, as long as it is for the benefit of the people, and
not the benefit of the Castro government,'' said White House
spokesman Joe Lockhart. ``We do have concerns on what I call an
institutional basis, based on the limits that it puts on
presidential prerogatives.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers from south Florida and groups opposed to Cuban
President Fidel Castro remain opposed to the initiative.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Ileana Ross-Lehtinen, R-Fla., a Castro critic who
negotiated against Nethercutt, said the legislation would ``make it
as difficult as possible'' for such sales to take place. The
agreement would also write into law the existing ban on Americans
going to Cuba as tourists.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that what Castro has wanted is access'' to U.S.
financial markets, she said. ``He's not going to get any of that.''
</P>
<P>
   And Nethercutt's effort has energized anti-Castro groups to
launch ad campaigns against those supporting any form of trade with
Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   The largest and wealthiest _ the Cuban American National
Foundation _ announced a new round of television ads condemning
Castro for allowing 77 U.S. citizens convicted of felonies to live
in his country. The ads, which will initially be aired in
Washington, D.C., follow another ad broadcast 10 days ago in
several locations, including Nethercutt's district.
</P>
<P>
   ``We find it unconscionable that the U.S. Congress would be
debating economic overtures to the Castro government while Fidel
Castro protects and provides safe haven to 77 U.S. fugitive wanted
by the Federal Bureau of Investigation,'' said Jose Cardenas, head
of the Washington office of the Cuban American National Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Cardenas would not say if the new ad would run in Nethercutt's
district, but in describing the type of lawmaker that would be
targeted, he described Nethercutt. ``These ads are going to be run
against House members who favor lifting the sanctions and who are
in difficult elections.''
</P>
<P>
   The ad campaign, Cardenas said, is designed to ``remind the
American people who Fidel Castro is and what he stands for and ...
and why it is not a good idea to pursue any semblance of a normal
relationship with the Cuban dictator.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
