<HEADER>
A6583 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-SYRIA-POLITICS-NYT &LR;      06-27 1114
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SYRIA-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASSAD'S SON DESIGNATED SOLE CANDIDATE FOR SYRIAN PRESIDENCY 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN KIFNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIRUT, Lebanon _ As Hafez Assad, absolute ruler of Syria for 30
years, slipped into a final coma several days before he died on
June 10, his closest circle of aides and advisers worked swiftly
behind the scenes in Damascus to ensure that his untested
34-year-old son would have a smooth, well orchestrated ascension to
power.
</P>
<P>
   That steady, swift march continued Tuesday as that son, Bashar
Assad, was, not unexpectedly, approved unanimously by Parliament as
the sole candidate for president in a referendum scheduled for July
10.
</P>
<P>
   His father regularly won such referundums by an official tally
of 99.9 percent, and there is little likelihood of voter drop-off.
</P>
<P>
   The speaker of Parliament paused a second or so before declaring
the result of the show of hands, followed by cheers and chants.
</P>
<P>
   Assad had already, in rapid succession, been promoted from army
colonel to lieutenant general _ his father's rank _ and commander
in chief, elected leader of the ruling Baath Party by acclaim at
its first congress in 15 years and leader of its ruling Regional
Command Council, all in the last 16 days.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the only thing that slowed the bandwagon was the
eagerness of Syrian officials to climb aboard. A parliamentary
committee delegated to study his candidacy on Sunday found him
overwhelmingly qualified, and he was scheduled to be anointed in a
session on Monday night. But so many lawmakers _ about 200 of the
250-member assembly _ wanted to speak in his praise that the voting
had to be rescheduled for Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The late president, one delegate declared, made Syria ``the envy
of all the world.'' To his son the delegate pledged, ``We shall
march behind you with absolute loyalty and sincerity.'' Another
called him a ``knight, who will lead us day to day.''
</P>
<P>
   There was momentary consternation on Monday when one member
objected to a constitutional change put through in 15 minutes after
the president's death that lowered the age for president to 34, not
coincidentally the age of the son.
</P>
<P>
   The lawmaker who objected was shouted down and later apologized.
</P>
<P>
   Hafez Assad was known as a very careful planner, and the pieces
have been put into place in the last two years as his son was put
in charge of Syria's domination of Lebanon and given more and more
responsibility for governing at home.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most important, last year he was put in charge of an
anti-corruption drive that purged a number of high-ranking
politicians and generals who might have turned into challengers.
</P>
<P>
   Among the once-powerful figures no longer on the scene as a
result is former Prime Minister Mahmoud Zubi. After 13 years as
prime minister and several more as speaker of Parliament, Zubi was
reported to have committed suicide last month as security forces
surrounded his villa after accusations that he was corrupt.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Hekmat Shehabi, who had been the army chief of staff, fled
the country rather than face a graft investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The member of his father's old guard who appears to be most
protective and supportive of Bashar al-Assad is the defense
minister, Gen. Mustafa Tlas. He arranged at least two meetings for
senior military officers to get to know the young man and has been
by his side at many of his public appearances since the president's
death.
</P>
<P>
   Tlas' son, Manaf, is said to be one of Assad's closest friends
and has been introducing him to members of the country's Sunni
Muslim merchant class in an apparent attempt to broaden his base of
support.
</P>
<P>
   Manaf Tlas commands a battalion in the elite Republican Guard, a
mainstay of the late president's support, as does Assad's younger
brother, Maher. Tlas' brother-in-law, Asef Shawkat, is the director
of security and military intelligence. Another important supporter
is Bahajat Suleiman, director of internal security.
</P>
<P>
   The support of the military and the dozen or so overlapping
intelligence agencies, which were central to his father's rule,
will also be crucial to the new president's survival.
</P>
<P>
   Many key security positions are held by Alawites, who like the
Assad family are members of a once-poor minority sect risen to
power. It did not pass unnoticed that Zubi was a Sunni Muslim and
so is Shehabi.
</P>
<P>
   Assad was training in London as an ophthalmologist until his
older brother, Basil, a charismatic soldier and athlete who was the
heir apparent, died in a car crash in 1994. Michael Hudson,
director of the Center for Arab Studies at Georgetown University,
recalled meeting Assad at a computer convention and described him
as shy, studious and ``apparently a genuinely nice guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Hudson, who happened to be in Damascus at the time of President
Assad's funeral, said Assad must ``thread his way through
minefields of potential opposition as he moves to build his own
power base,'' warning that the anticorruption drive could be a
two-edged sword.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dozens of other high officials are vulnerable to similar
charges,'' Hudson said. ``They must already be strategizing about
how to curb this possibly dangerous young man.''
</P>
<P>
   While the plan to bring the young man to power appeared well
orchestrated, said Fawaz Gerges, a professor of Middle Eastern
studies at Sarah Lawrence College, Assad's most urgent task is
``not only to gain legitimacy and consolidate power, but also to
keep the military-security ruling elite united.''
</P>
<P>
   Gerges said that in the coming months, it will be crucial for
Assad to build `'a coalition of like-minded lieutenants who fully
support him, as well as to manage wisely and decisively rivalry
among the elite that might spin out of control.''
</P>
<P>
   A measure of the speed with which the old guard is moving to
consolidate itself around Assad is that the election date has been
set well before the end of the traditional 40-day Muslim period of
mourning, which would be July 20.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the shifting political alliances could be seen in the
appointments to the 21-member regional command, the Baath Party's
ruling body. Among those joining Tlas and Vice President Abdel
Halim Khaddam, who promoted Assad to general and commander, are
Foreign Minister Farouk al-Shara and Prime Minister Mohammed Mero,
new members who appear to be part of an established core of support
for Assad.
</P>
<P>
   Another major new appointment is of Saeed Bkhaitan, a close aide
of Assad who is now director of the National Security Bureau, which
coordinates party and government bodies.
</P>
<P>
   Several formerly important generals have been eased into
retirement and lost their political positions in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-27-00 2032EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000627.0341 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 20:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6587 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-BKN-DRAFT-TEXASPREPS-     06-27 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-DRAFT-TEXASPREPS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Cedric Golden
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas - When you hear national basketball aficionados
speak of the heart of the game, states such as Indiana, California,
New York and Kentucky are always the first ones mentioned.
</P>
<P>
   Californians will talk your ears off about UCLA, John Wooden,
Lew Alcindor, and the Showtime Lakers. Indy hoop fans proudly
recollect countless anecdotes from favorite son Bob Knight to Keith
Smart's jump shot to beat Syracuse to why Gene Hackman was cheated
out of the Oscar for his performance in ``Hoosiers.'' Bluegrass
basketball junkies reminisce about Adolph Rupp, Joe B. Hall, Goose
Givens and Rick Pitino. New Yorkers boast of playground legends and
some will even tell you Michael Jordan was born in New York, not
North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   But if you ask the aforementioned fans about Texas, they will
undoubtedly say, ``Yeah, Texas. That's a football state.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, football is a religion in Texas. Yes, high school football
is more popular here than Anna Kournikova on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   But what of basketball? Does Texas get enough respect for the
basketball talent it produces?
</P>
<P>
   In today's NBA draft, two Texas kids could go 1-2 in the draft.
Most of the experts have Kenyon Martin, the University of
Cincinnati forward who played at Dallas Bryan Adams High School,
tabbed as the top pick, going to the New Jersey Nets.
</P>
<P>
   University of Texas center Chris Mihm has been listed anywhere
from No. 1 to No. 7 in mock drafts. Experts like his athleticism
and versatility in addition to his 7-foot size.
</P>
<P>
   If either Texas player goes No. 1, it will be the third time in
the last 10 drafts that this state has yielded the NBA's top draft
pick. In 1991, the Charlotte Hornets grabbed Dallas Skyline's Larry
Johnson out of Nevada-Las Vegas with the first pick. Louisville's
LaBradford Smith, who played at Bay City, went the same year at No.
19 to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, Orlando used its top pick to take San Antonio Cole's
Shaquille O'Neal of Louisiana State. The Phoenix Suns also took a
Texas player in the first round, grabbing ex-Fort Worth Southwest
center Oliver Miller of Arkansas at No. 22.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1990, 28 players who played high school ball in California
have gone in the first round. New York has produced 16, Indiana
eight and Kentucky four.
</P>
<P>
   What about Texas?
</P>
<P>
   The Lone Star state has produced 14 first-round picks since
1990, more than enough to be mentioned in the same breath as
California and New York. Texas had at least one first-round pick in
all but two drafts of the 1990s _ 1993 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think due to our location, away from the eastern coast of
the country, Texas is often overlooked,'' said Bob Springer,
publisher of Texas Basketball Magazine. ``That doesn't mean we
don't have some of the best talent in the nation. If you look back
over past NBA drafts, all the way back to Larry Johnson and Shaq,
you will see that Texas has as much basketball talent as anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Longtime Port Arthur Lincoln coach James Gamble, who coached
former NBA player and UT ex B.J. Tyler, thinks high school
basketball is starting to get more recognition than it did in the
1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since the '80s, hoops is getting to be a larger spectator
sport, including high school basketball,'' said Gamble, who has
coached at Lincoln for 27 years. ``Fans are becoming more
appreciative of good high school basketball and that encourages the
kids to work even harder to get better.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Kunstadt, the publisher of Texas Hoops.com., said hoops has
evolved over the last decade, particularly on the high school
level.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think Texas is really that overlthe participation
level is another reason for its rise in popularity and the
subsequent crop of NBA first-rounders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know there are more kids playing basketball now than 15
years ago,'' he said. ``Some of the better athletes that used to
concentrate on the other sports, like football _ some of them are
playing basketball now. They are finding you can make the big money
in basketball, too.''
</P>
<P>
   .
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
