<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000627.0343 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 20:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6600 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-BKN-DRAFT-PREVIEW-C?X     06-27 1193
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-DRAFT-PREVIEW-C?X </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Who'll be the first pick in NBA draft tonight?
 &HT;    By Mark Rosner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas - Kenyon Martin fearlessly attacks the rim on
offense, making the backboard shudder with his dunks. He
aggressively protects the basket on defense, a human detour.
</P>
<P>
   Those skills seem to make Martin the likely No. 1 pick in the
NBA draft tonight in Minneapolis. Or do they?
</P>
<P>
   The New Jersey Nets, who on Monday appeared set to open the
draft by choosing Martin, now say they are also considering
Stromile Swift and Darius Miles. Martin, a 6-foot-9-inch senior
forward why played college basketball at Cincinnati, is recovering
from a broken leg. Swift is a 6-9 sophomore forward at LSU, Miles a
6-9 forward who just finished high school in Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, Kenyon is more ready, other than the injury, today
than the other two,'' Nets President Rod Thorn said Tuesday at a
press conference to introduce the team's new coach, Byron Scott.
``But you have to project what they are going to be.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a chance the Nets might not choose any of the three.
They have entertained trade offers, particularly from Orlando,
which has the Nos. 5, 10 and 13 picks and wants to move up to take
Martin, who is from Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago, which has the Nos. 4, 7 and 24 picks, also has shown
interest. Should the Bulls remain where they are, some analysts
predict they will draft Chris Mihm, the 7-foot former Texas
Longhorns center. If Chicago passes on Mihm, Orlando might be
waiting for him at No. 5. The worst scenario for Mihm, according to
a few analysts: he slips to No. 7, Chicago's second pick. Then
again, Cleveland is reportedly angling to obtain the third pick
from the Los Angeles Clippers in an effort to secure Mihm. The
bait? Cleveland's pick, No. 8, and point guard Brevin Knight.
Cleveland might make the same offer to Orlando if Mihm slips to No.
5.
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts believe this draft lacks a player capable of
single-handedly rescuing a foundering team anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in the projection business,'' Orlando General Manager
John Gabriel said. ``It was that way last year, that you have so
many players high in the draft who aren't ready for the NBA. It
means you have to be a little more tolerant about waiting. I do
think this draft is going to be a deep one. But the impact, like
the last few years, will be more clear by the All-Star break.''
</P>
<P>
   Everyone seems to agree that, for now, Martin most resembles a
franchise-type player _ despite a broken fibula in his right leg
that he suffered during the first round of the Conference USA
tournament in March.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike other players in the draft, Martin has not been able to
work out for NBA teams. But Martin has been examined by enough
doctors to fill two hospitals and a golf course. Doctors who
examined him at the NBA's pre-draft camp earlier in June expect a
complete recovery by training camp in October. Similar results were
reported by doctors who examined Martin for the Nets last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``They put that kid through so many tests, I don't think he
could go near a nuclear reactor because he'd be glowing,'' Martin's
agent, Dan Fegan, told the New York Post. ``They had leg and ankle
specialists, the best radiologists money can buy.''
</P>
<P>
   The Nets already have lost one player to a broken leg, Jayson
Williams, their starting center. Williams, who has not played since
April 1999, is on the verge of retirement. Starting guard Kerry
Kittles recently underwent surgery to his right knee for the fourth
time in two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the situation with Jayson Williams and Kerry Kittles,
they're going to be cautious,'' Fegan said. ``And their medical
people seemed satisfied. They're not going to say something will
never happen. Good doctors and good lawyers never say 100 percent.
It's 98 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, there is that shadow of a doubt. How will the injury
affect someone who relies so much on his ability to elevate
quickly? How many years of pounding can the leg absorb?
</P>
<P>
   Should New Jersey trade the No. 1 pick today, it will be the
first time in seven years a team has done that. In 1993, Orlando
drafted Chris Webber and traded him to Golden State for Penny
Hardaway and three future draft picks.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Orlando might use one of those picks, No. 5 this
year, in an attempt to move up to No. 1 and secure Martin. To
complete a trade with New Jersey, Orlando might have to also
relinquish the No. 10 slot in the draft as well as a player or two,
reportedly Corey Maggette and either Michael Doleac or Matt
Harpring.
</P>
<P>
   Vancouver, which has the second pick, has its eyes on Swift.
According to the NBA grapevine, the Grizzlies have considered
trading down to obtain more than one player.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Clippers, who pick third, are likely to take
Iowa State power forward Marcus Fizer as a replacement for
departing free agent Maurice Taylor. But there have been some
rumors suggesting the Clippers might opt for Miles.
</P>
<P>
   Most draft analysts predict the Bulls will take either Mihm or
Miles with the fourth pick. The Bulls need a center more than a
small forward, but some NBA scouts think that Miles might become a
star like Kevin Garnett and Kobe Bryant, both of whom skipped
college.
</P>
<P>
   Should Orlando remain at No. 5, it can pick whoever is left
between Mihm, Miles or Fizer.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Texas teams, all three are trying to move up in the
draft. For now, Houston owns the ninth pick and Dallas No. 12,
while San Antonio does not have a first-round selection.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts predict the Rockets will take DerMarr Johnson, a
thin, 6-9 shooting guard who was Martin's teammate at Cincinnati.
Others believe the Rockets will address their needs at power
forward with 7-foot Jerome Moiso of UCLA, 6-10 Nigerian Olumide
Oyedeji or 6-9 Etan Thomas of Syracuse.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas, which needs frontcourt help, might take Oyedeji or 7-2
Iakovos Tsakalidis, who plays professionally in Greece and
generally is considered the third-best center in the draft behind
Mihm and Joel Przybilla of Minnesota. According to one prediction,
the Mavs will take Keyon Dooling, a point guard from Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs have the 41st and 54th picks in the second round. They
might look for a center to back up David Robinson. Several should
be available in the second round, including LSU's Jabari Smith and
junior-college star Ernest Brown. Among the foreign players
available are Dalibor Bagaric from Croatia, Primoz Brezec from
Slovenia and Soumalia Samake from Mali.
</P>
<P>
   Draft analysts predict the Spurs might take a point guard,
shooting guard or small forward. Khalid El-Amin of Connecticut and
Ed Cota of North Carolina are potentially available point guards.
Lavor Postell of St. John's and Mark Karcher of Temple are possible
choices at shooting guard. Eduardo Najera of Oklahoma, Dan Langhi
of Vanderbilt or Pete Mickeal of Cincinnati might be around at
small forward. Among those players, Postell is considered most
likely to be taken before the Spurs' turn arrives.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-27-00 2046EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
