<SLUG> BC-PROSPERITY-DATA-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRS SAYS RECORD NUMBER OF TAXPAYERS EARN MORE THAN $100,000 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) By DAVID CAY JOHNSTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stock options, two-career couples and capital gains helped lift
a record number of taxpayers _ one in 15 _ to six-figure annual
incomes in 1998, the government reported Tuesday, an increase of
1.1 million from 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The Internal Revenue Service counts a married couple who file
jointly as one taxpayer.
</P>
<P>
   The number of taxpayers with incomes of $100,000 or more soared
in 1998 to 8.3 million, up 15 percent from 7.2 million in 1997,
preliminary figures from 1998 income tax returns showed.
</P>
<P>
   The book of statistics was issued Tuesday by the IRS.
</P>
<P>
   The data help explain why federal tax revenue has surged,
prompting President Clinton on Monday to raise the budget surplus
over the next decade to $1.9 trillion from the February estimate of
$792 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Analysis of the IRS data by The New York Times also showed the
number of taxpayers making $100,000 or more expanded to 36.9
percent in 1998 from 34.2 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   In the first glimpse of the impact of the Taxpayer Relief Act of
1997, the taxes paid by these Americans rose by 30.4 percent as
more of their income was subject to the 31 percent, 36 percent and
39.6 percent rates.
</P>
<P>
   The 6.6 percent of taxpayers earning more than $100,000 paid 58
percent of all income taxes in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Many more taxpayers in 1998 _ 828,000, which is a 40 percent
increase over the previous year _ paid the Alternative Minimum Tax,
the new data show. The tax, which phases out deductions for state
and local taxes, and even for children, was adopted 31 years ago to
stop rich taxpayers from using so many legal tax breaks that they
paid no federal income tax.
</P>
<P>
   ``This shows how this frightening tax complexity monster is
growing in our midst,'' said David Keating of the National
Taxpayers Union.
</P>
<P>
   Because Congress has not updated the law for inflation, the
minimum tax now reaches so far down the economic ladder that it can
sometimes tax a single parent making $28,000.
</P>
<P>
   The tax data also raised questions about the effectiveness of
the sharp reduction in capital gains taxes, a major element of the
Taxpayer Relief Act of 1997, which was sponsored by the House
Republican leadership.
</P>
<P>
   The highest long-term capital gains tax rate was cut to 20
percent from 28 percent in 1996 and part of 1997, yet the rate of
growth in capital gains fell by half, from 48 percent in 1996 to 22
percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bill Archer, the Texas Republican who is chairman of the
House Ways and Means Committee, promoted the lower rate as a key to
increasing savings and investment and building a prosperous future.
</P>
<P>
   At first glance, taxpayers with incomes less than $15,000 seem
to be lagging behind inflation. But interpreting the data is hard
because the lowest income category is now heavy with rich children.
</P>
<P>
   The number of people with income less than $15,000 annually
declined by 3 percent, from 40.5 million in 1997 to 40.1 million in
1998. The average income grew by just 0.6 percent, to $6,290, an
increase of a scant $45 over 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Complicating the picture is the growing number of prosperous
families who file tax returns for children who have their own
college funds.
</P>
<P>
   The one indication that the lowest income category is now
populated with rich children is that 44 percent of this group's
income came from capital gains, four times the contribution of
capital gains to the incomes of those making $30,000 to $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   Analysis of the IRS data also showed that the boom at the top is
overwhelmingly the result of more people crossing the $100,000
income threshold, rather than of increases in income among those
already there.
</P>
<P>
   Among the 6.2 million taxpayers making $100,000 to $200,000, the
average income fell by $514, to $131,189, from $131,703 in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The number of taxpayers with income above $200,000 _ the highest
category delineated by the IRS in these data _ grew by a brisk 18
percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
