<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ACCOUNTING-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: SEC PROPOSES STRICTER ACCOUNTING RULES 
</HEADLINE>
   By FLOYD NORRIS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission proposed new rules
Tuesday to tighten standards on what other services accounting
firms could sell to companies whose books they audit. The proposal
immediately ran into stiff criticism from some accounting firms,
but gained support from others.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without confidence in an auditor's objectivity and fairness,
how can an investor know whether to trust the numbers?'' asked
Arthur Levitt, the chairman of the SEC. ``Sound and verifiable
numbers are to financial markets what oxygen is to breathing. Our
financial markets simply cannot work without access to strong,
high-quality financial reporting.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposed rules, which will be subject to public comment for
75 days and then to public hearings before the commission decides
whether to adopt them, would in some cases bar accounting firms
from performing consulting services they now perform for companies
whose books they audit.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal asks for comment on a wide range of issues,
including whether auditors should be allowed to write promotional
materials for tax shelter advocates, whether they should be allowed
to help design the financial systems they will then critique as
part of their audits and whether it is proper for auditors to lobby
on behalf of their clients.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time there has ever been a rule proposal on
the scope of services these firms provide,'' said Lynn Turner, the
SEC's chief accountant. ``People have wondered whether that growing
scope related to some of the major audit failures we have seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Three of the five largest accounting firms, and the American
Institute of Certified Public Accountants, strongly criticized the
proposal as being unnecessary and seeking to solve a problem that
does not exist. They have already begun to enlist congressional
allies in case they need to seek legislation to overturn any rules
the commission adopts.
</P>
<P>
   They argued that there was no demonstrated problem, and
challenged the SEC to name one audit that was compromised because
the auditor also performed consulting services for the client. And,
they added, the knowledge of consultants helped, not hurt, the
audit.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us to protect investors, you need a wide range of
expertise within our firm,'' said Stephen Aliss of KPMG. ``The
direction of this proposal is to drive talent from our firm.''
</P>
<P>
   He argued that it would be hard to attract highly qualified
consultants because many potential customers would be off limits as
audit clients.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of Deloitte &AMP; Touche and Arthur Andersen joined
in the criticism. ``The more you know about the client, the better
the audit is going to be,'' said Jeffrey Peck, a managing director
of Arthur Andersen, adding that the SEC proposal would reduce the
quality of audits.
</P>
<P>
   But the remaining big five firms _ Ernst &AMP; Young and
PricewaterhouseCoopers _ said they broadly support the SEC's
initiative. ``We believe that the perceived independence problem is
becoming a factor in the marketplace and needs to be dealt with,''
said Larry Parnall, a spokesman for Ernst &AMP; Young. ``We hope the
rule-making process is the beginning of this effort and we look
forward to working with the SEC on this.''
</P>
<P>
   PricewaterhouseCoopers issued a statement saying: ``We are fully
committed to supporting the SEC's efforts to enhance audit quality
and investor protection. At this crucial moment in the history of
the accounting profession, the public interest must take precedence
over self-interest.''
</P>
<P>
   That split in the accounting profession could make it easier for
the SEC to take action this year. Some of the opponents contend
that the commission was rushing the comment period in an effort to
complete its work before a new president took office in January.
The new president would be able to name a new SEC chairman if he
wished to do so.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Levitt emphasized that the commission had
already discussed the ideas extensively with the industry and was
open to all comments. ``The firms have nothing to fear and
investors have everything to gain from this open public debate,''
he said. He said he hoped for broad public participation in the
process.
</P>
<P>
   The AFL-CIO offered support for the proposal. ``We believe that
the proposed changes, by extending the range of financial, business
and employment relationships that are deemed to create conflicts of
interest, will ensure that auditors are genuinely independent,''
said John Sweeney, the federation's president.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC proposal also includes a series of generally
non-controversial proposals to liberalize the rules regarding
investments by employees and officials of auditing firms. In
general, the rules would allow many more investments and would
substantially relax the rules relating to spouses of such people.
</P>
<P>
   A report released by the SEC in January concluded that most
partners at PricewaterhouseCoopers had violated the existing rules
and similar studies are now underway regarding the other four
firms.
</P>
<P>
   Accountants who are opposed to the other changes complained that
the SEC should have separated those rules to enable them to be
adopted quickly.
</P>
<P>
   All the major accounting firms have considered efforts to
separate themselves to some extent from their consulting divisions.
Ernst &AMP; Young has gone the furthest, selling its operation. Others
are considering a variety of revamping proposals, including the
sale of minority stakes. The proposal seeks comment on the extent
of separation that would be needed before a related consulting firm
could provide otherwise prohibited services to the accounting
firm's audit client.
</P>
<P>
   Turner, the SEC's chief accountant, said the argument that
providing consulting services made for better audits ``just doesn't
hold water.'' He noted that one study showed three-quarters of
audit clients get no other services from their auditing firms.
``Does that mean that in 75 percent of the cases, we have poor
audits?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
