<TEXT>
<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the following
stories for clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of
Wednesday, June 28, and thereafter. If you have any questions,
please call Mary Downes on the national-foreign desk at (206)
448-8158.
</P>
<P>
   CUBA-TRADE (Washington) _ With the House reaching a hard-won
agreement allowing Cuba to buy food and medicine from the United
States, Washington state farmer Cary Janson and Rep. George
Nethercutt are among those with good reason to look forward to the
fall harvest. For Janson, partially lifting long-standing trade
sanctions against Cuba and four other nations means he'll be able
to sell his crops _ peas, lentils and wheat _ to five large and
hungry markets. For Nethercutt, the harvest could mean the
difference between profit and loss in political terms. The
Washington Republican is hoping farmers will reward him with their
votes this fall in what promises to be a tight election for a
fourth term.
</P>
<P>
   By Charles Pope. (Story has moved in the ``w'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   AMA-SENATE (Seattle) _ The American Medical Association is
targeting Washington and two other states with Republican senators
in tough re-election races _ Michigan and Missouri _ in a
advertising campaign urging GOP lawmakers to drop their opposition
to a comprehensive patients' bill of rights.
</P>
<P>
   By Joel Connelly. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BBA-MARINERS (Seattle) _ Seattle Mariners host the Anaheim
Angels.
</P>
<P>
   By Dan Raley. (Story will move in the ``s'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-PATRIOT (Undated) Hollywood's new Revolutionary War drama
``The Patriot'' has so much going for it in terms of production
design, believable battle sequences and Mel Gibson's star power
that it's actually painful to gradually discover that it has a
flag-waving dumbness at its core.
</P>
<P>
   By William Arnold. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
