<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 21:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6611 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-YANKEES-SOSA-BOS &LR;      06-27 0494
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-SOSA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX OUT OF TALKS, YANKEES SAID NEAR DEAL FOR SOSA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   While the New York Yankees prepared to close a deal for Chicago
Cubs slugger Sammy Sosa, the Red Sox quietly bowed out of the
running, according to a major league source with direct knowledge
of the talks between the Cubs and Sox. The talks never advanced to
the point where the sides exchanged names, according to the source.
</P>
<P>
   Boston general manager Dan Duquette did make a phone call to the
Cubs, following up earlier contact made by one of his subordinates,
the source said, but club officials have not spoken in the last
four or five days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the Sox have been a player in this for a
while,'' the source said. ``Dan loves Sosa, but I don't think they
ever made a hard run for him. Whatever the reason, it never got
real serious. I don't know if it was because Dan decided he needed
pitching more, or didn't think the Sox could sign Sosa to an
extension, but no names were ever exchanged.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs, who scouted the Red Sox extensively since Boston first
expressed interest in Sosa two weeks ago, had put together a list
of names. Any package the Cubs would have wanted, the source said,
almost certainly would have included outfielder Trot Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Cubs were looking for big league help, too, not just
kids,'' the source said.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, while the Sox were in the midst of losing 8 of 12 to
the Yankees and Blue Jays, Duquette said the team's priority was to
upgrade its offensive production. Since that time, Nixon strained
his hamstring and the Sox called up three players from Pawtucket _
outfielders Curtis Pride and Izzy Alcantara and first baseman-DH
Morgan Burkhart _ and signed infielder Sean Berry, who was released
by the Milwaukee Brewers. Berry is in Fort Myers, Fla., getting
himself back into playing shape.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox have inquired about other infielders, including Rich
Aurilia of the Giants and Ed Sprague of the Padres. It appears the
Giants have decided not to move Aurilia, while the Sox have not
been happy with what the Padres want in return for Sprague.
</P>
<P>
   There are 4 1/2 weeks left before the trading deadline, plenty
of time for Duquette, who historically has gone to the final hours
before making a deal. According to another major league source, the
Red Sox might have interest in trying to rent Detroit Tigers
slugger Juan Gonzalez, who is eligible to become a free agent after
the season. But it is uncertain whether Gonzalez, who on Monday
rejected an offer from the Yankees, would be amenable to a deal.
</P>
<P>
   Some other big names could go on the market, including Astros
outfielder Moises Alou, if Houston can persuade him to waive his
no-trade clause. In the last few days, the Sox had accelerated
attempts to swing a deal for pitcher Scott Erickson, but those
talks apparently have gone nowhere.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
