<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-INATE-VOTE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAY STATE MOVES TO BAR JAILED FELONS FROM VOTING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK PHILLIPS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Massachusetts, one of three states that permits
prisoners to vote, is taking a step toward changing that as
lawmakers prepare to place a constitutional amendment on the
November ballot that would ban many inmates from voting.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican-sponsored change to the state constitution --
which will put Massachusetts closer in line with 47 other states --
would bar inmates convicted of felonies from voting while they are
incarcerated.
</P>
<P>
   House Minority Leader Francis Marini predicted the amendment
will easily be adopted when the House and Senate meet in a
constitutional convention Wednesday. The proposal _ which requires
passage by two successive legislative sesions before being put to
voters _ was approved 155-34 two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Using a reference to the game Monopoly, Marini said: ``It is
part of the penalty - you are in jail, you don't pass go, you don't
collect the $200, you don't vote until you get out.''
</P>
<P>
   Prisoners' voting rights have become a hotly debated issue among
criminal justice experts. Liberals argue stripping inmates of the
right to participate in elections disproportionately hurts
minorities, and call the measure a more subtle version of the poll
tax and literacy tests that Southern segregationists used to bar
blacks from voting. Racial minorities have a higher rate of
incarceration than whites.
</P>
<P>
   But conservatives argue that prisoners have proven by their
criminal acts to be untrustworthy citizens, and therefore should be
denied voting rights. They say convicts have only themselves to
blame and that society has the right to put limits on their civic
participation.
</P>
<P>
   Only Massachusetts, Maine, and Vermont now allow inmates to cast
ballots.
</P>
<P>
   The ban is being pushed by Governor Paul Cellucci. It would
apply to state, local and federal elections and be imposed on state
prisoners and those county inmates guilty of felonies.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the amendment argue that inmates, though
incarcerated, retain certain rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``When someone is sentenced to prison, they are sentenced to
lose their liberty, but not to forfeit every right they have as a
citizen,'' said Ann K. Lambert, legislative counsel for American
Civil Liberties Union of Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The constitution has worked well for hundreds of years and we
don't need to tinker with it to disenfranchise a segement of the
population,'' Lambert said.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Ogletree, the Harvard Law School professor and director
of its Criminal Justice Institute, said the measure lacks grounding
in moral reasoning and flies in the face of efforts to teach
prisoners basic lessons of democracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the clear signs of a strong democracy and participation
of citizens is exercising the right to vote,'' Ogletree said.
``This is one of the few ways to show them they can become a
respoonsible citizen.''
</P>
<P>
   Ogletree said the lawmakers should not be mixing the issue of
voting rights and crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope the rhetoric of crime does not blind them to the
reasons for participatory democracy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Marini rejected the argument that allowing prisons to vote
will prepare to them be better citizens once they are released.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their right to vote before they committed their crimes didn't
help them be part of better citizens,'' Marini said.
</P>
<P>
   Marini also dismissed the argument that the GOP amendment is
disproportionally tougher against minorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care one way or the other,'' Marini said. ``It is not
about race. It s about crime and people who serve felony sentences.
We ought to be less colorblind, not more.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, some Democrats are also privately expressing concern
that the presence of the amendment on the November ballot is in
part a political ploy to draw more conservative voters to the
polls. They said those voters would likely cast ballots for GOP
presidential candidate George W. Bush and for Cellucci's income tax
cut initiative also scheduled to appear on the ballot.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is great news for Bush and (tax-cut leader) Barbara
Anderson,'' said one top Beacon Hill Democrat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
