<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMA-SENATE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMA TARGETS THREE SENATORS IN PATIENTS' RIGHTS CAMPAIGN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The American Medical Association is targeting
Washington and two other states with Republican senators in tough
re-election races in a advertising campaign urging GOP lawmakers to
drop their opposition to a comprehensive patients' bill of rights.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation would give patients expanded rights to appeal
when health plans deny coverage. It would guarantee all 161 million
Americans with private health insurance the right to sue insurers
when harmed by delays or denial of treatment. The bill is backed by
the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an issue that cuts across all lines of age, race,
economic status and gender,'' Dr. Richard Corlin, president-elect
of the AMA, said in an interview Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The AMA campaign, which begins Wednesday, represents a change of
direction for the physicians' group _ long a conservative presence
in national politics. In 1965, the AMA targeted Washington state in
an unsuccessful campaign to block Congress' enactment of Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   The AMA is directing its latest message in this state at Sen.
Slade Gorton, a member of the Republican Senate leadership blocking
the AMA-backed bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``The patients' bill of rights is one vote from passage in the
U.S. Senate: He (Gorton) has the opportunity to be that one vote,
and put this bill on the president's desk for signature,'' Corlin
said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Nancy Auer, president-elect of the Washington State Medical
Association, noted that a state patients' rights bill was enacted
into law this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is obviously something that people in Washington agree
with,'' Auer said.
</P>
<P>
   Corlin, a gastroentrologist from Santa Monica, Calif., argued
that patients' rights to appeal are essential to what he called ``a
crucial issue of public need.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The appeals process must be external, it must be independent
and it must be binding on both parties,'' he argued.
</P>
<P>
   The AMA's initial campaign is also directed at Sens. John
Ashcroft, R-Mo., and Spencer Abraham, R-Mich.
</P>
<P>
   All were in the majority on a 51-48 Senate vote that blocked the
patients' rights bill June 8. With one absent Democrat likely to
vote for patients' rights, the AMA needs at least one of the three
targeted senators to switch and support the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Cynthia Bergman, Gorton's press secretary, said the senator is
``listening to the concerns of the local medical community.'' She
added that he is working on a ``grand compromise'' to allow
patients to hold health plans ``accountable.'' But she denounced
the AMA-backed legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The AMA's proposal would create a situation where patients
will be spending their time and money waging lengthy court battles
and lining the pockets of trial lawyers,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Health is an issue that has taken center stage in Senate races
around the country, including Gorton's.
</P>
<P>
   A major corporate lobbying group, the Business Roundtable,
recently ran newspaper ads praising Gorton for voting against
patients' rights proposals that, it claimed, would have led to
costly lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Americans for Job Security, an insurance industry committee, has
run a series of pro-Gorton TV spots. But the ads have focused on
topics far removed from patients' rights.
</P>
<P>
   The insurance-financed group has praised Gorton on education,
and recently hit the airwaves in Eastern Washington hailing the
senator's opposition to removing dams from the Snake River.
</P>
<P>
   Corlin denied that lawsuits will proliferate under patients'
rights legislation. When Texas enacted a 1997 accountability law
for health maintenance organizations, he added, ``the HMOs argued
it would open the floodgates to litigation.'' But only five
lawsuits have been filed since Gov. George W. Bush signed the bill
into law.
</P>
<P>
   He said it is necessary to get decisions on treatment out of the
hands of insurance companies. ``We have had health plans that
define `medical necessity' as the least intensive, lowest cost
alternative as determined by them,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Auer said patients' rights legislation is particularly needed in
emergency medicine. The legislation contains a clause mandating
insurance coverage in cases where, in her words, ``a prudent
layperson would have gone to the emergency room.''
</P>
<P>
   The AMA also plans to run ads thanking the four Republican
senators who defied party leaders voted for the patients' bill of
rights in the Senate. They are Sens. John McCain, R-Ariz., Peter
Fitzgerald, R-Ill., Lincoln Chafee, R-R.I., and Arlen Specter,
R-Pa.
</P>
<P>
   Forty-four Democratic senators voted for the bill. One
Democratic senator was absent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not into the issue of who Washington picks to be their
senators or representatives,'' Corlin said. ``We're simply saying
that Sen. Gorton needs to hear from his constituents.''
</P>
<P>
   Gorton has shown strong sensitivity to medical issues.
</P>
<P>
   He has introduced legislation to prevent drug companies from
selling prescription drugs in Canada and Mexico at a lower prices
than in the United States. Gorton extolled his proposal in a recent
taxpayer-financed mailing to Washington seniors.
</P>
<P>
   But Gorton also is a longtime ally of the insurance industry. He
is a leading sponsor of legislation to limit juries' awards of
punitive damages in product liability suits.
</P>
<P>
   The patients' rights issue has become a campaign theme for the
two Democrats vying for their party's nomination to oppose Gorton
in November.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gorton hasn't figured out yet that we need to restore the
patient-doctor relationship in determining a patient's health
needs. I'm glad the AMA is calling him on this,'' former Rep. Maria
Cantwell said yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   State Insurance commissioner Deborah Senn, at a breakfast for
her Senate campaign, Tuesday produced a succession of individuals
and families who were denied coverage by health insurers.
</P>
<P>
   Senn was introduced at the breakfast by Dylan Malone. Malone and
his wife, Christine, made national news in their fight with Aetna
when the insurer tried to cut off home nursing care for their
nine-month-old son, Ian. An angry call from Vice President Al Gore
caused the company to change its mind.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
