u a BC-MICHIGAN-SCHOLARSHIP-     06-27 0898
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICHIGAN-SCHOLARSHIP-SUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACLU SUES MICHIGAN, CITING BIAS IN GIVING COLLEGE AID 
</HEADLINE>
   By NICHOLE M. CHRISTIAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ The American Civil Liberties Union accused the state
of Michigan Tuesday of discriminating against minority students by
awarding thousands of merit scholarships solely on the basis of
standardized state test scores.
</P>
<P>
   In the lawsuit, filed in federal district court in Detroit, ACLU
lawyers asked that the state be prevented from using scores from
the Michigan Educational Assessment Program to award onetime
scholarships of up to $2,500 to college-bound high school seniors.
The lawsuit said the practice violated Title VI of the 1964 Civil
Rights Act.
</P>
<P>
   The group also wants a judge to order the Michigan Merit Award
Scholarship Program to re-evaluate students who were denied awards
this year and to include other gauges such as grade point averages
and extracurricular activities in its selection process. The ACLU
filed its suit Tuesday on behalf of five high school graduates, all
minorities, who failed to receive passing scores on the reading,
writing, science and math exams that make up the voluntary Michigan
test.
</P>
<P>
   The ACLU maintains that the Michigan test is flawed because
students in poor schools rarely receive the same amount of
preparation for the tests as student from wealthier districts and
private schools ``This is not an attack on the MEAP test,'' the
executive director of the Michigan ACLU, Kary Moss, said in a news
conference. ``What it is an attack on is the misuse of the MEAP. By
using the MEAP test alone, the state is essentially punishing
students for the schools they attend.''
</P>
<P>
   This fall, the state plans to give more than $100 million to
colleges and universities that have accepted the roughly 40,000
Michigan high school students who won scholarships. While states
are increasingly tying grade promotion and graduation to student
test scores, Michigan is considered the only one in the country to
base college tuition scholarships solely on test scores. Experts
say most states use a combination of measures in awarding tuition.
</P>
<P>
   The ACLU's lawsuit, which comes at a time of intense national
debate over standards in education and the use of test scores,
could set a precedent, much like a 1989 case in New York state. In
that case, a federal judge forbade officials to use SAT scores to
award the prestigious Regents and Empire scholarships, and the
ACLU's Women's Rights Project said that girls were
disproportionately discriminated against.
</P>
<P>
   ``A defeat in Michigan should stop other potential test-score
abusers in their tracks,'' said Robert Schaeffer, public education
director for the National Center for Fair and Open Testing, a
nonprofit advocacy group.
</P>
<P>
   State officials insisted that the test scores offer a clear
picture of academic achievement. ``A two-point grade average is not
the same in every school,'' said state Treasurer Mark Murray, whose
office administers the program. ``We have a uniform, unbiased
assessment instrument that is the same in every school. No student
has an advantage or disadvantage.''
</P>
<P>
   The program is paid for with money from the state's settlement
with tobacco manufacturers. Students who attend Michigan schools
are eligible for $2,500 in aid, while those who go out of state
receive $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   To further ensure equal access to a scholarship, Murray said
students who fail the test have two chances to retake it, and can
qualify by passing two of the four sections of the MEAP and
receiving at least a 24 on the ACT or 1170 on the SAT. The program
was created by the Legislature in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Heller, an assistant professor of education at the
University of Michigan who spent a year researching the
legislation's impact, said such allowances do little to close the
gap. Based on his research, he said one in three white students who
took all four of the tests in spring of 1999 received a
scholarship, whereas only one in 14 African-Americans, and one in
five Hispanics and Indians, received awards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michigan is the only state that uses a test like the MEAP test
as the sole criterion for awarding these scholarships,'' he said.
``In all other state measures such as high school rank, grade point
average or those in combination with a test like the SAT or ACT are
used to determine who is awarded these scholarships.''
</P>
<P>
   The ACLU lawsuit was based in part on Heller's research, which
was conducted independently months before the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vast majority of these awards are likely to go to students
who would have attended college anyway,'' Heller said.
</P>
<P>
   After maintaining a 3.45 grade point average through high school
and graduating sixth in her class at Beecher High School in Flint,
Mich., Bianca Kelly was certain that she would be selected as a
Michigan Merit Scholar. Even after learning she had scored a 19 on
the ACT and passed all but one of the MEAP tests _ science _ she
thought her record and extracurricular activities would help snare
an award. After all, Howard University had found reason enough to
accept her.
</P>
<P>
   But Michigan's scholarship program did not.
</P>
<P>
   Bianca is applying for loans and depending on help from her
family to pay tuition, room and board at Howard. ``It's just that I
worked so hard and it's like it still wasn't good enough,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-27-00 2109EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
