<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 21:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6617 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-R-AFGHAN-MERCHANTS-AR     06-27 0900
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-AFGHAN-MERCHANTS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT THESE PRICES, BUY TWO, AND USE ONE FOR PARTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating to add photo note)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Locator map is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase
one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By BARRY BEARAK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SPINBALDAK, Afghanistan _ Bargain hunters, perhaps it is time to
consider a shopping trip to Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
   Admittedly, it is a shlep, requiring a journey across Iran or
over the rugged mountains of the Hindu Kush or through the steep
gorges of the Khyber Pass.
</P>
<P>
   But in a place called Spinbaldak _ in the flat, desert terrain
near the Pakistani border _ there are ever-so-cheap cars,
television sets, stereos and cameras.
</P>
<P>
   Entire stores carry nothing but motor oil from England or sewing
machines from Japan or wheel rims from just about anywhere. There
are great deals on Vaseline Hair Tonic and Palmolive Shampoo. For
those who prefer to buy in bulk, there are sets of 72 Duralex
French tumblers, 10-packs of Sony tape cassettes and bars of Lux
soap by the gross.
</P>
<P>
   Spinbaldak is like a Price Club crossed with a Salvation Army
Store and a flea market. There are about 100 shops, each one spare
and decidedly inelegant. Most are merely open cargo containers _ 10
feet wide and 20 feet deep. There is no electricity. The climate
control seems stuck on the notch that calls for a dust storm.
</P>
<P>
   But service is friendly. ``Sprechen Sie Deutsch?'' called out
one merchant, Abdul Qadir. ``No? OK, I speak a little English, too.
And I give you the best deals.''
</P>
<P>
   Oddly enough, Qadir trades in television sets, which are banned
by the Taliban militia, rulers of most of the country. But his
customers are not Afghans. They are usually Pakistanis and Iranians
here to buy on the cheap for themselves or for resale back home.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you like?'' asked Qadir, a tall, persistent man standing
before two rows of televisions stacked eye-high, perhaps 70 in all.
``Samsung, Panasonic, Toshiba? Here look, I sell you a 29-inch Sony
for 10,000 rupees'' (about $200).
</P>
<P>
   There are some hitches to buying appliances in Spinbaldak, and
these became apparent as the sales pitch went on. ``I guarantee you
that 80 percent of my televisions work,'' Qadir said. ``And the
rest, easy to fix. No problem.''
</P>
<P>
   While the soap sold here is brand new, the appliances and cars
are all used. These are goods discarded by Japanese families and
gathered in large quantities by traders. They are then shipped to
Dubai in the United Arab Emirates and hauled into Afghanistan by
truck.
</P>
<P>
   The small-time merchants of Spinbaldak buy the wares by the
container-full, either on their own or with partners. They sell the
merchandise just as they bought it, unaware of whether it
functions. In this part of the world, repairs are cheap.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, there was no shortage of customers, but the new
military government in Pakistan seems to be unusually serious about
collecting customs duties at the border.
</P>
<P>
   In Spinbaldak, a three-hour drive from any sizable city, this
surge in enforcement is a bother. More border guards means more
people who must be bribed. Customers pass a far longer gantlet of
open palms.
</P>
<P>
   These greedy men in uniforms can be avoided by employing a
smuggler. Men with donkeys will carry just about anything along
more discreet trails. But this does add to the buyer's expense,
about $60 extra on that $200 television purchase. At the same time,
the condition of an appliance is unlikely to improve while it is
strapped to the back of a donkey.
</P>
<P>
   ``May I show you a camera?'' asked Abdul Bari, whose shop is
more eclectic than the others, filled with hair dryers, clocks,
ashtrays, motorcycle helmets and toaster ovens.
</P>
<P>
   He opened a large suitcase full of cameras, displayed in a heap
like ties at an end-of-the-season sale. ``For Nikon, I usually
charge more,'' he said amiably. ``But for you, my friend, the price
is the same, and I will give you one that will work for sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Down the way, Gul Khan was selling sewing machines. By his
guess, 90 percent were broken. ``But you cannot go wrong,'' he
said. ``I'll sell you this machine for 250 rupees'' _ $5 _ ``and if
you are worried about spare parts, you can buy two more at the same
price.''
</P>
<P>
   The Taliban are popular here. Indeed, when they began their
conquest of the country in 1994 they received financial support
from big traders who wanted the highways cleared of brigands. The
Taliban have made travel in Afghanistan safe again, and they, in
turn, make a hefty sum taxing cross-country shipments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before the Taliban, robbers would not only steal your vehicle,
they'd take your money and maybe even your clothes,'' said Amir
Muhammad, an auto dealer.
</P>
<P>
   Muhammad and his several associates run a car lot. The autos are
all used Japanese models. They were bought from traders in Dubai
who have a take-it-or-leave-it attitude. They allow the cars to be
started but not driven.
</P>
<P>
   He had a 1995 Toyota Land Cruiser on sale for a modest $5,600.
The interior was clean. The tires had treads. The engine operated
without a cough.
</P>
<P>
   But was it a good vehicle?
</P>
<P>
   Muhammad considered the question. ``If you want a cheap car,
this is the right place,'' he said bluntly. ``If you want a perfect
car, maybe you should go somewhere else.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
