u s BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-NYT &LR;      06-27 1011
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAPRIATI FINDS HER FORM WITH HELP FROM HER FIRST COACH, HER
FATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Belgium, France, Australia, the Netherlands)   By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ A bewildered Jennifer Capriati once
searched out a coach capable of salvaging the confidence she had
lost during the haze of her dysfunctional disappearance from
tennis. With her spirits in a puddle, she found a faith healer of
sorts in Harold Solomon to push her through a remarkable revival
last year.
</P>
<P>
   But he was not in the friends box of Court 1 Tuesday afternoon.
In mid-April, Capriati parted with Solomon, began a romance with a
talented but underachieving Belgian player, Xavier Malisse, and let
her discipline to diet slip. But with her ranking tumbling from
13th to 18th, and after a disturbing first-round exit in the French
Open, she did not reach for Solomon again to right her.
</P>
<P>
   Capriati turned to a familiar face. After she panted just a bit
Tuesday while overpowering 16th-seeded Dominique Van Roost, 6-2,
6-4, with fuel-injected ground strokes, Capriati stopped lumbering
and waved at a coach who once appeared to be part creator of her
dark teen-age funk: her husky father, Stefano. With him, she will
try to reinvent yet another comeback.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one thing I've learned, how to come back from feeling
down or not so confident,'' Capriati said. ``I can always get it
back, you know?''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, ``always'' seems to run out. But for this second day
of Wimbledon _ which left Andre Agassi and Lindsay Davenport, both
seeded second, with victories made simpler when their opponents
retired with injuries _ two players once branded as the next hot
items in American tennis had a chance to keep hope alive.
</P>
<P>
   At age 24, Capriati pulled off an upset in the first round, as
did the 23-year-old Jan-Michael Gambill. With herky-jerky forehands
and backhands, the 56th-ranked Gambill swiped the gloss off
Australia's paparazzi target, seventh-seeded Lleyton Hewitt, with a
6-3, 6-2, 7-5 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Gambill was once just like the 19-year-old Hewitt: fresh,
handsome and all the rage. Just one week removed from undoing Pete
Sampras at Queen's Club and several days into a news media frenzy,
Hewitt was facing high expectations. Gambill remembers the hype
well.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very tough to live up to what we have to live up to,
frankly,'' said Gambill, referring to his generation of players.
``Pete has done unbelievable. If I somehow make it to anywhere near
that level, I'd be very happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Gambill never wavered against Hewitt. With unshakable nerves, he
came up with 5 break points in 11 opportunities. When Hewitt had an
opening for a break, he sprayed the ball and converted just one of
six. It was odd to see Hewitt so flat. Normally, the buoyant
Australian can manufacture enough positive energy to overcome
pressure situations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just had one of those days,'' he said. ``There wasn't much
to get pumped up about.''
</P>
<P>
   Agassi was different in his ability to come with an edge on
call. He was playing against a qualifier, the American Taylor Dent,
who was ranked 256th but very capable of unveiling the game of his
life on Center Court. At least for half an hour. With volleys that
kissed the baselines, a 130-mile-an-hour serve that generated eight
aces and with pinpoint approach shots, Dent unsettled a crowd
assembled to rave about Steffi Graf's domed beau. In 24 minutes,
Dent had the first set, 6-2.
</P>
<P>
   Unfazed, Agassi sharpened his focus and took a 2-6, 6-3, 6-0,
4-0 lead when Dent left the court after falling awkwardly on his
right knee. In Dent's wake, there was a question: is this unknown
19-year-old from California, the son of the former Australian Davis
Cup player Phil Dent, another American hope?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always hard to say,'' Agassi said. ``There's a lot you
need to have to succeed out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Having just the right support group is as critical as having the
tools. Capriati appeared to have just the right mix with Solomon.
Fresh off her success at the U.S. Open, she zipped through the draw
at the Australian Open. On her way to the semifinals, she was
effusive about the miracles Solomon had worked on her will. Then,
everything changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not always going to last forever, be a forever thing,''
Capriati said. ``Just one of those things. We didn't see things,
you know, the same way.''
</P>
<P>
   Some on the tour wonder if Capriati's budding romance started
taking priority over her practice schedule and suspect Malisse's
spotty work ethic as a player has rubbed off on her. Whatever the
case, Solomon has been dropped, and her father has stepped in at
the controls again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just that he's known my game ever since, well, he started
me playing,'' Capriati said. ``Really, just he knows, I guess, the
way to tell me things. He just says the little things here and
there the simple way he knows that will make me really understand
it.'' MATCH POINTS
</P>
<P>
   Six seeded players were upset Tuesday. Beyond Dominique Van
Roost and Lleyton Hewitt, 13th-seeded Amelia Mauresmo lost to
47th-ranked Gala Leon Garcia, 4-6, 6-3, 7-5; seventh-seeded
Nathalie Tauziat was beaten by 31st-ranked Kim Clijsters, 6-3, 3-6,
6-2; Tommy Haas upset his fellow German Nicolas Kiefer, seeded
13th, 5-7, 6-4, 6-2, 6-3; and Julie Halard-Decugis, the 14th-seeded
woman, lost to Kristie Boogert , 7-6 (4), 0-6, 6-1. . . . Lindsay
Davenport was in an uncomfortable position when her friend and
doubles partner, Corina Morariu, slipped in the second set of their
first-round match. Morariu lost her footing, fell to the grass and
injured her left shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   On a day when she was testing her sore back and getting good
results, Davenport was in control, 6-3, 1-0, when Morariu retired,
but she felt uneasy with the way her victory came about. ``It's
very bittersweet,'' Davenport said. ``It's good I won the first set
with two breaks. I was going to have break point at the beginning
of the second, but then when something like that happens to a good
friend, it's terrible.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
