<SLUG> BC-WOMEN-SPORTS-MAGAZINE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONDE NAST CLOSING WOMEN'S SPORTS &AMP; FITNESS MAGAZINE 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALEX KUCZYNSKI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After less than four years of publication, Women's
Sports &AMP; Fitness, an enthusiast magazine for women that was perhaps
best known for featuring the volleyball player Gabrielle Reece on
its cover more times than any other magazine in the world _ will
cease publication with the September issue.
</P>
<P>
   The move signals a continued trend toward watching the bottom
line at Conde Nast, which publishes Women's Sports. In March, S.I.
Newhouse Jr., chairman of Conde Nast and its parent, Advance
Publications, announced that he would temporarily shut Details
magazine, a magazine for young men, and transfer it to Fairchild
Publications, which Advance bought last summer, for a makeover.
</P>
<P>
   The demise of Women's Sports came one day after EMAP Petersen
announced that it will cease publication of Sport magazine, a
general-interest monthly that has been published since 1946.
</P>
<P>
   From the first issue in 1997, Women's Sports &AMP; Fitness ambled
from one editorial identity to another. First titled Conde Nast
Women's Sports &AMP; Fitness, the magazine changed its name to Women's
Sports &AMP; Fitness in 1998. Its publication schedule went from
monthly to every other month and then back.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine recently raised its rate base _ the circulation
guaranteed to advertisers _ to 650,000, but Conde Nast executives
said the additional circulation was acquired through off-price
subscription offers and was not reliable over the long term.
Overall circulation grew by 9.9 percent for the six-month period
ended Dec. 31, but newsstand sales fell by 3.9 percent during the
same period, according to the Audit Bureau of Circulations.
</P>
<P>
   James Truman, Conde Nast's editorial director and the editor who
conceived of the idea for a women's sports magazine, said that
Women's Sports never found an audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt we were publishing a very good magazine, and we had
been really holding on with it for a long time, 18 months,'' he
said. ``We kept hoping the audience would materialize, but it did
not.''
</P>
<P>
   Advertising pages were up _ by 41.9 percent through July to 346
pages, according to Mediaweek Magazine _ but not sufficiently.
Advertisers never flocked to the title, citing its lack of focus.
Lucy Schulte Danziger, the magazine's editor in chief, said Tuesday
that she would resign.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-27-00 2115EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000627.0361 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 21:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6621 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-ZIMBABWE-ELECTIONS-AR     06-27 1081
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ZIMBABWE-ELECTIONS-ART-820(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZIMBABWE'S RULING PARTY SUFFERS BIG SETBACK IN PARLIAMENTARY
ELECTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By RACHEL L. SWARNS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARARE, Zimbabwe _ In a pointed rejection of President Robert
Mugabe, voters here have taken away what was his governing party's
almost unchallenged authority in Parliament by electing a powerful,
new opposition party to more than a third of the seats.
</P>
<P>
   Counting in the closely watched election ended early Wednesday
with the new party winning 57 seats in the 150-member Parliament, a
share large enough to prevent Mugabe's party from unilaterally
changing the constitution, as it has been able to do for more than
a decade.
</P>
<P>
   For years, Mugabe's party has controlled all but three seats in
Parliament, giving it virtually unlimited power over lawmaking and
governance. His party, the Zimbabwe African National
Union-Patriotic Front, will still control a majority of seats. But
analysts agree that the election this past weekend will inevitably
reshape legislative politics here, introducing consultation and
negotiation into a chamber that has rarely needed or allowed it.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech broadcast on national television Tuesday night,
Mugabe promised to deal with the new opposition as lawmakers
wrestle with the nation's economic problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look forward to working with the new Parliament as together
we grapple with the pressing challenges of improving the livelihood
of our people and developing our nation.''
</P>
<P>
   And as supporters of the nine-month old opposition party cheered
their victory Tuesday, honking horns and dancing in impromptu
sidewalk celebrations, other government officials also admitted
that the world they knew had dramatically changed. After years of
apathy, frustrated urban voters had finally turned their backs on a
governing party that had failed to focus on the issues of
joblessness, soaring inflation and government corruption.
</P>
<P>
   ``When there are diverse voices, the government of the day is on
its toes,'' said Jonathan Moyo, a spokesman for the governing
party, known as ZANU-PF. ``And there is no doubt that for the next
five years we are going to be on our toes.''
</P>
<P>
   Mugabe's party won only 62 of the 120 contested seats, most of
them in rural areas where the party's support has traditionally
been strongest, the final tallies showed. (Under the constitution,
the public elects only 120 of the 150 members of Parliament. The
president appoints 20 members. And local chiefs select the other
10.)
</P>
<P>
   The opposition party, the Movement for Democratic Change, won
its seats in lopsided victories in the country's urban centers.
Almost overnight, the party, known as the MDC, became the most
powerful opposition force in Zimbabwe's history.
</P>
<P>
   In a news conference Tuesday morning, the party's leader, Morgan
Tsvangirai, generally praised the weekend's peaceful voting. But he
said his party is also carefully scrutinizing the results and is
considering challenging the count in about 20 races.
</P>
<P>
   The races include those in which the MDC had lost by a margin of
500 or less and those in which intimidation and political violence,
which has claimed at least 26 lives since March, may have
influenced the vote. Tsvangirai, who lost his race for Parliament,
plans to challenge the result in his own district.
</P>
<P>
   Once that is resolved, Tsvangirai said he would turn his
attention to running for president in the year 2002, facing off
against Mugabe, 76, if Mugabe chooses to run again. And in the
meantime, he urged people to work together across party line to
rebuild trust and to improve the unraveling economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Zimbabweans have to learn to work together,'' said Tsvangirai,
reflecting on what has been a bitter and divisive campaign, as the
cameras flashed and the television cameras rolled. ``This election
result means that neither Zanu-PF nor President Mugabe can go it
alone.''
</P>
<P>
   It has certainly been one of the most extraordinary political
campaigns in Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in this nation's 20-year history, opposition
candidates contested all 120 parliamentary seats that are up for
election, riding a wave of voter frustration and anxiety. For the
first time, dozens of politicians defected from Mugabe's party to
run as independent candidates, many of them men in their 30s and
40s who saw little future for themselves in a party still dominated
by aging freedom fighters.
</P>
<P>
   And for the first time ever, the white minority, which still
controls much of the economy here, woke up from years of political
hibernation to bankroll the MDC, allowing the fledgling party to
wage a successful campaign, which was critical since the party had
virtually no access to government controlled media.
</P>
<P>
   The unprecedented political activity owes much to growing public
frustration over Mugabe's often iron-fisted style of governance,
the unraveling economy and government corruption. And for many
whites, the government's increasingly hostile racial rhetoric and
support of the recent spate of land invasions became increasingly
intolerable.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In the past decade, the percentage of people living in poverty
has surged to more than 60 percent from 40 percent. Wages have
fallen to pre-independence levels. The government can no longer pay
creditors, buy adequate fuel or supply medicines to hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   And by early this year, it was clear that Mugabe, who was once
revered for expanding access for the entire population to schools
and clinics during his first decade in power, was no longer
unassailable. In February, in an astonishing rebuke to the ruling
party, the nation voted against a constitutional referendum that
would have expanded President Mugabe's power.
</P>
<P>
   And this weekend, energized by frustrations with what had
virtually become a one-party state, voters turned out in heavy
numbers. Election officials estimate that about 60 percent of the
5.8 million registered voters went to 120 polling stations on
Saturday and Sunday, up from about 26 percent in the parliamentary
elections of 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Voters also ousted several of Mugabe's cabinet ministers,
including Simon Moyo, the tourism minister, Thenjiwe Lesabe, the
job creation minister and Sydney Sekeramayi, the security minister.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In their places, voters elected opposition candidates and
political novices who had experienced the hardships of ordinary
people. Among the newly elected is Evelyn Masaiti, 35, a high
school science teacher who struggles to feed her family and was
repeatedly intimidated and attacked by supporters of the governing
party.
</P>
<P>
   Benni Tumbare Mutasa, 44, runs a local butchery and beauty
salon, and can no longer afford to buy spare parts for his trucks.
Tafadzwa Musekiwa, 24, is a university graduate who has been unable
to find a job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel over the moon,'' Musekiwa said Tuesday. ``All night
yesterday, I didn't sleep.''
</P>
<P>
   Mugabe had campaigned heavily on the pledge that he would make
good on his promise to redistribute fertile land, which is still
mostly owned by the tiny white minority here. He supported the
invasions of hundreds of white-owned farms by black squatters and
was widely blamed for supporting the waves of political violence.
He repeatedly disparaged opposition party members as puppets of the
whites.
</P>
<P>
   Mugabe seemed more than ready Tuesday night to reconcile.
Prominent members of his party are already admitting that they will
have to change their message and, perhaps, reshuffle their ranks to
appeal to a younger and increasingly urban population.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech Tuesday night, Mugabe said, ``There is a great
expectation in our country, around the land, which is still to come
to our people in a big way, and around the economy, which is going
through a bad patch and for which lasting answers will have to be
found.''
</P>
<P>
   For many ordinary people in this country, that is the message
they have been longing to hear.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is important at the end of the day is that they solve our
problems, whoever is in charge,'' said Edwin Ncube, 47, an
accountant, who voted for the MDC this weekend. ``All we want to
see is the economy picking up, life getting better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
