<HEADLINE>
TV NOTES: `SURVIVOR' AND CBS  

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The ``Survivor'' connection to CBS News will be extended next
week when the news magazine program ``48 Hours'' broadcasts a
segment featuring two of that adventure show's contestants in an
edition devoted to the subject ``The Price of Fame.''
</P>
<P>
   The segment, which will offer a profile of two of the people who
signed up to compete for a $1 million prize on ``Survivor,'' the
hit CBS summer series, will be one of four reports on the program
exploring the lengths to which Americans are willing to go to to
achieve some measure of fame. The program, normally seen on
Thursday nights at 10, is to run as a special next Wednesday at 10.
There will also be a Thursday edition.
</P>
<P>
   That Wednesday is the same night that ``Survivor'' will be
broadcasting its fifth episode at 8, leading in directly to the
first episode of CBS' other heavily publicized summer reality
series, ``Big Brother,'' at 9 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Both shows have already become closely tied to CBS News, mainly
through regular features on ``The Early Show.'' The news announcer
from that show, Julie Chen, will participate directly in ``Big
Brother,'' supplying the voice that will tell the contestants in
the competition which one of them has been banished each week.
</P>
<P>
   Chen's role in ``Big Brother'' has initiated concerns within
some quarters of CBS News that ratings concerns are eliminating
barriers between news and entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Zirinsky, the executive producer of ``48 Hours,'' said
that the ``Survivor'' segment on her news program had nothing to do
with a network-wide promotional push for the reality shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody from the entertainment division suggested I do this,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   But she said that she had long planned to do a show on fame and
that the ``Survivor'' participants seemed a natural fit with that
theme. ``These are people who agreed to go to this island because
they are lusting after fame,'' Zirinsky said. ``We're looking to
answer the question: Why are these people willing to do these
things?''
</P>
<P>
   The idea for the fame program began, Zirinsky said, when a ``48
Hours'' crew was following an 11-year-old singer, Sammie Bush. The
program trailed him for a year, during which he did in fact emerge
as a young singing sensation.
</P>
<P>
   The program will also present profiles of the actors who starred
in the award winning ``Whass-up?'' commercials for Budweiser.
</P>
<P>
   Almost inevitably, Zirinsky is also including an interview with
Darva Conger, who exploded into fame on the year's most discredited
reality show, ``Who Wants To Marry a Multi-Millionaire?'' and then
spent months disdaining that performance in interview and is now
topping off the collision with fame by appearing nude in Playboy.
</P>
<P>
   ``People seem to believe they have an inalienable right to be
famous,'' Zirinsky said.
</P>
<P>
   As for the chances that her program might be accused of being
swept up in the ``Survivor'' tidal wave sweeping CBS, Zirinsky
said: ``I don't think that would be fair. We're doing an honest
deal here on fame. I still believe in the total separation of
church and state.''
</P>
<P>
   _ BILL CARTER
</P>
<P>
   POKEMON, UNCHOSEN
</P>
<P>
   Pokemon, it seems, may not be immune to children's very rapid
aging process, in which 1.5 adult years can be equal to, say, 86
kiddie years.
</P>
<P>
   Following the fizzles of the Teen-age Mutant Ninja Turtles and
the Mighty Morphin Power Rangers crazes, there are signs that the
appetite for all things Pokemon, once considered insatiable, is
starting to subside.
</P>
<P>
   One bellwether: Quarterly ratings figures released Tuesday show
that viewership is shrinking for ``Pokemon,'' the cartoon show
based on the Nintendo video game that runs at various times
throughout the week on the WB network.
</P>
<P>
   According to the latest figures, the audience for the show's
flagship broadcast on Saturdays at 10 a.m. was 1.8 million strong
during the second quarter of 2000, down by nearly 1 million viewers
from the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, the household audience for the 9 a.m. Saturday showing
of the cartoon was down by nearly 1 million viewers compared with
its February debut in that time slot. Ratings for the 4 p.m.
weekday broadcasts were off a bit as well.
</P>
<P>
   One thing WB executives can tell their sponsors is that the
second quarter includes some of those lazy days in June when school
is out and youngsters are soaking in the sun rather than the
cathode rays of the television.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the show did not have the same sort of audience declines for
from the first to second quarters in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   That is delighting executives at other networks that run
children's programming, especially Nickelodeon, the cable channel
that had held first place on Saturday mornings for two years until
``Pokemon'' came on strong in the fall and helped WB take it over.
</P>
<P>
   With the show's decline, Nickelodeon's ``Rugrats'' has reclaimed
its place as the No. 1 show in children's television, returning
Nickelodeon to its former state of Saturday morning glory.
</P>
<P>
   Executives at WB said they believed that they had nothing to
fear and that ``Pokemon'' would continue to show strength.
</P>
<P>
   On July 21 Warner Brothers will release the second Pokemon
movie. When the first feature was released last year, it did
extremely well and helped the entire Pokemon franchise. The WB
executives said that they believed the same thing would happen this
year and that the film would help their ratings into the fall.
</P>
<P>
   _ JIM RUTENBERG
</P>
<P>
   CHALLENGE TO CNN
</P>
<P>
   The 24-hour cable news competition, it appears, is continuing to
close in on CNN, which, until the mid-1990s, was the only national
all-news network.
</P>
<P>
   CNBC, the financial network, was watched in more homes per day
than CNN during the second quarter of 2000, representing the first
quarterly ratings period in which that has happened. CNBC was
watched in an average of 280,000 homes per day compared with
253,000 for CNN from April through late June, according to Nielsen
Media Research statistics.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, CNN faced increased competition from the Fox News
Channel. Its household audience grew by 20 percent, an average
132,000 households, between the second quarter of 1999 and the
second quarter of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   During that same period CNN's audience decreased by 35 percent,
marking its worst second quarter in a decade.
</P>
<P>
   CNN executives, who recently celebrated the channel's 20th
anniversary, have been contending with reports about their ratings
for some time now and have blamed the figures on a slow news
period.
</P>
<P>
   They have maintained that Fox and CNBC have separate reasons for
their audience gains. While the overall news cycle is slow, there
has been plenty of significant financial news for CNBC. And Fox's
20 percent growth in audience coincides with a 22 percent gain in
subscribing households.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, MSNBC is in 14 percent more households than it was
last year, yet its audience was 17 percent smaller.
</P>
<P>
   CNN did have some positive news: It had 19 of the top 20
most-watched programs among all-news channels during the period.
</P>
<P>
   _ JIM RUTENBERG
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
