<SLUG> BC-TV-WRESTLING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIACOM WRESTS WRESTLING SHOWS OFF USA CABLE 
</HEADLINE>
   By BILL CARTER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The most popular weekly programs on cable television, hourlong
wrestling shows produced by World Wrestling Federation
Entertainment Inc., will leave the USA cable network in the fall
and move to cable channels owned by Viacom as a result of a
decision Tuesday in a Delaware court.
</P>
<P>
   The decision, which awarded the rights to WWF programs to Viacom
based on a higher bid that the court said USA had not matched as
required by its contract, was widely seen as a serious blow to USA
Networks Inc., which had sued to try to prevent Viacom from buying
away the five hours of wrestling shows that have been carried on
USA.
</P>
<P>
   Sumner Redstone, the chairman of Viacom, said, ``This is a much
more important victory for us than most people know.'' In
particular, he said, the shift will benefit the TNN cable channel,
which was previously owned by CBS and is now part of Viacom's MTV
Networks. The channel, once known as The Nashville Network, had
mainly been known for programming oriented to country music fans.
</P>
<P>
   Viacom plans to revamp TNN programming in the coming television
season, and wrestling will be the biggest part of that improvement,
Redstone said.
</P>
<P>
   Among other WWF programs, two Monday night wrestling shows,
``Raw Is War'' and ``Live Wire,'' which are routinely watched more
than any other shows on cable television, will shift to TNN.
</P>
<P>
   ``That will surely mean a big increase in the distribution of
the channel,'' Redstone said. ``TNN has not been in the same class
as other MTV networks, and now it clearly will be. As a result of
this and other programming we plan for that channel, TNN will
become a much more valuable asset for Viacom.''
</P>
<P>
   The loss of wrestling may have the opposite effect on USA,
though the channel's executives took pains Tuesday to try to play
down the effect on the channel. In a statement, Stephen Chao, the
president of USA Cable said, ``We would have preferred a different
decision but, as we said, the loss of the WWF will have a
negligible effect on our ratings and a positive effect on our
profits.''
</P>
<P>
   USA executive had previously tried to argue that wrestling was
not all that important to the USA channel because other programming
could replace it and because it was never as profitable as its
ratings would seem to indicate because the wrestling company itself
took most of the advertising revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Chao, nor Barry Diller, the chairman of USA Networks,
nor any other USA executive would comment further, said Ron Sado, a
USA spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   But one executive involved in the lawsuit noted that USA
executives had testified that WWF programming was highly profitable
and amounted to a crown jewel in the schedule because it brought
more viewers to other USA programs.
</P>
<P>
   USA executives have not said what programs will replace
wrestling, though it had previously announced a lineup of potential
new shows including a comedy about warring neighbors and a drama
about female bounty hunters.
</P>
<P>
   The court case centered on USA's contention that it did not have
to match every aspect of a Viacom offer to satisfy a clause in its
contract that allowed its deal with the wrestling company to
continue as long as it matched any new offer.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, USA argued that it should not have to match
promises like promotion on radio and billboards and sale to
international television channels and an agreement not to pre-empt
the wrestling shows regularly, as USA Network had done with
programs like the Westminster Kennel Club Dog Show. The decision by
Chancellor William B. Chandler III of Delaware Chancery Court found
that USA was obligated to match on those points, though not on some
others, like carrying a new package of football games being
produced by the wrestling company.
</P>
<P>
   Viacom plans to carry games of the new XFL football league on
TNN on Sunday afternoons as well as on one of its broadcast
outlets, the UPN network, on Sunday nights. It will also shift one
of the WWF wrestling shows, ``Sunday Night Heat,'' to MTV, where it
will have a younger, more rock-music-oriented format.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Viacom has promised to stage WWF events at its
theme parks and to stage pay-per-view wrestling events at its
theaters in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   The decision against USA comes at a time of transition in part
of its ownership. USA Networks is 45 percent owned by the Seagram
Corp., which is being acquired by the French media company Vivendi.
One executive close to the deal said Tuesday that the loss of the
wrestling programming was unlikely to have any effect on the
Seagram-Vivendi deal.
</P>
<P>
   Redstone, who has had previous battles with Diller, most notably
a financial battle over the Paramount studio in 1994, which
Redstone also won, said, ``I don't feel badly about winning against
my friend Barry Diller.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
