u f BC-WORLDCOM-SPRINT-2TAKE     06-27 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLDCOM-SPRINT-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICE DEPARTMENT MOVES TO BLOCK $115 BILLION WORLDCOM-SPRINT
MERGER 
</HEADLINE>
   By SETH SCHIESEL   with DAVID LEONHARDT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Justice Department sought to curb the headlong consolidation
of the telecommunications industry Tuesday by moving to block
WorldCom Inc.'s proposed $115 billion acquisition of Sprint Corp.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time in the face of opposition in Europe, WorldCom
and Sprint formally withdrew their deal from consideration by the
European Commission, reserving the option to file again in the
future.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department, while seeking an injunction against the
deal in federal court, cited concerns that the combined company
would stifle competition on the Internet and in the long-distance
telephone industry. Industry executives said the filing probably
doomed the deal, which was agreed to last year and would have
created an Internet powerhouse and the nation's second-largest
long-distance phone company after AT&AMP;T. Two days ago, the European
Commission's top antitrust regulator said he was unlikely to
support the deal, contending that it would place too much Internet
traffic under control of one company.
</P>
<P>
   Regarding their plans, the companies said only that they would
review their options. WorldCom and Sprint could fight the
government in court, but executives from the companies have said in
the past that they would almost surely abandon their deal in the
face of a government suit.
</P>
<P>
   People close to the companies said that while Sprint and
WorldCom remained unlikely to battle the Justice Department through
an entire trial, they might file preliminary objections to the suit
in hopes of reopening negotiations to win approval.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Sprint fell $1.1875, to $58.375, while Worldcom stock
rose $2.1875, to $39.6875.
</P>
<P>
   The attempted merger is the biggest the department has ever
tried to block, dwarfing the previous largest _ the Lockheed Martin
Corp.'s $8.3 billion plan to acquire the Northrop Grumman Corp.,
which would have created a behemoth in the military industry.
Lockheed and Northrop abandoned their pact in 1998 in the face of
the Justice Department's opposition.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's move indicates that the Justice Department intends to
draw limits, even amid the multibillion dollar consolidation in
various sectors of the telecommunications industry, as companies of
all size and description try to expand their geographic and
technical reach.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, AT&AMP;T won conditional approval from the
Federal Communications Commission for its $58 billion acquisition
of MediaOne Group Inc., one of the nation's biggest cable
television companies. And less than two weeks later Bell Atlantic
won the FCC's conditional approval of the company's $53 billion
acquisition of the GTE Corp., a deal that will create the nation's
biggest phone company. In both cases, the Justice Department had
already signed off on the mergers, provided that certain conditions
were met.
</P>
<P>
   One merger still pending antitrust and regulatory review is
America Online Inc.'s proposed $165 billion acquisition of Time
Warner Inc. That deal would create the biggest company in both
traditional and electronic media.
</P>
<P>
   But the America Online-Time Warner deal could have an easier
time with regulators than the WorldCom-Sprint merger, at least on
antitrust grounds. Because Worldcom and Sprint currently compete in
many of the same markets, their merger appears much more vulnerable
to a traditional antitrust challenge than the deal between America
Online and Time Warner, which are not significant competitors in
any of their far-flung operations.
</P>
<P>
   Antitrust regulators traditionally consider whether a merger
would reduce competition and, as a result, limit customer choices.
In its filing with the U.S. District Court in Washington, the
Justice Department made just such an argument, saying that a
Sprint-WorldCom merger would reduce competition in markets where
the two companies are currently rivals.
</P>
<P>
   ``This merger threatens to undermine the competitive gains
achieved since the department challenged AT&AMP;T's monopoly 25 years
ago,'' Attorney General Janet Reno said in a statement Tuesday.
``It is critical to our economy that we preserve competition for
services that many of us rely upon in our everyday lives _
long-distance calls, data network services and Internet
connections.''
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference, Joel Klein, the assistant attorney general
in charge of the Justice Department's antitrust division, said that
his main concern about the WorldCom-Sprint deal was that it would
reduce the number of major competitors in the long-distance market
from three to two.
</P>
<P>
   WorldCom acquired the MCI Communications Corp. in 1998 and still
uses the MCI brand for some products. AT&AMP;T controls roughly half of
the $80 billion long-distance business while WorldCom currently
controls about 20 percent and Sprint about 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference between two and three bidders can be very, very
significant,'' Klein said in an interview. ``They're both on the
tube and in telemarketing to compete for your business. When you
take one of them out, most consumers are aware, that restricts your
options,''
</P>
<P>
   Similar considerations would probably not apply in the America
Online-Time Warner deal, since the companies generally do not
compete in the same markets. The exception is areas where Time
Warner's Roadrunner cable modem Internet-access service competes
against America Online's Internet service over telephone lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sprint-WorldCom is irrelevant to AOL-Time Warner,'' said Scott
Cleland, a regulatory analyst in Washington for the Precursor
Group, an independent research firm. ``WorldCom-Sprint is a very
different sort of merger in that it is a straight horizontal
merger, and AOL-Time Warner is a vertical merger. The horizontal
mergers have a lot of precedents and very clear guidelines.
Vertical mergers have very few guidelines and few standards so it's
much more an unknown.''
</P>
<P>
   Cleland said the closer comparison for AOL-Time Warner would be
the AT&AMP;T-MediaOne deal that the government has already approved.
</P>
<P>
   That comparison is cold comfort for WorldCom.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   People close to WorldCom and Sprint had said last week that the
two companies were considering big concessions _ including a
complete spin-off of Sprint's long-distance telephone business and
Internet operation _ to appease antitrust regulators. But in the
end, the concession offer never came, those people said, because
the Justice Department wanted the companies to also agree to a
spin-off of Sprint's local phone business. WorldCom was reluctant
to agree, while Sprint was adamantly opposed, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Klein refused to discuss details of his negotiations with the
two companies.
</P>
<P>
   WorldCom could consider some concessions because its main goal
in acquiring Sprint was to gain control of Sprint's extensive
wireless telephone network _ a business in which WorldCom has a
negligible presence.
</P>
<P>
   In a terse statement Tuesday, WorldCom said only: ``WorldCom was
advised today that the U.S. Department of Justice intends to file
suit to block WorldCom's proposed merger with Sprint. WorldCom will
promptly review its options with Sprint.''
</P>
<P>
   J. Richard Devlin, Sprint's general counsel, said in a
statement: ``We are disappointed that we have been unable to
convince the Justice Department that the merger is in the best
interest of the American public and would advance competition.''
</P>
<P>
   Investors Tuesday were already trying to handicap the companies'
next moves. If WorldCom and Sprint do in fact tear up their deal,
WorldCom will still lack a wireless operation and will probably
still seek one.
</P>
<P>
   The most likely candidates are Nextel Communications Inc., based
in Reston, Va., and the VoiceStream Wireless Corp., based in
Bellevue, Wash. Shares of both companies rose Tuesday on
speculation that either could become the next potential target for
WorldCom. Nextel stock rose by $1.4375, to $60.625, while shares of
VoiceStream closed at $126, up $4.875 in Nasdaq trading.
</P>
<P>
   If Sprint remains single, its most likely consolidation partners
appear to be the BellSouth Corp. and Deutsche Telekom of Germany.
BellSouth, the only one of the seven original Baby Bell local phone
companies that has not yet participated in a major merger, lost a
bidding war for Sprint with WorldCom last year.
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Telekom, meanwhile, has long cast about for entry into
the U.S. market, and until last year was a partner with Sprint in
an international venture called Global One. Each of those
companies, however, could face serious regulatory or legal hurdles.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth, as one of the regional Bell companies that emerged
from the breakup of the old American Telephone &AMP; Telegraph Co. in
1984, is currently not allowed to sell long-distance communications
services to customers in its core Southeastern region.
Long-distance, of course, is Sprint's main business.
</P>
<P>
   Under current laws and regulations, Deutsche Telekom, Germany's
main phone company, would probably face few serious hurdles to
acquiring Sprint. But Tuesday, Sen. Ernest Hollings, D-S.C.,
introduced a bill that could block such a deal.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Hollings bill, companies in which foreign governments
own a stake of 25 percent or more would not be allowed to acquire
U.S.-based communications companies. The German government owns 58
percent of Deutsche Telekom.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
