u e BC-TRIXIE-FILM-REVIEW-NY     06-27 0936
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRIXIE-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TRIXIE': NAIVE DETECTIVE PACKING GOOFY MALAPROPISMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Production notes at end of review) 
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Few filmmakers are as generous toward actors as Alan Rudolph.
That's why they flock to be in his films, even though the chances
of a box office hit are next to nil. Like his actor-friendly
mentor, Robert Altman, Rudolph is a maverick who has always gone
his own way, strewing behind him a filmography (now 17 movies) the
bulk of which might be described as ambitious failures.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trixie,'' this director's latest experiment in combining
genres, tantalizingly (and accurately) bills itself as a
``screwball film noir.'' But with its off-kilter mixture of menace
and cornball humor attached to a sketchy, sluggishly paced story
whose holes are left gaping, it is unlikely to break the pattern.
</P>
<P>
   The sad thing is that there is enough to admire about ``Trixie''
to make you wish it were much, much better, but not enough for the
movie to be called even a qualified success. Still, ``Trixie'' is a
comeback of sorts; it isn't half as frustrating as the surreal
sludge Rudolph left behind last year with his impenetrable film
adaptation of Kurt Vonnegut's ``Breakfast of Champions.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Trixie'' is above all a showcase for Emily Watson, who appears
in almost every scene as the title character, a saucer-eyed,
virginal amateur sleuth from Chicago (Watson lays on an extra-thick
Midwestern accent) investigating a murder in a lakeside casino
resort somewhere in the Far West. If Trixie is a much less meaty
part than Watson's roles in ``Breaking the Waves'' and ``Hilary and
Jackie,'' it still allows her ample space for flexing her talent,
starting with that accent. And underneath the character's wary,
prudish exterior lurks an erotic spark waiting to ignite.
</P>
<P>
   With her carefully exaggerated accent, this squeaky-clean
character often seems like a first cousin of Frances McDormand's
intrepid, unfailingly polite police investigator in ``Fargo,'' the
far superior Coen brothers film to which ``Trixie'' bears a
sometimes uncomfortable resemblance. In much the same way that the
Coens fetishized their heroine's squareness to throw us off balance
by gently mocking her decency, Watson's Trixie is given to naively
spouting slogans using the wrong words. ``You've got to grab the
bull by the tail and look it in the eye,'' she blurts. Or ``That's
the truth, the hole in the truth and nothing but the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Giving the character one or two goofy malapropisms might have
been a refreshing touch. But the screenplay (written by Rudolph
from a story he concocted with John Binder) makes the mistake of
basing much of its humor on Trixie's continual verbal stumbling,
and the joke is quickly beaten to death.
</P>
<P>
   Trixie's adventures begin in the casino where while working as
an undercover detective she attracts the lustful attention of Dex
Lang (Dermot Mulroney), a bar-hopping Don Juan who works as a gofer
for Red Rafferty (Will Patton) a sleazy local developer. In the
movie's best scene, Trixie winds up with Dex on Red's boat, along
with Red's drunken, pill-popping girlfriend, a pathetically inept
pop-country singer named Dawn Sloane (Lesley Ann Warren). Also
aboard is Drummond Avery (Nick Nolte), a hard-drinking senator who
is Red's partner in several kinds of mischief. In a scene rumbling
with undercurrents of violence and sex, Trixie tussles with Red and
is ordered off the boat.
</P>
<P>
   The story darkens after Dawn disappears and is discovered by
Trixie, beaten up, hysterical and in possession, she claims, of a
sexually incriminating videotape. Soon afterward, she is found dead
beneath her hotel window. Determined to solve the case, Trixie
stalks the senator to an exclusive restaurant where, sozzled on
martinis, he delivers a rambling, incoherent monologue about
presidential hanky-panky. Only a director as fond of actors as
Rudolph would have allowed Nolte the room to deliver a
scenery-chewing rant that for all its dramatic heat, also stops the
movie cold.
</P>
<P>
   Skulking around the outskirts of the story are Kirk Stans
(Nathan Lane), a lounge impressionist with a shady past, and Ruby
Pearli (Brittany Murphy), a reckless barfly and ex-lover of Dex.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its occasional flashes of brilliance (every Rudolph film
has them), this unsavory stew never comes to a boil. The biggest
problem is the screwball side of the equation. From its forced
malapropisms to sudden, clumsy lurches into farce, the movie's
humor feels like a painfully self-conscious exercise in genre
bending. It turns out that the kind of ironic playfulness that
comes so naturally to younger filmmakers nowadays is just not
Rudolph's forte. Even when ``Trixie'' is being ``light,'' the
weight of the director's heavy hand keeps the lid on any genuine
levity.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `TRIXIE'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Alan Rudolph; written by Rudolph, based on a story
written by him and John Binder; director of photography, Jan
Kiesser; edited by Michael Ruscio; music by Mark Isham and Roger
Neill; production designers, Richard Paris and Linda Del Rosario;
produced by Robert Altman; released by Sony Pictures Classics.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Emily Watson (Trixie Zurbo), Dermot Mulroney (Dex Lang),
Nick Nolte (Senator Drummond Avery), Nathan Lane (Kirk Stans),
Brittany Murphy (Ruby Pearli), Lesley Ann Warren (Dawn Sloane) and
Will Patton (Red Rafferty).  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 117 minutes. ``Trixie'' is rated R (Under 17
requires accompanying parent or adult guardian). It contains sexual
situations, profanity and some mild violence.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
