<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CABLEBOXES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Scientific-Atlanta readies for sale of set-top boxes
 &HT;    By Kathy Brister
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - For 18 months, a team of Scientific-Atlanta engineers
has been working a brutal schedule and marking the days until
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   It's a fast-approaching deadline set by federal regulators who
say they want cable companies, such as those served by
Norcross-based cable-equipment maker Scientific-Atlanta, to
re-engineer the boxes that sit atop TVs. The idea is that with some
technical changes to the set-top box, a cable subscriber won't have
to get the device from the same company that provides his cable
service. This, say the feds, will foster competition among makers
of the set-top boxes.
</P>
<P>
   But nobody _ not Scientific-Atlanta, the cable operators they
serve, not even the retailers who lobbied for the Federal
Communications Commission to impose the deadline _ expects to see a
generic set-top box on a store shelf anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   Circuit City ``will not have the boxes available for retail in
July,'' said Bill Cimino, spokesman for the electronics chain.
``Our company's waiting at this time for the evolution of the
product. We are hesitant about selling a product that doesn't have
the same functionality as boxes leased from (cable companies).''
</P>
<P>
   Circuit City has been the most vocal retailer pushing for
commercial availability of set tops. In papers it filed with the
FCC opposing some cable operators' requests for an extension of the
deadline, the retailer claimed the cable industry was dragging its
feet on adopting standards and encouraging its manufacturers _ such
as Scientific-Atlanta _ to build fully functional set tops for
retail distribution.
</P>
<P>
   Broadband industry analyst George Hunt of Charlotte-based
Wachovia Securities said retailers aren't just looking out for
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   They hope to tap into the same kinds of revenue-sharing
agreements they have with direct broadcast satellite, Hunt said.
Generally, a retailer selling a satellite kit gets a piece of the
ongoing revenue stream created by subscribers' monthly fees.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing Circuit City wanted was a portion of a monthly
cable bill. The cable operators hated that. They hate revenue
sharing,'' Hunt said.
</P>
<P>
   The cable industry admits there are pros and cons to retail
set-top boxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Conceptually, this is a good idea to have these boxes
available at retail,'' said Chris Bowick, vice president of
technology development for Atlanta-based cable company Cox
Communications, controlled by the same corporation that owns The
Atlanta Journal-Constitution. ``Set-top boxes are capital
intensive. We, Cox and the other (cable companies), wouldn't mind
getting that capital expense off our books.''
</P>
<P>
   But there's no proven retail model for cable. Unlike direct
broadcast satellite, cable has a targeted base of customers who
live along its lines. In addition, even though the industry says
it's moving toward open technical standards, there are many kinks
to be worked out. And a generic box won't be cheap _ at least not
at first.
</P>
<P>
   Cable companies don't want to see a $400 set-top box on store
shelves next to a $250 direct broadcast satellite system, said
Bruce Leichtman, an analyst for Boston technology research firm the
Yankee Group.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only reason cable companies like (retail sale of set tops)
is because it gets the expense off their books. That's the
operational side. Marketingwise, it's like fighting Mike Tyson with
your hands tied behind your back,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Scientific-Atlanta chief scientist Tony Wasilewski said the
company doesn't expect its year and a half of work to pay off
anytime soon. ``We haven't been getting too many orders.''
</P>
<P>
   There are a number of reasons those orders haven't been pouring
in, starting with limitations of the re-engineered set-top box
itself. While it's now possible for someone to cart a set-top box
from Atlanta to Milwaukee, all he could do with it is watch TV. And
with the burgeoning plethora of digital interactive cable services
_ from video-on-demand to online shopping _ who'd want to settle
for that?
</P>
<P>
   Until the industry works out standards for software and hardware
needed to juice up traditional set-top functions _ a process that's
already begun but that could take two years to complete _ it's
unlikely consumers will want to buy the devices, Wasilewski said.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the Saturday deadline and the set-top rebuild is a
paragraph sandwiched into the 1996 federal Telecommunications Act.
The paragraph _ known simply as Section 629 _ never mentions the
word ``cable.'' What it says is that the FCC should ensure the
commercial availability of multichannel video programming
equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators are using that paragraph as the basis for requiring
cable companies to separate set-top box security _ what keeps
someone from illegally tapping into the cable network _ from
broadcast functions.
</P>
<P>
   Separating those components makes it possible to build a fairly
generic set-top box that could be used to watch TV on any cable
system, anywhere. One that could be sold retail, ending cable
companies' grip on the supply of set-top boxes and freeing them
from the dual role of supplying both service and equipment. One
that could erode the set-top market dominance of Scientific-Atlanta
and its major competitor, General Instrument Corp., a subsidiary of
Motorola.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, if a consumer wants a cable set-top box with all the
digital bells and whistles, he leases that box from his cable
company. The cable company orders it according to the technical
specifications of its local network from, generally,
Scientific-Atlanta or General Instrument.
</P>
<P>
   Section 629 was designed to change that, to open the set-top box
market to consumer demand the way the retail market for telephones
sprang open after the breakup of Ma Bell.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not what's going to happen here. (The cable set-top
box) is a much more sophisticated device than the telephone,''
Leichtman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Near term this deadline means very, very little. Consumers are
not going to be going to Circuit City to buy a cable set-t
</P>
</TEXT>
