<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-DRAFT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bearcats' Johnson looms as Hawks' choice in NBA draft
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA The Atlanta Hawks sit on a major decision today, but
they're not complaining
</P>
<P>
   With the sixth pick of tonight's NBA Draft, they can take a
player with a terrific shooting touch and the credentials to be a
very solid player in the league for years .
</P>
<P>
   Or they can elect to gamble a little, take a less proven player
with star potential but also with slightly higher chance of
failure.
</P>
<P>
   On the one hand there is Mike Miller, 6-7 1/2 from Florida, as
comfortable shooting from 24 feet as he is from 15. Miller is quick
enough to play guard.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand there is DerMarr Johnson, 6-8 1/4 from
Cincinnati. Johnson is one in a small crop of long, lanky athletes
who left school too early but offer a smorgasbord of developing
skills and awesome potential. He has the wing span of a 7-footer
and the knack of floating so high he appears to fly.
</P>
<P>
   When the Hawks make their pick about 8 p.m. the name most likely
will be Johnson, and the reason is that he can be that good.
</P>
<P>
   This draft ``is all about athleticism and potential,'' Hawks
general manager Pete Babcock has said repeatedly. ``If you can find
a player with star potential, you have to really take a look at
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the lottery was set May 21, the Hawks have been fitted
with Miller by every national survey taken. They worked him out
last week. They were intrigued initially, and they were impressed
by a workout in which he showed dedication and an ability to shoot
3-pointers better than anyone else entered in this year's draft.
</P>
<P>
   But Johnson also has great range and has the chance to be a
franchise player, perhaps even the Dominique Wilkins of the coming
decade.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, Johnson raises questions. He is seven months younger
than Dion Glover, one of last year's Hawks rookies. Johnson
attended four high schools, and the Hawks would be his sixth team
in that many years. After playing at three schools in metro
Washington, Johnson transferred to tough Maine Central Institute
for his senior year. There, he averaged 26.1 points, 6.3 rebounds
and 3.9 assists a game. His team went 34-4 and won the New England
Prep School championship.
</P>
<P>
   As a freshman at Cincinnati, as the third and fourth option on a
highly ranked team, Johnson averaged 12.6 points and shot .478 from
the floor. Scouts say he deferred willingly to All-American Kenyon
Martin and senior Pete Mickeal, the dominant personalities on the
Bearcats. Johnson could have averaged 15-20 shots a game but took
fewer than 10.
</P>
<P>
   The Hawks must like that about him. They had him in twice and
the second visit confirmed the first. They liked his ability, and
they liked his personality and his intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   The Orlando Magic, in fifth position, could make the decision
easier on the Hawks by taking Miller.
</P>
<P>
   The Hawks have had offers to trade down and get an additional
pick, plus something for later. They can get a talented player a
few spots down the list.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had discussions, some of them pretty intriguing,''
Babcock said, ``but I'd say right now we're going to keep the pick.
I like our chances with it.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said, ``I hope we never draft this high again.''
</P>
<P>
   That's why he is likely to gamble on potential greatness.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
