<SLUG> BC-KNOW-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`GETTING TO KNOW YOU': IN A BUS STATION, SURROUNDED BY STORIES AND
LIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (Production notes at end of review) 
 By ELVIS MITCHELL    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``That's why people lie, out of necessity,'' says Judith
(Heather Matarazzo), the clear-eyed protagonist of Lisanne Skyler's
entrancing ``Getting to Know You.'' The movie is based on Joyce
Carol Oates stories and conjures an alluring spell of mistrust and
hope, getting to the self-deception that Oates' characters often
weave for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Matarazzo's Judith _ her face a conglomeration of angles and
rounded curves with a hint of a dimple in her cheek _ is stuck in a
bus station with her older brother, Wesley (Zach Braff). The
squabbling between the siblings, who have that way of getting on
each other's nerves as only a brother and sister can, is an honest
outcropping of their defense mechanisms.
</P>
<P>
   The easygoing Judith, with her clear blue eyes, has a friendly
streak of curiosity in her, compared with the closed-off ambition
of her brother, who pursues his studies as if school were a one-way
ticket out of his misery. Judith's interest leads her to Jimmy
(Mark Weston), who claims to know her from school.
</P>
<P>
   Judith and Wesley have been essentially abandoned by their
parents, Trix (Bebe Neuwirth) and Darryl (Mark Blum), a pair of
former ballroom dancers. These self-absorbed failed performers
play-act at being a grown-up couple; they have turned their
marriage into dinner theater.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't talk much about the future or us, just
themselves,'' Wesley observes as he and his sister hide on a
staircase while their parents float across the living room of a
house from which they will probably soon be evicted.
</P>
<P>
   The soured practicality of these children, who have become like
a married couple as they fend for themselves, is chilling and, like
many of the details in ``Getting to Know You,'' is underplayed.
</P>
<P>
   Judith and Jimmy have their own sort of game, making up stories
around the lives of other people at the bus station.
</P>
<P>
   Skyler has woven her film from Oates' strains of self-deception
and fear of betrayal. In doing so, she strikes a note of hope. And
even though it's the kind of hope that comes out of a delirium,
it's still more than one might feel the right to ask for.
</P>
<P>
   The hope comes across in the giddiness of her actors, who take
to the material with welcoming arms. Skyler doesn't pursue the
modest, petty desperation Oates can traffic in. The director
supplants it with the neediness of small-time dreamers, offering
people who can feel better about themselves only by loving others.
She makes the ache in Jimmy and Judith all the more real because
they're creating these bus-station scenarios, like a pair of
Scheherazades in a treehouse.
</P>
<P>
   In one of these stories, which function as subplots, Irene
(Tristan Skyler, the director's sister) falls for Sonny (Chris
Noth), a gambler whose surface confidence is a magnet to her. The
story unfolds almost as fully in Irene's big, expressive brown eyes
as it does through action and dialogue. When Sonny's luck goes cold
and his depressive side emerges _ Noth is better at the low notes
than the high ones _ Irene feels his downturn more deeply than he
does and wants to help.
</P>
<P>
   Lisanne Skyler has cast her actresses well. Audiences who have
seen Neuwirth only as the emory-board Lilith from ``Frasier'' and
are unaware of how fully she can use her dancer's body will
experience the elation she feels through movement. Her Trix refuses
to allow Judith and Wesley to call her Mother or Mom and is
slightly nonplused at the concept that these tall strangers came
from her. She uses them more as an audiences than anything else,
and she turns mean at the idea of their growing up and leaving her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting to Know You'' is the kind of independent movie that
tests the system, because it's missing the cramped, high-concept,
low-budget pushiness that makes many small films the bargain bin
equivalent of studio pictures. Skyler's patience and skill reveal
themselves in a number of small, gratifying ways. The vivacious
color scheme contrasts with the plangent emotional tone, most
noticeably in the bus station; it takes on life beyond just a
framing device. She's not only a filmmaker, she's truly a director.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `GETTING TO KNOW YOU'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Lisanne Skyler; written by Lisanne Skyler and
Tristine Skyler, based on stories from ``Heat'' by Joyce Carol
Oates; director of photography, Jim Denault; edited by Julie Janata
and Anthony Sherin; music by Michael Brook; production designer,
Jody Asnes; produced by George LaVoo and Laura Gabbert; released in
association with the Sundance Channel.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Mark Blum (Darrell), Bebe Neuwirth (Trix), Zach Braff
(Wesley), Chris Noth (Sonny), Leo Burmester (Lamar Pike Sr.), Jacob
Reynolds (Lamar Pike Jr.), Bo Hopkins (Officer Caminetto), Tristine
Skyler (Irene), Heather Matarazzo (Judith), Sonja Sohn (Lynn), Mary
McCormack (Leila Lee), Celia Weston (Bottle Lady) and Michael
Weston (Jimmy).
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 91 minutes. This film is not rated. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
