<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WILLIAMSTOWN-THEATER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TONIGHT AT 8:30': SAVORING FLEETING JOYS WITH EYEBROWS ARCHED 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review.) 
 By BEN BRANTLEY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILLIAMSTOWN, Mass. _ If seizing the moment were an Olympic
event, like figure skating, Noel Coward's characters would surely
take the honors for form. True, they generally don't have the
athleticism of American hedonists; ``seize,'' in fact, may not be
quite the correct word for what they do.
</P>
<P>
   But as demonstrated in the choppy but intriguing Williamstown
Theater Festival production of ``Tonight at 8:30,'' a sextet of
short Coward plays presented over two evenings, much can be said
for savoring fleeting joys with the restraint and rueful elegance
of the people portrayed here.
</P>
<P>
   Even when they break into spontaneous song, which they do in the
most unexpected places, these charmed souls keep their backs
straight, their smiles suave and their eyebrows arched. Their
choice of rhythms, as often as not, is waltz time. And their
crisply rhymed lyrics are as tart as they are sentimental, as in:
</P>
<P>
   Life needn't be gray,
</P>
<P>
   Although it's changing day by day,
</P>
<P>
   Though a few old dreams may decay,
</P>
<P>
   Play, orchestra, play.
</P>
<P>
   That fragment of song comes from ``Shadow Play,'' a surreal and
fluid vision of life as a dark musical comedy and a work that
prompted the critic Kenneth Tynan to identify Coward as a precursor
to Harold Pinter. It appears on the second part of the bill at
Williamstown, under the direction of Ann Reinking, and it may come
as a slight jolt to audience members who know Coward only for
``Private Lives'' and ``Blithe Spirit.''
</P>
<P>
   Its tone is throughly typical of the Coward regularly performed
in repertory; its form is less obviously so. The same might be said
of two of the offerings in the first trio of plays, directed by
Michael Greif, in which thought-defining songs erupt among both a
group of Victorian mourners and a tense romantic triangle at a
colonial supper club.
</P>
<P>
   As a character in ``Shadow Play'' speculates, ``It would be so
much easier if we had music when things go wrong, music and a
little dancing.'' Coward, being a gentleman, saw fit to grant that
wish, and the results, if imperfectly executed in these
productions, are truly fascinating.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `TONIGHT AT 8:30'
</P>
<P>
   Programs A and B
</P>
<P>
   Six one-act plays by Noel Coward; sets by Allen Moyer; lighting
by Rui Rita; sound by Kurt B. Kellenberger; production manager,
Stephen Judd; orchestrations by Larry Moore. Presented by the
Williamstown Theater Festival, Michael Ritchie, producer; Deborah
Fehr, general manager; Jenny C. Gersten, associate producer. At
Williamstown, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-27-00 2132EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000627.0372 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 21:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6635 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-COLUMBUS-CIRCLE-2T     06-27 1156
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COLUMBUS-CIRCLE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW DESIGN APPROVED FOR COLUMBUS CIRCLE 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID W. DUNLAP   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Four months ago, with demolition of the New York
Coliseum under way, a final design had yet to be approved for
Columbus Center, the project that would take its place. Instead,
the developers, their architects and city officials were at a tense
impasse.
</P>
<P>
   About all they could agree on was this: Columbus Center had
become a camel.
</P>
<P>
   Architectural visions for the Columbus Circle site had begun
with a gargantuan prism in 1985, and evolved into an overscaled
Central Park West apartment tower in 1988 and then a glass-sheathed
echo of Deco in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   But by February, as the development group and a mayoral design
advisory panel were negotiating over the percentage of stone in the
facade, the vision had turned into two boxy towers; a horse
designed by committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's common denominator was not a good plan,'' said the
chief architect, David M. Childs of Skidmore, Owings &AMP; Merrill.
</P>
<P>
   With little time to lose, Childs drew up a new plan. The
55-story, 750-foot towers would shed their stone for broad planes
of sheer glass. Shaped like parallelograms, they would skew to
Broadway's angle. They would rise from a curved seven-story base
hugging Columbus Circle, with a prow at one end announcing the
presence of the company formed by the pending merger of American
Online and Time Warner, and a midblock atrium, where 59th Street
once ran, topped by a glass-walled performance space for Jazz at
Lincoln Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I saw it, I liked it immediately,'' said Mayor Rudolph W.
Giuliani, who is to unveil the design Wednesday at Columbus Circle.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani gave credit to the the five-member panel of civic
leaders, architects and planners that advised him on ``what they
thought was the most beautiful and aesthetically pleasing
project.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It worked very well,'' he said of the review process.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the occasional tumult that resulted, Giuliani
laughed. ``Luckily, I wasn't a part of it,'' he said. ``Usually I'm
in the middle of these things. By having a committee come to me,
sometimes with Band-Aids on their faces, I didn't know about all
the fighting. I just got the end result.''
</P>
<P>
   After much pushing and pulling _ as well as some table pounding
and gauntlet tossing _ room was found in a single building for AOL
Time Warner headquarters and a suite of CNN studios; Jazz at
Lincoln Center, including a theater with a seating capacity of
1,300 and a performance atrium overlooking Columbus Circle; 543,000
square feet of retail space (almost as much as in Saks Fifth
Avenue's flagship store); a 249-room, five-star Mandarin Oriental
Hotel; 203 condominium apartments; and 548 parking spaces.
</P>
<P>
   Each element had not only its own needs but also its own
architect: Rafael Vinoly for Jazz at Lincoln Center, Elkus/Manfredi
for the retail space, Brennan Beer Gorman for the hotel, HLW
International for AOL Time Warner.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of the building _ though he could just as well have
been describing the process _ one of the developers, Kenneth A.
Himmel, said: ``This is like a Swiss clock. Everything you move
moves everything around it.''
</P>
<P>
   Himmel, president and chief executive of the Palladium Co., is
managing the $1.7 billion Columbus Center project with Stephen M.
Ross, chairman and chief executive of the Related Companies. The
other developer is William L. Mack, co-founder and senior partner
of Apollo Real Estate Advisors.
</P>
<P>
   They make up the second group in 15 years to try to claim the
prize of developing the extraordinarily visible 3.4-acre site at
the confluence of Central Park, Clinton and the Upper West Side; a
void along Broadway between the theater district and Lincoln
Center.
</P>
<P>
   Mortimer B. Zuckerman and Edward H. Linde of Boston Properties
were the first. With the financial concern of Salomon Brothers as
their major tenant and co-developer, they proposed a 2.7
million-square-foot building designed by Moshe Safdie as a bundle
of angled shafts rising 925 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Among the opponents was Joseph B. Rose, now the chairman of the
City Planning Commission, then the chairman of the mid-Manhattan
community board. At the time, he assailed the ``striking numbness
to any aesthetic criteria whatsoever'' in the choice of the Boston
Properties plan.
</P>
<P>
   Protesters with black umbrellas captured the public imagination
in 1987 by tracing the shadow they said the building would cast
across Central Park. Later that year, Salomon withdrew from the
project just before opponents won a court case that challenged the
zoning benefit given to Boston Properties.
</P>
<P>
   With that, Zuckerman turned to Skidmore, Owings &AMP; Merrill.
``People hated the Safdie scheme,'' Childs recalled. ``It was so
alien. I was trying to find ways to make it fit in.'' In 1988,
Boston Properties offered a plan that was frankly derived from
1930s towers on Central Park West.
</P>
<P>
   By 1989, the bottom had dropped out of the real estate market.
Three years later, Boston Properties dropped out of the Columbus
Circle project.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, the Giuliani administration and the Metropolitan
Transportation Authority, which owned the site, issued a new
request for development proposals. Ross and his partners offered an
apartment and hotel project designed by Childs. In overall massing,
though not in architectural detailing, it was similar to the
earlier Boston Properties design.
</P>
<P>
   The development guidelines limited the towers to 750 feet and
the size of the project to 2.1 million square feet.
</P>
<P>
   (The approved project will actually have 2,768,700 square feet
of space _ almost as much as the former Pan Am Building at 200 Park
Avenue _ but 668,700 square feet are not counted for zoning
purposes because the space is under ground or used for equipment.
That calculation does not convince Olive Freud of the Committee for
Environmentally Sound Development, a longtime opponent of Columbus
Center, who regards it as an unauthorized increase of 30 percent in
the project size.)
</P>
<P>
   Two things happened in 1997 that profoundly affected the design.
Ross and Himmel persuaded Richard D. Parsons, the president of Time
Warner, to join the project. Giuliani insisted that the Columbus
Circle development include a performing arts center, perhaps for
opera. ``I felt we could extend Lincoln Center by doing that,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   It turned out that the constituent most in need of a permanent
home was Jazz at Lincoln Center. ``Until you have a physical
presence,'' said Rob Gibson, its executive producer and director,
``you're not connected to the industry of the city. Or the
public.''
</P>
<P>
   The developers have agreed to set aside 100,000 square feet of
space and build the basic structural shell for Jazz at Lincoln
Center, which will complete and maintain the space, for which it
has begun a $103 million capital campaign.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, the Columbus Center partners were chosen as the new
developers. That was when the hard work of reconciling all the
diverse occupants began. Each occupant would lay claim to the
highest possible profile in the project.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most important change in layout was the skewing of
the towers, which were originally aligned in such a way that
occupants on the north side of the 58th Street building would have
a view of another building only 65 feet away. Ditto for occupants
on the south side of the 60th Street tower.
</P>
<P>
   There began a series of revisions and compromises resulting in
designs that pleased no one. ``You looked at it and your heart
sank,'' recalled Rose. ``I said, `We did not go through this whole
process to end up with a building designed by committee. We want
something here the city can be proud of, an iconic building, not a
series of unsuccessful compromises.'''
</P>
<P>
   But didn't the administration itself create just such a
committee?
</P>
<P>
   No, Rose said. The purpose of the panel was not to fine-tune but
to point the developers in a direction that would be acceptable,
ultimately, to Giuliani. Besides Rose, the panel includes John S.
Dyson, a former deputy mayor; Jack L. Goldstein, executive director
of the Theater Development Fund; Andrew Heiskell, chairman emeritus
of the New York Public Library; and Jaquelin T. Robertson of the
architectural firm Cooper, Robertson &AMP; Partners.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the architects came back treating the feedback as if it
were `tweak this and tweak that,' the response was fairly brutal,''
Rose said.
</P>
<P>
   Childs, too, was reaching the end of his patience. ``I'm pretty
good at compromise,'' he said. ``But at a certain point, I said:
`I've let this go too far. We'll get the building done but frankly,
I don't want to have my name on it.' Thank God, it went over.
Everyone agreed. Everyone realized that it had gone too far
overboard.''
</P>
<P>
   Understandably, the developers did not take quite so bleak a
view, although they acknowledged the camellike aspects of the
interim version.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody was happy, but we were prepared to accept it,'' Ross
said. ``Time was marching on. We had already ordered the steel. It
was pretty scary. There had to be a lot of faith on both parts _
but more from us than them.''
</P>
<P>
   In late winter, Childs and his partners T.J. Gottesdiener and
Mustafa K. Abadan made another try. ``When this orthogonal geometry
slid into the modern shape of a parallelogram, its expression
couldn't be in square brick any longer,'' Childs said. ``It's now
in ice, sliced ice. Glass.''
</P>
<P>
   Another expanse of glass is the source of some contention. The
600-seat performance space of Jazz at Lincoln Center, which once
was to overlook Columbus Circle directly, will now be recessed 20
feet behind a larger glass curtain wall framing the central atrium.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue of presence and visibility is critical,'' said
Vinoly, the architect for Jazz at Lincoln Center. ``Do we have
presence?''
</P>
<P>
   Rose, the planning chairman, said the jazz space would be a
``major presence'' in the project. ``It's the best design yet,'' he
said. ``The building captures its place in the city, in the urban
context. David Childs rose to the occasion. There were some raised
voices involved, but it was to good effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a place for a bad building.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-27-00 2134EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
