</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOOT-ENVIRON-355&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEATHS OF THE ELDERLY ARE TIED TO AIR POLLUTION 
</HEADLINE>
   By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Microscopic particles of air pollutants from
tailpipes, power plants and other sources are causing measurable
increases in deaths and the hospitalizations of the elderly, a
study of the nation's 90 largest metropolitan areas has found.
</P>
<P>
   The study was conducted by an independent scientific
organization funded by auto manufacturers and the Environmental
Protection Agency and is scheduled to be released on Wednesday by
the Health Effects Institute of Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   It found a 1 percent increase in the death rate for each small
increase of tiny particles in the air and a 2 percent to 4 percent
increase in hospitalization of the elderly. The quantity of
particles _ 20 micrograms per cubic meter _ is equivalent to about
7 ten-millionths of an ounce.
</P>
<P>
   At that rate, an ounce of the particles added to a five-story
building that is 950 feet wide would raise the death rate 1
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The correlation was strongest in the Northeast, researchers
found, and in the New York City area, the increase in the death
rate was twice as high as the average of the other cities studied.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers said the reason was not clear but might be that New
York has better monitoring of particulate pollution than some other
cities. With a clearer picture of pollution levels, the
correlations were stronger. Or, the researchers added, it might be
because the tiny particles in the Northeast are made up of
different chemicals, tending to be sulfur-oxygen compounds, while
in the West, they are more likely to be nitrogen-oxygen compounds.
</P>
<P>
   Although 1 percentage point sounds small, government officials
said the finding was important because of the huge number of people
exposed to particulate pollution. Robert W. Perciasepe, the head of
the EPA's air pollution program, said that elevated particulate
levels might occur ``two days this week, two days next week,'' and
other times in the year. Considering that this short-term effect
could be repeated over and over, and considering that there is
probably also a long-term effect, which was not addressed by this
study, ``it's thousands of deaths a year.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But the study's authors did not give a number of deaths.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is still some work that needs to be done in terms of
translating our numbers,'' said Dr. Jonathan Samet, the principal
investigator and a researcher with the Johns Hopkins University
School of Public Health. ``We didn't do that exercise.''
</P>
<P>
   The study raised another question it did not answer: whether the
additional deaths were among frail people whose demise was simply
hastened by a few days, or whether the people dying would otherwise
have lived for many years. Some air pollution experts blame many of
the 5,000 asthma deaths per year on particulate pollution, although
they acknowledge that some of those who die have heart and lung
problems that would probably have killed them soon anyway.
</P>
<P>
   The study is only the latest in a series that links particulate
emissions to illness and death. Others, in fact, found a larger
correlation, but they covered one or a handful of cities. This one
is considered by statisticians to be more reliable because it
integrates data from a large area.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, by looking at death rates and particulate
concentrations over time, in a variety of different weather
conditions, the authors say, it isolates the effect of the
particles from the effects of summer heat, or of other pollutants,
like smog.
</P>
<P>
   The study is being published as the EPA is making a major effort
to clean up diesel engines, a major source of particulate
pollution. The agency has recently proposed sharp reductions in the
allowable level of sulfur in diesel fuel and hopes to issue a final
rule by the end of the year. The new rule would reduce the tailpipe
emissions of sulfur compounds that can form particles, and it would
also allow the use of sophisticated catalytic devices that capture
nitrogen compounds. The catalytic devices are poisoned by
high-sulfur fuel and thus are not practical now.
</P>
<P>
   The authors, from Johns Hopkins University and the Harvard
School of Public Health, wrote that their study provided ``new and
strong evidence linking particulate air pollution to adverse health
effects.''
</P>
<P>
   Clean air advocates and government officials familiar with the
findings of the report praised it. Perciasepe said, ``I believe the
study substantially validates some of the basic science behind the
regulations, with real-world data.''
</P>
<P>
   At the American Lung Association, Ronald H. White, the director
of national programs, said, ``this is additional scientific
evidence that supports toughening the standard for particulate
matter.'' The study, he noted, does not appear to identify a
threshold concentration level, below which particles are safe. That
means the government should pursue any strategy to reduce
particulate emissions, he added. The current federal limit is an
annual average of 50 micrograms per cubic meter and 150 micrograms
in a 24-hour period.
</P>
<P>
   At Ford Motor Co., which is a sponsor of the institute, Phil
Colley, a spokesman, said: ``we respect their findings. We're not
arguing with their findings.''
</P>
<P>
   In a written statement, the company said it would continue
developing new technologies to control particulate emissions, and
would continue supporting scientific research.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
