A6639 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-AOL-MUSIC-NYT &LR;      06-27 0694
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AOL-MUSIC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICA ONLINE TO OFFER MUSIC IN ITS NEWEST SOFTWARE  
</HEADLINE>
   By AMY HARMON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a deal that may break a logjam in promoting the secure
downloading of music from the Internet, America Online said Tuesday
that it had agreed to include software from the InterTrust
Technologies Corp. on compact discs containing AOL 6.0, the newest
version of its own popular software, later this year.
</P>
<P>
   Like several other companies providing digital rights
management, InterTrust allows a recording company to wrap music in
software that ensures it will only be played according to rules
specified by the company. Before downloading a song, customers
would agree to terms like how much they would pay, or how long they
would be able to play it. But in order to be able to make that
choice, they would need to have special software to interpret what
is being offered.
</P>
<P>
   Although the software itself would be invisible to consumers,
depositing it on enough computers to make the whole system worth
using has been a stumbling block.
</P>
<P>
   With more than 20 million subscribers _ more than the next 15
largest Internet service providers combined _ and a notorious
strategy for blanketing the nation with its compact discs, America
Online could serve as a particularly potent delivery vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   The online service also said that it would integrate
InterTrust's system into a version of its Winamp music player,
another piece of the digital music puzzle required to make secure
distribution work. Already one of the most popular MP3 players,
Winamp could become more attractive to companies seeking to
securely distribute digital music.
</P>
<P>
   With the huge popularity of the MP3 format, which allows music
to be sent quickly and at no cost across the Internet, the
challenge for recording companies is to find a way to entice
consumers to use a system that would require them to pay and
restrict their ability to copy. But the music industry has been
slow to even try, in part because of the difficulties in putting
the technology in place.
</P>
<P>
   ``So far, it's been that consumers don't need the players that
use the secure format because there's no content in the format, and
content owners don't put content in the secure format because the
consumers don't have the players to play it,'' said Eric Sheirer,
media and entertainment analyst for Forrester Research, a
consulting firm in Cambridge, Mass. ``This gets them over the
chicken-and-egg hurdle.''
</P>
<P>
   Other companies competing in the area of digital rights
management include Microsoft _ whose software is currently being
used by Sony Music to distribute about 50 singles for $2.49 each
that can be played only on Microsoft's Windows Media Player _ and
IBM, which along with InterTrust is among the companies that
Bertelsmann's BMG Entertainment unit selected to use in its own
digital download system, scheduled for introduction later this
summer.
</P>
<P>
   Whether America Online's pending merger with Time Warner means
that Warner Music will endorse InterTrust as a result of the deal
is unclear, although officials at InterTrust, which is based in
Santa Clara, Calif., indicated that they certainly hoped so.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the beginning of our figuring out how to commercialize
digital downloading,'' an AOL spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   Even less clear is whether consumers will choose to use the
technology of secure distribution, however easy it is made for them
to do so.
</P>
<P>
   But Talal Shamoon, senior vice president for media at
InterTrust, said America Online's large user base would be an ideal
setting from which to start a secure version of Napster, the widely
used system for swapping pirated music files. For instance, music
companies could harness AOL's subscribers to drive sales by
offering incentives like free concert tickets to individuals who
convince their friends to buy a particular piece of digital music,
Shamoon said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could be at the threshold of something very big,'' Shamoon
added. ``A robust electronic community of people exchanging content
in a safe way, where rights holders get paid and consumers feel
good about the experience.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
