A6644 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-EDUCATORS-COMPUTE-COX     06-27 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDUCATORS-COMPUTE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    California educator not enamored of school technology
 &HT;    By Alan Judd
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   To William L. Rukeyser, the Georgia World Congress Center this
week has seemed like a temple of technology for schools.
</P>
<P>
   But during the National Educational Computing Conference, he
said, the temple was filled with false idols.
</P>
<P>
   Inside a cavernous meeting room, next to an exhibit hall filled
with the latest educational software and hardware, thousands of
educators listened Tuesday to the chief executive of the world's
largest computer microchip maker. It was hardly a surprise when
Craig Barrett of the Intel Corp. said that educational technology
offers ``one of the best opportunities we have to make advances''
in such subjects as math and science.
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, the nation's top education official agreed _ and
said nonbelievers should change their ways. ``Everyone responsible
for teaching children in this new century,'' said U.S. Education
Secretary Richard Riley, ``should know how to use the tools of this
new century.''
</P>
<P>
   But a few blocks from the conference, in a downtown Atlanta
motel, Rukeyser asserted that the effectiveness of the heavily
promoted technology is unproven. And, he said, it is prohibitively
expensive to buy and maintain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody loves to play with new toys,'' said Rukeyser,
coordinator of a California-based group called Learning in the Real
World. ``That's why we love Christmas. But the fact is, when it
comes to technology in schools, there is no Santa Claus. Taxpayers
are going to be picking up the bill.''
</P>
<P>
   Rukeyser is part of a small but increasingly vocal group of
educators who are raising questions about the growing reliance on
technology in the classroom.
</P>
<P>
   His privately funded, nonprofit organization describes classroom
computers as ``expensive flash cards.'' It says that ``a child must
be literate before he or she is computer literate.'' And it
cautions that ``children are not little adults'' and shouldn't be
pressured to learn complex computer skills.
</P>
<P>
   At events like the computing conference, though, Rukeyser's is
such a lone voice that he might as well be wandering through the
wilderness.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, he said it's important to offer an alternative view,
especially considering that, according to Intel's Barrett, American
schools have already spent $40 billion on technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they don't tell you at these conferences,'' Rukeyser
said, ``is that the ongoing costs (of technology) are an immense
issue.''
</P>
<P>
   For every $3 million in school technology, he estimated, it
costs $1 million a year to train users and to install upgrades to
keep it from becoming obsolete.
</P>
<P>
   ``These costs,'' he said, ``have gone unrecognized in this rush
to computerize schools.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, said Rukeyser, a former official with the California
Department of Education, it hasn't been proved that students are
learning more because of the expanding classroom technology.
</P>
<P>
   On this point, Rukeyser and Barrett agree. Barrett noted that
despite the growing use of educational technology, American
students still fare poorly in math and science when compared to
children from other industrialized countries. American
fourth-graders rank third in science scores and 11th in math among
25 countries, he said. But in a study of 21 nations, U.S.
12th-graders come in at 16th in science and 19th in math.
Nevertheless, some studies have found that specific computer
programs improve student performance.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his criticism, Rukeyser is hardly a Luddite.
</P>
<P>
   He thinks technology can be a useful tool for some students:
those with physical disabilities, those who are geographically
isolated or those living in extreme poverty.
</P>
<P>
   And his organization _ largely funded by a foundation called the
Center for Ecoliteracy, which promotes nature appreciation programs
in schools _ has a presence on the World Wide Web, where it uses
technology to advocate a lesser reliance on technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do know how to use a mouse,'' Rukeyser said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he said, the reaction he initially gets from most
technology-loving educators is usually the same: ``Go away.'' But a
book published last year by another anti-technology advocate from
California also questioned the value of classroom computers, and
Rukeyser and some federal education officials have expressed doubts
about the focus on technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly is a minority view,'' Rukeyser said of the
anti-technology movement. ``But there is a growing minority of
people saying there is a good reason to be skeptical.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
