u w BC-HOUSE-CUBA-HNS &LR;      06-27 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSE-CUBA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. NEAR TO EASING EMBARGO ON CUBA &HT;    
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle &HT;    WASHINGTON _ Republican leaders struck a deal with House GOP
<TEXT>
members Tuesday to clear the way for the sale of agriculture goods
and medicine to Cuba, altering a 40-year embargo on trade with the
communist country.
<P>
   The agreement, all but forced on a reluctant GOP leadership by
Rep. George Nethercutt, R-Wash., is expected to win approval by the
full House as either an amendment to the 2001 agriculture spending
bill or as part of a funding measure for military construction
projects.
</P>
<P>
   The leadership would prefer it be attached to the popular
military construction measure, which would avoid a divisive debate
over Cuba policy between farm state lawmakers and members who
represent the Cuban-American community in south Florida.
</P>
<P>
   The House signaled its backing last year in a vote calling for a
change in sanctions policy. The Senate also passed a non-binding
measure on easing sanctions last year, and is expected to back the
Nethercutt proposal or something close to it.
</P>
<P>
   Nethercutt's proposal has the backing this year of more than 100
farm state lawmakers from both sides of the aisle, who have long
argued in favor of a major change in the U.S. trade sanctions that
were imposed on Cuba after Fidel Castro took control in 1959.
</P>
<P>
   But in a concession to Cuban-Americans, aimed at attracting more
support, Nethercutt's measure would prohibit the extension of U.S.
credit or loan guarantees to help the Castro government buy
American farm products and medicine.
</P>
<P>
   The prohibition could make it more difficult for Cuba to
purchase U.S. goods because it would force the cash-starved country
to use hard currency or seek more costly third-party financing _
probably through another trading partner such as Canada or France _
to make the U.S. purchases.
</P>
<P>
   That provision was added at the insistence of Rep. Lincoln
Diaz-Balart, R-Fla., who said it amounts to tougher restrictions on
sales to Cuba than are currently written into law.
</P>
<P>
   ``I prefer this deal to current law,'' said Diaz-Balart.
</P>
<P>
   Nethercutt also had to make other compromises. He agreed to
include current restrictions on travel by Americans to Cuba in his
bill, and to continue the prohibition on Cuban exports to the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   His bill also would ease similar sanctions on food and medicine
against Iran, Sudan, North Korea and Libya.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Nethercutt told reporters that the agreement still
represents ``a fundamental shift in American foreign policy''
toward Cuba that will open the door to expanded trading
opportunities for American farmers, drug and medical companies.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement also marks a fundamental shift in the attitude of
the GOP leadership, which has listened closely to the
Cuban-American community in shaping its positions on sanctions and
other issues regarding Castro.
</P>
<P>
   But in this election year, the support of farm and business
interests could make a big difference in close races around the
country.
</P>
<P>
   House Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas, who opposes changing
the sanctions policy, acknowledged as much in a briefing for
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can count votes,'' Armey said. ``There's a strong desire to
open that market to American sales.''
</P>
<P>
   Armey said the Nethercutt measure also has the support of the
Senate GOP leadership, and will likely be accepted by President
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   At the White House, Clinton spokesman Joe Lockhart said the
president would back the legislation if it includes provisions that
will ensure that any sale of medicine and food ``goes to the
benefit of the Cuban people and not Castro's government.''
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart also sought to dispel any speculation that the
Nethercutt bill could lead to a further lifting of U.S. sanctions
against Cuba or to a warming of relations between Washington and
Havana.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't believe it's time to provide any kind of aid that
will help the Cuban government,'' Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement was hailed by the U.S. Chamber of Commerce as ``a
positive development'' that will end a ``senseless'' policy that
only harmed the Cuban people.
</P>
<P>
   Agriculture interests, such as the Texas Farm Bureau Federation,
also voiced approval. But they were skeptical about the bill's
benefit to small American producers and companies in desperate need
of new markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a step in the right direction. . . . But our gains are
going to be minimal because of the restrictions on credit,'' said
Steve Pringle, legislative director for the Texas Farm Bureau
Federation.
</P>
<P>
   Texas farm interests ``will be looking at thousands of dollars
in trade rather than hundreds of thousands,'' he predicted.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Pringle said, the state's farmers ought to celebrate
the change in ``political attitudes in Washington'' regarding Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to understand where we've come from on this thing.
Two years ago, we couldn't even get a vote'' on lifting sanctions,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to credit restrictions, the agreement would continue
a 1992 law that bars ships that visit Cuba from entering U.S. ports
for 180 days. In order to accommodate U.S. exports to the island,
shipping companies would have to be willing to change their
freighter schedules.
</P>
<P>
   Lengthy and tedious licensing requirements through the State
Department for U.S. companies wanting to sell to Cuba, Libya, Iran,
Sudan and North Korea also will remain in place.
</P>
<P>
