<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 21:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6649 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-CUBA-U.S.-1STLD-WRITE     06-27 1143
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBA-U.S.-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE AGREES TO ALLOW SALES OF U.S. FOOD AND MEDICINE TO CUBA 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS for rewriting throughout; note subbed byline and dateline)  
(ART ADV: Photo NYT1 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By LIZETTE ALVAREZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House Republican leaders agreed on Tuesday to end
four decades of sanctions on sales of food to Cuba, in a decision
that carried great political significance.
</P>
<P>
   But the economic value is relatively minor, as Cuban-American
lawmakers managed to place severe restrictions in the bill.
</P>
<P>
   The deal would in principle allow American farmers and
agricultural businesses to sell their goods directly to Cuba for
the first time since 1962. The agreement also echoes existing
policy allowing the sale of medicine.
</P>
<P>
   But the federal government and American banks would be barred
from providing any financing for Cuba, making it difficult for
Cuba, with little cash, to buy goods.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the trade would be one-way: Cuba would not be
permitted to export to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate has already approved a more expansive version of the
legislation as part of its agriculture spending bill. The House and
Senate must now resolve their differences, but the more stringent
House language is expected to win approval.
</P>
<P>
   The full House and Senate could take up the bill in the coming
weeks as part of a larger spending package. That means there would
be no vote specifically on lifting the Cuba sanctions, only on the
larger bill. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The bill would also lift food and medicine sanctions against
Libya, the Sudan, North Korea and Iran. Under the bill, Iran would
also be ineligible for private financing from American banks.
</P>
<P>
   The House Republican leaders reached their agreement early on
Tuesday morning after nearly six hours of negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   House Republican leaders long opposed any weakening of the
embargo against Cuba, which is meant to put pressure on Fidel
Castro. But an intense lobbying campaign from agribusiness and
recent action by Congress and the Clinton administration to ease
trade restrictions on other nations, including China and North
Korea, helped soften the Republican opposition this year.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the White House expressed reservations about the deal,
mostly because it would require the president to get congressional
approval for imposing future sanctions on sales of food and
medicine to other countries. To date, the imposing of such
sanctions has been a presidential prerogative.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. George W. Nethercutt, the Washington Republican who
championed the bill, described the agreement as a ``fundamental
shift in American foreign policy.''
</P>
<P>
   Doing business with Cuba, he said, is ``not as easy as it would
otherwise be'' because of the restrictions. . ``But,'' he added,
``the door is open and that's what's important.''
</P>
<P>
   Reps. Lincoln Diaz-Balart and Ileana Ros-Lehtinen, both Florida
Republicans, said they viewed the agreement as a symbolic matter
that benefited their agenda as well. For instance, the bill would
turn existing federal restrictions on tourism into law. Currently,
federal rules specify who can travel to Cuba, with cultural and
religious groups among them.
</P>
<P>
   That provision triggered a round of criticism from House and
Senate Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican proposal ``not only does too little to insure
that U.S. food and medicine will reach the Cuban people,'' said
Rep. Sam Gejdenson, D-Conn. ``It also will unnecessarily interfere
with critical people-to-people contacts.''
</P>
<P>
   The reaction from Cuba was negative. The president of the
National Assembly, Ricardo Alarcon, said the bill contained
``unacceptable discriminatory conditions.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill is also silent on existing law that complicates the
transport of farm goods to Cuba. Under a 1992 law, any ship that
visits Cuba, whether registered in the United States or a foreign
country, is barred from calling on any U.S. port for six months,
and most analysts agreed this adds another obstacle to the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Still, agricultural and business groups, as well as academic
experts, said the bill could be the first chink in the armor of
American sanctions to clear Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main thing that it means politically is that this is the
first time that the U.S. congress has taken a decision to open up
economic sanctions with Cuba, I think ever,'' said Jorge Dominguez,
a professor of government at Harvard University.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   For the House Republican leadership, the agreement was a
political calculation. Nethercutt faces a tough re-election bid in
a swing district and, with a slim Republican majority in the House,
leaders did not want to defeat him on his signature issue and anger
his constituents. Neither did they want to anger Cuban-Americans,
who are mostly Republican.
</P>
<P>
   The Elian Gonzalez saga also played into congressional
sensibilities this year, after the boy's plight prompted a
widespread discussion of America's foreign policy toward Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush, the presumptive Republican presidential
nominee, said on Tuesday during a news conference in Wayne, Mich.,
that he continued to oppose the legislation, saying no softening in
sanctions are warranted until Fidel Castro puts an end to human
rights violations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have opposed lifting the sanctions, and I still continue to
do so,'' Bush said. He expressed skepticism that Castro would let
food reach his people, and added, ``I like to remind people, this
is a man who is tyrannical.''
</P>
<P>
   Aides for Vice President Al Gore, the likely Democratic nominee,
said Gore takes issue with the bill's interference with a
president's right to issue sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest beneficiaries of the bill would be large
agricultural companies, which have lobbied Congress for years to
lift the embargo.
</P>
<P>
   They are best equipped to help secure loans for Cuba from
foreign banks at little risk to the banks or to themselves. But
unlike Iran, with its oil, Cuba has no hard currency exports to
speak of.
</P>
<P>
   Cuba withdrew from the World Bank and the International Monetary
Fund in the 1960s, and so is barred from any financing from them.
Cuba buys agricultural products from countries like France, China
and Canada, whose governments heavily subsidize the sales.
</P>
<P>
   The American Farm Bureau calculates that Cuba spends $1 billion
a year on agricultural products.
</P>
<P>
   During the next 12 months, American farmers stand to make sales
to Cuba of $25 million to $45 million, according to an estimate by
the U.S.-Cuba Trade and Economic Council, a center financed by
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The Cuban-American National Foundation, the leading anti-Castro
lobby, said it would fight the bill.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
