<DOCNO> NYT20000627.0385 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 22:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6650 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-PUBLIC-PRIVATE-COX     06-27 1449
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUBLIC-PRIVATE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hospital netcasts will show off Junior
 &HT;    By Jill Vejnoska
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - First comes love. Then comes marriage. Then comes a
newborn shown off live on the Internet before its powdered bottom
ever hits the baby carriage.
</P>
<P>
   That's the premise behind BabyPressConference.com, a
fast-growing new company that has signed up more than 75 hospitals
nationwide and could be coming to metro Atlanta by late summer.
</P>
<P>
   New parents will be able to conduct personal, live-action
``netcasts'' direct from the hospital, meaning friends and loved
ones scattered around the country and co-workers stuck back at the
office don't have to miss Junior's first gurgles and coos.
</P>
<P>
   And surely these friends and relatives will want to witness such
momentous events, after they've spent months checking out sonograms
and other details of the developing pregnancy on the
parents-to-be's personal Web page. And even before that, perhaps,
getting a preview of the reception, bridal party and more on the
couple's wedding Web page. Remember when experts warned us about
the possible isolating effects of computers? Check your e-mail
again.
</P>
<P>
   If anything, the Internet now affords us the chance to learn
more than ever about others' traditionally ``personal'' moments.
And although there's definitely something to be said for letting
your Web site do the talking to nosy Aunt Mabel in the hectic weeks
leading up to the wedding, some experts wonder how much of a good
thing is -- oo much.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever we have a technological explosion like right now,
there's the issue of playing with the technology and the separate
issue of `Why are we doing it?''' said Greg VanHoosier-Carey, an
assistant professor specializing in new media in Georgia Tech's
department of literature, communication and culture. ``The whole
question of what is private and what is public is difficult for us
to sort out right now.''
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing new, of course, about this urge to tell all.
What is different now is the ease and speed with which the Internet
allows that to occur and, to a lesser extent, the concerns it
raises for the privacy of everyone involved.
</P>
<P>
   Yet some trendsetters point to the increasing de-personalization
inherent in modern life and say they are harnessing the Internet's
power to counteract some of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're recapturing something old by using the
technology of today,'' said Lee H. Perlman, president of
BabyPressConference.com, pointing out that new mothers now spend
very little time in the hospital, and their family and friends
often are far-flung. ``What we're doing is using the Internet to
re-create the experience that's been taken away from people. People
get to see the new baby now, bonding with the parents, instead of
two or three weeks or even months later.''
</P>
<P>
   There's almost no end to what the Web can make instantly
share-able. Expectant parents who register with the service create
a family Web page where they can chart the progress of their
pregnancy, create a gift registry and post sonograms. They put
together a list of people to receive an e-mail when they firstsign
up and later can invite them to attend the live netcast, usually
the day after the baby is born.
</P>
<P>
   The in-hospital broadcasts, which cost the parents and
``invited'' guests nothing, can last as long as 30 minutes and are
archived for 14 days. Perlman hopes to make money through sales of
copies of the netcasts for $29.95 and the company's share on items
such as flowers, cribs, toys (Toys ``R'' Us is an investor), even
bronzed baby shoes, sold through its online store.
</P>
<P>
   The concept sounds like a natural for metro Atlanta, where
newcomers are pouring in at an unprecedented rate and everyone, it
seems, is worldwide-wired. Seventy percent of households here have
computers, according to the Metro Horizon Poll of 2,000 adults in
16 metro Atlanta counties conducted in March by The Marketing
Workshop. In homes with children, that number rises to 77 percent _
compared with 59 percent of all households nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Northside Hospital, the place for delivering babies in Atlanta
and the Southeast, already has an online ``Web nursery''
(http://63.64.125.218/), featuring still photographs of newborns,
accessible only with a secret code given to family and friends.
Katherine Watson, marketing communications specialist at Northside,
said she ``couldn't confirm'' whether the hospital is in
negotiations with BabyPressConference.com.
</P>
<P>
   Some new parents may already have taken the Internet plunge via
wedding Web sites. At DigitalBliss.com, which creates personalized
wedding Web sites,packages are offered for as little as $39.95 and
for as long as six months. Each package includes lists of
recommended hotels and information for the ceremony and reception
sites, while some offer an online RSVP feature and a list of
important dates.
</P>
<P>
   For $139.95, the top-of-the-line ``PlatinumPak'' includes an
online gift registry, with direct links to any stores with an
Internet presence; a photo album, where ``you'll be able to quickly
share your honeymoon pictures''; and e-mail ``ticklers'' sent to
everyone you want to direct to your site.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rather than having to tell 100 different people 100 different
times where to stay, what time dinner is, where you're registered,
this way you can publish it once and everyone can stay current,''
said Tom Czajkowski, 35, of the Chicago suburb of Naperville. Going
through all that with wife Lisa before their wedding prompted the
couple to create a Web site and, eventually, DigitalBliss.com.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even couples who apparently think nothing of posting
photographs of their bridal party are concerned about who actually
gets to view their site. Toward that end, Czajkowski said,
DigitalBliss creates a unique ``url'' address for each customer,
who determines to whom it will be distributed.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Akula, who was born in India and lives in North Potomac,
Md., helped talk his daughter into creating a Web site for her
upcoming nuptials. When the engagement of Heather Akula and Eric
Clapprood was announced in The Washington Post recently, along with
the particulars on their professions and parents, the article also
included the address for the couple's Web site
(members.xoom.com/akulamd1/wedding.htm.).
</P>
<P>
   ``I've moved around to many states for my job, so we have
friends all over,'' said Charles Akula, an engineer. ``And all of
my family are in India, so I thought it would be good to show them
what we are doing here. No postage, no customs, no immigration.
People can see it any time from anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the Web site idea initially struck the bride-to-be as a
bit ``dorky,'' she never was unsettled at the thought of strangers
logging on to critique her choice of bridesmaid dresses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's great that other people can look at our Web site,
especially if they want to get ideas from it,'' said the
21-year-old bride-to-be, whose wedding is scheduled for August
2001. ``A lot of people are clueless when it gets to weddings.''
</P>
<P>
   Some people have even bigger ideas when it comes to sharing
their personal moments on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   At BabyPressConference.com, a few prospective customers have
``implied'' they'd like to include video of the birth, but Perlman
said that's not a business they're getting into.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think that is too personal,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And what about the flip side of the privacy issue? Some people
might resent receiving electronic suggestions to check out a site_
and maybe even buy a gift.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have to open them,'' Wendy Simonds, a sociology
professor at Georgia State University, pointed out. ``I get files
all the time from people sending me photos and I don't open them
all.''
</P>
<P>
   But that's a private decision. And even private and personal
moments can go unexpectedly public on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we get more used to the technology, I think it's something
where we'll say, `Hey, maybe I shouldn't put that out there,'''
said Georgia Tech's VanHoosier-Carey. It's always possible for
someone to stumble across a supposedly secret Web site address or
password, or to forward a ``private'' e-mail to an unwanted
recipient, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once someone sends some bad e-mail or shows up at a (private)
party,'' he said, ``people will start to think about it a lot
more.''
</P>
<P>
   Unless, of course, they're too busy thinking up the next big
thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't imagine what we'll be doing 20 to 30 years from now,''
said Simonds, 37. ``When I grew up, you still had to walk across
the room to change the TV channel.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
