<DOCNO> NYT20000627.0392 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 22:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6669 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-DAVIDIANS28-COX     06-27 0912
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAVIDIANS28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Burn victim describes fateful day in Waco
 &HT;    By MARK ENGLAND
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas - Misty Ferguson raised her right hand Tuesday to
take an oath to tell the truth and the sleeve on her dress fell to
reveal more about the injuries she suffered April 19, 1993 than
words ever could.
</P>
<P>
   She lost the fingers on both hands in the fire that destroyed
the Branch Davidians' Mount Carmel complex. The inferno led to the
deaths of David Koresh and 75 followers _ and a $675 million
wrongful-death lawsuit against the government that's in its second
week.
</P>
<P>
   Ferguson was 17 and hiding in a back bedroom on the second floor
of Mount Carmel when the fire started.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had come out into the hallway, and I felt heat underneath my
feet,'' Ferguson, 24, testified.
</P>
<P>
   She tried going down the hallway, but the stairs had been
buckled by FBI tanks ripping into Mount Carmel to disperse tear
gas, Ferguson told Houston attorney Mike Caddell, lead attorney for
the plaintiffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The floor was caved in,'' Ferguson said. ``Before I knew it, I
was engulfed in smoke.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferguson was the last witness called by Caddell and wife Cynthia
Chapman, as they rested their case.
</P>
<P>
   Former U.S. Attorney General Ramsey Clark, representing longtime
Davidians such as Clive Doyle and Sheila Martin, had just started
presenting his case to U.S. District Judge Walter S. Smith Jr. and
an advisory jury when court recessed. Houston attorney James
Brannon, representing the estate of Koresh's legal children, will
follow Clark.
</P>
<P>
   After being enveloped in smoke at Mount Carmel, Ferguson dropped
to the ground, she testified Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I seen a little bit of light down toward the other way,''
Ferguson said. ``At that point, there was a lot of crackling
noise.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferguson said she crawled toward the light and found a gap in an
outside wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a hole toward the front side of the building where a
tank had come in,'' Ferguson said. ``I jumped from the building
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Caddell asked Ferguson if she knew the extent of her injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that point, the only thing I knew that was burned was my
hands,'' Ferguson testified. ``They were already burnt.'
</P>
<P>
   Ferguson was one of three Davidians taken to Parkland Memorial
Hospital's burn unit in Dallas. The other two, Marjorie Thomas and
Clive Doyle, were also in court Tuesday. Ferguson was also burned
on her face and body, requiring a long hospitalization and
rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
   Caddell submitted a written deposition from Frederick Lanceley,
an FBI negotiator at Mount Carmel, critical of the FBI's decision
to aggressively insert tear gas into the building. Lanceley said he
agreed with the assessment of Gary Noesner, who coordinated the
negotiation team at Mount Carmel.
</P>
<P>
   A 1993 government report of an interview with Noesner after the
fire was then read.
</P>
<P>
   ``Noesner ... determined that no one asked the negotiators and
behavioral scientists what the response would be if the tanks
punched holes in the building,'' the report said. ``Noesner sees
this as a fundamental flaw in the implementation of the operation.
Any negotiator would have told them that dismantling the building
would provoke a violent response. ... He believes that is what
triggered the starting of the fires and the shooting of the
children.''
</P>
<P>
   Government counsel Michael Bradford then read an excerpt from
Lanceley's deposition in which the former negotiator stated that he
wasn't critical of the FBI agents on the Hostage Rescue Team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was drinking coffee and eating donuts and they were out
there lying in the grass, and I understood some of them even
entered the burning building to pull some of those folks out,''
Lanceley said. ``They risked their own lives to save lives and
that's more than I did.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferguson began her testimony with a description of Feb. 28,
1993, the day of the raid on Mount Carmel by agents of the federal
Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the women, I can't remember who they were, said,
'They're coming. They're here,''' Ferguson testified. ``Shortly
after I heard the words, 'They're coming,' there was shooting.''
</P>
<P>
   Government co-counsel Marie Hagen had Ferguson recount her
testimony since other Davidian women have testified they didn't
know there was going to be a raid. Ferguson told Caddell that she
didn't know either.
</P>
<P>
   Caddell asked if Ferguson saw any Davidians carrying weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so close to the floor,'' Ferguson said. ``I had my head
buried. I didn't see anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferguson was accompanied to court by her mother, Rita Riddle,
who testified last week. Riddle left Mount Carmel during the siege.
</P>
<P>
   In other testimony, Caddell submitted a written deposition from
Livingstone Fagan, who is serving a prison sentence on manslaughter
and weapons charges. Fagan said the Davidians' boast after the ATF
raid that they had weapons capable of blowing a tank into the air
was an idle threat intended to keep the government from realizing
``how vulnerable we were.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We only stated that so they would think that,'' Fagan said.
``As long as they thought that, we had a little grace.''
</P>
<P>
   Fagan also said he saw ATF agents on the roof of Mount Carmel
during the raid and shot at them. One fell off the roof, but Fagan
said he doesn't know if he shot him.
</P>
<P>
   The trial resumes today.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-27-00 2218EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000627.0393 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 22:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6670 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-PENDER-SFCHRON-COLUMN     06-27 1113
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PENDER-SFCHRON-COLUMN </SLUG>
  
Golden Gate Fund to Keep Clients' Investments Close to Home &HT;    By KATHLEEN PENDER 
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ It had to happen sooner or later: The first
mutual fund to invest exclusively in San Francisco Bay Area
companies will premiere next Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Golden Gate Fund will join a smattering of other regional funds
that have had varying degrees of success.
</P>
<P>
   It will be run by a smallish Larkspur, Calif., investment
advisory firm, Collins &AMP; Co. Its managers, Bruce Raabe and Brian
Eisenbarth, have never run a mutual fund. Until now, they have
focused on value investing, but the new fund will be ``a blend of
value and growth with a bias toward growth,'' says Raabe.
</P>
<P>
   Any pro will tell you that investing in a single state or region
makes little sense. But then the Bay Area is not any old place.
It's home to more than 600 public companies, concentrated in the
fast-growing technology, medical and financial sectors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bay Area has been a place where things always happen ahead
of the curve,'' says Raabe.
</P>
<P>
   Golden Gate will face stiff competition from Franklin California
Growth. This fund can invest throughout the state, but at the end
of March, 22 of its largest 25 holdings were headquartered in the
Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   At $2 billion in assets, Franklin California Growth is the
largest regional fund, and the best performing. For the five years
ending May 31, it was up 34 percent a year on average, beating the
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 by more than 10 percentage points a year.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, almost two-thirds of the portfolio was in
technology. The next-biggest sectors were services, health and
financials.
</P>
<P>
   Morningstar analyst Scott Berry says technology helped the
fund's performance, but so did nontech winners like Robert Half
International (up 100 percent this year) and Silicon Valley
Bancshares (up 67 percent).
</P>
<P>
   The main argument for regional funds is that managers gain an
edge by being close to the companies they own. With the Franklin
fund, ``proximity helps, but so does size. A fund of this size can
get in front of a lot of (company) managements,'' Berry says.
</P>
<P>
   He's not sure Golden Gate Fund will get the same kind of access.
Its investment options will also be more limited. If tech goes
south, Franklin can also go south _ as in Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd wait to see how (the new fund) does before I'd jump right
in,'' Berry says.
</P>
<P>
   Golden Gate Fund is licensed for sale only in California and
will be distributed mainly through  &LR; www.goldengatefund.com &LR; . Annual
expenses will be steep, at 1.95 percent of assets.
</P>
<P>
   Other regional funds include Safeco Northwest, WM Growth Fund of
the Northwest, HomeState Pennsylvania Growth, Aquila Rocky Mountain
Equity, Growth Fund of Washington, Maxus Ohio Heartland and New
York Equity.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of 5SPENDER (96253 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  MORE NEW FUNDS: Golden Gate Fund is just one of a slew of new
funds coming out of the Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Litman/Gregory, based in Larkspur and Orinda, will
open the third in its family of Masters' Select Funds, this one
focusing on value stocks.
</P>
<P>
   For each fund, Litman/Gregory picks a handful of top mutual fund
managers who each select no more than 15 stocks for the Masters'
fund. The idea is to get the best ideas from the top minds.
</P>
<P>
   So far, it seems to be working. In fact, Ken Gregory says most
managers are doing better with their Masters' picks than with their
own funds.
</P>
<P>
   From January 1997 through May 2000, Masters' Select Equity fund
was up 21.1 percent a year on average, according to Gregory. ``The
weighted average of the managers' own funds was only 16.9
percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Gaul of Morningstar says the Masters' fund is in the top
quartile of ``large-blend'' funds for the past three years.
</P>
<P>
   The Masters Equity Fund mixes growth, value, large and small
companies, with each manager chosen for his expertise in one style
of investing.
</P>
<P>
   Of the fund's six managers, two are doing slightly worse in
Masters' than in their own funds. Of the four who are doing better,
``three are ahead by a wide margin,'' Gregory says. But he refused
to name names.
</P>
<P>
   Masters' Equity was in the news in March when it replaced one of
its managers, Robert Sanborn of the Oakmark fund, with Bill Miller
of Legg Mason Value Trust. Around the same time, Sanborn resigned
from the Oakmark and was replaced by Bill Nygren, who also runs
Oakmark Select.
</P>
<P>
   The lineup for the new Masters' Select Value Fund includes
Miller and Mason Hawkins of Longleaf Partners, who also pick value
stocks for Masters Equity; Nygren; and Larry Sondike of Franklin
Mutual Shares.
</P>
<P>
   Morningstar's Gaul is not surprised that Litman/Gregory would
pick two managers from the Equity fund for the Value fund. ``If
they think (Miller and Hawkins) are the best managers overall, then
they'd think they're the best value managers, too,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   But, he adds, ``I wouldn't buy both funds, because there's going
to be a certain degree of overlap.''
</P>
<P>
   If you like the Masters' concept, check out the Managers funds.
This family also picks multiple outside managers to run its funds.
But the Managers funds are not as concentrated, because its
managers are not limited to 15 stocks.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of 5SPENDER (96253 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  (Full disclosure: I own shares in the Masters' Equity Fund.)
</P>
<P>
   I-YI-YI: That brings us to Barclays Global Investors, which
launches funds faster than Barry Bonds knocks out homers.
</P>
<P>
   BGI is behind the new exchange-traded funds called iShares.
These are index funds that trade on the American Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco company has launched 27 iShares since May and
will add 13 more before the end of July. (This doesn't include 17
overseas iShares previously known as WEBS.)
</P>
<P>
   BGI will have an iShare tracking every index you can imagine and
some you can't, such as the Standard &AMP; Poor's 600.
</P>
<P>
   iShares have some advantages over regular index funds: You can
trade them and get prices throughout the day, instead of once a
day. And expenses are rock-bottom, ranging from 0.09 percent a year
on the S&AMP;P 500 fund to 0.99 percent on emerging-markets funds.
However, you have to pay a brokerage commission when you buy and
sell them.
</P>
<P>
   IShares compete with Spiders, which are exchange-traded unit
investment trusts managed by State Street Bank and Trust, and
Nasdaq 100 Shares, better known by their ticker symbol QQQ. Soon,
they'll face a lineup of exchange-traded funds from Vanguard Group.
</P>
<P>
   Net Worth runs Tuesdays, Wednesdays and Fridays. E-mail Kathleen
Pender at kpender(at)sfgate.com.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 3 of 5SPENDER (96253 ) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
