<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   Try to Find a PC at This Year's PC Expo &HT;     By CAROLYN SAID  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Maybe they should call it ``Post-PC Expo.''
</P>
<P>
   You could walk a mile in the cavernous Jacob K. Javits
Convention Center here, passing many of the 600 vendors exhibiting
at PC Expo without seeing an actual personal computer. Instead of
boring beige boxes, vendors were hyping small, wireless and
Web-enabled devices. And no hoopla was greater than that
surrounding Palm and Palm-compatibles.
</P>
<P>
   From Sony Corp.'s entry into the market to Palm Computing's
announcement that every existing Palm soon will have wireless Web
access, handheld organizers hogged the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   The handheld device market today resembles the PC market in
1982, said Jeff Hawkins, co-founder of both Palm and its licensee
Handspring, in a keynote speech. In other words, the best is yet to
come.
</P>
<P>
   Quoting a study that says more people will eventually access the
Internet from mobile devices than any other platform, Hawkins
predicted that within two years, most handheld devices, including
both Palm-like machines and phones, will have persistent Net
connections, obviating the need to manually connect. And the
potential wireless audience is immense: Research firm IDC projects
that 1.3 billion people will soon have Web-capable phones.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Palm is stepping in to give wireless connectivity to
the majority of its user base. Although the Palm VII is the only
model that comes with built-in wireless access, Palm said it will
offer cables and software that will let other Palm users link their
devices to a cellular phone to get online.
</P>
<P>
   ``Virtually all Palm users will be able to connect their devices
to the Web,'' said Douglas Solomon, chief strategy officer at Palm.
The products will be available in September for less than $50. The
speed will be only 8 to 9 Kbps, but Palm said that will be adequate
for viewing Web sites that use its Web clipping technology.
</P>
<P>
   Palm also said its future devices will add a slot to plug in
postage stamp-size cards for data storage or specific applications.
Cards could be developed for such uses as monitoring your heart
rate and blood pressure, Palm said.
</P>
<P>
   Palm has some 70,000 developers, including quite a few that have
licensed the operating system to run on their own hardware. But its
latest licensee had TV crews lining up to film its prototype Palm
OS device, which it kept housed in a glass bubble. And that's
despite the fact that consumer electronics giant Sony was mum on
just about every detail of its forthcoming PDA. The price, the
features, even the name will be revealed later, a representative
said.
</P>
<P>
   The device will use Sony's memory stick technology to accept
plug-ins the size of a stick of gum, has a ``joy-dial'' control (a
kind of thumbwheel) for selecting applications and will be marketed
to average consumers, said David Yang, a Sony public relations
specialist. It will have unspecified ``digital imaging''
capabilities for both still and moving pictures.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of PCEXPO28 (32978 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  If Palm's OS licensing program is ``too'' successful, would Palm
ever pull the plug, the way Apple Computer did on its OS licensing?
Solomon, who used to be in charge of licensing at Apple, said the
situation is different with Palm because it is licensing the OS
early in the product life cycle. Instead of cannibalizing existing
sales, as happened with Apple, presumably Palm licensees would help
grow the overall market.
</P>
<P>
   Handspring, the Mountain View company whose Visor devices use
the Palm OS, said the OmniSky wireless modem and service will be
ready this fall for Visors. Already available for Palms, OmniSky
modems are $299; the service is $39.95 a month.
</P>
<P>
   Although at a quick glance it seemed like the majority of PC
Expo's 85,000 attendees use Palm devices, Palm's entire installed
base is just 7 million units. That's a drop in the bucket compared
with 400 million PCs, noted Dell Computer founder Michael Dell in a
press meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's actually quite a small market despite all the attention
it gets,'' he said, adding that Dell does not plan to make its own
handheld devices.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Carolyn Said at  &LR; csaid &LR; (at) &LR; sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 2 of PCEXPO28 (32978 ) &QL;
</P>
