<SLUG> BC-MP3-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   New MP3 Players Use Disks for Storage &HT;     By BENNY EVANGELISTA  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A major limitation for portable MP3 players is
the high price of memory needed to store the music. But two
companies, MP3 newcomer Iomega Corp. and pioneer Diamond Multimedia
Systems Inc., introduced new products yesterday designed to solve
that problem using small, cheap, removable disks.
</P>
<P>
   At the PC Expo in New York, Iomega Corp., the Utah maker of the
Zip storage drive for desktop computers, said it was jumping into
the growing portable MP3 player market with the RaveMP 2300, made
by Sensory Science Corp. of Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the new handheld digital audio players on the market use
internal flash memory chips that store one or two hours of near-CD
quality music or audio files. Adding another 32 megabytes of
memory, about one hour's worth of music, costs about $100.
</P>
<P>
   But the RaveMP 2300, which will cost $299 when it goes on sale
next month, uses a built-in Iomega Click drive, which reads
removable 40-MB minidisks. A pack of 10 Click disks costs about
$100.
</P>
<P>
   ``So for the same $100, you can have 400 MB of memory,'' said
Craig Rathbun, director of Iomega's Click product line.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the company plans to sell its own Iomega-brand
digital audio player by the end of the year. Iomega, trying to
rebound from a year of cutbacks and a management shakeup, is hoping
to capitalize on the fast moving evolution of music lovers using
computers and the Internet to listen to their songs. Iomega hopes
to spread the use of its Click drive to handheld computers,
cellular phones and digital cameras.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is part of a larger strategy to reinvent our company,''
Rathbun said. ``We see the MP3 player as just being part of the
portable products marketplace we want to make a foray into.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of IOMEGA28 (101847 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Meanwhile, Diamond Multimedia Systems Inc., which produced the
first portable MP3 player in 1998, will ship its third generation
Rio 600 digital audio player today.
</P>
<P>
   The $169 Rio 600 comes with 32 MB of flash memory, while the Rio
800 will come with 64 MB. Both, however, are designed to
accommodate a minidisk drive that should be available by late 2000,
said Jim Cady, communications division president for Diamond
Multimedia, a unit of S3 Inc. in Santa Clara, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Diamond has a stake in Dataplay Inc., a Colorado company that is
developing a 500 MB disk that is thinner than a quarter and should
cost ``less than $10'' each, Cady said yesterday during a product
demonstration in San Francisco. The price of Dataplay's minidisk
drive, which snaps into the back of the Rio, will be in the $120 to
$150 range.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that it holds more memory and is a lot cheaper is
attractive,'' said Phil Leigh, an Internet analyst with Raymond
James &AMP; Associates of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only drawback is that you have a moving part,'' the
spinning disk, Leigh said. The advantage of flash memory used in
other digital audio players is that it has no moving parts that
break or cause the sound to skip.
</P>
<P>
   But Rathbun said the new RaveMP 2300 reads the music off the
disk, then stores it in an internal buffer memory during playback,
so the sound won't skip if the player is bumped or dropped.
</P>
<P>
   And Cady said the Dataplay drives are being designed to
withstand the force of being dropped 4 feet onto cement.
</P>
<P>
   Leigh expects sales of portable MP3 players to double this year.
He added that sales could increase by three or four times if
Napster, the controversial file-swapping software, survives
copyright lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Benny Evangelista at &LR;  bennye &LR; (at) &LR; sfgate.com. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 2 of IOMEGA28 (101847 ) &QL;
</P>
