<SLUG> BC-GROW-SFCHRON-COLUMN </SLUG>
  
Bay Area Students Still Seek Internship Opportunities &HT;     By PETER SINTON  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Summer has already arrived but that doesn't mean
it's too late to hire a student intern for your business or
nonprofit organization.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco Chamber of Commerce, for example, has placed
about 300 high school students and recent grads with San Francisco
employers but has applications from 100 more students still looking
for work.
</P>
<P>
   It's a nifty program for both employers and students interested
in learning about the workplace and making some money. Businesses
agree to pay at least $6.50 an hour, 20 hours a week for six weeks
to those students hired.
</P>
<P>
   Nonprofits don't have to pay anything because local temp agency
owner Richard Essey and a few other entrepreneurs have put up about
$35,000 to cover the salaries for 50 student interns.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the pay, students get three hours a week of
career education hosted by the Federal Reserve Bank, Internal
Revenue Service, City College of San Francisco, Bank of America and
others.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Young, manager of the chamber's School-to-Career program,
said big companies such as BofA, Bechtel and Schwab hire most of
the students, while small businesses such as Elite Repographics,
Stevens &AMP; Associates architects and even a few startups such as
Listen.com hire about 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Although the chamber has set $6.50 as base pay for business
employers, Young said the pay goes as high as $15 or $16 an hour
for students with Web page design skills.
</P>
<P>
   Real estate manager the Swig Co. has hired two summer interns
``to help us get caught up on things,'' said Mills Building manager
Agnes Wyman.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of GROW28 (66608 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Amy Ying Cong Jiang, who will be a senior at Lincoln High School,
is getting $6.50 an hour doing clerical work and making sure all
the building signage and directory information is correct. And
Michael Stallings, who just graduated from Balboa High School and
will be going to City College, is an engineering assistant, working
on the building's machinery and operations.
</P>
<P>
   Arriba Juntos, a nonprofit employment and training agency, hired
a student for the second year to assist in its office. ``This is my
first job,'' said McAteer High School senior Jose Montalvo. ``I
want to know what it's like after high school.''
</P>
<P>
   For more information on the chamber-sponsored program, contact
Keith Young at (415) 217-5195 or e-mail
 &LR; kyoung &LR; (at) &LR; sfchamber.com. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   There are plenty of other programs and Web sites with
information and links to other services. One of the best is JobStar
California ( &LR; www.jobstar.org &LR; ), a guide to jobs and careers
supported by local libraries.
</P>
<P>
   JobStar's San Francisco Bay Area job search guide, which began
four years ago, offers career information and community resources
for Alameda, Contra Costa, Marin, Monterey, Napa, San Francisco,
San Mateo, Santa Clara, Santa Cruz, Solano and Sonoma counties.
</P>
<P>
   The site covers resume writing, career planning, salary
information, and has extensive listings of jobs, job fairs, job
hotlines and summer opportunities for high school and college
students.
</P>
<P>
   T-RAM IS TOPS: Last week, we wrote about Stanford University's
Global Entrepreneurs Conference 2000, an Olympic-style
business-plan contest for university entrepreneurs. Five winners
have been picked and the Stanford team, T-RAM, won two of the
prizes: most innovative product and elegance of business strategy.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of GROW28 (66608 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Conference planners insist that home-field advantage or the fact
that many of the 30 judges had local roots had nothing to do with
the choice. The T-RAM startup, it seems, has T-Rex-like power. Its
proprietary memory has the potential to revolutionize the
semiconductor industry by providing the memory density of dynamic
random access memory (DRAM) and the speed of static random access
memory (SRAM).
</P>
<P>
   The nearly $40,000 in prize money on top of the $25,000 first
prize in a recent Stanford engineering school contest is good news
for T-RAM founders and recent doctoral recipients Farid Nemati, 29,
and Homan Igehy, 27. But the financial faucet is just starting to
open for the two Iranian-born engineers. Igehy, who moved to the
United States at age 5, said T-RAM is going after a $100
billion-a-year chip market and a couple of Palo Alto VC firms are
poised to invest in the company.
</P>
<P>
   University of Buenos Aires' Latinarte.com team won positive
social impact award for its online art concept.
</P>
<P>
   The EyeGen team from Massachusetts Institute of Technology won
the global-market-potential prize for its plan to produce a dye
that makes DNA visible to the naked eye and is safer, cheaper and
faster than the radioactive and fluorescent probes used in genomic
and biomedical research.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the University of Sydney's Sydney Worldwide Pty. Ltd.
won the $150,000 Hewlett-Packard products-and-services prize for
best Internet concept. The team is planning 3-D online tours of
Australia and Southeast Asia. For flavor, try using your mouse to
surf Sydney's skyline on the Web ( &LR; www.sydneyworldwide.com &LR; ).
</P>
<P>
   Grow a Business appears every Wednesday in The Chronicle. Send
small-business tips, comments and questions to
 &LR; entrepreneurs &LR; (at) &LR; sfgate.com,  &LR; or to Peter Sinton, Grow a
Business column, 901 Mission St., San Francisco, CA 94103.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-27-00 2222EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
