u w BC-GORE-RENO-NYT &LR;      06-27 0722
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-RENO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RENO DEFENDS HER DECISION ON INQUIRY OF CAMPAIGN 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID JOHNSTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Attorney General Janet Reno said Tuesday at a
Senate hearing that no one ever pressured her into deciding to
refuse to seek an outside prosecutor to investigate President
Clinton and Vice President Al Gore for their political fund-raising
activities during the 1996 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Reno, who has repeatedly rebuffed requests for outside inquiries
of Clinton and Gore, testified that she had made judgments on the
basis of the facts and her interpretation of the independent
counsel law.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have not been shy about appointing independent counsels when
the facts and the law required it,'' she told the Senate Judiciary
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans sought to probe beneath the surface of Reno's
decision-making, but she blunted their efforts, frequently reading
aloud Justice Department documents, made public long ago, in which
she had explained her thinking.
</P>
<P>
   For their part, Democrats rallied around Reno. In an exchange
with Sen. Patrick J. Leahy, D-Vt., the attorney general said she
had never asked any Justice Department official to reach a
particular outcome when interpreting whether to send a case to an
independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you ask him to come out a certain way, though, in
determining which way _ whether to prosecute or not to prosecute on
those campaign finance cases?'' Leahy asked, referring to Lee J.
Radek, head of a unit that advised Reno on such matters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never,'' Reno replied.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did the president of the United States ever pressure you to
come out a particular way on any particular matter?'' the senator
asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, sir,'' Reno said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did the vice president of the United States ever pressure you
to come out a particular way on a particular matter?'' the senator
then asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, sir,'' she replied.
</P>
<P>
   Reno testified five days after Justice Department officials
confirmed that Robert J. Conrad Jr., head of the agency's campaign
finance unit, had urged her to appoint a special counsel to
investigate Gore's fund-raising in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Gore aides criticized a Republican on the committee,
Arlen Specter of Pennsylvania, who has been leading hearings into
how the Justice Department handled campaign finance issues and who
was the first lawmaker to publicly disclose Conrad's
recommendation.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Lehane, a spokesman for the Gore campaign, accused Specter
of ``McCarthyite tactics.'' Lehane said that Specter and other
Republicans ``have turned the Congress into a scandal industrial
complex designed to manufacture and create partisan scandals and
inflict political damage on the vice president a mere four months
before voters go to the polls.''
</P>
<P>
   At the hearing, Specter said he had announced Conrad's
recommendation for purposes of ``public accountability'' only after
Conrad had refused to respond when Specter asked him in an earlier
hearing whether the prosecutor had sought a special counsel for
Clinton or Gore. ``That disclosure was made in the course of the
committee's business,'' Specter said.
</P>
<P>
   Reno is weighing the proposal and has asked Conrad to respond in
writing to questions she has raised about it, government officials
said Tuesday. Conrad is expected to meet in a few days with Reno,
who, the officials said, seems unlikely to opt for an outside
prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   Reno has twice refused to seek an independent counsel to
investigate Gore's political fund raising. Although the law
governing such appointments has lapsed, Reno still has the
authority to name special counsels under rules that grant these
prosecutors much the same powers as an independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Conrad's recommendation to appoint a special counsel was based
largely on Gore's sometimes combative answers during an April 18
interview with prosecutors in which Gore was asked about a number
of events, among them his appearance at a Buddhist temple in
California, White House coffees for campaign supporters and missing
e-mail messages.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Republicans sought to persuade Reno to discuss her
deliberations on Conrad's recommendation, but she would not comment
on what she said was a pending case. She said, ``If the
circumstances justify the appointment of a special counsel, I'll be
the first to make it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
