<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-COACH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCOTT HAS ANSWERS TO NETS' QUESTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Just over a week ago, Rod Thorn and
Byron Scott sat in a room in Chicago's O'Hare Airport talking
basketball. There were no game films to watch, no statistical
profiles to ponder, just Thorn and Scott and a magnetic board
between them.
</P>
<P>
   Thorn, the Nets' president, asked Scott to use the magnetic
pieces to demonstrate everything he knew about basketball _
offensive game plans, defensive philosophy and fast-break theories.
For six hours, Scott worked the board, astounding Thorn with his
knowledge and convincing him that he was the coach the Nets needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went over every possible conceivable situation that could
happen on the basketball court,'' Thorn said Tuesday at the Nets'
Champion Center. ``That's when I became sold on Byron. He had all
the answers, so I was very impressed with what he knew about the Xs
and Os part of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only was he a terrific player, but he also has been doing
his homework regarding how the game is played, how the game is
taught, how the game is coached. This team needs a terrific coach.
This team needs somebody who will nurture our young players and
this team needs a firm hand where rules will be set and rules will
be followed. That's what Byron Scott brings to the table.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Scott, the former Los Angeles Lakers guard who won
three championships playing with Magic Johnson and Kareem
Abdul-Jabbar, was announced as the Nets' new head coach. He
received a three-year deal for $6.3 million, and the Nets have an
option to keep him for a fourth season.
</P>
<P>
   Scott, who played for the Lakers, Indiana Pacers and Vancouver
Grizzlies during his 14-year career, said the day's events were the
fulfillment of a dream that began six years ago, when Larry Brown
told him that he would make a good head coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Larry allowed me to come in there and teach the guys, teach
them how to win and what winning was all about,'' Scott said of the
two years he played under Brown with the Pacers. ``That was the
first time I really started thinking about coaching. He was the
first person to tell me that I think you'd be a great coach. It's
been on my mind ever since.''
</P>
<P>
   While Scott's strategic knowledge impressed Thorn, his
background also served as an advantage. In addition to playing for
Brown, he also played seven seasons for Pat Riley with the Lakers,
giving him the distinction of having played for two of the league's
top coaches. Scott, 39, said he learned a great deal from the two
coaches and incorporates much of their style and teachings into his
coaching.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll bring the type of discipline that they bring to a team,''
Scott said. ``I'm very demanding because I've had two very
demanding coaches, so I have nothing but that in my blood right
now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a positive person. I understand that these guys love to be
patted on the back, but they also want that discipline of knowing
that they did do or didn't do the right thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott, whose only coaching experience came when he assisted Rick
Adelman in Sacramento the past two seasons, compared himself to Doc
Rivers, the former player who was coach of the year this season in
his first year with Orlando. Scott said he believes that former
players have an advantage as coaches because they can better relate
to the players.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been through all the stuff the players are going
through, so what you tell them carries a little more weight,'' said
Scott, who retired in 1997. ``I understand the players. I
understand what it takes to win. I've been to the mountain top.
I've achieved unbelievable success as an NBA player so I know what
it takes to get to the next level, and I know how to push those
buttons.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephon Marbury, the Nets star point guard, is already sold.
</P>
<P>
   ``He brings respect from the door, as soon as he walks in,''
Marbury said. ``Having a guy like that, you know his mentality as
far as practice. You know what's going to be expected of you. You
know you're going to have to come in everyday and work, and that's
what we need. We need that attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott said he will attempt to bring the fast-break style of the
Lakers to New Jersey. Offensively, that will mean lots of ball
movement. He will also encourage Marbury to push the ball in the
open court. Defensively, that will mean improved on-the-ball and
help coverage and stronger rebounding.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
