<SLUG> BC-MEDIAMETRIX-JUPITER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEB MEASUREMENT TRACKER MEDIA METRIX ACQUIRES JUPITER
COMMUNICATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   By BARNABY J. FEDER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Media Metrix Inc., an influential arbiter of who's
hot and who's not in the Internet world, will acquire Jupiter
Communications, a leading analyst of Internet trends, the two
companies said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Combining the two companies will create ``the definitive source
for Internet measurement and analysis,'' said Tod Johnson, chairman
and chief executive of Media Metrix, which calculates the
popularity of more than 21,000 Web sites based on software tracking
the habits of 70,000 computer users in the United States and
overseas.
</P>
<P>
   But in the volatile Internet economy, no one's traffic
statistics are universally accepted as reliable, and the
projections of research firms often turn out to be wildly off the
mark. Tracking Internet activity has turned out to be surprisingly
difficult because there are so many different possible
measurements, including how often people visit a site, how long
they stay, and whether they transact any business there. There are
no standards for comparison comparable to those used in accounting.
</P>
<P>
   Still, both Media Metrix and Jupiter are seen as industry
leaders in providing valuable insights into Internet trends,
however questionable the actual figures on which they are based.
</P>
<P>
   ``Media Metrix's monthly reports definitely move stocks,'' said
Henry Blodgett, who tracks a broad portfolio of Internet companies
for Merrill Lynch. ``It's the closest thing there is to a
standard.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said that the merger should help the two companies
expand overseas, where demand for Internet information is growing
rapidly. It is also intended to provide opportunities for
``hybrid'' products, including analytical commentaries on Media
Metrix data and databases that help Jupiter produce analysis of
more narrowly defined market segments.
</P>
<P>
   Media Metrix's largest competitor is Nielsen/NetRatings, an
alliance of Nielsen Media Research and NetRatings Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Jupiter, which gets most of its revenue from subscribers to
monthly research reports and seminars, competes most directly with
Forrester Research, based in Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Investors were not immediately impressed by the possibilities.
Media Metrix's shares fell $4.875, or 17 percent, to $23.375 while
Jupiter's dipped $1.937, or 8 percent, to $21.625. Under the terms
of the agreement, Jupiter shareholders will receive .946 shares of
Media Metrix stock for each of their shares. The stock swap, which
was valued at about $414 million when the deal was announced, was
worth $343 million by the end of trading.
</P>
<P>
   One possible dampening factor was the expectation that the
Gartner Group, a Stamford, Conn.-based consulting firm with just
under 20 percent of Jupiter's stock, will sell the roughly 9
percent stake it would end up with in Jupiter Media Metrix. And,
indeed, a Gartner spokeswoman confirmed Tuesday that such a selloff
was likely.
</P>
<P>
   Jupiter Media Metrix would not be profitable until the end of
this year, according to Johnson. Jupiter earned just $11,000 from
continuing operations on revenues of $17.2 million in the first
quarter while Media Metrix lost $2.3 million on revenues of $10.2
million in the same period.
</P>
<P>
   The company would be based in New York, where both Jupiter and
Media Metrix are headquartered. Johnson will become chairman and
chief executive. Gene DeRose, chairman and chief executive of
Jupiter, will become president and vice chairman of Jupiter Media
Metrix. .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
