<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LINDROS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS WANT MORE INFO ON LINDROS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL SEGUNDO, Calif. _ The medical report the Kings hoped would
bring some clarity to Eric Lindros' future in the NHL was released
Tuesday, but shed little light on whether the former league MVP
will play again after suffering four concussions in the last four
months.
</P>
<P>
   The Philadelphia Flyers, who are hoping to trade Lindros before
Saturday, received the findings of neurologist James Kelly, who has
treated the former Flyers captain this past year.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly's report ruled out playing for now, but said Lindros needs
to be reevaluated after symptoms of post-concussion syndrome have
passed. Lindros told the Kings on Monday that he still is groggy
from the fourth concussion, which occurred last month during Game 7
of the Eastern Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have not seen the report and did not talk to (Flyers general
manager) Bobby Clarke today,'' Kings general manager Dave Taylor
said Tuesday. ``But I know what Eric told me. That there still were
problems. I don't expect any decision to be made before the
weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia must offer Lindros $8.5 million, the equivalent of
last year's salary, by Saturday or risk losing him to unrestricted
free agency without compensation. The Flyers have granted
permission to the Kings, New York Rangers and Toronto Maple Leafs
to speak to Lindros, but without a positive medical report,
everything is on hold.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dr. Kelly wants Eric to be free of symptoms for one week's
time before he examines him,'' Philadelphia team physician Jeff
Hartzell said Tuesday. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
