<HEADER>
A6694 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-NORMANSURGERY-COX     06-27 0735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NORMANSURGERY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Norman to have hip surgery, will miss British Open
 &HT;    By Craig Dolch
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. - Greg Norman will miss next month's
British Open at St. Andrews after he undergoes hip surgery
Wednesday to repair a problem he says has bothered him since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   While it pains him to miss his favorite tournament at his
favorite course, Norman was upbeat Tuesday when discussing his
second operation in the past 27 months. The relatively new,
hourlong arthroscopic surgery is expected to have Norman, 45, back
playing the PGA Championship in mid-August at Valhalla, Ky.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know this will give me a new lease on life,'' Norman said.
``When I walk out of there after surgery, it's going to be very
exciting because I will be 100 percent repaired. This is not a
degenerative condition like Bo Jackson or Jack Nicklaus. I should
have done this two or three years ago, but they didn't have this
technology back then.''
</P>
<P>
   Norman said he's had pain in his right hip for several years,
but it became more severe in recent months. He said he constantly
tried to fix the ailment, but doctors either didn't diagnose it
properly or didn't know what they were looking for.
</P>
<P>
   He said it wasn't until he shot an 82 in the second round at
Pebble Beach _ his worst score in a U.S. Open _ and missed the cut
by 10 shots that he felt compelled to get the hip repaired. The
surgery will be performed by Dr. Marc Philippon at Holy Cross
Hospital in Fort Lauderdale. Philippon will be assisted by Dr.
Richard Hawkins, who operated on Norman's left shoulder in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of humility at what happened at Pebble Beach,''
Norman said. ``It was kind of what happened at the (1998) Masters
when I almost killed the guy with my driver (on a tee shot on the
18th hole). There's no more humbling experience than walking off
the course after you've shot 17-over. You get to the point where
enough is enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Norman said Philippon and Hawkins both told him the hip
situation likely led to his shoulder injury. X-rays showed there
were calcium deposits in his hip that may have been there as long
as seven years ago, which led him to put more stress on his
shoulder to compensate.
</P>
<P>
   Philippon said the surgery _ which Norman will be able to watch
on a monitor _ will include cutting away dead tissue from the
labrum, which lines the inner rim of the hip socket. Philippon also
might need to use laser treatment to decrease the size of Norman's
ball joint which, because of a slight abnormality, is bigger than
the socket.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a degenerative condition, and it's possible Greg
can be hitting balls as soon as within 10 days,'' Philippon said.
``Physiologically, Greg has the body of a 20-year-old. There's no
reason he can't go back to playing the way he was before the hip
started hurting.''
</P>
<P>
   Norman has won 86 tournaments worldwide, but none since he
underwent the shoulder surgery in April of 1998, which caused him
to miss the rest of that season. His 18th PGA Tour title came in
the 1997 World Series of Golf and he last won at his Holden
International in Australia in early 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Norman returned to tie Jose-Maria Olazabal for the back-nine
lead at the 1999 Masters, but made two late bogeys and finished
third. He also contended at last year's British Open _ where he won
both of his majors _ at Carnoustie before finishing sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Norman, 45, knows many golf fans will think his career is
nearing an end.
</P>
<P>
   ``First off, I don't look at this as major surgery,'' he said.
``People can think that (I'm done), but they don't know what the
intensity is like in myself once I know I'm 100 percent healthy and
I can go out and execute again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time is not on my side, admittedly. But 45 is just a number.
It's how you feel and how your body reacts that's important. The
doctors have told me I can come back and play 10 years as hard as I
want.''
</P>
<P>
   Norman said he considered having the surgery after the British
Open, but that would jeopardize him playing in the PGA and possibly
the Presidents Cup in mid-October.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no guarantee I wouldn't go over and shoot 17-over
again,'' Norman said. ``This way, I know I'll be healthy and I
won't miss the PGA. It was a tough decision, but it was the
decision I had to make.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
