<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 23:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6826 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GORE-FUNDRAISING-NYT &LR;      06-27 0999
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-FUNDRAISING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE'S OWN WORDS WILL HURT HIM, REPUBLICANS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   By JAMES DAO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When Vice President Al Gore announced last week
that he was releasing the transcript from his April 18 interview
with Justice Department investigators, he confidently declared, ``I
think the truth is my friend in this.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats are convinced he is right. Attorney General Janet Reno
is unlikely to appoint a special prosecutor to investigate Gore's
1996 fund-raising activities, they say. And voters will be inclined
to view Gore as having been truthful in the interview and
forthright in releasing the transcript.
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans clearly believe Gore's transcript will also be
their friend. Even if Reno does not appoint a special prosecutor,
they say, the mere whiff of scandal emanating from the transcript
will hurt the vice president this November.
</P>
<P>
   And perhaps more useful, Republican strategists argue, will be
Gore's words themselves. In the frequently combative four-hour
grilling, conducted under oath, the vice president often comes
across as evasive or legalistic, they assert. Many of his answers
are too carefully parsed. And more than a few times, his memory _
considered to be quite excellent _ fails.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, Republicans argue, Gore's performance that day
can only bolster their contention that he, like President Clinton,
plays fast and loose with the truth.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I read one of his answers, I laughed out loud because it
sounded so Clintonesque,'' said Mark Miller, the executive director
the Republican Leadership Council, a centrist Republican group.
``He was trying to define the word `raising.' And I just said to
myself, he's learned from the master.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller was referring to a passage in which Robert Conrad, the
head of the Justice Department's task force investigating campaign
finance abuses, quizzed Gore about White House events in which
Democratic contributors, or potential contributors, met with
Clinton or Gore over coffee. Had anyone told Gore that those
coffees would be used to raise money? Conrad asked.
</P>
<P>
   Gore replied, ``Well, let me define the term `raising,' if I
could, because if you mean by it, would they be events at which
money was raised, the answer is no.'' In fact, Gore said, the
coffees were a means to show a potential contributors ``respect,''
and the pitch for money would come later. Hence, they were not
fund-raisers, he argued.
</P>
<P>
   Conrad followed up. Did Gore know that, according to a Senate
Republican report, more than 103 White House coffees had helped
raise $26.4 million for the Democrats? And given that report, would
it not be fair to describe the coffees as ``a fund-raising tool?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I hesitate to wordsmith it,'' Gore replied. ``I would not call
them fund-raising tools.''
</P>
<P>
   To some political analysts, such hair-splitting echoes Clinton's
famous response to a question about whether he was having an affair
with Monica Lewinsky: ``It depends on what the definition of is,
is.'' Or Gore's own explanation for why he had not broken the law
when he made fund-raising phone calls from the White House, that
there was ``no controlling legal authority.''
</P>
<P>
   About that reply, Ross Baker, a professor of political science
at Rutgers University, said: ``If he had not used that tortured
expression a few years ago, which has become a mantra for evasion
and subterfuge, I would think this would be less damaging. But
there is a prelude to this. And the prelude has come to define
political weasel words.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's aides argue that the public will see Gore's answers as
reasonable and forthright, given the contentious conditions of the
interview. More important, they assert that the public no longer
cares about the continuing scandal investigations, and that there
may even be an electoral backlash against Republicans who continue
to push for more.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republicans think this plays into Clinton fatigue,'' said
Chris Lehane, Gore's press secretary. ``But the thing people are
fatigued with is scandal.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's argument with Conrad over the definition of
``fund-raiser'' spilled over into questions about his 1996
appearance at the Hsi Lai Temple in Los Angeles. In 1996, Gore
described that event as ``community outreach.'' In 1997, he called
it ``a political event'' at which ``finance people were going to be
present.'' And to Conrad, he described it as a ``finance-related
event.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked by Conrad to define what that meant, Gore explained that
the event was not a fund-raiser because, ``There was no
solicitation of money. I did not see any money or checks exchange
hands.''
</P>
<P>
   But several people who attended the temple event, including
Buddhist monks and nuns, later gave checks to the Democratic
National Committee, in many cases using money that was not their
own. The event's organizer, Maria Hsia, was convicted in March for
hiding $109,000 in illegal contributions and making false
statements to federal regulators about the temple luncheon.
</P>
<P>
   At another point, Conrad questioned Gore about a memorandum in
which Gore was quoted discussing his fund-raising activities. The
vice president asserted that the memorandum was written by an aide.
Conrad asked if the memorandum accurately expressed his views.
</P>
<P>
   Gore responded with this carefully constructed sentence: ``It
would have contained recommendations by someone else as to what I
could say in order to support his understanding of my views.''
</P>
<P>
   In yet another passage, Gore seemed to raise questions about the
sincerity of his own form letters to his supporters. One letter,
full of superlatives, contained ``the kind of routine overstatement
that is quite common,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, when you refer to them as great friends, you don't
necessarily mean that?'' Conrad asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do mean it,'' Gore replied. ``But I don't mean it in the way
that you and I would use the phrase with a lifelong friend that you
met in college or something.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
