<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE  

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   U.S. GOES TO COURT TO STOP WORLDCOM DEAL FOR SPRINT
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department sought an injunction in federal court
against WorldCom's proposed $115 billion acquisition of Sprint,
citing concerns that the combined company would stifle competition
on the Internet and in the long-distance telephone industry.
</P>
<P>
   The companies said only that they would review their options.
WorldCom and Sprint could fight the government in court, but
executives from the companies have said that they would almost
surely abandon their deal in the face of a Justice Department suit.
Shares of WorldCom increased $2.1875, to $39.6875, while Sprint
fell $1.1875, to $58.375.
</P>
<P>
   ORACLE ADMITS HIRING DETECTIVE FIRM
</P>
<P>
   Oracle acknowledged that it had hired a detective firm to
investigate groups sympathetic to Microsoft, an effort that
included searching the groups' trash for documents.
</P>
<P>
   FDA REVIEWS PRESCRIPTION STATUS
</P>
<P>
   Spurred by two pharmaceutical companies that want to take their
cholesterol-lowering medications over the counter, the Food and
Drug Administration is considering whether many more medicines _
from antibiotics to birth control pills _ should be made available
without a doctor's prescription.
</P>
<P>
   MEDIA METRIX PLANS TO BUY JUPITER
</P>
<P>
   Media Metrix, an arbiter of who's hot and who's not in the
Internet world, will buy Jupiter Communications, an analyst of
Internet trends, for $414 million in stock.
</P>
<P>
   STOCKS FALL IN A TECHNOLOGY SLUMP
</P>
<P>
   Stocks ended lower, led by a slide in the technology sector,
after a Wall Street analyst cut his estimate for second-quarter
revenue at IBM. The Dow Jones industrial average was off 38.53
points, or 0.4 percent, to 10,504.46. The technology-dominated
Nasdaq composite index dropped 53.16 points, or 1.4 percent, to
3,858.96. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index slipped 4.76
points, to 1,450.55.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. FUND TO ACQUIRE JAPANESE BANK
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese government said that it would sell the bankrupt
Tokyo Sowa Bank to an investment fund led by Wilbur L. Ross, a
specialist in corporate rescues, for $331 million.
</P>
<P>
   A COMPETITOR, BIG ON PEAKS
</P>
<P>
   The Internet life is stressful, says Lewis David Gersh, founder
and chief executive of Worldly Information Network, an online
financial information company. But he is ``having a blast'' and
does not think he has peaked.
</P>
<P>
   DESPERATELY SEEKING ACCOUNTANTS
</P>
<P>
   Jobs are so plentiful and applicants so scarce that big
accounting firms have started grooming talent at high schools, the
latest battlefield in a recruitment war.
</P>
<P>
   ESTIMATES RAISED FOR AD SPENDING
</P>
<P>
   Robert J. Coen, a leading forecaster of advertising spending,
has raised his estimates for 2000 to a record $235.6 billion, up
9.4 percent from a revised figure of $215.3 billion spent in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   A SUMMER OF WAITING IN AIRPORTS
</P>
<P>
   Summertime flight delays are starting to pile up as traffic
increases at domestic airports. And despite new strategies for
better-coordinated air traffic control responses to weather-related
delays, the industry is worried that this summer is going to be one
of the worst ever for delays.
</P>
</TEXT>
