<SLUG> BC-EDIT-GENOME-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: AFTER THE GENOME ANNOUNCEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Wednesday, June 28:
</P>
<P>
   Now that decipherment of the human genome has been so grandly
trumpeted, practical and highly personal questions inevitably
arise. What difference will this make to me? How soon will it help
or hurt me? The answers were not always easy to discern in the
torrent of commentary after Monday's triumphal announcement that a
public consortium of academic institutions and a private company
had each determined the exact sequence of the vast majority of
chemical letters in the human genetic material. It is those letters
that determine, when strung together as genes, how all the cells in
the human body develop and function. In the commonly used metaphor,
the genome is a blueprint for life.
</P>
<P>
   In the long run, there seems no question that deciphering the
genome will help propel research and medicine to a deeper level of
understanding. Using so-called gene expression chips, scientists
will be able to detect which genes are active in a heart cell and
which are active in a kidney cell, shedding light on what makes
those cells develop differently. They will also be able to compare
gene activity in normal cells and cancer cells, in an effort to
identify all the genes involved in causing the cancer and then to
find a way to intervene at the molecular level. That would leave
today's primary treatments for cancer _ cutting the cancer out, or
zapping it with radiation, or hitting it with a toxic brew of
chemicals _ looking like crude and barbaric relics of a less
sophisticated past.
</P>
<P>
   But what is often lost in the excitement is how long the process
of discovery may take. Everyone expects some medical breakthroughs,
in the form of drugs or diagnostic tests based on the new genetic
understandings, to emerge in the next 5 to 10 years, but no one can
say for certain just what the breakthroughs will be. Dr. Francis
Collins, head of the publicly funded Human Genome Project, hazarded
a guess that within the next decade there will be tests to tell
people what genetically influenced diseases, such as diabetes and
heart disease, they are at increased risk for, and that in 15 to 20
years drugs will be targeted on the precise molecular problem
contributing to, say, cancer or mental illness. But Collins seemed
much less sanguine about manipulating the aging process to extend
the human life span, calling that far less certain to happen over
the next 40 to 50 years, though it could.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody really knows. Indeed, the truth is that simply knowing
the exact sequence of chemical units in the human genetic material
does not tell scientists much about how the genes function, how
they interact with each other, or what proteins they produce to
catalyze events in the body's cells. The proteins are the real
center of interest in biology and the most likely targets of drug
treatments. Their mysteries will be far harder to penetrate than
was the genome. That is why eminent biologists have been saying
there is a century of work ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, having the entire genome laid out on computer
databases will be a great advantage because researchers can search
for relevant genes at speeds unimagined in the recent past. At
Monday's ceremonies, key scientists in the genome work recounted
how genes that took a decade of hard work to find in the 1980s
could be found today by a single postgraduate student in anywhere
from 15 seconds to two weeks, just by searching a database. That
enormous amplification of research power alone warrants all the
exuberance over the genome project. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-27-00 2324EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000627.0424 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 23:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6844 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-NBA-DRAFT-NYT &LR;      06-27 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-DRAFT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN NBA DRAFTS, THE EMPHASIS IS ON THE FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE WISE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ Kenyon Martin is still rehabilitating the leg he
fractured three months ago, but insists he will be healthy for
training camp. ``I should be fine,'' he said. ``I just have to work
extra hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Darius Miles has not had a full-time job but he would like to be
a sixth or seventh man for a National Basketball Association team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think teams will pick me like they did Kevin Garnett or
Tracy McGrady or Kobe _ a player that comes straight out of high
school that can learn quickly, like they did,'' the 18-year-old
said Tuesday. ``That's how I think teams look at me. I don't think
they look at me to dominate the game.''
</P>
<P>
   This is not your grandfather's draft. It is not even Garnett's
1995 draft. They're calling it the Stars of Tomorrow Auction.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, the consensus national college basketball player of the
year, is expected to be taken No. 1 Wednesday night by the
soft-in-the-middle Nets.
</P>
<P>
   Stromile Swift's two-month ascension from unknown LSU
shot-blocker to bona fide lottery pick will most likely end with
the Vancouver Grizzlies selecting the 6-foot-9 forward No. 2.
</P>
<P>
   Iowa State power forward Marcus Fizer may not get past the Los
Angeles Clippers at No. 3, leaving the Chicago Bulls with the
prospect of taking Miles with the fourth pick. Chris Mihm, the
7-foot Texas center, is expected not to go lower than No. 7.
</P>
<P>
   After Florida's Mike Miller, Cincinnati's DerMarr Johnson and
Fresno State's Courtney Alexander, the nation's leading scorer, a
plethora of forwards and 6-foot-and-under point guards will compete
for attention in the Target Center green room.
</P>
<P>
   Another bumper crop of early-entry candidates applied. Of the 37
prospects, 27 are college underclassmen, eight are international
players and two are high school teen-agers. After Miles, DeShawn
Stevenson out of Washington Union High School in Fresno, Calif.,
hopes to become the 15th player in the league's modern era to jump
straight from high school to the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   With the proliferation of teen-agers still storming the league
with alarming regularity, free agency has proven more of a quick
fix than the draft in recent years. But there are power brokers who
still see the annual talent auction as a genuine way to build their
teams.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago general manager Jerry Krause, who once nabbed Scottie
Pippen and Charles Oakley, possesses the Nos. 4, 7 and 24 picks in
the first round, not to mention the 32nd through 34th picks in the
second round. Orlando has the 5th, 10th and 13th selections, while
the Clippers pick No. 3, No. 18 and No. 30.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, six players from three teams were swapped today in
the first action of the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   Milwaukee dealt forwards Robert Traylor and J.R. Reid to the
Cavaliers while trading veteran guard Vinny Del Negro to the
Warriors. Cleveland dealt guard Bob Sura to the Warriors, and
Golden State sent forwards Jason Caffey and Billy Owens to
Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, out of Cincinnati, would become the second power forward
to go No. 1 in consecutive years after Chicago plucked Elton Brand
out of Duke last June. He would also be the first top pick from
Dallas since the Charlotte Hornets selected Larry Johnson No. 1 in
1991.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets ran a battery of tests on Martin's broken leg and had
their doctors closely inspect the injury. No long-term effects were
projected, and Nets president Rod Thorn has intimated he will most
likely take Martin with the first pick _ if Orlando does not pry it
out of his hands with a lucrative deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``That remains to be seen,'' Martin said today. ``I'm going to
do all I can to help the team win if I'm there. They have Keith,
Stephon, Kendall Gill and people like that, so they have a pretty
good nucleus already.''
</P>
<P>
   If Martin does not go No. 1? ``I don't think I'll slip far,'' he
said. ``If I don't go No. 1, there's a good chance I'll go two or
three.''
</P>
<P>
   Miles is the most intriguing player available. Lean and agile at
6-9 and less than 220 pounds, he can sky over defenders or contort
his way through mounds of muscle in the pain. Last year, he worked
as a counselor at Michael Jordan's summer camp in Santa Barbara,
Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played a little counselor game every night and he picked me
to be on his team every night,'' Miles said of Jordan, who has
publicly stated he would take Miles if Washington had the No. 1
pick. He truly liked the kid's precocious behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``If somebody like the Lakers or Portland had a top pick, I know
I'd never get to play,'' Miles said when asked if he'd rather go to
a lottery team. ``Sometimes I'd probably just put my warm-up suit
on, and not even my jersey. Low teams need the lottery pick. They
need players that are going to make a difference. Like Vince
Carter. He came in, and three years later they made the playoffs.
If you get a player with a whole lot of potential, he can turn your
franchise around.''
</P>
<P>
   In earlier times, that was the goal on draft day. These days,
NBA teams realize they have more projects than perennial All-Stars
on their hands. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
