u s BC-BBA-YANKS-SOSA-NYT &LR;      06-27 0839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-SOSA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOSA TALKS NEARLY OVER, ONE WAY OR ANOTHER 
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ The Sammy Sosa trade talks envelop the New York
Yankees like a fog that won't go away. But the president of the
Chicago Cubs wants the discussions settled, one way or the other.
And the Yankee manager, Joe Torre, has suggested to club executives
that for the good of the team, they should make a deal or move on.
</P>
<P>
   With pressure for a resolution mounting from both sides, Sosa
could be a Yankee within 24 hours, in a trade of five to seven
prospects for Sosa and pitcher Ismael Valdes. Or the Yanks might
make another deal, perhaps with the Oakland Athletics, Pittsburgh
Pirates or the Baltimore Orioles. Or, they might do nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no reason for this thing to be prolonged any
further,'' said Andy MacPhail, the Cubs' vice president, in a
telephone interview Tuesday night. ``I will push for this to come
to a resolution one way or another shortly. It's not that hard. We
can agree, or we can agree to disagree.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre said, ``Make it happen, or make it go away.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees and the Cubs are on the verge of settling on a trade
that would send a stable of prospects _ shortstop Alfonso Soriano,
infielder D'Angelo Jimenez, pitchers Jake Westbrook and Alex
Graman, outfielder Jackson Melian and outfielder Ricky Ledee are
among those being discussed _ to Chicago for Sosa and Valdes, a
right-handed pitcher who would presumably join the Yankees'
rotation. Once the two sides reach an agreement on players, then
the Yankees would presumably receive a 72-hour window within which
to negotiate a contract with Sosa and to persuade him to waive his
right to veto the trade.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides understand now where the middle ground is. They both
understand what it will take to complete a deal. But while the
Yankees continue to talk to the Cubs _ one Yankee official
indicated that the Cubs are pushing to complete the deal _ New York
is evaluating the implications of the huge commitment in money and
prospects the trade would entail.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees, whose farm teams are solid but not teeming with
prospects, would bite deep into their system and swap a handful of
young players who could help them, while earning low salaries, in
the years to come. In return, they would receive Valdes, a talented
but erratic pitcher whose mound fortitude has been repeatedly
questioned, and a high-impact offensive player who could contribute
lots of home runs, lots and lots of strikeouts and phenomenal
marquee value.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees could go in another direction. They have had
discussions with the Oakland Athletics about acquiring an offensive
player, possibly outfielder Ben Grieve, whose salary will skyrocket
next year, or Olmedo Saenz or Matt Stairs; Oakland covets Soriano
and Shane Spencer.
</P>
<P>
   The Pittsburgh Pirates represent a more modest deal that would
bring the Yankees a pitcher and a hitter _ either Francisco Cordova
or Jose Silva, both right-handed pitchers, paired with either the
proven hitter Wil Cordero or the veteran John Vander Wal. The
Yankees also spoke with the Baltimore Orioles today about the
availability of the right-hander Scott Erickson, and continued
discussions about the left-handed-hitting outfielder B.J. Surhoff;
these talks are not yet serious.
</P>
<P>
   Talks regarding Houston's Moises Alou are all but destined to
fail; Alou has a no-trade provision in his contract and doesn't
want to be dealt.
</P>
<P>
   What the Yankees must decide is whether they are ready to take
the Sosa leap; it's the bungee jump of their trade options.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody involved, from executives to players, want the Yankees
to jump quickly, or back off quickly. Bernie Williams, the Yankees'
center fielder and the team's leader, believes the trade talks have
weighed on the team, which has lost 24 of its last 39 games. ``You
see a guy trying to press, like it's their last game,'' Williams
said. ``Everybody's wondering what's going to happen. Even if it
takes away only 5 percent of our attention, or 10 percent, it's
still a distraction.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams didn't mention Ledee's name directly, but he might as
well have. Ledee has been on edge since spring training, when his
name was part of the Jim Edmonds trade talks, and particularly
since May, when George Steinbrenner wondered aloud whether Ledee
was tough enough to play in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Ledee learned last Thursday that he was part of the conditional
Juan Gonzalez deal with Detroit, and for four days, he waited to
see if Gonzalez would reach a contract agreement with the Yankees.
Each day, Ledee wondered if it was his last with the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night, Ledee flipped on his computer in the Atheneum
hotel in downtown Detroit, and the first headline he saw said that
Gonzalez had turned down a one-year offer from the Yankees. Ledee
signed on to the Yankees' Web site, and he read as fans batted his
name back and forth in trade rumors, for Sosa, for Cordero. He
turned the computer off well past midnight.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
