<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WIMBLEDON-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Editors: subs for budgeted Agassi item.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Dad as coach helps Capriati win at Wimbledon
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Clarke
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ Jennifer Capriati won her first-round match
Tuesday at Wimbledon, this time with the same coach she had when
she became the youngest player in history to win a match here: her
father.
</P>
<P>
   Stefano Capriati recently received the official title from his
daughter after not having it for seven years, she said after
upsetting No. 16 seed Dominique Van Roost 6-2, 6-4 in her
first-round match.
</P>
<P>
   Capriati, 24, realized she needed a coach after her first-round
bomb-out in Paris and then jointly decided with her father that he
was the right man for the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the French, it was just like, 'Forget this. I need
somebody as my coach.' I think my dad is the perfect person for
right now,'' she said. ``So far it's good. I've done well the last
couple weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Capriati and former coach Harold Solomon parted ways in April,
soon after she was linked romantically with fellow player Xavier
Malisse at the Ericsson Open. Solomon won't discuss the split, but
it came at his request.
</P>
<P>
   ``That happens,'' she said. ``Just because we got together and
had that relationship, it's not always going to be a forever thing.
We didn't see things on the same terms in some areas.''
</P>
<P>
   She credited Solomon with helping her get over a competitive
hump in the 12 months they worked together and she plans to carry
on with many things he taught her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I've definitely had enough experience playing this
game,'' Capriati said. ``Hopefully I'm strong-willed enough that I
don't need somebody there all the time. You know, I'm not like a
little baby here.''
</P>
<P>
   But her fitness level has faltered _ she looked winded
throughout her match _ and her results bottomed out for a few weeks
with three straight opening-round losses.
</P>
<P>
   It was a shock after Capriati had started the year in great
shape and with great fanfare, losing a close match to Lindsay
Davenport in the Australian Open semifinals and defeating Serena
Williams at the Ericsson before losing in the quarterfinals.
</P>
<P>
   However, since putting her father on her official team, Capriati
reached the quarterfinals in Birmingham two weeks ago and the
semifinals last week in Holland where she lost to eventual champion
Martina Hingis.
</P>
<P>
   Stefano Capriati, of course, was widely blamed for _ however
unintentionally _ smothering his daughter and pressuring her as a
young player. She turned pro at 13 and advanced to the fourth round
of Wimbledon in 1990 at age 14.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, she reached a career-high ranking of No. 6, but by late
1993, she had quit the tour and for several years, she struggled
publicly with growing up.
</P>
<P>
   This time around, Dad will restrict his work primarily to
coaching duties, Capriati said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before, he was my dad, there doing everything,'' she said.
``But now, on the court, I just let him say whatever as any
coach.''
</P>
<P>
   She thinks he's a perfect fit to help her tennis because he
knows her game and her so well.
</P>
<P>
   ``He started me playing tennis,'' she said. ``He knows the way
to tell me things so I understand them.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though flags certainly will rise at this reconnection,
Capriati said she's aware and feels confident he will be able to
separate the father/daughter relationship from the coach/player
relationship and that it won't cause problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's getting better at it, especially now that I'm
older,'' she said. ``It's going to be tough always to get a
complete separation. I don't want that anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Capriati is seeking a balance between those roles, despite
knowing many players have struggled to find it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're learning,'' she said. ``It helps that I'm older and I
have my own things going. I have my boyfriend here. That makes it a
little bit easier.''
</P>
<P>
   She wouldn't reveal anything her father has done to help her
game but did say Malisse provided a pointer on her serve that has
helped.
</P>
<P>
   But both men in her life have pushed her toward contentment and
that has made tennis easier, whether she's winning or losing, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good thing because I won't take it as serious,''
Capriati said. ``It's good having the support in my personal life,
off the court. That helps me cope with the tennis.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
