<SLUG> BC-AIRLINES-DELAYED-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORT: AIRLINES BLAMING CONTROLLERS FOR DELAYS, RATHER THAN
TRUTH 
</HEADLINE>
   By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Airlines, required to tell their passengers if a
flight will be delayed, often blame air traffic control, even if
the real reason is bad weather, a shortage of crew members or
maintenance problems, the Transportation Department said in a
report Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The report, intended to gauge how well the airlines are meeting
their customer service commitments, was ordered by Congress last
fall and issued by the department's inspector general.
</P>
<P>
   The report said there was ``major room for improvement in the
accuracy, reliability and timeliness of the airlines'
communications to customers about the status of flights.'' In
general, the inspector general found, the airlines were making a
``clear and genuine'' effort to keep their promises, but that the
results were mixed. The airlines ``have a ways to go to restore
customer confidence,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   The airlines agreed to improve service last year to stave off
legislation that would have required such action. The House and
Senate held hearings on the issue because of growing complaints
about overbooking, lost baggage and delays, including an incident
in Detroit last year, when hundreds of Northwest Airlines
passengers were stuck on snowbound planes for up to eight hours.
</P>
<P>
   The inspector general, Kenneth Mead, said there was still room
for improvement on the airlines' promise to offer consumers the
lowest fare for which they are eligible. In some cases, the report
said, telephone ticket agents did not ask callers if they were
willing to adjust their itineraries to get a cheaper fare.
</P>
<P>
   The airlines promised to use their best efforts to return lost
baggage within 24 hours, but the report found that the carriers
cannot agree on what 24 hours means. Some started the clock when a
passenger filed a missing bag claim, while others started it only
when the bag finally arrived at the destination airport.
</P>
<P>
   The airlines, at a news briefing earlier Tuesday, said they had
generally improved. American Airlines said it was providing more
leg room on all domestic flights by removing some seats;
Continental said it had set up service planning centers at hub
airports to help re-book passengers or find them hotel
reservations; Delta said it was installing automated ticketing
kiosks to cut waiting time; and United said it was providing
``mobile workstations'' to help reduce lines when passengers rush
to rebook.
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. Ron Wyden, D-Ore., said the report was evidence that
Congress should have made the improvements mandatory.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is hard, independent evidence that there is a big gap
between what the airlines have promised the passengers and what
they have actually delivered,'' Wyden said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
