<SLUG> BC-COOPERATIVE-BAPTIST-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COOPERATIVE BAPTISTS TRY TO PUT THE PAST BEHIND 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CARY McMULLEN   
 The Ledger, Lakeland, Fla.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   They are the ``other'' Southern Baptists _ the ones who don't
have a quarrel with Disney.
</P>
<P>
   Many are ``moderates,'' those who largely ran Southern Baptist
Convention agencies and seminaries until conservatives, in a long,
determined effort, wrested control away and ousted them. They still
carry wounds, many of them, from those wars in the convention in
the 1980s. The bitterness of the struggles occasionally shows up in
their conversations.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the members of the Cooperative Baptist Fellowship say they
have tried to put the past behind them and create an organization
united around what made them Baptist in the first place: individual
and congregational autonomy, evangelism and missions.
</P>
<P>
   The fellowship will hold its annual national General Assembly in
Orlando, Fla., from Thursday to July 1, with about 4,500
participants sitting in seats recently vacated by Southern Baptist
Convention members, who met at the Orange County Convention Center
June 13 and 14. Unlike the Southern Baptist Convention, which has
asked members to boycott the Walt Disney Co., the fellowship is
holding sessions at Epcot with Disney's cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   The assembly marks the ninth year for the organization that
began as a refuge for like-minded Southern Baptists who were
alienated from their denomination. It now has more than 1,800
contributing churches and a $15.5 million budget that supports 40
staff members and 150 missionaries. By contrast, the Southern
Baptist Convention counts more than 41,000 churches and has a
comprehensive budget of more than $927 million.
</P>
<P>
   Most churches that contribute to the fellowship also give money
to and would be counted by the Southern Baptist Convention, which
is possible because Baptist churches are autonomous and
participation in any organization is voluntary.
</P>
<P>
   Fellowship leaders insist it was never intended to be an
organization like the Southern Baptist Convention, only a
loose-knit cooperative, but it has the outward appearance of a
denomination. It supports, but does not run, 11 seminaries that
sprang up as moderate alternatives to the six Southern Baptist
schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a partnering network rather than owning and operating a
lot of programs. I think we fulfill a denominational role, but we
don't do it with a convention model,'' said the Rev. Daniel Vestal,
the fellowship's chief executive, from his office in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Vestal said the CBF is healthy and growing, pointing to 20 state
or regional affiliated ``networks.'' Ongoing controversies in the
SBC, such as this year's revision of the Baptist Faith and Message
document that declared ``the office of pastor is limited to men as
qualified by Scripture,'' continue to drive churches into the arms
of the fellowship, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The CBF is at something of a crossroads, and one of its major
agenda items, to be considered Friday, is a strategic plan to
continue the direction the fellowship has chosen: putting together
networks rather than building a bureaucracy. Offices in Atlanta
would be named the CBF Resource Center, and a chief operating
officer would be added to coordinate the plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the CBF has done a good job of focusing the energy of
disaffected people,'' said Greg Warner, executive editor of
Associated Baptist Press, an independent news agency in
Jacksonville, Fla., formed in 1990 with support from the CBF. ``It
has been a struggle at times, because `moderate Baptist' means
they're not going to get excited about much of anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Pat and Carolyn Anderson, who live in Lakeland, Fla., are
coordinators of the CBF in Florida. They said differences between
the CBV and the SBC are illustrated by each group's annual
meetings. The upcoming assembly will keep business sessions to a
minimum, spending most of its time in educational workshops and
small discussion groups. There will be no resolutions or
pronouncements on social issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``An observer would see more openness. You would see a lot more
lay persons. You'd see a lot more women in leadership roles,'' Pat
Anderson said. ``Our moderator is Sarah Frances Anders, a lay woman
from Louisiana, and next year it will be Donna Forrester, who is on
the staff of First Baptist Church in Greenville, S.C. At the
Southern Baptist Convention, all the speakers in favor of the
Baptist Faith and Message were white male clergy.''
</P>
<P>
   The disputes between factions in the convention 10 to 15 years
ago centered on the interpretation of the Bible. The issue of
whether women could be ordained or be pastors served as a dividing
line between the way conservatives and moderates interpreted the
Bible.
</P>
<P>
   The Andersons both were raised in Southern Baptist churches.
Pat's father was a pastor and director of missions for an
association, or district. Pat was elected first vice president of
the Florida Baptist Convention for 1986-87. Carolyn was elected
second vice president of the state convention _ the second woman to
hold statewide office _ for 1988-89.
</P>
<P>
   But Florida Baptists were firmly in the conservative camp, and
as the conservatives gained power in the national convention, the
Andersons say they were no longer welcome in state convention
circles. In August 1990, after it was clear that conservatives had
consolidated their hold on the SBC's power structure, disaffected
moderates met to consider their options. Pat Anderson was asked to
coordinate the group from Florida.
</P>
<P>
   The Andersons' first mailing list had 112 people. Today they
have about 8,000 addresses, a staff of five _ soon to be six _ and
a $450,000 budget. About 50 churches in Florida support them.
</P>
<P>
   Southern Baptist leaders seem to have adopted a strategy of
officially ignoring the CBF. There are occasional discussions in
national or state meetings about not accepting money from churches
that also give to the fellowship, but Florida Baptist Convention
leaders say that has never been an issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a CBF-aligned church needs assistance from our staff, we're
going to work with them,'' said Don Hepburn, vice president for
public relations at the Florida Baptist Convention. ``We have not
tried to draw any line in the sand. We don't view them as
competitors. There's such a great need for evangelism, it's going
to take all of us working together.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Ledger in Lakeland, Fla., is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-27-00 2334EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
