<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SOTOMAYOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOTOMAYOR, BANNED FOR DRUG, IS OUT OF GAMES 
</HEADLINE>
   By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Javier Sotomayor, the Cuban world record-holder in the high jump
and the only person to leap eight feet, was suspended Tuesday for a
positive drug test and banned from competing in the 2000 Summer
Olympics in Sydney, Australia, track and field's international
governing body announced.
</P>
<P>
   Sotomayor, the 1992 Olympic champion, who has jumped 8 feet {
inch, tested positive for cocaine at the 1999 Pan American Games in
Winnipeg, Manitoba, and was stripped of first place.
</P>
<P>
   Cuban sports officials declined to suspend the 32-year-old
Sotomayor, saying that his urine sample had been manipulated. But
in international sports, it is up to the athlete to prove his or
her innocence in a doping offense, which Sotomayor was unable to do
before an arbitration panel of the International Amateur Athletic
Federation, which is based in Monaco.
</P>
<P>
   The two-year suspension from international competition is
retroactive to last summer and will remain in effect until July 30,
2001.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, he would have been subjected to a four-year
suspension, but the IAAF has reduced its most severe punishment in
doping offenses to two years after losing several right-to-work
cases in court.
</P>
<P>
   Next week, another IAAF arbitration panel is expected to rule on
an appeal of a suspension by Merlene Ottey, a multiple world and
Olympic medalist from Jamaica, who tested positive for the steroid
nandrolone, Reineri said.
</P>
<P>
   The IAAF's doping commission will also probably review the case
of Dieter Baumann, the German distance runner who won the 5,000
meters at the 1992 Summer Olympics and who also tested positive for
nandrolone last year.
</P>
<P>
   Nandrolone, which has been easily detectable for years, has
surfaced in recent months in several cases. Some athletes and
scientists believe that it is being consumed in nutritional
supplements that are not properly labeled.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-27-00 2339EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
