A6866 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-KIMES-TRIAL-NYT &LR;      06-27 0792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-KIMES-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOTHER AND SON RECEIVE LIFE IMPRISONMENT FOR KILLING WOMAN 
</HEADLINE>
   By KATHERINE E. FINKELSTEIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A mother and son who were convicted of killing a New
York city woman in a plot to seize her town house proclaimed their
innocence Tuesday in bizarre, rambling, and sometimes vulgar,
statements before a judge, who then sentenced them both to life in
prison.
</P>
<P>
   A jury on May 18 had found Sante Kimes, 65, and her son,
Kenneth, 25, guilty of murdering Irene Silverman, whose body was
never found.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Judge Rena K. Uviller of State Supreme Court in
Manhattan sentenced Kimes to 120 years to life in prison, and her
son to 126 years to life.
</P>
<P>
   Uviller described Kimes as a ``sociopath'' of ``unremitting
malevolence,'' and her son as a ``vacuous dupe'' who had evolved
into a ``remorseless predator'' under his mother's influence.
</P>
<P>
   The sentence capped a bizarre day in which Sante and Kenneth
Kimes railed against their own lawyers, the police, the district
attorney and the judge in meandering statements. Kimes even accused
Uviller of using hand signals to conspire with prosecutors
throughout the trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of our precious civil and constitutional rights were
trampled,'' Kimes said. ``Much like the witch hunts of old Salem,
the police planted and planted and planted evidence to fool the
jury,'' she said, adding, ``No one has been told the truth in this
case.''
</P>
<P>
   The grandiosity and self-pity of their statements came as little
surprise to more than a dozen detectives who sat in the jury box
Tuesday to watch the sentencing. They had searched for Silverman's
body without success, but had uncovered what they have called a
trail of fraud, theft, arson, identify theft and murder that
stretched from Hawaii to Las Vegas to the Bahamas.
</P>
<P>
   Police also turned up 14 notebooks in which Kimes, whose son had
rented an apartment in Silverman's house in 1998, wrote of her plan
to murder the wealthy socialite, dispose of her body, then assume
her identity and steal her townhouse, valued at $7.7 million. The
notebooks, along with a forged deed to the house, allowed
prosecutors to build a successful murder case, even without a body.
</P>
<P>
   The Kimeses' legal battles do not end in New York. They are
expected to stand trial in Los Angeles on charges that they killed
a former business associate, David Kazdin, whose body was found in
a garbage bin near Los Angeles International Airport. A spokeswoman
for Gil Garcetti, the Los Angeles district attorney, said that
extradition proceedings would begin this week.
</P>
<P>
   Kimes' lawyer, Michael Hardy, argued before the sentencing
Tuesday that his client was not so evil that she deserved to die in
jail. ``Is Kimes a Hitler?'' he asked. ``Is she a Mussolini? Is she
a Jack the Ripper?''
</P>
<P>
   Kimes' own statement did little to soften her image as she
criticized almost everyone who participated in her trial, then
proclaimed it was ``the first time in United States history that an
innocent mother and son have been convicted of a crime that didn't
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Uviller urged her to come to the point, but as Hardy intervened
in an effort to stop her from speaking further, Kimes went on to
say that ``the only murderers in this case are the prosecutors, for
murdering our Constitution.''
</P>
<P>
   When Kimes finally exceeded her allotted time, Uviller
interrupted her and said, ``Ms. Kimes, your performance, I mean
your statement, is over,'' at which point jurors and friends of
Silverman cheered.
</P>
<P>
   Mel Sachs, the lawyer for Limes' son, then tried to distinguish
his client from Kimes by saying that the son did not have the
luxury in life of choosing his own mother and that unlike her, the
son felt remorse.
</P>
<P>
   But Kenneth Kimes then gave a long, disjointed. He began by
saying that his mother was scared of law enforcement officials. He
then turned to the detectives in the jury box and said, ``No
offense, but you're spooky.''
</P>
<P>
   He went on to accuse a witness in the California case of
murdering Silverman, claim that he had been illegally interrogated,
and complained about the exclusion of Court TV from the courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   In sentencing, Uviller first spoke of Silverman as someone who
embodied the best of New York City and was interested in its
``buzz,'' opening her home to boarders without regard to ``class,
education or wealth.'' Then she described Kimes as ``the most
degenerate defendant who has ever appeared in this courtroom.''
</P>
<P>
   As the judge made her remarks and imposed the maximum sentences,
the mother and son sat silently. As they were led from the
courtroom, detective Anthony Vasquez called out from the jury box,
``You have plenty of time to tell us where Irene Silverman is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
