<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-APPLE-TOURS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BID TO KEEP APPLE TOURS CLOSED IS REJECTED 
</HEADLINE>
   By ANDY NEWMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ New York Apple Tours' red double-decker buses, which
have been banished from this city's streets for nearly a month, may
be rolling again as early as this weekend. On Monday, a panel of
state appellate judges rejected an attempt by the city and state to
sideline the buses while they try to shut the company down
permanently.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which has racked up hundreds of regulatory and
safety violations and accidents in its nine years of ferrying
tourists around the city, has been under siege by the authorities
and residents since May 22, when one of its buses struck and killed
a 71-year-old pedestrian in midtown Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the accident, the state Department of Motor Vehicles
and the city Department of Consumer Affairs had started
administrative hearings to revoke New York Apple's licenses. But on
May 31, Gov. George Pataki issued an order pulling the registration
of the company's 63 buses pending the outcome of the hearings.
</P>
<P>
   New York Apple challenged the order, saying it violated its
rights to due process, and on June 14, a state Supreme Court judge
in Manhattan agreed. Judge Phyllis Gangel-Jacob reversed the
governor's order, although she also appointed a former city
official to monitor the company.
</P>
<P>
   The city and state immediately appealed the ruling, forcing the
buses to stay off the road until the appellate ruling on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The state and city both said Tuesday that they would abide by
the appellate panel's ruling, which rejected their appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We disagree with the decision, but we will comply and will
work closely with the monitor to ensure the safety of the
pedestrians and motorists of New York City,'' said Suzanne Morris,
a spokeswoman for Pataki, on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   New York Apple's president, Hayim Grant, said the buses would
roll again as soon as the company did two things: demonstrated to
the court-appointed monitor, Ross Sandler, a former city
transportation commissioner, that its buses and drivers are in
compliance with safety laws; and found enough employees to get back
in business.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to call over 350 employees that were laid off to
convince them to come back to work,'' Grant said Tuesday. ``I'm
sure many have already gotten replacement employment. But we are
hopeful that we'll be back on the road by this weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   Grant said New York Apple officials planned to meet with Sandler
on Tuesday night to ``to determine what steps we need to take
before we can operate again.'' Sandler could not be reached for
comment Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   New York Apple's problems with the authorities escalated on May
22, when one of its drivers, who was not licensed to operate a bus,
made an illegal turn onto West 45th Street and ran over and killed
Randolph Walker, an actor walking home from an audition.
</P>
<P>
   The accident galvanized neighborhood opposition, which had been
building for years, and the authorities reacted by pulling the
company's licenses.
</P>
<P>
   But in her ruling last week, Gangel-Jacob said letting the buses
continue to operate would ``not do any harm to any public
interest,'' while shutting the company without a full trial would
hurt the company and its employees and could damage the city's
tourism industry.
</P>
<P>
   Grant said he was pleased with the ruling, which was not
accompanied by any comments from the justices.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel that we're entitled to a proper defense before we're
shut down,'' he said. ``We've been serving visitors to New York for
close to 10 years now, we're the leader in the industry, and to
shut us down without a proper hearing and defense we felt was not
constitutional.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-27-00 2357EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
